<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DEADKIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Children's bodies found; illing suspected
 &HT;    By Jason Spencer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUTTO, Texas _ The bodies of two small childrn _ apparent
homicide victims _ were found in a shallow creek near a cemetery
late Monday afternoon, according to Williamson County Sheriff Ed
Richards.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's investigators do not know the identities of the
children, both of whom had visible injuries and seemed to be about
3 or 4 years old, Richards said. Richards would not describe the
children's injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are things at the scene I cannot discuss,'' Richards
said.
</P>
<P>
   No children matching either of their descriptions have been
reported missing in the area, Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have none reported that fits this at all,'' Richards said.
Several other Central Texas law enforcement agencies also said they
had no unsolved reports of missing pre-school children.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe the children had only been dead ``a short
while'' and that the deaths were not accidental, Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was an accident, you'd think someone would have reported
it by now,'' Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had anything like this in a while,'' he said.
``It's very disturbing when any person appears to be murdered,
especially when it's small children. Hopefully, someone can call
and tell us about two children who are missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators do not believe the dead girl is either of the
girls reported missing recently from the Irving and Fort Worth
areas, Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   The dead girl could match the description of Cristy Ryno, a
3-year-old from Irving reported missing on Saturday, Richards said,
adding it was ``very unlikely'' they are the same person.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff's department issued a statewide bulletin describing
the children and has been in touch with authorities investigating
Ryno's disappearance. Members of the Irving Police Department and
FBI agents may be in Williamson County today, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A couple walking along Brushy Creek near County Road 137
discovered the children's bodies shortly before 5 p.m. and reported
the discovery at Hutto City Hall, said Mel Yantis, Hutto city
administrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was pretty upset,'' Yantis said. ``She and her husband
were out just walking along the creek apparently.''
</P>
<P>
   The rocky creek bed where the bodies were found is about 100
feet from the county road, down a rough path that leads to a steep
dropoff, which bottoms out at a gravel bank. The children were in
about six inches of water near the bank of the roughly 35-foot-wide
creek, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   The area is surrounded by corn fields and a few scattered farm
houses. The Hutto Cemetery also is nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a common place for people to stop and go down to the
creek,'' Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   Their bodies were taken to Condra Funeral Home in Taylor, and an
autopsy is planned for today at a location that had not been
determined as of Monday night, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators received one call concerning the dead children
Monday night, ``but it did not pan out,'' Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Spencer writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
