<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside game lifts Rockets to win
 &HT;    By Mark Rosner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Rockets lost one of their best players Monday, but
for one night, at least, they were able to duck the fallout from
the absence of Othella Harrington, who will miss the remainder of
the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Using their strong inside game to open up the perimeter for
three-pointers, the Rockets defeated Seattle 120-113 at the Compaq
Center. Charles Barkley scored 25 points, including 13 in the
fourth quarter. Hakeem Olajuwon added 24 and Scottie Pippen scored
22.
</P>
<P>
   Houston (27-14) hit 13 of 27 three-point shots. Sam Mack
provided the bulk of the treys, making seven of 11 to score all 21
of his points from behind the arc.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington, the Rockets' top reserve and fourth-leading scorer,
will miss a minimum of two weeks after undergoing surgery Monday on
his left foot to drain a bacterial infection. The infection is
under a soft corn in Harrington's foot and was the result of a cut
between two toes that did not properly heal.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of the 6-foot-9-inch Harrington was more than
negated by Seattle having to play without third-leading scorer Vin
Baker, who has a sore right knee. Baker is no defensive star, but
he is 6 feet, 11 inches, and the Sonics could have used his height
inside, where Olajuwon, Barkley and Pippen dominated the game. When
Seattle tried to help inside on Barkley and Olajuwon, they passed
the ball outside for three-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   Detlef Schrempf led Seattle with 28 points, five more than Gary
Payton, who also had 15 assists. Dale Ellis scored 22.
</P>
<P>
   Payton, who would be a strong MVP candidate if the Sonics were
better than 19-22, had no impact during the first half, when
Houston took a 56-45 lead. He missed all eight of his shots,
scoring only on a pair of free throws. Payton extended his streak
to nine missed shots early in the third quarter, then he suddenly
went to work, scoring 17 points in the period.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics trailed by only five late in the third quarter, but
Mack hit consecutive three-pointers to provide some separation.
Barkley then held Seattle off in the fourth quarter, scoring 10
straight points.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rosner writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
