<SLUG> BC-HOTRODDER-SAVED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVE YOUNG MEN STOP RUNAWAY CAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Johnny Lara and his two buddies felt fortunate to
come across famed hot rod enthusiast Louis Senter as he worked on
his flashy yellow 1923 Model T roadster, the same one as on the
cover of Hot Rod magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But Senter said Monday he's actually the fortunate one: The
1,300-pound hot rod rolled on top of him while he was talking with
the three _ and they managed to pull him to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably would have kept going with me under it. I was
lucky that the boys were there,'' said Senter, a burly 78-year-old
who escaped with only a broken right ankle and injured left knee.
</P>
<P>
   The trio _ Lenny Trujillo, 16, Lara, 18, and Roland Gomez, 29 _
said anyone would have had the same reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, anybody would do it. If I would have been the one under
the car, he would have done it,'' said Lara.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very scary because there were cars coming in the
opposite direction and they had to swerve,'' Lara recalled. ``I
thought he was hurt really bad.''
</P>
<P>
   To thank the trio, Senter plans to give them a session about how
to build hot rods.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were really very nice. I'll give the kids a little
talk,'' said Senter, who has built three Indianapolis 500 racers
and displays his street rod in shows and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The accident occurred about 9:10 p.m. Friday on a street in
suburban Reseda when Senter's car stalled on the way home from a
car show. While working on the car, the rod rolled backward over
him, pinning him to the ground and crushing his right leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started right on me. It started rolling backward and I
tried to run to turn the key off, but the left front wheel caught
me. Next thing I knew, I was lying on the ground,'' Senter said.
</P>
<P>
   The three had been at a church sleepover nearby and were playing
football when the flashy car captured their attention. Minutes
after they began talking to him, the car jolted back.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, the car just turned on and went in reverse.
The man tried to hold the car back, but it dragged him,'' said
Trujillo, a Reseda resident.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez and Trujillo found the ignition switch under the dashboard
and turned it off. ``He had so many switches on his car. I finally
switched the right one off,'' said Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pushed the car forward and Rolando helped him up,''
Trujillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Senter later realized that he had inadvertently knocked the
vehicle in gear before turning on the ignition.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Senter said he has learned a lesson: He will
install the safety switch he's been meaning to install for years on
his street rod.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Thompson, a parishioner at International Missionary Church
who was working with a youth group at the time of the accident,
also lauded the three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it sets an excellent example. Not everyone gets
involved. I think they acted without any regard for their own
safety. They acted on impulse, and I'm proud of them,'' Thompson
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
