<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HALL-NOBELNOMINATION-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Rep. Hall nominated for Nobel prize
</P>
<P>
   By Timothy R. Gaffney
</P>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A fellow lawmaker and two foreign officials have
nominated U.S. Rep. Tony Hall (D-Ohio) for the Nobel Peace Prize.
</P>
<P>
   It's the second time in as many years that Hall has been
nominated for his efforts to reduce world hunger and promote
humanitarian concerns. He's one of 136 candidates for the prize, a
Hall aide said.
</P>
<P>
   One of those nominating Hall is Rep. Frank R. Wolf, R-Va., who
also nominated Hall last year. The others are Tsutomu Hata, a
former Japanese prime minister and current member of parliament,
and Hussain Muhammad Ershad, former president of Bangladesh and
current parliament member.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who learned about the nomination from the Norwegian Nobel
Committee, said the three nominated him separately. The committee
will announce the winner in October.
</P>
<P>
   Hata noted Hall's efforts to reduce hunger in North Korea, and
Ershad was familiar with Hall's efforts to reduce suffering in
Bangladesh after it was swept by terrible floods, Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall worked in the Peace Corps and has promoted humanitarian
causes since he began serving in Congress in 1979. He was chairman
of the former House Select Committee on Hunger and chairs the
Congressional Hunger Center .
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got 25 million people in our own country who are
hungry,'' Hall said. ``Overseas, you've got 1 billion people who
are malnourished.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, John Hume and David Trimble won the peace prize for
their efforts to end the conflict in Northern Ireland. Other
recipients have included Mother Theresa, Martin Luther King Jr.,
Albert Schweitzer, and presidents Theodore Roosevelt and Woodrow
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about it,'' Hall said. ``I really don't deserve to
be in that kind of company, but I'm not complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
