<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-NAME-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. SCHOOL TO SHED GANG-TIED NAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Blythe Street Elementary School doesn't print
sweat shirts or bumper stickers with its name for a simple reason:
A notorious gang uses the street's name, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's opposed to having their kids walk around with a
gang name on their T-shirts,'' parent Sandra Cervantes said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   So now parents and teachers at the quiet campus in suburban
Reseda are working to rename the school and started canvassing the
community for suggestions. They plan to select the winner with a
public vote this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Students aware of the reputation of the gang whose home turf is
several miles to the east welcome the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes me scared, because I think that a gang member is
going to come to the school and do something to us,'' said Vanessa
Castillo, 9.
</P>
<P>
   The 450-student campus is not even close to the stretch of
Blythe Street in Panorama City where the gang operates. The school
lies several miles to the west, tucked among pine trees on a
secluded strip of Blythe in Reseda.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is so bad on the gang-occupied section of Blythe
Street that residents there have proposed changing the street's
name, trying to rechristen part of the street Amber Way.
</P>
<P>
   Parents at Blythe Street Elementary have talked about renaming
the campus for years, Cervantes said. To make sure it finally
becomes a reality, they formed a name-change committee with some of
the school's staff members and started asking the community for
suggestions earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Students, parents, teachers and administrators have until April
30 to pitch new names. The committee then will research the
suggestions, narrow the field to perhaps five finalists and ask the
community to vote for its favorite in June. Any proposed change
must be approved by the Los Angeles school board to take effect.
</P>
<P>
   The source of inspiration for a new name can be most anyone or
anything, Cervantes said. Well, anything positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking it should be the Mr. Castro School,'' said Juan
Gomez, 9, explaining that Castro is his homeroom teacher. ``He
helps us learn math and reading. He's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Cruz, 11, suggested naming the school after Harriet
Tubman. Other students would rather take the name of their favorite
television star, Cervantes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why we want the teachers to work with students on
selecting names,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Los Angeles schools rarely switch names, they will
occasionally take on a new identity to honor a local hero.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, the Board of Education is scheduled to vote on
whether 102nd Street School in Watts can become the Florence
Griffith-Joyner School and on whether Crenshaw's Dublin Fundamental
Magnet School can rename itself after former Mayor Tom Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Julie Korenstein said she's not aware of another
school switching identities out of concern that crime had tarred
its original name. But if parents believe the change would help
shield students or boost pride in the school, she said, she would
support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever needs to be done to protect the children, it's a good
thing,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
