<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COULD HARRIS HAVE HANDLED RODMAN?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Dennis Rodman and Del Harris barely passed each
other in the Forum hallway on their respective ways in and out of
the building Feb. 23. Rodman was hired the same day Harris was
fired, and at least one person who knows Rodman well believes
that's where the problems began.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago Bulls assistant coach Frank Hamblen, who became close to
Rodman in his three seasons with the Bulls, was consulted by
Harris, an old friend, before the Lakers signed Rodman. Hamblen
thought Rodman would be a good fit for the Harris-led Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But then Harris was dismissed and Kurt Rambis was promoted to
rookie head coach status.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't a good situation, as it turned out,'' Hamblen
said, ``I thought Del would be there _ a veteran coach who would
have had a better handle on the team. The Lakers made so many
changes, it turned out not to be a good situation. I just don't
think there's much leadership out there.... Dennis ended up being
the show, which wasn't a good situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Bull, Ron Harper, added his voice to the chorus of NBA
insiders who believe the 38-year-old Rodman is through playing
professional basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked to see that happen,'' Harper said of Rodman's
termination last week. ``I thought he would last at least until the
season was through.... I guess I'm kind of shocked, but then again,
I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaq on top: Not that he cares, but Shaquille O'Neal regained
the lead in the NBA scoring race for the first time since early
this season. Philadelphia's Allen Iverson scored just six points
Sunday, dropping his scoring average to 26.1, behind O'Neal's 26.5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he gets it,'' O'Neal said. ``He's working hard, he's
playing hard. Whoever gets it, I don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal repeated his general philosophy on scoring titles, MVP
trophies and all other nonchampionship honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``That mean's nothing to me. Just winning,'' he said. ``Right
now my team ain't winning, so nothing else matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: The revolving door on the Lakers' training room
spun again Monday. Rick Fox, nursing a sore right knee suffered
during his 24-point performance Saturday at Utah, did not dress for
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Harper, who missed the Utah game with a sore right foot,
was in uniform Monday but was held out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   All this comes just as the Lakers got a relatively healthy Glen
Rice back from a bout with tonsillitis.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make a coach feel a bit insecure about his
roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go home with peace of mind, I know that,'' Rambis
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
