<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5270 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-FILMFEST-COX     04-20 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-FILMFEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio filmmaker shows latest effort at L.A. festival
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Every filmmaker dreams of connecting with an
audience. Dayton, Ohio-area director Ed Radtke made people laugh
and moved many to tears with The Dream Catcher , a locally produced
drama that had its world premiere Sunday afternoon at the fifth
annual Los Angeles Independent Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The sold-out premiere at the Directors Guild of America Theater
on Sunset Boulevard drew the likes of pioneering independent film
director Paul Bartel ( Eating Raoul ) and Academy Award-winning
actress Marisa Tomei. The emotionally involving film, largely shot
in Ohio's Miami Valley, was acclaimed for its subtle direction,
strong performances and stunning cinematography.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of praise was remarkable,'' said producer Steven
Bognar of Yellow Springs, Ohio. ``People were gushing.''
</P>
<P>
   Erik Bork, a transplanted Beavercreek, Ohio native who won
recent Emmy and Golden Globe Awards as a writer-producer of Tom
Hanks' HBO series, ``From the Earth to the Moon ,'' called Radtke's
film powerful and compelling from beginning to end. ``I was in
tears at the end, as was the person next to me, who didn't know the
filmmaker and had never seen the film,'' Bork said. ``I guess the
highest praise I could say is it makes me wish I was back in Ohio,
part of this group of filmmakers and working with them. It's
humbling. It's so good it's truly humbling.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright State University Theatre Department chairman W. Stuart
McDowell, wiping tears from his eyes in the lobby after the
screening, said the film is exceptional. ``I'm so proud of them,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tomei, who won an Oscar for My Cousin Vinny , praised the film's
cinematography, as well as its honesty. ``There were no lies in
anything _ the acting, the writing, the way it unfolded,'' she
said. ``It was just really honest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dream Catcher is a road drama about two delinquent
teen-agers who hitchhike from Dayton to Reno, Nev. Freddy (Maurice
Compte) is faced with becoming a teen-aged dad and is searching for
his own father, recently released from prison. Albert (Paddy
Connor) is a youthful runaway en route to Reno, where his mother
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty personal,'' Radtke, 36, told the festival
audience. ``By the time I was 18, I was a convicted felon and a
father.'' Like his characters, the Japanese-American Bellbrook
native hitchhiked and hopped freight trains. He said the film was a
way to deal with his past and move beyond it. ``I thought it would
be a wonderful backdrop for a story,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Radtke earned an NEA Filmmaking Production Grant and a
Guggenheim Fellowship, which became the initial financing for the
film, and used a predominantly local crew.
</P>
<P>
   Among those making the trip from Dayton were producer Julia
Reichert and editor Jim Klein, both Wright State film professors;
film-score composer Georgiana Gomez; and casting director Alison
Kennedy Maier. Radtke was also joined by his parents, Jim and
Kazuko Radtke of Bellbrook; his brother, John; and his
screenwriting partner, Marc Nieson of Minneapolis, Minn. ``He's
gone too far not to share this with him,'' Nieson said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's premiere was the first time Radtke and company saw the
film projected in its entirety. The fifth and final reel didn't
arrive until Friday from the film-processing lab in New York City.
Unable to screen the film beforehand, Radtke and Bognar partially
unspooled each reel on Sunday afternoon to ensure that each was
numbered correctly. ``I think it's just a matter of nervousness,''
Reichert said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dream Catcher premiered with opening titles but only partial
end credits, because of problems with the crawl. ``The print is
still going to be wet,'' Radtke said on Sunday morning. ``It's the
reality of the process. We haven't seen the film ourselves and have
been busting our butts to get it done and get it done well.'' The
credit sequence will be completed by Thursday in time for the
film's New York premiere at the Lincoln Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Independent Film Festival opened last Thursday
with the world premiere of Phil Joanou's romantic comedy, Entropy ,
starring Stephen Dorff, Lauren Holly, Hector Elizondo, Bono and U2.
It closes tonight with the premiere of George Hickenlooper's The
Big Brass Ring , a political drama adapted from an Orson Welles
screenplay, starring William Hurt and Miranda Richardson. The
festival was expected to draw 25,000 people, with film distributors
chief among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular festival is unique in that because it's in Los
Angeles, so many of the buyers are actually here, so it makes our
jobs a little easier because the right people might actually be
attending,'' said Ira Deutchman, the producer's representative who
would negotiate the sale of Radtke's film. ``Whereas if you to
smaller, regional film festivals, as much of an honor it is to be
in them, you may not have the buyers there. So it's the best thing
about it and it's also the most nerve-racking thing about it,
because all the distributors will be there ... for better or for
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who see it are important to the future of the
film,'' Radtke said.
</P>
<P>
   The director and producers met with Deutchman for 1 hours
Saturday night to discuss strategy and assuage nervousness. He
advised them to be modest in their expectations. ``We're not going
to sell the film (Monday) night,'' Reichert said. ``That's just not
going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's premiere was most likely attended by lower-level
distribution executives who would report back to their superiors.
The best gauge of the screening's success would be ticket requests
for the second showing Monday night. No calls for tickets would
indicate that the distributors were not advising their higher-ups
to see the film; an influx of industry requests would imply
interest.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the overwhelming response to the premiere, the
filmmakers were cautiously optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you hope for,'' Deutchman said. ``Get a crowd in
there to see it and get that kind of reaction. Step one
completed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the film was beautiful,'' said Bognar, basking in
the accolades that immediately followed. ``I feel very thrilled to
see it as it should be seen, and I need a beer.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Larsen writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
