<SLUG> BC-BBA-EDMONDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDMONDS OUT FOUR MONTHS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO -- Jim Edmonds, whose talent on the baseball field is
matched only by his penchant for injuries, has decided to have
surgery on his right shoulder and will be out through the end of
August.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels center fielder arrived at Edison Field Monday morning
planning to take batting practice in front of hitting coach Rod
Carew, and if all went well, he would make the trip with the team
to Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   But the shoulder, which has bothered him for the past four
years, wouldn't allow Edmonds to swing a bat and he finally decided
to have the arthroscopic procedure, which will repair a torn labrum
and ``tighten up the shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels medical director Dr. Lewis Yocum will perform the surgery
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried a variety of avenues, via medication and therapy,
to treat the shoulder,'' Yocum said. ``The surgery should allow for
full return of arm strength, but we will know more following the
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minimum amount of recuperation time should be roughly four
months.
</P>
<P>
   The news that Edmonds will have surgery is only the latest in a
career filled with aches and pains. Before this season, Edmonds had
been placed on the disabled list three times during his five year
career, not to mention the numerous times he has missed a game or
two at a time because of an injury. And it continued just before
the start of this season, when Edmonds was placed on the disabled
list April 4 because of a strained groin.
</P>
<P>
   It was later revealed that Edmonds aggrevated his shoulder
lifting weights only three days before the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds shoulder has been a source of pain for the past four
years because of the way he plays, diving for balls and crashing
into outfield fences. But he has ``kept it real strong for the last
year-and-a-half by lifting weights.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago he said he considered having surgery during the
offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have got it done last year probably,'' Edmonds said
during the Angels season-opening series. ``I just didn't want to
have surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   But now it's a reality, and the Angels seemed to have settled
their dilemma of what to do with too many outfielders. Garret
Anderson is the center fielder, Tim Salmon is the right fielder and
Darin Erstad will move back to left from first base once Mo Vaughn
returns from his ankle injury. Vaughn is due back Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' Angels pitcher Chuck Finley said when informed of the
news on Edmonds. ``We've got to move on, we can't worry about that
stuff. Nothing shocks us anymore. We're a good team, we'll move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the absence of Vaughn and Edmonds, the Angels are
also without starting shortstop Gary DiSarcina, who is recovering
from surgery to repair a broken bone in his left forearm. He's
expected back around the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worry about not only Edmonds' injury, but everyone,''
Angels pitcher Shigetoshi Hasegawa said. ``If we stay healthy, we
can win. If everybody stays hurt we're not going to win. We learned
that last year. Still, we can win right now, and Mo Vaughn's coming
back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
