<HEADER>
A5282 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-BUDGET-2takes-LADN     04-20 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-BUDGET-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR'S BUDGET PROPOSAL FOCUSES ON QUALITY OF L.A.   LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Today in first graf refers to Tuesday.) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shifting his top priority to quality of life in
the neighborhoods, Mayor Richard Riordan will propose today a $4.2
billion budget for 1999-2000 that expands tree trimming, street
resurfacing, alley closures and removal of abandoned buildings.
</P>
<P>
   In a reflection of the city's improving economy, the mayor's
budget also seeks to hire more police officers and firefighters,
lengthen library and pool hours, and eliminate a swimming fee for
kids 17 and younger.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we've done from our first year, our budget is
goal-oriented,'' Riordan said Monday during an interview with Daily
News editors and reporters. ``Depending on what goal you want,
whether it's a safer L.A. or more parks or library services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is essential that every part of our city feel the benefits
of a growing economy and safer city. My budget invests significant
new resources in neighborhoods in need.''
</P>
<P>
   This has been a theme stressed more often by the mayor in recent
months, particularly as crime has continued to decline and the
economy has improved.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Cindy Miscikowski said she welcomed Riordan's
ideas, but wants to scrutinize the funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the sound of a lot of what is being highlighted,'' she
said. ``To be fair I have to see where the money is coming from and
what is being curtailed to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a sign of that improving economy, Riordan's budget again
proposes no new taxes, is $87 million bigger than the present
budget and has no deficit to cover _ a first in the six years he
has been in office. Most of the increase over the current budget is
going for salaries.
</P>
<P>
   And Riordan said he is proposing the largest reserve fund in
city history at $60million.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the city's credit rating recently improved to AA,
and bond houses took Los Angeles off a negative watch in place
since the 1994 Northridge Earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor credited the improving economy _ in particular the
housing market and higher property taxes _ with providing more
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   While he is emphasizing quality-of-life improvements, Riordan
said he is not abandoning public safety.
</P>
<P>
   The spending plan calls for 157 new police officers beyond the
number needed to replace those who retire or leave for other
reasons, bringing the force up to its highest level of 9,900.
Federal funds are available to pay most of the cost of hiring more
than 700 officers for three years, and Riordan said he intends to
take advantage of the program in future years.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the mayor is calling for expanding the anti-gang Community
Law Enforcement and Recovery program around the city.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Police Department represents the largest share of the
budget _ some $1.3billion _ the mayor has set aside $500,000 to
conduct its first full financial and management audit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if things are being run well, you want to look to see
where the money is going,'' Riordan said. ``There may be programs
that started 20 or 30 years ago and are no longer needed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's interesting,'' said Greg Nelson, press deputy to
Councilman Joel Wachs. ``I don't think that has ever been done. We
always tend to be supportive of audits, especially of large
departments, where there is the potential for greater efficiency
and cost savings.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan also pointed out that the budget covers $96 million of
the $100 million cost of those officers hired under federal
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows those who doubted if we would be able to afford to
pay for the officers that we can,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also calls for continued expansion of the Los Angeles
Fire Department, with 126 recruits. Riordan said this will make up
the loss of some positions and also reduce the need for overtime
pay to firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also adds money for two new basic life support
ambulances and to upgrade existing helicopters and purchase a new
one.
</P>
<P>
   On the quality-of-life issues for rundown neighborhoods, Riordan
said he is providing money to step up enforcement on nuisance and
abandoned properties.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the city will speed up its efforts on closing alleys that
have become havens for gangs and drug dealers, create an unlawful
detainer unit in the City Attorney's Office to take action against
criminal tenants, and expand the Department of Animal Services to
deal with stray and dangerous dogs around the city.
</P>
<P>
   Expanded hours at libraries, pools and parks are also seen as a
way to help neighborhoods in need, Riordan said. In particular, he
cited dropping the swimming pool fee to open access to more kids at
a cost of $800,000 this coming year.
</P>
<P>
   One area that could generate controversy with the City Council
is a Riordan proposal to use the $300 million the city is to
receive in its settlement of a lawsuit with the tobacco industry to
make sidewalk repairs and come in compliance with the Americans
with Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   Several council members had criticized this proposal in the
past, saying the money should be used for health-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   However, Riordan remained confident his approach would be
adopted.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the major complaints that all of us as city officials
receive are about the condition of the sidewalks,'' Riordan said.
``I think the council has come to realize that at least some of
this money can be used for sidewalk repairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan said he also expects to have a battle with council
members over a proposal he is making regarding the use of money
from the Special Parking Revenue Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Council members want to restrict the mayor's ability to use the
funds for purposes other than parking.
</P>
<P>
   The fund, which now is at an estimated $26 million, is generated
by parking meters and is to be spent only in the City Council
district in which the meters are located.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite a need for parking facilities throughout the city,
only those districts that have have meters receive project
funding,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   He is proposing a change to allow the funds to be used
throughout the city on parking projects in a list to be developed
on priorities. Also, he is suggesting that those projects that are
more than 2 years old be abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan said he is also girding for a potential battle over his
proposal to eliminate the $1 surcharge on building permits to cover
the cost of one-stop construction centers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time, the fee was needed to pay for these centers,''
Riordan said. ``We don't think it's needed now.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy could come because the trust fund is now
administered by a City Council-appointed committee that wants to
remain in operation, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also includes $4 million to continue the city's
efforts to deal with the Y2K computer bug.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in as good as shape as anyone,'' Riordan said. ``We've
done some tests and run-throughs and there were no serious
problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 0036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
