b x &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BKC-CELTICS-PACERS-BOS     04-20 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S A NO-WIN SITUATION FOR CELTICS
</HEADLINE>
 BKC-CELTICS-PACERS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL HOLLEY 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could have reshuffled it, remixed it, revised it, and even
replayed it. Nothing would have changed the final result of
Pacers-Celtics Monday night at the FleetCenter. Really, there was
nothing complicated about it.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a one-sentence summary? Try this one: The Pacers had
the right men in uniforms while the Celtics had the wrong men in
suits.
</P>
<P>
   Or this: The Pacers' major injury was to Sleepy Sam Perkins,
while the Celtics were missing Antoine Walker, Kenny Anderson, and
Ron Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, all of that inevitably led to this: A 120-104 Pacers
win, their 27th of the season, before 18,352.
</P>
<P>
   It would be surprising if anyone left the building shaking their
heads, wondering where it all went wrong for the Celtics. That's
because the problems were obvious. In this case, it had very little
to do with words and phrases such as ``rebounding,'' ``transition
defense,'' and ``defensive rotations.'' The updated Celtics
glossary includes words such as ``sprain,'' ``pull,'' ``spasm'' and
``underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   The last entry is necessary because the Celtics probably will
not be favored to win for the rest of the season, especially if
Walker is out for the year, as Rick Pitino believes. And then there
are the back and leg injuries for Mercer and Anderson,
respectively, injuries that may keep them out until at least the
end of the week. If that weren't enough, Dana Barros may be out,
too, after suffering a groin injury Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all of that, the Celtics did the ``Hoosiers'' thing for
the first half. They trailed by 4, the most entertaining halftime
deficit they've had this year. It's not often that you can see a
68-64 halftime count in today's NBA, especially when you consider
that it was just over a week ago that the Celtics scored 67 points
in an entire game. But that dose of the NBA's golden age _
generally recognized as the 1980s _ wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the situation we were in, we played very well,'' Pitino
said. ``It's just that they're a much better basketball team. We
played them tough, but we ran out of players and gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Pierce was one of the available players. He sat for a total
of four minutes. When he wasn't sitting, he was resetting his
career highs in points (30) and assists (6). He also had 12
rebounds. When the Celtics weren't looking to him, they went to
Vitaly Potapenko. The center promptly made Rik Smits look like an
inexperienced summer camper. Potapenko had 26 points and 16
rebounds and got Smits (4 points, four rebounds) into foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to keep most fans in their very expensive seats
beyond the third quarter, when the Pacers took control. It was even
enough to inspire Pitino to say, ``Having all these injuries is a
major plus for our basketball team'' because it allows players a
chance to see what Potapenko can do on offense. But there wasn't
enough talk and hope that would translate into a win.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics had their own fashion catwalk going at the end of
the bench, reminiscent of the Lost Celtics of 1996-97. Walker,
crutches by his side, still found time to talk trash with Jalen
Rose. Mercer tried to keep his back loose and Anderson stretched
out his right hamstring. On the court, the Celtics tried to run
with the older Pacers, but even that didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of works to our favor,'' Reggie Miller said of the
tempo, ``because we can spread out the floor and we've got a lot of
good shooters.''
</P>
<P>
   Based purely on the numbers, Miller is correct. He led seven
double-figure scorers with 23 points. Chris Mullin had 21, Dale
Davis had a double-double (10 points, 12 boards), and Antonio Davis
had 17 off the bench for Larry Bird, who is now 7-0 against his
former team. After the game, Pierce was asked if he thought the
Pacers were the best team the Celtics have played. He paused for
about two seconds and said yes. Potapenko was asked about the
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a choice but to play,'' he said. ``No one else
is going to play for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fans in the arena seemed to sense that attitude from the
hustling Celtics and jumped behind them. The building was a
different place (i.e. no boos). And those NBA fans watching the
telecast via TNT were probably impressed with the Boston effort.
But there was never any suspense about the winner and the loser. If
the Celtics' injuries linger, that most likely will be the case for
the rest of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 0045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
