<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      04-20 0619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: THE EDIFICE THAT PIERPONT MORGAN BUILT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The English art critic Roger Fry, who perplexed what might have
been a straightforward relationship with Pierpont Morgan, once
wrote that Americans ``have a desperate desire to get at real
things . . . they jump at enlightenment.'' Even so, Fry and his
fellow critic Bernard Berenson had deeply ambivalent feelings about
Morgan and his art collecting, feelings that had as much to do with
commerce _ the marketing of art _ as they did with esthetics.
Berenson, being as kind as he was able, could only say, ``It seems
Morgan's desire now is to re-value the masterpieces of Italian art.
The worst of it is he will succeed. The fact that he liked a
picture will probably be remembered for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Remembered, of course. Morgan will never be just a line in the
provenance of a painting or illuminated manuscript. He was too
dominant, too omnivorous a collector for that. But beyond some
threshold in time, which we have already crossed, the fact that
Pierpont Morgan liked a picture tells us something meaningful only
about Morgan and his era, and not about the picture. His influence
has been almost wholly absorbed, and his collections have long
since become the foundation on which other collections were built.
The marketplace itself has blurred his significance, if only
because we now attribute the Fragonards at the Frick Collection,
for instance, to the eye of Henry Clay Frick and not to Morgan, who
bought them for his London house in 1897.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Strouse's impressive new biography of Morgan reassembles
the separate dimensions of Pierpont Morgan. When added together,
those dimensions make a man who is still as large as history. But
with one exception, Morgan's artistic holdings have been as widely
dispersed as his financial holdings. That exception, of course, is
the Pierpont Morgan Library in Manhattan, which was completed in
1906. Morgan used it for only seven years before his death in 1913,
but he spent so much time there that it came to be known to his
business partners as the uptown branch of J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co., which
was located at 23 Wall Street. When he died, it was still Morgan's
library, but 75 years ago this spring it was chartered, according
to his wishes, as a public institution _ given, that is, by his son
to the City of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Even 20 years ago, when I worked there, you could still feel
among some of the staff at the Morgan Library an air of family
retainership, though the last direct link with Morgan _ his
flamboyant librarian, Belle da Costa Greene _ died in 1948. The
library is now decidedly a public edifice, and as it has expanded,
it has nearly encircled the original building designed by Charles
McKim. But if you stand on 36th Street, halfway between Madison and
Park avenues, and consider only the library Morgan knew, or wander
through its interior, from the West Room _ Morgan's study _ across
the Rotunda and into the East Room, you can see that in this place
Morgan disguised his towering energy with a uniquely scholarly
serenity, the atmosphere of a very different life than the one he
actually lived.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Fry was right. Americans do have a desperate desire to get
at real things. As Ms. Strouse observes, Pierpont Morgan always
believed he was acting in the best interests of this nation,
whether he was consolidating railroads or helping to retire the
Civil War debt. Given the pressure of his business and the sheer
number of real things that Morgan collected, he could not have
known many of his books and manuscripts intimately. That is a task
he left to his successors, who are us. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
