<SLUG> BC-PAT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL DELEGATION SEES FAILURE, TRAGEDY ON KOSOVO TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Washington) _ After a weekend visit to the region surrounding
war-ravaged Kosovo, Republican Sen. Pat Roberts of Kansas said
Monday that he saw mostly failure and heartbreak.
</P>
<P>
   Failure was seeing that the bombing of Serbia has achieved none
of NATO's goals, including an end to the killing and deportation of
Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   Heartbreak was meeting Kosovo refugees, like a 12-year-old boy
and his 2-year-old sister who were forced from their homes by
police in ski masks and separated from their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``When asked what he needed, he said a shower and some medicine
for his sister's sore throat,'' Roberts said. ``People were
standing in line for four hours for an apple, a half-loaf of bread
and some tuna fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty members of Congress made the trip, including Rep. Karen
McCarthy, a Missouri Democrat from Kansas City, and Sen. Sam
Brownback, a Kansas Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts expects Congress this week to support President
Clinton's request for $6 billion for military and relief supplies
and that Republicans will seek more money to pay for supplies and
equipment obtained from other countries.
</P>
<P>
   He supports both expenditures but does not favor use of NATO
ground forces unless their mission is clear. As a former Marine,
Roberts said he thinks a military campaign can't succeed without
both air and ground attacks.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy and Brownback also voiced concern Monday about the
Serbian campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy wondered if Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic could
be deterred in his quest to rout ethnic Albanians from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest with you, I'm not sure that this man is rational
at this point or if air strikes alone will work,'' McCarthy told
federal union workers at the Bolling Federal Building in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope within the next few days or a week or two, we can have
a better sense of the engagement that will be necessary to bring a
halt to the ethnic cleansing and the fatalities going on in that
region,'' McCarthy said.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback told students at Shawnee Mission East High School in
Prairie Village he opposes sending U.S. troops into combat in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see is the potential of us getting involved in a
long-term, very difficult and costly conflict with a great deal of
U.S. bloodshed,'' he said. Troops should only be used as a
peace-keeping force in a negotiated settlement, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said that despite the problems so far, he and the other
delegates agreed that NATO has to see it through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no alternative but to escalate the air campaign and
hope and pray it's successful,'' said Roberts, a member of Senate
committees on armed services and intelligence. ``Quite frankly, I
have serious doubts.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO has failed in its goal of stopping the killing and
deportation of ethnic Albanians, Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of those objectives have gone sour,'' said Roberts, who
went from military briefing rooms to muddy fields of refugees. ``In
my view, the situation is worse in each and every case.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said the chief goal should be removing Milosevic from
power and putting him on trial as a war criminal. Only that would
bring a reasonably quick end to the atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can kill this snake one inch at a time or we can do it with
one blow,'' Roberts said. ``The American people need to be told
there will be no refugees returned as long as Milosevic and the
Serbs remain in power.''
</P>
<P>
   As NATO and the United States continued to say that air power
would succeed, Roberts said the Serbian campaign was ill-advised
and remains flawed in that it is being overseen by NATO rather than
by the military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the targets are being selected by the 19 nations of
NATO,'' he said. But NATO is now so involved that to back off the
air campaign would undermine the credibility of NATO and the United
States, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brownback, Roberts and U.S. Sens. Kit Bond and John Ashcroft of
Missouri, also Republicans, voted last month against starting the
NATO bombing. Bond and Ashcroft continue to question the purpose
and direction of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said that seeing 20,000 of the Kosovo refugees in
Macedonia was ``a paradox of enormous irony'' because of the
setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``A beautiful spring day, snowcapped mountains, green valleys
and human tragedy,'' Roberts said. ``Tent after tent (was) swollen
with broken and anguished families. The night before, there was
four inches of rain and some people slept in cold and water.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said he talked to an elderly man wearing a stocking hat
and a pair of shoes he retrieved from a dead friend. Serbs took his
life savings of 50 marks, burned his home and killed his friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``With fierce determination,'' Roberts said, ``he grabbed me by
the shoulders, and said, we believe in God, we believe in NATO and
we believe in America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
