<SLUG> BC-COMDEX-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER TRADE SHOW THIS YEAR IS LESS COMPUTER, MORE NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Chicago) _ If there is any question about how much the Internet
is changing our lives, the answer lies here at Comdex.
</P>
<P>
   The world's largest technology and computer trade show isn't
anymore. It's still big, all right. But it's become the world's
largest (begin ital)Internet(end ital.) and technology trade show.
Computers? Well, they must be around here (begin
ital.)somewhere(end ital.).
</P>
<P>
   In fact, only a couple of computer makers even bothered to buy
booth space at Comdex Spring '99, which is expected to draw 80,000
computer professionals this week.
</P>
<P>
   The word ``eBay,'' the popular online auction site, is being
thrown around a lot more than ``Compaq,'' ``Dell'' and ``Gateway''
put together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PC industry is seeing the focus move away from it and more
toward the Internet,'' said Aaron Goldberg, principal analyst for
Ziff-Davis, the computer magazine publisher that organizes and runs
the Comdex show.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to look far to see how much that focus has
changed.
</P>
<P>
   IBM isn't showing off computers here. But IBM subsidiary
Catapult is showing off the latest version of its online employee
training system. Gateway didn't buy booth space, but online career
site Hotjobs.com did.
</P>
<P>
   Even Microsoft is getting in on the action. The world's largest
software company is using Comdex to promote a new computer mouse
design. Among the improvements? The mouse has extra buttons to make
Web browsing easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is the emergence of the software companies
as the big dog and the hardware companies as the tail on the dog,''
said Howard Anderson, managing director of the Yankee Group, a
Boston market research firm.
</P>
<P>
   So what hardware will consumers buy to get on the Net?
</P>
<P>
   Anderson predicted that by 2003 non-PC devices _ anything from
smart telephones to television set-top devices to small hand-held
devices _ would outnumber PCs on the Net. Currently, about 99
percent of Net access comes from PCs.
</P>
<P>
   But if the computer, er, Internet industry can't make money off
computers, where will the profit come from?
</P>
<P>
   ``Follow the money,'' Anderson told industry analysts and
reporters in an early morning briefing.
</P>
<P>
   And in this case, ``money'' is spelled ``e-commerce,'' the
industry's term for business done over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Geeks who used to brag about the speed of their microprocessor
and attend Comdex to see the latest hard drive now are attending
sessions on ``E-commerce technology options'' and ``Commerce,
creating a direct selling site.''
</P>
<P>
   ``E-commerce will permeate what every vendor on the floor you
see today is doing,'' said Clay Ryder, chief analyst for Zona
Research
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, just about everywhere you look in the sprawling
McCormick Place convention hall you see the e-word.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've heard about e-commerce, you've read about e-business,''
boasts Snickelways Interactive of New York. ``Now experience
e-profit.''
</P>
<P>
   At the door to the theater where Bill Gates, Microsoft's
chairman, delivered a keynote address Monday morning, /{Forbes/}
gave away copies of its April 19 magazine with the cover story:
``Getting rich at the speed of light.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Gates, whose company shunned the Internet during its early
growth years hoping to create a network of its own, gave homage to
its growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last year has been a year of incredible change,'' Gates
said in his speech, which drew an overflow crowd of more than
6,000, including some who lined up 2 1/2 hours early to get good
seats.
</P>
<P>
   But Gates noted that the PC industry was far from dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, over 100 million new PCs will be sold,'' Gates
said. ``It's a pretty amazing number when you think that every year
for the last five or six years people have said: `Well, this is the
peak, this is the most that could possibly ever be sold. We'll get
no more home penetration, no more business penetration.' And yet,
we go from record to record.''
</P>
<P>
   Growth will come in nontraditional devices that people will use
to get on the Net or to make their lives easier in other ways,
Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   In his 50-minute talk Gates focused not only on how important
the Internet has become but also on how important it (begin
ital.)will(end ital.) become.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, for a lot of us here, we're already using the Internet
every day,'' Gates said. ``It's common sense that when we want to
buy things, when we want to organize a trip, we go out there to the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft chairman gave a 20-minute sales pitch for the
company's next computer operating system, Windows 2000. The system
is being tested now and is expected to be available next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Windows 2000 represents the biggest investment we ever made in
a Windows product,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   Gates and several Microsoft employees are in Chicago for Windows
World, a trade show that runs concurrently with Comdex.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, another operating system, Linux, is
challenging the Microsoft flagship product. Perhaps because of
that, Microsoft is running workshops at Windows World showing how
Microsoft products can do everything from protecting Web users'
privacy to helping them live a full ``Web lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   The buzz around the trade floor is focusing on Linus Torvalds,
the developer of the Linux system. Although Linux has been around
since 1991, industry analysts said it now has enough support for at
least a small challenge to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Linux has 10 million users and accounted for more than 17
percent of all computer-server operating-system shipments last
year, according to International Data Corp., a research firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
