<SLUG> BC-ROYCOM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING AND BASEBALL: A GROWING CONNECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE ROCK  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Kansas City, Mo.) _ Imagine this scene on a warm spring night
in Kansas City's future:
</P>
<P>
   Some 25,000 fans are settling in as the sun casts a glow against
(begin ital.)Kauffman Stadium at Sprint Park(end ital.). It's Gates
Barbecue Night, and leadoff hitter Carlos Beltran _ his uniform
tinged with the colors of H&AMP;R Block's corporate logo _ gets the
fans going with a home run to left field. The ball doinks off the
outfield foul pole, a pillar shaped and painted like a pencil that
doubles as advertising for Office Depot.
</P>
<P>
   Beltran trots back to the dugout, disappearing under the Harley
Davidson logos emblazoned on the top.
</P>
<P>
   This scenario _ hypothetical and exaggerated _ could never
happen in this town, right? Think again.
</P>
<P>
   It's a growing trend in the world of professional baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Prentice, the would-be buyer of the Royals who is awaiting
the approval of Major League Baseball, is not a man of Ewing
Kauffman-type wealth. Already, he has made clear his intentions of
increasing advertising revenues at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Prentice, who says money-making tactics are ``just limited by
imagination,'' will explore the idea of attaching a corporate
identity to the name of the stadium in exchange for a healthy
paycheck. Billboards will likely become more prevalent as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go out to my ballpark in Midland, there are signs
wherever it's tastefully possible to put signs,'' said Prentice,
who owns a Class AA minor-league baseball team in Midland, Texas.
``That's a source of revenue we have to tap into.''
</P>
<P>
   As player salaries skyrocket out of control, teams are exploring
all possible avenues of making a buck. A few examples:
</P>
<P>
   _ Half of the league's 30 teams already have naming-rights
agreements.
</P>
<P>
   _ The pencil-shaped foul pole is no joke. The left-field pole at
Pro Player Stadium in south Florida, complete with fake lead tip,
also serves as advertising.
</P>
<P>
   _ League officials have, in recent months, even toyed with the
idea of putting corporate logos on player uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals have been pursuing more and different ways to
increase revenues since Kauffman's death in 1993. But this is still
foreign ground for longtime fans, the ones who remember Royals
Stadium and its tri-vision advertising boards _ which fit snugly
into the outfield water spectacular _ but little else in terms of
commercial intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Kauffman didn't want any advertising,'' said Royals' then-
and now- general manager Herk Robinson. ``If we went up to him and
said, `Mr. Kauffman, we can gross an additional $20,000 by putting
a big sign in left field,' he'd say, `Heck, no. This is a beautiful
stadium. I'll (begin ital.)give(end ital.) you the $20,000.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, it's not like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The outfield fence is now decorated with ads for Pepsi, Bud
Light and Price Chopper. A Ford ad peeks over the left-field wall,
joined by Master Card in right field. Viewers watching the game on
TV are fed a steady diet of rotating ads behind home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Royals officials won't disclose specifics of advertising
revenues. Since 1994, though, the team has tripled its input and
now makes millions _ though less than $10 million _ in advertising
and sponsorship revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those dollars add up,'' Royals vice president Mike Levy said.
``It spells business. You just can't get around it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Prentice suggests that the amount of untapped advertising
revenue at Kauffman Stadium is ``upwards of $5 million, easily.''
</P>
<P>
   A year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal,'' Prentice said, ``is to try to increase it by a
healthy number each year that would be north of $500,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there are unused advertising avenues at the stadium.
Although Major League Baseball prohibits signage along the outfield
wall in dead center, gaping holes still exist that could command
six-figure billboard deals. And the current regime has found
advertising dollars in unlikely places.
</P>
<P>
   An example: This season, for the first time, an ad for Farmland
Industries is embedded in the grass beyond the left-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the Royals have resisted the temptation to open up the
dugouts to corporate logos. As Levy said, ``There are certain
sacred spots on a baseball field.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Houston Astros have displayed advertisements on the
inside back wall of their dugouts, just above players' heads, since
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to have a lot more advertising,'' Prentice said.
``Perhaps it won't be (on the dugouts). I have a sneaking suspicion
it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the enormous revenue potential from a naming rights
deal.
</P>
<P>
   When Detroit's Comerica Park opens next season, for example, it
will do so with an agreement that Comerica Inc. will write $66
million worth of checks in the next 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, that's an option we would hope to look at,''
Prentice said. ``But we haven't gone down that road at all.''
</P>
<P>
   One potential stumbling block, of course, is public reception to
renaming the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kauffman is the reason the Royals are here today,'' said J.T.
DeWitt, a fan from North Kansas City who attended Monday's game
with his wife and two children. ``I think the name should stay the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in today's world, it's probably a necessary evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, fans in Kansas City remember the Kauffman name with a
bit of reverence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be very respectful of that,'' Prentice said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint spokeswoman Laura Meyer said the company was approached
at least once, ``way back when they were looking for buyers for the
Royals,'' about any naming-rights interest but expressed none. As
for now, Meyer said, Sprint is probably not considering it.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hall, a local civic leader and assistant to the chairman of
Hallmark Cards Inc., said his company also would have no interest
in attaching its name to the stadium. And he understands the
affinity that Kansas Citians have for the Kauffman name.
</P>
<P>
   But...
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very difficult issue because of Mr. Kauffman and all
he did here,'' he said. ``On the other hand, our biggest issue is
how to keep the team here. And right now, the biggest problem we
have is revenue. Mr. Kauffman would be in favor of doing whatever
it took to keep the team in Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the question of who would get the money from a
naming-rights deal. Would it go to the owner of the team, a la
Prentice, or the owner of the stadium?
</P>
<P>
   The Royals pay annual rent of $450,000 to the Jackson County
Sports Complex Authority, the agency charged with overseeing both
Kauffman and Arrowhead stadiums. Jackson County owns both
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would suspect that the money would go to the county,'' said
John Friedmann, executive director of the authority. ``In turn, it
would end up with the team because the county would make
improvements at the complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, to my knowledge, that question has never been discussed
with the authority.''
</P>
<P>
   That, both sides agree, is a discussion for another time. Until
then, Prentice will continue to explore that and other potential
sources of revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at it from a fan's point of view,'' Prentice said.
``But I'm also looking at it from an investor's point of view. I'm
looking at the team's long-term viability.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
