r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCKETDYNE-HEATLH-LAD     04-20 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKETDYNE-HEATLH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE BUILDS FOR NEW STUDY ON ROCKETDYNE FIELD LAB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA MASCARO AND TERRI HARDY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. _ Legislative pressure intensified Monday on
the state Department of Health Services over its handling of health
concerns linked to rocket fuel and radioactive material research
conducted at Rocketdyne's Santa Susana Field Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Several legislators said they would push for funding of a
long-sought community health study that won legislative approval
last year but was vetoed by Gov. Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   And Assemblywoman Sheila Kuehl, D-Encino, accused the department
of being so cozy with the company that it withheld critical
information and worked against a community advisory panel
overseeing a worker health study at the 50-year-old facility in the
hills between Chatsworth and Simi Valley northwest of downtown L.A.
</P>
<P>
   The state agency officials ``weren't interested in people's
health. They were protecting (Rocketdyne),'' said Kuehl, who last
week released a more than year-old study that had found high
incidences of lung cancer among residents living in neighborhoods
around the lab.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, researchers at the University of California, Los
Angeles, released the second part of their worker health study,
showing unusually high rates of cancer among Rocketdyne workers who
had contact with the toxic chemical hydrazine, used in rocket fuel.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials defended their role, as did Rocketdyne
officials, saying they have established an unprecedented forum for
public input into the UCLA work, and have been working to secure
the best possible public health study of workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our department does not obstruct or work to obstruct the
results of the studies,'' said Dr. Robert Harrison, chief of the
Occupational Health Surveillance and Evaluation branch of the
department, which has been overseeing the UCLA study of Rocketdyne
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I would point to the record,'' Harrison said. ``We
have, I think through all those steps, ensured we had the best
science that would be free from influences from the company.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance of the health department will come under
scrutiny today in the Joint Legislative Audit Committee, which is
expected to call for a full investigation of the agency's handling
of tobacco-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   Rocketdyne spokesman Dan Beck said the company's record is clear
about operations at Santa Susana. It wants to get answers for its
workers and neighbors, and has not put undue control over the
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a cozy relationship between Rocketdyne and DHS,''
said Beck. ``I reiterate the fact _ that there is ... a close
relationship between DHS and Rocketdyne is inaccurate. It's just
not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns over health hazards at the 2,600-acre field lab were
first raised in 1989 when the Daily News reported that toxic
contamination was found in soil at the facility.
</P>
<P>
   A massive federal cleanup of the site is now under way, and the
Department of Energy last year awarded the facility's new owners,
Boeing, a $148.5 million contract to complete cleanup work by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA's initial worker health study, released in 1997, showed
higher cancer rates among employees exposed to radiation at the
lab, which no longer conducts nuclear research.
</P>
<P>
   Residents and community activists have pressed for a health
study of surrounding residential areas, which they had been told in
the early 1990s would be considered if a worker study showed health
problems among employees at the lab that conducted rocket and
nuclear testing for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a commitment that was made,'' said state Sen. Cathie
Wright, R-Simi Valley, who was among a trio of local legislators
who helped secure the UCLA study and the community advisory panel
that has been monitoring the research.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said the health department had successfully urged Gov.
Wilson last year to veto $150,000 in funding for the community
health feasibility study. She said Gov. Gray Davis has put the
renewed funding request in his upcoming budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to end this issue and put it to bed, and it's
done and over with, then (they need) to go forward with the next
step,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   DHS officials did not return phone calls for comment on whether
the department had played a role in vetoing the funds last year.
</P>
<P>
   Wright added that Rocketdyne, which has questioned the UCLA
study and pledged to conduct its own series of worker and community
studies, should allow a community study without company influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've lost the support of the community when it took all
this time to get to this point,'' Wright said. ``It would have to
be independent from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocketdyne said they supported calls for a community study, and
only want to be assured they have ``a place at the table,'' Beck
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our facility, our employees,'' said Beck, adding that the
community residents are its neighbors. ``We should be a part of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Tom McClintock, R-Granada Hills, called on the
Legislature to consider urgency funding that would bypass the
traditional budget sessions now under way in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Health Services has estimated that the next
step, which would determine how to proceed with a community health
study, would cost $300,000 more than is earmarked in Davis' budget.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein, who also has been working with
federal agencies to resolve questions about the health of workers
and residents living near the field lab, said Monday that recent
developments have only heightened her concerns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
