</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS GET WELL AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Cocky, confident, egotistical. Those were the Lakers
of February.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate. Deflated. Those were the Lakers who returned to the
Forum on Monday _ a three-game losing streak hanging over them like
a thick, brown haze over the San Fernando Valley in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Nine games to go in a season teetering on the edge of disaster,
the Lakers needed something, anything to boost their self-esteem,
if not their playoff seeding.
</P>
<P>
   Desperation? Yes, Kobe Bryant admitted, the Lakers felt it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't wanna drop three in a row, you don't wanna drop four
in a row,'' Bryant said before the Lakers avoided a season-worst
losing streak with a 117-102 victory over Vancouver. ``Right now,
because we only have nine games left, you definitely want to get
this win. We've got three tough games coming up (at Portland, San
Antonio and Houston).''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off double-digit losses at Utah and Portland, the Lakers
figured to be due for a blowout of their own against the Grizzlies,
who had just one win in 20 road games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Lakers trailed at halftime 60-56, their flowing
offense offset by yet another defensive disaster. Vancouver shot 56
percent in the first half, led by offensive outbursts from the
likes of Tony Massenburg and Felipe Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   It took coach Kurt Rambis busting up a white, plastic clipboard
during a third-quarter timeout and a solid round of boos from the
home crowd before the Lakers put together a solid run.
</P>
<P>
   Down by six points late in the third, the Lakers put together a
9-2 run _ with seven points from rookies Tyronn Lue and Ruben
Patterson _ to take an 81-80 lead heading into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The expected rout wasn't far behind. The Lakers opened the
fourth with a 15-4 run, led by Shaquille O'Neal and Patterson, to
increase the lead to 12. The stubborn Grizzlies, who already upset
the Lakers in Vancouver earlier this year, clawed their way back.
With Lopez and Massenburg again leading the charge, they cut the
lead to 98-94 with 4:07 to go.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal and Glen Rice started another run and held off
Vancouver's final charge.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal finished with a game-high 35 points. Rice added 18, and
Bryant and Robert Horry added 17 each. Lue scored a career-high 15,
capped by a couple of gutty drives to the hoop (he was fouled both
times) late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Massenburg led Vancouver with 28. Lopez finished with 23.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's 16-point loss at Utah, the Lakers took Sunday
off to clear their heads. It was a welcome mental break, Bryant
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to get away from things a little bit, just
think about things, think about individually what we all can do to
get this thing back together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's relaxed, instead of being all uptight,'' Bryant
said. ``You have no choice but to be uptight under the
circumstances, because you're only human. But it's how you get used
to it and how quickly you get out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The only thing left to do was erase all memories of the prior
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, but you have to do it,'' he said. ``That's
something that we've kind of been doing all year. And as the year
went on, we found ourselves getting better at it, because you don't
have a choice. That's what you have to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 0134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
