A5312 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     04-20 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS OUTCLASSED BY BRAVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Forget about the postseason failures that will
always be the asterisk on the Atlanta resume. When the rest of the
National League wants a barometer, they measure themselves with the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson spoke of that. So did general
manager Kevin Malone.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Dodgers' first chance to measure themselves produced
nothing but raised eyebrows and loads of head-shaking. They didn't
even do enough to gain consideration of being a notch on the
Braves' measuring stick, bowing 11-3 in a gruesome display Monday
night at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (7-7) have lost three of four, and were taken to
task by Braves right-hander John Smoltz in the opener of the
three-game series. Each of Atlanta's starters had at least one hit
as the Braves pounded out 18 hits for the game.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Raul Mondesi homered for the Dodgers, his
league-leading sixth of the season. Todd Hundley and Dave Hansen
also hit solo homers for L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dodgers starter Carlos Perez never gave Johnson a
chance to show confidence in the lefty into the seventh inning,
where he'd given up four runs in each of his first two starts. The
train wreck came much earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Perez didn't make it out of the fourth inning, giving up six
runs on eight hits in 32/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Robinson Checo, the middle reliever the Dodgers
received from Detroit in the Dave Mlicki trade Friday, had an
equally rough time in his debut, getting tagged for five runs on
eight hits in 31/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Let's put it this way: The Dodgers' Eric Young led off the first
with a single, stole second, moved to third on a pop out and stayed
there. It was an extension of the Dodgers' weekend series in San
Diego, when they went 3 for 24 with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   And against Smoltz (2-0), there aren't many chances to be had.
Heck, he is so good he can even hit. It was his single over
shortstop in the second inning that scored to start the onslaught.
It scored two runs and gave the Braves a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   An inning later Chipper Jones, who left the game in the sixth
with a rib cage strain, hit a solo homer and Perez began to
unravel. He walked Andruw Jones, balked him to second and then
threw a pickoff attempt into center field to move the runner to
third. Jones scored on Brian Hunter's single.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves knocked Perez (0-3) out in the fourth by stringing
together three hits with two outs. It began with Bret Boone's
infield single. Jones walked and Brian Jordan smacked a two-run
double to left, pushing Atlanta's lead to 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're an improved ballclub,'' Johnson said before
the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are hoping Checo could be their long reliever, and
to do that he must build arm strength. When he arrived in the
clubhouse in San Diego during the weekend, he said his arm was
strong enough to pitch two or three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson put that theory to the test, opting not to burn out the
bullpen. Checo breezed through his first 11/3 innings before
Atlanta's lineup got to him.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves pushed their lead to 8-0 in the sixth when Boone hit
a two-run homer to right field.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, it wasn't pretty, but it got worse in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter singled to lead off the eighth and scored on Walt Weiss'
triple into the right-field corner. Gerald Williams then doubled
and scored on Boone's single to give the Braves an 11-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing the game did was afford Johnson the
opportunity to rest some of his starters. When the eighth inning
began, Tripp Cromer was in left, Jacob Brumfield in center, Jose
Vizcaino at second, Hansen at first and Rick Wilkins behind the
plate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
