<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5318 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SONICS-HN     04-20 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-SONICS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
By the second quarter, with another lead slipping away, Rockets
coach Rudy Tomjanovich called time out, looked away and
half-sighed, half-griped, ``Here we go.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the fourth quarter, SuperSonics coach Paul Westphal was
talking not about the Rockets on the other end of the Compaq Center
court but of the team 200 miles down I-10.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets had blown most of another lead Monday night, and if
they refused to feel the pressure and horror of a recurring
nightmare, Seattle had visions of a Sunday in San Antonio to spur
it.
</P>
<P>
   This time, however, there was no way the Rockets would permit
another rival to catch and crush them. Having vowed not to relive
that feeling, Charles Barkley took over, and the Rockets finally
put away the SuperSonics 120-113.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all NBA games, teams are going make a run,'' said Sam Mack,
who gave the Rockets 21 points on seven 3-pointers. ``The key is
keeping composure. It's how you handle it. In San Antonio, they
made their run, and we didn't handle it well at all. We did pretty
well with it tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets were, however, far from perfect. They led by as many
as 16 in the second quarter. By the third, the lead was down to
five.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets pushed it to 15 in the fourth. But with less than
three minutes left, and with the Sonics' Dale Ellis and Detlef
Schrempf matching Mack trey for trey, the edge was down to four.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what happened in San Antonio,'' Westphal said. ``I
kept urging my guys to keep coming at them. I reminded them about
that. Plus, I coached Charles. I know he doesn't play as well with
a big lead.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Gary Payton and, of all people, Olden Polynice taunting
him with whatever they could come up with, Barkley stepped up.
</P>
<P>
   With the game on the line, Barkley had his hands on every
Rockets point for eight minutes. He passed outside either for 3s or
to the shot left open by the SuperSonics' double teams inside. He
sent passes downcourt for fast breaks. And with the Sonics
sufficiently burned by the post-and-pass part of the Rockets'
offense to call off their double teams and leave Polynice alone on
Barkley inside, Barkley destroyed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's pretty much our normal philosophy, isn't it?''
Barkley said. ``If they double me, I'm going to pass it. If they
don't double me, I'm going to go one-on-one. It's simple
basketball. I don't try to do too much. Bad players worry about
their numbers and averages. I try to take what the defense gives
me. I know how to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics' defense gave Barkley _ or he took _ pretty much
whatever he wanted. With the Rockets leading by nine, 92-83, he
scored their next 10 points, nailing a jumper, scoring on three
drives to the basket and forcing Polynice to foul him on yet
another move too quick to stop.
</P>
<P>
   His free throws gave the Rockets a 15-point lead. And even when
the Sonics closed within seven, Barkley took over again. He drove
to a four-footer and, when the Sonics went back to the double
teams, passed to Mack for another 3 and a 10-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barkley was sensational,'' Westphal said. ``He picked us apart
with his passes when we doubled him and with his shots when we
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley finished with 25 points, 10 rebounds and seven assists.
And he and Mack were just two of four Rockets to top 20 points in
the team's highest output of the season. Hakeem Olajuwon had 24,
and Scottie Pippen totaled 22 with 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But even with the SuperSonics playing without starters Vin Baker
and Billy Owens, that was almost not enough.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rockets have yet to master protecting a lead, Tomjanovich
was ready to settle for the hope that the concept might be about to
take hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always sort of feel like that,'' he said. ``You always feel
that this is the day we're going to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with the lead back to double digits, 114-104, on Mack's
seventh 3-pointer with 1:48 left, the Rockets had to sweat out the
remaining moments. Schrempf hit a 3, and after an Olajuwon layup,
Payton drove for a layup that cut the margin to seven and gave him
23 points, 21 in the second half, to go with 15 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Cuttino Mobley missed a 3 for the Rockets, and when Ellis beat
the Rockets down the floor for an uncontested layup, the difference
was down to 116-111 with 1:04 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we've been in that situation, we continue to
panic,'' Olajuwon lamented. ``We were lucky making the big shot.
Yesterday's last shot (for the Rockets) rolled in and rolled out.
And that was the difference in the game. That's just tough luck.
Today, the shots went in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets did at least handle the last minute efficiently,
setting up Olajuwon for a dunk and, after Seattle's Don MacLean
missed consecutive 3s, a short jumper.
</P>
<P>
   And if they weren't quite giddy with a win they had to have, the
Rockets celebrated with a sigh of relief, having so recently
experienced the alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday was a devastating loss for us,'' Pippen said. ``We
had a team down (23) points. We allowed them to get back too fast.
I don't see us handling it better. I think we get by at times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to realize it's our defense. We let (the Sonics) score
68 points in the second half. You're not going to win too many
games (like that).''
</P>
<P>
   They got by on Monday, enough to leave Sunday behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
