<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5319 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     04-20 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WITH about six minutes left in the night when the NBA became an
honest-to-goodness entertainment product again, all Charles Barkley
needed was a pair of hip waders.
</P>
<P>
   He had spent the opening half of the fourth quarter baiting the
hook for Olden Polynice, spinning by him down on the left baseline
and coming out on the other side of the hoop for easy baskets or
wheeling across the lane and dropping in a soft fadeaway over those
long, outstretched arms.
</P>
<P>
   Now as the two teams returned to the floor from a timeout, Sir
Charles stood at midcourt, casting an imaginary fishing line in
Polynice's direction and smiling broadly while slowly reeling in
the big lunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Olden was talking a lot out there,'' Barkley said. ``The first
time I went by him, he said I took advantage of him because he
wasn't loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the fourth time I went by him, I turned around and asked
him, `Are you loose yet?'''
</P>
<P>
   Call this one: A River Runs Through It.
</P>
<P>
   Not just in honor of Polynice's defense, which was like trying
to catch water in a net. But for the way the Rockets and Sonics
tore up and down the floor on offense, spilling over the banks like
a spring flood, leaving the Laptop chimney deep in points.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't know better, you might have thought you had
stepped into a time machine and been spat out in the '70s. You
expected to see bell bottoms and long sideburns and platform shoes
and hot pants.
</P>
<P>
   Surely, this couldn't be the modern NBA, where conservative
philosophies are too often passed off as great defense, where teams
hang on to the ball as if it were a miser's last dollar.
</P>
<P>
   There was running and shooting, plenty of it. About the only
things missing were Dr. J and Darnell Hillman and those
reach-for-the-moon Afros and the old red, white and blue ABA ball.
</P>
<P>
   In an ugly, ugly season, one in which the Chicago Bulls once
managed just 49 points and most teams couldn't drop the ball in the
basket if you sat them on the back of the rim, the Rockets beat the
Sonics 120-113.
</P>
<P>
   And to continue the nostalgia theme, 36-year-old Charles Barkley
again turned back the clock and played like a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   This time it was 25 points, 10 rebounds and seven assists that
told the tale in the final box score. But to more closely
appreciate those numbers, you had to see the way he compiled them _
with quick moves, fancy steps and a grin he has been wearing lately
as a permanent part of his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really just about being healthy and able to do a lot of
the old things like I used to,'' Barkley said. ``You won't hear me
going around saying that I'm back to the peak days of my career.
But there are times, there are moves when I know that my body is
strong and ready and I can do whatever I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off another collapse in San Antonio on Sunday, this was a
time when the Rockets had to jump right back into the pool full of
confidence and energy to show there were no lingering scars. They
did it with Scottie Pippen setting the pace with a 12-point first
quarter on his way to 22, plus 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   They did it with Hakeem Olajuwon posting 24 points and nine
rebounds and passing Jerry West to move into 11th place on the
all-time scoring list. They did it with Sam Mack stroking in seven
treys on his way to 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, and every time they needed a really big play,
they did it because Barkley was able to do it. Because after
suffering for more than a year with a hernia he sustained in March
1997, he was finally able to get back in shape and start the season
ready to take charge again. And even after he was sidelined for two
weeks this season after arthroscopic surgery on his knee, he has
regained his edge and his spark.
</P>
<P>
   He was like a cat toying with a mouse he plans to eat for supper
against the Sonics. When they committed themselves to coming at him
in the low block with the double team, he calmly zipped passes back
outside to Mack or Cuttino Mobley to nail 3s. When Seattle tried to
play him one-on-one, he simply spun like a buzz saw and chewed the
Sonics up with baseline moves.
</P>
<P>
   He can't do the things he did in Philly in the '80s or in
Phoenix in the early '90s. But he can still do the things to beat
you.
</P>
<P>
   Like shove aside Detlef Schrempf when the Sonics cut the lead to
108-104 to get a key offensive rebound and convert a critical
three-point play with two minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to talk about him as MVP,'' said coach Rudy
Tomjanovich. ``I think so.''
</P>
<P>
   He was challenged by his buddy Michael Jordan to get into shape,
and he has had his fuse lit by the enthusiasm of playing with
teammates he truly likes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thrilled to be back in shape,'' he said. ``I just
wanted to be able to say I had fun at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   And could still land the big one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
