<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5320 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NETS-HORNETS-NYT &LR;      04-20 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-HORNETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORNETS BEAT NETS,120-113 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ After meeting with Jayson Williams for
the first time since he suffered his season-ending leg injury, the
New Jersey Nets played with the vigor and the resolve that their
inspirational leader always displayed. But the spirit of Williams
was not enough against the rejuvenated Charlotte Hornets, who shot
down the hustling Nets to win by 120-113 on Monday night at
Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   With Williams, who broke his right leg on April 1, watching from
the stands, the Hornets made 59 percent of their field goal
attempts, including 11 of 21 3-pointers, to torch a Nets defense
that was high on energy but low on effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the Hornets' 3-pointers, including three by Chuck
Person, came in the fourth quarter, when Charlotte staved off a
Nets rally that saw them cut a 13-point third-quarter deficit to 1.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the eighth straight for Charlotte (20-20) and
moved it within one-half game of Cleveland (21-20) for the final
playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. It also officially
eliminated the Nets (12-29) from playoff contention, though that
had been a foregone conclusion since March.
</P>
<P>
   Though disappointed with the loss, the Nets were glad they put
forth a solid effort in front of Williams. ``I'm almost positive
that Jayson's happy with the way that guys aren't laying down,''
said Stephon Marbury, who had team highs of 27 points and 13
assists. ``Because he's the type of guy that wouldn't lay down, and
he goes out and gives 110 percent, and I think he can see that
we're playing the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Phills led Charlotte with 23 points, Elden Campbell added
22 and Person scored 16. Keith Van Horn followed Marbury with 26
points and 9 rebounds, Scott Burrell added 17 points, and Jamie
Feick, Williams' fill-in, scored a career-high 17 and matched his
career high in rebounds with 15.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who was injured in a collision with Marbury in a game
against the Atlanta Hawks, was his usual fun-loving self, despite
being in a wheelchair with his leg in a brace.
</P>
<P>
   He joked about everything, saying that his first thought after
being injured was getting up so as ``not to get stepped on by Mrs.
Marbury,'' who ran on the court to see if her son was all right.
</P>
<P>
   But the injury is no laughing matter. Dr. Russell Warren, the
orthopedist who performed the surgery, told Williams last Monday
that his chances of returning to the National Basketball
Association were ``hit or miss,'' said Sal DiFazio, Williams's
agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's worried,'' said DiFazio, who sat beside Williams, the
Nets' president, Michael Rowe, and General Manager John Nash at a
makeshift pre-game news conference in an arena corridor. ``But
Jayson's convinced in his mind that he will make it back. Dr.
Warren said hit or miss last week, but we spoke to him today and I
think was more hit than miss. What Warren told me was that this is
an injury that you see in motorcycle accidents, not on basketball
players. It was very unusual the way it happened because it
hyperextended, fractured and rotated all at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   The fracture in Williams' leg is 8 to 10 inches long and runs
from the knee cap down the tibia. He underwent four hours of
surgery on April 2, when bone was grafted from his hip to his leg
and five screws and a metal plate were inserted. He also had torn
cartilage repaired.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 31, will have to remain in a bed, in a wheelchair or
on crutches for 8 to 10 weeks. Six weeks after that, he could be
playing basketball. Williams said his goal is to be walking after
seven weeks and he has drawn encouragement from the fact that he is
a couple of weeks ahead of the doctor's schedule in terms of the
degree to which he can extend the leg.
</P>
</TEXT>
