<HEADER>
A5333 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-NYT &LR;      04-20 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE COMMISSIONER DEFENDS FRISKING POLICY BEFORE A PANEL OF
SKEPTICS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At a City Council hearing punctuated by testy
exchanges, Police Commissioner Howard Safir provided his most
detailed portrait yet of the department's Street Crime Unit on
Monday and defended the unit from allegations that it stops people
because of their race.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing _ which was called to scrutinize the unit after four
of its officers shot and killed Amadou Diallo on Feb. 4 _ centered
on discussions of race, police procedures and the department's
guidelines for stopping people and patting them down for weapons.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since the Diallo shooting _ and after many
refusals _ Safir gave the racial breakdown of the 362-member unit:
82 percent white, 3 percent black, 14 percent Hispanic and 1
percent Asian. Women make up 9 percent of the unit. Safir has said
that he plans to transfer 50 more minority officers to the unit,
which patrols many neighborhoods that are mostly black or Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon S. Leffler of Queens, the Democratic chairman of the
Council's Public Safety Committee, asked why steps were not taken
to increase the unit's racial diversity before the Diallo shooting.
He pointed to a July 1996 memorandum by Sandra M. Marsh, then the
department's deputy commissioner for equal employment opportunity,
urging the department to do something about the lack of women and
minority group members in four special units, including the Street
Crime Unit.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said that he had referred the memo to a subordinate.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that 50 street crime officers _ or 13.5 percent of
the current squad _ had fired their weapons before coming to the
unit. Seven were involved in fatal shootings, 10 in shootings that
caused injuries. Questions about the shooting history of the unit's
officers were raised because three of the four officers in the
Diallo killing had been in shootings before. Most officers on the
force never fire their guns.
</P>
<P>
   But much of the hearing centered on the department's tactics for
stopping and frisking people, which are the subject of state and
federal civil rights inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said an analysis of the reports filled out by officers who
stopped and frisked people had led him to believe that they did not
unfairly single out black and Hispanic people. But he said that the
number of reports filled out may not accurately represent the
number of people stopped and frisked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The racial and ethnic distribution of the subjects of
stop-and-frisk reports reflects the demographics of known violent
crime suspects as reported by crime victims,'' Safir said.
``Similarly, the demographics of arrestees in violent crimes also
correspond with the demographics of known violent crime suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   Several council members challenged him, saying that they
believed that members of minority groups were unfairly stopped.
Mary Pinkett, a Democratic Council member from Brooklyn, drew an
analogy to the pass laws in South Africa under apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were somewhere that someone thought you didn't belong,
they could ask for your pass,'' she said. ``In New York City, in
the United States of America, it was considered customary not to
ask for that kind of identification unless you were committing a
crime. Now, what I've been told is that people will see you and
say, `Where are you going? What are you doing here? Why are you
here? Have you identification?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The hearing grew heated when Councilwoman Ronnie M. Eldridge,
Democrat of Manhattan, spoke. ``I am asking if you cannot find a
different way of reducing crime or keeping the crime statistics low
without threatening people's civil liberties,'' she said. ``And
that, I believe, is what's happened with the Street Crime Unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir shot back, ``Is that, `When did I stop beating my wife?'
''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Eldridge replied that the people who elected her were
interested in the issue, ``and I resent your lack of respect and
your outrageous comments.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Christine Quinn, a Democrat from Manhattan's West
Side, added, ``And I don't think domestic violence is anything to
joke about, commissioner.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir said: ``Your suggestion that we do racial profiling is not
true. What we do is we take the victim's description of the
perpetrator, and that's what we use to look for perpetrators.''
</P>
</TEXT>
