<HEADER>
A5335 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-ARNETT-NYT &LR;      04-20 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-ARNETT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CNN, PETER ARNETT AGREE TO PART 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After weeks of steadfastly refusing to comment on the status of
Peter Arnett, its onetime leading foreign correspondent, CNN said
Monday that it had reached a financial settlement with Arnett that
would end his 18-year career at CNN.
</P>
<P>
   No specific terms of the deal were disclosed; Arnett had two and
a half years remaining on a five-year contract with the network.
Both sides said the agreement was amicable.
</P>
<P>
   The situation leading up to the settlement was not amicable.
CNN, which is owned by Time Warner, had shut down all previous
attempts at initiating settlement talks, aiming for a date in July
when an option in Arnett's contract would allow the network to
dismiss him without any further payment, Arnett said.
</P>
<P>
   CNN executives refused to say Monday why the network had changed
its strategy and agreed to settle with Arnett. But on Monday,
Arnett, who had previously avoided speaking publicly about his
status at CNN, discussed his displeasure with how CNN was treating
him. He said the network had stopped giving him assignments and had
refused to work out a settlement of his contract. ``I don't think a
journalist of my reputation should be in limbo,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett's agent, Richard Liebner, was able to conclude the
settlement agreement with Tom Johnson, the chairman of CNN, Monday.
</P>
<P>
   CNN issued a terse news release calling the settlement ``an
understanding that will bring Arnett's 18-year service to an
amicable conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   In the statement, Johnson said CNN was ``grateful for Peter's
contributions to CNN and we wish him the very best in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   In the same statement, Arnett said, ``I've had a long and
wonderful relationship with CNN and have been proud to be part of
this great news organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnett became CNN's most recognizable correspondent after he
reported the American bombing of Iraq during the Gulf War, live
from Baghdad, in 1991. That was the highest moment in CNN's
history, and transformed it into a fully credible competitor of the
news divisions of CBS, NBC and ABC.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, Arnett also took part in what became CNN's lowest
moment, when a report in June called ``Tailwind,'' which contended
that American forces in Vietnam had used the lethal nerve gas
sarin, was found to be so unsupported by the facts in a subsequent
in-house investigation that CNN retracted it and apologized to the
public for having aired it. Two producers were dismissed and a
third resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett, who had been the chief correspondent for the report,
defended himself by saying he did virtually no work on the report,
and received a reprimand.
</P>
<P>
   While his job was saved at that time, the network has used him
just once since the retraction last July. He was never called to
take part in CNN's coverage of the war in Yugoslavia despite his
experience. He won a Pulitzer Prize in 1966 for his coverage of the
Vietnam War for The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Arnett will be free to seek other jobs in television, an
associate close to him said Monday. But he may try to work as a
writer instead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
