<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMBIS' OUTBURST SPARKS LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Cocky, confident, egotistical. Those were the Lakers
of February.
</P>
<P>
   Desperate. Deflated. Those were the Lakers who returned to the
Forum on Monday _ a three-game losing streak hanging over them like
a thick, brown haze over the San Fernando Valley in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Nine games to go in a season teetering on the edge of disaster,
the Lakers needed something, anything to boost their self-esteem,
if not their playoff seeding.
</P>
<P>
   They got it with a 117-102 rout of the Vancouver Grizzlies but
not without the usual struggle.
</P>
<P>
   A shattered clipboard did the trick.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers trailed by a half-dozen points midway through the
third quarter when coach Kurt Rambis focused all his frustrations
on an 8-by-14 piece of white plastic, blasting it into pieces
against the Forum hardwood. The Lakers got the message, gaining the
lead by the end of the quarter and sending it into double digits by
early in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was like, `Did he just do what we think he just
did?''' Robert Horry said of Rambis' clipboard abuse. ``You see we
took over after that. We played a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   It started with defense, the Lakers' source of many a loss over
the last four weeks. Though they allowed Vancouver 56 percent
shooting and 60 points in the first half, and surrendered 100-plus
points for the fourth straight game, the Lakers gave themselves a
passing grade for improved defense. The Grizzlies ended up shooting
47.5 percent for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really happy with the way our guys improved tonight,''
Rambis said. ``You could see their activity, you could see guys
stunting, you could see guys trapping. They were in the right place
most of the time, though they still got some offensive rebounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in the first half, when the Grizzlies seemed to score at
will, it was not for lack of effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were hitting shots with hands in their faces,'' Rambis
said. ``I wasn't displeased with the defense in the first half....
We were doing the right things most of the time. They hit some
tough shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Offense has rarely been the Lakers' problem, but that was
improved as well. They hit 53.5 percent of their field goals and
dished out 30 assists, led by eight from Kobe Bryant, who scored 17
points.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal led six Lakers in double figures, with 35. Glen
Rice scored 18 and the bench did the rest _ Robert Horry (17
points, 12 rebounds), Tyronn Lue (15) and Ruben Patterson (11) all
scored season highs.
</P>
<P>
   Rookies Patterson and Lue led the late third-quarter charge that
regained the Lakers' lead and they kept it up in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just go out and play hard, it's a lot of innocent
energy,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off double-digit losses at Utah and Portland, the Lakers
figured to be due for a blowout of their own against the Grizzlies,
who had just one win in 20 road games this season.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's day off let them clear their heads of Saturday's loss
to the Jazz. The only thing left to do was erase all memories of
the prior week with a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, but you have to do it,'' Bryant said. ``That's
something that we've kind of been doing all year. And as the year
went on, we found ourselves getting better at it, because you don't
have a choice. That's what you have to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
