<SLUG> BC-HKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT ONE A SUPERSTAR WITHOUT THE AIRS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ While speaking to school kids, service clubs and
journalism students, the question is inevitable: Who's your
favorite athlete?
</P>
<P>
   I'm always evasive, because a) I don't have one; b) if I did,
disclosure would reveal a bias, and c) I'd also have to explain why
somebody's hero isn't my favorite, which inevitably leads to some
truth-telling most sports followers don't want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   Once in awhile, however, the question is more sharply defined:
Who's your favorite interview?
</P>
<P>
   That one's easy.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Gretzky.
</P>
<P>
   Since Gretzky shows up in Seattle about as often as a parking
space downtown, his choice might sound surprising. The absence of
the National Hockey League here makes Gretzky a distant sort of
exotica, a little like, say, penguins or the British royals.
</P>
<P>
   He used to show up in Victoria, however. For years, one of his
old clubs, the Los Angeles Kings, held training camp in musty old
Memorial Arena. Aside from the odd exhibition game in Tacoma,
Victoria might be as close as Gretzky would come, and the ride to
Vancouver Island is a tad more pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   So 10 years ago I called the Kings for Gretzky's schedule,
jumped on the Clipper and figured when I got blown off for the
interview, at least I'd be somewhere besides the Tacoma Dome
parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Timing turned out to be good, on two counts: Gretzky had just
begun training with the Kings after his controversial departure
from Edmonton in what was then known as the Trade of the Century,
and almost nobody else was there.
</P>
<P>
   I walked into the Kings' cramped, stinky locker room after
practice, and almost everyone was gone except Gretzky, who was
pulling on cowboy boots that I knew would just have to be left
behind if he expected to get a table anywhere in LA.
</P>
<P>
   No entourage. No PR flacks. No toothless teammates. No hovering
trainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi,'' he said brightly _ speaking first, which remains
unprecedented in my superstar-interview history.
</P>
<P>
   A stranger, I explained myself, apologized for my lack of
appointment, and just before blaming my mother for having me, he
said, ``Sit down. What's on your mind?''
</P>
<P>
   Whereupon a 45-minute conversation followed that went from the
obvious topics of the trade and hockey's future, to American
politics, the NBA, Seattle's absence from the NHL and why it is in
Southern California that fire season follows mudslide season by
about a week.
</P>
<P>
   I waited for him to glance at his watch. Instead, I ran out of
questions.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious he was concerned about what Canadians were
feeling about his departure that he helped arrange, since it
symbolized what was happening throughout the Great White North _
anyone or anything that made good, went south.
</P>
<P>
   ``Throughout my career, I've been worried about what people said
or thought,'' he said. ``But for the first time, I decided to do
what's best for myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I conferred with my wife and parents, and a couple of close
friends. Even they thought I would stay in Edmonton. This time, I
thought I would do something for Wayne Gretzky.''
</P>
<P>
   Selfish as it sounded, Gretzky felt compelled to explain himself
honestly, a characteristic that served him at least as well as his
stick handling.
</P>
<P>
   He also acknowledged that his departure to LA was bigger than
him. The NHL's financial survival depended on selling the game to a
larger American market.
</P>
<P>
   The wisdom became apparent. When he spoke, the NHL had 21 teams.
Now it has 27, with newcomers mostly in the prosperous Sunbelt.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of that can be credited to Gretzky's move, but there's
not an NHL fan who won't tell you the presence of the game's best,
most artful player in a major market was the most significant
development in assuring hockey's place in North American sports.
</P>
<P>
   Wrenching as was the trade, Canadian hockey fans even 10 years
ago seemed to understand. A couple of days before in Victoria, the
old arena was packed with 5,400 fans who cheered him lustily,
without rancor, during an exhibition game. The feeling followed him
throughout one of sports' most stupendous careers.
</P>
<P>
   The logic and inevitability of Gretzky's move was apparent, as
was the trust and respect hockey fans had for him, apart from
adulation.
</P>
<P>
   Even beyond his numbers, perhaps the most remarkable thing about
Gretzky's 20-year career is that no one in these skeptical times
had anything bad to say about him.
</P>
<P>
   Even upon his departure, Gretzky knew he couldn't go out a
champion, as did Michael Jordan. So he let it be known a few days
ahead that his career was over, allowing a mutually fulfilling
tribute that was neither drawn out nor maudlin.
</P>
<P>
   Greatness is a difficult enterprise to manage. There is no
manual on how, and to whom, to say yes and no. While the
impossibility of pleasing everyone is well-known, the ability to
care about how one's conduct impacts others is anything but.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was an exit, or an interview, or rewriting sports
history, Gretzky demonstrated how to be great beyond one's gifts.
</P>
<P>
   The man's final score was not a goal, but an assist.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 0230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5348 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      04-20 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFFS IN DOUBT AS SONICS FALL THREE GAMES UNDER .500 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Detlef Schrempf thought he had defensive position.
</P>
<P>
   He had played Houston forward Charles Barkley tough all night.
So when Barkley received the ball in the paint with the Rockets
clinging to a 108-104 lead, Schrempf bore down for a stop.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, though, tossed Schrempf aside on his way to the hoop.
The whistle blew as Barkley scored. Then he converted the
three-point play.
</P>
<P>
   The sequence may not sum up the Sonics' season, but it did put
the finishing touches on Monday night's 120-113 loss at the Compaq
Center.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Schrempf has yet to look at the standings this season.
The once-formidable Sonics _ the NBA's last undefeated team at 6-0
_ have been pushed aside. And no matter what they do, they can't
escape that sinking feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Down to their last nine games, the Sonics find themselves tied
with Sacramento for the eighth and final playoff berth in the
Western Conference. The Kings defeated the Los Angeles Clippers
Monday for their second straight victory while the Sonics lost
their third in a row.
</P>
<P>
   At 19-22, Seattle is three games under .500 for the first time
this season. One of the teams ahead of them, the 22-20 Minnesota
Timberwolves, visit KeyArena Wednesday night in a must-win game for
the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Houston earned its victory Monday. When Barkley wasn't punishing
the Sonics with three the hard way down low, the Rockets were
lighting up the Sonics with conventional treys.
</P>
<P>
   Houston made 13 of its 27 3-point attempts, including two big
ones that kept the Sonics at bay down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after Barkley burned Schrempf with 2:14 left in the
game, Sam Mack drained a 3-pointer to put the Rockets ahead 114-104
and the game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game is a battle,'' said Schrempf, who led the Sonics
with 28 points and 13 rebounds. ``We can't beat anybody big the way
we're playing. ... So I never look at the standings. Otherwise I'd
be disappointed because I've never seen us anywhere but the top
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics played their fifth game in six nights. They won just
one of those games _ an overtime affair at Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not into it right now,'' Sonics point guard Gary Payton
said. ``Hopefully, we'll be ready for the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   If they make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Sacramento, the Sonics also must hold off the
Golden State Warriors, who were idle Monday but gained ground
because the Sonics lost. At 18-22, the Warriors are just a
half-game behind the Sonics and Kings.
</P>
<P>
   At least one person had a positive attitude after Monday's loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying hard to find something to complain about,'' Sonics
coach Paul Westphal said. ``We're playing hard and giving a good
effort. ... If we can play that well, we can make the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Westphal's crew led only once in this one. Schrempf
scored a layup for the game's first basket. From there, it was an
uphill battle for the Sonics, who could never get over the Rockets'
pile of 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Sonics won the rebounding war, 45-37. Forget
about their 51-percent shooting and mere 13 turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   With forward Vin Baker sitting out because of a sore right knee,
the Sonics could not match up with Barkley or Hakeem Olajuwon. Both
players forced the Sonics to double-team the post.
</P>
<P>
   But when the Sonics doubled down, Barkley and Olajuwon found
open jump shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some reason our rotations were a little slow,'' guard
Hersey Hawkins said. ``But you have to give them credit. They
knocked it down whenever they were open.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Rockets team that missed 22 of 27 3-point
attempts in a 101-84 loss to the Sonics April 4 at KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had wide-open looks,'' Sonics reserve Dale Ellis said.
``It was a simple game, inside out, for them. They made the shots.
You're not going to contest every shot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics avoided a slow start and stayed close to the Rockets
in the opening period. But they dug a big hole in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Houston extended a 34-29 first-quarter lead to 16 points by
exploiting the Sonics' weak interior defense with hard drives to
the basket and deft low-post offense from Barkley and Olajuwon.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics turned the ball over eight times in the second
quarter and trailed 56-45 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Payton helped erase an 11-point deficit in the third quarter and
sparked the Sonics' last run of the period _ a 7-1 spurt _ that got
the Sonics within 84-79 heading into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   After going 0-for-8 in the first half for just two points,
Payton was all but unstoppable. He hit eight of his 10 field-goal
attempts in the third quarter and scored 17 points in the period.
Payton's outburst came on a variety of moves, and mostly with
Houston rookie Cuttino Mobley defending him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided to get after it,'' said Payton, who collected
21 of his 23 points in the second half. ``But it still wasn't
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics kept fighting back throughout the game. They nearly
overcame a 15-point deficit in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the same story for us,'' Schrempf said.
</P>
<P>
   A precarious one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 0234EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
