A5349 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     04-20 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS NO MATCH FOR BRAVES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Forget about the postseason failures that will
forever be an asterisk on Atlanta's resume. When the rest of the
National League wants a barometer, they measure themselves with the
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson spoke of that. So did general
manager Kevin Malone.
</P>
<P>
   And in their first chance to measure themselves Monday night,
the Dodgers produced nothing. They didn't even do enough to gain
consideration of being a notch on the Braves' measuring stick,
bowing 11-3 in a gruesome display at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Each of Atlanta's starters had at least one hit as the Braves
pounded out 18 hits for the game. The onslaught came a day after
the Braves scored 20 runs against the Rockies in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never pretty when your pitching isn't good and their
pitching is good,'' Johnson said. ``It's almost as if they knew
what was coming. You'll make a good pitch and they'd hit it hard.
There's not a whole lot to say about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers (7-7) have lost three of four after being taken to
task by Atlanta right-hander John Smoltz in the opener of the
three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we had that feeling in '88 or '89, we looked at the
top teams and wondered what it would take to get there,'' Smoltz
said after tossing six innings of one-run ball. ``The bottom line
for us any time is it really doesn't matter who we play. We don't
look at any series we play as bigger than another.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers do, or did, if only from the perspective of wanting
to prove worthy of challenging the Braves six months from now.
</P>
<P>
   Considering this was game 14 of 162, that may still happen. But
the Dodgers have immediate issues to deal with, including what's
wrong with starting pitcher Carlos Perez. He may have pitched
himself out of his next start after being racked for six runs and
eight hits in 32/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and pitching coach Charlie Hough are deciding what spot
in the rotation will be skipped because of off days Thursday and
Monday. After collapsing in the seventh inning in each of his first
two starts, the shortest outing by a Dodgers starter this season
may be enough to bump Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is deciding between Perez (0-3, 8.31 ERA), Darren
Dreifort (2-0, 2.25) or Ismael Valdes (1-0, 4.12).
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to figure how the guy pitched,'' Johnson said. ``The
guy who hasn't pitched well more than likely is going to miss a
start. At this point, it might be Carlos.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Perez not pitch well, he didn't exhibit much
confidence or awareness on the mound. He yielded a two-run single
to Smoltz (2-0) in the second inning and came unnerved in the
third. Chipper Jones, who left the game in the sixth with a rib
cage strain, hit a solo homer to give the Braves a 3-0 lead. Andruw
Jones then walked, Perez balked him to second and his attempted
pickoff went into center field to move the runner to third. Jones
scored on Brian Hunter's single.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves knocked Perez out in the fourth. It began with Bret
Boone's two-out infield single. Chipper Jones walked and Brian
Jordan smacked a two-run double to left as Atlanta went ahead 6-0.
Perez should have been backing up home, but instead was in front of
the plate and cut off the relay throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave up eight hits and I believe all eight were on
off-speed pitches,'' Hough said. ``It tells me he wasn't real sharp
or they were just dead sitting on it. He was a little high with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a debacle kind of night, the only salvageable thing for the
Dodgers were solo homers by Dave Hansen, Todd Hundley and Raul
Mondesi, who is tied for the league lead with six.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Robinson Checo, the middle reliever the Dodgers
received from Detroit in the Dave Mlicki trade Friday, had an
equally rough time in his debut. Johnson tried to save his bullpen
from burning out, so Checo was tagged for five runs on eight hits
over 31/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone feels like they're doing a wonderful job, that's
where problems exist,'' Dodgers second baseman Eric Young said.
``We know we can all do better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
