A5354 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-EXPORTS-SFCHRON &LR;      04-20 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-EXPORTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
U.S. WINERIES FLOURISHING IN OVERSEAS EXPORTS
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. wine exports have rocketed more than 1,400
percent in the past 12 years, the industry reported Monday, with
California vintners accounting for 90 percent of those sales.
</P>
<P>
   Exports rose 20 percent last year alone, to $537 million. Wine
Institute President John De Luca predicted another big increase
this year and said export sales could hit $1 billion within five
years. Exports now account for 12.5 percent of the industry's
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Releasing the results at the Wine Institute's annual Washington
luncheon, De Luca also noted that China has promised to slash its
wine import tariffs from 60 percent to 20 percent over five years
if the Clinton administration agrees to support China's entry into
the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   De Luca attributed the booming exports to a rise in worldwide
consumption of more expensive premium wines. The United Kingdom has
become the largest market for California wines, accounting for a
quarter of U.S. wine exports. Sales there rose 32 percent from a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Second in line is Japan, with exports there rising 101 percent
last year to $93 million, followed by Canada, with $91 million in
sales.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. winemakers now rank fourth in the world in wine production.
</P>
<P>
   California vintners said the export growth is all the more
remarkable given high overseas wine tariffs and heavy government
subsidies to European winemakers. They said they are continuing to
battle for lower tariffs and are also making a new effort at
cooperating with their European counterparts to keep wine from
being used as a bargaining chip in international trade
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   During the recent banana trade dispute between the United States
and the European Union, winemakers on both sides of the Atlantic
asked their governments not to draw them into the dispute, De Luca
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to both governments with a message that the wine trade
should not be used as a bargaining chip involving corn brooms,
poultry or bananas or anything else,'' De Luca said.
</P>
<P>
   The winemakers said they are also continuing to attack what De
Luca described as domestic interstate trade barriers _ a peculiar
holdover from Prohibition _ which give states unusual regulatory
controls over alcohol marketing. These include state monopolies
that restrict retail liquor sales and bans on wine sales in food
stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may well indeed make faster progress overseas'' than
against interstate trade barriers, De Luca said. The industry has
been negotiating mini ``trade agreements'' with each state, ``as
though dealing with a foreign government,'' De Luca said.
</P>
<P>
   Internet sales have become the biggest domestic issue for
winemakers, particularly small vintners who have trouble getting
their wines distributed to major wholesalers and retailers and rely
heavily on direct sales.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen states have long prohibited out-of-state direct
shipments to consumers _ including tourists who visit wineries and
want to send home a case.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, became alarmed by the growth of such
shipments, particularly the potential for minors to order alcohol.
Hatch has introduced legislation to allow states to sue in federal
court to stop wine shipments that violate state marketing laws or
are purchased by minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is apparent that modern technology has opened the door for
abuse,'' Hatch said at a hearing he held in March.
</P>
<P>
   But Hatch has promised to work on a compromise with California
Sen. Dianne Feinstein, a Democrat, to improve ``certification and
verification'' of Internet sales to make sure they comply with
state regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
