<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-CAPSULES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN CONFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 
First-round playoff previews 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 1. Dallas Stars (51-19-12) vs. 8. Edmonton Oilers (33-37-12) Season
series: Stars won, 3-0-1 The Stars' symptoms: Sure, Derian Hatcher
will miss the first five games of the playoffs with a suspension,
but the Stars are a tougher team because of it. Hatcher's hit sent
a message to the NHL, and his absence will require his teammates to
take up the slack against an Oilers team that is promising a
physical series. The Stars need to dominate to prove they've
stepped up their playoff intensity from last season. The heart: The
veterans. There is a hunger here that stretches from Guy Carbonneau
to Ed Belfour to Brett Hull. The brain: The Stars' playoff hopes
revolve around Belfour's ability to handle pressure in goal. The
Stars play low-scoring hockey, so the pressure will be there almost
every game. The prognosis looks good if: Belfour is a rock, Hull
adds some scoring punch, the Stars luck out on injuries, and the
players keep their hunger for the Stanley Cup. The Oilers'
symptoms: This is one interesting dog. The Oilers aren't sure if
they want to keep coach Ron Low, yet they play best when he's cocky
and letting them run. They went to the trouble of picking up
talented defensemen Janne Niinimaa and Roman Hamrlik last season
and already don't like them. And still they went 6-3-1 down the
stretch. The Oilers have speed and grit, but the big question is
whether Tommy Salo can replace Curtis Joseph (now in Toronto) in
goal. The heart: Doug Weight. The gritty goal scorer still drives
the bus. Despite a knee injury, he has to be good for them to win.
The brain: Todd Marchant. As difficult as it is to say, the yappy
little forward has his finger on the pulse of the team. And they
respond to him. The prognosis looks good if: The Oilers rough up
the Stars, and the Stars' power play doesn't respond to the
challenge. But with leading goal scorers Bill Guerin and Josef
Beranek out at least two games with injuries, the Oilers might not
be able to score.
<TEXT>
<P>
   2. Colorado Avalanche (44-28-10) vs. 7. San Jose Sharks
(37-26-19) Season series: Avalanche won, 3-1 The Avalanche's
symptoms: No team has more raw offensive talent on the top end than
the Avalanche, which boasts Peter Forsberg (97 points), Joe Sakic
(96 points) and Theo Fleury (93 points). And they put all three
together on the same line at times! The Avalanche has skill, a
fantastic goalie in Patrick Roy (32-19-8, 2.29 goals-against
average) and an underrated defense (Adam Foote and Sandis Ozolinsh
are All-Stars). However, they get frustrated by muck-it-up teams
and could face three in a row (the Sharks, Red Wings and Stars).
The heart: Roy. His cockiness is alarming, but it's also a show
that he could be getting ready for something special. The brain:
Fleury. People can't get past his 5-foot-6 height and gap-toothed
grin, but this is one hockey player who rises to every occasion.
The prognosis is good if: Roy doesn't slip and the Avalanche
doesn't try to win every game, 5-1. The Sharks' symptoms: Lying in
wait in San Jose could be the West's giant killers. The Sharks play
a physically demanding, mentally demanding style that forces
opponents to take hits, play cautious and wait for a chance at a
2-1 victory. Along the way, opponents have to put up with the
annoyance of chippy players Bryan Marchment, Mike Ricci and Owen
Nolan and maybe the most annoying arena for an opponent: the Shark
Tank. The heart: This team has no clear leader, and that could be
its biggest problem. The brains: Recently acquired center Vincent
Damphousse gives the Sharks an air of offensive legitimacy. Not too
much, though; they rank last among playoff teams in scoring at 2.4
goals per game. The pieces come together if: Nolan doesn't try to
kill everyone on the ice, Marchment doesn't try to kill everyone on
the ice and Ricci doesn't try to kill everyone on the ice. Oh, and
either Mike Vernon or Steve Shields will have to save the team in
net.
</P>
<P>
   3. Detroit Red Wings (43-32-7) vs. 6. Anaheim Mighty Ducks
(35-34-13) Season series: Red Wings won, 3-1. The Red Wings'
symptoms: Face it, that deadline-day scared you. Detroit appeared
dazed by Stanley Cup hangover and a injury spate that seemed to
drain the heart out of the team. But adding Chris Chelios, Wendel
Clark, Ulf Samuelsson and Bill Ranford in a span of three hours
changed everything. The Red Wings had offensive depth and improved
it. And now the defense _ featuring Chelios, Samuelsson, Nick
Lidstrom, Larry Murphy, Aaron Ward and Todd Gill _ is as good or
better than the Stars' defense. Not one Red Wings player has played
over his head this season, and that's a scary thought heading into
the playoffs. The heart: Steve Yzerman. Captain Courageous is just
a darned good hockey player every night. The brain: Coach Scotty
Bowman has had a hand in nine Stanley Cups and knows how to tweak
his players and an opponent. The prognosis looks good if: They play
sound hockey and goalie Chris Osgood doesn't make too many
mistakes. The Ducks' symptoms: They are a fun team to watch ... and
a fun team to play against. There's good reason: They're all about
offensive chances and the splendor that is Paul Kariya and Teemu
Selanne. The Ducks frustrate teams that are undisciplined, like
Phoenix, but they grind to a halt against teams like the Stars and
Red Wings. Anaheim will have trouble moving the puck against the
Red Wings' trap and will likely have goalie Guy Hebert face even
more than his average of 32 shots per game. The heart: Selanne. His
47 goals and 60 assists speak to his skill. But even more
impressive is his love of the game. The brain: Kariya. He is like
Wayne Gretzky without emotion. He sees things in a different way.
The prognosis looks good if: Selanne, Kariya and underrated center
Steve Rucchin fight through the Red Wings' forwards, then through
the Red Wings' defense, then through Osgood.
</P>
<P>
   4. Phoenix Coyotes (39-31-12) vs. 5. St. Louis Blues (37-32-13)
Season series: Blues won, 2-1-1 The Coyotes' symptoms: Does anyone
remember that this team was 24-11-7? That means since mid-season,
they have been below .500 at 15-20-5 _ ranking 19th in the league
over that span. Add to the mix the fact leading scorer Jeremy
Roenick will miss the playoffs with a broken jaw, and there's
little to like about this team's chances. The heart: Captain Keith
Tkachuk. He's obnoxious, loud and talented. Tkachuk had 68 points
in 68 games and was plus-22. He chipped in 151 penalty minutes just
for fun. The brains: Goalie Nikolai Khabibulin pushed this team to
the top early in the season but has been mortal since the All-Star
break. The prognosis looks good if: Role players such as Rick
Tocchet, Greg Adams and Robert Reichel start scoring goals and the
Coyotes learn not to self-destruct. The Blues' symptoms: Throughout
the season, the Blues have had one of the most confusing teams in
the NHL. They were strong offensively, great on special teams and
limited opponents to a league-low 22.3 shots per game. So why
couldn't they break .500? The problem turned out to be goaltending,
where the Blues missed injured No. 1 goalie Grant Fuhr and posted a
league-worst .887 save percentage. Since Fuhr has returned, the
Blues finished on a 5-3-2 run and appear ready to take the next
step in the playoffs. The heart: Al MacInnis. He should be the
clear winner of the Norris Trophy as the top defenseman this season
and is a threat to win any game with his thundering slapshot. The
brain: Forward Pavol Demitra. He has 37 goals and 52 assists,
picking up the scoring slack left when Brett Hull departed for the
Stars. The prognosis looks good if: Fuhr stays healthy. The veteran
is wearing down, and the Blues have absolutely no depth at the
position.
EASTERN CONFERENCE 1. New Jersey Devils (47-24-11) vs. 8.
Pittsburgh Penguins (38-30-14) Season series: Devils won, 4-1. The
Devils' symptoms: After getting off to a shaky start under new
coach Robbie Ftorek, the Devils have quietly overtaken the Eastern
Conference and come in with the top seed and the hottest road team
in NHL history (28-10-3). They finished the regular season on an
8-2 run and could win the Stanley Cup. The heart: Defenseman Scott
Stevens leads a group of no-names who have decent size, decent
speed and balanced scoring. None of them will be among the
finalists for any postseason award. The brain: Goalie Martin
Brodeur isn't shaken easily. The prognosis looks good if: The
balanced scoring of Petr Sykora (29 goals), Bobby Holik (27 goals),
Jason Arnott (27 goals) and Brian Rolston (24 goals) keeps up. The
Penguins' symptoms: No team has fallen faster than Pittsburgh. It
is a miracle that coach Kevin Constantine held them together; now,
there are rumors of bad feelings between Constantine and Jaromir
Jagr and the Penguins finished the season on a 2-7-2 run. The
heart: Jagr. He led the NHL in scoring (127 points) and should be
the Hart Trophy winner as regular-season MVP. The brain:
Constantine was heralded as a coach-of-the-year candidate before
the rift with Jagr. The prognosis looks good if: Everything is
perfect, Jagr goes crazy, Tom Barrasso is reborn in goal, and
Martin Straka, German Titov and Alexei Kovalev outscore everyone
else.
2. Ottawa Senators (44-23-15) vs. 7. Buffalo Sabres (37-28-17)
Season series: Senators won, 1-0-4. The Senators' symptoms: They
are a miraculous team, a bunch of young Europeans that have
overtaken the hearts of many Canadians. They have speed, strong
defense, good coaching and solid goaltending. What they might lack
is toughness and experience. The heart: Alexei Yashin. He had 44
goals and 50 assists this season, and he overturned the Senators'
applecart and helped bring in new management three years ago. The
brain: Stoic Jacques Martin is viewed by many as the best coach in
the NHL. The prognosis looks good if: The Senators play their
controlled game, get timely scoring and are able to work out an
unusual goalie split between Damian Rhodes and Ron Tugnutt. The
Sabres' symptoms: They are the most unpredictable team in hockey,
and quite possibly a real trap for the Senators. Two-time league
MVP Dominik Hasek has regained his form, and the Sabres love to
play a high-risk game knowing Hasek is backing them. The heart:
Captain Michael Peca. When he is on, he is the most complete player
in the league this side of Colorado's Peter Forsberg. Peca can
score (27 goals), get dirty and play defense. The brain: Hasek's
head is the turning point of this franchise. If he's on, they win.
If he's distracted, they fall. The prognosis looks good if: Hasek
is light's out, Peca and the band of 20-something goal scorers get
hot, and the Sabres find some semblance of defense.
3. Carolina Hurricanes (34-30-18) vs. 6. Boston Bruins (39-30-13)
Season series: Tied, 2-2-1 The Hurricanes' symptoms: This team
should be given credit for surviving hardship. The former Hartford
Whalers have to travel an hour to home games, play in front of
crowds of about 9,000 and are somewhat controversial because they
gained the third seed in the East by winning the weak Southeast
Division despite having the eight-best record in the conference.
That's likely too much to overcome. The heart: Arturs Irbe. The
former Stars goalie has dragged this team to a spot nobody thought
it could get to. The brain: Sami Kapanen. A Jere Lehtinen clone,
Kapanen has 24 goals and 35 assists, and plays great defense. The
prognosis looks good if: The hockey gods decide to play a joke on
the league and allow the Hurricanes to advance despite nobody in
Carolina caring. Ah, maybe a Carolina Cup finals before a sellout
of 11,000. The Bruins' symptoms: They are a young team looking for
an identity. They are a step ahead of a near miracle season last
year and two steps away from missing the playoffs two seasons ago.
But they have solid forwards, underrated goalie Byron Dafoe and Ray
Bourque, one of the best defensemen in NHL history. The heart:
Dafoe. The young goalie could finish in the top three in voting for
the Vezina Trophy for the best goaltender. His 32-23-11 record and
1.99 goals-against average are impressive. The brain: Bourque. A
five-time Norris Trophy winner as the league's best defenseman,
Bourque is in his 20th season and hasn't worn out. The prognosis
looks good if: Dafoe continues his acrobatics, and the line of
Jason Allison, Sergei Samsonov and Dmitri Kristich finds its
groove.
4. Toronto Maple Leafs (45-30-7) vs. 5. Philadelphia Flyers
(37-26-19) Season series: Flyers won, 3-1 The Maple Leafs'
symptoms: They have gone from missing the playoffs last year to the
fourth seed thanks to the addition of goalie Curtis Joseph and a
new philosophy. With Joseph in net, Toronto has become a
high-rolling, take-chances team that led the NHL in scoring with
268 goals (3.3 per game). The heart: Joseph. Cujo killed the Stars
two seasons ago and took out the Avalanche last season. He's not
afraid of anyone. The brain: Mats Sundin. Though soft-spoken,
Sundin has taken well to the role of captain. The prognosis looks
good if: Joseph is Cujo. The Maple Leafs' balanced scoring only
works if they have full faith that their goalie will stop almost
everything. The Flyers' symptoms: They did everything possible to
wrangle a chance at the Stanley Cup this season, and now many will
be surprised if they get out of the first round. The Flyers
continue to be the NHL's enigma. Eric Lindros has become a leader,
but a collapsed lung put him out of the playoffs. Mark Recchi had
returned home, but dizzy spells sidelined him late in the season.
John Vanbiesbrouck was a goalie with timing until he realized he
was wearing a Flyers uniform. The heart: Lindros is it, and he's
not there. Maybe Rod Brind'Amour can take over. The brain: John
LeClair. He's painfully quiet, but he's one of the top goal scorers
in the NHL the past five seasons. The prognosis looks good if: The
players stop hating coach Roger Neilson for his hard-driving ways,
Vanbiesbrouck finds a groove, and everyone picks up the slack left
by Lindros' absence.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
