<HEADER>
A5549 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOWS-MY-DRIVING21-COX     04-20 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOWS-MY-DRIVING21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `How's my driving' calls keep truckers in line, studies say
 &HT;    By Trebor Banstetter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Don't like my driving? Call
1-800-BUZZ-OFF,'' reads one bumper sticker.
</P>
<P>
   The joke has gotten old. But while the witticism aged, the
serious practice of inviting the general public to report on
truckers' driving skills has blossomed.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands of trucks now sport ``How's my driving?''
decals with toll-free telephone numbers, requesting complaints _
and, sometimes, praise _ from motorists. Begun in the late 1980s,
the simple concept has boomed in popularity in recent years,
spurred by the proliferation of cellular phones and increasing
friction between cars and trucks on congested highways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it effective? Without a doubt it is,'' said Joe Zingale,
executive vice president of Driver's Alert, a Lighthouse Point
company that was one of the first to get into the truck monitoring
business.
</P>
<P>
   The primary force driving the boom in toll-free truck tattle
lines is money. Commercial truck crashes bring not only property
damage, injury and loss of life, but the possibility of
multimillion-dollar court judgments. Insurance companies have taken
notice, even paying the cost of the programs in many cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, people just made a lot of jokes, but today it's
taken pretty seriously,'' said Zingale, whose company has pasted
decals on 300,000 vehicles nationwide and is one of the largest in
the country. ``A crash can be devastating, and you have to look at
anything that decreases that possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   But some transport companies fear that monitoring decals send
the wrong message to those on the highways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like advertising to the general public, `Hey, I have some
bad drivers and you need to watch out for them,' '' said Mike
Smith, safety manager of Palm City-based Armellini Express Lines,
which transports cut flowers from Florida to points all over the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we have professional, safe and courteous drivers and
they just don't need these decals on their trucks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some truckers also believe ``How's my driving?'' decals draw
fake reports from competing truck drivers, or false complaints from
motorists who just don't like sharing the road with big rigs, Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither state nor federal highway safety agencies have analyzed
whether call-in decals decrease truck-related crashes. But two
recent studies by insurance companies indicate monitoring programs
do have an impact on highway safety.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Hanover Insurance Co. of Worcester, Mass.,
compared 445 trucks in 11 fleets with and without decals, and found
that those with decals had 22 percent fewer traffic crashes.
</P>
<P>
   A study by Reliance Insurance of Philadelphia found that truck
fleets using monitoring stickers had a 35 percent reduction in
crash-related costs the year after they began using the program.
</P>
<P>
   Many insurance companies now give discounts to businesses that
affix ``How's my driving?'' stickers to their vehicles. Reliance
pays the cost of the monitoring program and provides a discount on
the customer's insurance premium, said Tom Turansky, risk control
officer for Reliance Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as those trucks leave the dock, they're essentially
unsupervised,'' he said. ``But driving a heavy truck is like
operating a deadly weapon. Putting decals on trucks gives you an
additional tool to increase safety.''
</P>
<P>
   A truck monitoring program typically costs between $12 and $20
per vehicle per year, depending on the type of truck and the size
of the fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Major insurance companies began study truck monitoring two years
ago, said Dick Lea, president of FleetSafe, a vehicle monitoring
firm in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   FleetSafe guarantees a 10 percent reduction in crashes, or
customers can get their money back. So far, no one has taken them
up on the offer, Lea said.
</P>
<P>
   When someone calls to complain about a truck, the caller is
interviewed to determine what happened and whether the truck driver
was at fault. The caller typically must give his name and address,
Lea said.
</P>
<P>
   The complaints are sent to the trucking companies immediately.
In addition, both Driver's Alert and FleetSafe compile and analyze
complaints to show trends among a company's drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The chief goal of the decal program is to identify unsafe
drivers before they get in a wreck.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that the vast majority of truck drivers are safe
and careful drivers,'' said Rivers Buford of the Florida Trucking
Association. ``But you have a small percentage responsible for the
majority of problems.''
</P>
<P>
   A truck driver who receives numerous complaints is usually
warned and given additional training to reduce the chances of a
crash in the future, Zingale said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They usually won't fire a driver outright for getting
complaints,'' Zingale said. ``The companies see it as an
opportunity to intervene and provide more education and training to
make that driver a safer driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Decals can also have a psychological influence. ``The decal
makes the driver think, `Hey, people are observing me all the
time,' '' Zingale said.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint call-in stickers aren't just on big rigs. Driver's
Alert's customers include delivery vans, couriers, moving trucks _
``just about anyone who drives a vehicle on the job might want
one,'' Zingale said.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the decal system has even gone beyond the
trucking industry _ some worried parents of teenage drivers have
developed their own stickers, complete with home telephone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But in those cases, the phone call goes right to the young
driver's parents, and instead of being fired, the driver faces the
ultimate teen penalty: Being grounded.
</P>
<P>
   Trebor Banstetter writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
