<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 10:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5550 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLOCAUST-DEBATE21-CO     04-20 1493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLOCAUST-DEBATE21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debate rages over future of the Holocaust's legacy
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the past 14 months, the director of
the United States Holocaust Museum in Washington, D.C., was fired
when he objected to the museum being used for political purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The editor of an influential magazine on Jewish affairs was
called ``brainless when it comes to the Holocaust'' for criticizing
the growing field of Holocaust studies.
</P>
<P>
   And scores of museum directors, curators and academics have been
accused of commercializing the memory of 6 million Jews killed in
the Holocaust to further political agendas and boost ticket sales
for an increasing number of Holocaust exhibits and museums.
</P>
<P>
   More than half a century after the Holocaust, defining, owning
and placing it in context have become more complex and more
contentious issues than ever. As the last generation of survivors
enters their 70s and 80s, a debate within the Jewish community is
intensifying: Who will speak for the victims after the last
witnesses are gone? And what will they say?
</P>
<P>
   The questions are not new, but as American colleges and
universities study the Holocaust through a continually broader
variety of lenses, the debate surrounding it is intensifying.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who say the Holocaust should be treated as a
sacred and distinctly Jewish event. Comparing the horror to
anything else is demeaning to the legacy, the argument goes.
</P>
<P>
   But others say for the Holocaust to be fully understood, it must
be put into political context and interpreted through as many
perspectives as possible. One result of that argument: Dozens of
academic conventions pop up every year and hundreds of papers
deconstructing the Holocaust through feminist, environmental and
current geopolitical viewpoints are presented.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, conservative columnist George Will slammed the
growing industry of Holocaust studies in a column: ``As the
Holocaust becomes academicized, it becomes trivialized, reduced to
just another instance of injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   And in an opinion piece that ran in newspapers across the
country last month, Gabriel Schoenfeld, the senior editor of
Commentary Magazine, accused many Holocaust museum and exhibit
curators and academics of ``treating the most shattering event in
modern history as a banality, or worse, as entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Trivializing tragedy
</P>
<P>
   ``As the generation of survivors passes from the scene, this
tragedy is up for grabs,'' Schoenfeld said last week from New York.
``There is a wide-scale trivialization being committed by people
who purport to be the custodians of their memory. In a way, the
Holocaust is being pigeonholed into the general trend of
victimization.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Feinstein, the acting director of the Center of
Holocaust and Genocide Studies at the University of Minnesota, and
the man who called Schoenfeld ``brainless,'' said that
deconstructing the Holocaust through secular or feminist or even
environmentalist lenses is inevitable. The Holocaust did not just
happen to Jews, Feinstein said, it happened to the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people out there who want to make (the
Holocaust) a sacramental, pseudo-religious event to remember the
victims,'' Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But whether we like it or not . . . the words `Holocaust' and
`genocide' have come to intersect.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the academic debate on the Holocaust, Feinstein sees
no basis for criticism: ``Anything that gives rise to a rational
discourse is good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it also can lead to charges that the memory of the 6 million
is being exploited. That's what Walter Reich accused state
department officials of doing when they invited Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat to visit Washington's United States Holocaust Museum
last year during stalled Middle East peace talks. Arafat would have
been the first Arab leader to acknowledge the Holocaust, but Reich
did not want the museum to be used as a political tool to
jump-start the negotiations. Reich ultimately lost his job as the
museum's director.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors from 40 years ago would be amazed there is any debate
at all. In the 1940s and 1950s, the Holocaust was considered a
footnote to World War II. Even among Jews the subject was taboo.
</P>
<P>
   The silence began to lift in the '60s, first with the trial of
Adolf Eichmann in Israel in 1961 and then with the Six Day War in
1967. Through the 1970s and into the '80s, most high school history
books dedicated an average of one paragraph to the Holocaust,
Feinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Things began to change by the 1980s as Holocaust literature _
memoirs and histories _ began to be published en masse. Throughout
the '90s, Hollywood and foreign filmmakers, through movies like
Schindler's List and Life is Beautiful, brought stories of the
Final Solution to millions more.
</P>
<P>
   But as pervasive as the story of the death camps may seem, it is
not universally understood, argue those who support more memorials.
</P>
<P>
   Eva Weiss, a counselor who works with Holocaust survivors in
Palm Beach County, was training a group of about 25 nursing aides
last month _ mostly Haitian and South American women _ about how to
deal with problems they might encounter when taking care of
survivors. Suddenly, she realized she was getting a lot of blank
stares.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked the group if they knew what the Holocaust was,'' Weiss
said. ``One girl raised her hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Education for understanding
</P>
<P>
   Educating people about the Holocaust and informing contemporary
debate about broader issues are important reasons to promote
Holocaust scholarship, said Devorah Dwork, the director of the
Center of Holocaust Studies at Clark University, the only school in
the country that offers a doctorate degree in the Holocaust. The
reason the American Civil War is understood today and will be
understood in 100 years is because of scholarship, Dwork said. The
same holds for the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially now, given Kosovo, we couldn't be looking at a more
compelling argument for the experience of Holocaust scholarship,''
Dwork said.
</P>
<P>
   But how much is too much? There are 73 Holocaust centers
nationwide, and about 200 universities offering some sort of
independent Holocaust curriculum, according to William Shulman,
president of the Association of Holocaust Organizations in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 10 years, several large American cities with
substantial Jewish populations have built memorials to the Jewish
victims of the Holocaust. A learning center opened in September in
New York and another is planned in Berlin. Hundreds of thousands of
people annually visit Yad Vashem, the Israeli Holocaust Memorial in
Jerusalem. And more than 12 million have visited the United States
Holocaust Museum in Washington since it opened in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But as the field of holocaust studies has grown and the number
of memorials has mushroomed, so has the fear that the Holocaust
will overshadow Judaism. There are plenty of museums dedicated to
Jewish death, a common complaint goes, but not so many dedicated to
Jewish life.
</P>
<P>
   The answer, some rabbis believe, is to ritualize the
commemoration of the Holocaust like the festival of independence.
Passover is a ritualized ceremony celebrating the exodus of the
Hebrews from Israel about 3,500 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Yom HaShoah, which is Hebrew for the day of the Holocaust, has
begun to do that. Started in 1951 in Israel, it comes a week before
Israeli Independence Day on the Jewish calendar. The most
traditional Yom HaShoah ceremony is the lighting of six candles _
one for each of the million killed _ as was done at a service at
the Jewish Community Center in West Palm Beach for about 130
survivors last week.
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, opinions varied about the legacy of the
Holocaust. Several survivors said it does not matter through what
vessel the Holocaust is remembered, but that it is remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not important whether future generations remember me or
my father,'' said survivor Carl Willner. ``What is important is
that they remember the lessons and they remember that catastrophe
starts from very small beginnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Others applauded Steven Spielberg's project to videotape
survivors telling their stories for future archives. About 50,000
survivors have been videotaped so far. Many told of speaking at
schools to educate children. To them, the question of how the
Holocaust will be remembered is less an intellectual argument than
a matter of personal urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time someone says it didn't happen, as long as I am
alive, I am going to answer that it did happen,'' said Ed
Lefkowitz, in his baritone. ``And after I am gone, the people I
have told will be here and they will say it was so. Someone should
always know my story.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
