<HEADER>
A5552 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-COLUMN21-COX     04-20 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barr drawing potential opposition
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If he had to decide right now, Wayne Garner says, he
probably wouldn't run against Rep. Bob Barr next year. But as he
took his leave from the job of state prisons chief last week, the
Democrat couldn't resist a poke at his potential Republican rival.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't sure if the 7th District needs a congressman, Garner
quipped, because ``they've been without one for such a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   If Garner does decide to run against Barr, he'll have company.
Two months after the end of Bill Clinton's impeachment trial, it's
hard to say whether his raised profile will make Barr more
vulnerable in the next election. But it's clear the competition to
see who will oppose him is going to be a lot more spirited.
</P>
<P>
   State Democratic Party Chairman David Worley said seven or eight
people already have talked with him about the race. Among those
already putting together their campaigns are businessman Roger
Kahn, who recently sold out his interest in his company, Empire
Distributors; Floyd County police Chief Jim Free; and Chip Warren,
a former Atlanta policeman who is now vice president of the
International Brotherhood of Police Officers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Garner, former state Sen. Steve Langford, who ran
for governor last year, is being mentioned as a possibility, along
with Rep. Tracy Stallings and former Rep. Tim Perry. After getting
45 percent of the vote on a shoestring budget in last year's race,
Rome businessman Jim Williams also may be contemplating another
run.
</P>
<P>
   A common theme among the Democrats is that with Lockheed and
Dobbins vulnerable and textile jobs leaving the district, the
national attention Barr received over the past year hasn't helped
at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody in the country knows about our congressman,
but not too many know about the district,'' Free said.
</P>
<P>
   The large field of possibilities underscores one reason Barr
could be vulnerable. His district, which stretches from west Cobb
to the outskirts of Chattanooga, has a lot of Democrats in it,
including some powerful ones: Worley, Gov. Roy Barnes and House
Speaker Tom Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes quickly quashed the suggestion earlier this year that he
was looking for a Democrat to oppose Barr, but the governor doesn't
have to do much to have an impact.
</P>
<P>
   As for Barr, he said he's had record attendance at town hall
meetings in his district over the past several weeks. At every
meeting, some voters thank him for his role in the impeachment, he
said, but the focus is now on ``other issues,'' including taxes and
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat who isn't interested in the race is former Rep.
Buddy Darden, who lost the seat to Barr in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever runs needs to know that the numbers in that district
are unfriendly at best,'' Darden said. ``They shouldn't think it
will be easy just because he ran so poorly the last time.''
</P>
<P>
   But that won't stop a lot of Democrats from trying, with Barr
looking more vulnerable and the prospects of raising money to run
against him much better than they were a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
