<SLUG> BC-FIRE-GEL21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thanks to former firefighter, power poles safe
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Flames roar from Homestead to Port St.
Lucie, Fla., but wooden power poles that should be tinder in their
path stand tall thanks to John Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett is the firefighter from Jupiter, Fla. who made national
news and a tidy profit by turning absorbent diaper gel into a
booming fire-shield business.
</P>
<P>
   His curiosity about how a pile of diapers remained uncharred
through a 1993 house fire led to the creation of Barricade, a
solution of water-absorbent polymers that sticks to just about any
surface and wards off flames.
</P>
<P>
   The company he founded sold about $250,000 worth last year,
working mostly out of his father's warehouse-garage. Among his
increasingly loyal customers: FPL, which has rushed spray crews and
pumper trucks to coat poles threatened by the region's wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works, absolutely,'' said Patrick Dennison, the power
company's distribution supervisor in charge of new products and
training methods. ``It's a tremendous thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Heat still may damage poles beyond repair, but they don't
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier and safer to replace them when they're still
standing,'' Dennison said. ``You don't have transformers and wires
on the ground. And you don't have customers without power.''
</P>
<P>
   The company lost more than 800 power poles in the fires that
ravaged Flagler County last summer. Dennison heard about the
success Bartlett had there in saving 20 homes sprayed with
Barricade and asked if the gel could be used on poles.
</P>
<P>
   A bit of experimentation proved it was effective even when
sprayed on poles that are already burning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our crews would douse poles with water, water and more water,
and they'd still reignite,'' Dennison said. ``The gel let us
salvage them before they burned to the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   FPL has five Barricade-filled pump trucks around the state.
Crews also carry back-pack sprayers.
</P>
<P>
   The gel works because the whitish solution that comes out of the
pumps is about 94 percent water, Bartlett said. He likens the
polymers to tiny water-soaked sponges that cling to each other as
well as to the surface they're sprayed on.
</P>
<P>
   ``A power pole burns kind of like a cigarette,'' Bartlett said.
``Slowly and from the inside.'' The coating seals out fresh oxygen
and smothers the fire in the pole's core.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett's company sent a crew to help FPL sprayers in Port St.
Lucie last week. Together, they saved about 100 poles, although 180
were already destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   They were too late to spray Barricade on the already ruined
homes. While a number of fire departments across the country keep
Barricade at the ready, St. Lucie County's isn't one of them, he
said. Martin County's is, but it wasn't there in time to use it.
</P>
<P>
   News of the fires has kept Bartlett busy answering calls from
fire departments and from homeowners. He sells a spray-it-yourself
kit that starts at $189, but enough gel to coat a house can bump
the cost to $500.
</P>
<P>
   Barricade sells for about $35 a gallon. It takes about five to
10 gallons to coat most houses. The household kit comes with a
sprayer. Fire departments don't need any special equipment,
Bartlett said, because standard pumper trucks can spray the
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   After an extended leave to get the company started, Bartlett,
44, has returned to work as a Palm Beach County firefighter. He
leaves most of the business decisions to new CEO David McIntosh,
former chief administrator of the Gunster Yoakley law firm.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the company has been aiming sales efforts overseas _ it
recently changed names from Fire Protection Inc. to Barricade
International _ and at the western U.S. Bartlett was in California
on a demonstration tour when the Port St. Lucie fires broke out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, they have fires every year,'' he said. ``Now it
looks as though Florida is catching up.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Kalajian writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
