<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why a big refund is a bad idea
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now we get to the good news about income taxes: Two out of three
taxpayers will get a refund on their federal taxes, averaging about
$1,563.
</P>
<P>
   It's a refreshing windfall, one that some people like so much
that they build it into their spending expectations every year.
</P>
<P>
   Two points need to be made: One, you shouldn't leave that much
money in Uncle Sam's account next time. Two, it's up to you to
decide whether this year's refund is a toy or a tool. You can party
or plan ahead, and either one will feel good.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Louis Harris survey shows that 23 percent of those who
expect a refund think that it will be more than $2,000. Those are
certainly people who don't mind leaving a lot of extra money with
Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   The survey says that most Americans already plan to do something
fruitful with their refunds. About a third said they plan to save
or invest the money, another third said they will pay debts, and
only one in six said they will buy something.
</P>
<P>
   People get refunds, large or small, because they have too much
withheld for taxes from each paycheck. Bad idea. The surplus ends
up in a government account, rather than going to some purpose that
you select. Think about it this way: That was your money to start
with; you just let the government hold onto it for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that refund represents is an interest-free loan to the
government,'' said Larry W. Nichols, a certified public accountant
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   At work, you can ask your payroll department to help work out a
more accurate estimate of how much you should have withheld. Or you
can call 1-800-829-1040, ask the IRS to send you Publication 919 or
Publication 505, and figure it out yourself.
</P>
<P>
   For this year's refund, there are a number of ways to feel good
by doing good.
</P>
<P>
   _ Put it away for your future. Suppose you put $1,563 into an
individual retirement account, invest it in stocks and earn a 10
percent annual return. Your one-shot investment would grow to
$10,515 in 20 years, $27,273 in 30 years and $70,740 in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   That may not sound like a lot of cash, especially for the
shorter periods and especially because you will have to pay income
taxes on most or all of it when you withdraw the money.
</P>
<P>
   But financial planners will tell you that the hardest part is
getting started. Most people feel proud when they've done the right
thing and rewarded when they see their investment grow. Another
factor is that the first step is the hardest _ once you've started
saving, it gets easier to take the next step.
</P>
<P>
   You might also put a refund away for some other specific goal,
such as buying a house or car, or for the kids' college education.
Believe me, it feels good.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pay off debts. ``When you have an opportunity to make a power
payment on your credit cards, you should take advantage of it,''
said Suzanne Boas, president of the Consumer Credit Counseling
Service of Atlanta. ``In the long term, reducing monthly interest
charges makes a tremendous difference in the total amount you
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Start an emergency fund. It's another thing that you can feel
good about _ knowing that you've got some grocery and rent money
set aside if things go bad. Sooner or later, everybody needs some
cash to fall back on.
</P>
<P>
   _ Give it away. A charitable donation, even if it's only a
fraction of your refund, is bound to give you the warm fuzzies.
Family members or clergymen usually can suggest a favorite
beneficiary. Looking for just the right organization? Check out the
United Way's Web site (www.unitedwayatl.org/Issues/index.htm) or
the National Charities Information Bureau
(www.give.org/qrguide.cfm) for high-quality alternatives.Hank Ezell
writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
