r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMAIL-HUMOR21-COX     04-20 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMAIL-HUMOR21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In cyberspace, everybody's a comic
 &HT;    (EDS: Runs with EMAIL-HUMOR-LIST.)
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Lee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Delete this if you've read it before: A guy logs on to
his computer, calls up his e-mail, and ...
</P>
<P>
   There's the joke about the Barbie head that was sent to the
Smithsonian for analysis as an archaeological discovery. One about
upgrading Girlfriend 1.0 to Wife 1.0. Top 10 lists on any subject
you can imagine. Bill Gates jokes. Smutty jokes. Bar jokes. Work
jokes. Photo, video- and sound-clip jokes.
</P>
<P>
   You've read them before. You may have read them dozens of times
before.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you hit the delete key as soon as you saw an ``FWD'' in
the subject line. Or maybe you forwarded them to your entire
address book.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, it seems, everyone's a comedian, but not
everybody is funny. How many times can you scroll through dozens of
such jokes before you come up with your own list: ``The Top 10
reasons I hate the forward button''?
</P>
<P>
   50 Fun Things to Do in an Elevator: No. 1. Make race car noises
when anyone gets on or off. No. 2. Blow your nose and offer to show
the contents of your Kleenex to other passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, somebody's reading. E-mailed jokes have spawned several
books, dozens of World Wide Web sites and millions of groans and
chuckles. The water cooler and fax machine? Just beta versions of
the ultimate joke-dispensing machine. If you're typing busily away,
who's to say that you're reading jokes instead of working (unless
your employer monitors e-mail)?
</P>
<P>
   The Top 2 reasons people love e-mail humor: It brightens up
their day, and it's a good way to stay in touch with friends. The
Top 2 reasons people hate e-mail humor: They see the same bad jokes
repeatedly, and it's an impersonal way for friends to stay in
touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the trend toward communicating without
communicating,'' says Alice Kahn, co-editor of ``Your Joke Is in
the E-Mail: Cyberlaffs From Mousepotatoes'' (Ten Speed Press,
$7.95). ``It's like when you call someone and you don't really want
to talk to them, you just want to leave a message on the answering
machine and get credit for the call.''
</P>
<P>
   Such callers don't get credit anymore from Bill Orr, 27, a
Buckhead lawyer who set up the e-mail equivalent of call blocking
after a few months of humor spam. Anything sent from known
jokesters to him and at least one other person gets trashed,
courtesy of a filter he set up in his e-mail program. That way, he
doesn't have to read the jokes _ ``a bunch of crud,'' he calls them
_ and he doesn't have to offend friends by telling them to knock it
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``An '80s Love Story''
</P>
<P>
   I was working part time in a five and dime. My boss was Mr.
Magee. He was 6-foot-4 and full of muscles and walked liked an
Egyptian, but I was happy to be stuck with him. One manic Monday,
while I was busy working for the weekend, I overheard him make a
careless whisper. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that one was really stupid when I got it, and I
thought it was stupid when I got it the next eight or 10 times,''
says Steve Knopper, a Chicago free-lance writer who compiles Yahoo
Internet Life's Forward of the Day joke site.
</P>
<P>
   Knopper receives dozens of such jokes daily. Usually uncredited,
they may be ``borrowed'' from such comedians as Steven Wright,
Jerry Seinfeld or Norm Macdonald, or from humor Web sites such as
the Onion. Sometimes it's tough finding one good enough to proclaim
Forward of the Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem funny at the time, then when I'm on deadline and
struggling to find one, they all suck,'' Knopper says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet they're not all horrible. He's started joke chains himself,
sending copies of an Onion story about a blues singer to friends.
Six hours and several generations later, someone forwarded it to
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wife 1.0''
</P>
<P>
   Last year a friend of mine upgraded Girlfriend 1.0 to Wife 1.0
and found that it's a memory hog leaving very little system
resources for other applications. ... He's finding that some other
applications such as PokerNight 8.3, BeerBash 2.5 and PubNight 7.0
are no longer able to run in the system at all....
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Sutton, 30, of Duluth, Ga. lists Wife 1.0 as her
favorite e-mail joke, but there's only so much risque humor she can
take _ and none at work, please. She had just learned about her new
employer's e-mail monitoring policy when a friend forwarded a
sketch. Set up like the label of a vegetable can, it wasn't exactly
advertising greenery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to be asparagus, but it did not look like
asparagus,'' says Sutton. ``I thought I was going to throw up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahem.
</P>
<P>
   The gender gap lives on in cyberspace. Put-downs of both sexes
and off-color humor abound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opens up a whole new world of sexual harassment via
computer,'' says Alice Gamble, 36, of Atlanta, who receives about
50 joke e-mails daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad, who's your typical engineer, sends me jokes that I
would never expect him to,'' she says. ``I had some of the more
risque e-mails coming from some of my conservative friends. I'm not
sure what that's about.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble likes having a little humor pop up unexpectedly during
the day, so she sent lots of jokes after she got an e-mail account
last year. Now that the novelty has worn off, she's more selective.
</P>
<P>
   How many Microsoft engineers does it take to change a light
bulb?
</P>
<P>
   None. Bill Gates will just redefine Darkness as the new industry
standard.
</P>
<P>
   For some people, the novelty of Internet humor never wears off.
For them, cyberspace is a limitless comedy show.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Loveless, 32, of Monticello, Ga. loves to receive jokes, and
keeps an archive of his favorites. It's at 667 and growing.
</P>
<P>
   Not too long ago, through a typo, his address was added to
someone's e-mailed humor list. The joke was cute, so Loveless wrote
back. Now he gets up to 20 e-mails a week from the guy.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Lee writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
