<HEADER>
A5558 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOCKTV-NASH21-COX     04-20 1582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOCKTV-NASH21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    He's the shock king of reality TV
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Bruce Nash's philosophy on hooking
viewers is simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a movie of the week, you've only got one shot to get 'em
and you've gotta get 'em good,'' says the man behind such TV
specials as When Good Pets Go Bad and World's Scariest Police
Shootouts. ``It's got to be compelling. The World's Deadliest
Whatever. Look right at the title. It says `Watch me!''
</P>
<P>
   More and more, viewers are doing just that. Nash's in-your-face
reality shows have become ratings gold for Fox, NBC and ABC. For
instance, Breaking The Magician's Code: Magic's Biggest Secrets
Finally Revealed drew more than 24 million viewers in November
1997, making it Fox's highest rated special ever. More than 18
million people watched pit bulls mauling kids and old ladies on
When Good Pets Go Bad. And World's Most Amazing Videos, NBC's new
Wednesday night reality series from Nash, is doing well, too.
</P>
<P>
   But critics hiss that such grisly shows _ fuel tank explosions,
mid-air jet collisions and navy crewmen being sucked into a jet
engine _ are nothing more than glossy ``shockumentaries'' that
don't belong on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's much different from people stopping at a
train wreck,'' says Meryl Marshall, chairman and CEO of the Academy
of Television Arts and Sciences. ``I don't believe it's the best
use of the medium.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash, 51, who heads the Los Angeles-based Nash Entertainment,
dismisses his many detractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do shockumentaries. We do non-fiction programming.
Hey, we're not going to cure cancer with what we're doing, but at
least we're trying to tell dramatic stories.''
</P>
<P>
   So how did a guy who grew up in West Palm Beach, graduated from
Forest Hill High School and Florida Atlantic University get into a
line of work like this?
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Bruce Nash is an idea man. He reads everything. He
needs newspapers and magazines like the rest of us need air. He's
always hunting for the next hot trend. That special something he
can tweak, promote and turn into a jaw-dropping TV show.
</P>
<P>
   Nash keeps a pad of ideas in different rooms of his house as
well as one in his Los Angeles office. He keeps several hundred
ideas with him at all times and likes to come up with 10 new ones
each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding a new idea is what charges me up,'' says the boyishly
excited Nash, who pitches about one-third of his brainchilds.
``It's like treasure. It's more valuable than money.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash started out writing trivia books on such disparate topics
as Elvis, ghosts and baseball. Soon after, he began peppering
Hollywood with script ideas. After countless rejections, Hollywood
finally liked what it saw.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Nash was reading People a few years ago and
noticed that Volcano and Dante's Peak, two similar disaster movies,
were coming out at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a blurb, but I said, `I can capitalize on all the
promotion they're going to do with these two movies,''' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   The result: World's Deadliest Volcanos, which aired on ABC. Not
only did Nash get ABC to pick up World's Deadliest Volcanos, the
determined TV producer convinced the network to give him a World's
Deadliest franchise. ABC has since aired World's Deadliest Storms
and World's Deadliest Sea Creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Nash's knack for giving viewers what they want has been noticed.
Fox Family Channel has inquired about producing a cartoon based on
_ can you believe this? _ When Good Pets Go Bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about some pets that get all rough and tough when pushed
around,'' says Nash.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, NBC may have publicly blasted Fox in the past for
airing such gross-out reality specials as When Animals Attack, but
after those garish shows started getting huge ratings, not only did
NBC stop bashing Fox, it even asked Nash to crank out specials for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can have Bruce work for us, there are less specials he
can do for Fox,'' boasts John Miller, NBC's executive vice
president of event programming. ``When you can't beat 'em, hire 'em
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Nash producing World's Most Amazing Videos for NBC,
which the network picked up for 13 episodes next season, he's also
producing You Asked For It, a '90s version of the '50s game show in
which people call in and ask for strange things they want to see on
TV, like lady sumo wrestlers and five-legged pigs. You Asked For It
is scheduled to air in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Nash is also partnering with some of TV's heavy-hitters, namely
Ted Harbert, former chairman of ABC Entertainment and Warren
Littlefield, former NBC Entertainment President. Harbert is now a
producer at Dreamworks SKG and with Nash is developing Dates From
Hell, a one-hour anti-Love American Style comedy and The Ludermans,
a futuristic family sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV thrives on people like Bruce because TV eats up so many
ideas and Bruce is one of the best idea machines I've come
across,'' says Harbert, who has known Nash for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Littlefield is working with Nash on a wrestling sitcom for NBC.
``There will be people who don't like his work and the answer for
them is that's why there's Bassmasters is on cable. There are many
choices out there. If you don't like it, execute your free will not
to watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Why are so many viewers watching Nash's shows?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce has a very keen sense of what makes the adrenaline rush
and what makes compelling visuals,'' says Tim Brooks, co-author of
The Complete Directory To Prime Time And Cable TV Shows. ``There's
been a lot of other syndicated stuff with the host lumbering around
at the beginning and telling you what you're going to see and the
re-creations were awkwardly cut into the middle of it. Bruce cut
out all that stuff. He said, `Let's cut right to the chase.' He
knows how close he can get to the edge without going over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash believes his shows are successful because they're
unpredictable. In a scripted, formulaic TV world, most dramas and
comedies are far from original.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this stuff, you don't know what's going to happen next. A
cop stops a guy for speeding and the guy pulls a gun _ what's going
to happen next? What's going to happen next?''
</P>
<P>
   It's also important, says Nash, that viewers already know that
no one dies.
</P>
<P>
   To put together a reality TV show, Nash relies on 50 staffers.
He says they comb video libraries, foreign news services, contact
news stringers, police departments, prisons, local TV stations, and
conduct massive Internet searches to find eye-popping footage. Nash
says clips normally cost anywhere from several thousand to a couple
of hundred thousand dollars. The most Nash ever paid for a clip was
$10,000. That was for Fox's upcoming The Road To Fame, a special
about what stars did before they got famous.
</P>
<P>
   Nash snared a brief clip of Tom Cruise and Heather Locklear
doing a screen test together for the 1982 TV series, The Powers of
Matthew Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extraordinary to have both of them so young in the same
clip, so the casting director held us up,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Nash is not your typical Hollywood insider. Nash was born in
Brooklyn, moved to Long Island when he was 4, then to West Palm
Beach at age 8. His mom was a teacher (she lives in Delray, Fla.),
his dad a jeweler (he died of a heart attack in 1984 at age 63.)
His grandfather was a butcher and lived next door to Nash's folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were hardworking people and that's what I carried out
here (to Los Angeles),'' he says. ``I didn't have it made. I came
out here hungry, with the eye of the tiger.''
</P>
<P>
   Nash's route to Hollywood was certainly unconventional. With a
B.S. and Masters in Criminology from Florida State, Nash was the
director of planning and research at the North Carolina Department
of Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   But the imaginative TV trivia buff and wannabe author yearned
for something more.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to always write stories in elementary school,''
remembers Greg Nash, Bruce's 44-year-old brother who owns Nash
Jewelry in West Palm. ``When I was four, he made up stories about
pirates and left all kinds of treasure notes around the house. It
was like a little game for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Nash was so obsessed with entertainment and TV Guide (he'd
go to the library to read every issue), he wrote Tube Teasers, a TV
trivia book at age 25. Soon after, Nash quit his corrections gig to
pursue his dream of becoming a Hollywood writer. Nash has since
published 80 books on such subjects as pets, baseball and ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   But Nash wanted to write for TV. NBC finally bit when it bought
America's Best Kept Secrets. But Nash's big break came in 1994 when
ABC aired his Before They Were Stars, which topped the mighty
Murder, She Wrote in the ratings. Such mild reality specials as The
Secret World of Dreams and TV's All-Time Favorites soon followed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, breaking free of the ``Shock King'' TV tag is a goal for
Nash. Reality shows, he points out, represent a small fraction of
what he wants to do. ``There's nothing wrong with what I'm doing, I
just feel there are other things out there for me to do that could
be my legacy,'' he says. ``I want to do sitcoms, dramas and movies.
You can only be so creative when you're doing real stories. And I
know I'm not going to win any prizes with this stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin D. Thompson writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
