<HEADER>
A5559 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COURIER21-COX     04-20 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COURIER21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courier hopes not to repeat '98 AT&AMP;T ChallengeBy Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the second year in a row, Jim Courier will come to
the AT&AMP;T Challenge as the reigning U.S. Davis Cup hero. The former
world No. 1 only hopes it will be different this time.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Courier saved the American team with a five-set
victory over Marat Safin of Russia in the deciding fifth match in
the first round. Courier followed that up two weeks later by
winning a clay-court tournament in Orlando, his hometown. He
survived Michael Chang 7-5, 3-6, 7-5 in a final that exhausted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I went to Atlanta tired and lost in the first round,''
Courier said. ``I seemed to lose my momentum after that.''
</P>
<P>
   In his one-night stand on stadium court at Atlanta Athletic
Club, qualifier Marcio Carlsson beat him 6-3, 2-6, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Plagued by an arm injury that had him pondering retirement,
Courier would win just three more matches through the U.S. Open. He
endured one stretch of five consecutive first-round losses and
plunged as low as No. 118 on the ATP Tour computer. He finished the
year No. 76, his first final ranking outside the top 30 since he
turned pro as an 18-year-old in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Courier is optimistic that 1998 was an injury-induced
aberration, just as 1997 was for Todd Martin. Courier's Davis Cup
teammate was shelved for seven months with an elbow ailment, but
now he's back in the top 10. Martin's elbow still gets sore, but
Courier's arm is fully healed. If he could just watch his step.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rolled my foot in Memphis, Tenn. and tweaked my groin in
Australia, but my arm is no longer an issue,'' Courier said. ``Last
year, I was still trying to fiddle with my racket and my training
for my arm, to find out if I was going to be able to keep playing
or if I was going to have to hang it up. So, I don't have that dark
cloud hanging over me right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Most encouraging is that Courier is playing better now than he
did a year ago. Leading up to the match against Russia here last
year, Andre Agassi openly lobbied for U.S. captain Tom Gullikson to
bypass the slumping Courier for Jan-Michael Gambill. And while
Courier's victory over Safin was inspiring for its show of
willpower and clever strategy, it wasn't great tennis. The Russian
teenager led 6-0, 4-1 before Courier stared him into blinking under
the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   This month's triumph over Great Britain was another story
altogether. Courier faced two heavyweights in No. 7 Tim Henman and
No. 11 Greg Rusedski on an indoor surface tailored to the Brits'
fast games. Courier's warrior heart wouldn't be enough this time.
He had to play like the Courier who won the Australian and French
Opens six years ago. Courier defeated both 7-5 in the fifth set,
breaking each at love to clinch the epic battles that lasted two
minutes short of eight hours combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing here is that all the other players around the
world are aware of what happened, and they know I beat two good
players under really adverse circumstances,'' said Courier, ranked
No. 54. ``That goes a long way toward (re-establishing) the fear
factor. If I can get the fear factor back in the locker room, then
I can go back on the court already up a break against a lot of
guys. That carries a lot of weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier, 28, now can put his Davis Cup achievements on the same
mantel as his 58 weeks at No. 1 in 1992-93 and his four Grand Slam
titles. The U.S. is 13-0 when Courier is in the lineup. Courier's
latest heroics surpass the comeback against Safin and the clinching
wins in 1997 against Brazil (vs. Gustavo Kuerten) and the
Netherlands (against Jan Siemerink after trailing two sets to
love). Given a couple of weeks to think about it, Courier still
can't find anything that beats his Great Britain conquest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given all the circumstances _ playing on foreign soil, playing
on not my best surface and playing two players ranked No. 7 and No.
11,'' Courier said, ``I don't have any better performances than
that.''
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T CHALLENGE
</P>
<P>
   _ When: Monday through May 2 (qualifying rounds Saturday and
Sunday).
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Atlanta Athletic Club, Duluth, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   _ Top players: Patrick Rafter, Michael Chang, Jim Courier,
Jan-Michael Gambill, Mark Woodforde and Todd Woodbridge.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tickets: 404-249-6400.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Holcomb writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
