<HEADER>
A5563 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAITH-PSYCHIATRY21-CO     04-20 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAITH-PSYCHIATRY21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Can faith, prayer heal mentally ill? Ohio doctor wants to know
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ People don't expect to see a yarmulke on their
psychiatrist's head, but Dr. David Rube says they're often
reassured at the sight of his. It tells them they are welcome to
talk about God here, even if they don't share his Orthodox Jewish
faith.
</P>
<P>
   That's not true in every psychiatrist's office, Rube (pronounced
``Ruby'') says. Many of his colleagues prefer to keep spirituality
as far from their practices as palm reading or spoon bending. ``The
history of psychiatry has been extremely secular,'' he says,
``taking the view that religion is something to be interpreted and
is a neurotic defense mechanism.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Rube says psychiatrists often shut out their
patients' spiritual sides at a time when they're most likely to
surface. That's one reason he developed the course for residents at
that Wright State University School of Medicine that was awarded
nationally last week for incorporating spirituality into medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Rube isn't saying religion should always be a part of
psychiatry, just that it shouldn't always be excluded. His goal is
to reduce the common biases not only that doctors have against
discussing religion but also that churchgoers have against seeing
psychiatrists.
</P>
<P>
   ``If doctors in training are exposed to these practices and
views, hopefully they'll be more well-rounded when their patients
come in,'' says Rube. ``So when the subject comes up, the
psychiatrist isn't squirming in his seat and the patient doesn't
feel he can't talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the agnostic doctor should find the information useful, he
says, considering ``what we do in psychiatry is figure out ways to
help people open up doors.''
</P>
<P>
   The slow but growing acceptance that faith plays a role in
health is surfacing more and more in med school curricula, says the
National Institute for Healthcare Research, which presented the
Spirituality and Medicine Awards to seven schools. NIHR has
encouraged much of the research behind that acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``These programs reflect the growing necessity within the
medical community to focus on all dimensions of patient care _ the
physical, emotional and spiritual,'' says Dr. Christina M.
Puchalski, NIHR's education director.
</P>
<P>
   The Wright State course will focus on Rube's specialty of
children and teen-agers as psychiatry director at The Children's
Medical Center. But research has associated faith with healing
across age groups as well as medical specialties. People who
regularly pray or attend religious services have demonstrated
better recovery rates from heart surgery, depression, orthopedic
surgery, drug addiction and hospitalizations in general among
people older than 60.
</P>
<P>
   One team of Swiss investigators even felt the need 2 years ago
to demonstrate statistically that ``being highly religious was not
a risk factor for neuroticism, as has been often taught in
psychiatric training programs,'' NIHR summarized.
</P>
<P>
   The connection between belief systems and anatomical systems is
still widely ignored by the medical establishment. In a survey of
doctors last year, only 9 percent thought faith might significantly
help patients deal with illness, compared with 40 percent of
hospital patients who said it helped them. In other studies of
seriously ill patients, more than nine out of 10 called prayer a
helpful coping mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   That helps explain why NIHR has found that people with mental
health disorders are more likely to turn to clergy than to
psychiatrists and psychologists combined. ``It's imperative that
those of us in the mental health community begin working more
closely with the clergy,'' says Dr. David B. Larson, the NIHR
president, who determined last year that only 2 out of 10,000
reports in psychology journals from 1991 through '94 even
considered clergy in their research.
</P>
<P>
   It's hardly press-stopping news that people who get sick turn to
prayer. ``I see patients with schizophrenia, manic depression,
horrible diseases,'' Rube says. ``If they can find comfort from
whatever church, synagogue or mosque they attend, I encourage it.''
</P>
<P>
   He cites Alcoholics Anonymous as a rare but successful union of
religion with health care. The first three of its 12 steps for
shaking addiction involve relinquishing control to a greater Power,
which AA leaves to every individual to define.
</P>
<P>
   Any psych patient who grew up with strong Catholic or Jewish
influence knows that guilt is a place where religion and therapy
overlap, Rube says. Without understanding that religious
groundwork, a psychiatrist would have a hard time ``helping people
process what is the difference between appropriate guilt and guilt
that is irrational.''
</P>
<P>
   Rube's two-semester course will cover such classroom topics as
the religious and educational fundamentals of Catholicism,
Christianity, Judaism and Islam; the spiritual needs of children
and of families with sick or injured kids, and the roles of
pastoral care and religious school counselors. Hospital chaplains
and religious school administrators will be among the faculty.
</P>
<P>
   The second semester will take students out of the classroom to
schools, hospitals and hospitals' pastoral departments. ``The goal
is to assess firsthand how spirituality, religiosity, mental health
and academic issues are dealt with in a religious school setting,''
Rube said in accepting the award. One of the things students will
see firsthand there is the stigma that goes with being marked for
mental health treatment in a religious population.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all need to understand the importance of being sensitive to
a belief system,'' Rube says. ``Whether it's Jewish or Catholic or
whatever, a lot of people find some sort of grounding helpful. As
psychiatrists, we need to know how we can work within that belief
system without being judgmental.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 1054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0062 </DOCNO>
