   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   ARTS-GRANTS _ Report on new grants from the NEA, including
several to Atlanta arts groups. Weave in related topic of Michael
Hightower testifying in Congress in favor of Clinton's proposed 50%
NEA budget increase. (Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CADILLAC-VOODOO _ AUSTIN, Texas _ For a band that likes to bare
its chest hair, and that gets the award for the local act most
likely to see female fans baring their chests, the five members of
Cadillac Voodoo Choir are actually pretty down-to-earth guys. ``Put
this in your article and write it as the headline,'' drummer and
CVC mouth Taxi Haskell says excitedly, into his third or fourth
cocktail. ``The Cadillac Voodoo Choir are rock stars. We are rock
stars, because no one else is doing it these days.''
(Riemenschneider, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SHOCKTV-NASH _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Bruce Nash's philosophy
on hooking viewers is simple. ``Like a movie of the week, you've
only got one shot to get 'em and you've gotta get 'em good,'' says
the man behind such TV specials as When Good Pets Go Bad and
World's Scariest Police Shootouts. ``It's got to be compelling. The
World's Deadliest Whatever. Look right at the title. It says `Watch
me!'' More and more, viewers are doing just that. Nash's
in-your-face reality shows have become ratings gold for Fox, NBC
and ABC. (Thompson, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
