<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, April 20, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for the
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-FOUNDATIONS (San Francisco) _ While stock-rich
philanthropies are giving away more money than ever, foundation
support for AIDS causes has dropped sharply in the past three
years, according to a survey of charitable foundations. The decline
in foundation giving mirrors widespread reports of a steep drop in
individual donations hitting AIDS groups in many parts of the
country. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   SF-POOR (San Francisco) _ Mayor Willie Brown has become the
latest in a series of San Francisco mayors to zero in on people who
are down and out as re-election draws near. With just more than six
months before he goes before voters seeking a second term, Brown is
backing legislation to crack down on panhandlers. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DYING-LISTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ To-do lists usually are reserved
for trips to the grocery store, or projects or weddings. Not many
folks list the things they want done when they die. And as baby
boomers lose their parents these days, many find their grief woven
thick with questions they can never answer. By KATE GURNETT.
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL-RECORDING (Troy, N.Y.) _ It began as a small venture:
recording performances of a community symphony orchestra. Today
Craig Dory and Brian Levine of Dorian Recordings. The company
boasts one of the biggest international profiles of any independent
label in the rarefied world of classical recordings. By AMY
BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BOOK-DIRECTORS (Undated) _ Forget Monica Lewinsky. Forget
George Stephanopoulos. This is the real deal. ``Easy Riders, Raging
Bulls,'' the story of Young Turk directors having their way with
Hollywood in the 1970s, dishes more dirt than all the White House
tell-alls could ever dream of doing. By EVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALON-IPO (San Francisco) _ Three weeks ago, Salon Internet Inc.
announced it would change its name to Salon.com, so it came as no
great surprise when the inevitable follow-up announcement arrived:
The San Francisco Web 'zine is going public. By JOHN BERGER.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-CRUISES (Aboard the Norway) _ The first Sports
Illustrated Afloat cruise aboard the Norwegian Cruise Line's Norway
was rated an overwhelming success by both passengers (some 1,500)
and athletes (13 on the ship's team). So the two companies plan to
do it again this year, featured some great sports talent. By BARRY
ROBINSON.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ There is some irony in San
Francisco's Transportation Authority rejecting The Foot. The half-
million-dollar sculpture represented the only reliable form of
transportation in San Francisco. But it also represented the most
reliable way to cause a stink in San Francisco: Propose a piece of
public art. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ My heart leapt when I read about
a possible parallel universe discovered a mere 44 light years away.
While it would come as no surprise to the late ``Star Trek''
creator Gene Roddenberry, this discovery gives us further reason to
presume . . . we are not alone. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ The toasts and speeches that
attended the recent reception of the Tula-Albany Alliance for two
visiting Soviet cosmonauts framed the dilemma facing the American
people and their government as the air war against Serbian
brutality in Kosovo is pressed. By HARRY ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   RISING-OCEANS (San Francisco) _ Three regions of the United
States are threatened more than others by a rise in sea level from
global warming. The San Francisco Bay Area is one of them.
According to a study by the research group Pacific Institute,
business and residential structures near the shores of San
Francisco Bay, presently valued at an estimated $48 billion, will
be threatened by a 3-foot rise in the Bay. By JOE MIRABILE.
</P>
</TEXT>
