   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOS AND THREE COLOR ILLUSTRATIONS
</P>
<P>
   THE POKIMON INVASION: Move over, Beanie Babies. Pokimon have
seized the day. And, like those cuddly, stuffed, fabled toys of
yesterday's trend, there's seemingly a million of 'em. Since
hitting the U.S. market in September 1998, Nintendo has sold 1.5
million units, making it the fastest-selling Gameboy game ever.
(Includes one 3-column color illustration and two 1-column
illustrations of Pokimon characters; one 3-column photo from
Pokimon web site.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH BRIEFS: Computers and operating systems break down
all too often. Now you can find solutions to some problems: The
cover story of the April issue of Windows magazine is devoted to
fixing 15 common PC problems. (Includes one 1-column color photo of
a printer.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: It wasn't too long ago that computers were
fairly easy to understand and fix. Nowadays, computers are so
complex that most of us are way over our heads when it comes to
working on them. (Includes 1-column color mug shot of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BLACK COLLEGE TECH: Students at historically black
colleges and universities have less access than most other students
to the computer technology that is a key to today's cutting-edge
jobs, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PAGE INCLUDES THREE COLOR PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   CANCUN: I had, with some skepticism, signed up for an ``el
cheapo'' package to Cancun. I found that even with a discount
package, Mexico's tourist capital can be a budget-buster. (Includes
one 4-column color photo and two 2-column color photos of author
enjoying his vacation.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: INFO BOX: A fact box on Cancun.
</P>
