President Slobodan Milosevic in Kosovo makes George Mosse's
enlightening volume on the nature of fascism especially timely. As
Lawrence Wechsler recently noted in The New Yorker, Milosevic is a
classic fascist. His appeal is to a kind of fanatical Serbian
nationalism; he is popular; he has fused the historic sense of
Serbian victimhood with a cult of blood vengeance against
non-Serbs. (Includes one 3-column color photo of children refugees
in Kosovo.)
</P>
