<P>
   PRESERVING AMERICA'S HISTORY _ ON PAPER: The principles have
stood the test of time _ it's the ink words and the sheepskin
parchments they were written on that worry archivists charged with
taking care of three of the most important documents in American
history: the Constitution, the Declaration of Independence and the
Bill of Rights. Enter scientists at NASA's Langley Research Center.
A research team has used a laser to peer inside the glass case that
holds the original documents. Their work proves that protective
gases injected into the cases 40 years ago are still inside. This
also will help archivists safely transfer the documents into new
cases. (Includes 3-column color photo of laser and 1-column color
photo of measuring device.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MAGNETS: Therapeutic magnets have been around for more
than six decades in Asia and in Europe. Here, however, the Food and
Drug Administration has not approved their use, although it hasn't
banned them either. Instead, they've been treated as a harmless
form of fringe treatment. But in the past five years, doctors and
biophysicists have been giving magnets another look. (Includes
2-column color photo of patient receiving magnatherapy treatment.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CONTACTS: CIBA Vision, a contact lens manufacturer,
recently began widespread distribution of its new Focus Dailies
lenses. The lenses are notable for their convenience and low cost,
but especially for their reputed comfort. (Includes 1-column color
photo of woman putting a contact lens in her eye.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS: About 5.3 million Americans are living with
long-term disabilities caused by traumatic brain injuries,
according to a recent study by the Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention.
</P>
