<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5687 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSICAL-RECORDING-H     04-20 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-RECORDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMALL RECORDING LABEL IS MAKING A CLASSICAL SPLASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ Pablo Cora was stretched out on the dull-gray
carpet, legs crossed, arms behind his head, mouth pursed in a hard
line of concentration.
</P>
<P>
   Above him hung a naked 75-watt bulb. Beside him, in chairs and
on the floor, sat six young men of similar age and intensity, two
of them balancing scores on their knees.
</P>
<P>
   Around them swirled the airy, ancient harmonies of an old
Renaissance Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Words from the ``Agnus'' scudded along Tomas Luis de Victoria's
music, written four centuries ago for an ensemble of seven pristine
male singers. Back then, monks probably sang it. But at 6:15 on a
Thursday night in 1999, the voices belonged to the Concord
Ensemble, a luminous a cappella sextet (plus an extra countertenor,
for the occasion) from Bloomington, Ind., who were gathered in Troy
Savings Bank Music Hall to record their debut compact disc with
Dorian Recordings.
</P>
<P>
   They had just sung one portion of the Mass. Now, huddled around
two five-foot speakers in a spartan recording booth along with Tina
Chancey, their bristly, go-to producer, and Craig Dory, Dorian's
president, co-founder and droll engineering guru, they listened.
And listened. And listened some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``That last note...'' said Chancey, speaking to Cora. ``Too
sharp?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes it sounds hard to sing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to sing,'' said Cora, like he meant it.
</P>
<P>
   It had been a long week of late-night recording sessions. Long
hours of singing in the hall. Long stretches of listening in the
booth. Lots of sharps to pull down, flats to push up, phrases to
shape and chords to nail. Lots of suggestions from Chancey, lots of
them. And lots of time spent sitting, standing and lying flat in a
10-by-12 hermetically sealed cereal box in the farthest reaches of
the building.
</P>
<P>
   Way, way up, past the lobby, past the hall's main floor, past
the dress circle, past the balcony, past the gallery, at the top of
a broad staircase, hides the recording booth leased and occupied by
Dorian. If you didn't already know it was there, you'd never find
it. It's a low-profile operation.
</P>
<P>
   The same can't be said for Dorian Recordings, based in the
upstate New York city of Troy. The company now boasts one of the
biggest international profiles of any independent label in the
rarefied world of classical recordings. Only one other independent
company, Telarc, is bigger.
</P>
<P>
   But Dorian has built its business on being at once low-key and
high-profile, laid-back and ferociously competitive. It's known for
allowing its artists plenty of room, plenty of input. And it's
known for producing one gorgeous compact disc after another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever been to a movie, and seen a scene that makes you cry?
Just all of a sudden you're crying with people on the (screen)?
That's what I want to bring to the music _ not the tears, but that
sense of emotion,'' said Dory, the articulate bear of a man who
co-founded the label with Brian Levine (Dory plus Brian equals
Dorian).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not interested in working with artists who can't swell
up something inside of you. If they can't do it, we're not talking
to 'em. And on a recording, how successful I am as an engineer in
making a great record is how well I can put that emotion on tape
and have it played back for the listener. In other words, if you
get goose pimples or get choked up or you laugh, I did my job, and
the artists did their job.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dory, it's that simple and that complicated. A mathematician
with a musician's ear (he plays flute and sax), Dory was working at
Bell Labs in New Jersey when his wife, a violinist, joined a
chamber orchestra in the New York City area. Long interested in the
science of recording and long equipped with the gizmos to do it, he
started recording their concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Then he started recording other musicians' concerts. And as he
recorded, he figured out the recipe for a good disc how to make one
deliberately, rather than tempting fate with happy accidents. By
the late 1980s he had a regular gig recording the now-defunct
Cathedral Symphony of Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Levine, an executive at a Canadian children's
charity, was moonlighting as an agent for the organist Jean
Guillou. When Guillou performed a concert with the Cathedral
Symphony, Dory recorded it. That recording wasn't a keeper, but the
one that followed a smaller effort, featuring Guillou's solo work
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``That constituted our first recording,'' said Dory, ``for this
new label called Dorian.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Levine remains in Toronto, where he handles the artists' end of
things: He sniffs out new musicians, maintains relationships with
old ones and takes charge of the programming for upcoming CDs.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of it. In Dorian's plump catalog reside 250-plus
compact discs in three main genres: early music (loosely meaning
anything written before 1800), acoustic traditional music and, the
newest arrival by far, jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Dorian more than doubled its new releases from 23 last year to
50 this year. That compares to the 35 produced by the major label
BMG and the 60 by the hulking Sony.
</P>
<P>
   The last few years were tough ones for the classical-recording
industry: staffs were cut, revenues were down and returns were up.
(``It's tough to pay telephone bills with CDs,'' Dory said). Things
are looking better, but still a mere 2.3 percent of all American
record sales are classical-music purchases.
</P>
<P>
   In the pie of all recordings, the classics account for a
minuscule slice.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the trouble is the limited repertoire churned out by
most labels, which have drowned the market in new recordings of old
war horses. Even the most dedicated audiophile can only own so many
recordings of Beethoven's 9th Symphony. Dorian has survived by
promoting neglected music _ long-lost medieval polyphony, for
instance, or music from the American Civil War and by focusing on
technical and artistic quality.
</P>
<P>
   Sheer chutzpah helps. In the middle of the industry drought,
while other labels were paring back their output, Dorian made its
plans to expand. It was a risky move but, as they saw it,
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a choice in this business: grow or die,'' Dory said.
</P>
<P>
   In Levine's words: ``You can be a moving target or a smashed
one.''
</P>
<P>
   One result is this year's fattened catalog. Another is its
embryonic jazz list, which the pair hope to christen with a few big
names (they won't say which).
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't even scratched the scratch-and-smell for jazz
yet,'' Dory said. ``We're figuring out how we're gonna do it. We
have projects in mind, but we need more critical mass to launch a
label.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Levine: ``We're trying to bite off one enormously oversize
chunk at a time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
