<HEADER>
A5699 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPORTS-CRUISES-HNS &LR;      04-20 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-CRUISES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMCHAIR QUARTERBACKS NEED NOT TAKE THIS CRUISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BARRY ROBINSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE NORWAY _ Ozzie Smith, one of the greatest fielding
shortstops ever, patiently showed a 65-year-old baseball fan the
proper technique of fielding a grounder up the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Carson, an all-pro middle linebacker who led the New York
Giants to victory in Super Bowl XXI, had a good time teaching a
60-year-old lady how to rush the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Weatherspoon, defensive player of the year the last two
seasons in the WNBA, encouraged a middle-aged father of five to get
lower and spread his arms and legs on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Mikita, a hockey hall-of-famer, taught children and adults,
male and female, the secret of a successful slap shot.
</P>
<P>
   The first Sports Illustrated Afloat cruise aboard the Norwegian
Cruise Line's Norway was rated an overwhelming success by both
passengers (some 1,500) and athletes (13 on the team).
</P>
<P>
   The Dec. 5, seven-day sailing from Miami to St. Maarten, St.
John, St. Thomas and Great Stirrup Cay, Norwegian's private island,
highlights a unique corporate relationship worked out between
Sports Illustrated and Norwegian Cruise Line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a post-mortem meeting with Sports Illustrated in New
York and we were both delighted with the cruise and the
relationship,'' said Nina Cohen, vice president of marketing for
the cruise line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got feedback from the passengers and athletes and everyone
was positive. The guests were totally knocked out. They had such a
great time. They couldn't believe the accessibility of the
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``And all of the athletes enjoyed it. In fact, they all want to
do it again this year. They were so good interacting with the
passengers. They turned adults into kids. The adults were as giddy
as kids,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The athletes had such a good time, it presents Norwegian Cruise
Lines and Sports Illustrated with somewhat of a problem. All the
athletes want to do it again so it will be difficult adding
different athletes for the 1999 Sports Afloat sailing, scheduled
Dec. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes on the cruise were baseball players Darren Bragg, Dave
Mlicki, Smith and Don Mattingly; basketball players James Worthy,
John Havlicek and Weatherspoon; retired hockey greats Mikita and
Brad Park; retired NFL players Carson and Norm Bulaich; golf
instructor Larry Shaver; and Olympic gold medalist Al Joyner.
(Joyner's wife, the Olympic great Florence Griffith Joyner, died
before the cruise.)
</P>
<P>
   Although the courtship between Sports Illustrated and Norwegian
Cruise Line is relatively new, Norwegian has long been recognized
as the most sports-minded of the cruise lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``First time my agent booked me on a sports cruise was in 1984,
and it was on this same ship,'' Worthy said.
</P>
<P>
   For years, the line has had separate cruises featuring athletes
from the NHL, NFL, NBA, baseball and fitness. The Sports
Illustrated Afloat cruise becomes NCL's sixth sports-theme cruise
for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cost of the cruise: Starting at $749 per person, double
occupancy. To book: Call your travel agent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
