<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH IN THE SKY: A WORLD WITHOUT WAR OR JERRY SPRINGER 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ My heart leapt when I read about a possible
parallel universe discovered a mere 44 light years away.
</P>
<P>
   According to scientists at San Francisco State and Harvard
universities, at least three planets similar to Jupiter and Neptune
have been spotted in orbit around a sun that astronomers named
``Upsilon Andromedae.''
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, the probability is excellent that there are smaller
planets, like Earth, Venus and Mars of our solar system, also
orbiting Upsilon Andromedae. We just can't ``see'' them yet with
our limited star-gazing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, while it would come as no surprise to the late
``Star Trek'' creator Gene Roddenberry, this discovery gives us
further reason to presume we are not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because I'm an eternal optimist (or because I grew up
in the Midwest), but I can't bring myself to imagine another planet
out there with human-like life forms who have done a worse job of
things than we have.
</P>
<P>
   (Think about it: We've been around 70,000 years as a species and
have amassed no small number of peace-preaching deities. Our
technology is so advanced, we can implant healing atoms in the
human body or launch space cameras to map the Milky Way. But we're
still murdering one another in huge numbers over the same things we
always have: real estate, bloodlines, religion, or all three.)
</P>
<P>
   So, when I think of that possible parallel universe and a
parallel planet like Earth orbiting Upsilon Andromedae, I can only
envision a better world. Until we hear otherwise, I'm calling the
parallel planet ``Willoughby,'' after a paradisaical town in one of
my favorite episodes of ``The Twilight Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   As I envision it, Willoughby is a world on which:
</P>
<P>
   _ Ground for impeachment of the leader of a superpower _ if such
an entity still exists _ is not an extramarital affair but an
attempt to combat an insane, power-grabbing ethnic cleansing
campaign with an insane rain of aerial bombs on a messed up but
sovereign nation slightly smaller than Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   _ By virtue of being born, a Willoughby life form is guaranteed
healthful food, clean water, health care and shelter from the
elements forever. No exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The only requirement for this universal care is the swearing
(and keeping) of a universal loyalty oath. It is based (what a
coincidence!) on Gandhi's declaration, ``There are many causes for
which I would die, but not one for which I will kill.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Nothing runs via finite planetary resources. If it rolls,
hums, generates, flies, sails, plows, irrigates, computes, cools,
heats, lights or inspires Willoughbeans to shake their booty, its
energy source is the great Greek fraternity in the sky, Upsilon
Andromedae.
</P>
<P>
   _ Birth control is part of the brain chemistry of every
Willoughbean, female and male. If one person thinks,
``Contraception,'' during lovemaking, that's all it takes to block
that kick. When both folks think, ``Baby,'' the green light is on,
and Nature has her chance.
</P>
<P>
   Not a penny, let alone billions, is wasted on a war on drugs
because there are no illegal drugs on Willoughby. If life forms
choose to alter their consciousness, they are allowed to do so.
Oddly enough, not many do because unadulterated daily life on
Willoughby _ with clean air and water, universal peace, adequate
food and shelter and worry-free, guiltless sex _ is pretty damn
good.
</P>
<P>
   _ There is not and never can be a Jerry Springer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter &LR; examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
