<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS CAN EAVESDROP ON COMPANY-ANALYST CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eugene McQuade, speaking from a crowded room at the Helmsley
Hotel in New York, came through loud and clear to anyone with a
computer wired to the Internet and the interest to listen.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a little bit of shareholder democracy in action.
</P>
<P>
   McQuade, the chief financial officer at Fleet Financial Group,
was leading a routine quarterly conference with brokerage analysts
and institutional investors last week.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet can count itself among a small but growing number of
companies using the Internet to level the playing field for
individual investors when it comes to those conference calls, which
had always been private conversations with professional
stockholders. In these cases, individual investors can now listen,
but not ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology has evolved so it can be done well and you're
comfortable with it,'' said McQuade.
</P>
<P>
   Conference calls are almost always dry, often tedious, and
sometimes useless. But top managers explain events and plans in
detail on those calls and stocks often trade up or down on those
comments while the conversation is taking place.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't have it both ways. You can't trade on that
information and not expect the media and individual investors to
have access to it,'' said Louis Thompson, chief executive of the
National Investor Relations Institute in Vienna, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``The on-line traders are really going to start pushing the
envelope for real-time disclosure and real-time access,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies balk at the idea of permitting virtually anyone
onto their call, complaining that information could be
misunderstood. Many analysts worry the practice will turn a
sophisticated financial conversation into mush.
</P>
<P>
   But the convenient old excuse, that it was impractical to tie
many hundreds or even thousands of people into a telephone
conference call, is history.
</P>
<P>
   A few companies now offer services that put conference call
audio on Internet sites. The cost, usually around $800, is
inconsequential to most public companies.
</P>
<P>
   These corporate ``Webcasters'' have been in operation for about
two years, but few companies signed up before the middle of last
year. Since then, most say their rosters of corporate clients have
increased by more than 100 percent quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   V-Call Corp., a Philadelphia firm, specializes in live
conference audio available at no charge to anyone who registers at
its site (www.vcall.com). Free software to play audio is easy to
download from the Web.
</P>
<P>
   V-Call's list of registered users has grown from 33,000 in
January to 125,000 as of last week. It boasts a roster of more than
300 companies using at least some of its services.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate Communications Broadcast Network in Boston handles
audio for clients who want it posted on their own Internet sites,
and Broadcast.com Inc. of Dallas (www.broadcast.com) posts some
live corporate conference calls, along with commercial radio and
other kinds of audio.
</P>
<P>
   C-Call Corp. of San Francisco (www.ccall.com) uses the same kind
of technology but most of its corporate clients restrict access to
the same professional investors who used to dial into conference
calls by phone. It may turn out to be an intermediate step before
companies use the Web to transmit to retail shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they get comfortable with the medium, it's easier to
transfer that out to the retail (investors),'' said Blake Hayunga,
a vice president for the public company group at C-Call. ``It
happens in pieces.''
</P>
<P>
   Conference calls open to the public have attracted groups of
several hundred to a few thousand. Microsoft Corp. conference calls
are heard by more than 10,000 people, including employees.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies tend to Webcast their analyst conferences
more often than other businesses and attract a larger listening
audience.
</P>
<P>
   But more companies, including Fleet, have an increasing number
of individual shareholders, and they are giving all their investors
the same access to calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is changing,'' said Rob Adler, president of
Corporate Communications Broadcast Network. ``The Internet is
changing the way a lot of things are done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
