<SLUG> BC-CNS-HARLEM-TOURISM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARLEM TOURISM ADVOCATES SAY 'GET OFF THE BUS' 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By BRAD FOSS  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Larcelia Kebe began Harlem Your Way Tours in
1983, the thrust of her business was the ``Champagne Jazz Safari,''
which introduced outsiders to popular uptown New York nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   Since many of those clubs have closed down, these days Kebe's
most popular trips into Harlem take place on Sunday mornings, when
busloads of Europeans are brought into neighborhood Baptist
churches to hear the sounds of gospel music.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite brief glimpses of Harlem's churches _ and the
growing interest in its historic homes and cultural museums _
tourists for the most part are still viewing the neighborhood from
the seat of a bus. Tourism boosters want to put an end to this
``safari''-like industry, which, they say, shortchanges both
visitors and residents.
</P>
<P>
   The only way tourists will have a truly authentic visit to
uptown Manhattan, Kebe said, is if they get out and walk around.
``You don't get a feeling of a community otherwise,'' Kebe said.
</P>
<P>
   While noisy tour buses are a concern for some residents,
encouraging visitors to hit the pavement is important for economic
reasons, too.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, millions of dollars in federal, state and city
money are being used to improve streetscapes along historic and
retail corridors in Harlem and Washington Heights.
</P>
<P>
   About $4 million has been earmarked to renovate churches that
``are falling down structurally,'' said Alex Saavedra, program
officer at the Upper Manhattan Empowerment Zone. And $250,000 is
being spent on preliminary plans for a national jazz museum. As
part of this ``heritage tourism'' plan, signs will be posted at the
southern edge of Harlem, which adjoins Central Park, to guide
pedestrians to points of interest.
</P>
<P>
   Row houses built in the early 20th century, during the Harlem
Renaissance, will be renovated, sidewalks will be spruced up and a
visitor's center will be built along 125th Street, Harlem's main
street.
</P>
<P>
   By combining improvements to uptown Manhattan's landscape with
financial assistance to restaurants and nightclubs, Saavedra is
optimistic that tourists will stay longer and spend more money.
</P>
<P>
   What really hurts local businesses, says Lloyd Williams,
president of the Greater Harlem Chamber of Commerce, is the lack of
patronage from Harlemites. This summer, Williams and other business
leaders will begin a ``Discover Harlem'' campaign to ``retain the
disposable income of the community'' by marketing restaurants,
entertainment and cultural institutions to residents.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging the economic benefits of sprucing up Harlem,
New York City Councilman Bill Perkins believes that, ultimately,
tourism can also have a positive impact on the ``currency of human
relations.''
</P>
<P>
   But in order for that to happen, he said, ``you have to give
people reasons to get off the bus.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Persons, who heads the Harlem Historical Society, said
bolstering the arts and culture is a crucial step toward reviving
the neighborhood's economic vitality. He is planning the creation
of a Harlem Historical Museum, which he predicts could open as
early as 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Persons brushes off the notion that increased tourism would
somehow impinge upon the lifestyle of local residents. As with any
popular tourist destination in the world, he said, Harlemites will
continue to patronize restaurants and clubs that visitors do not
even know exist.
</P>
<P>
   Crime is down throughout New York City, but the perception of
danger in uptown Manhattan has not necessarily waned. In fact, some
tourists are attracted to Harlem because they want to see the
poverty and crime that is often portrayed on television, said
Lauren Craniotes, who is overseeing a study of tourism in Harlem
for the Empowerment Zone. ``Obviously, that is not what we want to
promote,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When New York Apple Tours began offering ``hop on, hop off''
sightseeing tours throughout New York City six years ago, ``there
weren't a lot of people hopping off the buses in Harlem,'' said
Michael Alvich, vice president of sales and marketing. But that is
slowly beginning to change, he said, and the company recently began
offering walking tours to the 200,000 people it shuttles through
Harlem each year.
</P>
<P>
   Kebe, of Harlem Your Way Tours, said the atmosphere in uptown
Manhattan has been more relaxed in the past decade as a result of
reduced crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the muggers are downtown,'' Kebe noted. Ironically,
that could be a bad sign for Harlem. As Kebe pointed out, muggers
follow the tourists.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Brad Foss is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
