<HEADER>
A5760 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-MONKEY-ART &LR;      04-20 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-MONKEY-ART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONKEY SEE, MONKEY DO: THE CAPUCHIN ART MOVEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By RAMONA JENKIN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The crowd of 60 patrons of the National Arts Club on
Gramercy Park _ dressed in dark business suits and designer
cocktail dresses and wearing plenty of gold jewelry _ pushed their
way to the front of the room.
</P>
<P>
   They hoped to meet one of the painters whose works were on
display. The excited crowd gathered, closing in on the lectern.
</P>
<P>
   Like many artists this one was a private and delicate creature,
not used to being surrounded by strangers. She let our several
rhythmic high-pitched howls and jumped from the lectern into the
speaker's arms.
</P>
<P>
   She was, after all, just a monkey.
</P>
<P>
   The guests had just heard how little 7-pound, 6-year-old Ayla, a
brown two-toned capuchin monkey, and others like her have provided
companionship, independence and occasionally art for quadriplegics
through Helping Hands, a non-profit organization based in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Capuchins are small, gentle and dexterous monkeys. They live to
be about 40 years old.
</P>
<P>
   This makes them the perfect long-term companions for this group
of disabled people, most of whom are injured in early adult life,
said the program's director, Judi Zazula.
</P>
<P>
   On this night the proof of their dexterity was in the artwork.
</P>
<P>
   To the left of where Ayla clung to Zazula was a display of six
paintings _ the fruits of the monkeys' recreational labors and
their first New York show.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to get a lot of monkey art out there,'' Zazula
said. ``It's also
</P>
<P>
   a way for people to give something so that it helps the
program.''
</P>
<P>
   The going price for an 8-by-10-inch piece of framed monkey art
is $100.
</P>
<P>
   Zazula, 43, said Helping Hands uses the artwork to raise money
to help get a monkey to someone else in need.
</P>
<P>
   ``It costs about $25,000 to $30,000 to breed, raise and train
these monkeys and to follow them for life,'' Zazula said.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 200 monkeys in the program, she said.
</P>
<P>
   After oohing and aahing over Ayla the crowd moved toward the
table with the monkey masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   There were two paintings with small, green delicate monkey
footprints against a white background, as if little primates had
stepped in a container of paint and walked across the canvases.
</P>
<P>
   One abstract piece featured a few strokes of red, blue and
yellow that seemed to spin off from the center of the painting.
Another was a set of simple but elegant mauve brush strokes.
</P>
<P>
   The art program started in 1995 when a monkey sitting on
Zazula's lap started scribbling, she said. The little capuchin
seemed to enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   Zazula said she thought that if she gave them paints they might
make something worth framing. Soon the art program was in full
swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are links between the personalities and the things they
paint,'' Zazula said.
</P>
<P>
   But they don't all paint and they're not all artists, said
Helping Hands' treasurer, Susan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many just scribble,'' Keyes said.
</P>
<P>
   Besty Brewer, 40, has been breeding capuchins for Helping Hands
for the last five years at Southwick's Zoo in Mendon, Mass. She was
skeptical about the capacity monkeys have for art, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to anthropomorphize _ thinking that they know how
an animal thinks,'' Brewer said.
</P>
<P>
   Capuchins have a large brain-to-body ratio and are very
intelligent, she said. But Brewer added that she had not witnessed
any of the monkeys or chimpanzees at her zoo initiating any art
activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all depends on how much interaction they've had with
humans,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Zazula agreed.
</P>
<P>
   One monkey has learned to paint with the brush in his mouth, the
way his quadriplegic companion does, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of what others think, Zazula gives the monkeys a set of
non-toxic paints when each monkey is placed with a quadriplegic.
</P>
<P>
   The art is a way for the monkeys to express themselves, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just good fun and the fun starts and ends with
the manipulation of the medium,'' Zazula said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people appreciate it the way you appreciate your
child's art work,'' Zazula said. ``We think we have such unique
pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the pieces were sold that night.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the people were amused by the monkey art and some were
skeptical about its artistic value, but one of the guests, Jody
Widelitz, said he was impressed with its quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better than a show I saw the other day at a SoHo
gallery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Ramona Jenkin is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;  _
</P>
