<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5761 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-BIRD-WATCHERS &LR;      04-20 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-BIRD-WATCHERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIRDS AND BIRD NERDS FLOCK TO CENTRAL PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By ANDREW GLAZER  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It takes a lot to excite New Yorkers, but Bob
DeCandido enthralls his followers every Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two birds live right up on Woody Allen's building,'' he
said as he pointed to a five-foot nest built by a pair of
red-tailed hawks across an archway high on a concrete building on
Fifth Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   DeCandido, an Urban Park Ranger based out of Belvedere Castle in
Central Park, leads a group of birdwatchers on bird safaris every
Sunday at 9 a.m. The birders, like the birds they observe, come in
a variety of sizes and shapes. On a cold Sunday morning, some
donned nylon Patagonia parkas and leather boots, while others wore
mink coats and hi-top sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   Most New Yorkers don't realize this, but birds flying from
Canada to South America and back again like to layover in
Manhattan's Central Park. In the past decade, an increasing number
of birds have rested and nested in the park, drawing more than
10,000 binocular-bearing bird enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   DeCandido estimates that Central Park is a rest-stop or
permanent home to nearly 250 species of birds that feed off of its
berries, acorns and grains, and hunt its plentiful stock of rats,
mice, squirrels and small birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Central Park is an island of green surrounded by concrete,''
said Paul Kerlinger, a biologist and environmental consultant who
has studied Central Park's ecology. ``The birds migrating might
look down and see the only spot of green for miles around.''
</P>
<P>
   DeCandido is delighted to have the birds land in his backyard.
He clearly and patiently explains park biology while surefootedly
traversing muddy slopes and slippery rocks. With a green mesh
trucker's hat pulled low on his head and a forest green nylon
windbreaker, he has the basic appearance and demeanor of a park
ranger.
</P>
<P>
   But because he is an urban park ranger who grew up in the Bronx,
DeCandido has a manner of speaking that differs from his fellow
rangers in Yellowstone and Yosemite National Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the way he described why more birds come to the park in
the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the summer, people leave food around,'' he said. ``This
food attracts prey: rats, squirrels, pigeons, mice. The raptors
come into the park and it's like they're walking into a McDonald's
with no one at the cash register.''
</P>
<P>
   New York birds, like New York park rangers, have a distinct
urban edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This part of the park has some of the fastest and slimmest
pigeons thanks to the red-tailed hawks,'' said Dennis Geisel of
Manhattan, an amateur ornithologist and friend of DeCandido. Woody
Allen's feathered neighbors, usually hunters of less-urban
creatures like rabbits, field mice and small snakes, hunt pigeons
in Central Park. The fattest and slowest pigeons are usually their
victims.
</P>
<P>
   A short walk from the hawks' domain, a small cluster of pine
trees stands in a field of green grass. A man in his 60s swept his
battered pair of binoculars through the trees as his wife stood
impatiently beside him.
</P>
<P>
   DeCandido pointed out an eggplant-shaped silhouette with pointed
ears _ a long-eared owl. A young man passed by. ``Tell those people
down there he's in the tree to the right, because they're lost,''
DeCandido said.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, DeCandido met up with the couple and
discussed the owl. ``It has small talons, so it eats young rats and
small birds but not squirrels or bigger birds like pigeons,''
DeCandido explained.
</P>
<P>
   DeCandido said Central Park has become more desirable to birds
not only because there are fewer surrounding green areas for them
to land, but because the park's trees and shrubbery have matured. A
decade ago, park officials kept trees and bushes neatly groomed,
but rangers successfully lobbied for a more natural look. The dense
trees and thickets are more suitable for nesting.
</P>
<P>
   With the birds come the bird-watchers, who once attracted almost
as much attention as the brightest cardinal. But jaded New Yorkers
soon stopped noticing the urban naturalists wading through the park
while making strange whistling sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The socioeconomic group of people who live around Central Park
are the type of people who travel around the world to see nature,''
DeCandido said. ``They understand the attraction of nature. If they
saw us bowling, they'd be surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Stotz of the New York City Audubon Society said that
recently there have been territorial battles between birders and
dog owners who unleash their pets in areas of the park where birds
feed. The dogs chase and sometimes catch the birds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some friction,'' Stotz said. ``You say, 'Could
you put your dog on a leash,' and people get incensed.''
</P>
<P>
   Stotz said, however, that most park visitors supported his
hobby. ``When I'm walking around with binoculars peering into
trees, people ask: 'Did you see this and this bird?' Sometimes they
point me to a bird. Other times it's their active imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost all who make up Central Park's birding community believe
that once people see the variety of birds Central Park offers, they
will be hooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see an owl or a hawk in their spotting scope,''
Kerlinger said, ``and it's like a light went off. A learning
experience right here in Manhattan!''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday-morning birder Sandy Shepps from Manhattan remembered one
such moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We once saw a night heron eat a baby mallard,'' she said. ``He
slurped it down like a piece of spaghetti!''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Andrew Glazer is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
</TEXT>
