r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-MALCOLM-X-MUSEUM &LR;      04-20 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-MALCOLM-X-MUSEUM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALCOLM X MUSEUM SEARCHES FOR A HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By WILLIAM MURRAY  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK --The Malcolm X museum is an idea in search of a home.
Hundreds of photographs, audio recordings, ticket stubs and letters
from the assassinated black Muslim leader gather dust in boxes and
bins scattered around the country, all awaiting a permanent
repository.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have photographs of Malcolm X starting from 1954 when he
began his Muslim ministry here in Harlem, to the front pages of New
York City's six daily newspapers the day Malcolm was shot,'' in
1965, said Andy Owens, a member of the proposed museum's board of
directors. But despite several years of organizing, Malcolm X
devotees have been unable to gather the collection in a permanent
location.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Owens and eight other people organized a foundation
to honor the onetime prison inmate who became a hero of the black
Muslim movement and in recent years has achieved a new icon status
among young African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The group had always hoped a Malcolm X museum would be
established in the Audubon Ballroom, the site of his assassination
34 years ago. A small area in the first floor of the Ballroom
houses a life-sized bronze statue, a mural and an etching depicting
Malcolm X, but the spacious second floor of the Ballroom is empty
and would work well as a museum, foundation members say. But the
city, which owns the onetime dance and concert hall and has allowed
it to open just six times over the past four years for special
occasions, has never provided a fulltime operating budget.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Sam Anderson said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's
administration closed the site for a year to renovate a room
honoring Malcolm X's widow, but failed to provide the hoped-for
budget to pay for regular hours of operation. Giuliani's press
office directed all questions to the city's Economic Development
Commission, which did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city has made it clear that it is not willing to give the
Audubon over to any organization unless it has the financial
resources to run it itself,'' said Michael Mowatt-Wynn, the curator
of the Audubon space where the statue, mural and etching are
displayed. ``The city has said it doesn't have the resources to
operate a the museum and so far no one has been able to pay for its
operation.'' He said it would take $300,000 a year to run a museum,
and organizers now are looking beyond city coffers for support. The
foundation plans to raise money on its own to build a new facility
in Harlem, but a specific plan has yet to be developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the people on the board tried to have the Audubon
Ballroom as the museum,'' said Ghiuslaine Hermanuz, a board member
and an urban planning professor at City College of New York. ``Now
nobody is very sure about where it will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, New York politicians have joined the push to
commemorate Malcolm X's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent a lot of time in the early '90s negotiating with the
Giuliani administration. The real issue was trying to reach an
agreement over whether the exhibit and museum would have an
operating budget,'' said Ruth Messinger, Manhattan Borough
President from 1989 to 1997 and Giuliani's opponent in the 1997
mayoral race. But some of the impetus waned with the 1997 death of
Malcolm X's widow, Betty Shabazz, who had been a prime organizer,
Messinger said.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm X is credited with awakening black militancy and racial
pride in black America in the early 1960s. Harlem is where he
became famous for his sidewalk debates and attacks against white
racism. As chief spokesman for the Nation of Islam, he was among
the first leaders to articulate the anger felt by black Americans
about segregation and economic exclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Museum organizers currently sponsor or conduct many Malcolm
X-related programs, such as a memorial this past February on the
anniversary of his death, at the Schomburg Center for Research in
Black Culture at 135th Street and Malcolm X Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a place to commemorate his spirit. The motivation is
to recognize the teachings of Malcolm X and the struggle for a
community for dignity and political strength,'' said Hermanuz.
``And it has not stopped. This museum,'' whatever its eventual
location, ``will not just be a place to keep things. It will be a
place of action.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: William Murray is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
