<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5763 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-IN-SHADOW-OF-NASA     04-20 1326
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-IN-SHADOW-OF-NASA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR TOWN NEAR CAPE CANAVERAL TRIES TO FIGHT OFF DEVELOPMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By GEORGINA GUSTIN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAK HILL, Fla. _ Off Route 1, not far from Daytona, a small road
leads east to Mosquito Lagoon, a sparkling expanse of deep blue
water where pelicans rest on old docks and a barrier island lies in
the distance under a mantle of shrub oak and palmetto grass.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the rest of Florida's Atlantic seaboard is ragged
with construction, no condominium complexes or hotels mark the
coastline here _ in fact, there are very few buildings of any kind
at all. Just a few fish camps line the lagoon where trailers, many
of them decades old and worn with time and salt water, look as
natural as the gnarled driftwood sticking out of nearby swamps.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in one of Florida's poorest towns, a quiet, almost
bewildering tranquillity pervades.
</P>
<P>
   This peace is only occasionally interrupted with a violent
shudder and a sonic boom, the source of which lies some 30 miles
away. At the Kennedy Space Center, the Vertical Assembly Building
houses NASA's space shuttle. And when the multibillion-dollar
shuttle is wheeled out of its home and launched, the little town of
Oak Hill and all of its trailers shudder in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place really rumbles,'' said Jeaneen Clauss, 30, Oak
Hill's city clerk who works in the two-room city hall that shares
quarters with the five-member police department. ``The buildings
definitely shake.''
</P>
<P>
   Oak Hill was incorporated in the 1950's as a direct response to
the development of NASA's space program at Cape Canaveral, and back
then, ``the Cape'' as locals call it, promised bigger and better
things. The area's fishing industry had languished, the timber
industry was obsolete, but the infinite frontier of space inspired
great hopes. The sleepy town was swept up in the euphoria of
America's great ventures into space and optimism abounded along
with jobs. A map in the town hall announced Oak Hill as ``the
gateway to the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I grew up, it was always the Cape, the Cape, the Cape,
the U.S, the U.S, the U.S.,'' said Donna Bennett, Oak Hill's mayor
and a third-generation resident. ``I was indoctrinated in that
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But these days, the shaking and rumbling of the space shuttle
are nothing more than tangible reminders of the town's past _ a
time when the golden age of space travel consumed the town and
promised a brighter future. Now, Oak Hill is struggling to survive,
the unlikely site of a battle between new and old.
</P>
<P>
   For this tiny town of ``a thousand and a couple,'' as Clauss
describes it, the triumphs and tragedies of space travel are more
than events on the evening news. The town has revolved around the
Cape _ it has felt the giddy joy of its successes and a penetrating
sadness at its losses.
</P>
<P>
   Today Donna Bennett, a 51-year-old single mother, lives a few
steps away from the house where she grew up. And on a recent
afternoon, she walked through a small orange grove where her
parents produce enough fruit to pay town taxes and knocked on the
door. The power had just gone out and her father, Allen Williams,
sat shirtless in the dark. The walls of the concrete house were
lined with deer heads and turkey beards, the spoils of hunting in
the countryside around Oak Hill. On the floor rested an alligator
head and a sea turtle ``paw.''
</P>
<P>
   William's taxidermied artifacts are not the only trophies in his
house. Nestled among them are framed certificates honoring his
service at the Cape. One, from the U.S. Department of Defense,
recognizes his contribution to the Apollo 11 mission, the first
landing on moon. Another honors his service as a firefighter in
1956 when three astronauts were instantly killed after a flash fire
consumed a test rocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were eating supper when we heard the bell,'' said Williams,
dolefully. ``We got there as fast as we could, but it was too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   The flash fire in 1956 was the first tragedy that rattled the
town's psyche. In 1986, Betty Bellamy, now Oak Hill's town
historian, was a grade school teacher. She had assembled her class
outside of the school to watch the Space Shuttle Challenger carry
the teacher Christa McAullife, the first civilian on a shuttle
mission, into orbit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching with my class,'' Bellamy said. ``And there was
this little space-crazy boy, and he kept saying 'There it goes,
there it goes!' And then I thought, Oh my, something's wrong.'' As
most of America watched on television as the space shuttle
exploded, Bellamy's class saw the hurtling fragments of the craft
plunge into the ocean with their own eyes. ``The boy was taken to a
priest, and then a doctor,'' said Bellamy, shaking her head. ``He
almost had a nervous breakdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Pictured on Oak Hill's town seal, are an orange, a leaping fish
and a rocket, but all of the industries these symbols represent are
now gone. A deep freeze killed most of Oak Hill's orange groves in
the mid-80s, and several years ago a ban on gill net fishing shut
down what was left of the town's fishing industry. Then, the final
blow came as most of Oak Hill's residents were laid off from
service jobs at the Cape.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bennett is struggling to maintain the idyllic beauty of the
town she grew up in while staving off hungry developers who many
say are the town's only hope for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said, ``When Kennedy made his speech and said 'Ask not
what your country can do for you, but what you can do for your
country' I thought, 'What can I do for my town?'''
</P>
<P>
   For Bennett, the most important thing is fighting off a county
proposal to build a $10 million sewage plant in Oak Hill and
construct a town water system. (The town currently uses only
residential septic systems). If constructed, Bennett says, the
plant and the water system will drive up town taxes, making Oak
Hill unaffordable for many of its residents. But more important,
the added infrastructure would be a virtual green light for
developers, many of whom will not build in Oak Hill until a town
water system is in place.
</P>
<P>
   For a town that grew up in the shadow of one of the most
ambitious and technologically advanced projects in the world, where
rockets are launched into the nether reaches of space, septic
systems and sewage plants seem a mundane and somewhat odd
preoccupation.
</P>
<P>
   But rockets and space shuttles have let the town of Oak Hill
down, and now these closer-to-earth concerns are of greater
importance.
</P>
<P>
   For people of Bennett's generation, the Cape still fascinates.
``I still go out and watch the launches,'' Bennett said. ``I still
remember the first time one went off. I felt like I'd been shot.''
But for Oak Hill's younger residents, rocket launches into space
are just another part of life.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's 14-year-old daughter, Shona Lee, has dreams of leaving
Oak Hill for New York City and a career in modeling. ``Her
generation grew up with it,'' Bennett said of the space program.
``For her it's like 'Oh, the shuttle's going up and the windows are
shaking again.'''
</P>
<P>
   On a clear day, when the shuttle takes off, it appears to arc
over the town itself. And days later, when the shuttle re-enters
the earth's atmosphere and approaches its landing strip, a sonic
boom rattles the town with shock waves. As the town staves off the
future, a rumbling shuttle from outer space remains part of its
rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Georgina Gustin is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
</TEXT>
