<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Columbia News Service provides feature stories from the New York
City area every week for your use as desired. There is no cost to
you. CNS stories are transmitted every week courtesy of The New
York Times Syndicate/NYT News Service.
</P>
<P>
   The stories are slugged  &UR; BC-CNS-keyword &LR;  and move in the ``l''
news category.
</P>
<P>
   They are edited by adjunct professors who are working
journalists at The New York Times, Newsday, the Associated Press
and The Wall Street Journal. The stories are written by degree
candidates at the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia
University. All we ask is that you send us a tearsheet.
</P>
<P>
   So please, if you can, use our stories. Most of them are news
features that can be held until you have a pesky hole to fill.
</P>
<P>
   To send us a clip:
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   GRADUATE SCHOOL OF JOURNALISM
</P>
<P>
   COLUMBIA UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   2950 BROADWAY
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK, NY 10027
</P>
<P>
   Many thanks,
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &UR; Professor Wayne Svoboda (212-854-3837) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Columbia News Service &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; e-mail ws52 &LR; columbia.edu &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; web site http://cns.jrn.columbia.edu/ &LR;  This week's stories:
</P>
<P>
   MONKEY ART _ Sixty patrons of the National Arts Club hoped to
meet one of the painters whose works were on display. The excited
crowd gathered, closing in on the lectern. Like many artists this
one was a private and delicate creature, not used to being
surrounded by strangers. She let our several rhythmic high-pitched
howls and jumped from the lectern into the speaker's arms. She was,
after all, just a monkey.
</P>
<P>
   BIRD WATCHERS _ Most New Yorkers don't realize this, but birds
flying from Canada to South America and back again like to layover
in Manhattan's Central Park. In the past decade, an increasing
number of birds have rested and nested in the park, drawing more
than 10,000 binocular-bearing bird enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   TV TURNOFF _ It has been called the ``idiot box,'' the ``boob
tube'' and a ``vast wasteland.'' On April 22, Esther Forrest is
calling it quits. As part of National TV-Turnoff Week, the
elementary school principal and her teachers at Public School 51 in
the Bronx will hand out signs for students to tape over the screens
of their TV sets. The signs are a reminder that the tube is
off-limits for an entire week. Seven whole days _ 168 hours.
</P>
<P>
   BRAIDERS _ The ancient tradition of hair braiding is being
threatened by the modern bureaucracy. In many states, hair-braiders
must go through up to 1,600 hours of training in order to receive a
cosmetology license _ training that can cost as much as $5,000, and
covers perming, tinting and use of chemicals, all skills that
braiders say they have little need to know. In some states,
especially California, Ohio and Texas, the cosmetology boards have
cracked down on unlicensed braiders. To protest what they view as a
draconian requirement, some braiders have taken the cosmetology
boards to court.
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN MARKET _ On a recent Saturday, Betty Delacruz leaned
against a wall at the Knickerbocker Live Poultry Market and waited
for her two chickens and three quail to be killed, plucked, and
gutted. Now she shops, sometimes twice a week, at the
Knickerbocker, which for 62 years has catered to several immigrant
cultures in Brooklyn. Each has its own idea of what makes good
chicken.
</P>
<P>
   DISABLED SKIERS _ The world of disabled skiers is filled with
the same exhilaration, achievement and camaraderie that all skiers
share. For the disabled, however, it takes a little more to get out
on the slopes: more equipment (which costs a little more money),
more help from the able-bodied and more guts.
</P>
<P>
   HEAT PILL _ John Glenn has been on the pill. So have some
firefighters and deep sea divers. This pill is not a contraceptive,
Prozac or even Viagra. Researchers have been testing this product
to prevent heat exhaustion in firefighters. The three-quarter-inch
capsule monitors body temperatures of those who work in extreme
environments.
</P>
<P>
   MALCOLM X MUSEUM _ The Malcolm X museum is an idea in search of
a home. Hundreds of photographs, audio recordings, ticket stubs and
letters from the assassinated black Muslim leader gather dust in
boxes and bins scattered around the country, all awaiting a
permanent repository. ``We have ministry here in Harlem, to the
front pages of New York City's six daily newspapers the day Malcolm
was shot,'' in 1965, said Andy Owens, a member of the proposed
museum's board of directors. But despite several years of
organizing, Malcolm X devotees have been unable to gather the
collection in a permanent location.
</P>
<P>
   IN SHADOW OF NASA _ While most of the rest of Florida's Atlantic
seaboard is ragged with construction, no condominium complexes or
hotels mark the coastline here _ in fact, there are very few
buildings of any kind at all. Just a few fish camps line the lagoon
where trailers, many of them decades old and worn with time and
salt water, look as natural as the gnarled driftwood sticking out
of nearby swamps. Here, in one of Florida's poorest towns, a quiet,
almost bewildering tranquillity pervades.
</P>
<P>
   HARLEM TOURISM _ Popular trips into Harlem take place on Sunday
mornings, when busloads of Europeans are brought into neighborhood
Baptist churches to hear the sounds of gospel music. Yet despite
brief glimpses of Harlem's churches most tourists are still viewing
the neighborhood from the seat of a bus. Tourism boosters want to
put an end to this ``safari''-like industry, which, they say,
shortchanges both visitors and residents. They say the only way
tourists will have a truly authentic visit to Harlem is if they get
out and walk around.
</P>
</TEXT>
