<SLUG> BC-CNS-DISABLED-SKIERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISABLED SKIERS TAKE ON THE MOUNTAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By NAOMI STAROBIN  
 C. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Betsy Hurley boasted to her father that she fell only
twice in her morning of skiing at Pico Mountain in Vermont. Robert
Ferrusi prefers speed to finesse, and avoids moguls. Al Fenton
stopped after one run, because the rain and fog made it tough to
ski.
</P>
<P>
   An ordinary day of skiing in most ways, but take a closer look.
To get up after a fall, Hurley, 17, who has spina bifida, digs her
poles into the snow and rights her mono-ski _ a contraption that is
basically a bucket seat mounted on a ski _ often needing an
able-bodied instructor's help. Ferrusi, 38, a paraplegic, hoists
himself out of his wheelchair and streaks down the slopes on his
gleaming purple mono-ski as snowboarders stare in envy. Fenton, 65,
who has multiple sclerosis, has no feeling in his legs, and relies
on his sight to ``feel'' the topography of the slope, although on
this day it was too foggy to get an accurate read.
</P>
<P>
   The world of disabled skiers is filled with the same
exhilaration, achievement and camaraderie that all skiers share.
For the disabled, however, it takes a little more to get out on the
slopes: more equipment (which costs a little more money), more help
from the able-bodied and more guts.
</P>
<P>
   At least half of the able-bodied people who try skiing give it
up after one day. Not so with disabled skiers. ``The fact that a
person with a disability is here and ready to try this means that
they've already conquered a huge mental hurdle,'' said Jim
Hutchins, the program director of Vermont Adaptive Ski and Sport.
``The rest is downhill from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Literally.
</P>
<P>
   For seven days a week, Hutchins _ a large man with a Santa Claus
kind of merriness _ is out on the slopes at one of several Vermont
ski resorts, teaching the disabled to ski. For $70 a day, a
disabled skier rents a mono-ski, gets a full-day ski lesson with
one or two instructors, and a lift ticket. In the past, Hutchins
could handle walk-ins, but so many people are interested in
mono-skiing now, that reservations are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchins is part engineer, part teacher and part cheerleader.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent weekend, he and Hurley teamed up to coach Kip St.
Germaine, a new student, who became disabled as a result of an
accident. Hurley skied out in front on her mono-ski, St. Germaine
followed with Hutchins skiing behind him, holding onto the back of
St. Germaine's mono-ski. As the morning went on, Hutchins gradually
released his grip. By his third run down the mountain, St. Germaine
was skiing on his own. Most new skiers take much longer, as long as
an entire season of lessons. But St. Germaine is quite an athlete _
he is on the U.S. Disabled Ice Hockey team, which competed at the
Paralympic Games in Nagano, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The bucket on Hurley's mono-ski has bumper stickers that read
``You Go, Girl'' and ``Brakes are for Wussies.'' She also
participates in downhill mountain biking, whitwater rafting and
horseback riding. Because of the spina bifida, she has no use of
her legs and little use of her hips. St. Germaine has use of
everything above his bellybutton. Of course, skiing is different
when only half of the body is available. ``We use our hips and legs
and knees'' to turn, said Hutchins, ``Kip uses his arms, shoulders
and torso.''
</P>
<P>
   That is where Hutchins the engineer comes in. The bucket of the
mono-ski comes in three sizes, but Hutchins spends about an hour
customizing the fit to a skier's body with padding and duct tape.
The bucket seat of the ski must be snug, like an able-bodied
skier's ski boot, so the skier's movements can be directly
translated to the ski. The seat rests on a shock absorber, which
has to be adjusted to the skier's weight so that as the skier hits
bumps on the slope, the ski stays in contact with the snow. Five
straps, from ankle to chest, hold the skier on the mono-ski. Double
amputees need only two straps.
</P>
<P>
   A mono-skier also holds poles, called outriggers, much the same
way able-bodied skiers do. The top of the outrigger has Velcro
straps and a handle, and the bottom has a ski tip that can flip up
to dig into the snow when the mono-skier needs to push off or hop
onto a chair lift. Ferrusi is able to get on and off chair lifts on
his own, and so skies totally independently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love life, I follow my passions, I don't sit around,'' said
Ferrusi, who owns his own mono-ski (the ``Mobile Master''). He is a
veteran, and the Eastern Paralyzed Veteran's Association paid for
his mono-ski and helmet, and sponsors races. The mono-skis cost
about $3,000, and are made by about six manufacturers in the United
States and abroad. Outdoor sports are nothing new to Ferrusi. He
was injured in a mountaineering accident in 1979, and since then
has skied competitively and also does other sports. It took him two
years to feel comfortable in a mono-ski.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you first start out, you wipe out really hard, and it's
hard on your body and your morale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fenton has had multiple sclerosis for 35 years. He was an avid
skier in his 20s, before he developed MS. ``I was a quadriplegic,''
he said, describing how little use of his arms and legs he had when
the MS was most serious. Through exercise and therapy he got
himself back on his feet. After getting married, having four sons,
and spending many years watching them ski, he learned about
adaptive skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchins has worked hard to adapt a pair of skis to suit Fenton.
Because one of his legs is shorter than the other, Hutchins canted
one ski, and as a result Fenton's skis stay flat on the snow when
he skis. Hutchins also struggled to help Fenton squeeze his left
foot, which has no feeling and little muscle mass, into his ski
boot. On the slopes, Hutchins assists Fenton off the lift by
simultaneously lifting Fenton's arm up and pushing his bad leg
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``His instruction and encouragement have been fantastic,''
Fenton said. ``There are times when I've come down the bunny slope
and he says, 'That's the best I've ever seen you do!' And I feel
perfectly safe with him. It's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Fenton has skied with one son, but his dream is to ski with his
whole family. ``That would really be a delight,'' he said. ``All I
need is one time.
</P>
<P>
   That would mean the world to me.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Naomi Starobin is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
</TEXT>
