<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5766 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-BRAIDERS &LR;      04-20 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-BRAIDERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE HAIR AND RED TAPE TANGLE, BRAIDERS FIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By VIOLET LAW  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Diane Bailey mashed a sunflower petal into a dab of
mellow orange hair honey and gently massaged it into her client's
bushy black hair. Then she pinched a tiny strand, split it, and
looped some synthetic hair around it. Instinctively, her fingers
danced in and out of the three strands, kneading, twisting and
locking it into a fine braid.
</P>
<P>
   A diva crimp, to be precise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Braiding is a grass-roots tradition in Africa passed on from
mother to daughter,'' explained Bailey, 42, the master braider at
Tendrils, the salon she owns in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter knows how to braid, too.'' She looked sidewise at
6-year-old Kai, a pint-sized girl sporting dreadlocks. ``She even
tried to braid the dog's hair,'' Kai's mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Braiding is common in the Caribbean, too. Tracy Willacey, 27, a
fourth-grade teacher in the Brownsville section of Brooklyn, grew
up in Jamaica and spent every Sunday at her mother's knee having
her hair braided into cornrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Braids meant that your parents took care of you and took pride
in you,'' Willacey said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Willacey has her hair braided every few months, paying
from $75 to $100 for a session that might last as long as 10 hours.
When she requests that extensions be tied to her own hair, she pays
an additional amount, $30 or so.
</P>
<P>
   But now, this ancient tradition is being threatened by the
modern bureaucracy. In many states, hair-braiders like Bailey must
go through up to 1,600 hours of training in order to receive a
cosmetology license _ training that can cost as much as $5,000, and
covers perming, tinting and use of chemicals, all skills that
braiders say they have little need to know. In some states,
especially California, Ohio and Texas, the cosmetology boards have
cracked down on unlicensed braiders. To protest what they view as a
draconian requirement, some braiders have taken the cosmetology
boards to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you define 'culture' in a bureaucracy?'' asked JoAnne
Cornwell, a hair-braider and associate professor of Africana
Studies and French at the University of San Diego. She is one of
the plaintiffs in the California lawsuit. ``The cosmetology board
is antithetical to the whole idea of developing a cultural art form
which is a self-expression to a specific group of people,''
Cornwell said.
</P>
<P>
   But Nathan Barankin, spokesman for California's Department of
Justice, which represents the cosmetology board, said that culture
was not the issue. ``The Department of Consumer Affairs and the
Board of Barbering and Cosmetology are required under law to
enforce the law'' on hair-braiders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   With help from the Institute for Justice, a public-interest law
firm in Washington, D.C., and the American Hairbraider &AMP; Natural
Haircare Association, a trade group, braiders have won exemptions
from the licensing requirement in Washington, D.C., Maryland and
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that hair braiding is a cultural art and we have the
right to do it,'' said Sheila Everette-Hale, a Detroit-based
hair-braider who sued the state and won.
</P>
<P>
   The tenacity of the braiders _ predominantly women of African
descent _ who fight state licensing requirements to practice their
traditional craft has been matched by the assertiveness of their
clients. Over the past few years, many of them have braved
criticism by appearing in conservative workplaces in intricately
woven twists and crimps. They say the braided hairstyles provide
not only relief from the Eurocentric standards of straight-haired
beauty, but also affirm their African heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Braids are part of the African-American culture, and the '90s
is a celebratory period of the African American culture,'' said
Mikki Taylor, beauty and cover editor of Essence, a magazine for
black women.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time that these women are embracing hair braiding as
an essential part of their heritage, they are also testing
outsiders' understanding of their indigenous culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of hairstyle goes around the status quo,'' said
Marilyn Houlberg, an art historian and anthropologist who for more
than three decades has studied the sociology of hair and done
extensive fieldwork on hair-braiding in Nigeria and Haiti. ``That's
why it is seen as a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that need not be the case. In New York State, Bailey,
co-founder of the International Braiders' Network, another trade
association, worked with the state to design a curriculum to cover
relevant topics in braiding, such as sanitation and detection of
scalp diseases. As a result, the lawsuit against the New York State
cosmetology board was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Willacey, the fourth-grade teacher, says she is confident the
hair-braiders pose no danger. She says she washes her braids about
once every week or two weeks, and uses a blow dryer to speed the
drying process. ``Braiding my hair is the best thing ever. I wake
up in the morning and I'm ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Saturday afternoon at Tendrils, three clients
relaxed in armchairs, bowing slightly while hair-braiders wove each
strand of their hair into a braid. A few other clients were pacing
the salon, waiting for their turns. A full-scale braiding typically
takes from eight to 10 hours, and will last three to four months.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the days when hairdressers wielded hot combs to
forcibly straighten the kinky hair of African-American women. While
many still undergo the laborious ritual of brushing their curls and
coils and applying chemical relaxers, more and more are discovering
the benefits of wearing their hair natural _ adopting the kind of
braids and locks whose style best suits their hair texture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just re-defining what is beautiful to us,'' Bailey said.
``Our African-ness is beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Hair-braiding can be traced back thousands of years to the
Egyptians and the Nubians, according to Carla Brown, a
hair-braiding instructor at York College in Queens who has
conducted research in hair braiding. She said that on a pilgrimage
to Cairo she saw engravings of pharaohs in braids and locks.
Hiddekel Burks, a Chicago-based master braider whose mentor hails
from Liberia, observed that even in today's Africa different styles
of braids are still used to signify different occasions.
</P>
<P>
   At Tendrils, patron Carol Thomas, 42, examined a display of hair
products while taking a break from her six-hour braiding session.
She said she did not care how much training her braider had so long
as her hair was well groomed. Her hair was half done, with a
delicate microbraid sprouting up from each diamond-shaped patch of
hair on the lower half of her scalp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Braided hair makes me feel proud. You don't feel that you have
to reinvent yourself,'' Thomas said. ``Just be natural.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Violet Law is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
