<HEADER>
A5767 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-TV-TURNOFF &LR;      04-20 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-TV-TURNOFF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVING UP THE TV HABIT, COLD TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 by ERIK HOLM  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has been called the ``idiot box,'' the ``boob
tube'' and a ``vast wasteland.'' On April 22, Esther Forrest is
calling it quits.
</P>
<P>
   As part of National TV-Turnoff Week, the elementary school
principal and her teachers at Public School 51 in the Bronx will
hand out signs for students to tape over the screens of their TV
sets. The signs are a reminder that the tube is off-limits for an
entire week. Seven whole days _ or 168 hours.
</P>
<P>
   If last year was any indication, it will be harder for some
people than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of kids tell me they really wanted to do it, but that
their parents couldn't handle a week without television,'' Forrest
said. But in the end, she said that nearly everyone who
participates in the voluntary program learns something. Parents
reported that their children actually played together. Some picked
up books. Others ventured outside.
</P>
<P>
   The students and parents of P.S. 51 in the Bronx were among the
5 million who took part in last year's TV-Turnoff. And organizers
for this year's event estimate that children at 45,000 schools
across the country will again swear off their favorite cartoons,
movies and video games for the fifth annual TV-Turnoff Week, to be
held April 22-28.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone thinks switching off the television for a week
is such a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was boring,'' complained Leah Gonzalez, 8, of last year's
TV moratorium. ``I couldn't watch even one cartoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Classmate Andres Marin, 8, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave me an opportunity to do something else,'' the
third-grader said. ``I listened to the radio, and I played with my
toys, and I went outside. If you give it a chance, it's not so
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was boring,'' Gonzalez repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Hatmaker of the National Cable Television Association
sides with Gonzalez. Hatmaker argues that it is more important for
children to understand the media than to learn to live without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``While parents should turn off the TV at times, we believe
there's a better and more constructive alternative than arbitrarily
turning off the set for an entire week: it's called critical
viewing,'' Hatmaker said. ``It's important to learn how to watch TV
as well as to make smart decisions about what and when to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatmaker recommends that parents talk to their children about
what they see on television and discuss the ways in which
television can be used to manipulate viewers.
</P>
<P>
   If they are like most parents, they will have plenty of
TV-watching experience to draw upon. TV-Turnoff Week founder Henry
Labalme said that the average American will have watched nearly
nine years of TV by age 65, on average of four hours a day. But the
Turnoff is designed to do more than force schoolchildren _ and
their suffering parents _ to stare at the wall when they could be
watching ``Seinfeld'' reruns.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a huge decline in civic engagement in the last 25
years,'' Labalme said. ``Whenever people are home watching
television, they're not involved in their community. They're not at
the Kiwanis club or the Girl Scout meeting. They're not sitting on
the front porch, watching the neighbor's kids. When people give up
television for a week, they let the silence creep back into their
lives and they realize what's missing.''
</P>
<P>
   For some people, living without the television is already a way
of life. But those people are outnumbered 50-to-1 in America, so
they are often misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people find out I don't have a television, they look at
me like I stockpile weapons in my backyard,'' said Kate Alley, 26,
a manager for Bell Atlantic in Manhattan who has been TV-free for
almost four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I don't have a television, I get a lot more done,'' Alley
said. ``There's so little to be gained by watching TV. There's a
limited number of hours in a day, and I don't like to waste my time
as a passive participant where I sit and learn nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   TV-Turnoff participants take note: while other people are
watching ``World's Scariest Police Chases,'' Alley reads, goes for
walks, and keeps in touch with friends. When she needs to zone out,
she will look at magazines or listen to music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Television is primarily a comfort food,'' said TV critic David
Wild, a senior editor at Rolling Stone. ``Certainly there are
people who become television gourmets. They're the kinds that watch
``Masterpiece Theater'' or the Discovery Channel. But these people
are always going to be the minority. The rest of us just use it to
relax.''
</P>
<P>
   There is at least one person leading the monastic TV-free life
who is ready to give in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was addicted,'' said Mark Lyons, 41, of his old television
habit. ``In fact, I'm still addicted. When I visit my parents, I
still have to be very careful to stay away from the television.
Otherwise, I'll sit there with the clicker all day and zone out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lyons, an assistant director of an advocacy group in
Washington, D.C., suspects the lack of a television has hurt his
social life. Lately, he has been pricing out a high-end system to
replace the 12-inch black and white set that was gathering dust in
the back of his closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been looking in the Sunday papers, where they have all
the ads for the sales at electronics stores, and I drool over the
27-inch Sony television sets and the state-of-the-art laserdisc
movie players,'' Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know my fascination with television can get out of
control,'' he said. ``When I get this thing, you may never hear
from me again.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Erik Holm is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
</TEXT>
