<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-HEAT-PILL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPERATURE PILL COULD SAVE FIREFIGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  _
 By DOUGLAS STEINKE  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Glenn has been on the pill. So have some
firefighters and deep sea divers.
</P>
<P>
   This pill is not a contraceptive, Prozac or even Viagra.
Researchers have been testing this product to prevent heat
exhaustion in firefighters. The three-quarter-inch capsule monitors
body temperatures of those who work in extreme environments.
</P>
<P>
   Each CorTemp capsule contains a battery, a temperature sensor
and a transmitter that sends a signal to a computer monitor. The
capsules are produced by scientists at Human Technologies Inc., or
HTI, in St. Petersburg, Fla. They have been used almost exclusively
by NASA and in clinical tests so far.
</P>
<P>
   But the company hopes to start selling the pill to fire
departments in June, HTI spokeswoman Lindy Brounley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``First we would go to several of the firefighter conventions
and demonstrate the product,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters can collapse or die from heat exhaustion,
especially in warmer climates. In Southern California, a
firefighter recently died from the condition while fighting a fire
in the woods, Orange County Fire Authority Capt. Dennis Childress
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all carry water around with us all day and it's a big deal
for us to stay hydrated when we're out there,'' said Childress, who
also heads the health and safety committee of the California State
Firefighters Association. ``I wouldn't say we see a lot of heat
stroke, but we do see an awful lot of heat exhaustion.''
</P>
<P>
   Heat exhaustion is caused by excessive fluid loss, and heat
stroke is caused by the failure of cooling processes, such as
sweating. Heat exhaustion can often be treated by lying down in a
cool place and drinking water or fruit juice, but heat stroke
requires immediate hospitalization and can be fatal. Anyone can
suffer from the conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Childress had not yet heard about CorTemp, which HTI calls the
``ingestible thermometer,'' effective for about three days. ``I
could definitely see it having an application,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, heat exhaustion is a serious issue, said Lt.
Kevin Malley, the fire department's director of human performance.
Malley himself suffered from the condition in 1987 while putting
out a fire in Harlem. Today his picture appears on a poster that
tells firefighters how to avoid heat exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just put out a fire and then you're out on the ground,''
he said. ``If you get out and live then you can laugh about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under New York's one-bottle rule, firefighters are allowed to
work until their first bottle of air is empty. This prevents them
from working in hot temperatures for more than 30 to 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Malley said the New York Fire Department was doing pilot tests
with a number of different products designed to prevent heat
exhaustion. But, he said, ``We haven't ordered anything yet.'' He
would not say whether the department would consider using CorTemp.
</P>
<P>
   HTI bought the product's license in 1988 and started selling a
modified version to paper manufacturing companies, which mount the
device on machines to make sure the rolls of paper do not overheat.
Since 1989, the company has sold 15,000 units.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original use for the CorTemp product_ selling it to the
government_ was not profitable at all,'' said HTI President Bill
Hicks, adding that they are exploring other applications, perhaps
in the food industry.
</P>
<P>
   At $40 a pill and $2,500 for the monitors that display the
pill's signal, fire departments may not be able to afford the
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd imagine the product would have to be significantly proven
before fire departments start putting aside that sort of money for
it,'' said Childress of the Orange County Fire Authority. ``It's
something that would really have to be worked in, because the
profession is very tradition-conscious.''
</P>
<P>
   HTI's Brounley said the pill's price could fall to $12 each if
the company decides to mass-produce it. Currently, scientists must
use a microscope to make each pill in order to see its tiny
circuitry.
</P>
<P>
   Even at $40 a piece the pill may be useful to some fire
departments, said Jerry Knight, a former chief of the St.
Petersburg, Fla. fire department hired by HTI as a marketing
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't really be for the routine, day-to-day
firefighter,'' said Knight, who retired from the fire department in
1986. ``Where I believe it would be appropriate is with the
hazardous material teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters with those teams, Knight said, wear suits that
prevent perspiration and retain heat. Even when those firefighters
are not near a fire, their chances of suffering from heat
exhaustion are higher than usual when wearing the heavy clothing,
especially in the warmer, Southern states.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn White, a scientist and research coordinator for emergency
medicine at the Akron General Medical Center in Ohio, has conducted
three studies using the CorTemp pill.
</P>
<P>
   In one of her studies, which is published in an emergency
medicine journal, White found that the body temperature of
firefighters who were working in hazardous material suits in a
training session increased by nearly one and one-half degrees. An
increase of two degrees is considered dangerous, she said, noting
that firefighters would face higher temperatures in fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get really hot in those puppies really fast,'' she said,
referring to the hazardous material suits.
</P>
<P>
   The $30 to $40 dollars for the CorTemp pill isn't unreasonable,
White said, ``if you're saving someone's life.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Douglas Steinke is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC; _
</P>
</TEXT>
