<HEADER>
A5774 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDREN-VIOLENCE-ART     04-20 1418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-VIOLENCE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN AFFECTED BY DOMESTIC VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might have been a scene from a family photo album. Wendy
Lonergan-Gillen's year-old daughter and preschool son were curled
up on the couch watching a video of their favorite lullabies. They
had just finished eating dinner with their parents and were
settling down before bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   But what was going on in the family's suburban home that evening
in May 1995 was far from a portrait of domestic tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, within earshot of the children, the children's father
was beating their mother, holding her by the neck and pounding her
head into the top step.
</P>
<P>
   During the beating, which lasted several minutes, the
30-year-old mother was praying that the sweet lullabies downstairs
would distract the children and drown out the growing perversion of
their family's home life. Lonergan-Gillen, a waitress, had spent
most of her six-year marriage trying to diffuse her husband's anger
and violent outbursts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to tell myself that (the children) were too young . . .
they were asleep, they couldn't hear it,'' she said. ``It was
easier to say all that. None of us wants to think our children are
affected.''
</P>
<P>
   While parents and others might think that children are not
seriously hurt by domestic violence unless they are physically
injured, researchers have arrived at a far different conclusion:
Children who see or even hear a parent being battered by someone
they love are as traumatized as children who themselves are beaten.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a whole sea change emerging, looking at the
horrendous impact of trauma on children,'' said Dr. Bessel van der
Kolk, medical director of The Trauma Center in Brookline, Mass.,
who since the 1980s has studied post-traumatic stress disorder in
children. ``Resiliency is wishful thinking. It is emotionally too
hard to deal with the stories we hear from kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings are beginning to change the thinking of children's
advocates and those who work with battered mothers. What is
emerging is a growing sense of urgency that the needs of children
who witness violence must be addressed separately from those of
adults.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high. There are about 43,000 Massachusetts
children who see violence at home every year, from shoving to
bloody beatings. Beyond those numbers, thousands of other domestic
incidents go unreported, and many of those are probably witnessed
by children.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting the needs of youngsters who have witnessed violence will
not be easy. They often exhibit troubling behaviors, such as
tantrums, night terrors, bed-wetting, abuse of their mothers, and
talk of suicide.
</P>
<P>
   The movement against domestic violence has long stood for
protecting and empowering women, but some advocates for battered
women acknowledge that the movement has done little more than offer
baby-sitting for their children. But specialists say the advocates
can no longer expect battered mothers alone to help their
youngsters cope with the sight, sounds, and aftermath of domestic
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very encouraging now to see the movement supporting
children and supporting women as parents, and recognizing the
vulnerability of families in the aftermath'' of violence, said
Carrie Pekor Jasper, director of Project We Can Talk About It, a
domestic violence clinic at the Children's Charter Program in
Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Like Children's Charter, The Child Witness to Violence Project
at Boston Medical Center is one of only a few centers in
Massachusetts that specialize in treating children who have
witnessed domestic violence. The project began in 1992 to help
youngsters cope with street violence, but within months, it changed
course as referrals for domestic violence streamed in.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the clinic has been a pioneer in developing methods
to help these children. Some of its approaches include play
therapy, drawing, and one-on-one counseling. Lonergan-Gillen's
children, who have not seen or heard from their father in almost
two years, are receiving therapy through the project.
</P>
<P>
   Still, efforts to help the children of domestic violence are
largely in the planning stages, and professionals say there is an
overwhelming shortage of specialized care. The scarcity is
particularly striking in light of a reported increase in domestic
violence in many cities even as overall rates of violent crime have
gone down.
</P>
<P>
   Those who do offer effective help generally are experienced in
domestic violence work. ``One of the biggest dangers is when
clinicians don't understand the impact of domestic violence, and do
things like require the family and the batterer to meet together to
reconcile,'' said Nalina Narain, a senior policy analyst with Jane
Doe Inc., a Massachusetts coalition for battered women. ``When
there is battering, you just can't resolve a power relationship
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been other miscues, as well. ``The common belief is
that if women leave, then everything will be OK,'' said Betsy
McAlister Groves, director of the Child Witness to Violence
Project, which sees about 125 families a year. ``But what we see is
that children's symptoms are quite persistent, and that they are
affected for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Battered women's shelters, the first line of defense for
troubled families, took in almost 2,000 youngsters last year, and
at least 28 of the state's 32 shelters now have child advocates, as
well as support groups for children, Narain said.
</P>
<P>
   The push to pay more attention to children has spilled over to
other arenas. Since last year, for example, judges have been
required to consider, in writing, the effects of domestic violence
when deciding custody cases and visitation issues. And, starting
this summer, the Massachusetts Department of Social Services is
slated to spend $630,000 on services for children affected by
domestic violence. Such children make up more than 60 percent of
its caseload.
</P>
<P>
   As awareness of the issue grows, schools and pediatric offices
might also play a more important role in identifying symptoms of
domestic trauma. In the past, these symptoms often went
unrecognized or were mistaken for other problems.
</P>
<P>
   Van der Kolk, Narain, and others, for example, suspect a link
between the skyrocketing diagnoses of attention deficit disorder
and hyperactivity, and the apparent inability of many child
development specialists, teachers, and other professionals to
recognize post-traumatic stress disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Van der Kolk's other findings about trauma in children suggest
there might be biological implications as well. ``Kids' biology
actually changes by witnessing (violence), by being terrified, and
having no one to calm them down. Kids can't do that themselves.
They totally rely on their caregivers for that. If it doesn't
happen, you get alterations in the brain.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the issues are emotional or biological, the pain is
indisputable. Maria, a mother of three, was stalked, burned, cut,
and punched over several months by an ex-boyfriend _ horror that
was witnessed by her 5-year-old son. The child was overcome by
fear.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week at her home, she said her decision
``not to share her private business'' ended when her son's
preschool teachers called her in for an emergency meeting last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told (the teachers) he didn't want to go home. He brought a
knife to school and told them, `I will kill myself. Mama is going
to die,' '' said Maria, 25, who asked that her real name not be
used. Her son was hospitalized for 10 days in December 1996, and
has been in therapy at Child Witness to Violence since January
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Maria's daughter, age 6, does not say much about what she saw
and heard, but Maria said she has been warned that signs of trauma,
such as acting out, could appear. As for her youngest son, now 2,
whom she had with her abusive boyfriend, Maria is unsure what to
expect. An infant, he was lying in his bassinet in her bedroom the
first time his father punched her. The baby was a late walker, slow
speaker, and still shrieks or fusses when she leaves his side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think they heard it,'' Maria said. ``I thought they
were heavy sleepers. But I never thought things would reach the
level of violence they did. I kept thinking it would stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
