<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT TOO LATE TO COOL GLOBAL WARMING 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOE MIRABILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco Bay area is one the regions of
the United States threatened by a rise in sea level from global
warming.
</P>
<P>
   So says the Union of Concerned Scientists, an environmental
think tank in Cambridge, Mass. How will the Bay area be affected
if, as the United Nations Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change
says could happen, the sea level rises by as much as 3 feet?
</P>
<P>
   According to a study by the Oakland, Calif.-based research group
Pacific Institute, business and residential structures near the
shores of San Francisco Bay, valued at an estimated $48 billion,
will be threatened by a 3-foot rise in the Bay.
</P>
<P>
   This group estimates the costs of protecting these buildings
will be about $1 billion. Add another $1 billion to protect or
restore wetlands and to build protective structures and buy
equipment such as pumps, drainage systems and navigation locks.
</P>
<P>
   Maintenance costs would run $100 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   A rising sea level also means a threat of saltwater incursion
into the Bay and rivers. In December 1997, the National
Environmental Trust, a Washington-based advocacy group, warned of
saltwater intrusion from rising sea levels miles into the
Sacramento-San Joaquin River Delta, from which two-thirds of the
population of California derives its fresh water. California cannot
afford to have its principal water supply threatened, especially
since the state's population (currently 33 million) is expected to
almost double by 2040.
</P>
<P>
   According to Ellen Mosley-Thompson of Ohio State University, a
glacier specialist, the rising sea level will be primarily due to
glacial and ice cap melting and the expansion of warming seas.
</P>
<P>
   Some examples are:
</P>
<P>
   _ In Southern Peru the rate of melting of the Qori Kalis glacier
from 1983 to 1991 was three times the pace of the previous 20
years.
</P>
<P>
   _ If present rates of warming continue, all glaciers in Glacier
National Park will be gone by 2030.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Lewis Glacier on Mount Kenya has decreased in size by 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the Ruwenzori range of mountains in Uganda, glaciers are in
severe meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Bering Glacier, North America's largest glacier located in
Alaska, is retreating rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a new wrinkle. Recent findings of severe thinning at
the southern and eastern edges of Greenland's ice sheet surprised
scientists at the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   If the melting on Greenland's icy borders continues, glaciers
won't be the sole contributors to rising sea levels. And if both
ice sheets start to go, meaning Greenland and Antarctica, it's a
new ballgame. A 3-foot sea-level rise will only be the start.
</P>
<P>
   Now add China to the mix. In December 1996, Bill Nitze, the
assistant administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency,
noted that China, before 2050, may be producing as much carbon as
the entire world is producing now (more than 6 billion tons of
carbon annually).
</P>
<P>
   The first step is to get the Kyoto Protocol ratified by the U.S.
Senate. The Kyoto Protocol requires that industrialized countries
cut carbon emissions by the year 2012. While awaiting the
ratification of the Kyoto Protocol, this country and other
industrialized countries should be making plans for a general
mobilization to convert to green technologies to produce
electricity and to manufacture vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Global warming is upon us, but we have the know-how to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Mirabile is director of EcoBridge, a nonprofit
environmental organization based in San Francisco,
www.ecobridge.org.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
