<HEADLINE>
AGENCIES SPLIT ON `DATE-RAPE' DRUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROSSE ILE, Mich. _ For 15-year-old Samantha Reid, it was a dose
of death, a poison allegedly delivered to her in the false
innocence of a fizzy drink.
</P>
<P>
   For 55-year-old Bob Cloud, it is daily salvation, a drinkable
solution to an ailment that threatens his livelihood and, at times,
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Reid's killer and Cloud's savior is a drug known as GHB, a
chemical chameleon that has gained notoriety as a deadly
``date-rape'' drug, while also showing promise as a treatment for
the debilitating sleep disorder narcolepsy.
</P>
<P>
   Those contrasting uses have resulted in a paralyzing faceoff
between two federal agencies over how quickly and how strictly to
control the drug, most commonly found as an odorless, colorless
liquid that depresses the central nervous system. Rapists use the
drug to render their victims unconscious. With narcoleptics, for
reasons of body chemistry that are still being studied, it seems to
have the opposite physical effect.
</P>
<P>
   The Drug Enforcement Administration is seeking fast action and
the toughest controls on GHB, hoping to classify it along with
heroin and LSD as a drug without any redeeming medical value,
carrying with it the heaviest possible penalties for manufacture,
distribution, and possession.
</P>
<P>
   But the Food and Drug Administration, eager to explore its value
to narcoleptics like Cloud, is still reviewing the drug. It is
expected to recommend a much less stringent control level for
illicit use, which would allow continued examination for beneficial
treatments. The FDA already has approved GHB for several drug
studies, effectively blocking the DEA from immediate action.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has entered the fray as well, with two pending bills
that reflect the competing interests. One seeks the strictest
federal limits on GHB, citing its reported involvement in at least
32 deaths since 1995 and dozens of alleged sexual assaults. The
other puts a priority on helping perhaps 100,000 people who suffer
from the worst symptoms of narcolepsy, specifically a condition
called cataplexy that causes sudden collapses in potentially
dangerous situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides have a point, but right now we're doing nothing to
close this loophole and regulate this drug on a federal level. I am
anxious to see some action, not only as a member of Congress, but
as a dad,'' said Representative Fred Upton, a Michigan Republican
who, as chairman of a House Commerce subcommittee, convened a
hearing on the drug last month.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of federal action, states have passed a patchwork
quilt of laws and regulations. At least 20 states have outlawed GHB
largely because of its role in date rapes, but they have adopted a
wide range of approaches. Massachusetts has placed GHB in its most
dangerous illicit drug category, while Tennessee, for instance,
treats it as the equivalent of more benign drugs like Valium.
</P>
<P>
   Adding urgency to calls for a national approach is the fact that
several Internet sites promote GHB as a muscle builder, sexual
booster, sleep aid, age-fighter, and antidepressant. Several
Internet sites also offer a recipe for kitchen-sink chemists to
transform a related substance called GBL (gamma butyrolactone) into
GHB (gamma hydroxybutyrate).
</P>
<P>
   Until the FDA issued a warning earlier this year, products
containing GBL were sold since the late 1980s at health food stores
nationwide as dietary supplements. Although those products are
supposed to be off the market, GBL can still be ordered via the
Internet, ostensibly for use as an industrial solvent.
</P>
<P>
   While federal agencies and lawmakers struggle with how best to
respond, the subtleties of the debate are lost on Judith Clark,
Samantha Reid's grieving mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think date-rape drugs like GHB should be in a class by
themselves, the highest possible class,'' Clark said in an
interview. ``With cocaine, marijuana, whatever, you have to want to
take those drugs. These can be slipped to you without you even
knowing it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that is just what authorities say happened to Clark's
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 16, Reid and two other 15-year-old girls decided to test
the limits of their weekend curfews. They accompanied four young
men to an apartment on Grosse Ile, an affluent bedroom community 20
miles from Detroit that prides itself on its three golf courses and
three yacht clubs. With 14,000 residents and a nearly nonexistent
crime rate, Grosse Ile bills itself as ``Michigan's Safest
Community.''
</P>
<P>
   As midnight passed and the girls watched videos, police and
prosecutors say, their hosts mixed a potion of Mountain Dew, orange
juice, and a secret ingredient, either GHB or GBL.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, Reid was dead from an apparent overdose,
authorities said. Her best friend, Melanie Sindone, fell into a
coma but later recovered. The third girl also drank the concoction
but was unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the four young men _ one 17, two 18, and one 25 _ has
been charged with three counts of poisoning and one count of
manslaughter. They face up to life in prison if convicted at a
trial expected to be held later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Grosse Ile police Detective John Szczepaniak, who is overseeing
the case, said the men did not obtain the drug through the
Internet, but he declined to elaborate on the alleged source.
Attorneys for the men declined to comment other than to say their
clients are innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, sitting outside a court hearing on pretrial
motions, Clark sat quietly, cradling a photo of her daughter. It
showed a brown-haired girl in a freshman basketball uniform, a
broad smile creasing her face. She was a fine athlete, played
trumpet, wrote poetry, and took special pleasure in watching old
couples who seemed to be in love, her mother said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray her death isn't made meaningless. I'm going to do what
I can to help get the drug banned for good,'' said Clark, a single
mother who also has an 18-year-old son. ``I know they talk about
using it for narcolepsy, but I think that's just a copout for the
big pharmaceutical businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Some 250 miles away, in Cincinnati, Bob Cloud has nothing but
sympathy for Reid's family. But he fears how he and fellow
narcoleptics would be affected if lawmakers and federal agencies
reacted emotionally to Reid's death and the deaths of others who
ingested GHB or GBL, some of them in search of an illicit high, and
some unwittingly.
</P>
<P>
   Although it can be used to put people to sleep, GHB _ under
controlled circumstances and doses _ appears to have something of
an opposite effect on narcoleptics, limiting the cataplexy episodes
that result from sudden surges of emotion, including surprise,
anger, and even happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Before he started taking GHB more than 16 years ago as part of
one of the earliest scientific studies, Cloud said, he suffered
potentially deadly bouts of cataplexy in which his muscles would be
temporarily paralyzed. He fell off docks into the water on several
occasions. One time, Cloud said, he fell down a department store
escalator, then lay motionless at the bottom as the moving stairs
hit his head over and over until someone pulled him to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of this drug, I live a relatively normal life,'' said
Cloud, a lawyer who has been married for 26 years and is the father
of two grown children. ``I am sure that without it, I would be on
disability. Or worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The use of GHB as a narcolepsy treatment _ the only legal way to
obtain it is through clinical studies _ is being investigated by a
small Minnesota drug company called Orphan Medical, which calls its
product Xyrem. If GHB were classified as one of the highest two
levels under the federal Controlled Substances Act, as proposed by
the DEA, Orphan Medical would be forced to abandon its research,
said Vice President Patti Engel.
</P>
<P>
   Other drugs, such as Ritalin, have been successfully marketed as
medicine despite having one of those illicit drug classifications.
But Engel said the potential market for narcolepsy drugs is so
small it would be impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The requirements around the manufacture, storage and
distribution (of drugs under those classifications) are so
extremenly onerous we could never afford to develop it, nor could
patients who need it ever afford to purchase it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Engel said one possible approach by federal authorities would be
a compromise under which GHB and related drugs like GBL would
receive a moderate classification for the purposes of research, but
carry the toughest possible penalties when used for illicit
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Reuter, associate FDA director for domestic and
international drug control, last week declined to say how long it
would take for the agency to decide how it wants GHB classified for
illegal use, saying only it would take a ``delicate balancing act''
between public health and public safety issues.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Clark said she will continue to press for a complete
ban on the drug, while Cloud will work to keep it available for
narcoleptics like himself. ``I wish they would recognize this is
our only hope for health,'' Cloud said. ``People can overdose and
kill themselves on aspirin, but we don't do away with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
