<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-VOTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT TO WEIGH MONEY'S ROLE IN POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After serving 22 years in the Georgia House of
Representatives, John White felt he had a strong chance to win a
state Senate seat in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoyed name recognition as the first black legislator to
represent southwest Georgia since Reconstruction and commanded a
loyal following among voters across the red clay farmlands of the
region. What White lacked was money.
</P>
<P>
   The incumbent, Mark Taylor, spent $17 for every dollar White
produced. Using $90,000 of his own money to help finance a $270,000
campaign, Taylor blanketed the nine-county district with billboards
and television commercials. White raised only $16,000 from friends,
black social clubs and a few white supporters and relied on
hand-shaking to convey his message.
</P>
<P>
   White lost, yet in a way the battle continues. The election
became the genesis for a lawsuit designed to force public campaign
financing on Georgia, and after nearly two years of setbacks and
delays, White's allies who adopted his case will get a hearing next
month before a three-judge panel of the 11th Circuit of the US
Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the case could have national ramifications by
opening the increasingly costly political process to candidates
with little money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that private funding of campaigns systematically
excludes people of modest means,'' said Gregory Luke, an attorney
with the Boston-based National Voting Rights Institute. ``It's a
common theme around the country: People without a lot of money
can't participate in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Congress set up public financing for presidential
campaigns more than two decades ago, only four states,
Massachusetts, Maine, Vermont and Arizona, have taken steps to
provide funds for contests on the state level.
</P>
<P>
   The Voting Rights Institute, founded in 1994 and funded by
foundations, is handling the litigation for the Georgia NAACP,
which sought help following White's loss in a campaign that
involved racial overtones as well as lavish spending.
</P>
<P>
   White, in an interview, said he decided in 1995 that Taylor
``was not going to go back to the Senate without a challenge''
after Taylor served as the ``architect'' for a reapportionment plan
that White considered unfair. ``He reduced the black population in
our congressional district,'' White said, in an unsuccessful effort
to oust Representative Sanford Bishop, one of three black members
of Congress from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Although blacks account for about half of the population in the
state Senate district that extends from the city of Albany to the
Alabama border, ``Taylor swamped us with money,'' White said.
Taylor won, drawing 58 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, elected lieutenant governor last fall, did not respond
to a request to discuss the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit, filed in August 1997, the plaintiffs invoke the
``equal protection'' provisions of the 14th Amendment and attack
what they describe as a ``wealth primary'' in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georgia sanctions and exacerbates the exclusionary operation
of wealth in state elections,'' the suit charges, noting that
expensive ``multimedia advertising has replaced traditional forums
of public debate,'' forcing candidates to amass tens of thousands
of dollars to buy TV and radio time.
</P>
<P>
   Citing statistics that show that victors in recent Georgia
Senate races raised an average of $56,530 and outspent the losing
candidates, the NAACP suit argues that ``access to wealth has
become a precondition of participation in electoral politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Luke, who will argue the case here May 18, said it is possible
for the plaintiffs to succeed without reversing the Supreme Court's
1976 landmark decision in Buckley v. Valeo, which upheld the First
Amendment rights of a candidate to spend personal funds without
restriction.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't prevent Mark Taylor from doing anything,'' Luke said,
``but we can allow people of modest means to mount viable
campaigns.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than seeking to limit personal expenditures, the suit
suggests several court-ordered remedies _ ranging from state-issued
media vouchers to public funding _ ``to permit candidates to run a
competitive state Senate campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathryn L. Allen, senior assistant attorney general, will
represent the state. ``The state didn't cause the disparity''
between rich and poor candidates ``and did nothing to promote it,''
she says. ``You can't prove it's the state's fault.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Legislature chooses to subsidize campaigns with public
funds, Allen said, ``they should be allowed to do so. But it should
not be mandated by the federal court.''
</P>
<P>
   The case was dismissed without a hearing by a US District Court
judge last year, but the plaintiffs won a victory last month when
the 11th Circuit agreed to hear their appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Founding Fathers tried to strike a balance'' when they
developed voting rights 200 years ago, said Luke. ``But so much has
changed in the last 20 years with the professionalism of politics''
and the high cost of consultants and TV time.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the system is changed, he said, politics will become an
exclusive preserve for the wealthy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
