<HEADLINE>
THRILLS, CHILLS, AND SPILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Do (newspaper columnists) use frisson to mean `hint' or
`inkling' about three times per 600-word column _ or is it just in
New York, especially the bigger daily newspaper there?'' grumbles
Bill Earls of Middletown, Conn. ``A terrible word, terribly
overused. Next to it, famously'' _ another '90s vogue word _
``looks discreet.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a bit hard on frisson, which can spice up prose nicely,
used in moderation. However, frisson doesn't mean ``inkling,''
though Earls may have seen such a misusage: Not long ago, a New
York Times reviewer wrote ``Lansky goes his calculating way with
never a frisson of threat.''
</P>
<P>
   But a frisson _ French for ``shiver'' or ``thrill'' _ is not the
hint or inkling, but the shudder of anticipation aroused by the
hint; not what Meyer Lansky did or didn't radiate, but what people
around him felt. A frisson can be scary or delicious, or both at
once, if you like horror movies.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no doubt it's a trendy word, as Earls suspects. But
this newspaper, as it happens, has been sparing with its frissons,
averaging one per month even in the most thrilling years of the
decade. (The low of the past 20 years was sober 1981, during which
not a single event was stimulating enough to bring forth a frisson.
And in 1979, frisson was new enough that one writer got it
completely wrong, describing ``a frisson of pompoms'' at an Orange
Bowl game, when he surely meant a flourish.)
</P>
<P>
   The Times may appear more excitable, with 17 frissons so far
this year, compared to the Globe's four, and 37 last year to our
11. But since our big-sister daily publishes far more total words,
the proportion may be about the same. And New Yorkers being New
Yorkers, they were already lamenting their weakness for frisson in
the '80s; now they're using the word with that conscious air that
says ``I know this is a buzzword, and I'm using it ironically and
amusingly, not because I'm a language lemming.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, New York magazine describes the Caldor store in
Bridgehampton, which closed last month, as a place where ``the
rarefied clientele that frequented Barneys during the week got a
declasse frisson from wading knee-deep into a pile of house
slippers or sizing up a shelf of Thighmasters.'' The thrill of
novelty may be gone, but the frissons, it seems, are lingering on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If only it were simple &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's no flood tide, but pleas keep trickling in from
defenders of the subjunctive, concerned that journalists are
helping to kill off a useful feature of the English language.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the fossils of subjunctivism _ Come what may, heaven
forbid _ that worry the writers. Nor is it the poetic subjunctive,
as in Shakespeare's ``If this be error and upon me proved / I never
writ, nor no man ever loved.'' No, the daily battle, they say, is
over were and was, and which goes where.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was in Dixie''? Wrong, wrong, wrong. Using was for
were is incorrect and illogical, writes Robert Haddleton of
Norfolk, seconded by Dale Cook of Woodville. Were should be used in
statements that are contrary to fact, our teachers told us: ``If I
were a rich man,'' subjunctive mood; ``When I was a rich man''
indicative mood. And yet, since at least the '50s, usagists have
noted that was often appears in contrary-to-fact statements; the
diligent editors of Merriam-Webster's usage guide find that was for
were has been common in contrary-to-fact clauses since about 1700.
</P>
<P>
   Once out of school, most of us seem to judge the acceptability
of the subjunctive was by ear. Few people say ``If I was you,'' for
example. (If I'm wrong, I don't want to know it.) But the M-W
editors quote from a Henry Adams letter that describes people ``all
staring gravely, as if it were a funeral, at me as if I was the
coffin.''
</P>
<P>
   How many subjunctive detectives would notice that the was,
according to the rules, should be were? Does was fly under our
radar because the as ifs have so firmly established the
counterfactual nature of the premise? Or because we share
(consciously or not) Adams's urge to vary the verb?
</P>
<P>
   Other subjunctivists, in any case, are more alarmed at seeing
were used for was, a mistake often triggered by an If clause: ``If
he were wrong, he should apologize.'' Had we but world enough and
time, we would hear from them, too _ but it will have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378;
freeman(at)globe.com. Include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
