<HEADLINE>
EUROPE SAILING ARE A HIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the cruise world, Alaska is hot, not cold, and Europe is
rapidly warming.
</P>
<P>
   While Alaska, in season, has become one of the hottest cruising
regions in the world, cruise lines are sending more and more of
their ships to European waters. And the number of ships is expected
to increase in the upcoming years.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing cooling off this season is the war in
Kosovo, which is causing lines to avoid the entire Adriatic. One
thing is certain: Cruise lines will always avoid any area where
there is trouble.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Even river cruises along eastern European countries are being
affected by some cancelations as travelers express concerns about
the escalation of war or other war-related problems in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Princess Cruises' Grand Princess, the present holder
of the world's largest cruise ship title, had its maiden voyages in
Europe. And it will return this year along with three additional
Princess ships. The demand for cruises in Europe, the
Mediterranean, and the Baltic is growing with each year and the
lines are deploying more and more ships. Popular lines like Royal
Caribbean, Celebrity, and Norwegian Cruise Line are joining regular
European cruisers like Holland America, Cunard, Costa, Crystal,
Radisson Seven Seas, Royal Olympic, Seabourn, Silversea, Windstar,
Bergen, Classical, and Orient Lines.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the list, travelers interested in sailing in Europe
will find great flexibility in ports of call.
</P>
<P>
   There are many good reasons to consider a European cruise:
First, there's Europe itself with all its culture, history, dining,
and other pleasures; then there is price, with cruises beginning at
around $1,300 plus air fare (even air fares can be less costly
booked with a cruise); and, finally, there is the cruise itself _ a
relaxing, stress-free way to travel. On a cruise there is no
packing and unpacking at each port.
</P>
<P>
   Should a cruise on the ocean not be to your liking, Europe also
has some grand river cruises. Grand Circle Travel, which
specializes in travel for those 50 and older, has found that river
cruises so popular that it is now building its own vessels. The
company said that in the last two years sales of its European river
cruises grew 50 percent and it predicts even greater growth for
this year and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Majesty's season
</P>
<P>
   Boston's cruise season began last Sunday as the newly stretched
Norwegian Majesty headed for Bermuda for the first of its 26 weekly
voyages to the island. In January, the Majesty was cut in half and
a 112-foot addition was added. But don't be concerned. Norwegian
Cruise Line has done this twice before with its Norwegian Wind and
Norwegian Dream, both in 1998 and both with 130-foot midsection
additions. And if that's not enough assurance, consider this: On
its crossing from the shipyard in Germany to Boston, the Majesty
hit not one but two massive storms with 35-foot waves. Captain
Einar Lindlupsen said the ship handled the storms well. Some of the
workers sent along on the trip for finishing work didn't do so well
and ended up seasick. But they worked through the night last
Saturday to make the ship ready for its first Bermuda sailing last
Sunday at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hudson River
</P>
<P>
   James Fenimore Cooper called The Hudson River ``this nation's
Rhine . . . the mighty river, complete with our own humble castles,
legends, and ancient associations.'' Now cruises are being offered
in summer aboard the 63-foot Crescent. The vessel is followed by a
chartered bus that meets the boat at docks to take travelers to
historic and scenic spots, then brings them to a variety of inns
and hotels where their luggage will be waiting. The cruises are
planned for June 13-20, Sept. 12-19. Sept. 26-Oct. 3, and Oct.
10-17. The all-inclusive cost is $1,890. For information, call Karl
Rodman of River Valley Tours at 800-836-2128.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Holiday cruises
</P>
<P>
   It's never too early to plan ahead. And Holland America is
offering passengers who book a Christmas cruise in the Caribbean on
board either the Nieuw Amersterdam or the Westerdam
two-fo-one-savings. The cruises, which leave on Dec. 18 and 19,
begin at $1,149 (air fare extra), are for 10 days, and include all
the holiday favorites, from foods and decorations to music and
services conducted by on-board Catholic, Protestant, and Jewish
clergy.
</P>
<P>
   In Hawaii, the classic SS Independence (built in Quincy, Mass.)
is featuring three holiday cruises (two for seven nights, one for
three nights) that include a stay in Honolulu, the site of a
spectacular holiday light display. Children also travel free (port
charges and taxes are extra and there are some restrictions). On
these cruises, a family of four can enjoy a three-night cruise and
one night at the Outrigger East hotel, beginning at $2,258.
</P>
<P>
   For its holiday cruise, the Crystal Harmony is featuring the
Glenn Miller Orchestra during a 13-day South American voyage
leaving Barbados Dec. 14. During the cruise passengers will be
treated to 11 days of dance by the band now led by jazz trombonist
Larry O'Brien.
</P>
</TEXT>
