<HEADLINE>
A CAPE COD MARITIME CELEBRATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cape Cod is celebrating its maritime history. The sixth annual
celebration runs through May 16 and includes lighthouse tours,
walks, cruises, boatyard tours, and more.
</P>
<P>
   Among some of the highlights are a symposium of Cape Cod
Maritime History May 8 at the Sheraton Hyannis Resort ($40 a
person, for details call 508-394-7505); an in-the- water boat show
April 30 and May 1-2 at Falmouth Inner Harbor; a Spring Fling May 8
in Chatham; a lighthouse tour in Truro and a tour of the Crosby
Boatyard (the oldest in the country), both on May 12; a Marstons
Mills Maritime History walk May 13; a Highland lighthouse tour in
Truro, a tour of Provincetown, a Hyannis history walk, and a sunset
lighthouse cruise from Falmouth Harbor (call 508-548-7270 for
tickets), all on May 14; lighthouse tours in Eastham, Woods Hole,
North Truro, Chatham, and Provincetown, along with an open house at
the Massachusetts Maritime Academy in Buzzards Bay and Coast Guard
station open houses, all on May 15; more lighthouse tours and an
open house at the Cape Cod Canal control center in Buzzards Bay,
both on May 16. And throughout the month there will be talks on the
people and places of the Cape.
</P>
<P>
   For a complete listing of events, stop by any information center
on the way to Cape Cod or call 508-888-1233; or visit
www.heritagecapecod.org. Ask also for information on the sixth
annual Cape Cod Heritage Week June 11-20. More than 150 events are
planned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Literary Trail
</P>
<P>
   The Literary Trail of Greater Boston, developed by the Boston
History Collaborative, has been so successful that it has been
extended through May. The 20 mile, four-hour trolley tour is held
Saturdays beginning at 1:15 p.m. and visits famous authors' homes
and other literary sites. Tickets are $35 for adults. For
reservations, call 617-574-5950 or visit www.lit-trail.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cape travel show
</P>
<P>
   Explore 99, the second annual adventure and ecotourism dhow,
will be held Saturday from 5 to 8:30 p.m. at the Cape Cod Museum of
Natural History in Brewster. Among topics will be small-ship
expeditions, Antarctica, Nepal, Costa Rica, and African safaris.
The show is free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Coffee milk?
</P>
<P>
   Coffee syrup, the key ingredient in coffee milk, Rhode Island's
official state drink, is now available in nostalgic souvenir-size
bottles. The Blackstone Valley Tourism Council is offering
four-ounce bottles of the syrup as a way to raise funds for the
British canal boat being built in England for the Blackstone
Valley. The canal boat will be used for tours of the Blackstone
River. ``Coffee milk is important to every Rhode Islander,'' said
Robert Billington, president of the tourism council. ``This is a
wonderful way for those not familiar with coffee syrup to sample
its many uses. It's best enjoyed mixed with milk, or as an ice
cream topping.'' The syrup is made by Autocrat Coffee, based in the
Blackstone Valley of Rhode Island. Bottles are $2 and can be
obtained by calling 401-724-2200 or stopping by the Visitor Center
at 171 Main St., Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tiffany exhibit
</P>
<P>
   ``Brilliant Ideas: The Designs of Louis Comfort Tiffany'' will
be on display at the Mark Twain House National Historic Landmark in
Hartford, Conn. through June 1, 2000. The exhibit features Tiffany
pieces from exquisite lamps and vases to stained glass. The Twain
house, where Samuel Clemens (better known as Mark Twain) lived, was
redecorated in 1881 by Tiffany's firm and is the only
Tiffany-designed interior open to the public. The Tiffany exhibit
in the museum's Visitor Center is free. Admission to the house is
$9 for adults, $8 for seniors, and $5 for children 6-12. For
information, call 860-247-0998.
</P>
</TEXT>
