<HEADLINE>
HEALTH AND FITNESS, 1830'S STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's those rich, spicy foods that are ruining your health _ and
washing them down with alcohol or caffeine-laced drinks makes
things worse! That was the no-nonsense message spread by Sylvester
Graham, a former minister, as he toured New England and the
mid-Atlantic states in the 1830s. The result? Both ridicule (the
man did have a prickly personality) and a devoted following.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, perhaps the original low-fat diet guru, advocated eating
``vegetables, plain bread made from coarse, unbolted wheat, and
other bland natural foods,'' said Tom Kelleher, a research
historian at Old Sturbridge Village, Mass. ``He thought that the
correct diet, combined with a regimen of sleeping on a hard
mattress, fresh air, pure water, exercise, and sexual restraint
would lead to a happier, healthier life.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham's views are included in a new exhibit at Old Sturbridge,
``Picture of Health: Illness and Healing in New England
1790-1860,'' which runs from this April 24 through Jan. 1, 2001.
Here's what else you'll find:
</P>
<P>
   --Early American home remedies. For a cough: ``Make a hole
through a lemon, roast it, and catch the juice.'' For consumption
(tuberculosis): ``Every morning cut up a little turf of fresh
earth, and lying down, breathe into the hole for a quarter of an
hour.'' For an earache: ``The smoke of tobacco blown into the ear
is excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   --Evidence of tooth transplants in early America. ``While some
dentists claimed that the teeth took root and remained firm for
years, the true failure rate must have been near 100 percent,''
said Kelleher.
</P>
<P>
   --Colorful advertisements for pills, potions, and assorted
nostrums, such as Dr. Benjamin Smith's ``Improved Indian Vegetable
Pills.'' Many of the medicines consisted mostly of inert
ingredients, alcohol (thus making the patient at least feel good),
or substances that remain largely unknown today.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit provides a chance to learn about the healers and
preachers who are now forgotten. Well, not quite forgotten.
Sylvester Graham, the diet guru, is memorialized in a creation of
his disciples: the graham cracker.
</P>
<P>
   (Old Sturbridge Village is a re-created New England community of
the 1830s in Sturbridge, Mass. For more information, call
800-SEE-1830, or TTY, 508-347-5383.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: You're visiting South America, so it's important to
know the difference between a cougar, a puma, a catamount, and a
mountain lion. What's the difference? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: In Thailand, the movie ``There's Something About Mary''
is called ``My Love Will Stand All Outrageous Events.'' In Hong
Kong, it's ``Enjoy Yourself in the Game of Love.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``It is not he who has lived the longest, but he who has
traveled the farthest, who knows the most.'' _ Armenian proverb. &QL; 
 &QL; 
It's contest time: In connection with Carla Neggers' new romantic
novel ``Kiss the Moon,'' which is set in New Hampshire, Mira Books
is offering a chance to win a three-night, four-day stay for for
two at the Battenkill Inn in Manchester Village, Vt. In 100 words
or less, tell why you want to discover the romance of New England,
and mail your essay to Kiss the Moon Contest, Dunwoodie
Communications, 386 Park Avenue South, 18th Floor, New York, NY
10016 by May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, for a chance at winning a $10,000 vacation
custom-designed by you, visit www.resortquest.com or print your
name, address, and daytime phone number on a 3- by 5-inch card and
send to ResortQuest Escape Sweepstakes, c/o Thompson &AMP; Price, 50
Peabody Place, Fourth Floor, Memphis, TN 38103. Electronic entries
must be recieved by April 30; mailed entries must be postmarked by
that date and received by May 10. Good luck. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fascinating facts: Things we learned while visiting Walt Disney
World's Animal Kingdom: (1) Bugs make up 80 percent of the animal
world; (2) the cheetah is the only great cat that purrs. (The theme
park has just opened a visually stunning section devoted to the
animals of Asia. Among attractions are a jungle trail and a wild
river ride on which you will get wet.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Thanks for the help: Directions on a snack-sized bag of American
Airlines peanuts: ``Instructions: Open packet, eat nuts.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Whoops: In Australia, Burger Kings are known as Hungry Jack
restaurants, not Happy Jack as we unconsciously wrote recently
because we were in a jovial mood. A reader adds: ``I did, however,
see one such fast-food restaurant labeled as `Burger King' while we
were there. I wonder if they will all be renamed? Maybe for the
2000 Olympics?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? No difference. They're the same animal. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
