<HEADER>
A5793 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-EGYPT-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAK     04-20 0965
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EGYPT-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 ASWAN, Egypt: ... more tranquility.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tranquil also describes the Winter Palace's Royal Bar, the place
to put your feet up after a hot day of sightseeing and challenges
like dealing with the endless bargaining any ride in an Egyptian
taxi requires. The bar is all dark woodwork, lit with glowing,
backlit stained glass. It has a formal feel, as does the entire
place. On the night when I ambled across the hall to make dinner
reservations in the 1886 Restaurant, the hotel's fanciest, I was
reminded that my companion would have to wear a jacket and tie. She
did.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel acts as a giant buffer between the frenzy of Luxor and
the calm of the gardens, the most glorious in town, overflowing
with palms, hibiscus, hollyhocks, nasturtiums, marigolds,
ornamental pools, and an aviary filled with cooing doves. (Dinner?)
The star attraction in this oasis is a huge swimming pool, where,
during my visit, there were a lot of seriously flabby Europeans of
a certain age wearing skimpy swimsuits, exposing pale,
soon-to-be-sunburned flesh. You wonder what the Egyptian male
waiters serving them poolside _ men accustomed to seeing Egyptian
women covered head to toe _ make of this display.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Nile is just another patch of water, a manager at the Mena
House informs me. But the Pyramids are unique.
</P>
<P>
   The Mena House has the world's greatest view of the world's
greatest monuments _ if you get the right room. Because the hotel's
18-hole golf course is so close to the Great Pyramid, guests in the
past have occasionally climbed it in order to use it as the world's
largest golf tee. You can't do that anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Originally built as a royal hunting lodge, the Mena House was
expanded with the 1869 opening of the Suez Canal, when Cairo
welcomed the Empress Eugenie by building a brand new road out to
Giza. The spiffy road helped spur tourism, and eventually, some
wealthy Britons bought the Mena House and spent a fortune turning
it into a deluxe hotel, fitting it out with elaborate latticework,
tiles, screens, and arabesque arches. More than a century on, the
sense of luxury still prevails.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in 40 acres of jasmine-scented grounds, the hotel has
an outline that is as complex as that of the pyramids is smooth.
Turrets, towers, and long rows of arches punctuate the facade.
Inside the lobby, hanging like so many stalactites, are dozens of
glass pendants that cast a soft golden glow on you as you check in.
If you've just arrived from chaotic Cairo, or its equally hectic
airport, you'll find basking under them soothing indeed.
</P>
<P>
   The Mena House is a self-contained world, with sports facilities
including the Cairo area's largest swimming pool, several
distinguished restaurants _ including The Moghul Room, Egypt's
finest Indian eatery, where the Red Sea prawns are divine _ and a
casino, nightclub, and discotheque. Heretical though the thought
is, there would be enough to occupy you for a few days even without
the Pyramids. But of course you'll want to explore them thoroughly,
and since they're a five-minute stroll from the hotel door, you can
do so in easy stages, breaking for a poolside lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The decor in the Mena House's larger rooms and suites is
completely over the top, with Islamic arches, mirrors, and gilding
the dominant motifs. Consider my bathroom. Beware the bather who
steps from this tub with a less than confident body image. You're
confronted with a full-length mirror. Step to the sink and there's
a five-sided mirror to reveal your every flaw. En route to the
dressing room you run a gantlet of full-length mirrors on both
sides. In the bedroom, a huge, scallop-shaped mirror hangs over the
dressing table. The sole occupant of this extravagant space, I
nevertheless never felt alone.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A couple of caveats. In addition to the 19th-century rooms, all
three of these hotels have modern wings that, while comfortable,
are relatively charmless. Meanwhile, the historic sections of all
three have some rooms with views of the Nile or, in the case of
Mena House, the Pyramids, and others that overlook the hotel
grounds. If you feel you haven't traveled all the way to Egypt to
gaze at a plot of petunias, you'll want the more dramatic vistas.
Be prepared to pay extra for them, though.
</P>
<P>
   Also worth remembering is that the Egyptian government's idea of
what constitutes a five-star hotel _ a classification all the above
have received _ isn't necessarily up to the standards of, say, the
Savoy Group. Rooms in all three hotels are slightly run-down. The
government actually owns all three properties, which are managed by
foreigners: the French Sofitel group in the case of the Winter
Palace and Old Cataract; the Indian-based Oberoi company in the
case of the Mena House. The top managers in the hotels are
foreigners, but most of the staff are Egyptian, and haven't
necessarily ever even seen a truly great hotel. So the managers are
left trying to describe one to them. Sometimes it works. On the
other hand, in the Winter Palace I was served wine with a blob of
cork floating in it. When I mentioned this to the waiter, he told
me to take it out.
</P>
<P>
   About the wine. Egypt has good grape-growing conditions but also
an Islamic government that has little interest in developing the
industry. So the wine, which comes in three generic varieties _
``white,'' ``red,'' and ``rose'' _ tastes like turpentine.
Meanwhile, the government slaps a staggering 450 percent duty on
imported vintages, which managers in top hotels are forced to buy
because their guests expect good wines as a complement to the good
food they offer. The first time I went to Egypt, I learned the
solution to this dilemma from a couple of savvy American travelers:
Bring your own.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
