<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-COUNTRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMEDIC LOOK AT DYSFUNCTION'S MANY FORMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE COUNTRY LIFE 
By Rachel Cusk 
Picador, 342 pp., $24. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rachel Cusk's ``The Country Life'' is an oddly ingratiating
social comedy about an unlikely governess who finds herself working
for an impossible family.
</P>
<P>
   Cusk confidently draws the reader into the troubled mind of the
narrator, 29-year old Stella Benson, as she's leaving London
behind, quitting her job, abandoning her flat, writing farewell
letters to her parents and to Edward _ presumably the man in her
life, although that is never spelled out.
</P>
<P>
   Stella is unhappy with her parents. We get an idea of the nature
of their relationship when she comes upon a packet of letters her
father wrote to her at school, using the persona of the family dog
(``Your faithful friend, Bounder''). The problem, Stella explains,
is that her parents, aspiring to ``a social position to which they
had not been born,'' sent their children off to prestigious
schools, institutions that made her older brother ``homogenous,''
and killed her younger brother at age 13 in a bizarre javelin
accident (. . . his small body on the grass like a bird struck by
an arrow''). Stella is haunted by her parents' inability to
criticize the school's role in her brother's death: ``They didn't
dare; as if by questioning the sport they would have betrayed their
inferiority, the public discovery of which they feared more than
all the private sorrow in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Stella has been hired, unseen, as a companion to Martin Madden,
17 and disabled, who lives with his family in an imposing house
next to the family farm, a huge agribusiness called Franchise Farm.
The Maddens, born to the social position Stella's parents aspire
to, are as dysfunctional as any family on ``Sally'' or ``Jerry
Springer.''
</P>
<P>
   The brittle Pamela Madden, whom Stella dislikes on sight, veers
between being superior and condescendingly chummy. Piers, Pamela's
husband, is a hen-pecked cipher given to talking in cliches, when
he talks at all. Toby, the priapic Madden older son, has designs on
any female who crosses his path including, Stella guiltily
suspects, his own mother. Caroline, a married daughter, is a nasty
snob. Martin, misshapen and confined to a wheelchair, is smart and
sarcastic, and very angry, justifiably, as Stella soon sees.
</P>
<P>
   Stella struggles to adapt to her new position as ``help.'' She
can't help noticing what's going on around her, and commenting on
it. She is a subversive force in the Maddens' world. She's also
completely inept at her job and unequal to the challenge of living
in the country. Beset by sunburn and allergies, scratched by
brambles, inappropriately dressed for nearly every occasion, Stella
bumbles on, trying to do her job, but failing. Her bad judgment and
ineptitude lead to some farcical situations, as when, despite being
unable to drive, she takes Martin for a ride in the family car.
</P>
<P>
   The novel ambles along from disaster to disaster. The plot, such
as it is, takes a back seat to Stella's distinctly unhomogenous
personality and her perceptions, as when she first meets Pamela:
``I had a remote sense of some inner derangement, whose faint call
I could hear as if momentarily borne on a favorable wind from a
great distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Stella's voice is smart, literate, offbeat, confiding. Near the
end of the novel the reader finds that the narrator has been
holding back vital information about herself, although it remains
unclear whether this is deliberate or accidental, or a combination
of both. Cusk has dropped hints about Stella's past along the way.
At one point Martin, who seems as though he could have a bright
future as a therapist, manages to draw a reluctant Stella out on
the subject of Edward. Ultimately, though, Stella's secrets are
less interesting than Stella's observations.
</P>
<P>
   Cusk is an astute social critic with a gift for comedy. Her
first novel, ``Saving Agnes,'' won the Whitbread Prize for best
first novel in 1993. ``The Country Life,'' her third, and the first
published in America, is a pleasure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
