<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-DAFOE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOGGONE IT, DAFOE'S THE MAN FOR THE BRUINS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- These are not German shepherds. They're
(itals)German(unitals) German shepherds. Born in the mother
country. Bred at an exclusive kennel in Glendale, Calif. Schooled
in the rarefied discipline of Schutzhund training, which emphasizes
protection, tracking, and obedience. Peak value of $20,000-$30,000,
given the proper bloodlines and development. Top of the line.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Dafoe's house pets.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, that's merely their temporary status, Dafoe explains
as he roughhouses with Vamp, the male, and Zona, the female, in the
upstairs study of his North Shore home, a room garnished with dog
paraphernalia and a photo album charting their upbringing. These
dogs were meant for shows, for competition, not lounging about. And
his job _ as the Bruins' No. 1 goalie, a viable candidate for the
Vezina Trophy as the NHL's best, and the key ingredient in Boston's
Stanley Cup run, which begins Thursday night in Carolina _ doesn't
afford Dafoe enough time to train them properly. Maybe after
hockey.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, they're not to be confused with those wimpy
poodles or coddled Scotties who consider leaping onto the couch
taxing activity. These dogs are more intelligent, more ambitious.
They demand more, and that's why Dafoe or his bride, Kim, a former
Rottweiler owner whom he has converted in their five years
together, regularly takes Vamp and Zona to the Boston Canine
Training Center in Middleton to have them put through their paces.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot of drive, a lot of energy,'' says Dafoe, his
eyes lighting up. ``If they didn't do something, they'd probably
tear the house apart. They get so pumped, so excited _ they love to
go out and work.''
</P>
<P>
   He attaches no cosmic significance to this trait, sees no
special connection between owner and animal. When he describes his
own attitude toward work _ ``I'd go crazy if I wasn't playing
regularly; I'd be climbing the walls; I need a challenge'' _ he
doesn't acknowledge that he could just as easily be discussing Vamp
and Zona.
</P>
<P>
   But Dale Sproule, Dafoe's junior coach at Victoria, British
Columbia, who became his surrogate father, gets the drift.
``They're big, strong dogs, not lap dogs; they give a good insight
into Byron,'' he says. ``Some dogs have no identity; these do. And
there's an identity to Byron, a very strong personality.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a point of departure, however, and Dafoe unwittingly
articulates it with this analogy on raising animals: ``It's like if
you have kids. If they're good at something, you want to push them
along.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he is the antithesis of that philosophy. ``Everyone in
Comox Valley,'' says Kim, referring to their hometown on Vancouver
Island, ``is so proud of Byron because they know he did it all on
his own.''
</P>
<P>
   He had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His family tree really is a hodgepodge of branches scattered
about by winds of discord.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe was born to a Canadian father and British mother in
Sussex, England, and like many things concerning his genealogy,
he's vague about what brought them there. ``Work or something, I
guess,'' he says with a shrug. In fact, his father was a would-be
poet, and his mother was a great admirer of Lord Byron, after whom
she named her first-born child; he must thank his lucky stars every
night that she wasn't reading Percy Bysshe Shelley instead.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 3 months old, the family emigrated to Canada, where
a bit of destiny may have come into play. His mother lacked the
proper papers for her infant son, but a sympathetic Customs
official in Montreal said, ``He looks like a hockey player. We'll
let him in.''
</P>
<P>
   Hockey was only one of sundry diversions on Vancouver Island,
about 10 miles _ a two-hour ferry ride _ from mainland Canada. In
Comox Valley, an area of some 20,000 comprising Courtney, Comox,
and Cumberland, there were two ski resorts within 20 minutes, the
Pacific Ocean just two minutes away, plus the Campbell River, which
featured some of the best salmon fishing in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe embraced all the popular local activities _ skiing,
waterskiing, sailing, fishing, street hockey, tennis _ but this was
not a boyhood idyll.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers that his father took him public skating for the
first time when Byron was 3; a year later, he abandoned wife and
son. Jane Dafoe remarried, and when Byron was 7, his stepfather
introduced him to youth hockey; three years after that, he, too, up
and left. ``I never really had a male influence a lot growing up,''
says Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   He says this without a trace of resentment, though he maintains
no contact with either man; it is simply a fact he had to deal
with.
</P>
<P>
   There wasn't a strong maternal bond to fill the void. With her
second husband, Jane Dafoe had two more children _ Benji, now 22,
and Chelsea, 21 _ and she found it a struggle to feed three mouths
on her salary from a series of secretarial and clerical jobs. ``I
counted one time,'' says Byron. ``I lived in 14 houses by the time
I was 21. We were always renting, always moving.''
</P>
<P>
   There was more to keep Jane Dafoe occupied. Benji has Down
syndrome, and his mother raised him at home. ``So you can see she
had quite a lot on her plate,'' says Byron.
</P>
<P>
   Again, there is no bitterness as he recounts this; these were
his circumstances, and nothing was going to change them.
</P>
<P>
   He speaks with pride about how Benji has handled his handicap:
``He works out of a group home now that contracts jobs. He's like
the town mascot. Everyone knows him.''
</P>
<P>
   Good thing, because Benji occasionally was prone to
misadventures. Byron remembers the time his 4-year-old brother rode
his new bike around town _ right onto the ferry, winding up on the
mainland. ``He got off in Powell River,'' says Byron, ``and the
people there knew who he was and put him right back on the ferry
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe laughs over these reminiscences, but he also acknowledges
the bottom line: ``I got a lot of responsibilities put on my plate
that a lot of kids didn't. Sometimes I wish I could've enjoyed
being a kid more without all the pressures of how was I going to
get this done or that done. But I think it made me a better
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he became a self-starter with a vengeance. At the age of
10, he was doing two paper routes. By 12, he also was working in a
supermarket butcher shop. ``The worst job was Friday nights from
6-9,'' he says. ``I had to clean the rotisserie. All that grease .
. . ''
</P>
<P>
   There were days when he would be up at dawn to deliver the
papers, head off for a full day at school, proceed to the butcher
department, rush to the rink for a 5 p.m. practice . . . then start
his homework.
</P>
<P>
   But he flourished. He was an age-group tennis champion in his
early teens. He was a straight-A student who skipped sixth grade
and graduated from high school at 16. All of which took a back
seat. ``To me,'' says Dafoe, ``school was a steppingstone to get
out of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   So he could have more time for hockey. The people along the
trail of Dafoe's athletic development all refer reverently to his
``focus'' as the trait that sets him apart. They don't know the
half of it.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after his first organized game, Dafoe came to the
conclusion that he was going to be an NHL goalie. ``I remember
signing up for my first youth league,'' he says. ``They asked you
to list your two favorite positions. I put `center' because I
wanted to score goals and `goalie' because I liked the equipment.
Before our first game, we didn't have a goalie. The coach asked for
a volunteer. I said I'd give it a shot. I loved it. And I never
skated out again.''
</P>
<P>
   His mother had one admonition: ``If you're going to play goal,
do it right, because I don't have the money for this.''
</P>
<P>
   He went beyond that. Goaltending became his obsession. And he
had exacting standards at an early age. Among his memorabilia is a
laminated color drawing he did at age 10 of his idol _ Gerry
Cheevers, the Bruins' former champion goalie and current scout,
whose recommendation ultimately brought Dafoe to Boston. ``The
thing I loved about him was that he was such a competitor,'' says
Dafoe. ``He didn't care what the score was or what his stats were
as long as his team won. If the score was 7-7, then he just wasn't
going to give up the eighth goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words are often repeated these days. About Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From the start, he showed extraordinary promise, all the while
fending for himself. ``I had no father, no money,'' he says. ``I
had to make my own way.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he never recalls feeling lonely, perhaps because he was
embraced by the community of hockey. ``There was always a father
around who would give me a ride to the rink,'' says Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   One of those dads was Warren Fleenor, who now lives in
Providence but at the time was Dafoe's Pee Wee, Bantam, and Midget
coach _ and chauffeur. ``He was just one of the gang,'' says
Fleenor. In the car, maybe, but not on the ice. ``He shone,'' says
Fleenor, a former junior goalie. ``He was an excellent goalie. I
didn't have to work that much with him because he had it all down;
it was just a matter of him coming into his own. I knew out of the
whole crew, he was the one who was going to make it to the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that's a convenient observation to make in hindsight,
but there's no question Dafoe was considered special. He generally
played a year above his age group, and when he was 14, he was
selected for the all-star team that would represent the island in
the Super Series tournament at Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   One problem. The players had to provide their own funds for the
trip, and there were none to spare in the Dafoe household. So, well
versed by now in self-reliance, Byron made the rounds of the local
businesses, raised sponsorship money, and took the ice in Vancouver
looking like a Winston Cup race car. ``I had decals up and down
both sleeves, on my back, on my front,'' he recalls.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisers got their money's worth _ Dafoe was the
first-team all-tournament goalie and Vancouver Island made it to
the final before losing to Minnesota. Dafoe also got something out
of the enterprise _ an introduction to Sproule and a ticket out of
Comox.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sproule, who coached Dafoe's Super Series team, owned, operated,
and coached the Tier II junior club in Victoria, some three hours
down island from Comox Valley. He was impressed enough with Dafoe's
tournament showing to invite him to training camp the next fall. It
was to be nothing more than a sneak preview; there was no way Dafoe
was going to stick. ``He was 15,'' recalls Sproule, ``and this was
a league dominated by 17-, 18-, and 19-year-olds. It was
exceptional for a 15-year-old to play in that league, especially a
goalie.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dafoe crossed up Sproule by having an outstanding camp, and
there followed a battle for his services. Dafoe wanted to accept
the Tier II bid. His mother wanted him to pursue his education, and
he had a scholarship offer to a prestigious private school for
gifted students that happened to be two blocks from Sproule's
house. Byron wanted out of Comox _ ``I was getting bored with it,
looking for stimulation, hanging out with a bad crowd,'' he says _
but the education he wanted to pursue was in hockey.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5800 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-DAFOE-2ND &LR;      04-20 1724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-DAFOE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... in hockey.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over his mother's protests, he took Sproule's offer. And found a
family. He moved in with Sproule; Dale's companion, Hannah; and his
5-year-old son, Aaron. Dafoe and Aaron initially shared a room;
Aaron considers him an older brother and took up goaltending
largely through his inspiration. Eventually, Byron got his own
room, and even after leaving Victoria the following year, he
returned regularly in the offseason until he bought his first house
in California two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he was playing regularly _ ``again, unheard of for a
15-year-old goalie,'' says Sproule _ and unwittingly triggering
another bidding war. The following season, he was a Tier II
All-Star. He was also a 16-year-old high school graduate with
impeccable grades, and he was wooed by several colleges that wanted
him in their classrooms and their nets. Harvard recruited him.
Illinois-Chicago, Michigan, and North Dakota brought him in for
visits on consecutive weekends, ``and I changed my mind about where
I wanted to go each weekend,'' says Dafoe. ``Those last three
months of the season were hell because I couldn't decide what to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   There was another factor _ the Portland Winter Hawks of the
Western Hockey League, the top junior level, had been courting
Dafoe since he was 13 and now were relentless.
</P>
<P>
   His mother wanted him to go to college. Byron wanted to go to
the NHL, and he figured the fastest route was through Portland. But
he also wanted to hedge his bet a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Sproule solved the dilemma. He had a Victoria lawyer draw up a
10-page contract with Portland _ ``unheard of for junior hockey,''
says Dafoe _ that provided money, a car, and a lifetime guarantee
of full college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe has yet to exercise the last perk, but he's had steady
work ever since.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to take the last two seasons out of context. Dafoe's
tenure in Boston has been an upward graph of success _ a 30-25-9
record and 2.24 goals-against average last season when the Bruins
vaulted back into the playoffs after having finished last in the
league in 1996-97; a 32-23-11 mark, 1.99 GAA, and 10 shutouts, all
of which place him at or near the top of the NHL statistics this
season and confirm what Bruins president-general manager Harry
Sinden considers his emergence into elite status. ``He's above the
level of a No. 1 goalie now,'' says Sinden. The performance was
punctuated by Dafoe's recent 13-4-4 record and 1.78 GAA during a
life-and-death stretch in which the Bruins climbed from out of the
playoff race to a comfortable position entering the last week of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people act as if I've had nothing but success,'' says
Dafoe. ``This is my eighth pro year. It didn't happen overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the long haul took Dafoe through many travails and much
frustration, including stops in two NHL organizations, Washington
and Los Angeles, where he couldn't find a home. Though he allowed
more than five goals a game at Portland _ ``We had some bad
teams,'' says former Winter Hawks coach Ken Hodge, ``and Byron
learned a lot about mental toughness and perseverance; he never
pointed fingers'' _ Dafoe was the Capitals' second-round pick in
the 1989 entry draft. Even that was something of a disappointment;
Central Scouting had him rated as the top goalie in the draft, and
he thought he'd be going in the first round to Washington. Instead,
the Caps picked his archrival from juniors, Olaf Kolzig, ahead of
him. ``When you look back,'' says Nashville Predators general
manager David Poile, who at the time was running the Capitals,
``you could say we did the right thing taking both. But maybe we
didn't because they shared the same spot.''
</P>
<P>
   After getting to know each other during the Capitals' Foreign
Legion training camp in Russia and Sweden, the two newcomers became
unlikely friends. ``I felt he was a cocky s.o.b. in junior,'' says
Kolzig. ``Then on that first trip, we found we had a lot in common.
Like he lived 10 minutes from my house on the island.''
</P>
<P>
   They roomed together for a year in the minors _ ``Our teammates
in Baltimore were asking, `Are you sure you guys want to do this?'
'' recalls Dafoe _ and served as best man at each other's wedding
last summer. But Dafoe was never able to establish a foothold as he
bounced between Washington and the minors for four years, and
``Olie, right or wrong, was always just a tad ahead,'' says Poile.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe lobbied for a change of address and got it when the
Capitals dealt him to the Kings before the 1995-96 season. In two
years there, he alternated in net, first with Kelly Hrudey and then
with Stephane Fiset, on one of the league's most dreadful defensive
clubs. His records _ 14-24-8 and 13-17-5 _ reflected that, but the
experience wasn't a total waste. The veteran Hrudey became
something of a mentor, and Dafoe recalls at least one invaluable
lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Against Winnipeg one night, Hrudey surrendered five first-period
goals, and on the bench, Dafoe says, ``I knew I'd be coming in for
the second period. He deserved to be lifted.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hrudey finished the game, and though he lost, 6-5, he
played brilliantly the rest of the way. Afterward, Dafoe asked him,
``How the hell did you do that? Why didn't you just take the rest
of the night off when you were struggling?''
</P>
<P>
   Hrudey responded by scolding him, ``You never give up, no matter
what the score. All you worry about is making the next save. And
you can never stop fighting for yourself, because once you do,
they'll know you've given up.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe took that advice to heart the following year when Hrudey
left for San Jose as a free agent and the Kings assured him he
would be the No. 1 man _ a week before they acquired Fiset.
</P>
<P>
   He still hadn't fully established himself, except in one mind.
While doing TV work years before, Cheevers had taken a busman's
holiday at an AHL game in Baltimore. Afterward, he had expressed
his admiration for Dafoe's play that night to a friend in the
Skipjacks organization, who told him, ``Gerry, they've got the
wrong guys in Washington.'' Cheevers kept that in mind,
occasionally saw Dafoe with the Capitals and Kings, and as a Boston
scout, he reported to his bosses that Dafoe ``had an excellent
chance of becoming a No. 1 goalie,'' says Sinden.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was spunky and all that,'' says Cheevers. ``I endorsed him,
but Harry and Mike (O'Connell, the assistant GM) made the deal. We
checked a lot of things before we went after him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were rebuffed in their initial attempts to acquire
Dafoe, and in the summer of 1997, they considered LA's asking price
_ center Jozef Stumpel _ too high. But Stumpel was a holdout, and
``and his demands were so high,'' says Sinden, ``that we said, `The
hell with it.' We wanted Dafoe badly.''
</P>
<P>
   So on Aug. 29, Stumpel, Sandy Moger, and a 1998 fourth-round
draft choice were packaged for Dafoe and Dmitri Khristich, a deal
that in retrospect qualifies as another Sinden coup.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe knew there were no guarantees when he arrived. Jim Carey,
a Vezina laureate who once had beaten him out for the Capitals job
and had joined Boston for the past 20 games of the previous season,
was still around. Rob Tallas was also in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a new coach, Pat Burns, who assured his goalies
that he came in with no preconceptions and that the job would go to
the best man. Dafoe took him at his word, and when camp ended, he
was sharing the job with Carey.
</P>
<P>
   After an early 6-2 West Coast swing, Burns turned with
increasing frequency to Dafoe, ``and I couldn't get him out of
there,'' says the coach.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe didn't begin to feel secure until one of his lowest
professional moments. On Nov. 26, 1997, at Florida, he allowed the
Panthers six goals in 12 shots before being lifted from a 10-5
loss. ``I figured I was headed to the bench after that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think that was one of the nights you quit hockey,''
says Kim with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Burns approached Dafoe the next morning and said, ``See
that big yellow thing up there? That's the sun, and it came out
today. Don't worry about it. You're going back in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to let him down after that,'' says Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't _ and since Carey was demoted to the minors on Dec. 5,
1997, there's been no question about who's No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe has removed all doubts, even during this season's dry
spells that left the Bruins in playoff peril. ``The defense wasn't
as solid in front of him as we were last year,'' says captain Ray
Bourque. ``We've had more breakdowns. But he's never lost his
confidence, and then he had that great stretch. Thank God.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe attributes it to maintaining an even keel, never wavering
in his determination. ``If you put consistency next to any
goalie,'' he says, ``he's probably one of the better ones in the
league. This year I've really tried to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns's system, which mandates defense at all costs and enables
Dafoe to focus on the shooter, has played a role. But Burns, who
has coached Patrick Roy, Grant Fuhr, Felix Potvin, and Damian
Rhodes, among others, during NHL stops in Montreal and Toronto,
feels there's more to it than that. Temperamentally, he compares
Dafoe to the unflappable Fuhr, and he illustrates his point with a
pantomime of a frazzled goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never looks behind him after he's made a save,'' says the
coach. ``If he lets in a goal, he doesn't keep looking at the puck
in the net; he just sweeps it out and he's ready to get on with it.
If he has a bad game, he doesn't let it get to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important, ``he's accepted by his teammates,'' says Burns.
``Everyone likes Byron. He doesn't make excuses or point fingers
when things go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the team feeds off that,'' says Sinden.
</P>
<P>
   Now Dafoe, an $850,000 bargain this season who stands to reap a
multimillion-dollar bonanza as a free agent this summer, has one
bit of unfinished business. ``I've never won a playoff series,'' he
says, recalling last year's first-round ouster by Kolzig's
Capitals. ``I want to get out of that first round, see how far we
can go.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend and sometime rival has an idea. ``The season he's
had,'' says Kolzig, ``it wouldn't surprise me if Byron won the
Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   That would cement his status as top dog.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
