<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5804 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-20 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LET FIDELITY DO IT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The most successful public policy innovation since the Clean
Air and Water Acts of 1971, just possibly, has been the Community
Reinvestment Act of 1977.
</P>
<P>
   It put banks in the business of neighborhood-building, after
half a century of neglect. Although it hasn't yet had a persuasive
audit, there's a widespread and growing feeling that it has worked.
</P>
<P>
   Now the statute is under attack. Republican Senator Phil Gramm
of Texas, chairman of the Senate Banking Committee, has vowed to
block the financial services reform bill that cleared the House
Banking Committee by a large margin _ because it extends the CRA's
applicability to such institutions as mutual-fund companies and
insurance firms, in exchange for broader lending powers.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are Gramm will fail; the CRA is a broadly popular
measure. If Republicans don't agree to its extension before the end
of the legislative season, they'll have to take their chances with
financial overhaul in the next Congress. Still, it is worth
remembering the circumstances that gave rise to its birth.
</P>
<P>
   The great suburban migration of the 1950s and 1960s in the
Northeast and Midwest, and the 1960s and 1970s in the South and
West, is still relatively little understood. One thing in
particular seems clear. It often involved a kind of panic, where
the usual community-sustaining institutions didn't hold up.
</P>
<P>
   An especially good glimpse can be had from Gerald Gamm's new
book, ``Urban Exodus: Why the Jews Left Boston and the Catholics
Stayed.'' This thoroughly reported and elegantly written book
surely is the best interpretation of Boston politics since J.
Anthony Lukas's ``Common Ground'' in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   From the turn of the century until the 1950s, Dorchester and
upper Roxbury consisted of two large and nearly opposite halves. To
the west of Blue Hill Avenue were the Jews, peaking in the 1920s at
about 77,000 people _ half the Jewish population in the Boston
area.
</P>
<P>
   To the east were the Catholics, around 136,000, most of them
Irish. A slow-growing community of African-Americans was
concentrated in Roxbury.
</P>
<P>
   In the next 20 years, however, the Jewish population emptied
out, replaced by a checkerboard of white enclaves, a few integrated
districts, and large African-American, Haitian, Hispanic, and
Vietnamese neigborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   It's relatively simple, argues Gamm, who is interested in why
some neighborhoods persist for generations and others quickly
change. The Jews fled, and the Catholics stayed.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are territorially defined and hierarchically
organized, Catholic parishes urged their families to stay put.
Because their survival was predicated on portability and autonomy,
Jewish institutions in many cases actually led the flight.
(Protestant congregations have found it similarly easy to move
lock, stock, and church-house door, says Gamm.)
</P>
<P>
   Far from being the fault of banks and real estate agents who are
ritually blamed, the explanation for the ``white flight'' that
afflicted Boston from the slow beginnings in the 1920s to the
dramatic climax in the 1970s is to be found in the Jewish readiness
to flee from harassment and tension, given their historical
experience.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to blame the Jewish community. Yet it is easy to wish
there were some countervailing forces at work, especially now after
large tracts of Boston have been stripped of their local
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   It's here that the CRA comes in.
</P>
<P>
   There's no way to move whole religious communities back into the
city, but it has been possible to cause banks to search for ways to
make profitable loans in neighborhoods they once avoided.
</P>
<P>
   Because banks seeking regulatory permissions are judged partly
on the basis of their compliance with the act, Gramm claims the CRA
has become a vehicle for ``fraud and extortion.'' No doubt there
have been times when activists have pushed banks to make unwise or
even improper loans in order to present a good report _ though the
purchase of low-income housing bonds has become an alternative to
direct lending.
</P>
<P>
   But on balance, the CRA has been highly successful in stopping
bad practices and fostering good new ones. It will be even more so
when mutual funds, insurance companies, and other bank-like
entities are required to take an interest in their communities'
success.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
