</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Tuesday, April 20, 1999    
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The Kosovo crisis has been compared
with Vietnam, to remind us of getting bogged down in a losing war,
and World War II, to highlight the danger of ignoring a tyrant
trying to wipe out a whole population. A more apt comparison may be
with the United Nations' bloody ``police action'' in Korea, which
stopped communist expansion in the region. Nearly 50 years later
U.S. troops are still there, and North Korea is still a menace. By
MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5810 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SALON-IPO-HNS &LR;      04-20 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALON-IPO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY-LOSING WEB MAGAZINE PLANS PUBLIC STOCK OFFERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN BERGER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Three weeks ago, Salon Internet Inc. announced
it would change its name to Salon.com, so it came as no great
surprise when the inevitable follow-up announcement arrived: The
company plans a public stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   Salon officials said Monday they had filed papers with the
Securities and Exchange Commission to offer 2.5 million shares of
common stock.
</P>
<P>
   The stake amounts to about 26 percent of the company. Salon is
an Internet media company that began with an on-line magazine and
expanded to offer interactive, on-line forums and services targeted
at a high-income, educated clientele.
</P>
<P>
   The shares would be offered at between $10.50 and $13.50 each,
which would raise between $26.25 million and $33.75 million for the
San Francisco-based company. WR Hambrecht &AMP; Co., also of San
Francisco, is the lead underwriter.
</P>
<P>
   The company said in its prospectus it would use the money to
expand its sales and marketing efforts, improve distribution and
expand its business operations.
</P>
<P>
   Although Internet initial public offerings have been setting
records and awarding jackpots to investors, Salon's announcement
came on a day when the market shook as a stampede of money left the
technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   According to the company's prospectus, Salon will face the same
risks as other companies doing business on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The company has never made money. In the fiscal year ended March
31, 1998, Salon lost $3.8 million. It racked up another $4.3
million losses in the nine months ending Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The company expects those losses to increase for ``at least the
foreseeable future,'' the prospectus said in an SEC-mandated
section that details a wide array of potential problems a company
could face.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that its revenue was likely to fluctuate from
quarter to quarter and that revenue was almost entirely based on
the sale of sponsorships and banner advertising on its Web page.
Advertisers are not tied into long- term deals.
</P>
<P>
   Internet-based advertising is still a largely untested market,
the prospectus noted, a problem that has bedeviled other
content-driven companies in the sector. Only a few companies have
managed to make money providing non-pornographic editorial content.
</P>
<P>
   While Salon has achieved widespread recognition as an on-line
publication for literate, upscale Web surfers, some analysts
expressed concern that the company's business model was too
narrowly focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a magazine,'' said Steve Harmon, senior investment
analyst at Internet.com, an on-line financial news site.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon said the company needed to broaden its appeal to Web
users by expanding its chat room and electronic-commerce
components.
</P>
<P>
   The offering would make multimillionaires of some of the
company's board and senior managers. They include Bruce Katz, a
major investor in The Well, the Sausalito-based Internet discussion
board acquired by Salon this month, with 973,000 shares; editor and
chairman David Talbot, a co-founder and a former editor of the San
Francisco Examiner, 402,083 shares; and Michael O'Donnell, the
chief executive, 158,333 shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
