<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ The latest developments in the
U.S.-led NATO bombing campaign against Serbian-led forces in
Yugoslavia. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-APACHES _ RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania _ The first of the
long-awaited Apache attack helicopters finally land here. What is
their mission? When will the others arrive? How soon will they go
into action? What is their capability? Developing. (Albright, Cox
News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ KUKES, Albania _ Humanitarian aid groups are
taking the opportunity, now that the Serbs have once again closed
the borders with Kosovo, to get the refugees already in Albania and
Macedonia out to make room for the inevitable next wave. Will also
include something on the helicopter air lift plans, how they are
moving out about 10,000 a day, why some refugees don't want to go.
Developing. (Kunstel, Cox News Service). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-ALBANIA _ KUKES, Albania _ I always thought I would take
stringent care before putting the term ethnic cleansing in print. I
wondered about news stories from the Balkans _ stories I didn't
cover myself _ and questioned whether it was justified to describe
long-running civil conflicts as something of broad consequence,
something that is the younger brother of genocide. Now I know.
(Kunstel, Cox News Service). 25. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRANTS-MITCH _ BROWNSVILLE, Texas _ The United States
Information Agency is predicting that a second wave of migrants
fleeing the economic devastation of Hurricane Mitch is on its way
north. Twice as many Hondurans are thinking of leaving the country
as have already left, and 80 percent are thinking of heading to the
United States, according to a survey released March 26 by USIA.
Brownsville, Texas, is one of the key entry points for these
illegal immigrants. We take a look at who the Border Patrol is
finding and what their stories are. (Ferriss, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   COMDEX _ CHICAGO _ News from the Comdex show. (Glass, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CHARTER-PROBE _ CBS News on Wednesday will report on a year-long
undercover investigation of Atlanta-based Charter Behavorial Health
Systems, the nation's largest chain of psychiatric hospitals. The
report focuses on Charter's children's wards, where the network
says it found evidence of deaths, injuries and hospital
falsifications of medical records in institutions from
Massachusetts to California. Charter has 91 hospitals in 32 states,
which admit about 60,000 children and adolescents a year, and it
takes in more than $300 million of taxpayer money annually.
(Miller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (f) Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VISITS-AUSTIN _ AUSTIN _ President Clinton arrives
Wednesday to look at the new airport and raise money for the
Democratic National Committee. At Bergstrom, he'll get a handshake
welcome from a governor who doesn't think much of him. At the
Austin home of ad man Roy Spence, he'll get a rousing welcome from
some of his closest friends in a state that has never backed the
president. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN-FOUND-DEAD _ AUSTIN _ Follow-up on the two dead
children found hear Hutto on Monday. (Spencer, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-FIRE _ Explaining what the wildfire means to the
Everglades _ it's a good thing. (King, Palm Beach Post) 12-14. WITH
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   ABORTION-BAN _ Covering an afternoon announcement in Cincinnati
of a GOP drive in Congress to ban partial-birth abortions. Ohio
Sen. Mike DeWine is one of the sponsors. President Clinton has
vetoed a previous bill. (Rouse, Dayton Daily News). 12
</P>
<P>
   PLANECRASH-FOLO _ The customer who died in Monday's dogfight
simulation over Bartow County was an experienced pilot with Delta
Airlines. It was his third flight with Sky Warriors, the Atlanta
fantasy flight business the operated both planes involved in the
aerial maneuvers that ended in death for customer Ted McFann and
Dan Bouck, the experienced ex-military pilot of the T-34 trainer
that crashed. Talking with friends, family, flight associates and
Delta. McFann's family is faxing a paid obit with picture to us.
They don't want the photo used in the news story. (Reinolds,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   SKYWARRIORS _ A look at the fantasy flight operations such as
the Sky Warriors group out of Fulton County Airport-Brown Field
that lost a plane and two men during a simulated dogfight over
Cartersville Monday? Sky Warriors is reportedly one of the better
known outfits in the region, offering wanna-be combat pilots a
chance to experience aerial action for $600, $700 bucks. The
8-year-old group has about three dozen pilots, all
military-trained, who sit in the back, get the plane airborne, land
it and do some steering _ and run three video cameras. Flights are
full of dips, dramatic ``verticals,'' ''max-performance turns'' and
``high yo-yos.'' What kind of regulations are there for these
groups and who has the oversight? How many are there in the
country? Who do they attract? What kind of accidet rates do they
have? How much training/instruction do the fantasy participants
have before they actually fly the plane? Don't most people flying
planes normally have to have more training and instruction?
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-COLUMN _ ATLANTA _ If he had to decide right now, Wayne
Garner says, he probably wouldn't run against Rep. Bob Barr next
year. But as he took his leave from the job of state prisons chief
last week, the Democrat couldn't resist a poke at his potential
Republican rival. He wasn't sure if the 7th District needs a
congressman, Garner quipped, because ``they've been without one for
such a long time.'' (Baxter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOWS-MY-DRIVING _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``Don't like my
driving? Call 1-800-BUZZ-OFF,'' reads one bumper sticker. The joke
has gotten old. But while the witticism aged, the serious practice
of inviting the general public to report on truckers' driving
skills has blossomed. Hundreds of thousands of trucks now sport
``How's my driving?'' decals with toll-free telephone numbers,
requesting complaints _ and, sometimes, praise _ from motorists.
Begun in the late 1980s, the simple concept has boomed in
popularity in recent years, spurred by the proliferation of
cellular phones and increasing friction between cars and trucks on
congested highways. ``Is it effective? Without a doubt it is,''
said Joe Zingale, executive vice president of Driver's Alert, a
Lighthouse Point company that was one of the first to get into the
truck monitoring business. (Banstetter, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-DEBATE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the past 14
months, the director of the United States Holocaust Museum in
Washington, D.C., was fired when he objected to the museum being
used for political purposes. The editor of an influential magazine
on Jewish affairs was called ``brainless when it comes to the
Holocaust'' for criticizing the growing field of Holocaust studies.
And scores of museum directors, curators and academics have been
accused of commercializing the memory of 6 million Jews killed in
the Holocaust to further political agendas and boost ticket sales
for an increasing number of Holocaust exhibits and museums.
</P>
<P>
   More than half a century after the Holocaust, defining, owning
and placing it in context have become more complex and more
contentious issues than ever. As the last generation of survivors
enters their 70s and 80s, a debate within the Jewish community is
intensifying: Who will speak for the victims after the last
witnesses are gone? And what will they say? (Belkin, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
