<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5814 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECYCLE-2TAKES-ART-HN     04-20 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECYCLE-2TAKES-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(EDITORS: BRINE CQ) &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    TRASH SWEET TRASH: BUILDER USES RECYCLED MATERIALS TO CONSTRUCT
HOUSE 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICHARD VARA 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Allow Dan Phillips to glean a landfill and
he just might develop a subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   Slender, mustachioed and ponytailed, Phillips, a 53-year-old
former university dance instructor, is launching an ambitious
project to construct homes for the working poor using recycled
materials.
</P>
<P>
   He is completing a Victorian-style home in this city 75 miles
north of Houston and is starting a second home he has designed
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the first of 900 homes, give or take a hundred,''
Phillips said half-jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has an additional seven lots awaiting his homes _ trash
turned into treasures. He has mortgaged his own home to finance the
project, which sparks a bit of anxiety in art teacher Marsha
Phillips, his wife of 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd better get busy on that second house,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips acknowledges his ideas on homebuilding are
unconventional and even ``loony'' to a few contractors. More than
one has stopped by to explain to him why his homes won't last. But
that doesn't stop Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``That door and transom were headed to the landfill,'' said Dan
Phillips, gesturing toward a handsome wood and glass entryway of an
almost-finished Victorian-style home in the heart of Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got that absolutely free. That door unit is a $2,000 door
unit; it is an architectural antique,'' he said. Then he pointed to
the lock set on the door. ``That lock set is worth $200 alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips isn't just venturing a good guess on value. Since 1983,
he has operated the Phoenix Workshop, an antiques and art
restoration shop in Huntsville. He opened it after leaving Sam
Houston State University as a dance instructor. Now his passion for
antiques and his creativity, social activism and concern for the
ecology are driving Phillips into full-time home-building.
</P>
<P>
   The two-story Victorian home is built out of 2-foot cedar
end-cut beams. ``I bought a three-year accumulation of a
lumberyard's cedar end cuts,'' said Phillips, surveying his
handiwork at 1323 Avenue N.
</P>
<P>
   The blocks made from the end cuts, which were nailed and glued
together, form the walls of the 1,400-square-foot home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask yourself some basic questions like, `What is a
wall supposed to do?''' said Phillips, who holds a doctorate in
dance. ``A wall holds a roof up,'' he answered himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of materials accommodate that mission,'' he said. The
cedar end cuts are a good example. ``It doesn't have to be 2-by-4s
and Sheetrock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The home's roof is made of tin shingles he purchased at various
garage sales. ``That's a 75-year-old roof,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He used a donated sliding glass patio door as a skylight. Then
there's the turret that he fashioned out of 2-by-4 end cuts. ``If
you are going to have a Victorian house, you have to have a
turret,'' Phillips explained.
</P>
<P>
   He did have to special-order a curved window for the turret, and
not everything can be recycled. The home has a new central air and
heating unit. The electrical wiring and plumbing are also new.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the house's materials have had previous lives. The
flooring is yellow pine that Phillips purchased from a contractor
tearing down a house. He pointed out that the inside staircase was
obtained for only $20, including delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was mind-boggling that someone would let loose of that,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips delights in singling out the ``you wouldn't believe how
I got that'' items in the house, including rolls of copper
screening that he purchased for $15, a regular $500 value. There
are pallets of donated bricks that will form sidewalks around the
house. There is a donated 1950 gas stove that Phillips is restoring
that will be worth $3,000 when it is functioning. Then there are
the antique deadbolt locks, large blocks of steel with equally
large plates of steel as bolts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are as rare as you can find on the planet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He found a free lock, although he had to pay $18 for a key.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips estimates that materials alone would run $60,000 if
purchased on the market. His penchant for acquiring recycled
materials permits him to build the house at $30 a square foot,
about half the per-square-foot cost of a new home. It is a price
attractive to families barely making it.
</P>
<P>
   Secondhand materials don't mean a second-rate home, said Mike
Roempke, a city building official. ``What he has done is very
good,'' Roempke said. ``It hasn't been thrown or pieced together.
The project he has done is very, very good. It is very
impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips' plans and construction ideas are screened by a
supportive local structural engineer before they are submitted to
the city.
</P>
<P>
   While the construction is unconventional, it meets city building
codes and in some cases exceeds them. For example, house foundation
beams are 4 inches thick and 6 inches wide according to building
codes. Phillips' donated beams are twice the dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start to think outside the box a little bit, you can
have all these materials available to you,'' he said. ``You go to
garage sales, flea markets, salvage yards, junk piles, go into
Dumpsters, hit antique shops; it is everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Contractors avoid using recycled materials because of the
patience and time required to accumulate the items. Not everything
is available at garage sales or salvage yards when needed. The
items also may be defective or need trimming, refinishing and other
time-consuming work. It is far easier to shop for new materials.
</P>
<P>
   But Phillips' favorite pastime is checking out antiques shops
and garage sales with his wife, who also contributes design ideas
for the proposed homes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his eye for antiques, Phillips uses his creativity for
the modern. He created a bathtub out of a cementlike Fiberglas
compound. He hollowed out a short, thick, wood branch for the tub's
faucet.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's a price to be paid for using recycled materials.
``The design of the house grows out of the materials,'' Phillips
said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple purchasing the almost-finished Victorian home asked
for a three-bedroom, two-bath home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have absolute domain over design,'' Phillips said. There are
no contractor-client spats over where to put the pantry or what the
the upstairs bathroom's color scheme should be. And Phillips
constructed the home to be economically efficient.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything looks as though it comes right out of
Architectural Digest or House Beautiful, even if those are the
magazines that Phillips uses for ideas.
</P>
<P>
   An upstairs closet door warped. ``Well, that's what you get, a
warped door,'' Phillips said. It is not a major defect, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of his ideas work. He glued halved hickory-nut shells on
the trim and fencing, adding a touch of the artistic. But the
area's squirrels spotted the shells and have been launching attacks
with teeth and claws.
</P>
<P>
   For Phillips and his three-member building crew, it's a learning
experience. Jim Tullos has worked with Phillips for five years. He
began constructing the Victorian house nearly a year and a half
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I built houses before, but never something like that,'' said
Tullos, 30, who added that he thought Phillips ``was a little bit
looney, but you have to give him the benefit of the doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is building a second house next to the Victorian home.
Tullos and his family will be the new owners.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Padon, 20, a workshop employee, comes over to ``do the
things the guys don't want to do'' like ``color-matching, painting
and cleaning up their mess.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a marvelous house,'' she said. ``It spices up the whole
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Brine Robertson, who helped construct the Victorian house,
admits he ``didn't know what to think'' about the project. ``I
never saw a house built like that,'' Robertson said. ``But I would
love to live in a house like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips' concern goes beyond housing for the homeless. The
workers receive ``a hamburger above minimum wage,'' but the
experience is invaluable for their rsums, he said. And thanks to
Phillips' encouragement, Padon has decided to attend Sam Houston
State in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips' efforts have sparked interest in Huntsville. The
project attracts daily visits from the curious. Neighbors, and even
strangers, have donated materials and labor. City officials have
been ``cheerleaders,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips has received seven more lots from owners who want him
to build homes. The lot owners will receive payment when the homes
sell.
</P>
<P>
   A new home invigorates old neighborhoods, Phillips said. But it
also helps families who would like their own affordable home.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, recycling materials means less space taken up in
landfills _ a sore spot for Phillips, who is troubled by the
massive amounts of building materials being dumped and buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obscene,'' he said. Yet most cities prohibit anyone from
gleaning materials because of the fear of liability and lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   He is upset with today's ``throwaway'' mentality that consigns
even usable materials to the scrap heap. Every house he builds
rescues materials from disposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my missions is to use recycled materials and prove you
don't have to have new materials to build a house,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   And so far his experiment is working.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
