<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5823 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERALDINE-FERRARO-ON-     04-20 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERALDINE-FERRARO-ON-SERBIAN-AMERICANS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MUSSOLINI IS WRONG' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this ``separate buy'' article it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at
732-390-4697.) 
 For release: Tues., April 20 or thereafter  
 By GERALDINE A. FERRARO  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    In the early 1940s, I was a small child living in Newburgh, a
town 60 miles up the Hudson from New York City. Newburgh had a
substantial Italian-American population, many of them
first-generation immigrants from Italy.
 &HT;    And we were at war with Italy.
 &HT;    My father had come to America in 1920 and become a citizen soon
after, but he loved the country of his birth. He went back as often
as he could to visit his parents and siblings in Marcianese, a town
near Naples, until the war broke out and ended those visits.
 &HT;    The war was very real to our family. My mother's two youngest
brothers were in the Navy, and my cousins were represented in every
branch of the military, in every theater of the war.
 &HT;    And we were typical in other ways as well. To help the war
effort, my mother grew a ``victory garden.'' We all saved tin cans
and tin-foil gum wrappers that were collected each week, and my
father regularly bought War Bonds.
 &HT;    At one point, my mother said to my father, ``Do you realize,
Dominick, that you are giving the government money to send bombs
over your parents' heads?''
 &HT;    ``Of course I do,'' my father replied in his heavily accented
English. ``But God will protect them. Mussolini is wrong.''
 &HT;    That memory has come back to me over the past several weeks as
television and newspapers have brought images of other families
facing similar questions, this time the families of the
Serbian-American community.
 &HT;    The television reports out of Kosovo are depressingly familiar _
distraught refugees, lost children looking for parents, frantic
parents searching for children, women crying over dead family
members, the fragile elderly huddling together, sick and confused.
The stories of rapes, mass graves, summary executions and burning
villages all echo similar stories from 1993.
 &HT;    The place is different, though not so far away _ then it was
Bosnia-Herzegovina, now it's Kosovo. But the players are the same:
The oppressors are Serbs under the direction of Slobodan Milosevic,
and the oppressed are Muslims who have the misfortune to have made
their homes in an area which Milosevic covets for his Greater
Serbia.
 &HT;    I dealt with the Bosnian carnage firsthand. In 1993 I was
appointed as the American ambassador to the United Nations Human
Rights Commission. That June I testified before the bipartisan
Human Rights Caucus in Congress.
 &HT;    ``I feel strongly that the situation in the former Yugoslavia
could have been avoided, or at the very least contained, if we, the
world community, had been more vigilant,'' I told the caucus. ``I
mention this because I truly believe that the former Yugoslavia is
but the beginning.
 &HT;    ``The cold war is over,'' I said. ``The good news is that
repressive governments no longer control half the world. The bad
news is that those who have been repressed for so long have neither
the know-how or the money to convert to democracy.
 &HT;    ``I ask this Caucus to think ahead,'' I concluded, ``to look at
the emerging countries in Eastern Europe and figure out how we, the
United States government, can take the leadership in preventing
another Bosnia.''
 &HT;    The silence from Congress for the next six years was deafening.
 &HT;    In the meantime, the Clinton administration pressed for the
creation of an International War Crimes Tribunal and worked for a
diplomatic resolution to the Balkan crisis. But Milosevic, who
should have been indicted by the tribunal for his actions in
Bosnia, remained free and in control.
 &HT;    The results of that freedom and control are being played out in
Kosovo and on our television screens every night.
 &HT;    This is not merely a civil war. It is a continuation of the
premeditated armed aggression begun years ago by Serb leaders to
eliminate the ``problem'' of non-Serb populations under their
control.
 &HT;    To me, however, perhaps the most surprising aspect of the entire
Kosovo saga has been the fact that Milosevic's appeal to
nationalism has managed to span the Atlantic and reach Serb
communities throughout this country.
 &HT;    And, as I've watched the news shows and heard Serbian-Americans
blasting NATO and praising Milosevic, I've thought back again and
again to my father and his attitude about the war against
Mussolini.
 &HT;    He was right _ God did protect his parents. And during my 1984
campaign for vice president, I learned from a former GI that my
Uncle Angelo had been a member of the Italian resistance and had
saved that GI's life. Since my father died before the war ended, he
never knew that his younger brother was fighting on our side.
 &HT;    Were things different then? Did victims slaughtered by the
dictators of the 1930s shed a different, more valuable blood than
those being slaughtered today in Kosovo? Are raping, pillaging and
ethnic cleansing in the name of nationalism acceptable in the
1990s?
 &HT;    And, if not, I'm surprised we aren't hearing Serbian-Americans
saying, ``God will protect our families. Milosevic is wrong.''
 &HT;    Perhaps television is an irresistible allure _ protesting gets
coverage, supporting doesn't. And maybe patriotism is not cool in
today's irony-saturated world.
 &HT;    But in this age of freedom and broad ethnic tolerance in this
country, it wouldn't hurt for all of us who revel in our ethnicity
to remember that the word at the end of the hyphen is ``American.''
 &HT;    (Geraldine A. Ferraro, a former congresswoman and the Democratic
nominee for vice president in 1984, is a Manhattan-based
attorney.) 
 c.1999 Geraldine A. Ferraro 
