   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The U.S. trade deficit in goods and
services surged to a record in February as consumers snapped up
clothing, toys, cars and other imports at a record pace while
exports fell for the fourth month in a row. The deficit rose to
$19.4 billion after widening in January to a revised $16.8 billion,
the Commerce Department said. Imports rose 2.3 percent to $96
billion in February. Exports of goods and services fell 0.6 percent
to $76.6 billion. By Richard W. Stevenson.
