<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5831 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAKINGLAWS-AZR &LR;      04-20 1823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAKING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE BUDGET WRAPS, ONSLAUGHT OF LOBBYISTS RESUMES  
 (ADV: THIRD AND LAST OF A SERIES) 
</HEADLINE>
 LAWS-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Rep. Susan Gerard and her fellow ``Mushroom
Coalition'' members are sitting on the state House of
Representatives floor this morning, going through bills with the
other legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the signal comes from one lawmaker. House Speaker Jeff
Groscost is summoning the Mushrooms to his chamber. The group of
moderate Republicans rushes off, leaving the House without a
quorum.
</P>
<P>
   Behind closed doors, Groscost gives the group the lowdown on the
latest state budget deal. Schools can have an additional $60
million over two years, but money for cities and community colleges
must come out of another fund.
</P>
<P>
   Grudgingly, all relent. Everyone has had to give up something.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard takes the opportunity to vent. She tells Groscost that
the budget could have been resolved more quickly if House leaders
hadn't ignored the group and if they had included all members in
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   With that, she excuses herself and returns to the House. Action
on the floor had been at a standstill because there weren't enough
members present.
</P>
<P>
   After the House breaks for lunch, some Mushroom
Coalition &UR; members hold a news conference in the House lobby. It's
been a long &UR; week and the lawmakers are showing signs of fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Two snap at each other.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barry Wong tells the press that thanks is owed to many
people &UR; for helping to obtain this budget. He includes Lisa Graham
Keegan, state superintendent of public instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are you thanking Lisa Graham Keegan?'' Gerard demands.
``What &UR; did she do? Give me a break.''
</P>
<P>
   Taken aback, Wong says, ``Maybe I should retract that
statement?''
</P>
<P>
   Gerard walks out of the room, heads outside and paces the
Capitol &UR; Mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would he do that? I can't believe it,'' Gerard says. Then,
feeling a bit guilty, she adds: ``Maybe I shouldn't have said that.
I don't &UR; know.''
</P>
<P>
   She'll need to consider those laments later. Lobbyists have
surrounded her. They want to know, is it true? Has the House agreed
on the budget? With the budget out of the way, the lobbyists know
that lawmakers can return to their bills.
</P>
<P>
   She tells them about the money for schools. What she didn't know
was that the Senate was already placing conditions on the extra
money.
</P>
<P>
   Back in her office, Gerard discovers lunch has been delivered to
the lawmakers, courtesy of State Farm Insurance. Lunch comes in a
box, made to look like a home, and filled with a brownie, macaroni
salad and a roll-up sandwich made with a tortilla that looks like
it contains sun-dried tomatoes. As a bonus, a State Farm key chain
with a tiny flashlight is included.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when you don't go out to lunch with the lobbyists, they
find a way to bring it to you,'' Gerard says. ``I hate these
things.''
</P>
<P>
   She sits at her desk and starts flipping through messages and
prioritizing them. She calls the &UR; Governor's Office about a
managed-care bill and answers a few questions on its status.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need legislation on &UR; this,'' she tells the governor's
assistant. ``We need to get these idiots to talk to one another.''
</P>
<P>
   The hour for her caucus meeting comes too soon. Gerard stuffs
messages into her pocket and heads out the door. This time, she
takes the back &UR; way. The route is restricted and allows lawmakers to
avoid the public. She shows the visitor where leadership hides out
and a tunnel that &UR; leads to the Senate Building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never taken it,'' she confesses. ``But if you don't
want &UR; anyone seeing you cross the mall over to the Senate, you take
this.''
</P>
<P>
   That gives Gerard an idea. Even though the caucus has started,
she decides to visit her friends in the Senate. She looks in on her
buddy and mentor Sen. John Wettaw, R-Flagstaff. They talk about a
hideous lime-colored, velour couch in his office. They also talk
about the budget and other items.
</P>
<P>
   Two passing senators notice Gerard and ask to meet with her
privately. That's when she hears the rumors. The Senate wants to
extend the school year if the House decides to put more money
toward education.
</P>
<P>
   Grabbing her purse, she heads to a caucus meeting.
</P>
<P>
   When she enters the room, lawmakers are fuming. The proposed
budget has taken another twist. Senate leaders have told the House
they won't approve the extra funds for schools unless the House
extends the school year by two days.
</P>
<P>
   Questions fly. Don't &UR; they realize that costs the schools money?
Will two days make a difference? Aren't we micromanaging the
schools? Let them decide how they want to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing that most in the room are opposed to extending the
school year, Groscost ends the discussion and tells the group: ``We
don't have to do this, folks.''
</P>
<P>
   They agree not to, and the caucus meeting comes to a close after
4 p.m. Now, the waiting game begins again. The House staff needs to
get the paperwork together for a budget vote. That could take at
the minimum three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone braces for a late night. They finish with the budget
around midnight. Everybody got a little and had to give up a
little. No one was completely happy, but the tension was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday _ Lobbyists, constituents and an early morning vote.
</P>
<P>
   Morning comes too soon for Gerard.
</P>
<P>
   She finds herself rising a few hours after the budget vote to
attend a 7:30 a.m. district breakfast at the Sunnyslope Village
Alliance. And there's no time for a nap. Caucus meetings resume at
10:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   With the budget out of the way, House members listen to an array
of bills. At this hour, mobile slaughterhouses are monopolizing the
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative analyst is explaining that mobile
slaughterhouses must now kill, clean and carve beasts on the
property of the person who owns the beast. They can no longer take
the beast to their business and do the work there.
</P>
<P>
   For at least an hour, the group discusses whether the law will
put some companies out of business, the techniques used and why
such a law is needed. Then, Rep. Franklin Flake is called upon to
give firsthand knowledge about the business, as his father owned
such a company.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard can no longer contain herself: ``I can't believe this. We
didn't discuss the budget this long,'' she says, with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   They work through lunch, break at 1:30 and go back onto the
floor at 2:30 p.m. for the committee of the whole, where bills are
debated and amended.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard spends her lunch hour with two lobbyists, who have been
waiting for her outside the office.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Howard and Roselyn O'Connell, lobbyists for Planned
Parenthood, ask Gerard for help clarifying the definition of
``abortion'' on a bill in the Senate. Gerard had helped to get the
bill through the House.
</P>
<P>
   They walk over to the Senate and meet with Sens. Ann Day and Sue
Grace. Howard and Gerard explain the dilemma. Day and Grace agree
to add an &UR; amendment. They all shake hands and move on.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard crosses the mall and heads back to her office. &UR; But the
five-minute walk to the House floor takes nearly half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Capitol's front doors, two stop her. Inside the
House &UR; doors, another motions her over. As she climbs the stairs,
another wants to talk for a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Around here, everyone wants something,'' Gerard says.
</P>
<P>
   As she fumbles inside her purse for her cigarettes, a lobbyist
asks for her advice on a bill. Even though he doesn't smoke, he
pulls out a lighter and offers her a light.
</P>
<P>
   It's a warm day and lawmakers and lobbyists mill about outdoors.
Seeing two health care lobbyists, Gerard decides it's her turn to
ask for something.
</P>
<P>
   A low-income constituent is looking for prenatal care and having
difficulty finding any programs. Gerard stops a Department of
Health lobbyist and one from Maricopa County. Both tell her they'll
look into it and within 30 minutes, they are back with the
information.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Kathleen Dunbar's bill, pulled earlier in the week when she
opposed a budget deal favored by Senate leaders, is back on the
calendar now. Was leadership rewarding the Tucson Republican for
changing her position? Or did things just work out that way?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' Gerard says, shrugging.
</P>
<P>
   To accompany her animal cruelty bill, Dunbar has brought along a
bulletin board with pictures of tortured animals. She invites
anyone on the floor to look at it, but no one does. The bill is
approved.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar says her decision to side with leadership wasn't an easy
one. In the end, Rep. Michael Gardner, also of the Mushroom
Coalition, helped her decide.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me you have to do what's right for you. And I thought
about my bills and my constituents,'' Dunbar says. ``But I was
honest about it. Some people aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the day goes. Today, the House adjourns about 5:30 and
Gerard goes home to collapses.
</P>
<P>
   Friday _ A day of rest.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature rested on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But many lawmakers didn't. And neither have the lobbyists _ a
stroll through the Wesley Bolin Plaza parking lot is a testament to
that.
</P>
<P>
   There's a silver Mercedes E320 with cream leather interior. Down
the way sits a red convertible BMW 325i. There are Jaguars, Volvos,
a few Lexus models and about a dozen assorted convertibles.
</P>
<P>
   With the budget out of the way, lobbyists know that lawmakers
will now be returning their attention to bills and amendments.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard has phone calls to return and meetings to attend. Today,
she's scheduled to talk to St. Luke's Charitable Trust. She reads
bills that will be reviewed next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing is for certain,'' she says. ``Next week won't be as
crazy as this one.''
</P>
<P>
   The action, she confesses, will move to the Senate. &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE LINGO &QL; 
House speaks its own tongue &QL; 
Like most businesses and industries, the Arizona House has a lingo
all its own. Here are some examples. &QL; 
COW: An acronym for ``Committee of the Whole,'' which is when the
representatives meet on the floor. Lawmakers, for instance, use the
term to say they are in ``cow'' or will be ``cowing.'' This is not
to be confused with having a cow, which also takes place on the
floor. &QL; 
They: This is an all-encompassing term for the House leadership,
which includes the speaker, chairman and majority leader. &QL; 
In the box: A reference to a general fund for House bills. When a
bill is put in the box, that means monies for it will come from the
general fund and it must compete with other measures for the
money. &QL; 
Mushrooms: A coalition of moderate House Republicans. The group got
the name because its members contended that leadership kept them in
the dark and covered them with bull. &QL; 
The Motowns: House Democrats who believe they rarely get
information on important events through proper channels. Their
motto: ``I heard it through the grapevine'' from a popular Marvin
Gaye song. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
