<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5851 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLINDARTIST-2TAKES-AR     04-20 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLINDARTIST-2TAKES-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INNER VISION: ARTIST PAINTS FROM MEMORY, IMAGINATION &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By BARBARA KARKABI 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HOUSTON _ It was springtime 26 years ago when Joe Harris lost
his sight _ the victim of a drive-by shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Harris was walking back to his car after a quick trip to the
grocery store when shots rang out, and he fell to the ground. Hours
later he woke up in the hospital, his eyes covered with bandages.
Doctors told him that he was blind ... and that he would be blind
for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happened just like that,'' Harris recalled. ``I was minding
my own business. One minute I was seeing and the next, everything
was dark. I went back to being a little baby. I had to start all
over again. I was mad, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harris never let the anger poison him _ or keep him from
seeing the world's vivid colors and shapes in his mind's eye.
Eventually, after years of searching for his own style, Harris
learned to transfer the glistening blues, greens, reds and oranges
of his memory into paintings.
</P>
<P>
   The folk artist's first one-man show opened at the Blossom
Street Gallery &AMP; Sculpture Park in Houston last Saturday and runs
through May 4. A few days before the opening, Harris proudly sat in
front of the creations he can only touch and imagine. He's happy
that people seem to like his work and even happier that he learned
a way to express his inner vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``A folk artist is someone who is self-taught,'' Blossom Street
owner Richard Roederer said. ``To me, he is the epitome of folk art
because he developed his own style. No one taught him how to do it.
He's as folk art as it gets.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 52, the former construction worker and truck driver has
traveled a long road and is proud of what he has accomplished. Six
months after he got out of the hospital, Harris went to a facility
in Kerrville to learn the skills he needed to function as a blind
person and return to the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew a door was closed to me and I made up my mind to keep
up with the world,'' Harris said. ``I was ready. I wasn't going to
let that anger keep me down and keep me from doing. It was just a
total new adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his injury, Harris tried drawing and painting, enjoying
it so much he began taking correspondence courses from a Minnesota
art school. But after the shooting, Harris was so focused on his
everyday life that he almost forgot about his art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hadn't thought about painting or drawing in awhile until one
day my mother called me,'' Harris recalled. ``She said, `J.B., are
you still painting and drawing?' I always take her at her word, so
I thought that meant I should do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   From that day on, Harris said, he began to think about how he
could paint. Though he retained the memory of shapes and colors, it
took him a long time to figure out how to transfer his ideas to
canvas.
</P>
<P>
   He began his attempts in the '80s and ruined a lot of canvases,
he admitted with a grin, before he ``got it right.'' Harris first
tried working with oil, then started sketching with colored
pencils. But neither approach worked. Then he got a raised-line
drawing kit, which allowed him to make an image he could feel with
his hand. That allowed him to start making drawings and sketches,
though he still didn't know how to transfer them to canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Harris next tried crayons and found that if he applied layer on
layer of colors and built the spot up, he could actually feel the
shapes with his fingers. Once he realized he could do that, Harris
said, his work took off. He now works with wax pastels and textured
surfaces such as sandpaper, so he can feel the surface and shapes,
like Braille. Even so, it's an elaborate process.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes me three to four weeks to do a piece,'' he said.
``And I have to make notes to myself from where I left off so I
remember what step I was at.''
</P>
<P>
   When Harris gets his pastels, he has a friend or relative call
out the color so he can put them in a container marked with
Braille. Instead of drawing at an artist's easel, he works on a
flat surface, so he can bear down harder as he applies the various
colors.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage of using wax pastels, Roederer explained, is that
they are dry when Harris applies them. Harris adds a coat of
varnish after each layer so he can feel the difference in texture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe has no fear of color. That is one of the No. 1 things I
like about his paintings,'' Roederer said. ``The textured surfaces
and layers are excellent. To me he is just a phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris can also tell by touch what color he is using because the
feel of the color changes. He applies more pressure to some colors
than others; for fruits he uses a light hand, but with trees he
really likes to ``dig in.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Harris has taken several art courses at the
University of Houston to get a better feel for the use of color.
Besides his family, including his wife, Glenda, who is legally
blind, he has been helped and encouraged by a number of Houston
artists, including Jesse Lott and John Biggers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met Dr. Biggers at the Black Heritage Gallery, and he really
encouraged me to keep on going,'' Harris said. ``I was working on a
little piece, and I asked him to show me how to paint water. He
asked for me to put my hand on his to let me feel how he made the
stroke, and I could get the feel of how he was making the motions
with the water. He is real fast with his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott showed Harris how to make gravel surfaces to paint on,
though Harris prefers sandpaper, which is more predictable. One of
the 12 paintings in the exhibit is done on a gravel surface. It's
obvious that he loves colors, especially blues and greens _
predominant colors in his series ``The Garden,'' which also has
luscious red apples, a bright orange-yellow sun, and, in one
painting, a red-eyed snake peering over the brown branch of a tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to do landscapes because when I paint it has to make
sense to me, so I have a better idea of what I am doing or trying
to do,'' Harris said. ``I would like to try more variety. I have
done a self-portrait by feeling my face.''
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken Harris speaks calmly about his exhibit but says
he hopes it will launch his career and change his life. In the past
few years he has sold a number of paintings and has been in a group
show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would love to have people see what I do,'' he said. ``Some
people doubt that a blind person can paint. But I guess just
because you suffered a tragedy and it left you disabled, there is
no reason to quit living. You still need to try to pursue your
goals and ambitions. It's going to be a struggle but with effort
and perseverance you can overcome the disability.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
