<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DYING-LISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE LIFE EASIER BY PREPARING FOR DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATE GURNETT  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As baby boomers lose their parents, many find
their grief woven thick with questions they can never answer. Such
as: Who are these people in these old photographs? What was life
like way back when? And: Where's the key to the safe deposit box?
</P>
<P>
   The solution, according to Lynn McPhelimy, is to get ready now.
It will bring you peace of mind. It will help your family cope. And
it's easy to do.
</P>
<P>
   Her book, ``In the Checklist of Life: A Working Book To Help You
Live and Leave This Life!'' (AAIP Publishing, 1997), contains blank
work sheets for pertinent data from insurance and investment
information to family hiding places, letters to your children and
your choice of casket.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're alive and healthy, don't wait until you are dying to
plan your funeral,'' McPhelimy said. ``You have favorite songs.
It's very close to a wedding you've got your pallbearers, you've
got your readings and your songs. A funeral should be a celebration
of your life.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishers were so uncomfortable with McPhelimy's book that 15
rejected it, she said. One asked her: What do you think your market
is? She replied: ``Anyone who is breathing.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, after selling 100,000 copies by word of mouth and
spots on ``The Oprah Winfrey Show,'' ``The Today Show'' and
elsewhere, the Connecticut native travels the country trying to
convince others to plan for the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Too often when loved ones die, survivors spend months or years
coping with unresolved emotional and financial issues, McPhelimy
argues. McPhelimy's parents made it easy. Both were diagnosed with
terminal cancer in 1982. Her father started with the septic tank.
He sketched his daughter a map so she wouldn't dig up his beloved
garden. Her mother bought a special red-haired Cabbage Patch doll
to leave for her someday granddaughter. Today, McPhelimy's daughter
sleeps with the doll every night.
</P>
<P>
   From the meatloaf recipe to family secrets to the clothes they
wished to be buried in, McPhelimy's parents walked her through the
mysteries of dying.
</P>
<P>
   Her grief would be clear: She wouldn't miss her parents for the
wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, two months after McPhelimy's father died, the
septic tank needed pumping. ``I said, `This is not funny. I believe
in signs, but this is going a bit far.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking about death is practical, loving and cathartic, hospice
workers say.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to terminally ill patients to tie up loose ends,
said Linda Covert, regional director of Community Hospice of Albany
County, N.Y.. ``Some people take bigger steps and walk right in.
Others back up, then go forward slowly.''
</P>
<P>
   Some young parents often make videos or write letters to their
children. About 60 percent of hospice patients want to discuss
funeral arrangements, Covert said. She urges family members not to
dodge the ``death discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Even splitting up the family furniture before isn't
cold-hearted, McPhelimy argues. ``If you say you want something
because of a special memory, then a story comes out and you get all
the fun stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to march up with the workbook and say, `I need
to know your Social Security number.' More people do want to talk
about it than you'd realize,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She recommends a gentle approach. ``You can start it with a
photograph. Ask, `Who is that in the picture?' And then as you ask
about that eccentric aunt, more memories come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Covert recommends asking a terminally ill relative what they'd
like you to do to help. Tell them why they are important to you.
And sometimes, just being there is enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes what families don't realize is that they don't have
to talk,'' Covert said.
</P>
<P>
   And even after someone has died, families can write down
cherished memories or identify old photographs, McPhelimy said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here is a brief checklist of what you need to put your life in
order before you die, courtesy of McPhelimy's ``In the Checklist of
Life'':
</P>
<P>
   _ Social Security number and medical information
</P>
<P>
   _ Banking, credit union, charge card, insurance and investment
data
</P>
<P>
   _ Retirement, pension and real estate information; debts owed to
you
</P>
<P>
   _ Maintanence tips for the house, yard and vehicles
</P>
<P>
   _ Your stuff and the stories behind it, hiding places
</P>
<P>
   _ People who are important to you, special dates, memories,
photographs and tapes
</P>
<P>
   _ Letters to your children
</P>
<P>
   _ Information on your will, living will, burial and funeral
arrangements
</P>
