<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5859 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURTHOUSE-2TAKES-ART     04-20 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURTHOUSE-2TAKES-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURTHOUSE RISES FROM ASHES SIX YEARS AFTER FIRE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ALLAN TURNER 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HILLSBORO, Texas _ What locals saw on Jan. 2, 1993, the morning
after the fire, was enough to break their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   The palatial limestone Hill County Courthouse _ Waco architect
Wesley Clark Dodson's 1890 Second Empire-style monument to civic
pride _ lay in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   The third and second floors had collapsed. The basement was
flooded. Vital documents stored in fireproof vaults, though not
burned, were saturated with water. The ornate, three-tiered clock
tower beloved by generations had tumbled and disintegrated in a
shower of sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could stand on the first floor,'' County Judge Kenneth
Davis ruefully recalled, ``and look up at the sky.''
</P>
<P>
   Faced with such a calamity, many communities might have called
in the bulldozers and started over. But in Hill County, the grand
old edifice in the heart of town was more than a utilitarian
structure in which births were recorded and malefactors went to
trial.
</P>
<P>
   The grand old edifice was the town's heart.
</P>
<P>
   It also was the centerpiece of Hillsboro's historic downtown,
which played a major part in the city's growing tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, within days, county officials, aided by the Texas
Historical Commission and other agencies and foundations, launched
an ambitious campaign not only to rebuild the burned-out building
from the ground up, but to make it even better.
</P>
<P>
   On April 24, after six years and roughly $10 million, the
restored courthouse will make its debut. Gov. George W. Bush will
offer the dedication speech. Then Hill County native Willie Nelson
will sing the building's praises in a benefit concert to help pay
off a $250,000 balance.
</P>
<P>
   But the real star will be the courthouse, which will be open to
the public for the first time since the blaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wanted the fire,'' said Brad Patterson, a Texas
Historical Commission preservation consultant whose jurisdiction
includes Hill County, ``but it's amazing what came out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   What had been a down-at-the-heels, often modified and patched
public building _ its inside walls painted institutional pea green
_ now is a showcase.
</P>
<P>
   Stained glass accents have been returned to the multi-story
arched windows. Hardwood flooring removed from the Texas Capitol
during its restoration has been installed to replace grimy
terrazzo. Vaulted ceilings that had been lowered have been restored
to their soaring glory and sheathed in a dazzling armor of pressed
tin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hill County Courthouse,'' Bush said, ``is a magnificent
piece of architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire had an impact far beyond this north central Texas farm
community. Bush called the blaze the ``driving force'' behind his
Courthouse Preservation Initiative, a plan to provide public money
for restoring the state's remaining 225 historic courthouses. &UR;  &LR; Last
week, the Texas House approved an appropriations bill that provided
$100 million for such use.
</P>
<P>
   The fire also strengthened a historical commission effort to
survey the state's old courthouses and make recommendations for
their repair.
</P>
<P>
   Although the survey is incomplete, Patterson said it already has
revealed ``conditions probably are worse than we anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've found across the board,'' he said, ``is that
counties used a Band-Aid approach. They fixed the plaster, but
didn't fix the roof leak and it continues to leak over the years.
We found dangerous conditions in some places. Virtually all of them
need upgrades _ heating and cooling. Some counties didn't have
computers. And if they did, they'd blow the fuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one case, there clearly was an electrical problem, but the
circuit breakers wouldn't trip. We went up to look and there were
no circuit breakers to trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe the Hill County fire was started by an
electrical short in or near the third-floor office of District
Attorney Dan Dent.
</P>
<P>
   Dent recalled he had gone to his office New Year's Day to
prepare for an upcoming jury trial. It already was dark at 6 p.m.
when Dent got his files, turned off the fluorescent lights and
headed home.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, passers-by saw flames shooting from the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 6:15,'' said Davis, ``the fire was well out control.''
</P>
<P>
   As word spread that the courthouse was on fire, thousands of
area residents mobbed the town square. There, in a steady drizzle
and temperatures in the high 40s, many wept as they watched
firefighters' futile efforts to control the conflagration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of sadness,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the ordeal, the 70-foot-tall clock tower fell
with a crash of doom.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, some residents began lobbying for clearing the town
square of rubble and building anew. That's what was done when a
courthouse was burned by an arsonist in the 1870s, they noted. And,
despite the town's affection for the courthouse, it wasn't the
original _ it was the fifth incarnation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may have been talk like that,'' said Sherry Hayes,
Hillsboro's Main Street Program and tourism director. ``But among
county officials, it didn't get a lot of consideration ... I'd say
the decision to rebuild came almost immediately. They were out
there the next day, moving stuff out. They started making phone
calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the first floor and the limestone walls _ in some
places 2 feet thick _ were found to be sound. First-floor
furnishings were salvaged, refinished and returned to use.
Water-logged county documents were pulled from their soggy
surroundings and freeze-dried.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the projected cost for restoration was placed at $6
million, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it was $7 million, then $8 million, then $9 million,'' he
said. The final cost will be about $10 million. An insurance
settlement brought $3.5 million. The rest, with the exception of a
$250,000 balance, came from private donations, overnment and
foundation grants and county certificates of obligation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillsboro was the first Main Street Program city designated in
Texas,'' the historical commission's Patterson said. ``They got the
conservation ethic kind of early. They persevered. It took a lot of
time, effort and money, but they struggled through it. They always
had the goal of restoration in mind and it looks like they've
achieved it. It's really quite a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding the courthouse, Hill County residents _ present and
former _ said, was just the natural thing to do. The building was
``a shrine, a place of beauty,'' said Houston Chronicle associate
publisher and editor Jack Loftis, a Hill County native who helped
organize Saturday's ceremonies.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``We were raised with it,'' he said. ``We played around it. We
were in it for serious business matters. It was so much a part of
everyone's life, it didn't seem right not to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, thousands of Hill County farm families would
congregate at the courthouse on Monday trade days, buying and
selling produce when such markets really were ``farmers markets.''
Politicians _ William Jennings Bryan, Sam Rayburn, Lyndon Johnson _
thrilled locals with oratory from the second-floor balcony.
</P>
<P>
   The county judge, who as a youth blasted sparrows and pigeons
out of the eaves with his BB gun, recalled that for 18 months after
the fire he habitually glanced toward the then-absent clock tower
to check the time. ``I never knew I was such a creature of habit,''
Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a black hole in the center of town,'' Hayes, the
tourism director, added. ``At night, there would be lights all
around it. But it would be black. The darkness was so strange.''
</P>
<P>
   Vignettes of the courthouse flickered through the memory of
retired Hillsboro lawyer Donald Eastland, a lifelong resident. He
recalled when the courthouse housed the town library, the district
courtroom hosted Boy Scout ceremonies and barbecue tables were
spread in the lobby for a town festival.
</P>
<P>
   Old men, he remembered, would perch on benches across the street
in Bond's Alley to ``whittle, spit and criticize.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They had benches on both sides of the alley,'' he said.
``They'd sit in the shade in the morning, then go home for lunch
and come back and sit in the shade on the other side in the
afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, who grew up in the Hill County town of Abbott, visited
the courthouse ruins with a friend shortly after the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was depressing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of things happened in that courthouse,'' the singer
recalled. ``On Wednesday nights, they would have singing in the
courthouse _ a lot of old gospel singers. My grandparents were some
of them. I would go with them. I thought it was incredible they
would let us use the courthouse to do singing. It was part of my
growing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, born in 1933, recalled walking through the courthouse as
a boy, when he rode the train to Hillsboro to see cowboy movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a regular spot,'' he said. ``We'd walk around it. The
big marble halls seemed sort of awesome to me at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   It was in the Hill County Courthouse that the young Nelson first
encountered restroom graffiti, and he remembers it still: ``Bulls
with short horns have a force that's weak. You better stand close,
or you'll pee on your feet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent a lot of happy hours there,'' Nelson continued.
``When it was gone, it was just like a big hole in Hillsboro. That
courthouse meant a lot to people, more than we even thought at the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
