<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5876 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELTA-KIDS-COX     04-20 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-KIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta admits fliers bumped
 &HT;    to put exec's kids in first class
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ First-class passengers on a Delta Air Lines flight
last month got bumped to coach to make room for a top executive's
children, according to an account circulated by pilots.
</P>
<P>
   A Delta spokesman acknowledged the incident, described in a
pilot union newsletter and posted on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Tom Slocum conceded ``several mistakes'' were made in
the way Delta employees handled the children of Chief Financial
Officer Warren Jenson on a March 4 Atlanta-Denver flight.
</P>
<P>
   But Slocum said Jenson wasn't present and had no direct
involvement, adding the youths also were blameless.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he were there this never would have happened,'' Slocum
said. He added Jenson, who joined Delta last year from NBC,
reimbursed the airline more than $1,000 for the cost of vouchers
given to the bumped passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's sorry this situation occurred and has accepted full
responsibility,'' Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said the airline ``isn't going to quibble with the
facts'' laid out in the article, as follows:
</P>
<P>
   Jenson's secretary brought three of his children and one of
their friends to the gate for Flight 969 as it was about to depart.
First-class was full, but there were open seats in coach. The
secretary had an agent move first-class passengers to coach so the
youths could sit up front.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flight attendants and pilots were incensed,'' the unsigned
article said. ``They had been ready for an on-time departure and
now members of a senior manager's family were causing a delay and
inconveniencing passengers.''
</P>
<P>
   The flight left 24 minutes late.
</P>
<P>
   The article said the Jenson children's friend _ who, unlike
them, was ineligible to fly free _ had a discount coach ticket but
got the first-class upgrade free. That violates a policy championed
by Jenson in which agents cannot waive ticketing rules in most
cases, the article said.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum declined to provide any additional details. He said Delta
``sincerely regrets any inconvenience to any customers'' on the
flight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
