<HEADER>
A5939 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-20 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO GIVES THE BOOT TO PUBLIC ART 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There is some irony in the San Francisco
Transportation Authority rejecting The Foot, an 18-foot sculpture
that was to have been placed on the city's waterfront. The $475,000
sculpture represented the only reliable form of transportation in
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But it also represented the most reliable way to cause a stink
in San Francisco: Propose a piece of public art.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Authority (the Board of Supervisors wearing
conductors' hats) rejected The Foot on Monday by a vote of 6-4. The
supervisors didn't know much about art, but they knew what the
public disliked.
</P>
<P>
   I was almost sad to see The Foot go, or more precisely, not be
built at the foot of Market Street. It'll be great to escape all
the lousy foot puns, though.
</P>
<P>
   When I called Supervisor Mark Leno, who voted for The Foot, we
had a good laugh about it, even though I thought it was a
pedestrian idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, this drew attention, provoked thought and raised
criticism, the way art should,'' Leno said. ``Any art worth any
value would bring out voices of displeasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, The Foot made us laugh and propose alternative body
parts that would better represent San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Now that The Foot has been rejected, we can put a sculpture of
The Finger on the waterfront. It's the San Francisco national
symbol, judging by what you see in car windows, and no one finds it
as obscene as a foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have heard some of the testimony,'' Leno said.
``One woman said it's sexist because it's clearly a white, male
foot. An Asian man said it's an insult to his culture because the
head is the crown of the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Anything that gives us that big a laugh these days is almost
worth the half mill. The money for the Buster Simpson sculpture was
supposed to come out of funds set aside for public art, so don't
tell me you'd rather see it used to fill potholes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, public works crews are working all over San Francisco
as the mayoral election nears, and they work slowly enough to be
called road sculptors.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, their work won't endure as long as Rodin's.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Authority still has $475,000 that has to be
spent on public art on the Embarcadero, so the question now is what
to spend the money on.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't reach Stanlee Gatti, head of the Art Commission.
Perhaps this energetic, humorous guy was conjuring up some Silicon
Valley art for the waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he's having Apple Computer build a giant mouse, to take
the place of the giant spider he once proposed be put on the gilded
dome of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the public can send in all its ideas for art on the
Embarcadero. You see if you can do better than a foot. Any pierced
body parts will do.
</P>
<P>
   Deep down, the public has a notion it has more taste than
artists.
</P>
<P>
   The public would have voted down the Transamerica Pyramid, had
it been put to a vote. It was considered tacky. Now it's tacky to
consider anything tacky, particularly if it looks like a building
from ``The Jetsons.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Gate Bridge would never be approved today. It would
have to be strung with suicide barriers, barriers between lanes and
tracks for trains no one in Marin would ever take to work. No one
would like the reddish paint, and would demand real gold instead.
</P>
<P>
   The western span of the Bay Bridge would never be allowed today
because it's so industrial looking. It would have to look delicate
and highly strung, like the sensibilities of residents of
post-industrial San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The only piece of public art passed by a public referendum
recently was a stadium and adjoining mall. Consider that. People
voted for it because they consider 49ers football the highest of
arts in the Bay area, and it's true.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the public really hates about public art is that San
Francisco always has to go to Seattle to find an artist. What's
wrong with San Francisco? Is it a city of live/work lofts filled
with artists of stocks and bonds, and sculptors of their own
bodies? Don't answer that.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't like public art, go out and make your own. Nobody
is going to like it anyway. But you'll be rich.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
