<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., April 25) 
(jt) 
 By SUZANNE MacNEILLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Greenwich Dome Tickets
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is it possible to buy tickets for the Millennium Dome in
Greenwich, England, yet? _ Mitchell Peters, St. Louis
</P>
<P>
   A. Although admission prices to Greenwich's much anticipated
(and much criticized) Millennium Dome were announced last month,
tickets won't go on sale until Sept. 22. Entrance to this high-tech
indoor theme park will cost about $33 (at an exchange rate of 60
pence to the dollar); $27.50 for children 5 to 15 (under 5, free);
and a family of five will pay $95. The dome is scheduled to open
Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Jacinta Johnston, a spokesperson for the New Millennium
Experience Company, which is in charge of the project, said that
pricing was announced early so that travel agents could organize
packages. So far, at least one British tour-bus company _ National
Express, telephone (44-8705) 808-080 _ is offering packages from
any city in Britain for $50, including transportation and
admission. Ms. Johnston said that other tour organizers, including
United States travel agents, will also have packages _ updated
information will be posted on the dome's Web site,
www.dome2000.co.uk, as it becomes available. A telephone number for
ordering tickets, which must be purchased in advance, will be added
to the site on Sept. 22.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve million visitors are expected to visit the $1.2 billion
Millennium Dome, which, upon completion, will be 164 feet high,
1,049 feet in diameter, with some 20 acres of floor space. ``The
Millennium Experience,'' the dome's opening yearlong exhibition,
will include 15 thematic zones filled with high-tech games and
gadgets, virtual reality and interactive displays that will explore
work, leisure, travel, the human body, spirituality and learning
(among other topics) in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The dome, designed by Richard Rogers, one of the architects of
the Pompidou Center in Paris, has stirred up controversy mainly
because of its enormous cost and doubts about whether a new subway
line to the site, seven miles southeast of London, will be
completed. At this point, the Jubilee Line Extension is scheduled
to be completed in late fall.
</P>
<P>
   New York Walks
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be in New York City in July and would like information
on walking tours. _ Alyce Waltzman, San Diego
</P>
<P>
   A. Guided walking tours are a popular summer offering in New
York, and you're likely to find at least a dozen in July. You might
want to do some preliminary research on exactly what area you wish
to explore, since most of the walks focus on individual
neighborhoods like Harlem, the financial district and Greenwich
Village. Among the possibilities are these:
</P>
<P>
   On July 11 at 1 p.m., The New-York Historical Society and Big
Onion Walking Tours are offering a two-hour walk through Harlem.
The Abyssinian Baptist Church, Strivers' Row (a group of late
19th-century brownstones on 138th and 139th Streets that were once
home to Harlem's elite) and sites associated with the writers Zora
Neal Hurston and Langston Hughes are on the itinerary. Participants
meet at the northwest corner of 135th Street and Lenox Avenue. The
cost is $10, $8 for students and seniors. Reservations are not
required. On the day of the tour, call Big Onion Walking Tours,
(212) 439-1090, after 10:30 a.m. to verify the schedule. Among
other July walks, Big Onion has a Jewish Lower East Side tour
scheduled for July 11 at 1 p.m. and a Central Park at Twilight walk
on July 1 at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The 92d Street Y runs a number of tours. A 90-minute walk
through Chelsea on July 11 at 1 p.m., for example, takes in the
area's Greek Revival and Italianate town houses and art galleries.
On the itinerary are the turn-of-the-century Chelsea Hotel on West
23d Street; the Chelsea Market, a blocklong collection of food
shops near 15th Street between Ninth and 10th Avenues; and the
General Theological Seminary of the Episcopal Church, a shady
ensemble of 100-year-old red brick and brownstone buildings bounded
by 20th and 21st Streets and Ninth and 10th Avenues. For
information and reservations call (212) 996-1100. The tour costs
$20. The 92d Street Y also offers a tour of the Hudson River
Promenade at dusk (July 24 at 6:30 p.m.) and a walk through Union
Square's Green Market (July 28 at 10 a.m.).
</P>
<P>
   Other options include a customized culinary tour of Little
Italy, Chinatown and other areas through Savory Sojourns, (212)
691-7314 (prices vary), and a guided walk through Woodlawn Cemetery
in the Bronx, where Herman Melville and Miles Davis are buried,
with Signature Tours, (212) 517-4306 (starting at $30 a person).
And if your feet get tired, you can always sign up with Gray Line
for a double-decker-bus tour, (212) 397-2620 ($22 for the downtown
or uptown tours, $33 for the ``grand tour''). For more information,
call the New York Convention and Visitors Bureau, (212) 484-1222.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver B&AMP;B's
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you suggest a reasonably priced bed-and-breakfast (in the
$100-for-two range) in Vancouver? _ Shirley Shostell, New York,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Vancouver has plenty of centrally situated bed-and-breakfasts
that provide affordable alternatives to the city's big, expensive
harborside hotels. Super, Natural British Columbia, (800) 663-6000,
the division of Tourism British Columbia that deals with
accommodations, can provide information on such inns. You might
also refer to one of the numerous bed-and-breakfast guidebooks,
like Pamela Lanier's ``Complete Guide to Bed and Breakfasts, Inns
and Guesthouses'' (the 1999 edition is $16.95).
</P>
<P>
   Walnut House, for example, is a three-story 1912 Craftsman-style
house at 1350 Walnut Street next to the Granville Market, and
within walking distance of downtown and Stanley Park. The house has
a big front porch and an upper deck, and there are three guest
rooms decorated in a country style, each with private baths. The
$90 rate for a double room includes a full breakfast (smoked
salmon, eggs, fruit, bread pudding). Information: (604) 739-6941,
fax (604) 739 6942.
</P>
<P>
   The Manor Guest House, 345 West 13th Avenue, has 10 guest rooms
in a four-story 1902 Edwardian building surrounded by English
gardens in the downtown area, about 15 minutes from the airport.
Six of the large rooms, decorated with English antiques, have
private baths. A double room is $59 to $117. The price includes a
full breakfast. Information: (604) 876-8494, fax (604) 876-5763.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
