A6002 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT &LR;      04-20 0153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROBUST RED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gallo Zinfandel, Alexander Valley, Barrelli Creek Vineyard,
Sonoma County, Calif., 1995. About $14.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Gallo's single-vineyard Sonoma County wines, this is
a blend of 82 percent zinfandel and 18 percent petite sirah, both
from Barrelli Creek vines. The two grape varieties were fermented
separately, blended, then aged for almost 14 months, mostly in
American oak barrels.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a rich, full-bodied wine with a beautiful bouquet
and a surprisingly long finish. It might benefit from a few years'
extra aging, but it's perfectly ready to drink now.
</P>
<P>
   The alcohol level is high, 14.4 percent, but that's not uncommon
in zinfandels these days, and it gives them the robust quality
we've come to expect. Not exactly a summer wine, it would be ideal
for use with red meats, game and some assertive cheeses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
