<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BRIEFS-$Adv25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL NEWS AND NOTES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., April 25)  
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fancy Cars Available For Rent in London
</P>
<P>
   If you would like to rent a luxury car in London, Avis has
inaugurated a program that it says can guarantee you the make and
model you want within 24 hours of your request _ a distinction that
those who get ``or similar'' will appreciate.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The two dozen 1998 and 1999 models available range from an Audi
A3 SE 1.6SE to a Mercedes-Benz SLK 230 to a Porsche Boxster; the
daily rate if rented from, say, three to six days is $110, $263 and
$350, respectively, computed at $1.59 to the pound. The cars, which
include Jaguars as well, are available through Avis Prestige Cars,
a licensee. Avis says its guarantee means that if the make and
model are available when you call, you will get what you asked for.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Avis, however, has some stringent standards for anyone who
slides behind the wheel. In addition to a valid driver's license
that has been held for at least two years, two credit cards and a
passport are required. Renters must be at least 25 years old to
rent the lowest (if you will) tier of cars, and at least 30 to rent
anything else. A charge of $686 to $845 must be paid before the
rental; any damage to the car will be deducted from that payment.
Cars cannot be taken out of Britain. Finally, there is a charge of
a day's rental for no-shows, unless 24 hours' notice is given. The
fee includes unlimited free mileage, insurance and the 17.5 percent
VAT. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The major compensation for all the bother is, of course, the car
you're getting. It can be delivered free to a hotel in central
London or, for $40, to Heathrow Airport. Information: (800)
331-1084.
</P>
<P>
   Creatures of the Deep, On View in Monterey
</P>
<P>
   An exhibition of living deep-sea animals, most never seen before
in an aquarium, opened last month at the Monterey Bay Aquarium in
central California. ``Mysteries of the Deep'' features more than 40
species collected from as deep as 3,300 feet below the ocean's
surface. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition focuses on the Monterey submarine canyon, an
underwater chasm that begins offshore from the aquarium and
eventually reaches a depth of over two miles from rim to floor.
Through living animals, videos, a deep-sea lab and hands-on
activities, visitors examine the three major deep-sea habitats
found in Monterey Bay _ vertical canyon walls, the sea floor, and
the midwater zone, a dark ocean realm between sunlit surface waters
and the bottom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The species featured are from all three zones, and are hardy
enough so that pressure is not a factor in keeping them alive. They
include pallid eelpouts, mushroom corals, sea whips, filetail
catsharks and Pacific hagfish. Many of these colorful and graceful
animals are housed in multi-species tanks that recreate the look of
deep-sea communities. The exhibition includes a daily program of
live and taped video broadcasts from robotic research submarines
now exploring the canyon.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Monterey Bay Aquarium, 886 Cannery Row, is open daily.
Admission, which includes the deep-sea exhibition (through Jan. 6,
2002), is $15.95, $12.95 for seniors and students, $6.95 for the
disabled and ages 3 to 12. Information: (831) 648-4888.
</P>
<P>
   300th Birthday Party For Williamsburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred years ago, in 1699, the Virginia Colony moved its
capital five miles inland from Jamestown and named it Williamsburg
for the reigning English king, William III. The city remained the
capital until 1780 (when it was moved to Richmond), and this year
is celebrating the anniversary of its founding with a series of
exhibitions and programs. Through objects, manuscripts,
photographs, paintings, rare books and prints, visitors can view
the historical legacies of three centuries: the 18th at the John D.
Rockefeller Jr. Library in Colonial Williamsburg, the 19th at the
Swem Library at the College of William and Mary, and the 20th at
the Williamsburg Regional Library. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia General Assembly voted for the move to Williamsburg
on May 1, and many events mark the day. At the DeWitt Wallace
Gallery in Colonial Williamsburg, ``1699: When Virginia Was the
Wild West'' will be on display from May 1 through Feb. 13, 2000. It
features 17th century decorative arts and more than 300 artifacts
excavated from early Indian, English and African settlements, with
wall labels that illustrate the story in Classic Comics style. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A public archeological excavation of the Nassau Street Tavern
will start Saturday and continue into the fall. Festivities on
Saturday include a commemorative ceremony recalling the events of
1699 at 10 a.m. in front of the Wren Building at the College of
William and Mary, and a parade led by the Colonial Williamsburg
Fife and Drum Corps at 1:30 p.m. The National Symphony Orchestra,
conducted by Leonard Slatkin, will perform at the William and Mary
Hall at 7:30 p.m. The program will include selections from the
American composers Samuel Barber, Leonard Bernstein and Virgil
Thomson. Ticket prices range from $8 for students to $45; (757)
664-6492. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next day ``A Celebration in Song,'' a nine-hour vocal
concert, will be held from 1 to 10 p.m. at the William and Mary
Hall. Open-seating tickets: $15, $3 for students and children. Call
(757) 873-7333 for more information. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A calendar of 300th anniversary events is available at
www.300th.ontheline.com, or from the Williamsburg Area Convention
and Visitor's Bureau, (800) 368-6511.
</P>
<P>
   A French Painter's American Links
</P>
<P>
   The Parisian artist who arrived in New Orleans on a sunny fall
day in 1872 to visit his mother's American family, the
well-connected Mussons, stepped into the midst of stylish Creole
society. He left in March with a rich record of his visit, work
that can be seen in an exhibition that opens Saturday at the New
Orleans Museum of Art, ``Degas and New Orleans: A French
Impressionist in America.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The show, which runs to Aug. 29, will feature 40 objects,
paintings, drawings, pastels and prints, including 17 of the
approximately two dozen pieces that Degas is thought to have
created or begun during his visit to the city where his mother,
Celestine, was born. Family heirlooms on display will include
jewelry and a Bible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition is part of Francofete, a yearlong celebration of
French influence in Louisiana, which dates to 1699. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Degas' works are being gathered from, among other places, the
Metropolitan Museum of Art and the Pierpont Morgan Library in New
York, the National Gallery of Art and the Dumbarton Oaks House
Collection in Washington, the Musee d'Orsay and Louvre in Paris and
the Ordrupgaard Collection in Copenhagen.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the show's most notable paintings and Degas' first to be
bought by a French museum, ``A Cotton Office in New Orleans,'' will
be on loan from the Musee des Beaux-Arts in Pau. It portrays the
artist's Uncle Michel in top hat and frock coat musing over a scrap
of cotton in a clubby 19th-century place of business. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tickets, $10, $5 ages 3 to 17, are available through
Ticketmaster, (800) 409-9959. Beginning Saturday, tickets can be
bought at the New Orleans Museum of Art, 1 Collins Diboll Circle in
City Park; (504) 488-2631. The museum is open 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.
Tuesday through Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
