<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6010 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      04-20 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW OF GRAVITY APPLIES TO BORDEAUX PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the first time in four years, the prices of Bordeaux wines
are beginning to fall, in some instances significantly below last
year's levels. Among some of the better-known chateaus, Margaux is
down 14 percent, Cos d'Estournel 25 percent, Ducru-Beaucaillou 16
percent and Gloria 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But don't rush to your local wine store looking for a bargain
just yet. The price drop refers to the 1998 vintage, which is
maturing in chateau cellars and whose wines will not be sold in the
United States until 2000 or 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 Bordeaux, whose prices set off a debate among those in
the wine trade, will begin to arrive this year. More about them
later.
</P>
<P>
   The price drop was welcomed by the Bordeaux Wine Council, a
trade group, which announced it officially in Paris last week. As
always, the five most famous chateaus _ Haut-Brion,
Lafite-Rothschild, Latour, Margaux and Mouton-Rothschild _ were the
first to announce their prices, which are called opening prices.
</P>
<P>
   As the wine passes through the hands of brokers, shippers,
importers, distributors and retailers, that opening price can
increase by 50 to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bordeaux is France's biggest wine exporting region, so what goes
on there is closely watched by wine experts around the world. They
had been predicting a drop in French wine prices because of the
Asian financial crisis, declining Japanese demand and growing
competition from wines elsewhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   To other wine players, greed on the part of Bordeaux producers
also had a part. They point out that the 1997 vintage, a relatively
mediocre one, was offered for sale at prices well above the 1996, a
very good vintage, as producers tried to make the most of a hot
market.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary judgments of the 1998 vintage put it considerably
above the 1997 in quality, which means that the 1998s are being
offered at lower prices than the less-good 1997s.
</P>
<P>
   But where did the astoundingly high prices for Bordeaux wines of
the last few years come from anyway?
</P>
<P>
   After a succession of indifferent years _ 1991, 1992, 1993 and
1994 _ worldwide demand for a good wine was great. The 1995 vintage
was excellent, and anticipating the demand for it, Bordeaux
producers set their opening price 35 percent over 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, demand was so strong that prices were pushed up 50
percent more. Growers were encouraged to offer the 1996 vintage at
even higher prices _ in some cases, 55 percent or 60 percent higher
than what they had asked for the 1995s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to this point, there was some logic to all this,'' said
Anthony Barton, owner of Chateau Leoville-Barton in St.-Julien, in
Bordeaux wine country. That is, good wines sold in a buoyant market
in a generally expanding world economy. ``When things ceased to
make sense was when the 1997 vintage was put on the market,'' he
added. Although that year produced some excellent wines, few would
say they were equal to, let alone better than, 1995 or 1996. Yet
prices went up again.
</P>
<P>
   Barton said it was ``a grave error'' for producers to think that
there was a true demand for the 1997 vintage at this high price.
``Now the 1998 campaign is under way and it has caused producers
quite a problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Dulong, vice president of the Bordeaux Wine Council,
defended the 1997 vintage as ``overly criticized,'' but promised
``a significant effort'' to lower prices for the vintage, much of
which remains unsold.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Abdallah Simon, chairman of the Seagram Chateau and
Estate Wines Co., an important Bordeaux importer, said he was not
worried about selling the 1997s but criticized the Bordelais for
pushing the 1997 prices so high.
</P>
<P>
   In Bordeaux, Paul Pontallier, manager of Chateau Margaux, said
of 1997: ``We did what we had to do _ perhaps we went a bit too
high. Pricing is out of our hands. The market makes the prices. Our
job is to make the very best wine we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Will a measure of logic return to a market driven by ego and
tradition, as well as economic realities? Barton, whose family has
made wine in Bordeaux since 1822, is cautiously optimistic. ``With
luck and a small measure of good judgment,'' he said, ``the 1998
vintage will be sold at about the right price.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I look forward to returning to the old-fashioned
formula of increasing prices in good years and decreasing them in
lesser years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
