<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORM AN ALLIANCE TO BATTLE FIRE ANTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
Q: I have fire ants all over my yard. I've used everything, but
they seem to just move to some other spot. 
_ J.S.C., Houston 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are fire ants in my compost pile. How would you suggest
getting rid of them? &QL; 
_ A.B., Kingwood &QR; 
 &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; A: There are means to control these pests, but so far not to
eliminate them altogether. Scientists are studying effective
controls with natural predators. One, a tiny fly, is apparently
most promising.
</P>
<P>
   If all members of a mound are not killed, especially the queen,
then survivors are likely to set up again. Therefore, your best
shot is to kill off as much of the mound as possible.
</P>
<P>
   Many think that baits, even though they take weeks to reach 80
percent to 90 percent control, are most effective in fighting fire
ants. Some baits are faster-acting than others, but those that are
slower may actually have the longest-lasting control. Eventually,
if the bait is used according to label instructions, the colony is
put out of commission.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Agricultural Extension Service, Texas Agricultural
Experiment Station, Texas Tech University, University of Texas,
Texas Department of Agriculture, and Texas Parks &AMP; Wildlife
Department have joined forces to find the best means to combat fire
ants and to inform the public of the best current procedures in
controlling these ants. It is a program that encourages all of us _
neighborhoods and communities _ to work together. Since fire ants
move from garden to garden, it makes sense to team up with your
neighbors for a broader attack.
</P>
<P>
   The above organizations have put together a new Texas Imported
Fire Ant Research and Management Plan that suggests a two-step
approach, especially useful in heavily infested areas. The Web site
for this plan, http://fireant.tamu.edu/, gives detailed information
on fire ant control.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the plan suggests:
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast a fresh (preferably unopened) bait during warm weather
and when ants are foraging for food, usually late in the day.
Applications made between late August and mid-October, when weather
conditions are more stable, achieve greater control by early
spring, researchers say. A neighborhood effort will also achieve
greater control.
</P>
<P>
   Wait five days or more after applying bait, then treat any
nuisance mound in a high-traffic area with a drench, granular or
dust insecticide, or treat organically. But be patient and let the
bait do its thing on other mounds.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of products available for fighting the fire
ant mound. Injectable products that contain pyrethrum can help.
These products may come in a spray can with a plastic tube that is
inserted into the mound. This kills any ants in the mound at the
time of application. Of course, this won't kill any foragers. But
if you get the queen and her brood, the workers will be at a loss
and the colony will dry up.
</P>
<P>
   There are drenches with chemicals such as diazinon that are
mixed with water and sprinkled on mounds. These drenches vary in
kill time. And you may not want to work with concentrates.
Certainly, avoid contact. And keep the overall environment in mind.
Runoff pollutes.
</P>
<P>
   Granular products also are sprinkled on the mound, then gently
watered. Again, it may take several days before this type of
pesticide kills the colony.
</P>
<P>
   There are organic/home-remedies for treating ants: Drench a
mound with straight vinegar, soapy water or boiling water. Be
extremely careful approaching and treating a mound. Fire ants move
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Some gardeners have tried steeping manure to make a manure tea,
adding molasses and using this concoction as a drench. I have not
tried this method.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever you choose, follow the instructions carefully. And of
course, first suppress mounds in areas used by people and pets.
</P>
<P>
   To discourage ants in the compost pile, apply one of the
fast-acting baits that contain hydramethylnon. A pile that cooks
properly will eliminate any insecticide residues. But research says
baits break down quickly. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to all unpublished letters.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
