<SLUG> BC-TRIVIA-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JETS ROCKETED OUT OF WINNIPEG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What happened to the Winnipeg Jets hockey team?
</P>
<P>
   _ M.R., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: The Jets, an original World Hockey Association franchise that
joined the NHL in 1979, became the Phoenix Coyotes in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   More than $62 million was raised to build a new arena in
Winnipeg and keep the franchise from moving, including $13 million
from a radio telethon and ``Save the Jets'' concert. The effort
failed when the team's owners could not come up with their share of
the funding.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets were purchased for $68 million by Richard Burke and
Steven Gluckstern in October 1995. Burke, now the sole owner, is
considering another relocation to Scottsdale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Voters in Scottsdale will decide on May 18 whether to approve
funding for a new arena to house the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I write to Johnny Mathis?
</P>
<P>
   _ A.C.N., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to him in care of Columbia Records, 550 Madison Ave.,
New York, NY 10022-3211.
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, 63, was born in Gilmer, Texas, and grew up in San
Francisco. His most recent album is 1998's ``Because You Loved Me:
The Songs of Diane Warren.''
</P>
<P>
   The singer has an official fan club that publishes a quarterly
newsletter with a concert schedule, details on future projects and
a personal birthday greeting from Mathis.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, write to Johnny Mathis International Fan
Club, Box 2066, Burbank, CA 91507-2066.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm looking for the song ``Basketball Jones,'' which I
believe was a parody of the song ``Love Jones.'' Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   _ D.H., Livermore, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A: The song appears on the 1991 album ``Cheech &AMP; Chong Greatest
Hit'' and a 1998 compilation, ``Basketball's Greatest Hoop Hits.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also a remake by Barry White and Chris Rock on the
``Space Jam'' soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   The song was originally released by Cheech &AMP; Chong on the album
``Los Cochinos.'' It reached No. 15 on the charts in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
