Lakeshore, 15,000 acres of beaches, sandy dunes and forests on the
southern shore of Lake Michigan. (400 words.) By C.J. Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   LOUISIANA-BILL-CITY. Football MVP Terrell Davis may have
stuttered and spoke in a monotone before a Senate committee
Tuesday. But his speech about the importance of funding inner-city
parks seemed to give momentum to a bill sought by Louisiana
lawmakers that would redirect $1.4 billion in off-shore oil
revenues to the states. (350 words.) By Mark Stricherz
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN-ROSA-MEDAL. Monday's Senate vote awarding Detroit
resident Rosa Parks the Congressional Gold Medal will be followed
today by a vote in the House. The bill is expected to pass. (400
words.) By C.J. Karamargin
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-RAILROAD-BROWN. Rep. Sherrod Brown Tuesday urged a House
panel to dedicate money to establish a museum in Oberlin honoring
the city's contribution to the Underground Railroad. (400 words.)
By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-WILDLIFE. Reps. Ruben Hinojosa and Solomon Ortiz urged a
House panel to allot $5 million to the Lower Rio Grande Valley
National Wildlife Refuge to help it reach its goal of 132,000
acres. (400 words.) By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-KOSOVO-FUNDING. Madison Democrat Tammy Baldwin said
she is ``leaning against'' supporting President Clinton's request
for $6 billion in emergency funding for the NATO air attack in
Kosovo. Will also include comments from Senators and other members
of Wisconsin congressional delegation. (400 words.) By Elizabeth
Hurt
</P>
<P>
   WYOMING-TERRELL-PARKS. Terrell Davis was back in the game
Tuesday, but he wasn't wearing a helmet or cleats. The Denver
Broncos running back and 1998 league Most Valuable Player was
trying his hand at the policy game, testifying on Capitol Hill.
Dressed in a sober gray suit, Davis was in Washington to urge
Congress to help cities like Denver build more parks and ball
fields for young people, a change he said would keep kids out of
trouble. (400 words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
