<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO TIME LIKE THE PRESENT TO BUY PC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Think computers are too expensive? You haven't been
paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, eMachines (www.e4me.com) advertised a system with a
Cyrix M II-333, a 2.1-gigabyte hard drive, 32 megabytes of RAM, a
32-speed CD-ROM, Windows 98 and a 56kbps V.90 modem for $399. Want
to add a monitor? That'll be $499.
</P>
<P>
   Don't want to spend $400? How about a system for $299?
</P>
<P>
   Microworkz Computer (www.microworkz.com) is taking orders for
the WEBzter Jr., a $299 PC with a Cyrix M II-300, a 3.2-gigabyte
hard drive, 32 megabytes of RAM, Windows 98 and a 56kbps V.90
modem. Another $99 gets you a CD-ROM and floppy drive, and another
$140 gets you a 15-inch color monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of computers at the other end of the scale are falling,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, Dell advertised a $2,200 system with an Intel
Pentium II-450, a 10-gigabyte hard drive, 64 megabytes of RAM, a
32-speed CD-ROM drive, a 3D graphics card, a cutting-edge sound
card, a 17-inch monitor and a 56kbps V.90 modem. Today, you can get
basically the same system with a Pentium III-450 for $1,600.
</P>
<P>
   Yikes. Remember the days when you had to spend at least $1,500
to get a basic computer? And when really good computers cost more
than $3,000? That's all ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say it's due to increased competition between the three
big chipmakers _ Intel, AMD and Cyrix _ and traditional
computermakers _ Compaq, Dell, Hewlett-Packard _ and upstart
computermakers _ eMachines and Microworkz.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Compaq stock took a tumble after the company
said its earnings for the first quarter would fall below analyst
expectations. Among other things, Compaq blamed lower-than-expected
demand and increased competition in the commercial PC market.
</P>
<P>
   Falling PC prices also are due to the changing face of the
average computer buyer.
</P>
<P>
   There still are computer enthusiasts who will gladly fork over
$3,000 for the latest and greatest machine. But many of today's
buyers looking for their  reported
that 56 percent of all sub-$1,000 PCs are sold into households with
annual incomes of $35,000 or less.
</P>
<P>
   Other buyers have just figured out that they don't need to spend
$3,000 or $2,000 or even $1,000 when all they want to do is surf
the Web, trade e-mail, balance the family checkbook and write
letters to Grandma.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the number of consumers seeking low-cost
computers has outpaced the number looking for top-end machines. A
recent ``San Jose Mercury News'' story, for example, stated that 61
percent of all PCs sold in retail stores cost $1,000 or less.
That's up dramatically from just 25 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Some market analysts predict that the penetration rate of PCs in
homes could soon exceed 100 percent, because so many people will
seek multiple computers to run everything from lights and security
systems to entertainment centers and kitchen appliances.
</P>
<P>
   Will computer prices continue to drop? Many experts think so.
The power of the Web and the versatility of electronic commerce is
giving small companies a chance to compete, and major corporations
will have to cut prices to maintain market share.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how Apple Computer factors in to
all this. The company's iMac has proven hugely successful. Older
iMacs sell in the $900 range, but even new ones cost just $1,200.
And the Power Macintosh G3s _ Apple's top-of-the-line machines _
are getting rave reviews in the computer press.
</P>
<P>
   Any way you look at it, now's the time to buy. So get out there
and look around! But consider these thoughts before buying a
low-end PC:
</P>
<P>
   - As illustrated above, many of the cheapest systems are not as
complete as we might like them to be. Some come with all the
hardware you might need, but no operating system. Some don't come
with monitors or CD-ROM drives. Read the fine print and make sure
you know what you are buying.
</P>
<P>
   - Nobody is giving anything away. Makers of cheap PCs are
cutting corners. That's not to say cheap PCs are unreliable. But
don't expect the same performance as you would from a name-brand,
top-notch machine.
</P>
<P>
   - Think about how you will use the computer before you buy one.
Cheap PCs are great for Web surfing, sending e-mail and simple
computing. But if you like to play the latest 3D games, a cheap PC
probably will give you poor performance or none at all. &QL; 
SPIRITS ARE ABOUT TO SPEAK &QL; 
As you might expect, last week's column about the mystery at Harold
Temmer's Sun City West home sparked quite a few e-mails from
readers.
</P>
<P>
   In case you missed it, here's the nutshell version: Temmer's
wife wrote a letter to friends on the computer. Temmer later called
the letter up on the computer and found the name and address of a
stranger typed at the bottom. Turns out the stranger had been dead
10 years, and nobody could figure out how his name and address got
into Temmer's computer.
</P>
<P>
   Without any other explanation, Temmer and I joked that his
computer must be haunted!
</P>
<P>
   As I pointed out in the column, we ruled out the possibility
that Temmer bought a computer with a used hard drive that could
have contained the stranger's information. Temmer said he bought
the computer six years ago, and the stranger died four years before
that. And the stranger's information had never shown up on Temmer's
computer before.
</P>
<P>
   A reader named Richard wrote: ``To me, there was a delicious
irony in the coincidence that your article was headlined ``Do the
dead have PCs in heaven?'' _ appearing just below the Cyberslang
definition of ``Legacy Tech'' as ``outdated hardware and
software.'' Surely, if the dead have PCs in heaven, what they've
got is Legacy Tech: dead, gone and obsolete computers.
</P>
<P>
   A reader named Sharron had several ideas. Among them, ``Because
he is a retired assistant vice chancellor of the University of
California-San Diego, he could have an intelligent friend playing a
trick on him.''
</P>
<P>
   A reader named Virginia wrote, ``Since it was a man's name and
address, perhaps this bit of data came from a mailing list _ one
that hasn't been updated in a while or that is using very old data.
If Temmer and his wife haven't used any mailing lists and don't
have any on their computer, perhaps they have received something
from someone else's mailing list. An e-mail about a class reunion,
perhaps, or a church group, or fund-raising spam.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a reader named Tom wrote, ``In regard to your headline
in today's ``Republic,'' `Do the dead have PCs in heaven?' I have
the answer: No. In heaven, they have Macs. The PCs go to the other
place.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)home.net by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
