<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HOCKEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE-LOVING HOCKEY WRITER SHOULD HEAR FROM FANS  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE APRIL 20 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When the National Hockey League first began expanding
out of its northern, Canada-centric roots, purists feared the dire
consequences of diluting sparse talent. Where Maurice ``Rocket''
Richard once flew, thugs would now reign.
</P>
<P>
   They were right and wrong. Fights and mayhem still mar the game,
but latter-day hockey still produces genuine artists, like the
just-retired Great One, Wayne Gretzky. What the purists failed to
account for, however, was the expanding base of thugs in the
stands. And in the press boxes.
</P>
<P>
   In short, they didn't account for hockey being played before
Texans.
</P>
<P>
   To its great shame, the NHL promotes the brutality of its sport,
glorifying carnage even in its advertising. It does this for one
reason: Banal, mouth-breathing violence addicts who know nothing of
hockey's finer points are drawn like leeches to the blood.
</P>
<P>
   To some ``fans'' of hockey in Texas, the game is akin to a
Saturday night at an Amarillo roadhouse. There's drinkin' and
there's fightin'. And fightin' and drinkin'. Did we miss anything?
</P>
<P>
   That certainly appears to be the breadth of knowledge that Keith
Gave, a sportswriter who, incredibly, earns a living as a pro
hockey columnist for the ``Dallas Morning News,'' brings to his
readers.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Gave wrote with disturbing excitement about a
vicious cheap shot against Phoenix Coyote center Jeremy Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   It was, Gave wrote, ``a gruesome reminder of what it means to
mess with Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone suggested Roenick's injury might finally quiet one of
the biggest mouths in the NHL. Especially with his jaw wired,
requiring him to suck his meals though a straw for a few weeks,''
wrote the Texas hockey expert.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick, whose face was crushed into the boards as a result of a
blind-side cheap shot by Dallas' premier thug, Derian Hatcher,
dislocated his jaw, and broke it in three places. He has had two
metal plates inserted to hold his mouth in place. He will lose at
least eight teeth. And his thumb was fractured.
</P>
<P>
   Now, hockey is a tough game. It tolerates _ even expects _
retribution, vengeance and all the other Puzo-esque melodramas
among its players. But it is a game of paradoxes. The same NHL that
revels in its violent collisions awards the only
individual-achievement trophy in pro sports named after a woman.
Part of the Great One's greatness was winning the Lady Byng trophy
for sportsmanship four times.
</P>
<P>
   These are the sort of subtle distinctions, however, that are
lost on people like Keith Gave, who thought the oft-suspended
Hatcher should have received the first star of the game for his
handiwork. He seems to reflect his readership's acumen regarding
hockey. Two-thirds of respondents to a ``Morning News'' poll
rejoiced in seeing Roenick's blood on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   However unlikely, it might help Gave's perspective to hear from
real fans of the game. His number in ``Hockey Town USA - Not'' is
1-(214)-977-8034. Or, by e-mail, at keithgave(at)dallasnews.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
