<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROOFS-INSURANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAIL-PROOF ROOFS A TOUGH SELL: FEW HOMEOWNERS TAKE ADVANTAGE OF
PROGRAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS VAUGHN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Hail-resistant roofs will defend your house,
save you money and time, and perhaps over the long haul bring
insurance costs down for every homeowner in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, it's been a tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   A year after the state and insurance companies launched a
pioneering program to lower insurance premiums for homeowners who
put hail-resistant roofs over their heads, only a fraction of
Texans have taken advantage of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate, Farmers and State Farm insurance companies, which
insure two-thirds of all homeowners in the state, gave roof
discounts on 1,300 policies in the last year, a tiny fraction of
the more than 2.9 million policies they hold in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program needs some work,'' said Don Bassett, an Arlington
roofing contractor who has put on only one hail-resistant roof in
the last year. ``We've bid it many, many times, but the numbers
don't seem to work out for people.''
</P>
<P>
   The tepid beginning apparently isn't for lack of interest. Texas
contractors, insurance companies and state regulators report steady
inquiries from homeowners in one of the most hailed-on environments
in North America.
</P>
<P>
   A number of other states _ Colorado and Oklahoma, for example _
have similar programs, though Texas is apparently the only one with
regulatory authority over it.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is apparently money. Roofs that qualify as
hail-resistant can cost significantly more than those that don't,
money that must come from the homeowner, not the insurer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, few major manufacturers produce a shingle or roof
product that meets the standard, and a number of them have
questioned whether the testing _ dropping steel balls from varying
heights _ has anything to do with a hailstorm.
</P>
<P>
   And lastly, the discounts mandated by the Texas Department of
Insurance vary widely, according to the type of hail-resistant
roof, area of the state and type of insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the industry and the state say the program can benefit
everyone's bottom line. They contend that as more people become
aware of it, more will take advantage of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to just sit back and say: `This is Texas. We're going
to have hailstorms and there's nothing we can do about it,''' said
Lars Rosene, a State Farm spokesman. ``This is a proactive approach
for dealing with hailstorms and that's not something we've had in a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The discount program went into effect in mid-February 1998, the
result of years of discussion about how to minimize financial
losses for the insurance industry in Texas, which were staggering
after billion-dollar hailstorms in 1992 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a homeowner who puts on a hail-resistant roof must get a
discount on his insurance premium. The discounts range from 1
percent to 35 percent, with the greater discounts going to roofs
that rated better in the tests.
</P>
<P>
   Hail-resistant roofs, whether asphalt, wood or metal, are
considerably more expensive than regular roofs.
</P>
<P>
   For example, to cover a 3,500-square-foot roof _ a common size _
with asphalt shingles, a homeowner would expect to pay about
$3,100. The same size roof with the highest qualifying
hail-resistant shingles would cost about $1,100 more.
Hail-resistant wood shingles would run at least $3,300 more than
regular wood shingles on the same size home.
</P>
<P>
   John Fakhari paid more than $11,000 for his hail-resistant
shingle roof for his large Eagle Mountain Lake home last year,
close to $4,000 more than a standard shingle roof.
</P>
<P>
   His insurance premiums dropped dramatically, both for the
hail-resistant roof and for replacing wood shingles with asphalt,
so he expects to recoup the extra expense in four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at four different options, and I thought this was the
best decision,'' he said. ``I hope it turns out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   The insurance department and insurance companies say that when
homeowners decide whether to spring for a hail-resistant roof, they
should also figure in the cost of their deductibles, their time and
trouble in turning in a claim if they sustain damage, and in the
long term, the savings from making fewer damage claims that usually
increase premiums. They are also looking at how to make the program
more affordable for low-income homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   The industry favors reducing the discounts as the roofs age,
meaning that it would take longer for homeowners to recoup their
upfront costs. The state has not made a decision on that idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect the discount to offset the increased costs of
the roof, but there are other advantages,'' said Gary Julian, a
personal property specialist with the insurance department.
``Hopefully, over a period of time, by mitigating these losses, we
can reduce insurance costs.''
</P>
<P>
   A lack of confidence in the testing of hail-resistant roofs has
discouraged most of the nation's major shingle manufacturers,
according to Russ Snyder, general manager of the Asphalt Roofing
Manufacturers Association. Manufacturers fear that they will be
held liable if the roofs don't hold up in a hailstorm, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're quite concerned that the science that has been adopted
by the (insurance department) is not representative of what a
hailstone might do,'' Snyder said. ``It's not representative of
real-world conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rich Roe, technical director for Mississippi-based Atlas
Roofing, one of the few asphalt shingle manufacturers with a
hail-resistant product, said his company makes no claims about the
ability of its StormMaster shingles to perform in a hailstorm. The
company only says it passed the impact test, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The state isn't scheduled to take an in-depth look at the
program for another four years. The next time a hailstorm strikes
in North Texas, homeowners and the insurance industry are likely to
get the program's first real evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're comfortable with the discounts, and we believe in the
program,'' Rosene said. ``But we haven't had the big storm to know
where these products stand. We've tested and retested, but when it
comes to softball-size hail in Arlington, we just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
