<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECKLESS ABANDON OF YOUTH TOOK A TRIP TO PARTS UNKNOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I remember the most minute details of that trip like it was
just, well ... this morning. I was going to say yesterday, but I've
forgotten most of yesterday already. However, most of this morning
is still on my ``to-do'' list and, therefore, as easy to recall as
that fateful trip that I took all those many moons ago.
</P>
<P>
   Like Gov. Bush, I was ``young and irresponsible'' back in my
B.V. days.
</P>
<P>
   That's Before Velcro. I've divided my life into two distinct
periods: B.V. and A.V. Before and After Velcro. Even though Velcro
was invented in 1948, many years passed before it became a factor
in my life. Fastening has never been the same. I don't know how
Velcro affected the governor, but I am truly a better person
because of it.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, my roommate, Andrea, and I hopped into my little Dodge
Challenger one beautiful Friday afternoon intent on driving from
Houston to Waco. We were going there to hang out with my fiance and
his friend, who I alleged was exceedingly handsome even though I
had never actually seen him. I just didn't want to make that
three-hour drive by myself, and Andrea hadn't had a date since the
Alamo fell.
</P>
<P>
   We were halfway to our destination when, to our amazement,
snowflakes started to fall from the brooding sky. Undaunted, we
kept driving as the snowflakes enlarged and multiplied until we
were in engulfed in blizzard-like conditions.
</P>
<P>
   We were faced with the decision of either retracing our steps or
trying to drive through the storm. At this point, we could not
distinguish the narrow lanes of Texas 6 from the ditches that
embraced it just beyond the shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   There was no safe place to pull over. All we could see were
trees and snow-covered fields for miles around. Besides, we only
had about $5 between the two of us. I doubt that anyone except my
fiance even had a clue where we were. I didn't even have a spare
tire. The only thing in my trunk was some cans that I was going to
recycle when we returned to Houston so that I could afford to do my
laundry.
</P>
<P>
   Upon deciding that we had gone too far to turn around, we simply
pumped up the volume on the radio and, literally, plowed ahead. We
did not meet another car until we arrived safely in Waco four hours
later.
</P>
<P>
   Let's make that young, irresponsible and lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Warp speed ahead, Scotty, to a day last month when I was
preparing for another road trip. I had AAA designate the route for
me on a map so detailed that it would make NASA proud. I had seven
credit cards in my wallet along with enough cashier's checks to
tide me over for three or four days if necessary. My mechanic
changed the oil on my car and inspected it from headlights to
taillights with a diagnostic microscope.
</P>
<P>
   In the trunk next to my luggage was an emergency roadside kit
complete with flares and a thermal blanket. I definitely had a
spare, plus a can of Fix A Flat. A cell phone, a pound of bologna
and a loaf of bread completed my preparations.
</P>
<P>
   And all of this was just for the drive to my office five miles
away from my home.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder, is all of this elaborate preparation a result of age
and wisdom or is it fear and anxiety brought on by witnessing one
too many tragedies? Maybe it's just a result of having enough
quarters to do my laundry now. Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   But I must say that we had a really good time that weekend. At
least I did. Unfortunately, that fellow we matched Andrea up with
was ugly as sin. Oh, well.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
