<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BOOK-DIRECTORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS FOCUSES ON HOLLYWOOD'S SEEDY SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget Monica Lewinsky. Forget George Stephanopoulos. This is
the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Easy Riders, Raging Bulls: How the Sex-Drugs-and-Rock 'n' Roll
Generation Saved Hollywood'' (Peter Biskind, Simon &AMP; Schuster,
paperback, $15, 506 pages), the story of Young Turk directors
having their way with Hollywood in the 1970s, dishes more dirt than
all the White House tell-alls could ever dream of doing.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs? Oh, yeah. There are studio honchos admitting they'd leave
a line of cocaine as a tip for waitresses and big-name directors
confessing to habits topping a quarter of a million dollars per
year. Sex? Whew. Plenty of it. In Biskind's book, everybody sleeps
with everybody else and can't wait to talk about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Easy Riders'' has already made the best-seller list, and now
it's out in paperback. You won't find a more concentrated,
hard-core, make-you-gasp gossip book anywhere for $15.
</P>
<P>
   Serving as a backdrop to all the raw gossip is Biskind's premise
that a handful of up-and-coming directors wrestled control of
American movies from the studios in the '70s and started making
intelligent, timely films that saved the industry from imminent
collapse. Without them, argues Biskind, American movies would have
lost their hold on the world.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least a dozen saviors on Biskind's list _ Dennis
Hopper, Warren Beatty, Robert Altman, Bob Rafelson, Peter
Bogdanovich, Martin Scorsese, Billy Friedkin, Francis Ford Coppola,
George Lucas, Steven Spielberg, Brian De Palma and Hal Ashby. He
also takes major detours into the lives of actor Robert De Niro,
producers Peter Fonda and Bert Schneider and writers Paul Schrader
and Robert Towne.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind's argument is that films like ``Easy Rider,'' ``MASH,''
``The Last Picture Show'' and ``Shampoo'' came along at a time when
the studios were wallowing in Doris Day fluff and fat-budget
musicals. The new directors saved Hollywood from internally
hemorrhaging, argues Biskind _ their films said something to a
younger audience, opening up another generation to the power of
movies as the '70s tumbled into the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   The new directors made their mark by turning the studio system
on its ear, making the director the most important part of the
movie deal. But then, one by one, they proceeded to implode.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cimino's massive budget overrun on the 1980 film
``Heaven's Gate'' is usually seen as the death knell of the
director's freedom _ it cost $44 million to make and grossed only
$1.3 million. But the tapestry the young directors were putting
together started unraveling long before that.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of massive budgets, massive insecurities, odd
groupings of groupies, easy-to-get drugs, easy-to-get sex and the
pure pull of power brought the house down around them. That's where
the gossip of ``Easy Riders'' comes in, and such good gossip it is.
</P>
<P>
   Here's studio executive Don Simpson, who died in 1996, on
Altman: ``He was such an alcoholic. He was full of gibberish and
full of himself, a pompous, pretentious a--hole.''
</P>
<P>
   And this rejoinder from Altman: ``Simpson was a bad guy, a bum
... it's a plus to our industry that he's not here anymore. I'm
only sorry he didn't live longer and suffer more.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Easy Riders,'' private conversations are quoted, everything
from the size of a drug habit to the size of a man's tool, but
nobody has come back at Biskind, calling him a liar. The book is
written primarily from interviews he conducted in the years he
edited Premiere and American Film, moving easily through the world
of movie-making.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind sees ``Easy Rider'' as the first film to pull Hollywood
out of a prolonged slump _ a slump that saw box office attendance
at 15.8 million in 1971, an all-time low. But even as it was
showing Hollywood the way to make money, ``Easy Rider'' was
planting the seeds of self-delusion that would eventually bring
about the collapse of America's new cinema.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind points out that Hopper gathered the ``Easy Rider'' crew
in the parking lot of the New Orleans airport Hilton at 6:30 a.m.
before filming and went into a tirade. Fonda described Hopper as
``this little fascist blowin' us all off.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopper's combination of flying ego and crawling paranoia, fanned
by the success of ``Easy Rider,'' led to Hollywood footing the bill
for ``The Last Movie'' _ an artistic and economic fiasco that
spelled a quick and ugly end to Hopper's reputation as an emerging
talent behind the camera. Hopper's collapse as an up-and-coming
director was mirrored by other directors of his times, each
implosion a little more gruesome than the last.
</P>
<P>
   Hopper's ego had nothing on Friedkin, whose ``The French
Connection'' and ``The Exorcist'' were followed by duds such as
``Sorcerer,'' ``Cruising,'' ``The Guardian,'' ``Blue Chips'' and
``Jade.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with that list of flops, Friedkin couldn't come to terms
with his failure, saying, ``In the '70s, if you had a flop the
attitude was, `That's too bad, but it was a good picture.' Then it
became, if you made a film that was not a hit, they put you under
indictment.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, ``Easy Riders'' looks down its nose at George
Lucas and Steven Spielberg, the only two directors from the '70s
who have consistently made blockbuster movies, bringing the public
back to the theater and power back to Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind passes both men off as borderline dweebs, suggesting
that neither has the neuroses worthy of true genius. ``Easy
Riders,'' unable to find any real lust for the crazed life in
either Lucas or Spielberg, brushes off their movies as successful
but so-what.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coppola takes a swipe at Lucas and Spielberg by saying, ``Now,
here we are, 20 years after `Heaven's Gate.' Directors don't have
much power anymore, the executives make unheard of amounts of money
and budgets are more out of control than they ever were. And there
hasn't been a classic in 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The flaw in ``Easy Riders,'' the flaw in Coppola's take on
Hollywood, is the notion that we shall never see the like of the
'70s directors again _ that these men cradled a special kind of
genius. The truth is that John Ford made as many outstanding movies
in his lifetime as the class of the '70s, combined, and that there
are, even now, talents emerging that make Hopper and others seem
like pretty small potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   It smacks of pettiness to deny Lucas his standing among talented
directors because the Star Wars trilogy appeals too much to the
buying public, the great unwashed. And it's just as petty to deny
Spielberg his just due as a great director.
</P>
<P>
   Coppola can talk all he wants about the lack of classic movies
over the past 10 years. But the fact is, ever since his
``Godfather'' triumphs he's been eating Spielberg's dust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
