<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6128 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLASTICHOUSE-TEX     04-20 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLASTICHOUSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A '50S HOUSE IN TEMPLE, TEXAS, MAKES NATIONAL REGISTER OF HISTORIC
PLACES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know this house. You lived in it, or your parents did. Maybe
your grandparents still do. It is so normal, so average, the
neighborhood could be postmarked Anywhere, U.S.A. The house is like
thousands that were built in American suburbs in the '50s and '60s.
</P>
<P>
   The squat plastic coffee cups with a single ring for a handle _
you've held those. The plastic glasses, the melamine plates _
you've used those. There's a bread box _ you know how it will sound
when the door snaps closed. You know the kitchen counter, even
though flecked with gold glitter, will be as smooth as cornstarch.
</P>
<P>
   The colors on the kitchen cabinets _ turquoise, orange, lemon
yellow _ set the scene as effectively as the Saarinen and Eames
furniture that floats in the open expanse of the turquoise-floored
living room. You can practically smell the pigs-in-a-blanket
cooking in the copper-front Chambers wall oven. You can hear the
theme song to ``I Love Lucy'' playing somewhere in the house. You
know without looking it's a black-and-white TV recessed in a
cabinet with rough fabric-covered doors and rabbit ears on top.
</P>
<P>
   This house, built in 1959 by laminate magnate Ralph Wilson in
Temple, Texas, is so typically mid-century American, it has joined
Thomas Jefferson's Monticello and Frank Lloyd Wright's Fallingwater
on the National Register of Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   The house is also deceptively futuristic. Wilson, who died in
1972, covered every possible surface of his house with plastic
laminate. Some people may know the generic product by a
competitor's brand name, Formica. Wilson used his house as a
showcase and laboratory for his company, Ralph Wilson Plastics _
now known as Wilsonart International, the nation's largest
manufacturer of solid-surface materials.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Wilsonart bought the Wilson House from Ralph's widow,
Sunny. The company plans to store archives there and use it much
like Wilson did, as a showcase for Wilsonart goods.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson often used his house to test his product. He covered his
garage walls with brown laminate, then refused to install garage
doors. He wanted to see how the plastic walls would withstand the
extreme Texas temperatures. After he died, Sunny had doors put in
for security reasons. The laminate, though, still looks good.
</P>
<P>
   The shower stalls and bathroom cabinets and counter tops, used
daily for decades, show no signs of age or ravages of moisture. The
bedroom doors and sliding pocket doors, also laminate, are as
smooth and lustrous as the day they were hung.
</P>
<P>
   The rounded edges found on the kitchen counters seem
unremarkable, until you remember that when they were installed,
sharp edges covered in aluminum strips were state-of-the-art.
</P>
<P>
   The multicolored laminate kitchen cabinets had to be installed
by a contractor who specialized in beauty shops, that being the
only application at the time for plastic-coated cabinets. Now,
laminate cabinets are quite common.
</P>
<P>
   This is what made Wilson's house so attractive to the National
Register. It was directional; the materials that were used and the
manner in which they were applied affected the way subsequent
houses were built. Ralph Wilson was a visionary, but his home was
that of the middle class, built in the mid-century, in central
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few buildings that reflect the lives of average citizens
are ever saved,'' says Grace Jeffers, the curator of Wilson House.
This is what makes it so valuable, and so personal. Everyone who
walks through the door feels a connection.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   INFOBOX
</P>
<P>
   The Wilson House is open for tours by calling (254) 773-9898.
The house is at 1714 S. 61st St., Temple, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
