<P>
   STROKES-DRUG &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Before the night was over, it seemed that
everyone at All Saints Episcopal Hospital knew about the stroke
patient who watched ``Judge Judy.'' Lila Shaw's fondness for the
feisty judge of daytime television, backed up by a quick call to
911, helped give doctors the confidence to use a powerful but
time-sensitive, clot-busting drug called t-PA. By midnight, Shaw
was well on her way to recovery. But three years after the drug's
approval, doctors say, too many patients are missing out on its
potential. Studies show that only 3 percent to 5 percent of those
eligible nationwide get the intravenous medication, according to
American Heart Association officials. By CHARLOTTE HUFF. Story will
move in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   T E X A S &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN JACINTO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LA PORTE, Texas _ Veterans of the battle of San Jacinto once
collected free drinks for their battlefield heroics, but today, the
fight that gave Texas its independence is hardly mentioned beyond
the marshy reaches of Buffalo Bayou, east of Houston. Battleground
officials hope to change that attitude with an expensive new plan
to raise the image of the San Jacinto Monument to a level equal
with that of the Alamo. By ART CHAPMAN. Story will move in ``n''
regional category for Texas points only. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROOFS-INSURANCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Hail-resistant roofs will defend your house,
save you money and time, and perhaps over the long haul bring
insurance costs down for every homeowner in Texas. But so far, it's
been a tough sell. A year after the state and insurance companies
launched a pioneering program to lower insurance premiums for
homeowners who put hail-resistant roofs over their heads, only a
fraction of Texans have taken advantage of the program. By CHRIS
VAUGHN. Story has moved in ``n'' regional category for Texas points
only. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
