   CHILDREN-HEALTH ASSETS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Do your children have what it takes? The
Minneapolis-based child advocacy group Search Institute has
identified 40 assets that children need to grow up healthy. The
average child has only 18 of them. The institute's president will
be in Fort Worth on April 26 to give a seminar. By CAROLYN POIROT.
Story will move in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANDERSON-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ I remember the most minute details of that trip like
it was just, well ... this morning. I was going to say yesterday,
but I've forgotten most of yesterday already. However, most of this
morning is still on my ``to-do'' list and, therefore, as easy to
recall as that fateful trip that I took all those many moons ago.
By MONICA ANDERSON. Story has moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PLASTIC HOUSE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ You know this house. You lived in it, or your parents
did. Maybe your grandparents still do. It is so normal, so average,
the neighborhood could be postmarked Anywhere, U.S.A. The house is
like thousands that were built in American suburbs in the '50s and
'60s. The squat plastic coffee cups with a single ring for a handle
_ you've held those. The plastic glasses, the melamine plates _
you've used those. There's a bread box _ you know how it will sound
when the door snaps closed. You know the kitchen counter, even
though flecked with gold glitter, will be as smooth as cornstarch.
This particular house is in Temple, Texas, and it's made the
National Register of Historic Places. By GAILE ROBINSON. Story has
moved in ``l'' lifestyle category. &QL; 
