<P>
   COXNET WHEELS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS _ 0420 _ Finally for 1999, Chevrolet has given its
Blazer an upscale option _ the '99 TrailBlazer package. It includes
two-tone embossed leather seats, monochromatic paint and _ this is
significant _ a touring suspension that really smooths out the ride
of the 3,700-pound sport-utility. (DeVault, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Includes 3-column color photograph of a
Blazer, a 2-column color photo of Blazer's interior and a 1-column
detail photo of a leather seats.
</P>
<P>
   w/AT A GLANCE _ Fact box previewing the .
</P>
<P>
   THE MECHANIC _ Were I ever to pen an autobiography, the title
would be ``Femininity Under Grease.'' I think these three words
express volumes about my journey, both real and perceived, through
the world of auto mechanics. (Carter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). Includes 1-column color photograph of
columnist.
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is now available.)
</P>
<P>
   CHARTER-PROBE _ CBS News on Wednesday will report on a year-long
undercover investigation of Atlanta-based Charter Behavorial Health
Systems, the nation's largest chain of psychiatric hospitals. The
report focuses on Charter's children's wards, where the network
says it found evidence of deaths, injuries and hospital
falsifications of medical records in institutions from
Massachusetts to California. Charter has 91 hospitals in 32 states,
which admit about 60,000 children and adolescents a year, and it
takes in more than $300 million of taxpayer money annually.
(Miller, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (f) Financial and (a) General News categories.
</P>
<P>
   SEARS-RETIREES _ Sears retirees meet today to discuss protest
plans for next week's annual meeting in Atlanta. Retirees
nationwide are upset that Sears has reduced their benefits. (Bond,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12.
</P>
<P>
   COX-DELTA-KIDS _ATLANTA _ First-class passengers on a Delta Air
Lines flight last month got bumped to coach to make room for a top
executive's children, according to an account circulated by pilots.
(Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESSDEANS _ ATLANTA _ A thousand business school deans meet
in Atlanta to discuss the revolution in technology and its impact
on management education. (Holsendolph, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   HITECH-SECRETARIES _ Technology and an increasingly mobile
workforce will transform many of today's secretaries and
administrative assistants into Information Coordinators. In the
next six years, Information Coordinators will be the ``ground
control'' for the rapidly evolving workplace, according to a new
report on the office of the future. IC's will serve as the critical
communication link among far flung employees, people working on
projects and telecommuters. They will also provide training for
teams working on new technologies, according to the report by
OfficeTeam, an international staffing company in Menlo Park, Calif.
This week's professional secretaries week. (Joyner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ELDERBEERMAN-EARNINGS _ Elder-Beerman Stores Corp. reports
record earnings for fiscal year ended Jan. 30, 1999. (Bohman,
Dayton Daily News) 12.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-BANKS _ Federal Reserve Board Governor Edward Kelley is in
Cincinnati today to discuss the results of the most recent Y2K
regulatory examinations of banking institutions. The FRD, Ohio
Bankers Association and area financial institutions also will be on
hand (Townsend, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   COMDEX _ CHICAGO _ News from the Comdex show. (Glass, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (f) Financial and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   COKEBOTTLER-EARNINGS _ Coca-Cola Enterprises said today it lost
$62 million, or 15 cents a share, in the first quarter, partly
because of higher fixed costs from a stream of acquisitions. The
loss by the world's largest soft drink bottler was 2 cents more a
share than in the year-ago period. The results met Wall Street's
expectations. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FIRE-GEL _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Flames roar from Homestead to
Port St. Lucie, Fla., but wooden power poles that should be tinder
in their path stand tall thanks to John Bartlett. Bartlett is the
firefighter from Jupiter, Fla. who made national news and a tidy
profit by turning absorbent diaper gel into a booming fire-shield
business. His curiosity about how a pile of diapers remained
uncharred through a 1993 house fire led to the creation of
Barricade, a solution of water-absorbent polymers that sticks to
just about any surface and wards off flames. (Kalajian, Palm Beach
Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Now we get to the good news about income taxes: Two
out of three taxpayers will get a refund on their federal taxes,
averaging about $1,563. It's a refreshing windfall, one that some
people like so much that they build it into their spending
expectations every year. Two points need to be made: One, you
shouldn't leave that much money in Uncle Sam's account next time.
Two, it's up to you to decide whether this year's refund is a toy
or a tool. You can party or plan ahead, and either one will feel
good. (Ezell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
