<SLUG> BC-SPIRITUAL-DIET-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SPIRITUAL DIET: LOSING POUNDS THROUGH PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LYNN STEINBERG  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LeAnn Larsen has fought the battle of the bulge since she was a
teenager, sampling one weight-loss program after another without
much success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nutri/System, Weight Watchers, Jenny Craig, Dexatrim pills _ I
tried them all,'' said Larsen, a 51-year-old pastor's assistant at
the United Evangelical Free Church in the Ballard section of
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't until she stopped counting calories and put her
trust in God and a Christian weight-loss program called the Weigh
Down Workshop that the pounds came off _ and stayed off.
</P>
<P>
   Every week, thousands of men and women like Larsen flock to
Weigh Down meetings throughout the region and learn to substitute
God for food.
</P>
<P>
   The program, which started seven years ago in a Tennessee
church, has grown to an estimated 30,000 chapters worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   It is the largest of several Bible-based weight-loss programs _
including First Place, 3D and Step Forward _ that differ in their
particulars but have as their central element a reliance on a
higher power. In that, they bear some resemblance to secular
12-step programs such as Alcoholics Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   For the 58 million adult Americans who are overweight, these
programs offer a distinctly different approach to weight loss,
which has become a $33 billion-dollar a year industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a diet; that's why it worked,'' said Teri Lewis, a
42-year-old accountant, of Weigh Down, which helped her lose close
to 100 pounds and cut her dress size in half, from a 24 to a 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing was that it made my relationship with God
better,'' Lewis said. ``It got me reading the Bible more. It took
my focus off food and onto that relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   There were times, after a stressful day, when Lewis would have
sought comfort in potato chips and french fries.
</P>
<P>
   That changed after she began the Weigh Down Workshop. She
started turning to scripture instead. If she wasn't at home, or
didn't have a Bible handy, she offered a simple prayer: ``Lord,
help me to get through this and not eat what I shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The fundamentals of the program, founded by Gwen Shamblin, a
Tennessee dietician and one-time cheerleader, are laid out in her
book ``The Weigh Down Diet'' (Bantam Doubleday, $22, 317 pages),
which has sold more than 1 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Shamblin preaches that ``head hunger'' _ the urge to
eat when the body doesn't need food _ is really spiritual hunger.
</P>
<P>
   She teaches people to recognize the difference and counsels them
to eat when they're hungry, stop when they're full, and satisfy
their emotional and spiritual needs with prayer.
</P>
<P>
   There's no counting calories or fat grams. There are no
forbidden foods. ``God created Fritos and dip for our enjoyment,''
Shamblin said. So she advises people to eat what they want _ just
less of it. Have a small serving of ice cream instead of half the
carton.
</P>
<P>
   When folks come to her and say they have an urge to snack, she
hands them a Bible and tells them to ``Chew on this.'' The only
exercise she promotes is kneeling down to pray.
</P>
<P>
   That's where she and many other dieticians part company.
</P>
<P>
   The American Dietetic Association, a professional organization
that promotes sound nutrition, says regular physical activity is an
essential part of losing weight and keeping it off. It doesn't have
to be a 30-minute workout at the gym. It can be a brisk walk after
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is absolutely critical to good health, not just weight
loss, but long-term good health,'' said Sue Butkus, a dietician and
nutritionist at Washington State University.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to physical activity, she said a safe and effective
weight-loss program should include a variety of foods and promote
the slow and sustained shedding of pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Butcher, 47, tried for years to slim down, finally growing
so frustrated she resigned herself to being overweight rather than
risk disappointment again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to put myself through that anymore,'' Butcher
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the incident that sent her down the path of
redemption.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Bob, were at Seattle's Museum of Flight. A
B-52 bomber was on display. Butcher was so fascinated with the
aircraft that she braved the steep metal stairs up to the cockpit
so she could have a look inside.
</P>
<P>
   At about 210 pounds, on a 5-foot-3 frame, she had a tough time.
</P>
<P>
   She heard snickering behind her as she reached the halfway
point. ``I don't know if it had anything to do with me,'' she said,
``but in my head they were laughing at the fat lady going up the
stairs.''
</P>
<P>
   The impact of that incident led Butcher to decide later that she
could no longer ignore her weight. ``God help me,'' she says she
cried out. ``I can't do this. I hate the way I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, while running an errand at her church, she
accidentally stumbled into an orientation for the Weigh Down
Workshop. She sat down and listened. Then she joined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to look to food for everything,'' Butcher said. ``It
was a comfort. Then I transferred my love affair with food to a
love affair with God.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of satisfying what she came to recognize as ``head
hunger,'' she went to Shamblin's audio tapes or to the Bible and
began reading wherever it fell open. Soon, her desire to eat would
pass. She lost 55 pounds in 18 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Today, two years after her first session, Butcher leads the
Weigh Down workshop at her church. Her husband leads another group
for men.
</P>
<P>
   The program consists of weekly meetings at which participants
view an hourlong video, then engage in discussion and prayer. The
workshop costs $103 for the first 3-month session, including
workbooks and tapes. Follow-up sessions cost less.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:30 p.m. one recent Monday, 10 women of every size, shape
and age, gathered in a classroom at the United Evangelical Free
Church. They sat in folding chairs, facing a television at the
front of the room, with workbooks and Bibles in their laps.
</P>
<P>
   They listened attentively, occasionally nodding in affirmation,
as Shamblin preached: ``We all have hungry hearts ... but only one
thing will fill a hungry heart ... the Lord Almighty.''
</P>
<P>
   For information about the Weigh Down Workshop or meetings in
your area, call 800-844-5208 or visit the company's Web site at:
</P>
<P>
   www.wdworkshop.com
</P>
</TEXT>
