<HEADLINE>
PLANS UNDER WAY TO ENHANCE OBSERVATION OF BATTLE THAT WON TEXAS
INDEPENDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LA PORTE, Texas _ Veterans of the battle of San Jacinto once
collected free drinks for their battlefield heroics, but today, the
fight that gave Texas its independence is hardly mentioned beyond
the marshy reaches of Buffalo Bayou, east of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Battleground officials hope to change that attitude with an
expensive new plan to raise the image of the San Jacinto Monument
to a level equal with that of the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   For the first few years after the April 21, 1836, battle,
veterans gathered in Houston and rallied around a long flag pole
used during the fight. They put the pole on their shoulders and
took off on a round of bars. They would drop the pole in front of
the bar and demand free drinks in the name of patriotism.
</P>
<P>
   With that round consumed, they would rattle a gourd canteen with
a Mexican bullet inside and demand another.
</P>
<P>
   It worked then, but today, their battlefield accomplishments
have been muted. Though it is still a state holiday, San Jacinto
Day is not a prominent Texas celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people today don't understand the Battle of San
Jacinto,'' said J.C. Martin, executive director of the San Jacinto
Museum of History. ``Coming here to the battlefield doesn't make it
much easier.''
</P>
<P>
   The San Jacinto Battleground State Historical Park between
Houston and Bay City is an uncommon place with an irregular
history. Construction of the 570-foot monument began in 1936, but
when it was finished three years later it sat idle. All the money
was spent to make it taller than the Washington Monument _ fine for
a Texas-size boast _ but nothing was left to stock the museum at
the base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to keep the fans running inside because if you turned
them off, mildew would begin sprouting on the walls like a wheat
field,'' said Malcolm McLean, who served as an assistant director
and archivist at the museum from 1939 to 1941.
</P>
<P>
   McLean, who later taught history and Spanish at both Texas
Christian University and the University of Texas at Arlington,
began assembling the museum's artifacts in the third-floor attic at
the Houston Public Library.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the state struck a deal: The monument belonged to
the state, but the museum would be run by the private, nonprofit,
San Jacinto Museum Association.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, maintenance of the park was handed over to the
Texas Parks and Wildlife Department.
</P>
<P>
   That confederation stopped a helter-skelter management that
brought several unrelated changes to the 1,000-acre park. A
reflecting pool was built, again similar to the Washington
Monument, but because of its mud bottom, it doesn't cast a
reflection. Picnic sites were constructed on the battlefield, and
roads cut through it.
</P>
<P>
   The Battleship Texas was anchored at the corner of the park and
concession stands were built at the edge of Sam Houston's old camp
site.
</P>
<P>
   It is only within the museum that any measure of understanding
of the battle can be obtained. In what has been the most successful
addition to the entire park, a 35-minute slide presentation called
``Texas Forever,'' is shown in the museum theater.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-two computerized projectors cast more than 3,000 images on
the screen and tell the story of Gen. Antonio Lopez de Santa Anna's
campaign against the rebel Texians. With slides shown as fast as 20
per second, the presentation is seamless and flawless, ending with
Houston's victory on the high-grass prairie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well over half a million people have seen the slide
presentation since it began nine years ago,'' Martin said. ``It has
been very successful. In Texas Forever, we tried very had to tell
the truth from both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he said, it is time to get the message to more people. A
master plan has been developed that will cost an estimated $55
million over the next dozen or so years. It will attempt to restore
the battlefield to its original 1836 condition.
</P>
<P>
   The reflecting pool will be drained and filled in with natural
prairie grasses. The picnic areas will be moved off the
battleground to adjacent areas. The Battleship Texas can't
realistically be moved, but its ticket office and concession stands
can be shifted away from Houston's camp site.
</P>
<P>
   A new visitor's center will be constructed.
</P>
<P>
   The goals, Martin said, will be to preserve the park's
significant cultural, historical and natural resources, and raise
the public awareness of the battleground.
</P>
<P>
   The monument belongs to all the people of Texas not just the
Houston area, Martin said. ``We all need to share in the history
and share in the responsibility. This is not a Gulf Coast treasure,
it is a state treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
