<SLUG> BC-TIME-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TIME, LOVE, MEMORY': LESSONS OF FRUIT FLIES, FROM THE FINCH'S
FRIEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: publication notes at end of review)  
 (bl)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ``great biologist'' of Jonathan Weiner's new book, ``Time,
Love, Memory,'' is Seymour Benzer, a professor at the California
Institute of Technology and one of the pioneers in the growing
fields of genetics and molecular biology. But what do time, love
and memory have to do with genetics? A great deal, says Weiner, a
scientist and science writer who won a Pulitzer Prize for a
previous book, ``The Beak of the Finch,'' a study of Charles Darwin
and evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Benzer and the generations of students he has fostered studied
time, love and memory in fruit flies to see how genes govern
behavior. Fruit flies wake up at dawn and go to sleep at night even
when they are in a sealed room and never see the sun. Fruit flies
also have elaborate courtship rituals and mating behavior: love.
And surprisingly, experiments supervised by Benzer have proved that
flies can learn, for example, how to avoid electric shocks. That
is, they have memory.
</P>
<P>
   Weiner's book is a fascinating history of the effort, led by
Benzer, to find the specific genes that regulate time, love and
memory in fruit flies and therefore to demonstrate something larger
about the connection between genes and behavior. Benzer was dealing
with what Weiner calls one of the ultimate questions, like the
origin of the universe.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the most intimate, the most immediate, in some ways the
most intricate and the most important for our inquiring species
will always be the origin of behavior,'' he writes. Are we born
already programmed to behave in certain ways? Or is all our
behavior learned? These are questions that are explored in Weiner's
very readable, literate and authoritative account.
</P>
<P>
   The most engaging parts of ``Time, Love, Memory'' are the early
chapters in which Weiner introduces Benzer and gives some of the
scientific background. There is an intimacy to the story here that
fades as Weiner proceeds and his subject grows in complexity and
becomes more difficult to manage on the page. In the second half of
the book we almost lose sight of Benzer (who, in any case,
eventually lost interest in studying the genetic origin of
behavior), and we sometimes lose Weiner's narrative thread as well.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, ``Time, Love, Memory'' remains a solid and
absorbing story. If you aren't a biologist, you are likely to learn
a great deal about contemporary biology and the idiosyncratic,
sometimes bizarre ways of quarrelsome, ferociously ambitious
scientists. Weiner has a poetic and philosophical turn of mind, and
he manages to see the almost spiritual implications of the search
for the deepest truths about the nature of life. For example, when
he arrives at the discovery of the gene responsible for the sense
of time in fruit flies, he writes, ``The sense of time, mysterious
for so many centuries, was no longer a mystery that could be
observed only from the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   He continues, ``Qualities that people had always thought of as
somehow floating above the body, apart from the body, as if they
belonged to the realm of the spirit and not of the flesh, as if
they were supernatural, might be mapped right alongside qualities
as mundane as eye pigment.''
</P>
<P>
   When Weiner comes to the genetic basis of memory, he observes
that, in the broadest sense, ``genes themselves are ancestral
memories of life on earth.'' He cites Proust to the effect that
memory is ``a rope let down from heaven to draw me up out of the
abyss of not-being,'' and from there makes an apt comparison:
``Evolution is learning. Species store learning in chromosomes the
way individuals store learning in their brains and societies store
learning in books.''
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the tale is Benzer, a personable, eccentric
polymath. His experiments with fruit flies in the 1960s and '70s
departed from the conventional scientific wisdom, which held that
there was no important genetic basis for human behavior. They also
led the way in the field of behavioral genetics for a generation of
later scientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one way, this is a parable of the strangeness of life,''
Weiner remarks as he embarks on Weiner's story. ``So much
millennial science from such tiny and alien creatures.'' Weiner
goes back in time to summarize the speculations of Gregor Mendel,
the first modern geneticist, and of Thomas Hunt Morgan of Columbia
University, who established the genetic basis of inheritance early
in this century.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this early history is marvelously exciting. But as
science becomes more complicated, Weiner skips over what laymen
might find to be the most interesting details. He writes about
cloning and using enzymes to chop genes and altering their
sequences to find out how they work. But we don't get any colorful
sense of how this work is done, what it looks feels like in the
laboratory. And having had such good descriptions of those things
earlier in the story, we miss them.
</P>
<P>
   The subject remains fascinating all the way through, however,
and Weiner never lapses into a specialist's language. Some of the
best moments are furnished by his descriptions of the ingenious
experiments to determine whether fruit flies could learn. Then
there is the moment when Jeff Hall and Michael Rosbash fix a piece
of broken fly behavior (the loss of the biological clock) by
injecting a gene into an embryo. It was what Hall called a
mini-revolution, and Weiner brings us vividly and reliably there.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `TIME, LOVE, MEMORY: A Great Biologist and His Quest for the
Origins of Behavior'
</P>
<P>
   By Jonathan Weiner
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 300 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $27.50  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
