<SLUG> BC-ARTS-GRANTS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    $1.65 million in arts grants headed to Georgia
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Symphony Orchestra, which saw its grants
from the National Endowment for the Arts tumble 75 percent from
1990 to 1998, has rebounded for a combined $135,000 in 1999 grants,
its highest total in three years.
</P>
<P>
   The newest, a $50,000 grant, is to support ``Building Bridges to
the Community,'' an outreach and educational program that includes
such nontraditional venues as churches and community halls. It's
among 14 Georgia grants totaling $1.65 million _ part of the $58
million final round of 1999 national grants _ to be announced today
at the Woodruff Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   The federal largesse is especially welcome at the ASO, hurt in
recent seasons by a drooping box office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're extremely pleased and honored to get two major NEA
grants in a single year,'' said Allison Vulgamore, ASO managing
director. (An $85,000 gift was announced in December.) ``It
bespeaks our major roles in setting national trends in outreach.''
</P>
<P>
   The Southern Arts Federation, as usual the largest recipient
with a new $769,700 grant, enjoyed a slight increase over 1998 for
a yearly total of $1.1 million. The 1999 grant of $543,000 for the
Georgia Arts Council represents a 12 percent increase over 1998 and
the second increase in a row since the almost one-third cut the
council suffered in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm encouraged,'' said Caroline Leake, executive director of
the council. ``Bill Ivey himself has been in the trenches, and
that's part of why you're seeing more money in the underserved
areas.'' Ivey, chairman of the NEA, was formerly based in Nashville
as head of the Country Music Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has proposed a 50 percent increase in the $98
million NEA budget. Due to a ``winding down in the culture wars,''
in the words of Southern Arts Federation director Jeffery Kesper,
the NEA for the first time in years does not face substantial
resistance from conservatives. Michael Hightower, vice chairman of
the Fulton County Commission and a member of Americans for the
Arts, testified before Congress last week on behalf of the
increase.
</P>
<P>
   WHO'S GETTING WHAT
</P>
<P>
   Here are the new Atlanta- and Georgia-based grants of $25,000 or
higher:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Southern Arts Federation: $769,700. To support tours and
residencies of arts entities in eight states from North Carolina to
Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Georgia Council for the Arts: $543,000. To be distributed by
the council to various arts entities across the state.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Atlanta Symphony Orchestra: $50,000. For the ``Building
Bridges to the Community'' outreach program.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Alternate ROOTS: $50,000. To support residencies and fees for
artists, and publications documenting their activities, in
communities throughout the South.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  7 Stages: $35,000. For the creation of a cash reserve to
offset fluctuations in earned and contributed income.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jomandi Productions: $30,000. For development of a national
board of directors and a feasibility study for the acquisition of a
performance facility.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Valdosta State University: $25,000. To support the position of
a folkorist.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
