<SLUG> BC-WINE-SALES-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERSEAS WINE SALES SET RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BOB NORBERG   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ Overseas wine drinkers have discovered U.S
wines, particularly those produced in California, buying a record
$537 million in U.S. wine last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety percent of the wine exports were from California.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, U.S. wine exports totaled about 72 million gallons,
or $537 million, compared with 22 million gallons, or $98 million,
in 1988. In 1997, overseas wine sales were 60 million gallons,
valued at $426 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a continual increase in the last 10 years,
because of an increase in California marketing and the general
trend in large wine markets to look for other wines to taste,''
said Joe Rollo of the Wine Institute, a San Francisco trade
association. ``California wine in particular has become of interest
overseas.''
</P>
<P>
   Wine Institute President John De Luca predicted that
international sales could reach $650 million this year and more
than $1 billion by 2004. He said a potential trade deal with China
could open a huge untapped market.
</P>
<P>
   The leading market for U.S. wine in 1998 was the United Kingdom,
where exports were valued at $143 million, an increase over the
past year of 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Japan was second at $93 million, an increase of 134 percent,
despite the economic problems that have gripped that country.
</P>
<P>
   Ken-ichi Hori, Wine Institute trade representative in Japan,
said the boom coincides with the emergence of discount wine stores,
which increase competition; news reports about the health effects
of moderate wine consumption, and wine as a symbol of
sophistication.
</P>
<P>
   Sales were $91 million in Canada, $48 million in the
Netherlands, $23 million in Switzerland and $11 million in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is the fourth-largest producer of wine in the
world, and the ninth-largest exporter. Exports, however, account
for a relatively small 12 percent of total production. In
California, 125 wineries produce wine that is sold in 165 different
countries.
</P>
<P>
   (The Santa Rosa, Calif., Press Democrat is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
