<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CHARTER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`60 MINUTES II': RESTRAINT AS A EUPHEMISM IN PSYCHIATRIC
HOSPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.)  
 (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every year, scores of thousands of mentally ill people are
confined at one or another of the dozens of hospitals belonging to
Charter Behavioral Health Systems, the nation's largest chain of
for-profit psychiatric hospitals. About half the patients are
children, whose parents will find little comfort in Wednesday
night's hourlong report on ``60 Minutes II.'' With the help of an
undercover investigator, a hidden camera and some former Charter
employees, CBS News has unearthed evidence of deaths and injuries
of patients and falsification of records.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Bradley begins the report with a horror story: a 16-year-old
boy asphyxiated by a towel wrapped around his face while he was
under ``therapeutic restraint,'' his wrists and ankles strapped and
held immobile. He was the third patient in four months to die while
being ``restrained'' in this Charter hospital, in Greensboro, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The examples caught by a hidden camera in another hospital of a
screaming patient being ``restrained,'' to use that bland word for
an exercise in violence by what look like SWAT teams, are not
likely to find their way into Charter's advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   But the more basic indictment arising from the CBS investigation
goes beyond the occasional, possibly justified use of force.
Low-paid and ill-trained workers are found to be handling patients
without medical supervision; when doctors are available, they
sometimes provide only cursory attention.
</P>
<P>
   The undercover reporter, Terrance Johnson, a licensed social
worker, took a low-paying job at the Charter hospital in Charlotte,
N.C. He records the doings of a nurse who apparently fills out
reports on patients in accord with instructions to emphasize the
negative. Although most Charter workers try to do their jobs
conscientiously, the driving purpose of their employer, some former
employees are convinced, is to collect money from federal programs.
That came to $300 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley is understandably defensive about using the hidden
camera, a tiny device placed in the investigator's eyeglasses. Such
techniques can be troubling, but as Bradley explains, Charter is
not forthcoming about its procedures beyond a rote statement
avowing its compassion, and executives declined to be interviewed
for the program.
</P>
<P>
   June Gibbs-Brown, the inspector general of the federal
Department of Health and Human Services, deplores the scenes of
rough treatment of inmates that Bradley shows her, and her office
has taken action against a few Charter hospitals. But Dr. Dennis
O'Leary, president of the Joint Commission on Accreditation of
Health Care Organizations, which is entrusted with accrediting
psychiatric and other institutions, confesses to not even knowing
about incidents of abuse that have been reported in newspapers. He
tells Bradley, ``Our information pathways need to be improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, CBS News has now provided an information pathway. It
remains to be seen whether the authorities will travel it.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `60 MINUTES II'
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Wednesday night at 9
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 2 in New York) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Produced by David Gelber and Helen Malmgren. Jeff Fager,
executive producer of ``60 Minutes II''; Ed Bradley, correspondent
and anchor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
