<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6185 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-KUNZ-LANDMARK-ART-     04-20 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-KUNZ-LANDMARK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESERVATION CHIC: RESTAURANTS WITH A VIEW OF THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gray Kunz, the four-star chef without portfolio, has
generated nearly as much talk about his search for a space for his
own restaurant as he did while cooking at Lespinasse. Finally, he
is hoping to open in Lever House, the landmark office building on
Park Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Many obstacles remain between him and a sure deal on the former
employee cafeteria and terrace of Lever House, a 1952 edifice with
a glass-curtain facade that changed office building design forever.
Will there be enough room for the kitchen he needs, after the
million-dollar extravaganza he was accustomed to at Lespinasse?
Will the New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission allow him
to cut a door into the side of the building to allow direct access
to the dining room?
</P>
<P>
   Kunz said he knows there is ``added-on difficulty with a
landmarked building, but there's a lot of character and cachet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a landmark space, the rewards are so much better,'' he
said. ``You have a facade, an exterior so wonderful it attracts a
certain clientele that has an eye for that.''
</P>
<P>
   If the negotiations succeed, Kunz will join a growing contingent
of New York restaurateurs who have discovered the advantages of
recycling grand old spaces into culinary pleasure palaces. David
Rockwell, the architect who designed Michael Jordan's: The Steak
House in the landmark Grand Central Terminal, summed up the allure:
``There is something about a space revealing its layers that is a
richer, more exciting experience'' than working in a raw space, he
said. ``You are trading off being able to throw up Sheetrock
wherever you want for an incredible sense of quality of what was
there before. There is a shortage of spaces where the space itself
is the draw.''
</P>
<P>
   The recycling trend began two years ago when Le Cirque 2000
opened in the landmark rooms of the Henry Villard Houses, built in
1887 and now part of the New York Palace Hotel. Adam Tihany's
ultramodern design was controversial. But Jennifer Raab, the
landmarks commission's chairwoman, said: ``Le Cirque did one of the
best preservation jobs in the city. The new things they brought in
are all temporary, and when Adam Tihany's designs are no longer the
rage, a new set of designs will come.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last eight months, more and more owners have realized
that one way to stand out in the blizzard of new restaurants with
similar menus is to be in a landmark building. Tabla and Eleven
Madison Park made news in the Art Deco Metropolitan Life Building,
at Madison Avenue and 24th Street; Bayard's opened in India House,
the former home to the New York Cotton Exchange, built in 1851.
</P>
<P>
   And more are on the way. After years of delay, construction has
finally begun under the Queensboro Bridge on a project that will
include two restaurants. Pier A, the Victorian building near
Battery Park City whose reclamation has been in the works for 10
years, is to open in the fall as a restaurant with incomparable
views of the Statue of Liberty and Ellis Island. A private
apartment in Grand Central is becoming a lounge.
</P>
<P>
   Buildings like these, at ``the monumental end of the spectrum,''
are particularly suited to restaurants, said Dr. James Marston
Fitch, the founder of the Columbia University graduate program in
historic preservation and a partner in Beyer Blinder Belle, the
architectural firm that oversaw the restoration of Grand Central
and Ellis Island. ``It is new wine for old bottles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, developers have had a change of heart and
finally understand that there are substantial tax credits for
restoring landmarks. For landlords, a retail establishment can help
pay for a restoration. ``You can breathe new life into old
buildings by creating a new economic engine,'' Rockwell said.
</P>
<P>
   And the landmarks commission looks with particular favor on
restaurants. ``One of the great things about restaurants is that
they don't call for a lot of division of space, so they keep the
open feeling,'' Ms. Raab said. ``Restaurants often prize the same
features preservationists appreciate, like the ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   As Kunz has discovered, even a relatively new landmark has
irresistible allure. For 50 years, Fitch said, ``the policy was all
old buildings are bad buildings, all new buildings are good. But in
the last 10 years the public hostility to old buildings has turned
to enthusiastic support.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the preservation movement has grown beyond a
fringe element. New York City's 33-year-old landmark law, passed
after the razing of the old Pennsylvania Station, is one of the
strongest in the country, said Peg Breen, president of the New York
Landmarks Conservancy, a nonprofit group that gives financial and
technical help to owners of landmark properties. ``Now there is
more emphasis on buildings that are 30, 40 and 50 years old,'' like
Lever House and the Four Seasons Restaurant, she said. ``In many
instances there is a sense of prestige to own a landmark or to live
in a historic district, and people have seen their property values
maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission has designated 1,400 exteriors and 102 interiors
as landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   As businesses consolidate, particularly banks, more and more
grand spaces have become available. ``The large turn-of-the-century
buildings are perfect for restaurants because volume is a luxury''
in Manhattan, said Tony Goldman, whose company, Goldman Properties,
specializes in restoration. He has opened Wall Street Kitchen and
Bar in the 1907 neo-classical American Bank Note Co. building at 70
Broad St. in the financial district. ``When you have space that is
20 or 25 feet high, there's an aura. There's value in the artistic
quality _ the fabulously carved and elaborate ceilings, grand
columns and craftsmanship that is not available today.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most notable new-old restaurants are in one landmark,
the Metropolitan Life Building. While Tabla has Indian accents,
Eleven Madison Park has retained Art Deco characteristics. The
latter project ``took six months extra and cost 30 percent more
than had been budgeted,'' said Richard Coraine, the director of
operations for Danny Meyer's restaurants, including these. ``The
whole rich history of landmarked buildings is another story to
tell, and there is a certain amount of pride that the building is
important for other reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   Bayard's, in India House at One Hanover Square, is an even more
sensitive re-creation of an original space. The building, in the
Italianate palazzo design, has been a private club since 1914. The
club continues to operate at lunchtime, but Harry Poulakakos, who
owns Harry's at Hanover Square downstairs, and his son, Peter, have
restored the interior, peeling back layers of paint to reveal the
magnificent architecture and mahogany double staircase, and
removing the acoustical tile from the ceilings and linoleum from
the floors.
</P>
<P>
   Dining there is transporting, out of turn-of-the-millennium
Manhattan: you almost hear the rustle of silk damask gowns and feel
the warm glow from the candelabra.
</P>
<P>
   Farther uptown, in Tribeca, Henry Meer has opened City Hall in a
landmark 1861 Italianate building on Duane Street that used to
house a dry-goods wholesaler and was once Public School 10. The
creamy yellow exterior sparkles in sunlight; inside, the dining
room, with its two-story ceilings, has the original cast-iron
columns and support beams, enhanced by historic photographs of New
York lining the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really looking for another restaurant,'' said Meer,
who also owns the Cub Room in Soho. ``But being a passionate New
Yorker, I always wanted a restaurant to be reflective of New York
and have a New York experience.''
</P>
<P>
   At New York Harbor, Pier A is expected to be open by year's end
with a restaurant and banquet rooms; Levy Restaurants of Chicago,
which operates the highly rated Spiaggia there, is negotiating to
operate them. Pier A began life in 1886 as the headquarters of the
docks and ferries department and was a fireboat station before it
was set for demolition to make way for Battery Park City. The metal
and glass structure became a landmark in 1977, saving it, but the
project, which was to take six years, is now in its 10th year. The
budget has ballooned from $18 million to $26 million.
</P>
<P>
   At Grand Central, the Campbell Apartment, a hidden jewel of a
Florentine palazzo, is being renovated as a cocktail lounge by Mark
Grossich, who calls it ``a one-of-a-kind space in a one-of-a-kind
space.'' From the 1920s to the '40s, it was the office of a wealthy
businessman, John W. Campbell. The apartment, where he and his wife
entertained guests, had a pipe organ and grand piano. ``It gives
you a sense of how large a swashbuckling tycoon lived at the
time,'' said Grossich, who also owns Bar and Books.
</P>
<P>
   The organ and piano are gone, but the rest of the apartment is
being restored to its former grandeur, with painted beamed
ceilings, a huge stone fireplace, an enormous leaded-glass window,
even gargoyles. Grossich hopes to open by the end of spring.
</P>
<P>
   The landmark revival is also renewing activity at the
long-stalled Bridgemarket, the vaulted space beneath the Queensboro
Bridge, leased by the London-based Conran Holdings and Joel Kissin,
the owner of Guastavino's Inc., which will run two glass-front
restaurants and two Conran stores. After 22 years of delays,
workmen are finally cleaning the tiled ceiling, which soars 37
feet.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurants are scheduled to open by year's end. One of
them, Guastavino, at ground level, will be like Conran's Quaglino
restaurant in London, a grill with rotisserie food. The other, Club
Guastavino, a more luxurious French-accented version of Bibendum,
also in London, will be on a mezzanine, where a party of two could
easily leave behind $200. The names honor the architect Rafael
Guastavino, a 19th-century Spanish immigrant who invented vaulted
tiled ceilings, one of which can be seen in the Oyster Bar at Grand
Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go into these landmarked spaces, you get a definite
sense of place, of continuity with the past,'' said Ms. Breen, of
the Landmarks Conservancy. ``Places that give you a sense of the
past, and an understanding that there have been generations before
you help to ground you and help to make you feel a part of New
York.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
