<HEADLINE>
PERSISTENT FOX 
HAIRY-CHESTED HISTORY 
ANIMATION IMITATING LIFE
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fox may not pull off the upset it hoped for this season, beating
NBC for the top ratings position among viewers between the ages of
18 and 49, the category that both use to determine which network is
really television's leader.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox did beat NBC in that category last week, for its sixth
triumph over NBC this season, its most victories ever. It was also
the first time that Fox managed to beat NBC this season without
relying on some special sports event, like the World Series or
Super Bowl, or some slash-and-burn video special, like ``When Good
Pets Go Bad.''
</P>
<P>
   In one of the many ``if you can't beat 'em, join 'em''
developments of this season, NBC is now the network boosting its
ratings base with vivid video footage, like a man being sucked up
into a jet engine. The network's new Wednesday night entry,
``World's Most Amazing Videos,'' is apparently pulling in many of
the fans of that kind of Fox fare. Last week it was the
14th-highest-rated show of the week among young adult male viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even with that jet-propelled new addition, NBC again
showed that when its powerhouse Thursday night lineup is in repeats
it is vulnerable to attack from Fox. But the real secret to Fox's
gaining on NBC is the strength of its new animated shows.
</P>
<P>
   Both ``Futurama'' on Tuesday and ``Family Guy'' on Sunday are
putting down roots with the male viewers who are the core of Fox's
strength. On Tuesday, where Fox has been struggling, ``Futurama''
posted the best ratings for Fox of the season, managing to finish
13th of 129 shows last week among those younger male viewers.
</P>
<P>
   In the more hospitable (for Fox) surroundings of Sunday,
``Family Guy'' made a strong impression by finishing second only to
``The X-Files'' among male viewers between 18 and 49.
</P>
<P>
   Fox still trails NBC by a little less than three-tenths of a
rating point for the season in the age group. But that will be all
but impossible to make up because the May ratings sweep begins in
two weeks, and NBC will be fully armed with original episodes of
its Thursday shows, as well as a strong lineup of movies and
specials.
</P>
<P>
   But the animated series, if they continue to grow, may give Fox
a new power base from which to challenge NBC next season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter
</P>
<P>
   The War Channel?
</P>
<P>
   Some say the History Channel ought to be called the War Channel,
or perhaps the Murder-and-Mayhem Channel, because of its fondness
for programs about war, the military, fighter planes, guns, secret
police forces, dastardly crimes and prisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so far from that,'' protested Abbe Raven, the network's
senior vice president for programming. ``Military history is
important, but look at our new shows: It's probably less than 20
percent'' war-related.
</P>
<P>
   The network has tried to broaden its definition of history for
its 1999-2000 season schedule, which includes specials on the
history of basketball and of advertising, as well as ``History's
Lost and Found,'' about famous artifacts, and a series on natural
disasters called ``The Wrath of God.''
</P>
<P>
   The three most popular programs in the channel's history were
about the Hell's Angels and San Quentin and Folsom prisons, in that
order. But its most-watched night of the week, which is Sunday,
features ``Tales of the Gun'' and three programs related to the
military and to espionage.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for focusing on such topics is that they are
particularly popular with men. The network's prime-time audience is
roughly 70 percent male. Adult male viewers are considered
especially valuable to advertisers because they don't watch as much
television as other groups and are difficult to reach.
</P>
<P>
   Military history will remain a staple, ``but we're broadening,''
Ms. Raven said. ``The 50th anniversary of the Korean War is coming
up next year, and we'll do a definitive miniseries on it, and very
proudly, but we're also expanding with things like `History's
Mysteries,' for example, with Arthur Kent joining us as host for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The network recently began placing billboards or signs in sports
arenas and stadiums. Indeed, during retirement ceremonies for Wayne
Gretzky at Madison Square Garden in New York on Sunday night, the
hockey superstar was positioned in such a way that much of the
television coverage showed a huge History Channel banner in the
background.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawrie Mifflin
</P>
<P>
   Spade's New Cartoon
</P>
<P>
   Even NBC has noticed the strength of animation. The network has
commissioned its first original prime-time animated series, a
skewed take on family comedy, created by one of NBC's stars, David
Spade of ``Just Shoot Me.''
</P>
<P>
   The animated show is tentatively called ``Sammy,'' after one of
two main characters in the show, a ne'er-do-well deadbeat Dad named
Sammy who returns after 17 years to reunite with the three sons he
abandoned as toddlers.
</P>
<P>
   Spade had no trouble concocting this situation, he said, because
it more or less exactly parallels his own experience as a son.
</P>
<P>
   Spade, who conceded he was ``sort of working things out
psychologically'' by creating the series, said he never told the
animators that the situation was this close to his real life. When
the initial drawings came in, ``everybody looked so much like the
real people it freaked me out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the show began to germinate during his days on
``Saturday Night Live,'' he said, when he thought he would like to
do a skit in which he could do both his own voice and his father's.
Since he also wanted to be able to flash back to childhood scenes,
animation seemed the right way to go, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the series the father takes the three sons to the park, sends
them all out for long passes during a football game, and then takes
off.
</P>
<P>
   Admitting that there may be a bit more reality to this than in
most cartoons, Spade said he believed ``a lot of kids today are in
broken homes and they'll relate to the feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   As for how his father feels about it, Spade said: ``He sort of
likes the attention, but it's going to get ugly fast. No, really, I
think he has to grant a little leniency. I think by us growing up
this way, he has to bite his tongue a little bit and say, `All
right, this is what you want to do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   NBC plans to add ``Sammy'' to its schedule in January.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Carter
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
