 CHRON   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Food section 
 plans to move Tuesday, April 20, on the New York Times New 
 Service wire. Questions? Please call Holly Ocasio Rizzo at 
 415-777-8811. 
 &HT;       
   
 EDITORS NOTE: This week, The San Francisco Chronicle introduces 
 ``Learning to Cook,'' a new column by Marion Cunningham. Widely 
 known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks, 
 Cunningham has begun a crusade to revive the dying art of home 
 cooking.  
   
 Her column, which will be available regularly through the New 
 York Times News Service, teaches novice cooks the basics of 
 working in the kitchen and preparing recipes. Please look for it 
 when The Chronicle's food stories move on Tuesdays.  
   
 Today, we bring you a profile of Cunningham, who teaches new 
 cooks in her Walnut Creek, Calif., home. We also bring you her 
 first column.  
   
   
Walnut Creek, Calif. _  MARION _  Consider the case of the recently
divorced CBS executive. Stumped by a tarte tatin recipe instructing
him to toss sliced apples in a bowl, he stood on one side of his
kitchen and threw them into a bowl across the room. He thought the
tossing action somehow aerated the fruit. How about the woman who
stared blankly at a dairy case, searching in vain for a package of
softened butter? &HT;    Laugh if you like, but don't expect food expert and author
Marion Cunningham to join you. To her, these culinary fiascoes are
very real examples of a larger issue: America is forgetting how to
cook. With sidebars: Top 10 Marionisms, List of Basic Kitchen
Equipment, Recipes for Beginners, Miniprofiles of Novice Cooks.
MOVING IN TWO TAKES. 
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
