<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, April 21, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The seeds for a major spring storm system developing over the
Middle West on Wednesday were sown Tuesday as a narrow ribbon of
Pacific jet stream winds, with speeds in excess of 160 mph, dove
southeast toward the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, showers and thunderstorms, fed by an increasingly
speedy channel of moist winds from the Gulf of Mexico, will douse
parts of the central Plains in response to a compact but potent jet
stream disturbance ejecting east ahead of a developing low pressure
system over southwest Kansas. A few storms could become severe.
Recurrent rains will produce rainfalls to 2 inches or more from
northeast Kansas and eastern Nebraska. Moderate to heavy rains will
spread to northern Missouri, southern Iowa and northwestern
Illinois. The risk of flooding will be heightened in areas where
showers and thunderstorms repeatedly pass over the same regions.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate rains will fall over parts of southern South Dakota and
northwest Nebraska as moist winds from the east ascend the sloping
terrain. Accumulating snows will fall in the mountains of Wyoming
as moist winds wrap westward around the expansive Kansas low.
</P>
<P>
   Isolated severe thunderstorms are possible in west Texas along a
north-south line that marks the boundary between humid air from the
Gulf of Mexico and dry air from the plateaus of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a batch of showers will race eastward over parts of
the northern Middle Atlantic states as a warm front south of the
region teams with a jet stream disturbance to lift relatively moist
air.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Alaska Volcano
</P>
<P>
   At the far end of the Alaskan peninsula, a volcano erupted
Monday afternoon spewing an ash cloud over Unimak island. The plume
of ash and smoke prompted warnings for residents near Shishaldin
volcano to stay indoors until the ash fallout ceased. Volcanoes
have been known to disrupt worldwide weather patterns due to their
fine ash particles reaching into the stratosphere and being carried
around the globe by high level winds. However, the gelid atmosphere
of southwestern Alaska limits the ascent of a volcanic cloud and
this eruption's effects will only be noticed by nearby residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
