<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6193 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARION-SFCHRON &LR;      04-20 1974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARION-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: This profile introduces Marion Cunningham's new 
 column, ``Learning to Cook,'' which will move regularly on the 
 New York Times News Service wire in the regular San Francisco 
 Chronicle food package. This profile package is moving in two 
 takes. Please also look for MARION SIDE. And don't miss the 
 first column, LEARN TO COOK, also moving today. 
 &HT;     This take includes ``Top 10 Marionisms'' in optional trim at 
 the bottom.  
   
   
 CHAMPION OF HOME COOKING: Marion Cunningham fights to save a 
 fading art  
   
   
 By Kim Severson  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; WALNUT CREEK, Calif. &LR;  _ Consider the case of the recently divorced
CBS executive from Los Angeles.
<P>
   Stumped by a tarte tatin recipe instructing him to toss sliced
apples in a bowl, he stood on one side of his kitchen and threw
them into a bowl across the room. He thought the tossing action
somehow aerated the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   How about the Bay Area woman who stared blankly at a dairy case,
searching in vain for a package of softened butter?
</P>
<P>
   Or another who substituted cornstarch for flour, figuring the
two looked enough alike that the switch would work?
</P>
<P>
   Laugh if you like, but don't expect food expert and author
Marion Cunningham to join you. To her, these culinary fiascoes are
very real examples of a larger issue: America is forgetting how to
cook.
</P>
<P>
   At 77, the woman who wrote the Fannie Farmer cookbooks and spent
11 years at James Beard's side easily could rest on her reputation
as one of the America's grande dames of the kitchen. Instead, she
has embarked on a passionate crusade that may turn out to be one of
the most important culinary contributions to the 20th century: She
is teaching people who are completely lost in the kitchen how to
cook.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham believes the simple art of cooking and sharing food
is an essential part of a healthy society. But the skills are
fading.
</P>
<P>
   Some may argue otherwise, pointing out the proliferation of
cookware stores and the rise of the restaurant culture as proof
that America is in love with food.
</P>
<P>
   But Cunningham isn't talking about eating out or about people
with well-equipped, well-used kitchens. She's talking about the
newly divorced &UR;  &LR; father or the harried parent or the twentysomething
who grew up in a house where take-out food was the norm. Her
targets are men and women who don't have the time or the confidence
to cook regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking is important, she says, because the table is the modern
tribal fire, the place where stories are shared, families are
created and culture is passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The catalyst for social interaction is cooking and eating
together,'' Cunningham says. Serving food family-style teaches a
child to share, to leave something for the next person. Sitting
next to someone sparks interaction and teaches people how to have
conversations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone cooks at home, even if they're not very good, the
people they share it with take something with them when the meal is
over,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Given that philosophy, it's easy to understand why Cunningham
was so concerned about the apple-tossing executive. His story
prompted her to seek out similar tales. About two years ago, after
listening to an eye surgeon read from a cookbook and confess
ignorance about instructions that seemed simple to Cunningham, she
decided to dedicate herself to teaching the kitchen novice the art
of cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Few others are as qualified for such a quest. In the 1970s,
James Beard, the dean of American cooking, handpicked Cunningham as
his assistant. She went on to write six books and teach all over
the country and in Paris. She is regularly sought out as a source
in food media and a guest on panels with colleagues such as Julia
Child and Chez Panisse founder Alice Waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she gets it exactly right,'' Waters says. ``She's
talking about the good feelings that come from sharing food at the
table. It's not about fueling yourself. It's about connecting as
human beings. That's a terribly important ritual that is missing in
our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham set about her task by ferreting out people who knew
so little about cooking that, to them, ``blanch'' meant the female
lead in ``A Streetcar Named Desire.'' She found her first group
when she asked for volunteers from the 450 people who attended a
food seminar panel she was on.
</P>
<P>
   For 11/2 years, in batches of six or seven, students met in the
comfortable kitchen of her Walnut Creek home to make three dishes
each week. At the end of each class, they sat down and ate their
creations together. Cunningham taught them how to chop an onion,
how to navigate in the grocery store _ even how to clean the
kitchen efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, the students, who immediately took to Cunningham's
twinkling, gentle approach, taught her what they needed to know.
What does the phrase ``dot with butter'' mean? How do you cook
something until golden? How can flimsy egg whites be ``folded''
into batter? They showed her why recipes were confusing and shared
their bewilderment at simple tasks, like picking out the right sort
of rice at the grocery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I learned more from them than they did from me,''
Cunningham says.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by the success her students were achieving in the
kitchen, she compiled the experiences into a new book called
``Learning to Cook With Marion Cunningham,'' (Alfred A. Knopf,
$29.95, due out May 2). It's already getting good previews.
Publishers Weekly this month gave it a star, designating the book
as a new work of unusual interest and merit.
</P>
<P>
   The book has more than 150 recipes, with every step spelled out
in breezy language, and more than 100 accompanying photographs. And
although many of the book's recipes are simple _ scrambled eggs,
for example _ some allow the new cook to produce table-dazzlers,
like roast leg of lamb or shrimp curry.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham manages to get inside the head of the novice cook,
understanding befuddlement at something as seemingly simple as
dredging meat in flour. And it's all done with tremendous respect
for the beginner.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a true teacher. She's has so much joy in what she does,
and she just wants to share it,'' says Julie Scharmer, one of
Cunningham's novices and a woman who used to equate cooking with
chores like vacuuming.
</P>
<P>
   To understand what kept adults from the kitchen, Cunningham
turned to her experience teaching children to cook. But she found
that adults have something kids don't: fear of failure.
</P>
<P>
   To succeed in teaching adults, she reasoned, she would have to
address that fear. So Cunningham looked at her own. She recalled
how aggravated and anxious she was trying to use her new computer,
and realized that the language of hard drives and modems was as
foreign to her as the language of the kitchen was to her students.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham found lots of parallels. Take shopping, for example.
Her novice cooks were as lost in the grocery as she would be in a
computer store. Before they took her class, many only shopped once
or twice a month because the experience was so frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the first classes centered on three-hour field trips to
the grocery with lots of discussion about how and what to buy. Once
her students became comfortable selecting ingredients, they
understood that the success of a dish begins with the confidence to
pick the best _ and the correct _ ingredients at the store.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Cunningham set about teaching basic skills. Even that
proved challenging because adults were so concerned with doing
something wrong. Cunningham would show them a simple knife
technique _ like tucking their fingers under when holding food to
cut _ and they would get frustrated by the food's appearance and
how they held the knife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't fret about doing everything so it looks like Jacques
Pepin,'' she would tell them. ``Just get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Students also had no idea how to determine serving sizes and how
much food to cook. Leftovers were terrifying. Cunningham, who
enjoys the creative use of leftovers, converted them to her way of
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home cooking is about having to make something out of what you
have...of making yesterday's food taste very good.''
</P>
<P>
   She taught her students some of her favorite tricks. Bake two
chickens instead of one and have the second for another meal later
in the week. Find recipes, like the olive-oil-based green sauce in
today's recipe collection, that can be used on a salad one day,
pasta the next an even a baked potato another.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the matter of recipes themselves. Students froze
in the face of long ingredient lists and techniques that seemed as
convoluted as building a car engine from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   So Cunningham broke things into stages. She believes the best
recipes have only five ingredients _ and two of them are salt and
pepper.
</P>
<P>
   ``What people don't realize is that the recipe is just a rough
guide to a certain destination. There are many variations along the
way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Those variations depend on a skill she says isn't hard to
develop: critical tasting. She starts with lemonade, teaching
students that adjusting the balance of sweet to sour is critical
tasting at its essence.
</P>
<P>
   She also taught &UR;  &LR; them how to make simple food that would produce
big results. Her baking powder biscuits, one of the first things
her students made in the oven, were just the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they look in the window and see that little blob of dough
become this wonderful golden, puffy biscuit, it boosts their
confidence immediately,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The look in the eyes of a student who is peering at his or her
first batch of biscuits is reward enough for the teacher _ as long
as the student brings the biscuits to table and shares them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very tempting when we are old to become a missionary, to
see the world as lacking,'' she says. ``I really don't want to be
guilty of that. I don't want to be preachy. But I wish there were a
national law that made everyone cook steadily for two months. Then,
if they don't like it, they can quit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Top 10 Marion-isms &QL; 
 &QL; 
Author and cooking instructor Marion Cunningham uses the following
tips to help new cooks. These ``Marion-isms'' are based on a list
prepared by cooking student Jamie Jobb.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``When cooking, there is one main rule: Taste, taste and &LR; 
 &UR; taste again.'' &LR;  Problems with a recipe often can be remedied while
preparing a dish. It's much harder, if not impossible, to tweak
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The oven is our friend.''  &LR; You don't need to watch over
something if it's in the oven. Use the time to enjoy your dinner
guests.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``With each dish, try to achieve one taste.''  &LR; Too many
ingredients result in a culinary cacophony.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Your hands remember things because they're closer to the &LR; 
 &UR; ingredients.''  &LR; Don't be timid about touching the food you cook.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``There are no substitutes, except when you are forced by &LR; 
 &UR; fate to substitute.''  &LR; If you do substitute, keep track of what
you're changing so you can replicate the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Butter will smooth out sharp tastes and rough edges.'' &LR;  Use
butter as a flavor tool.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``No matter what the recipe, things can change.''  &LR; Slight
differences in ingredients, room temperature, humidity, lunar
gravitational pulls, solar flares or other unknown conditions can
affect how a dish turns out. So always taste as you go and make
note of any changes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Salt and sugar are instruments of flavor.''  &LR; They can help
marry ingredients in a recipe. They're usually best used when the
dish is cooking, not after.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Home food is not restaurant food.''  &LR; You don't have sous
chefs and busboys in your kitchen, so keep it simple.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Your attitude comes through the food.''  &LR; If cooking a
particular dish is true drudgery, don't do it. Cook what you like
to cook.
</P>
</TEXT>
