<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXTRA-BITTER CHOCOLATE  
 TO SAVE THE PARSLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How is extra-bittersweet chocolate different from regular
bittersweet, and where can I buy it?
</P>
<P>
   A. Chocolate sweetness is determined by the ratio of cacao
solids to sugar. Unsweetened baking chocolate is 100 percent cacao
solids, with no sugar. Bittersweet and semisweet chocolate are 35
percent to 60 percent cacao solids, 65 percent to 40 percent sugar
(although some chocolates also contain an emulsifier, at less than
1 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Extra-bittersweet chocolate (also called extra-bitter) usually
has 67 percebt to 70 percent cacao, and the rest sugar. Pastry
chefs prefer it for its fuller, more intense flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Most specialty stores and many large supermarkets sell Valrhona,
Lindt and Scharffen Berger brands. The Sweet Life, 63 Hester
Street, (212) 598-0092, fills mail orders; 3.5-ounce bars of
Valrhona and Lindt are $2.99 each, and Scharffen Berger is $9 a
pound.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Whenever I buy celery, parsley or scallions for a recipe, I
wind up throwing most of them out. Can I freeze them, or store them
better?
</P>
<P>
   A. Forget freezing _ it makes these vegetables flabby and
flavorless. Scallions and parsley keep well when immersed, root or
stem end down, in a glass of water in the refrigerator. Or they can
be wrapped in a damp paper or dish towel, put in a plastic bag and
stored in the vegetable crisper. They should last about a week.
</P>
<P>
   Celery also benefits from a damp-towel wrap and a home in the
vegetable drawer, but you can just store it in the plastic bag it's
sold in, or in your own plastic bag. Either way, the vegetable
crisper will help it keep its snap for up to two weeks. Even if the
outer stalks are slightly brown and withered, the inner ones may be
fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 1807EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6201 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUICKCOOK-SFCHRON &LR;      04-20 1564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUICKCOOK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Here is a recipe to make on the weekend, with 
 enough leftovers to use throughout the week in two other recipes 
 plus suggested ideas for other dishes. Recipes follow, plus 
 suggestions in optional trim.  
   
   
 THE WEEKEND COOK: Bulgur Stands In for Pasta, Rice, Potatoes  
   
   
 By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  As grains go, bulgur wheat is among the easiest to
prepare: Soak it in liquid, and soon the grains swell to a
chewiness that makes a pleasant base for numerous dishes.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even with this kind of ease, you can save even more time during
the week by preparing bulgur on the weekend and refrigerating it
for later. Bulgur's resilient texture and nutty flavor keep up to
five days.
</P>
<P>
   Most people associate bulgur with grain salads like tabbouleh.
But it's good, too, in a salad of finely chopped grilled
vegetables, nuggets of cheese and a pungent vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   We make the most of bulgur, however, when we also consider it
for hot dishes instead of rice, potatoes or pasta. Even when bulgur
is cooked after soaking, it retains texture.
</P>
<P>
   The accompanying recipes and ideas explore bulgur's hot
possibilities. The Asian-flavored weekend casserole is testimony to
bulgur's versatility with seasonings. The recipe pairing bulgur
with vermicelli and sausage may sound odd, but it is in the same
grain-cum-pasta vein as Rice-a-Roni and the Jewish dish known as
kasha varnishkas. The fresh and very springlike entree soup is
ridiculously easy and shows bulgur as a good alternative to soup
pasta.
</P>
<P>
   When you want a nutritious grain with good texture, versatility,
ease of preparation and convenience, think bulgur. And think about
heating it up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MASTER RECIPE: BASIC BULGUR WHEAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   7 cups water
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   4 cups bulgur wheat
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the water and salt in a medium-size saucepan over high
heat; bring to a boil.
</P>
<P>
   Place the bulgur wheat in a large bowl and pour the boiling
water over it; stir briefly. Let stand, stirring occasionally,
until the bulgur is chewy and almost all the water has been
absorbed, about 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the bulgur in a colander for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve 4 cups bulgur for the Weekend Recipe. Cool, cover and
refrigerate the remaining bulgur for use throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 12 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER 1/2 CUP: &LR;   &LR; 100 calories, &LR;   &LR; 3 g protein, 22 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 0 g fat (0 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 134 mg &LR; 
 &LR; sodium, 5 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKEND RECIPE: ASIAN-FLAVORED HALIBUT-BULGUR CASSEROLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   21/2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound shiitake mushrooms, stemmed, caps cut into 3/8-inch
thick slices
</P>
<P>
   10 large garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce fresh ginger, peeled and finely grated
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   4 cups prepared bulgur (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 halibut fillets (about 21/2 pounds)
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces baby spinach leaves, rinsed and drained
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 500 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 11/2 tablespoons of the oil in a large saute pan. Add the
mushrooms and saute over medium-high heat, stirring frequently,
until they are glossy and start to brown, about 3 minutes. Add 8
cloves' worth of the minced garlic and all of the grated ginger.
Saute, stirring constantly, for about 1 minute. Add the water and
boil until the liquid is reduced by half, about 2 minutes. Add the
sherry, vinegar and soy sauce; boil for 1 minute. Add the bulgur
and toss until heated through.
</P>
<P>
   Spread half of the bulgur in a casserole large enough to hold
the fish snugly. Lightly season the fish with salt and pepper.
Place the fillets over the bulgur. Spread the remaining bulgur over
the fillets. Cover tightly.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 16 to 20 minutes, or until the fillets are done.
</P>
<P>
   While the fish bakes, heat the remaining 1 tablespoon oil in a
large saute pan over medium-high heat. Add the remaining garlic and
saute, stirring frequently, until barely golden, about 3 minutes.
Add the spinach and toss until it is wilted, about 1 minute. Season
with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the fish to dinner plates. Spoon some of the bulgur
around each fillet and more on top. Top each fillet with a mound
spinach.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 630 calories, &LR;   &LR; 69 g protein, 51 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 16 g fat (2 g saturated), 91 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 1,241
mg sodium, 12 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: BULGUR &AMP; VERMICELLI WITH SAUSAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Boiling the sausage helps rid it of excess fat.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound reduced-fat hot Italian sausage links
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil &QL; 
2 large onions, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 pound medium-small button mushrooms, quartered
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup white wine or chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces vermicelli or capellini, broken into 2-inch lengths,
boiled until al dente, drained
</P>
<P>
   5 cups prepared bulgur (from Master Recipe), at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Prick the sausages with the tip of a sharp knife. Place them in
a large, heavy saucepan with water to just cover. Bring to a boil
over high heat. Boil for 5 minutes. Drain.
</P>
<P>
   Return the sausages to the saucepan and saute, turning once,
until both sides are golden, about 3 minutes total. Often this is
possible without extra oil. If the bottom of the pan starts to
burn, add a little oil.
</P>
<P>
   When the sausages are browned, remove them from the pan and cut
into medium dice; set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Add the oil to the pan and place over high heat. When the oil
ripples, add the onions and mushrooms and saute, stirring
frequently, until the mushrooms are browned, about 5 minutes.
Deglaze with the wine or broth, scraping up the browned bits on the
bottom of the pan. Stir in the parsley and oregano.
</P>
<P>
   Add the cooked vermicelli, stirring to separate the strands. Add
the sausage and bulgur, tossing thoroughly until the mixture is
hot.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 555 calories, &LR;   &LR; 27 g protein, 73 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 19 g fat (4 g saturated), 33 mg cholesterol, 745 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 15 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: VEGETABLE-BULGUR SOUP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This soup is light and fresh. Wine adds a slight edge to the
broth, but it may be omitted, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 large carrots, cut into paper-thin rounds
</P>
<P>
   2 cups prepared bulgur (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   10 asparagus spears, thinly sliced on the diagonal
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch watercress, leaves and tender stems only
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch scallions (including green tops), trimmed, thinly sliced
on the diagonal
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the broth and wine in a large saucepan; bring to a boil
over high heat. Season with salt if the broth is unsalted. Add the
carrots and bulgur; simmer for 1 minute. Add the asparagus and
simmer for 30 seconds. Add the watercress and scallions; heat until
they wilt, about 30 seconds. Season with pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 11 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CUP: &LR;   &LR; 70 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 13 g carbohydrate, 0 g &LR; 
 &LR; fat (0 g saturated), 1 mg cholesterol, 61 mg sodium, 3 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; More Ideas for Leftovers &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
With a pot of prepared bulgur in the fridge, the following ideas
are possibilities for mid-week meals:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Poultry Dressing. &LR;  Saute a generous amount of garlic and onions
in olive oil. Add raisins, prepared bulgur, chopped fresh mint and
lemon juice to taste. Season with salt and pepper. Use as a
dressing for chicken or pop it into a casserole, cover and
microwave until heated through.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bulgur Primavera. &LR;  Substituting bulgur for pasta in this dish,
aim for double the amount of bulgur to vegetables. Saute finely
diced onions until golden. Add julienned carrots and red peppers,
and asparagus and scallions that have been finely sliced on the
diagonal; saute for 20 seconds. Add 1/2 cup chicken broth, a
handful of frozen defrosted peas and chopped fresh dill and mint;
simmer for 30 seconds. Add prepared bulgur; toss until it is heated
through. Add toasted pine nuts; toss thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bulgur-Lentil Salad. &LR;  Aim for triple the amount of bulgur to
lentils. Marinate halved cherry tomatoes, diced radishes, diced
cucumbers and diced scallions for 15 minutes in a pungent
vinaigrette that is well seasoned with salt and pepper. Toss the
mixture with cooked lentils and prepared bulgur. Mound the mixture
on a platter. Toss diced avocado, crumbled feta cheese and coarsely
chopped cilantro in a little more vinaigrette. Spoon over the
bulgur salad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bulgur Grape Leaves. &LR;  Aim for triple the amount of bulgur to
lamb. Saute minced garlic until it begins to change color. Add
finely ground lamb and saute, stirring constantly to break up the
meat into tiny pieces, until the lamb is no longer pink. Add
prepared bulgur, chopped dill, salt, pepper, cumin and lemon juice.
Use as a filling for grape leaves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bulgur-Berry Breakfast. &LR;  Hull and slice strawberries, combine
them with blueberries and raspberries and toss with a little sugar.
Set aside for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon over a bowl of prepared bulgur. Sprinkle with a little
sugar, if desired. Pour cream, half-and-half or milk of choice over
all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
