<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6202 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAGOUTS-ART-NYT &LR;      04-20 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAGOUTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RITE OF SPRING: VEGETABLE RAGOUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Unlike putting asparagus on the menu in August or December, a
vice some chefs can't seem to shake, real spring vegetables can be
served for a limited season. Some, like ramps and fresh morels and
fiddlehead ferns, are pleasures as fleeting as daffodils in the
park, and New York chefs are making the most of them by assembling
what amounts to bouquets in a soup plate.
</P>
<P>
   Spring vegetable ragouts are the dish of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Even at Michael Jordan's: The Steak House, a bastion of beef,
customers are ordering David Walzog's warm ragout of spring
vegetables in a celery cream sauce. Not instead of the steak, but
before it.
</P>
<P>
   Dishes like this are replacing winter's sturdy roasted roots.
The key ingredients, sweet young things like spring garlic and baby
onions, are in the market only a month or two. Asparagus, baby
carrots, fava beans and garden peas sustain a longer stretch, but
they, too, seem most suited to this season.
</P>
<P>
   Suppliers say demand for these symbols of spring is up 20 to 25
percent over last year among chefs, who get a jump on home cooks
and receive early shipments. But produce markets are now starting
to carry items like fresh morels, although at inflated
first-of-the-season prices, and tender, mild spring garlic, which
has not be dried. And the more assertive wild leeks called ramps
are already turning up in the Greenmarkets.
</P>
<P>
   The fricassee at Payard Patisserie and Bistro, which combines
ramps, morels and spring garlic, is no great challenge for the home
cook, nor is Bill Telepan's delicate ragout at Judson Grill. The
ragout at the new Maison restaurant is a simple combination of
ramps, white asparagus and peas, but at Jo Jo, 27 vegetables are
cooked separately before coming together on the plate. Cena's
ragout of spring vegetables is in a sauce of Vidalia onions, those
erstwhile spring treats, while Veritas tops off a spring vegetable
fricassee with a splash of truffle oil.
</P>
<P>
   For the dinner he is preparing next week at the James Beard
Foundation, Georges Perrier of Le Bec Fin in Philadelphia will
combine morels and asparagus in a sauce enriched with cream.
</P>
<P>
   Put all those ingredients in the hands of a chef and one thing
is certain: out comes the butter. As virtuous as a spring vegetable
ragout may sound, especially with bathing suit season looming, its
flavor invariably depends on a gloss of sweet fresh butter.
</P>
<P>
   Laurent Gras' lightly sauteed early vegetables with watercress
at Peacock Alley is the exception; it's finished only with olive
oil. Obviously, without the fat you might as well serve crudites.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important as butter or olive oil is the cooking. Every
one of these vegetables needs a different amount of time over heat.
Cooking them to their own specifications may seem like one step too
many, after rinsing, peeling, trimming and shelling, but for one
short season, the result is worth the effort.
</P>
<P>
   SPRING VEGETABLE RAGOUT
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Bill Telepan, Judson Grill
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches baby carrots, peeled, with 1/2 inch of stem left
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches baby onions or scallions, trimmed, leaving 1 inch of
green
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces small creamer potatoes, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   1 medium head fennel, trimmed, quartered, cored and sliced
1/4-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups well-seasoned vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shelled peas (1/2 pound in pod)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup shelled, peeled fresh fava beans (10 ounces in pod)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound asparagus, peeled and cut in 1/2-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh chives
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place 3 tablespoons butter in 3-quart saucepan over medium
heat. When melted, add carrots, onions, potatoes, fennel and a
generous pinch of salt. Cover and cook 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add vegetable stock and bring to a simmer. Add a little more
salt, peas, fava beans and asparagus and simmer 5 minutes covered.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add remaining butter in bits, then chives and parsley. Check
seasoning and serve in shallow soup plates.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   FRICASSEE OF MORELS, RAMPS AND SPRING GARLIC
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Philippe Bertineau, Payard Patisserie and Bistro
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces fresh morels
</P>
<P>
   3 heads spring garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch small ramps (about 30)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   1 sprig fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, finely minced
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons minced flat-leaf parsley.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place morels in a bowl of water and soak 15 minutes. Drain
morels and cut off stems. Trim stems from spring garlic down to 1/2
inch, remove roots and peel off outer layer of skin. Slice garlic
heads thin. Rinse ramps very well, cut off roots and peel off outer
layer of skin.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place 1 tablespoon butter in a medium-size skillet over low
heat, add morels and cook about 2 minutes. Add crushed garlic,
thyme and shallot and cook a few more minutes, until morels have
softened and given up their liquid. Remove garlic and thyme, season
with salt and pepper and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   3. In another skillet, melt 1 tablespoon butter over medium-low
heat, add spring garlic and a pinch of salt and cook, covered,
about 5 minutes. Move garlic around so it does not brown. Add the
ramps and a tablespoon of water, cover and cook 4 minutes longer,
until tender. Season to taste with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   4. Add morels and their liquid to spring garlic and ramps,
increase heat to medium-high, saute briefly and add another
tablespoon of butter. Check seasonings, add parsley and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
