<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC-FABB-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related businesses 
 more than a half century old.  
   
   
 BAY AREA CLASSICS: From Speakeasy to Bar to Restaurant  
   
 By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 REDWOOD CITY, Calif. _  It grew from a speakeasy, it reportedly
housed the first off-track betting machine in California, but in
its respectable old age, Fabbro's now prides itself on being one of
the area's oldest restaurants.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fabbro's Restaurant and Bar has been a family business since
1933, when Redwood City was a small rural port that served a
growing logging business in the nearby hills.
</P>
<P>
   A few years earlier, George and Mary Fabbro, immigrants from the
Friuli region in northern Italy, had shuttered a speakeasy that
they had operated from their home. In 1933, they opened a bar in a
building George had purchased farther south on El Camino Real. They
ran the bar with George's brothers and lived in a flat upstairs.
Eventually, the bar grew into a restaurant and bar, which is still
located in the building George bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather liked to drink, party, gamble, go to the track
_ he was a real carouser,'' Michael Fabbro says fondly. He's the
third generation to run the business.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Fabbros, George's penchant for gambling led to
his setting up the first off-track betting machine in the state.
George installed a bookie in his living room upstairs so his
customers could walk up from the bar and place bets. When the
authorities objected to the bookie in the living room, George built
a shed out back, where he relocated the bookie and installed the
machine. Today, the shed _ painted the same rust red as the
160-seat restaurant that sits right on the curb _ is used for
storage.
</P>
<P>
   Indirectly, Mary inspired the restaurant. ``She'd make a few
dishes for lunch for the customers _ pasta, roasted meat _ peasant
food,'' Michael says. Cold marinated cracked crab, a Fabbro
signature dish, was also Mary's dish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was put on the tables for free for the drinking customers.
My father still makes it as a special a few times a month when
crab's in season. He gets a kick out of doing it,'' Michael says.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s, Michael's father, Frank (who still tends bar
at lunch), and uncle, Tarsizio ``Jim,'' took over from their father
and within a few years added dinner service.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the dishes popular then were abalone steak (a mere
$3.50) and ground sirloin steak ($3). Abalone is no longer on the
menu; ground sirloin is.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the choices include some of the restaurant's
long-standing dishes, like pan-grilled English sole and calamari
steak and newer inspirations _ spinach salad with fruit, bacon and
goat cheese; Sonoma chicken breast with roasted red peppers and
sun-dried- cherry demi-glace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making the menu more current, getting away a little from
the '70s Italian food,'' Michael says. The menu ideas come mostly
from Daryl Dillahunty, chef de cuisine, with input from Julia,
Michael's wife, who also helps manage the restaurant. The kitchen
executes the menu under head chef Scott Manit.
</P>
<P>
   Fabbro's interior has also changed with the times. In its bar
days, the floor and tables were bare, the place very simple. In the
'70s, Michael recalls, there was a ``loungy, cocktail feeling''
with red-flocked wallpaper and boarded up windows ``to make the
place as dark as possible,'' he says, laughing. ``There was lots of
cigarette smoke.'' By the '80s, the red flocking was gone and the
clubby look _ dark wood, white tablecloths _ was in.
</P>
<P>
   Michael remodeled last summer when he took the reins from his
father, knocking out partitions and reexposing the windows to
create a more spacious, light-filled look. The walls are now a
pretty yellow, and decor is simple, comfortable and attractive _
white tablecloths, neatly framed posters and photographs of Italy
shot by Michael and his sister Barbara Fabbro.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the building holds out, we'll be here,'' he says,
laughing. ``I like the building and the history that is here. And
the comfortable neighborhood bistro feel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 1808EDT &QL; 
