<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of 
 professional tasters tries a different product available in 
 supermarkets.   
   
   
   
 TASTER'S CHOICE: Ginger Beer With `Bite' Sparkles for Judges  
   
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Finally, finally, finally, the weather is warming
and we can turn our attention to cool, refreshing drinks. One
that's gaining store shelf space is ginger beer, the
stronger-flavored artisan cousin of ginger ale.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted eight ginger beers and found one that stood
far above the others. Panelists were divided on almost every other
ginger beer sampled. Interestingly, the company that took first
place also makes the concoctions that came in second and fourth.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reed's Extra Ginger Brew &LR;  (four 12-ounce bottles, $3.99 at
Whole Foods) was the panel's overwhelming favorite. Most of the
panelists liked the ginger bite, but one picked up bitter
overtones, and another thought it was a tad too sweet. Three would
buy it; two might.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Reed's Premium Ginger Brew &LR;  (four 12-ounce
bottles, $3.99 at Whole Foods). One panelist thought it had a
``nice restorative quality,'' but others wanted more ginger flavor.
Two detected caramel notes, which they found unpleasant and
slightly medicinal. Two would buy it, one might buy it, and two
would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Natural Brew Outrageous Ginger Ale  &LR; (four 12-ounce bottles,
$3.49 at Whole Foods) scored just two points lower than Reed's
Premium. Two panelists disliked the cloudy appearance, and one
panelist described the flavor as soapy and unpleasant. But another
panelist liked the balance of ginger to sweetness. One would buy
it, two might buy it, and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Scores dropped dramatically after third place, but the best of
the rest was  &UR; Reed's Original Ginger Brew &LR;  (four 12-ounce bottles,
$3.99 at Whole Foods). Three panelists thought it tasted like it
was made from dried ginger instead of fresh (it  &LR; is  &LR; made from
fresh ginger) and described the flavor as artificial. None would
buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Fifth place went to  &UR; Stewart's Original Ginger Beer &LR;  (four
12-ounce bottles for $2.99 at Draeger's). Three panelists thought
it had an overbearing spiciness, but one liked the ginger bite. Two
panelists also liked the cola-like color. One would buy it; four
would not.
</P>
<P>
   Three ginger beers scored too low to rate: Sioux City, Cock 'n
Bull and Journey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Shelley Handler,
consultant and food writer; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All
Seasons, San Francisco; Roland Passot, chef-owner, La Folie in San
Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park, Calif.; and
Kirk Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 1809EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6205 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARTHABOOK-SFCHRON &LR;      04-20 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTHABOOK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   COOKS' BOOKS: Visions of Martha's Parties Will Dance in Your 
 Head  
   
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  When I picked up home-and-hearth maven Martha
Stewart's new cookbook, ``Martha Stewart's Hors D'Oeuvres
Handbook,'' I visualized finding crocheted-chive napoleons and
monkey-picked jasmine rice balls filled with homemade truffled goat
cheese served on platters carved by the host from coconuts and
slabs of ice.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stewart is known for making complicated home and kitchen
projects, including cocktail parties, look so easy that even the
busiest people should be able to accomplish them on a lazy
afternoon. As we watch her television show or read her magazine, we
forget this is her livelihood, much the way we forget movie stars
are paid to spend the time and money to look that good. Normal
people with jobs and children and lives can't compete.
</P>
<P>
   The book ingeniously tempts from the get-go with more than 200
color photographs right in the front of the book instead of in the
middle or spread throughout. By the time you've leafed through
them, you'll have visions of cocktail parties dancing in your head.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the book is worthwhile for the photographs alone.
Photographer Dana Gallagher mixes shots of the food with some demo
shots, like how to make pommes annette and nori stacks with smoked
salmon. Readers will get ideas not only on food but also on
presentations, like using a hollowed-out bread loaf as a server for
tea sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   And that is the crux of this book: It needs to be approached
with realist's eyes. As with all things by Martha, it's great for
ideas, but you don't need to follow them to the letter.
</P>
<P>
   For example, I am not going to whittle fresh sugar cane into
skewers for tropical chicken. I won't feel guilty if I don't boil
the water for ice cubes for 10 minutes before freezing it so it
will be clear. And the idea of using chives to tie a plantain chip/
jerk chicken bundle is my idea of a prison sentence.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, crispy asparagus straws _ thick asparagus
spears wrapped in prosciutto and phyllo dough _ are at the top of
my list for my next get-together, as is the roasted red pepper and
eggplant dip (yes, Martha has included such mundane party food as
dips).
</P>
<P>
   Her methodology is sound most of the time. She gives tricks of
the trade, like slicing a whole loaf of bread horizontally into
long strips, topping them, then cutting them into diamonds or
squares for perfectly shaped canapes.
</P>
<P>
   She lists helpful notes and techniques _ how to use dried
mushrooms, how to work with phyllo dough _ on the same page as the
first recipe in which they're used. And many of her recipes tell
readers how far in advance the dish can be made.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most useful part of the book is in the back, where
she describes planning a party. She covers the usual stuff, like
how much to make for how many people, but she also gives tips on
balancing not just flavors and textures but workload _ mixing
labor-intensive appetizers with simpler recipes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martha Stewart's Hors D'Oeuvres Handbook'' isn't for people
who stress out over cooking and entertaining; it will only add to
the pre-party jitters. But for those who know a bit about cooking
and can comfortably skip making pain de mie from scratch without
guilt, the book will let readers tap into Martha's brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``Martha Stewart's Hors D'Oeuvres Handbook,'' by Martha &LR; 
 &LR; Stewart (Clarkson N. Potter, 1999; 496 pages hardcover; $35). &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 1809EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6206 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARTHABOOK-SFCHRON &LR;      04-20 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTHABOOK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   COOKS' BOOKS: Visions of Martha's Parties Will Dance in Your 
 Head  
   
   
