   Large wooden rolling pin
</P>
<P>
   Handheld egg beater
</P>
<P>
   2 wire cooling racks
</P>
<P>
   2-inch round cookie cutter
</P>
<P>
   Toothpicks
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Excerpted from ``Learning to Cook With Marion Cunningham.'' &LR;   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(THE FOLLOWING RECIPES ARE GOOD FOR NOVICE COOKS. THEY FEATURE FEW
INGREDIENTS AND A HIGH PROBABILITY FOR SUCCESS.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; LEEK AND POTATO SOUP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 leeks
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds russet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   6 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter (when serving the soup, put a slice of
butter in each serving)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To prepare the leeks: &LR;  Cut the tops off the leeks where the
color begins to turn from very light green to darker green. Cut off
the root ends and discard, along with the tops. Cut the leeks in
half lengthwise. Leeks often have dirt lodged between the layers of
the stalks. Separate the layers with your fingers and rinse under
cold running water to remove all dirt. Put the leeks on the cutting
board and cut crosswise into 1/4-inch pieces.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To prepare the potatoes:  &LR; Peel and rinse the potatoes under
cold tap water. Cut the potatoes in half lengthwise. Place the
halves cut sides down on a cutting board and slice crosswise into
1/4-inch-thick pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Melt the 4 tablespoons butter in a heavy-bottomed pot or Dutch
oven over medium heat, stirring regularly. Tilt the pot from side
to side so the butter covers the bottom. Add the leeks and potatoes
and use a large spoon to distribute the vegetables over the bottom
of the pot. Cook for about 5 minutes, stirring occasionally. If the
leeks begin to brown, turn down the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Add the broth and stir to mix leeks, potatoes and broth. Bring
to a boil, then lower the heat so the soup is simmering. Taste for
salt and add a little if the soup tastes flat. Cover the pot and
let the soup simmer for 35 minutes. When the potatoes are soft, the
soup is done.
</P>
<P>
   You can mash the vegetables if you want the soup coarse, or put
the soup through a blender or food processor if you want it
completely smooth. Some people like it simply left in chunks. Put a
pat of butter in each bowl and serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6 (yields about 3 quarts).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 315 calories, &LR;   &LR; 7 g protein, 38 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 16 g fat (10 g saturated), 42 mg cholesterol, 155 mg sodium, 4 &LR;   &LR; g
fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GREEN HERB SAUCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This sauce is good on baked potatoes, hearty fish like salmon,
scrambled eggs, added to a bowl of beans or broth and, of course,
on salads. To give the sauce a peppy edge, add 2 tablespoons capers
and omit the lemon. This variation is very good on steak or beef
roast.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   5 garlic cloves, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 lemons, grate the zest (the outer yellow skin) from both, then
squeeze the lemons, reserving the juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped cilantro leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped parsley leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the garlic, lemon zest and lemon juice in a bowl. Stir
in the chopped cilantro, basil and parsley, then add the olive oil.
Stir until well blended. Add the salt and pepper; stir to blend,
then taste it. Add more salt, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 125 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 g protein, 1 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 14 g fat (2 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 137 mg
sodium, 0 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ORANGE SOUR-CREAM CAKE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This cake really doesn't need a frosting. Powdered sugar
sprinkled over the top of the cake will do nicely.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter, let come to room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) butter, remove from refrigerator and let come
to room temperature
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons orange extract
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons grated orange zest (the outer orange-colored skin)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 325 degrees at least 15 minutes before you
plan to bake the cake.
</P>
<P>
   Rub the inside (bottom and sides) of a baking pan with the 1
tablespoon butter. The pan may be an 81/2x41/2x3-inch loaf pan or
an 8-inch round, 2-inch-deep cake pan. Sprinkle the 2 tablespoons
flour into the pan, then tilt pan, tapping bottom and sides with
your hand to distribute the flour as evenly as possible. Turn the
pan upside down over the wastebasket and tap the bottom to dislodge
any excess flour.
</P>
<P>
   Put the 1/2 cup butter and the sugar into a large mixing bowl.
Using a large spoon or an electric mixer, beat the butter and sugar
until thoroughly blended and smooth. Add the eggs and beat until
completely blended with the butter-sugar mixture. Add the orange
extract and orange zest, and beat and blend into the batter.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the 1 cup flour, the baking powder, baking soda and
salt in a small bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Add half of the flour mixture to the batter and beat well. Then
add half of the sour cream and beat until the batter is smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Add the remaining flour mixture to the batter, beating until
blended. Then add the remaining sour cream, beating until it is
blended into the batter.
</P>
<P>
   Spread the batter in the pan; smooth the top with a spatula.
</P>
<P>
   If using a loaf pan, bake for about 40 to 50 minutes, checking
after 35 minutes for doneness. If using a round cake pan, bake for
20 to 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Test for doneness by inserting a toothpick into the center of
the cake; if it comes out clean with no sticky batter clinging to
it, the cake is done.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the pan from the oven, place on a heat-resistant surface
and let cool for 10 minutes. Run a knife around the inside rim of
the pan and invert the pan over a plate or a sheet of wax paper.
Give the pan a little shake if the cake does not come out
immediately. Let cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; stats  &LR;   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 310 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 32 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 19 g fat (11 g saturated), 97 mg cholesterol, 276 &LR; 
 &LR; mg sodium, 0 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; NOVICES NO MORE &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Who:  &LR; Jamie Jobb, 53, Walnut Creek
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Why He Learned to Cook: &LR;  ``I wanted to get really orderly in
the kitchen and eat better. A lot of stuff you get in restaurants
you can do a good version yourself. But I wanted to learn how to do
that in a practical way ... and I wanted to become a better cook
out of the garden.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Biggest Hurdle: &LR;  ``Fear of flour. I still don't have a lot of
confidence about baking, but I'm getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Recent Success: &LR;  Perfecting a blood-orange vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Biggest Mistake:  &LR; ``I did the standard thing, like putting salt
instead of sugar in a baked thing. I had to throw that out. But I
tend to not remember those things.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Advice for Novices:  &LR; Don't be afraid to ask people who cook a
lot of questions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quote:  &LR; ``Cooking is an essential part of life. If you give it
up to Safeway or some deli, you're losing something.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Who:  &LR; Julie Scharmer, 47, Pleasanton
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Why She Learned to Cook:  &LR; ``I was tired of hearing my husband
joke that his dinner bell was the smoke detector ... and I wanted
to be able to go at Christmastime to somebody's house and take
something they wanted to eat. It was just embarrassing to have
whatever I brought just sit there untouched.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Biggest Hurdle: &LR;  ``The phone is a big problem. I get
distracted, and the food burns.'' She also had overcome a tendency
to throw in extra ingredients that detracted from the dish.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Recent Successes:  &LR; Roasting a chicken, baking cornbread and
making a cabbage/cranberry salad.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Biggest Mistake: &LR;  ``I learned that you had to cook fish 10
minutes per inch. So I bought this beautiful fish, and it measured
8 inches long. So I cooked it for 80 minutes.'' The rule, she later
learned, is 10 minutes for each inch of thickness, not length.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Advice for Novices:  &LR; Find simple recipes and follow them
exactly.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quote:  &LR; ``I've gone from being the person asked to bring the
potato chips to the person asked to bring a dish.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Who: &LR;  Jon Irwin, 25, San Francisco
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Why He Learned to Cook: &LR;  Eating out is too expensive, plus he
enjoys a wide variety of foods.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Biggest Hurdles: &LR;  Finding enough time to cook and finding
simple recipes. ``Some recipes are too complex. I won't do
something if it takes more than 45 minutes from start to finish.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Recent Success:  &LR; ``I made a fennel, three cheese and green
pepper stuffed chicken breast that ... was really good.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Biggest Mistakes:  &LR; ``Most of my mistakes come from not following a
recipe. I improvise a lot. I'll put the wrong spice with something
and it won't complement the other flavors. Recently, I made onion
rings and forgot that you are supposed to batter them. So I threw
the onions directly into the hot oil ... and I caught the stove on
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Advice for Novices:  &LR; ``Tools are the most important thing.
Spend the money up front because it's worth it in the long run. And
improvise. ... Don't always follow the recipe.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quote: &LR;  '`I try to learn as much as I can by watching other
people so I can come up with diverse, good-tasting things to eat
and I don't have to eat pasta every day.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Who: &LR;  Allan Temko, 75, Berkeley
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Why He Learned to Cook: &LR;  ``I got tired of eating in
restaurants.'' As a recent widower, he felt he had no choice but to
develop cooking skills. ``I've been spoiled all my life because
people have been cooking for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Biggest Hurdle:  &LR; ``Finding time ... good cooking takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Recent Success: &LR;  ``I have learned how to shop.'' He also has
perfected frying mushrooms and garlic for steak.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Biggest Mistake:  &LR; ``When I was first learning to make pasta, I
didn't realize that you had to heat the Paul Newman sauce. Now I'm
really good at it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Advice for Novices: &LR;  ``If you have time, take some courses.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Quote: &LR;  ``I don't really like cooking. It's in self-defense.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; _ Compiled by Kim Severson and Jennifer Straus, San &LR; 
 &LR; Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
