<HEADER>
A6224 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-20 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO AND KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Those convinced that ignoring history means we are
condemned to repeat it are comparing our increasing military
involvement in Kosovo with that in Vietnam and call it an example
of the folly of getting bogged down in a high-casualty, losing war.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's ethnic killings and
expulsions are also being likened to Adolf Hitler's mass murders
and deportations in the Holocaust. They are seen as a warning that
appeasement of murdering dictators does not prevent war but instead
encourages violence to spread.
</P>
<P>
   The two messages are contradictory and _ because history never
quite produces the identical situation twice _ not precisely apt.
</P>
<P>
   A more appropriate comparison, however, may be with the United
Nations' bloody ``police action'' led by the United States in Korea
from 1950 to 1953. The fighting was prompted by communist North
Korea's invasion of democratic South Korea in a brutal campaign to
militarily take over the entire peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   By the time a truce was negotiated and the North driven out of
the South, 88,000 U.N. soldiers had been killed, of whom 33,700
were Americans. South Korea lost a million civilians, 40 percent of
its industry and a third of its homes.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was simultaneously a political and military success
and a failure. The war ended with a U.N. armistice rather than a
peace treaty, and the north and south remain technically at war
today, their armies glowering at each other across a demilitarized
zone.
</P>
<P>
   President Harry Truman's policy of accepting a stalemate rather
than pursuing total victory over the North was sensible but not
politically popular at home. The controversy forced Truman to fire
an irresponsibly gung-ho Gen. Douglas MacArthur, who came home to a
hero's welcome. And the resulting political firestorm contributed
to Truman's decision not to seek reelection in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that South Korea remained intact and was
gloriously rebuilt with western aid. Communist expansion was
thwarted.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that North Korea went relatively unpunished for
its aggression and still poses a potential global menace despite
its internal repression and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Does this sound like Iraq or what? Just as Truman was in Korea,
President George Bush was content with pushing Saddam Hussein back
within his own borders but not pursuing him further. That avoided
further needless bloodshed but left him alive to fight again
another day.
</P>
<P>
   Reportedly China recently helped North Korea build a new
three-stage rocket with the capacity to launch nuclear missiles at
Alaska and Hawaii. Current diplomatic talks have focused on
exchanging U.S. promises of aid in return for access to the
suspected nuclear weapons site but have not yet produced visible
results.
</P>
<P>
   One indication of the intractable hostility is the North Korean
government's accusation this week, announcing that it expects to be
the next target attacked by Americans, after the bombing of
Yugoslavia and Iraq. The U.S. ``doctrine of strength applied
against Iraq and Yugoslavia does not work on us at all,'' the
official news agency said.
</P>
<P>
   And nearly 40,000 U.S. troops still patrol in South Korea almost
50 years after the war began. There has been constant tension along
the border but no new outbreak of fighting. Without casualty
reports, most Americans have forgotten that we are there and
probably will be for a long time to come.
</P>
<P>
   A similarly ambiguous outcome seems likely in the current Kosovo
crisis. Eventually the NATO air strikes will wear down Milosevic's
ability to control and destroy Kosovo. He will suddenly pretend to
be willing to talk peace. Then what?
</P>
<P>
   The appeasers want to turn and run, leaving him in charge of the
country he ruined but getting out before American blood is shed.
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., and his supporters want to go in with
guns blazing and demonstrate to the world that mass murder and
evacuation are not acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Some course in between that protects Kosovo, allows its people
to return and gets rid of Milosevic and his brutes but leaves
Belgrade standing seems the way to go. It may require a perpetual
NATO troop presence, but Korea proves that can be a tolerable, if
imperfect, solution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
