<SLUG> BC-BKN-COMMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALWAYS PLAY TIME FOR THE PACERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Celtics' bench looked pretty good Monday; they had
three starters in street clothes, all smartly attired. At the other
end of the court, Larry Bird had the same guys he's always had _ in
uniform, ready to go. It has been that way for two years.
</P>
<P>
   You can listen to Bird talk a lot about coaching, but one thing
he won't discuss is how well he deals with adversity and
roster-juggling. He hasn't had any. He's had to deal with tough
losses and a tough schedule, but he sees the same faces every day
and that is almost a miracle in this truncated season.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers played their 42d game Monday. The top nine players,
all of whom are averaging at least 17 minutes a game, have missed a
total of five games, no one missing more than one. And of those
five games, two were non-injured absences; Jalen Rose was suspended
for a game for fighting and Mark Jackson missed one to attend his
father's funeral. The notoriously fragile Rik Smits missed his
first game Sunday _ because of the flu.
</P>
<P>
   That is a remarkable number in any season, let alone this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beyond imagination,'' Bird said of the season. ``I
thought it was going to be great, playing every day. But it's not.
We're on the road all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But it also is consistent with what Bird has seen since he took
over. Last season, for instance, five of Bird's top eight went
wire-to-wire and a sixth, Miller, missed one game because of a
suspension. Only Smits (nine games) and Dale Davis (the first four
of the season) missed more than one game.
</P>
<P>
   How do the Pacers do it? They don't know. There is a connection
between health and winning, more of a connection when talent is
added to the equation. But there's no accounting for the ankle
sprain that Antoine Walker suffered Sunday. It could have happened
to Miller or Davis or Jackson. It did happen to Antonio Davis _
obviously not as severely _ but he missed one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do anything different than anyone else,'' said team
president Donnie Walsh. ``I mean, we have a conditioning coach and
we try to pick stuff up early. I think it's a roll of the dice in
this business. I just knock on wood every chance I get.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers do have three players on the injured list: Mark Pope,
Mate Skelin, and Fred Hoiberg. Even those guys are healthy. The
only legitimately hurt player this season is the maddening Derrick
McKey, who is trying to do the impossible: play himself back into
shape in a season with no time for practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like he never played before,'' a sympathetic Bird
said.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana will say they need McKey for this or for that, but they
can do quite nicely without him. Smits is absolutely critical to
the club's success and he's been a constant ever since Dan Dyrek
started working on his feet. Miller, Chris Mullin, and Dale Davis
have started all 42 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's big,'' Dale Davis said. ``It gives you a chance to play a
consistent game and have a consistent year. Some of it is luck. But
a lot of it is how you go about training.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about minutes distribution, Davis said, ``It has an
effect. You play less, the less chance you have of getting hurt.
(Bird) has done a good job of rotating guys.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also the experience factor. Dale Davis is the pup of the
litter and he's played seven seasons. The other four (Smits,
Miller, Mullin, and Jackson) all have played at least a decade.
They know how to take care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been around,'' Walsh said. ``But what amazes me is how
we've stayed healthy this season. With all those games in a short
period of time, that's when injuries occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Bird, ``We've been very fortunate. Overall, we've been
pretty healthy. The guys keep in shape. We also play a lot of guys,
so that helps. We try to keep their minutes down. I don't think
Reggie Miller needs to play 38 to 40 minutes a night (he plays
35.8).''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Bird even pretended that Smits was a pre-game
concern. Asked before the game if Smits was going to play, Bird
said, ``I have no idea. If he's not out there, he's not going to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Smits was out there and he played. It's the Indiana way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
