<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6231 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0421-     04-20 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0421-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RESISTANT REFUGEES SLOWLY BUCKLING TO PRESSURES TO LEAVE
ALBANIAN BORDER
 &HT;    With JOURNAL-KOSOVO-0421; KOSOVO-STRIKES-0421.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Relief agencies are beginning to lure out some
of the Kosovar Albanian refugees crammed into this mountain valley,
but many have adamantly dug in for a long stay here -- as close as
they can remain to their ravaged homes and missing relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``For two months, I won't move at all,'' said Osman Sllamniku(CQ
both), who is here with 21 people of his extended family in a tent
camp. ``After that, we'll consider it for the sake of the
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such commonly heard sentiments, on each of the past two
days truck and bus shuttles carried more than 10,000 refugees away
from the frigid nights and windy, rain-spattered days of this
mountain valley.
</P>
<P>
   And a NATO helicopter ferry service is expected to start flying
by Thursday, taking away people ill-suited to the 9- to 10-hour
ride out. They will be flown to Tirana and other cities further
south.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having helicopters here tomorrow,'' said U.S. Army Maj.
Hank Adams, who on Tuesday afternoon was inspecting the first loads
of gravel planned to turn a dirt track into a major access road at
an old Albanian military airstrip.
</P>
<P>
   Adams is attached to NATO's new HQ-A4, the headquarters
established to carry out humanitarian assistance in the region. He
said the grass air field will take out refugees and bring in the
food and other supplies now landing at a small site hard up against
a tent camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aviators don't like touching down with the potential of
chopping a civilian's head off,'' said Adams, of Bozeman, Mont.
Children often run out to wave at arriving helicopters, and there
are no barriers to stop them or anyone else from walking into an
incoming rotor blade.
</P>
<P>
   Precisely when the refugee airlift begins will be up to the
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), the agency
that will determine who gets to ride in the helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   UNHCR spokesman Jacques Franquin said the helicopters will be
used only for ``vulnerable'' people. But rather than further break
up families, such sick or elderly people will be accompanied by all
the relatives here with them.
</P>
<P>
   Franquin said he had heard no discussion of this same air
operation being used to drop food into the neighboring Kosovo
province.
</P>
<P>
   It is feared the Serbian-led Yugoslav military forces have
prevented the departure of hundreds of thousands of people who were
en route to the Albanian and Macedonian borders to escape ethnic
cleansing brutalities, and that these refugees may be in hiding in
remote mountains or forested areas.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. World Food Programme has begun discussing an air drop
to them, and has made an appeal to donor countries for six million
of the food packages called humanitarian daily rations.
</P>
<P>
   Nor had NATO's Adams heard of plans for air drops from the field
here. He noted there are neither the aircraft nor the supplies in
Kukes to mount such an operation.
</P>
<P>
   If the Kosovar Albanian refugees still trying to flee Kosovo are
permitted by the Serbs to exit, the situation on the borders of
Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro again will become critical.
</P>
<P>
   Once again on Tuesday, only a few refugees crossed into Albania,
although an estimated 2,000-3,000 did make their way into Macedonia
only to hear the UNHCR declare the border camps there full beyond
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   While the exhausted refugees faced a second night of driving
wind and rain, those fortunate enough to cross the border faced new
harassment in Macedonia, which has reluctantly taken in the refugee
throngs.
</P>
<P>
   With its largest camp packed with 25,000 refugees, the UNHCR was
forced to put recent arrivals outside the enclave's fence because
local farmers would not sell or lease land to expand the Brazda
camp. That leaves those on its fringes vulnerable to raids by a
local population resentful of the influx of ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian civilians come nightly to the exposed tents, throwing
stones, shining flashlights into the tents and shouting, while the
exiles cower inside, the Kosovo Albanians said.
</P>
<P>
   Another 2,000-3,000 refugees reportedly staggered over a
mountain crossing, overwhelming a remote hamlet of 60 houses called
Milana, the U.N. refugee agency said.
</P>
<P>
   Both groups of refugees said thousands more were behind them,
driven out by Serb purges of ethnic Albanian communities.
</P>
<P>
   That prospect of a resumed refugee flow is a major factor
fueling the effort to move out refugees who in many cases are
settling here to await the conclusion of NATO bombing aimed at
forcing Serbian leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia,
to allow the refugees back into an autonomous Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Albanians once made up 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million
people, and Yugoslav forces have expelled an estimated 640,000 of
them from the province since last month. Many ethnic Albanians
favor independence for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   New tent camps are making a white and green mosaic across the
spring countryside here in anticipation of a new rush of exiles.
But aid authorities are aiming to keep them as transit camps, not
semi-permanent homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``These camps have to be transitional,'' said Daniel Endres,
coordinator for UNHCR here. ``We have to explain to refugees that
staying up here means many risks, and those risks increase with the
intensification of war on the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross-border shelling already has pockmarked the countryside,
mostly northwest of here, as Serbian troops apparently try to knock
out camps of the Kosovo Liberation Army, or KLA.
</P>
<P>
   The high concentration of people without proper services also
means the refugees stay cold, dirty and subjected to disease and
other health hazards.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
