<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6232 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REFUGEES-STAYING-0421     04-20 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFUGEES-STAYING-0421-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVO REFUGEES RESIST RELOCATION, HOLD ONTO HOPE OF RETURNING
HOME
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0421; KOSOVO-STRIKES-0421.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Poor conditions have spurred some refugees to
depart this rugged border area, but many will not leave unless they
are dragged out.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Sllamniku(CQ) family is in that category.
</P>
<P>
   Only one of the five adult brothers, all here with their
families, is thinking about trying to leave. He would go to
Germany, where his wife's father lives.
</P>
<P>
   The rest will stay put.
</P>
<P>
   Every night Ismet Sllamniku and three other adults sleep out in
the tractor and wagon that was jammed with 46 people as it drove
out of Kosovo about 10 days ago. There isn't enough space to sleep
in the tents their 21-member family have been assigned, he said.
</P>
<P>
   His wife Zahide bemoans the cold water she must use to wash her
two-year-old daughter and baby son of 10 months. The camp stopped
giving out disposable diapers three days ago, she said, which is
quite a hardship with children suffering diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   The food given by the Italians who run the camp is OK, they
said, but it is food for Italians. Plates of hot pasta with a
tomato sauce were being served at lunchtime Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   There are few clothes changes for either adults or children, not
enough mattresses, and no cooking equipment even if they had food
to cook. A tent that housed 13 of the family was barren inside
except for three single mattresses, blankets covering the floor and
piled in a corner.
</P>
<P>
   So why not leave?
</P>
<P>
   ``If the point is to go from this tent to another tent, why
go?'' asked Ismet Sllamniku, 33. The question is a reflection of
the fact that refugees generally do not know what options await
them at the end of a ride down the mountain. Most are housed with
Albanian families or in collective centers such as gymnasiums.
</P>
<P>
   There is an additional factor of the tractor. At present
Albanian authorities are prohibiting most refugee tractors from
traveling the routes out of here, to prevent nationwide traffic
congestion on roads that are already narrow and potholed.
</P>
<P>
   It is the family's most valuable possession, and the going price
for tractors here is about one-fifth the normal market value.
</P>
<P>
   Ismet's 25-year-old brother Osman said there is some
psychological comfort in being close to the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be as near as possible to home, not as far as
possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the tractor as far as Tirana would be an 18-hour trip. If
the Kosovar Albanians are allowed back into their homeland, the
trip back would take much longer because of roads clogged with
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that in two months the situation will get better,''
said Osman Sllamniku. ``We know they burned our houses. But if even
a chicken coop remains there, I will go.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
