<HEADER>
A6233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KITCHEN-WARES-NYT &LR;      04-20 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KITCHEN-WARES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MOVING PART, NO BATTERIES: WHO'D EVER BUY IT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For all the thrill and efficiency of the whirl of a
food processor and the hyperbuzz of a spice grinder _ smooth sauces
form instantly, spices are reduced to a powder _ they are about as
sensual as a vacuum cleaner.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is the ancient mortar and pestle. This simple
tool _ a heavy hollowed base with a clublike pounder _ looks
hopelessly tedious to use. But after testing nine, I found them not
only efficient but effective in ways that no machine can be.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing the crack of every spice pod, seeing the sticky juices
released from a clove of garlic, smelling the pungency of basil as
I bruised the leaves, was an addictive experience. Hanging your
nose over the feed tube of a food processor isn't quite the same.
</P>
<P>
   Which is just one reason the tool has lasted millennia.
</P>
<P>
   David Page, an owner of Drovers Tap Room on Jones Street, said
the mortar and pestle was ``more efficient than what we replaced it
with.'' Spice grinders and food processors take up more room, have
many more parts to wash and just don't do the same job. Those
machines have blades at the bottom of the cylinder, so only what is
at the bottom is ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of defeats the purpose of having a mechanical tool if
you have to be physically shaking it to get it to work properly,''
Page said.
</P>
<P>
   But more than that, a mortar and pestle can perform tasks no
food processor or spice grinder can. Smooth paste or coarse spice
mixture _ the results are completely under your control. It's the
motion of your hand and the pressure you place on the pestle, not
the speed of a turning blade, that determine texture or thickness
of a sauce. A mortar and pestle can crush just a few fennel seeds.
Try that in a spice grinder.
</P>
<P>
   A delicate sauce like pesto is completely different when made
with a mortar and pestle instead of a machine. Pesto means
``pounded,'' but a food processor or blender chops and slices,
making for a bitter sauce.
</P>
<P>
   With a blender, you stuff in all the ingredients _ basil, pine
nuts, garlic and oil _ and everything is ground up before you're
sure the proportions are correct. With a mortar and pestle,
ingredients are pounded together gradually and build on one
another.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Bertolli, an owner of Oliveto Cafe and Restaurant in
Oakland, Calif., and a proponent of the mortar and pestle,
describes the mechanical alternative succinctly: ``It's noisy, it's
boring and it doesn't produce a pleasing, rustic kind of result,
which is what pesto is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The mortar and pestle is also a crucial tool in Indian cooking.
Many chutneys, like mint and coriander chutney, have to be made by
hand. In a machine, their texture becomes too uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Indian food, the texture is important,'' said Julie Sahni,
the cookbook author and owner of Julie Sahni's School of Indian
Cooking in Brooklyn Heights. ``Indians eat with their fingers, and
textured foods are easier to pick up.''
</P>
<P>
   Spice mixtures are also best made in a mortar and pestle. A
mortar and pestle crushes cardamom, for example, and forces out its
essence, while a grinder can only slice it. And as Ms. Sahni
pointed out, the heat of an electrical appliance can destroy the
volatile oils in spices.
</P>
<P>
   There seem to be as many types of mortars and pestles as there
are uses for them. They come in varying forms, sizes and materials:
rough stone, wood, textured porcelain and marble that is cool to
the touch.
</P>
<P>
   After the testing, I discovered a few essential characteristics.
It is important to choose a heavy mortar, so it won't move when you
beat or pound with the pestle. High, sloping sides are necessary
for grinding spices and making sauces, to keep ingredients from
flying out and to force them to fall back to the center of the
mortar, so you don't have to constantly push them back with the
pestle.
</P>
<P>
   The materials that the mortars and pestles were made of proved
critical. A small glass one was practically useless. It was
difficult enough to get used to the idea of grinding spices with
glass, but the smoothness meant that the spices flew right out of
the mortar.
</P>
<P>
   Wood wasn't much better. When I crushed peppercorns, they dented
the wooden pestle, and garlic and basil left the porous mortar
irreversibly stained and scented when I made pesto. A wooden mortar
was also too light and was difficult to keep still when I was
beating in olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Most successful were the marble and ceramic mortars and pestles.
A marble one four inches in diameter was finely weighted. The
cone-shaped mortar helped focus the pounding in the bottom center
of the mortar, and the marble pestle was heavy enough to crack hard
spices like cardamom. Because it stays cool, it is perfect for
pesto and sauces like aioli. It is also reasonably priced _ $9.99,
for example, at Lechter's stores.
</P>
<P>
   The best all-round mortar and pestle was the 5 1/4-inch Mason
Cash, a vitrified ceramic model made in England. It is perfectly
weighted and has a soft matte texture. The pestle, a hollow ceramic
wand, has a fat base, so that when you pound out spices, you hit
several at a time, not just one or two. Just as a larger whisk is
easier to use, the larger pestle simplifies sauces like pestos,
chutneys and mayonnaises. Mason Cash also makes an 8-inch mortar
and pestle. The 5 1/4-inch model is $24.98 at Zabar's, 2245
Broadway (80th Street); (212) 787-2000.
</P>
<P>
   Ceramic Japanese mortars with hard wooden pestles are not only
useful but beautiful. Shaped like soup bowls and often painted in
pretty greens and blues, the mortars are textured inside with
raised ridges. The tools, called suribachi, are perfect for almost
every use _ spices can be ground to powder against the rough
surface, herbs and leaves can be shredded _ but not for sauces.
When I made aioli, I felt that I was sanding down the wooden pestle
as it scraped against the mortar. A model painted with dragonflies
is available for $14.95 at a Cook's Companion, 152 Atlantic Ave.
(Clinton Street), Brooklyn Heights; (718) 852-6901.
</P>
<P>
   A small ceramic mortar and pestle from Sur la Table, (800)
243-0852, for $13.95, has a flat, disk-shaped mortar with a pestle
that fits into it like a tennis ball in a cupped hand. It is far
too tiny for making sauces but is perfect for crushing small
amounts of spices and is a good alternative to larger models for
everyday use.
</P>
<P>
   A 3 1/2-inch cast-iron mortar and pestle, $39.95 from Sur la
Table, was ideal for spices. The iron pestle, though small, had
ample heft, making for effortless crushing of hard, odd-shaped
spices like star anise.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what shape or material mortar and pestle you buy, it
will be difficult not to become enamored of the sounds and the
scents _ how something as plain as a peppercorn can be transformed
from a black pea to pungent shards under your command.
</P>
<P>
   WALNUT SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Recipes From Paradise,'' by Fred Plotkin (Little,
Brown, 1997)
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   7 ounces walnuts, broken
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons plain dry bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   Sea salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons freshly grated Parmigiano Reggiano cheese
</P>
<P>
   Pinch fresh marjoram
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup fresh ricotta
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil, preferably Ligurian.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large mortar, combine walnuts, bread crumbs, garlic and
salt to taste. Pound with a pestle to form a coarse-textured paste.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add Parmigiano Reggiano and marjoram. Pound again to blend.
Add ricotta, along with 2 to 3 teaspoons tepid water. Stir with
pestle to mix. Slowly drizzle in olive oil, stirring to combine.
Taste and adjust seasonings. Serve with gnocchi or tortellini, or
spread on small slices of country bread.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
