<HEADER>
A6256 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CADILLAC-VOODOO21-COX     04-20 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CADILLAC-VOODOO21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cadillac Voodoo Choir: `We are rock stars'
 &HT;    By Chris Riemenschneider
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ For a band that likes to bare its chest hair,
and that gets the award for the local act most likely to see female
fans baring their chests, the five members of Cadillac Voodoo Choir
are actually pretty down-to-earth guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put this in your article and write it as the headline,''
drummer and CVC mouth Taxi Haskell says excitedly, into his third
or fourth cocktail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cadillac Voodoo Choir are rock stars. We are rock stars,
because no one else is doing it these days.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, pay attention to the down-to-earth thing now. Four of the
five members of Cadillac Voodoo Choir are from Atlanta, Ga. They
range in age from the pouty-lipped, Steven Tyler-looking singer
Chad Drummond's 23 years to Haskell's 32. Their first show in
Austin was in front of a couple thousand people two years ago
opening for Ian Moore. It was some intro. A year later, the band
moved to Austin and started opening for the few other local bands
that could draw crowds, like Storyville, the Ugly Americans and
Breedlove. It also hit the road, mostly around Texas, living it up
as if it were Aerosmith traveling in an Econoline. Stories abound
about sexual encounters in Houston and onstage debacles in Abilene.
The word ``humping'' comes up often.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Cadillac Voodoo Choir released its first CD,
``Boomtown Flood'' _ a fiery, ambitious album that has since landed
a rock nomination with the independent Grammy Awards _ the group
had earned enough exposure in Austin to be thought of as either the
most happening new local band or the most overblown, ostentatious
rock act that ever took stage at the Saxon Pub (and that's saying a
lot).
</P>
<P>
   It's when they're defending themselves against the latter
sentiment that the members of CVC show their humble side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the reasons we've done so well in Austin is
because we're genuine about what we do,'' said keyboardist Danny
Smith, who, along with Drummond, Haskell and recently reacquired
guitarist Brian Huffman is part of the original CVC lineup that
dates back five years (new bassist Jason Crow is from our area).
``We play the same kind of music we played in Atlanta five years
ago. If we had tried to change to be in line with what's on the
radio, we would have been miserable. We play the kind of music that
we want to play even if it's not the trendy thing right now, and we
put on the kind of show that we want to put on no matter what
anybody says about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Haskell, interjecting as he always does, was quick to address
those who have anything negative to say about CVC 's classic-rock
sound. A band that falls and occasionally stumbles somewhere
between the Stones, the Allman Brothers, Aerosmith and James Brown,
they of course are inundated with comparisons to a fellow Atlanta
band, referred to several times in our interview as
``you-know-who.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a band from where we're from, and having the influences
that were practically shoved down our throats for better or worse,
how could we not sound like `said band?' '' Haskell said. ``That's
like being a band from Austin and not saying Stevie Ray Vaughan
influenced you. It would be a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the post-script of our interview, after the tape
recorder was off, that Haskell finally said you-know-who's name for
the first time. It was also the first time he put down his
rock-star guard and showed his unassuming side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you for not comparing us to the Black Crowes,'' Haskell
said, pointing out to me that I hadn't actually said the band's
name, either.
</P>
<P>
   It's a hard thing for a band. Rock 'n' roll is about 49 percent
idolatry, and to play music from the heart and perform on stage in
a way that seems natural, musicians want to do it like their
heroes. If CVC is guilty of anything, it's that they do it too
well.
</P>
<P>
   Haskell is right, though, Cadillac Voodoo Choir deserves more
than a Black Crowes comparison, probably as much as the Crowes
deserved more than the Stones. During our interview, an Otis
Redding disc came over Shady Grove's outdoor speakers and Drummond
_ quiet the rest of the interview _ sang along to himself. Songs
like ``Red Dress'' and ``You'' on the CVC's album show off his and
Smith's affection for R&AMP;B and soul. Haskell repeatedly mentions the
Georgia Satellites and Mother's Finest, barroom-style Southern
groups heard in his group's songs such as ``New Age'' and
``Treehouse Blues.''The overall mix on the album is at times
unique, with horn parts thrown in and special attention paid to
rhythm. There may be more spunk than original spark to the group,
but it's a lot of spunk.
</P>
<P>
   And anyway, maybe the members of Cadillac Voodoo Choir shouldn't
concern themselves so much with the originality thing. For a band
said to have several labels knocking at its door, a band with so
many female groupies purportedly in its reach, there are more
important things to focus on. Before he let down his guard, Haskell
seemed to agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can handle the Stones or Aerosmith comparisons,'' he said.
``These are the bands we admire. Those guys hold the torch, and let
me tell you, there are five guys from Atlanta and Austin who are
going, `Can I hold that for a while?'
</P>
<P>
   Chris Riemenschneider writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
