<HEADLINE>
JUDGE TO REVIEW NEWSPAPERS, NEWSCASTS BEFORE RULING ON MOVING
JASPER TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ A Jasper County judge agreed Tuesday to watch
more than 11 hours of videotaped newscasts and review piles of
newspapers before deciding whether the second capital murder trial
in the dragging death of a black man should be moved.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Monte Lawlis said he would announce his
decision Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr., a 32-year-old ex-con from Sulphur
Springs, is set to go on trial May 17. He is one of three white men
accused of beating James Byrd Jr., chaining him by the ankles and
dragging him behind a pickup truck last June 7. Byrd, a 49-year-old
divorced father of three, was decapitated when his head slammed
into a culvert. His dismembered body was dumped in the middle of
the road outside a rural black cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's co-defendant and fellow white supremacist, John William
``Bill'' King, 24, was convicted in Jasper earlier this year and
sentenced to death. The third man, 24-year-old Shawn Berry, will be
tried later.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's change of venue hearing, originally scheduled for
Monday, was postponed one day to avoid coinciding with the
anniversary of the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing and the 1993 Branch
Davidian fire near Waco.
</P>
<P>
   That anniversary date, along with a threat by a racist Texas
prison inmate that there would be more violence in Jasper on April
19, prompted some parents to keep their children home from school
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a small group of media outside the courthouse, the
town of 8,000 was quiet on Tuesday, and school officials said the
1,080 students, nearly a third of the town's enrollment, who were
absent Monday were back in class Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   As he was escorted to the front door of the Jasper County
Courthouse, a handcuffed Brewer, wearing khaki slacks, a white
shirt and a bulletproof vest, faced the photographers and held up a
handmade sign fashioned from a manila envelope.
</P>
<P>
   ``To all the lady folk who are mothers: Happy Mother's Day,'' it
said. It was signed ``Russell,'' with the outline of a heart and
the initials ``TMP'' for Tammy Perritt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my girlfriend,'' he told reporters in the courtroom,
handing over the sign for closer inspection.
</P>
<P>
   Perritt, who sat in the courtroom with a friend, Kara Pruitt,
approached the rail during a break and hugged and kissed Brewer for
several minutes. John Brewer, 27, patted his brother's arm and his
head as the defendant buried his face in his girlfriend's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray called the
exchange and Brewer's sign a defense tactic to ``invoke sympathy
and to humanize'' the defendant, but Brewer's lawyers denied that
they had put him up to the publicity stunt.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's court-appointed attorney, Doug Barlow of Beaumont,
asked the judge to review videotapes, Internet stories and
newspapers from as far away as the Caribbean islands before making
a decision.
</P>
<P>
   He also offered one witness to support his contention that a
Jasper County jury would feel pressured to ``vindicate'' their
community and cleanse its tarnished reputation by convicting Brewer
and giving him the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the people of Jasper County would like to be as
fair as possible,'' said Melody Celli, an advertising and media
consultant from Beaumont. ``But with the media microscope they've
been under, I don't believe they could do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors called seven witnesses during the hearing who
testified that county residents could judge Brewer's case on the
facts and could acquit Brewer if the state fails to prove its case
against him.
</P>
<P>
   He said later that the county should have no problem calling 500
potential jurors. Of those, he said he expects ``175 to 200 bodies
to show up'' when jury selection begins.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It's not enough for a lawyer to say I want it moved out of
here. It's not enough to say there was a lot of publicity. You've
got to prove facts,'' Gray said after the hearing. ``We put people
on the stand who have credibility and have actually talked to
people in the county and we asked them their opinions on whether he
can get a fair trial. Every one of them said he could.''
</P>
<P>
   Barlow said he also tried to get local people to testify in
favor of moving the trial to Beaumont or some other city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most are very reluctant to come forward. No one really wants
to sign on board to testify in this case,'' he said. ``If this case
does not set the standard'' for moving a trial, Barlow added,
``then there is no standard.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
