<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHFIRES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suspect indicted in Georgia church fires case
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A 36-year-old Indiana man was indicted Tuesday for
setting fire to three rural churches in North Georgia over the
Christmas and New Year's Day holidays, including one that took the
life of a volunteer firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Ballinger of Youngstown, Ind., has been in custody in
Indianapolis since February for allegedly setting seven fires in
southern Indiana. Authorities do not believe there was any racial
motivation for the arsons; instead, the suspect started the fires
simply because the churches ``had a religious purpose,'' said
Richard Deane, the U.S. attorney in the Northern District of
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public has been well aware of a string of church fires in
the South and in other parts of the country, which has created a
justified sense of danger and concern for many who attend churches
of all denominations and backgrounds,'' Deane said. Concerns over
church fires prompted the formation in 1996 of a federal task force
to investigate any suspected arsons at houses of worship.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-count indictment charging Ballinger with seven Indiana
fires was returned Tuesday, at the same time he was formally
charged in Atlanta with three counts of arson and three counts of
destroying religious property. Ballinger came to the attention of
investigators in Indiana after he was hospitalized for burns in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have yet to decide whether to pursue the death
penalty against Ballinger for the death of the firefighter Kenneth
Loy Williams, 27, of Bold Springs, Ga. Williams was killed in the
New Year's Eve fire at the 100-year-old New Salem Methodist Church
in Banks County, Ga. when the fellowship hall roof collapsed on
him.
</P>
<P>
   Deane said Ballinger will be brought to Georgia ``as
expeditiously as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Ballinger also is charged in Georgia with setting fire to
Amazing Grace Baptist Church in Murray County on Dec. 23, and the
Mountain View Baptist Church in Murray County on Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Two other North Georgia churches also burned during the holidays
_ the Johnson United Methodist Church in Oconee County on Jan. 1
and the Sardis Full Gospel Church in Walton County near Between on
Christmas morning. Ballinger is not charged in those fires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other arsons continue to be the source of investigation,''
Deane said.
</P>
<P>
   All five churches in Georgia were small, rural and more than 75
years old. Four of the fires were started about 1 a.m. in the
pulpit area by someone who broke into the churches, investigators
have said.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Cook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
