<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Tech football coach relegated to sidelines
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia Tech football coach George O'Leary will have
to coach the 1999 opener at Navy from the press box instead of from
the sidelines, because of an NCAA infraction.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary, found guilty of a secondary violation, also will be
barred from coaching in the team's final scrimmage Saturday and
from recruiting off campus next month. Georgia Tech was informed
Tuesday by the NCAA committee on infractions of the sanctions for
providing former player C.J. Williams with a loan.
</P>
<P>
   The coach was out of the office and could not be reached for
comment But athletic director Dave Braine said he hopes that the
ruling ends the matter, which became public in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be disappointed if it did not,'' Braine said. ``I think we
have gone overboard in our handling of this. We've taken care of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary gave Williams, a running back 1993-96, a loan of $200 to
$400 to cover dorm-room damage expenses in spring 1996. According
to the school's internal investigation, Williams needed to pay a
fine within two hours in order to enroll, and the loan was repaid
within 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   It is a violation of NCAA rules to provide assistance to
athletes not available to the general student body. However, the
NCAA found that O'Leary's action was not a major violation, which
could have led to probation for the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no recruiting advantage involved,'' Braine said.
``The only reason George made the loan was to help the young man
register for class. C.J. was already at Georgia Tech, there was a
timing factor with C.J. coming to George at the last minute, and
the loan was repaid promptly.''
</P>
<P>
   After the NCAA notified Tech in January 1988 that it was looking
into the matter, Tech hired the law firm Long Aldridge &AMP; Norman to
investigate and filed a report with the infractions committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're relieved that the committee agreed with our finding that
the violation was secondary in nature,'' Braine said. ``This keeps
alive the fact that Georgia Tech is one of the few schools in the
nation that has never been on probation in any sport.''
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Clemons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
