<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-EAST-MATCHUPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STANLEY CUP CAPSULES
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH VS. NEW JERSEY
</P>
<P>
   Records: Pittsburgh 38-30-14, third in Atlantic; New Jersey
47-24-11, first in Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth quarter: Pittsburgh 6-10-6, New Jersey 15-4-3
</P>
<P>
   Season series: New Jersey won 4-1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Playoffs in decade: Pittsburgh is 60-44 with two Stanley Cups;
New Jersey is 41-34 with one Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: The Devils turned into a more wide-open team this
season under coach Robbie Ftorek and set an NHL record with 28 road
wins; they were 28-10-3 on the road, 19-14-8 at home. Goalie Martin
Brodeur rebounded after a slow start and has a 1.84 playoff GAA.
New Jersey shouldn't have a problem against the Penguins, whose
best player (Jaromir Jagr) has been feuding with their coach (Kevin
Constantine). The Pens' power play is successful at only 17.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: New Jersey in six games.
</P>
<P>
   BUFFALO VS. OTTAWA
</P>
<P>
   Records: Buffalo 37-28-17, fourth in Northeast; Ottawa 44-23-15,
first in Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth quarter: Buffalo 9-8-5, Ottawa 10-5-7.
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Ottawa won 1-0-4.
</P>
<P>
   Playoffs in decade: Buffalo is 28-32; Ottawa is 8-10.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: Enjoy goals? You might want to turn away. Buffalo's
Dominik Hasek and Ottawa's Ron Tugnutt figure to keep scoring to a
minimum, as evidenced by the last three meetings _ all 1-1 ties.
All five meetings this year went into overtime. The Senators were
winless in their final four (0-1-3) to blow a chance for the best
record in the conference, but were outscored only 6-4 in those
games. Each team has a 40-goal scorer _ Ottawa's Alexei Yashin,
Buffalo's Miroslav Satan _ but the Senators' overall speed should
be the difference. However, all predictions involving Hasek are
subject to change.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Ottawa in six games.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON VS. CAROLINA
</P>
<P>
   Records: 39-30-13, third in Northeast; Carolina 34-30-18, first
in Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth quarter: Boston 13-6-3, Carolina 7-8-7.
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Even 2-2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Playoffs in decade: Boston is 28-39; Carolina/Hartford is 5-8.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: Boston and Greensboro, N.C., are at opposite ends of
the spectrum in terms of hockey interest. The Hurricanes probably
won't even sell out their scaled-down capacity of 11,000 in their
temporary home. Just as well. Carolina enters the playoffs as a No.
3 seed for winning the Southeast but has the conference's
eighth-best record. They will get Keith Primeau back from a back
injury but are without injured defenseman Sean Hill. The Bruins
surprisingly struggled against Carolina this year but enter with
one of the league's hottest goalies (Byron Dafoe) and best
postseason coaches (Pat Burns). Boston is superior in penalty
killing (89.2 to 85.3) and power play (17.7 to 11.0).
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Boston in five games.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA VS. TORONTO
</P>
<P>
   Records: Philadelphia 37-26-19, second in Atlantic; Toronto
45-30-7, first in Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth quarter: Toronto 11-9-2, Philadelphia 7-9-6.
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Philadelphia won 3-1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Playoffs in decade: Philadelphia is 29-22 with one finals
appearance; Toronto is 25-27.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: The ``good'' news for Flyers fans is that Eric
Lindros _ he of the recent collapsed lung and severe blood loss _
still believes he will be able to return later in the playoffs. The
bad news is that Philly might not make it past the first round.
Despite its success against Toronto this season, the Maple Leafs
have a big edge in goaltending (Curtis Joseph vs. the Flyers' John
Vanbiesbrouck) and have been the healthier and stronger team down
the stretch. Philly's best scorer, John LeClair, has been slowed by
back problems and Mark Recchi is coming off a concussion. Home ice
could be key: Flyers were 21-9-11 at home but only 16-17-8 on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Toronto in six games.
</P>
<P>
   SCHEDULE
</P>
<P>
   Today
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo at Ottawa, 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim at Detroit, 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton at Dallas, 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose at Colorado, 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia at Toronto, 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh at New Jersey, 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Boston at Carolina, 7:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   San Jose at Colorado, 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis at Phoenix, 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
