<SLUG> BC-SEARS-RETIREES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sears retirees plan to protest cuts in life insurance at annual
meeting
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An angry group of retired employees from Sears,
Roebuck &AMP; Co. is gearing up to take on Chief Executive Arthur
Martinez next month in downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 Sears retirees gathered Tuesday at First Baptist
Church in Decatur to plan a protest at the company's annual
shareholder meeting, which is scheduled for May 13 at the Atlanta
Apparel Mart. The Atlanta group is taking part in a nationwide
fight by thousands of retirees who are trying to restore the value
of life insurance policies cut by Sears in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Sears reduced life insurance benefits from an average of $17,000
to $5,000 as part of a cost-cutting effort. The cut, which affects
84,000 retirees, spurred hundreds of protests nationwide and led to
the formation of a National Association of Retired Sears Employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the mistakes Sears has made, the worst mistake was
losing 84,000 of its best friends,'' said Clifton Hooks, who flew
in from Michigan to help rally the Atlanta protest. ``We had a love
affair with Sears until they tried to take what was rightfully
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   The benefits had been part of retirement packages for 50 years.
Retirees say they paid into the program for 10 years or more before
they retired and were promised throughout their careers that life
insurance benefits would stay intact.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman Estates, Ill.-based Sears, which has battled consumer
lawsuits and financial trouble in recent years, said the cuts are
needed to keep the company competitive. The company said it was
spending almost twice as much as competitors on retiree benefits.
</P>
<P>
   In their 15-month campaign, the retirees have mustered support
from 221 local retiree clubs in 49 states. The national
organization says it represents 133,000 retirees, including about
1,000 in metro Atlanta. Up to 300 protesters could show up at the
annual meeting in Atlanta, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   Retirees have also taken their fight to court. In January, a
U.S. District Court in Illinois granted class-action status to a
lawsuit against Sears filed by a former store manager.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
