<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6265 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-DUQUE-DAD-ART-NYT     04-20 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-DUQUE-DAD-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY TWO SONS, CUBAN-STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAVANA, Cuba _ In his 50s, Arnaldo Hernandez still moves with an
easy, athletic stride, his long arms swinging in graceful arcs, the
same way they did in 1969, when he pulled off the rare feat of
playing all nine positions for one of this country's fabled
baseball teams, the Villa Clara Azucareros.
</P>
<P>
   But Hernandez is long past his playing days, and because he came
of age at the start of Fidel Castro's 40-year Cold War with the
United States, he was never given a chance in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Fate, though, has paid him back handsomely for that misfortune,
because the aging Cuban pitcher has two sons pitching in the major
leagues. Orlando Hernandez won a World Series ring on the 1998
Yankees and Livan was the most valuable player in the 1997 World
Series as a right-hander for the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to be a big leaguer,'' Hernandez said in an
interview in a cafe on a Havana rooftop earlier this month. ``What
I couldn't do, my two sons have done. I'm proud. In fact, I think
proud is too small a word.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnaldo Hernandez does not pretend to be a perfect man or to
have conducted himself as an exemplary father. He has left more
than one wife, remarrying and moving to another city. And he is
honest and modest enough to concede that he did not personally
train the two pitchers when they were boys, instead leaving that up
to the government's baseball academies.
</P>
<P>
   But the father nevertheless instilled in his sons a deep love
and commitment to baseball, family members said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing they saw was a glove, a ball, a bat,'' he
said. ``This talent comes partly from me, but there is a part that
comes from the will to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   That will to succeed included the daring to escape Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Livan left first, deserting the Cuban national team in
Monterrey, Mexico, on Sept. 27, 1995, and signing with the Marlins.
Two years later, Orlando fled after he had been suspended from
Cuban baseball on charges that he had planned to defect like his
brother.
</P>
<P>
   Livan, who at 22 became the youngest pitcher to start a World
Series game, won two games as the Marlins outlasted the Indians.
Orlando, who was signed by the Yankees soon after he arrived in
March 1998, was standing on the steps of New York's City Hall with
a World Series title under his belt eight months later.
</P>
<P>
   But their stories really begin long before, on the bedraggled
diamonds of Cuba, where they learned their craft at the hands of
trainers of their father's generation.
</P>
<P>
   And the elder Hernandez at least helped shape them.
</P>
<P>
   He played the game hard for 14 years, until an injury finally
sidelined him in 1979. He won four national championships and
finished with a .282 batting average. It was the elder Hernandez
who first earned the moniker, El Duque, for his magnanimous
behavior in the clubhouse in the 1970s. After retiring from play,
the original El Duque coached teams in La Isla de Juventud and Las
Tunas in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez left his first wife, Maria Julia Pedroso, when Orlando
and his older brother were 5 and 6 years old. But he maintained a
relationship with the boys, and when Orlando became a teen-ager, he
went to live with his father in La Isla de la Juventud. Arnaldo was
managing the Isla's top-tier club.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said it then that he persuaded Orlando that he had a
good enough arm to become a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to be a shortstop, but I told him he had to be a
pitcher,'' he recalled. ``I saw that in La Isla, he was not going
to become a player, so I sent him back to Havana, to the baseball
academy, with Pedro Chavez, a famous player and a friend of mine,
and they accepted him and he started working as a pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   There was only so much advice the new El Duque would listen to.
</P>
<P>
   ``El Duque is the kind of person that you can tell him he should
do something, but he will try to test it himself first,'' Hernandez
said. ``If it gives him results, he will follow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez played a more influential role in Livan's life. Livan
was born to Hernandez's second wife, Mirami Carera, in 1976, in
Villa Clara. He was a rotund little boy, but his father saw
potential in his agile movements and encouraged him to play ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never thought he would be a pitcher,'' Hernandez said.
``When he was little, he was fat, fat, fat. People told me I would
have a great cook on my hands. I told them he was a great
ballplayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Livan lived with his father until he was 10. By then, Hernandez
was coaching a team of teen-agers in Las Tunas. But he, never
feeling entirely comfortable coaching his own boys, sent Livan off
to a superior program in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sincerely, I never trained a son of mine, because even if they
had talent, the whole world would say, no, he's playing because
he's your son,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both boys rose quickly in the Cuban baseball world, becoming
aces on the Cuban national team. By the mid-1990s, Orlando had
become the most popular pitcher in Havana, while his brother was a
star on the Santa Clara team.
</P>
<P>
   All that changed four years ago when Livan was first contacted
by a Miami agent for players, Joe Cubas, while he was training with
the national team in Japan, the elder Hernandez said. Livan
confided in his father, saying he had been contacted by a big
league team and was thinking of defecting. Orlando had advised
Livan not to go, but the elder Hernandez, having spent his best
years isolated in Cuba, felt a tug of sympathy for Livan, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I wouldn't oppose it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Livan walked away from the team while playing an exhibition game
in Monterrey in September. The defection hurt Orlando more than
anyone else, his father said. The authorities summarily suspended
him from baseball, accusing of him of plotting his own escape.
Family members said Orlando felt cornered, unable to practice the
sport that meant more to him than anything. In late 1997, he
decided to risk a forbidden crossing of the Straits of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to help him, and encourage him, because here he could
do nothing,'' the elder Hernandez recalled. ``Here they had
unjustly suspended him, for life, and he was born to play
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Hernandez said, he doesn't have much to do. He helps
his youngest son, Marlon, 14. ``The boy has a rock for an arm,'' he
said, slapping his own right arm.
</P>
<P>
   He also dreams of the day when he might make a trip to America
to see his older sons play in person. He says he speaks to Orlando
from time to time on the telephone. He has been trying to get a
tourist visa, as well as permission from the Cuban authorities to
travel to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Until those documents are in hand, he is condemned to daydreams
about sitting in the stands and watching his sons take on big
league players. His only solace is an occasional televised
broadcast at a tourist hotel. He spends most of the North American
baseball season in hotel bars, hoping to persuade a friendly
bartender to let him see a game with the Marlins or the Yankees on
cable television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to a hotel and I ask for a beer and I watch,'' he said,
shrugging sadly.
</P>
<P>
