<SLUG> BC-LANNAN-PRIZE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ITS DEBUT, A BIG PRIZE FOR FREEDOM HELPS WRITER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., Calif., Uruguay)   (bl)  
 By DINITIA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Lannan Foundation of Santa Fe, N.M., announced Tuesday that
it would give its first $250,000 Prize for Cultural Freedom to
Uruguayan writer Eduardo Galeano. As part of the award, one of the
cultural world's largest monetary prizes, the foundation will also
donate $100,000 to three charities of Galeano's choosing.
</P>
<P>
   Galeano, 58, is best known for his trilogy, ``Memory of Fire,''
which consists of poetic vignettes about the history of the
Americas and indigenous peoples. It won the American Book Award in
1989. In 1974 he fled Uruguay after protesting government violence
and corruption. After a coup in Argentina, Galeano fled again, to
Spain, where he lived until he returned to Uruguay in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   In a representative passage in ``Faces and Masks,'' the second
book in the trilogy, Galeano writes of the death of the
19th-century naturalist Aime Bonpland, who knows ``that ants and
people will not stop being born; that there will be new clover
leaves and new oranges or suns on the branches; and that foals,
newly upright on their mosquito legs, will be stretching out their
necks in search of a teat. The old man bids farewell to the world
as a child does to the day at bedtime.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, which is family-run, said that the prize
recognized those ``whose extraordinary and courageous work
celebrates the human right to freedom of imagination, inquiry and
expression.''
</P>
<P>
   Foundation president J. Patrick Lannan Jr. said: ``We think he's
a great writer. Galeano has had a much greater impact than just the
field of literature.''
</P>
<P>
   Galeano began publishing political commentary and cartoons in a
Uruguayan socialist weekly at the age of 13. Later, he became
director of the daily Epoca and editor in chief of the University
Press of Montevideo. Reached by telephone in San Antonio, he said
that the charitable portion of his award would go to three
Uruguayan institutions, the Cinemateca Uruguaya, for promotion of
animation cinema; the Fundacion Vivian Trias, which promotes
readings and discussions in history and politics, and the political
and cultural weekly magazine Brecha.
</P>
<P>
   Lannan said that when he called Galeano with the news of the
award, ``he was incredulous. In fact, it wasn't clear initially how
much money I was talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't really have a great statement,'' Lannan said. ``He
was just very, very surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   Galeano said that his new book, to be published in English next
year by Holt Metropolitan, was titled ``Upside Down.'' He described
it as ``a portrait of the world at the end of the millenium.'' The
book is in the same vein as ``Memory of Fire,'' he said, ``about a
world that despises honesty but ill treats work and workers and
rewards lack of scruples.''
</P>
<P>
   With assets of about $220 million, the Lannan Foundation has
given away $70 million since 1986. It gives away $12 million to $14
million yearly, for programs including its Literary Awards, ranging
from $75,000 to $100,000 each, and grants for new and experimental
art and recently, for indigenous peoples.
</P>
<P>
   In the past the foundation has given money to projects that had
difficulty getting support elsewhere because of their political
content. In March, after the National Endowment for the Arts
withdrew a grant for an English translation of a children's book
written by the Mexican guerrilla leader known as Subcommandante
Marcos, the foundation donated $15,000 for the project. When the
Corcoran Gallery of Art in Washington canceled an exhibition of
Robert Mapplethorpe's homoerotic photographs in 1989, the
foundation gave $35,000 to the Washington Project for the Arts to
exhibit them.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation was begun in 1960 by Lannan's father, the son of
an Irish cabinetmaker. He had made a fortune as an investor and was
a director of International Telephone &AMP; Telegraph Corp. Two years
ago the foundation moved from Los Angeles to Santa Fe, where it is
housed in three 19th-century buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Recently it announced it was taking a one-year hiatus to rethink
its mission, though it will support continuing projects like the
writers' awards and grants to American Indians. Lannan said that in
the future the Cultural Freedom Prize might not go to someone in
the arts but rather ``to someone in indigenous populations.''
</P>
<P>
   The prize awarded to Galeano is among the largest of its kind.
Among family foundations, the Heinz Family Foundation also gives an
annual $250,000 award, primarily for humanitarian aid efforts. The
Nobel Prize in Literature is worth close to $1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
