<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA EASES OFF ON OPPOSITION TO KOSOVO BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia is still angry about NATO's airstrikes against
Yugoslavia. But suddenly, the chill is gone _ or at least some of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, it seemed every time a senior Russian official
expressed opposition to NATO's airstrikes, some ominous threat
would follow: retargeting its nuclear weapons, joining a loose
federation with Yugoslavia, readying warships for the
Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kremlin turned down the temperature this week. While
continuing to denounce the airstrikes, Moscow is no longer
underscoring that World War III is imminent. The change comes as
former Prime Minister Viktor S. Chernomyrdin, Russia's new envoy
for talks on the Kosovo crisis, has taken the lead in crafting the
tone of Russia's diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, who has a personal relationship with many Western
leaders from his more than five years as Russian premier, on Sunday
ruled out a Russian military response to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   While reiterating that Russia wants the airstrikes against
Yugoslavia stopped, Chernomyrdin has signaled that Moscow may be
ready to coordinate with the West and put pressure on Yugoslav
leader Slobodan Milosevic to accept NATO's conditions for a halt to
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin is widely believed to have gotten the job for
domestic reasons. Commentators say President Boris N. Yeltsin,
using one of his favored tactics, was looking to stem the steadily
rising influence of Prime Minister Yevgeny M. Primakov by replacing
him with Chernomyrdin as Russia's point man on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the motivation, the change has had a pronounced effect.
Primakov has made a career of opposing US initiatives as a way to
improve Russia's international stature. His ``peace mission'' to
Belgrade last month, accompanied by Russian army and intelligence
chiefs, looked more like a gesture of political and military
support for Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Symbolic of Primakov's approach to the Balkan crisis was the
U-turn he made the night NATO airstrikes began, turning his plane
to Washington back to Moscow in haughty protest that won praise at
home but set the stage for confrontation between Russia and the
West. Since then, Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov has issued a steady
stream of Cold War-style rhetoric to denounce NATO's airstrikes,
while denying Western charges of ethnic cleansing of Kosovar
Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Communist and Nationalist politicians have called for Moscow to
get involved militarily to help Yugoslavia, a fellow Slav and
Orthodox Christian state. Last Friday Yeltsin warned NATO
escalation could drag Russia into fighting and lead to a third
world war. The Kremlin also said Yeltsin supported a Yugoslav
effort to join the loose Russian-Belarus union.
</P>
<P>
   The Slavic alliance is a popular idea in Russia, but there are
signs the Kremlin is beginning to worry that uniting with
Yugoslavia would spoil Moscow's credibility as a potential peace
broker in the crisis. Tuesday, Yeltsin backed away from the idea of
an alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very complicated matter,'' Yeltsin's spokesman quoted
the president as saying. ``Haste will do no good.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin also tempered his daily criticism of NATO with an appeal
to regional governors not to let anti-American sentiments get out
of hand. ``We must not overdo it,'' the president told 19 governors
at a suburban retreat. ``Russia is part of Europe and cannot afford
to isolate itself from Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   A hint of Russia's new approach Tuesday was also offered by
Alexy II, patriarch of Russia's Orthodox Church. At a service
Tuesday in Belgrade Alexy II condemned NATO's bombardment. But he
also urged Serbs to do all they could to help ethnic Albanians
return to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin, meanwhile, Tuesday met with the leaders of Georgia
and Azerbaijan, and Wednesday is scheduled to visit Ukraine. All
three countries have protested the Slavic Union idea. All three
maintain a partnership with NATO, and their presidents will attend
the alliance's 50th anniversary celebrations in Washington this
week. Russia suspended its relationship with NATO over the
airstrikes, but Chernomyrdin's trip indicates Russia's desire to
minimize its differences with its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin's close ties with Russia's powerful state gas
company Gazprom give him added leverage in his negotiations. His
close relationship with Vice President Al Gore implies better
coordination between Moscow and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that will matter if Chernomyrdin's peace efforts
fail. The possibility of a NATO ground war remains a serious
concern among the Russian leadership _ both Ivanov and Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev warned Monday that NATO ground troop
operations in Serbia would escalate the war.
</P>
<P>
   If Chernomyrdin cannot forge a deal that halts the conflict,
Moscow's war of words could return in full force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
