<HEADER>
A6285 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-AIR-BOS &LR;      04-20 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-AIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP DETAILS CANCER RISK FROM _ BREATHING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: 1,3-butadiene is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An imperceptible mist of toxic chemicals in the air we breath
exposes the majority of New Englanders to an elevated risk of
cancer, including perhaps 4,500 who will develop some form of the
disease as a result, according to a groundbreaking new report by a
national environmental group.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the Environmental Defense Fund estimates that 360 of
every million Americans develop cancer as a result of these air
toxics, many of which are unfamiliar to the general public. But
rates vary widely from cities such as New York, where the rate is
four times the national average, to rural Essex County, Vt., which
is five times below the average.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of urban Connecticut and Massachusetts face this
region's greatest risks from these chemicals, according to the
report, thanks largely to motor vehicle tailpipes. The most
contaminated counties in New England, Fairfield County, Conn., and
Essex County, Mass., lay along major transportation routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers show that cars, trucks and small businesses tend
to be responsible much more of the nation's air toxicity than is
generally recognized,'' said David Roe, attorney for the New
York-based Environmental Defense Fund. ``Up to now, lack of
information has meant lack of attention to some of the biggest
causes of toxic air.''
</P>
<P>
   Although environmental officials have long targeted air
pollution such as summertime smog, the new report looks at a less
well understood part of the problem: the poisoning that occurs from
exposure to 148 different chemicals, many with obscure names such
as 1,3-butadiene, produced by motor vehicles, industry smokestacks
and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   States don't regularly test for most of these air toxics, and
scientists are unsure of all their effects.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, federal and state officials, along with fellow
environmentalists, praised the Environmental Defense Fund report,
posted on the internet at www.scorecard.org, as a powerful new tool
that will allow people to get detailed information on the
contaminants in their local air and compare it to other places.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's critically important that we get this issue on people's
radar screens. This is the first time that we and the public have
had any real numbers,'' said John DeVillars, regional administrator
for the US Environmental Protection Agency. ``Imperfect as the
numbers may be, they nevertheless demonstrate that this is a
significant problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Defense Fund report actually completes a job
begun by EPA researchers who calculated the levels of air toxics in
every census tract in the country, using 1990 pollution estimates.
But, under attack from urban mayors and scientists who questioned
whether the report was reliable, the EPA did not release their
findings.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Environmental Defense Fund obtained the EPA
research through a freedom of information request, and found that
the 1990-based pollution estimates were still generally accurate
today. The environmentalists then used federal guidelines to
estimate the risks from breathing these chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government created this information, but in some
ways, was frightened by its power,'' said Jason Grumet, executive
director of the Northeast States for Coordinated Air Use Management
in Boston, which advises states on air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Today, EPA agrees that its ``Cumulative Exposure Project'' is
generally not outdated, based on limited monitoring for air toxics
around the country. However, they say their pollution estimates are
not reliable below the county level.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Defense Fund report is ultimately an
indictment of motor vehicles, which account for 60 percent of the
cancer and non-cancer risks from air toxics across the country.
Only one of the top five hazardous chemicals _ a banned dry
cleaning fluid called carbon tetrachloride _ is not found in
tailpipe exhaust.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to New York City, which has the highest air toxics
levels, New England's air is relatively clean. Only Connecticut
(420 cancers per million residents) and Massachusetts (370 cancers
per million residents) had cancer risks that exceeded the national
average, while residents of Maine faced a risk of cancer from air
toxics that is about half the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the country's most contaminated places, the risks of
breathing are negligible compared to other high hazard activities
such as cigarette smoking. Nearly 150,000 of every million
cigarette smokers will die of cancer as a result of their habit.
</P>
<P>
   However, compared to the federal goal of providing clean air to
breath, the United States is failing. Almost 6 million people in
Massachusetts alone and 220 million people nationally live in
neighborhoods where the lifetime risk of cancer is at least 100
times the goal spelled out in the federal Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   For New England, all those air toxics translate into roughly
4,500 cancers among current residents, led by the 2,200 cancers in
Massachusetts and 1,400 in Connecticut, according to the report. In
addition, the region's residents face a significant but harder to
quantify risk of diseases other than cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, many of the policies that states and federal
agencies are pursuing against smog and other forms of pollution are
also expected to help reduce toxics, said DeVillars of EPA. For
example, EPA will soon require cleaner cars and cleaner fuel
nationally , while the state of Massachusetts will hold hearings
next week on more intensive vehicle emissions testing.
</P>
<P>
   And Nancy Seidman, deputy director of the Bureau of Waste
Prevention in the Massachusetts Department of Environmental
Protection, said she hopes the Environmental Defense Fund report
will give even greater urgency to controlling vehicle pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it does encourage people to think about how they use
their cars, (and) whether there's opportunities to combine trips or
take mass transit,'' Seidman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
