<HEADLINE>
RARE RIGHT WHALE FOUND DEAD OFF CAPE COD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just days after Massachusetts issued a warning for boaters to
watch for Northern right whales swimming in Cape Cod Bay, one of
the extremely rare animals has died off Wellfleet, Mass. Biologists
won't know the cause until an autopsy is performed.
</P>
<P>
   The dead animal, part of a group of 21 right whales that have
been feeding in eastern Cape Cod Bay, had no obvious signs of
injury. But researchers said that about half of all whales killed
by ship strikes suffer mainly internal injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The whale, nicknamed Staccato, had been observed by researchers
since 1974. She had borne at least six calves, making her one of
the most productive females among the remaining 300 right whales.
Although she was at least 30 years old, right whales can live to be
70 or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've known her for a long, long time. It's a sad loss,'' said
Amy Knowlton, a right whale researcher at the New England Aquarium
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists say the number of right whales has sunk so low that
the loss of even one whale, especially a female, is a cause for
concern. The species has been shrinking in the 1990s, due mainly to
collisions with boats, according to a recent study by researchers
at Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution and the University of
Massachusetts at Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Aerial observers spotted the whale Tuesday, floating about five
miles off Great Island in Wellfleet, just outside of an area where
the state Division of Marine Fisheries had urged ``extreme
caution'' by boaters because of an unusually large number of right
whales congregated there.
</P>
<P>
   An emergency response team from the Center for Coastal Studies
in Provincetown, Mass. reached Staccato by Tuesday afternoon, but
there was nothing to do for the animal except tow the carcass
ashore for an autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the National Marine Fisheries Service said it was
unlikely the autopsy could be performed until Wednesday. The Center
for Coastal Studies planned to tow the carcass to Truro, Mass.
where the analysis of the 40 foot-plus animal could be done on the
beach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
