<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-CARDINAL-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAYER SERVICE OVER POLICE SHOOTING MARKED BY A SIMPLE HUG 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a two-hour service filled with preaching, prayer
and psalms about healing and reconciliation, the most profound
statement came from a simple, silent gesture.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Calvin O. Butts III of Harlem's Abyssinian Baptist
Church, who less than a year ago denounced Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
as a racist, stepped off the podium at St. Patrick's Cathedral on
Tuesday and walked over to the first pew to shake the mayor's hand.
The two men ended up in a cordial embrace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing unites us like the humble, simple act of prayer,''
Butts told the crowd of about 1,500, including a wide array of New
York's religious and political leaders, who had gathered at the
invitation of Cardinal John O'Connor to help repair a city scarred
by the Feb. 4 police shooting of Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who was not listed on the program but was invited to
say a few words after the extraordinary handshake-turned-hug,
responded with perhaps his most conciliatory comments since the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our similarities are much greater than our differences,''
Giuliani said humbly. ``We're children of the same God. The mayor
needs to recognize that. The police do. And the citizens of the
city do.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 10 weeks after Diallo, a 22-year-old West African
immigrant, died in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment in a
barrage of 41 police bullets, the service aimed to shift civic
discourse over the incident from the fiery civil disobedience in
front of police headquarters to a more spiritual, forward-looking
sense of unity. Clergy from all faiths sat side by side, in robes
of black, magenta and white, vestments of gold, green and burgundy,
each offering similar messages about the common origin of all
people, regardless of race or belief.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a time for protest and a time for prayer,'' said
O'Connor. ``Today is a time for prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Quoting the Talmud and the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.'s Letter
from a Birmingham Jail, reading from the Q'uran and Corinthians II,
ministers and rabbis, imams and elected officials, police officers
and a high school valedictorian took turns at the microphone. Among
the dignitaries in the audience were Police Commissioner Howard
Safir; Bronx District Attorney Robert Johnson; and Mark Green, the
city's public advocate.
</P>
<P>
   In the ecumenical semicircle of clergy, the haberdashery
revealed the diversity of the service, from the crimson skullcap of
the Episcopalian bishop, E. Ron Taylor, to the gold cone atop the
head of Shayk Abd' Allah Latif Ali, from Sister Loretta Richards'
navy headscarf to Rabbi Robert N. Levine's knit yarmulke and the
large black hood of the Armenian Rev. Sooren Chinchinian.
</P>
<P>
   They offered prayers for Diallo's family, and for the four
police officers indicted on second-degree murder charges in his
death. They appealed for peace and justice, dignity and equality.
</P>
<P>
   But the fresh scars from weeks of tense and heated debate over
race and policing remained open and on view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do I feel authority seems to be at odds with society?''
asked Lorenzo Laboy, a Puerto Rican senior at Rice High School
whose harassment by the police was featured in an articles in The
New York Times last month. ``We don't want to be the scapegoat for
society's problems. Are the leaders of tomorrow going to have to
solve a problem that the leaders of today have been unwilling to
solve?''
</P>
<P>
   Noticeably absent from the service were Diallo's parents, who
met with the cardinal last month, and the Rev. Al Sharpton, who has
led dozens of demonstrations against police brutality since the
shooting. Sharpton said in an interview afterward that he boycotted
the event because the program did not include families of victims
of brutality or ministers who had been among the nearly 1,200
people arrested protesting the shooting last month. Representatives
of his National Action Network had been asked to give the
invocation but canceled at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like me saying I'm going to have a reconciliation service
on Yugoslavia and not invite the Albanians,'' Sharpton said. ``I
always like to see people act civil to each other, but I definitely
don't think it should be billed as reconciliation around Amadou.''
</P>
<P>
   The embrace between Giuliani and Butts, he added, ``has as much
to do with the police brutality movement as Yogi Berra making up
with George Steinbrenner.''
</P>
<P>
   Butts stunned city officials and black leaders alike last spring
when he called Giuliani a racist who was on the verge of turning
New York into a fascist state. Butts, whose political alliances
have included Gov. George Pataki but excluded Sharpton, has
previously spoken out about the Diallo case but has not been a
leader in the protest movement.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said Tuesday afternoon that Butts' gesture ``was part
of the spirit'' of O'Connor's interfaith service.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reciprocated in trying to demonstrate whatever differences
we have we should put aside,'' he said. ``We both worship the same
God.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That was the theme of nearly every speech at the cathedral, as
ministers and lay people pointed out that the diversity of New York
City _ and, indeed, the world _ had grown from a common seed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to go through justice to get to peace,'' the Rev.
James Goode, a Franciscan friar, said in a sermon that earned
several standing ovations. ``Are we willing to be a little
uncomfortable, so we can all be a little more comfortable?
</P>
<P>
   ``What are we willing to give up for the cause of justice? What
are we willing to give up to raise up one another?'' he demanded of
the audience. ``Let us never be so busy fighting each other that we
don't realize it is far more important to fight for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Joanne Henry, 59, a cosmetologist who lives in East Harlem, said
attending Tuesday's prayer service was a natural extension of her
marching over the Brooklyn Bridge behind Sharpton last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe God is sending out a message with Amadou Diallo,''
she said. ``We need a total circle to correct the injustice of New
York. People need to understand, enough is enough. We need to make
sure people hear all of the messages of today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
