<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6301 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUPONT-MUSEUM-$ADV25-     04-20 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUPONT-MUSEUM-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRECTING THE ERRORS OF A BENEFACTOR'S WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del.)   (For release Sunday, April 25)  
 (bl)  
 By RITA REIF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINTERTHUR, Del. _ Henry Francis du Pont probably did not know
where history ended and fantasy began when he devised the American
period rooms for the museum here that bears his name. Apparently
nobody else has known the difference either. Museum officials long
insisted that the rooms reflected life in America between 1640 and
1860.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 30 years after du Pont's death and nearly 50 years after
his mansion became the Henry Francis du Pont Winterthur Museum,
visitors are being told that, yes, du Pont erred. But guides will
point out the inaccuracies in only 20 of his favorite rooms among
the museum's 175. They have been returned to the way he had
arranged them, mistakes and all. They had been changed over the
years as masterpieces were refurbished, added or taken away to be
shown elsewhere. While experts have rarely doubted the authenticity
of the furniture, they have questioned the decor of some rooms
because objects were shown in ways that did not always jibe with
historical data.
</P>
<P>
   Rooms that were supposed to simulate those in homes of Colonial
or Federal America were actually arranged in ways that were unheard
of until the Victorian era, the turn of the century or even modern
times. The placing of furniture in conversation groupings, for
example, was introduced in the mid-19th century. Oriental rugs came
into use 50 years later. Crystal chandeliers throughout a house
were a bounty too costly even for aristocrats 200 years ago, and
the 15 at Winterthur may represent the total number that existed in
homes throughout the colonies. Cut flowers in punch bowls first
became popular in the flapper age. About the same time, high chests
and wing chairs were moved from bedrooms to parlors, since bed
linens by then were stored elsewhere and potties were gone from
such chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Lanmon, the director and chief executive officer of
Winterthur, prefers to look upon du Pont's decorating errors as
``misconceptions.'' Lanmon had learned of them while he was a
graduate student at Winterthur in the 1960s and later a curator,
and he wanted to address the inconsistencies when he returned as
the museum director in 1992. They also concerned Brock Jobe,
another Winterthur alumnus, who returned to the museum as deputy
director for collections in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both came in with the same idea in mind,'' Lanmon said.
``And we were both eager to make sure that du Pont would be better
understood and appreciated for assembling the largest and one of
the finest collections of American decorative arts.''
</P>
<P>
   Du Pont became a nonstop collector of Americana beginning in
1919, when he bought an 18th-century maple table. He insisted on
authenticity and the finest quality in the furnishings that he
purchased for the period rooms. `` du Pont often told others that
he wanted the style of these rooms `to be the way it was in early
America,''' Lanmon said. ``But Winterthur is still primarily a
collection of objects, not period rooms.''
</P>
<P>
   And the rooms, he added, expressed du Pont's taste. ``This is
how the rich lived in du Pont's world,'' Lanmon said. ``He
entertained the nobility of Europe and the wealthy of America in
what he viewed as his country house, until it became a museum. He
made early America fit that mold.''
</P>
<P>
   What the decor of houses in America looked like before 1860 was
not known until the 1970s, when several scholarly books on the
subject were published. Lanmon and his colleagues struggled with
the prospect of correcting the historical inaccuracies in the rooms
before going ahead with the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to make them as accurate as you possibly can,''
Jobe said. ``But the reality is that du Pont had created spaces
that, architecturally and from a furnishings standpoint, were
extremely challenging to retrofit as they might have been in an
earlier era. Historical accuracy is a moving target. The way a
period room looks reflects an understanding of history at the time
it was created.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everything was returned to the rooms. Absent are the
gooseneck lamps: du Pont had them placed in the bedrooms when
guests arrived and had them whisked away after dinner when he led
guests on a tour of the house only to have them brought back when
everyone turned in for the night.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, guides used flashlights to lead visitors through
the rooms, but once a new lighting system is in place, Lanmon wants
to see the flashlights done away with. ``For years visitors had
complained that they could not see the furniture across the room
and the paintings on the walls,'' he said. ``When our lighting
program is completed in 2001, I want to see a great bonfire of the
flashlights.''
</P>
<P>
   The new lighting has already improved the visibility in these
rooms and, on completion, will brighten the rooms throughout the
museum. A series of computerized floodlights and spotlights,
concealed in tracks above the ceilings in the rooms, will simulate
several levels of illumination: natural light, candlelight or, on
occasion, a more intense light equal to that available in modern
offices.
</P>
<P>
   In whatever light, these rooms bristle with one man's ideas of
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's celebrate this man's taste,'' Jobe said. ``It's the glue
that holds this place together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
