<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, April 25,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WU-CHINESE-FILMS (Undated) _ Wu Tianming is well acquainted with
the whims of fortune: During the 1980s, as an acclaimed director,
he headed Xian Film Studio, the cradle of the New Chinese Cinema,
which burst upon the international scene with the force of a
revelation. Less than a decade later, he was reduced to running a
video store in Los Angeles. Today, Wu, at 60, is once again working
as a director in China. On a recent visit to New York, he looked
back on these twists of fate with remarkable good humor. By leslie
Camhi.
</P>
<P>
   NICHOLS-AWARD (New York) _ Mike Nichols, having moved from comic
duologues with Elaine May from their student life at the University
of Chicago, to theater (winning seven Tony's as a Broadway director
and one as a producer) to film, will be honored by the Film Society
of Lincoln Center on May 3 with an annual lifetime achievement
award that first went to Charlie Chaplin in 1972 and was given to
Martin Scorsese last year. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SWAN-LAKE-BALLET (Undated) _ George Balanchine once told Peter
Martins: ``You know, dear, we should call all ballets `Swan Lake.'
People will come.'' Martins certainly hopes people will come to the
complete ``Swan Lake'' he is staging for the New York City Ballet.
It opens the company's spring, 50th-anniversary season at the New
York State Theater on Thursday night and will be performed through
May 9. By Jack Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   DANCE-ARCHIVE (New York) _ Four centuries of ballet tradition
and evolution are encoded in the bodies and minds of the dancers'
teachers and coaches: in Frederic Franklin, one of the last of the
Ballet Russe de Monte Carlo stars of the 1930s, in the great Soviet
ballerina Irina Kolpakova, who performed with the Kirov Ballet in
Leningrad from the 1950s through the mid-1980s, and in Georgina
Parkinson, a leading ballerina with England's Royal Ballet in its
late glory days through the 1970s. The first recorded attempts to
codify dance steps in a script of symbols occurred in mid-15th
century Italy. Today, whole ballets and modern-dance works are
written out and quickly retrievable in computer programs, down to
the smallest steps and gestures and most complex positionings and
travels of dancers across the stage. By Jennifer Dunning.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THEATER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE-BOOK (Undated) _ Harold Bloom, in his recent book,
``Shakespeare: The Invention of the Human,'' leaves no doubt of his
irritation with most of the interpretations he has encountered in a
lifetime of worshiping the plays; for him, the more daring the
attempt, the more excruciating the experience. Here and there in
his 741 pages, Bloom dredges up a kind word about a legendary turn
by an actor whom he has never seen _ Kean or Irving as Shylock _ or
a production that he saw long ago: most memorably for him, the
Henry plays with Ralph Richardson as Falstaff and, incidentally,
Laurence Olivier alternating between Hotspur and Shallow. By Walter
Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DUKAS-MUSIC (Undated) _ If the average American knows the name
of the French composer Paul Dukas at all, it is probably in
connection with an image of Mickey Mouse, wearing a baggy red robe
and a wizard's hat, battling anthropomorphic broomsticks to the
strains of Dukas' ``Sorcerer's Apprentice.'' Walt Disney's use of
that piece in the movie ``Fantasia'' made Dukas more famous than he
might have dreamed, or even hoped. By David Mermelstein.
</P>
<P>
   GUBAIDULINA-MUSIC (Undated) _ A woman among composers; a
freethinker among Soviet apparatchiks; a Christian among atheists;
an Easterner, half Tatar, among Europeans; a modernist among
reactionaries, and a reactionary among modernists, Sofia
Gubaidulina has lived with many conflicts, both with the outside
world and within herself. Her arrival, in her 50s and 60s, at
moments of extraordinary musical power has been a triumph of
persistence and self-searching. Ms. Gubaidulina, now 67, has become
a great light, and her achievement has happily been matched by
steadily increasing public recognition, which reaches a culmination
in New York on Thursday evening, when two big new works will be
presented almost simultaneously: ``Two Paths,'' at Avery Fisher
Hall, and ``In the Shadow of the Tree,'' at Carnegie Hall. By Paul
Griffiths.
 &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   POP-MUSIC-IDENTITY (Undated) _ ``Identity is the crisis can't
you see,'' declared the female singer Marion Elliott, better known
as Poly Styrene, in a 1978 punk rock song. Proving the prescience
of Ms. Elliott's words, a number of musicians have begun to explore
notions of identity, so often a part of pop music's appeal, by
adopting not just one pseudonym but many. They make the continual
reinventing of musical personas perhaps as entertaining and
meaningful as the music itself. By Michael Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DUPONT-MUSEUM (Winterthur, Del.) _ Henry Francis du PONT
probably did not know where history ended and fantasy began when he
devised the American period rooms for the museum here that bears
his name. Apparently nobody else has known the difference either.
Museum officials long insisted that the rooms reflected life in
America between 1640 and 1860. Now, 30 years after du Pont's death
and nearly 50 years after his mansion became the Henry Francis du
Pont Winterthur Museum, visitors are being told that, yes, du Pont
erred. But guides will point out the inaccuracies in only 20 of his
favorite rooms among the museum's 175. They have been returned to
the way he had arranged them, mistakes and all. By Rita Reif.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-NEWSROOM (Undated) _ On ``The Newsroom,'' Ken Finkleman's
dry, riotous take on a Canadian television news organization, any
war, plane crash or nuclear accident had better have the right spin
potential if it hopes to compete for attention with who gets the
prime indoor parking spot or which assistant to hire, the black
lesbian or the blond ski bunny. A huge hit on Canadian television,
``The Newsroom'' made its way south to PBS in 1997 (last New Year's
Eve, WNET in New York reran all 13 episodes back to back) and has
recently been released in a four-tape set by Acorn Media. By Peter
M. Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   MAD-TV (Los Angeles) _ ``Mad TV,'' is a sketch-show series that
Quincy Jones and David Salzman proposed in 1995 as a way for Fox
television to siphon away the X-chromosome contingent from NBC's
``Saturday Night Live'' audience. (``Mad TV'' starts at 11 p.m., a
half-hour before ``Saturday Night Live.'') But if the boys and
girls in baggy jeans whooping and hollering in the bleachers at a
Friday night taping are any indication, the show has become a big
draw for 12- to 17-year-olds of both sexes. By Margy Rochlin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (`t' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-ADRIATIC (Rome) _ Kosovo casts a shadow over Adriatic
resorts. By John Tagliabue. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Fancy cars available for rent in
London; Creatures of the deep, on view in Monterey; 300th birthday
party for Williamsburg, Va.; A French painter's American links.
(Moved).
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Travel questions and answers: Greenwich
