<HEADLINE>
NEW RULES RESOLVE US-EU INTERNET PRIVACY DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New rules drafted this week by the US Department of Commerce and
the European Union to ensure the privacy of people who exchange
information over the Internet may provide Europeans with additional
protection while leaving Americans to fend for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The rules, announced Monday, are intended to resolve a dispute
between the Unilted States and Europe over the best way to
safeguard privacy on the Internet. Last October, the EU set strict
limits on the ways that companies in Europe can use personal
information obtained from customers. For instance, such data cannot
be shared with a third party without the subject's permission. But
the United States does not have similar regulations, so American
firms can resell customer information without permission.
</P>
<P>
   This has become a touchy problem because, through the Internet,
Europeans can buy goods from American firms not subject to European
privacy law. European governments and privacy activists warned that
unless American Internet companies adopted EU-style privacy rules,
they might be barred from selling to EU citizens. But the Clinton
administration insists that the Unilted States should retain its
policy of letting businesses set their own privacy standards. ``We
have a long history of voluntary regulation,'' said Commerce
Department spokesman Morrie Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and the European Union have been negotiating
to find a way around this, by designing a ``safe harbor'' _ a set
of rules for American companies that will bring them into adequate
compliance with European standards. Firms that want to sell to
Europeans over the Internet will be expected to adhere to these
safe-harbor rules.
</P>
<P>
   The latest draft of the rules would require firms to provide
notice to customers if they plan to sell personal information to
third parties. Customers would be able to refuse permission by
``opting out'' of such an arrangement, perhaps by checking a box on
a Web page asking that the information not be shared. If the box is
not checked, the company would be free to share the data. But in
cases involving very sensitive information, such as religion,
political views, or sexual practices, there could be no sharing of
the information unless a consumer specifically grants permission, a
practice called ``opting in.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, information could be shared only with other
companies that had agreed to follow the same privacy rules as the
firm collecting the data. Consumers would also be guaranteed the
right to see their data files and correct erroneous information.
</P>
<P>
   American privacy activists have long sought federal legislation
that would require all US companies to adhere to such practices.
But the safe-harbor rule would not be mandatory for American firms
when they do business with Americans. That doesn't sit well with
Marc Rotenberg, executive director of the Electronic Privacy
Information Center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing the consequences of the lack of a coherent
privacy policy in the United States,'' said Rotenberg, who argues
that the US government is trying to avoid a disruption in trade
with Europe, without improving privacy protections for Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Under-Secretary of Commerce David Aaron will meet with EU
representatives next week to continue negotiations on the
safe-harbor rules. The Commerce Department hopes to complete the
text next month and sign a binding agreement during a US-EU summit
meeting June 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
