</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-285&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PARATROOPERS ENTER TIRANA TO GUARD HELICOPTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN KIFNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ Hundreds of paratroopers from America's elite
rapid-response force have begun arriving at the scruffy airport
here, but their assignment _ standing guard over Apache helicopters
that have not yet arrived _ only underscored the improvisational
nature of NATO's strategy against Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The deployment of a battalion from the 82nd Airborne Division
was not announced by the Pentagon, but the paratroopers were
spotted at the airport, identifiable by their distinctive unit
patch, with the airborne tab and a double A in a circle, dating
back to a World War I detachment known as the ``all-American''
division.
</P>
<P>
   One brigade of the 82d Airborne is kept on constant ready alert
at all times as a quick-response force to a crisis anywhere in the
world, marking the division as one of the Army's most respected,
powerful fighting organizations.
</P>
<P>
   But, at least for the moment, their job here is not combat.
Instead, they will be, in effect, policemen far behind the lines
for the 48 Apache attack helicopters that were expected here any
day for the past two weeks. While these troops usually are reserved
for more complex operations, military officials said they were
called upon in this case because they were the only unit that could
be deployed quickly enough to protect the Army helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a query, the Defense Department confirmed that
700 soldiers from the division's 3rd Brigade, second battalion of
the 505th Parachute Infantry, had been dispatched here to provide
security for the Apaches. The troops were mostly infantry, but also
included military police, intelligence officers, supply experts and
medics, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite four weeks of NATO air and missile strikes, the Serbian
forces have continued unabated in their brutal campaign to drive
ethnic Albanians out of Kosovo province. In the last month they
have forced 600,000 refugees across the borders, NATO says, and
relief officials fear hundreds of thousands more are on their way
or in hiding, without food or water, in the forest and mountains.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs, far from being crippled by the assault, have poured
thousands of reinforcements into Kosovo, increased their use of
helicopters, mixed military vehicles into refugee convoys and
stepped up their sweeps to drive out ethnic Albanians, NATO
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the failure of the air strikes to stop the Serbian
campaign to depopulate Kosovo _ largely carried out in small-scale
tactics of a handful of armed, masked men terrorizing villages _
the NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, asked not only for more
planes but for first 24 then 48 Apache attack helicopters, which
are capable of close-in combat.
</P>
<P>
   The Apaches, with a reputation as tank-killers from the Persian
Gulf war, could operate either on their own or in support of
attacking ground troops. They have what the military calls a
``stand-off capability,'' meaning they can fire their rockets at a
target from as far as three miles away. The helicopters operate in
tandem with batteries of rockets with a maximum range of 180 miles
that are designed to knock out air defenses before the packs of
helicopters attack.
</P>
<P>
   But the Apaches were clearly an afterthought, not part of the
original plan. Clark and other commanders are reportedly furious at
the repeated delays in getting the Apaches here. The helicopters
are now believed to be at a U.S. military base in Italy, but even
after they arrive in Albania, military officials say, it could take
a week or so to get them operational.
</P>
<P>
   With the ramshackle airport here consumed with bringing in
relief supplies and ferrying some of the goods up to the isolated
mountain border point near Kukes, where there are more than 100,000
refugees in makeshift camps, there has been speculation that the
Apaches would be based farther north, near Lezhe, at an old
military airfield variously marked on maps as Gramsh or Gjader that
was used by U.S. planes operating over Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The long-awaited arrival of the Apaches has become a matter of
consuming interest here. Albanians and Kosovo refugees fervently
believe it will mark a turning point; American television networks
begin staking out the airport at dawn each day in hopes of new
pictures. There was a brief flurry of excitement Tuesday morning
when television personality Geraldo Rivera, broadcasting live from
a rooftop, spied two of the large helicopters constantly ferrying
relief supplies and mistakenly announced the Apaches had arrived.
</P>
<P>
   It is conceivable that, over time, the troops from the 82nd
Airborne could become the nucleus of a ground force, if the event
the alliance decides to add ground troops. Already, at a more
tightly guarded section of the airport, there are men whose
insignia marks them as members of the Army Special Forces or of the
Recon Marines.
</P>
<P>
   But a ground deployment could face formidable obstacles as the
Serbs dig in, mining roads and hiding their tanks and artillery in
civilian buildings. NATO officials now say they believe there are
40,000 Serbian troops in Kosovo. A standard military rule of thumb
says the ratio of attackers to dug-in defenders should be
three-to-one, which would mean a force of 120,000. U.S. doctrine in
the Gulf war, however, called for an absolutely overwhelming force,
even against an Iraqi enemy that folded in the first hours.
</P>
<P>
   And in any case, at the rate Kosovo is being depopulated, by the
time such a force could be assembled it is unlikely there would be
any ethnic Albanians left to protect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
