<SLUG> BC-BANK-EARNINGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASE, BANC ONE AND WELLS FARGO CITE STRONG EARNINGS GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By TIMOTHY L. O'BRIEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several of the nation's big banks reported sharply higher
earnings Tuesday, with one of the biggest, Chase Manhattan Corp.,
posting robust trading gains comparable with the outsized results
already turned in by most of the country's big trading houses.
</P>
<P>
   Benefiting from an unusually strong trading season spurred by a
rebound from the global financial crisis of last fall, Chase said
first-quarter net earnings leapt 61 percent, to $1.17 billion, or
$1.32 a share, from $725 million, or 80 cents a share, in the first
quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Chase's operating income, a more accurate reflection of the
company's core earnings strength than net income, rose a more
modest 11 percent, to $1.17 billion from $1.05 billion. Net income
in the comparable quarter a year earlier included a reorganization
charge of $521 million.
</P>
<P>
   Although Chase, the country's third-largest bank by assets, beat
analysts' expectations of $1.25 a share, the stock was sharply
lower Tuesday as investors appeared to be concerned about the
unpredictability of such big trading returns and Chase's ability to
maintain its earnings momentum. The shares, which have more than
doubled in the last year, fell $2, to $83.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given how everyone has been blowing through their numbers, I
think there were higher expectations for Chase,'' said Sally Pope
Davis, an analyst with Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. ``But nobody should
complain about these numbers, because they're very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Chase's revenue in the quarter rose 11 percent, to $5.14 billion
from $4.62 billion in last year's first quarter. Revenue from the
New York bank's global corporate business, Chase's most important
segment and the one that includes trading, rose 8 percent, to $2.6
billion, while profits in the unit rose 11 percent, to $882
million. Trading revenue rose 21 percent to a record $837 million.
But investment banking fees fell 12 percent, to $317 million, on
weakness in the leveraged-finance business.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer unit, Chase's other main business, saw sales climb
12 percent, to $2.16 billion. But that business is much less
profitable than Chase's corporate business, generating earnings of
$350 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One Corp., the fourth-largest bank in the country and the
product of last year's merger of Bank One and First Chicago NBD
Corp., also reported strong earnings Tuesday. It said profits
jumped 23 percent, to $1.15 billion, or 96 cents a share, from $933
million, or 78 cents a share, in the first quarter last year. The
Chicago-based bank said that on an operating basis, earnings rose
nearly 16 percent, to $1.05 billion, or 88 cents a share, from $909
million, or 76 cents, meeting analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But the shares slipped 25 cents, to $59, Tuesday as investors'
confidence in the bank weakened.
</P>
<P>
   Bank One's stock was severely battered in the wake of last
year's merger as questions arose about the company's ability to
rein in expenses and still increase revenue, although it has
recovered smartly in recent months. But while yesterday's results
showed renewed expense discipline, Bank One still reported numbers
that, in Wall Street parlance, were ``noisy.'' The results included
$360 million of one-time gains offset by merger and restructuring
charges of $204 million.
</P>
<P>
   The bank also posted a big increase in nonperforming assets, a
harbinger of possible lending problems. It had $1.15 billion in
nonperforming assets in the quarter, up from $819 million at the
end of last year and far above the $670 million at the end of 1997.
Bank One said the recent surge was a result of $302 million of
problem loans to financial services and energy companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, however, were cautiously optimistic about the
bank's outlook. ``The issue still is whether the company will grow
the rest of the year,'' said Henry Dickson, an analyst at Salomon
Smith Barney. ``So far, I think the answer is yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo &AMP; Co. of San Francisco, the seventh-largest bank in
the country, said its first-quarter earnings rose 29 percent, to
$884 million, or 53 cents a share, from $684 million, or 41 cents a
share in the comparable quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   The results exceeded analysts' expectations of 50 cents a share,
sending the bank's shares up $1.25 Tuesday, to $42.375. Wells
attributed its strong performance to solid growth in mortgage
lending and returns from venture capital investments.
</P>
</TEXT>
