<SLUG> BC-LYCOS-LEADS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LYCOS TOPS YAHOO IN INTERNET RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For months, Internet company Lycos Inc. has said its on-line
audience would soon surpass that of industry bellwether Yahoo Inc.
</P>
<P>
   According to a leading Internet ratings firm, that's exactly
what has happened.
</P>
<P>
   New figures from Media Metrix Inc. found that 51.8 percent of
the nation's Internet users visited a Lycos Web site last month,
compared with 50.8 percent for Yahoo. New York-based Media Metrix
is generally considered the most trusted source of data on the
popularity of the top Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The Media Metrix survey found that just under 32 million people
visited Lycos-owned sites in March, compared to 31.2 million
visitors to Yahoo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world and just about every one in it said I was quixotic
in my quest to pass Yahoo,'' said Lycos chief executive Bob Davis
from company headquarters in Waltham, Mass. ``And here we are and
we've done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lycos's growth has been driven by a series of acquisitions of
other major Internet companies, such as the Tripod and Angelfire
Web site hosting services, the WhoWhere Internet directory service,
and the Wired Digital news service, as well as the Lycos and Hotbot
Internet search sites.
</P>
<P>
   Each site is run as a separate entity, but all are linked under
an entity known as the Lycos Network.
</P>
<P>
   The Media Metrix ratings for Lycos are based on the total
visitors to all sites in the Lycos Network. By contrast, Yahoo
builds all its services around a single core site.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos is presently moving to close its controversial deal to
merge with media properties now owned by USA Networks Inc.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report Tuesday on the CNBC financial news TV
channel, USA Networks chief executive Barry Diller is in talks with
possible partners who may join his bid for Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   Diller refused to comment to CNBC on the report, which raises
the possibility that the USA/Lycos deal could be restructured.
Major shareholders have bitterly criticized the deal, saying it
offers too low a return to Lycos shareholders. Lycos's largest
shareholder, CMGI Inc., an Internet venture capital firm, opposes
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos stock closed down $1 7/8 to $73 7/8 on the Nasdaq .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
