</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-WEST-MATCHUPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL PLAYOFF CAPSULES
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   EDMONTON VS. DALLAS
</P>
<P>
   Records: Edmonton 33-37-12, second in Northwest; Dallas
51-19-12, first in Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth quarter: Edmonton 10-9-3, Dallas 12-8-2.
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Dallas won 3-0-1.
</P>
<P>
   Playoffs in decade: Edmonton is 27-31; Dallas is 36-32 with one
finals appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: Edmonton stunned Dallas in the opening round two
years ago. Don't expect a repeat. The Oilers' goaltending has been
inconsistent all season, thanks to the free-agency loss of Curtis
Joseph. The Oilers are young and fast but short on experience and
point production, particularly with injuries to Bill Guerin. While
Edmonton loses players to the open market, Dallas gains them (Brett
Hull, Ed Belfour). The Stars had the league's best record,
including a franchise-record 51 wins, allowed the fewest goals
(168, 2.05) and appear primed for a title run. The absence of
suspended captain/defenseman Derian Hatcher shouldn't make a huge
difference this round.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Dallas in five games.
</P>
<P>
   SAN JOSE VS. COLORADO
</P>
<P>
   Records: San Jose 31-33-18, fourth in Pacific; Colorado
44-28-10, first in Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth quarter: San Jose 11-7-4, Colorado 14-6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Colorado won 3-1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Playoffs in decade: San Jose is 13-18; Colorado/Quebec is 33-25
with one Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: With a hot Patrick Roy in goal and forwards who seem
to have committed themselves under first-year coach Bob Hartley,
the Avalanche would have been among the Cup favorites even before
adding Theo Fleury at the trading deadline. Forward Vincent
Damphousse was a nice pickup for the Sharks, but their only hope in
this series is if goalies Mike Vernon and Steve Shields can shut
down the Avalanche's deep attack. Down the stretch, Shields was
10-2-3 and Vernon 0-4-1, but the latter is expected to start the
opener.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Avalanche in four games.
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM VS. DETROIT
</P>
<P>
   Records: Anaheim 35-34-13, third in Pacific; Detroit 43-32-7,
first in Central.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth quarter: Anaheim 9-9-4, Detroit 12-8-2.
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Detroit won 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Playoffs in decade: Anaheim is 4-7; Detroit is 67-44 with two
Stanley Cups and one finals loss.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: The Red Wings won eight in a row after late-season
trades for Chris Chelios, Wendel Clark, Ulf Samuelsson and Bill
Ranford. The deals mostly woke up others on the roster, leading to
better defensive play by the defenseman and forwards. Anaheim
doesn't have the depth to compete: the attack is limited to two
players, Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne, who combined for 86 goals
during the season but figure to wear down against coach Scotty
Bowman's rotation of lines. The Mighty Ducks went only 1-5-2 in
their last eight and are 1-10-3 all-time at Joe Louis Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Detroit in five games.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS VS. PHOENIX
</P>
<P>
   Records: St. Louis 37-32-13, second in Central; Phoenix
39-31-12, second in Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth quarter: St. Louis 11-8-3; Phoenix 9-11-2.
</P>
<P>
   Season series: St. Louis won 2-1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Playoffs in decade: St. Louis is 33-37; Phoenix/Winnipeg is
10-16.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy: The Coyotes are the best example of why the early
part of the season should be ignored. They played .800 hockey
(15-3-2) through 20 games, then .468 (24-28-10) the rest of the
way. Worse, they have lost their second-best player, forward Jeremy
Roenick, for the playoffs with a fractured jaw and they weren't a
high-scoring team to begin with. Phoenix's best hope is for a
tight-checking, low-scoring series, punctuated by the goaltending
of Nikolai Khabibulin. But the Blues have a solid attack with Pavol
Demitra, Geoff Courtnall and Pierre Turgeon, and Al MacInnis
anchors a strong power play.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: St. Louis in six games.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
