<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITECH-SECRETARIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Report says secretaries will become coordinators
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Technology and an increasingly mobile work force will
transform many of today's secretaries and administrative assistants
into information coordinators.
</P>
<P>
   In the next six years, information coordinators will be the
``ground control'' for the rapidly evolving workplace, according to
a report on the office of the future. ICs will serve as the
critical communication link among far-flung employees, people
working on projects and telecommuters. They will also provide
training for teams working on new technologies, according to the
report by OfficeTeam, an international staffing company in Menlo
Park, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will provide the necessary human element to `smooth out'
electronic communication,'' said Diane Domeyer, executive director
of OfficeTeam.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Office of the Future: 2005'' forecast comes as many of the
nation's estimated 3 million office professionals mark Professional
Secretaries Day today.
</P>
<P>
   The OfficeTeam study found that administrative assistants will
have a major impact on selecting and implementing new technologies,
according to 56 percent of the 150 executives at the nation's top
1,000 firms. They also will assume more responsibility in an
entry-level way for Internet research, desktop publishing, help
desk or computer training and assistance as well as Web page
development. They will also be called on to manage more projects.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to technical competence, people skills will be at a
premium, the study found. Seventy-seven percent of the 1,400 chief
information officers polled said that increased use of technology
will require workers to communicate more effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, it could well be your interpersonal and communication
skills that make or break your career,'' the study concludes.
</P>
<P>
   OfficeTeam commissioned an independent research firm to get a
realistic snapshot of the workplace in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what the office of the future looks like, according to
the research, as well as some of the top concerns:
</P>
<P>
   _ E-mail and videoconferencing will be the leading forms of
communication.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wireless communication, voice-activated technology and
personal digital assistants will be the three most prevalent forms
of technology.
</P>
<P>
   _ Self-managed work teams will increase productivity.
Eighty-four percent of executives believe employees have adopted a
better attitude toward teamwork in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Offices will be smaller and more people will telecommute.
Workspaces will also be open to accommodate teams of workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Balancing work and family will be the No. 1 career concern,
surpassing competitive pay and job security.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is little doubt that technology will virtually transform
the office of the future, with technical skills a prerequisite for
career success,'' the report noted.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Joyner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
