A6317 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP-COX     04-20 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STANLEYCUP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Third time will be charming _ if not 'dangerous' _ for Red Wings
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Detroit Red Wings overcame a 41-year NHL title
dought in 1997 that had turned Motown into Woetown, and then last
season they had to face several emotional obstacles to accomplish
the rare feat of consecutive Stanley Cups.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the Red Wings prepare to open the defense as two-time
hockey kings, they find themselves in an unenviable position. Many
people expect them to win it all, when reality screams otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations probably weren't as high last year as they are
now,'' Wings general manager Ken Holland said Tuesday. ``But now
we've won it two straight years, and we made all those deals at the
deadline and people expect us to do it again. But every team out
there is dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Some more than others. Detroit drew Anaheim as a first-round
opponent, which _ despite the Mighty Ducks' possession of two of
the league's top scorers, Teemu Selanne and Paul Kariya _ should
send the Red Wings into the second round. But some people think
that Colorado, the stronger team for most of the season, could end
Detroit's reign there.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, in fact, was only the third-best team in the Western
Conference during the season, behind the Avalanche and the Dallas
Stars. Colorado added high-scoring Theo Fleury to an already deep
lineup, and the Stars added Brett Hull in the offseason and
recorded a franchise record 51 wins.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Wings had to scramble to finish that high. They went
9-2-1 after a flurry of trades just before the deadline added Chris
Chelios, Wendel Clark, Ulf Samuelsson and Bill Ranford.
</P>
<P>
   The Wings did not have the best regular-season record in either
of their title seasons, but their road to the finals probably
wasn't this difficult. If they can pull it off, they would be the
first team team to win at least three straight Cups since the New
York Islanders won four in a row,1979-83.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've reached a point as a team where we really judge
our season on the postseason,'' forward Brendan Shanahan said.
``And that's a nice place to be. It says something for where we are
as an organization. We've kind of raised the bar and raised the
level of expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   By the admission of players and coaches, that attitude hurt the
Wings for most of this season. Holland's late-season deals added
depth to a roster that had been hurt by injuries and other moves,
but more importantly it seemed to wake up players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't necessarily make the trades to get the rest of the
team to respond,'' Holland said, ``but it certainly worked out that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Holland also knows better than to assume a series win over the
Ducks. In 1994, Detroit lost in the first round to San Jose. The
NHL playoffs annually presents upsets on the scale of the NCAA
Tournament. Last year, Colorado lost in the first round to
Edmonton, and New Jersey was stunned by Ottawa. Both losing head
coaches, Marc Crawford and Jacques Lemaire, lost their jobs despite
having won Stanley Cups. Detroit's Scotty Bowman isn't going to get
fired if the Wings lose, but he could retire, regardless of the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   This year's playoffs won't feature the NHL's all-time greatest
scorer, Wayne Gretzky, nor probably its current greatest player,
Eric Lindros, who is recovering from a collapsed lung and whose
Philadelphia team has a collapsed defense. The Flyers, who face
Toronto, might not make it out of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The opening round will feature Dallas trying to avoid another
playoff collapse, Ottawa trying to prove that its 103 points in the
regular season wasn't a fluke and Dominik Hasek again trying to
carry the Buffalo Sabres on his back.
</P>
<P>
   Holland is anything but overconfident.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you've done for six months means nothing,'' he said.
``All you have to do is come off your game a little, and in 10 to
12 days your season is over. People think we're an overwhelming
favorite to beat Anaheim because we've won two Cups. But I don't
buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Schultz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
