<HEADER>
A6319 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS21-COX     04-20 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS STRUGGLES FOR RESPONSE TO BALKAN FIGHTING
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Amid disarray in Congress over what to do about the
undeclared war against Yugoslavia, a bipartisan group of senators
led by John McCain, R-Ariz., introduced a resolution Tuesday
authorizing President Clinton to use ``all necessary force.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, the House Republican leadership said it
would allow a vote next week on whether to bring U.S. forces home
under the War Powers Act.
</P>
<P>
   And somewhere in the middle, lawmakers led by Sens. Max Cleland,
D-Ga., and Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, are pressing the president to
provide ``clear and distinct objectives'' and tell Congress what
``defines the endpoint'' for the military operation.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to be released Wednesday, the senators reminded
Clinton and Defense Secretary William Cohen of a measure passed
last year requiring the administration to give such information
whenever deploying more than 500 personnel on a military mission.
</P>
<P>
   It was far from clear whether any of the efforts would bring
decisive action.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he hoped his resolution ``will encourage the
administration and our allies to find the courage and resolve to
prosecute this war in the manner most likely to result in its early
and successful conclusion.'' Presumably, that would include ground
troops if Clinton changed his mind and decided to employ them.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, a presidential candidate and a consistent voice of
concern on the Balkan crisis, told his colleagues, ``Our central
purpose is to encourage Congress to meet its responsibilities,
responsibilities that we have thus far evaded.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it was unclear when the Senate leadership would permit
a vote on the proposal, which is cosponsored by Sen. Joseph Biden,
D-Del. and several other members.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers said they were in no hurry to make a final
determination on a war that many say they prefer to leave as the
president's responsibility for now, despite widespread
dissatisfaction with its conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it doesn't get to the floor very soon,'' Sen. Don
Nickles, R-Okla., said of McCain's plan. Nickles said he would not
want to see the resolution approved, but neither would he want it
to be defeated because of the message it might send to President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertain responses to the escalating crisis came as a new
delegation of lawmakers returned from a fact-finding tour of the
Balkans, voicing fresh concerns over the Clinton administration's
handling of the crisis. Some members took note of the arrival
Tuesday morning of 24 Apache attack helicopters and the troops to
support them.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Apaches, we're coming as close as possible to a
ground war,'' said Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Ala., the Appropriations
Committee chairman and one of the leaders of the delegation.
</P>
<P>
   A staunch critic of the NATO air war in the Balkans, Stevens
said he returned believing that ``the stubbornness of the State
Department has got us into a war that I don't know how we're going
to get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Stevens and other Republican leaders made it clear that
they intend to grant the Clinton administration's request for $6
billion for the Balkans operation and to double or even triple the
size of the spending package. House Majority Leader Dick Armey,
R-Texas, has suggested that $10 billion may not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have also used the request as an opportunity to
blast the Clinton administration's record on defense.
</P>
<P>
   In a period when the U.S. military has conducted some two dozen
``operational events,'' Armey charged, ``the Clinton-Gore
administration has drastically reduced our military capabilities''
and reduced the armed services by more than 800,000 personnel.
</P>
<P>
   That criticism has become a refrain among Republicans amid
widespread reports of shortages of spare parts, recruitment
shortfalls, and, most recently, the admission that supplies of
air-launched cruise missiles are running out.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary Cohen conceded last week to the Senate Armed
Services Committee that the air war in the Balkans, which is
expected to involve close to 1,000 U.S. warplanes if all of NATO's
requests are filled, has been a drain on resources.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mac Collins, R-Ga., a member of the weekend congressional
fact-finding mission to visit U.S. troops and refugee camps in the
Balkan region, echoed the call for increased military funding.
``Our nation is involved in a war that has greatly depleted our
defense resources and has jeopardized campaigns in other regions of
the world,'' he said. ``We have no choice other than to replenish
our resources.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
