u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANECRASH-FOLO-COX     04-20 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANECRASH-FOLO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2 plane crash victims were veteran pilots
 &HT;    By Chris Reinolds
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Veteran pilots Ted McFann Sr. and Dan Bouck flew
together Monday in a simulated dogfight over Bartow County.
</P>
<P>
   Bouck, 51, worked for Sky Warriors, an Atlanta company that
sells combat flight fantasy experiences. McFann, 60, was a
third-time Sky Warriors customer.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were killed when their military trainer crashed Monday
afternoon while engaged in a mock dogfight with another plane. The
two people in the second plane returned to Fulton County
Airport-Brown Field unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   National Transportation Safety Board officials said the T-34
model A plane crashed at 12:51 p.m. The single-engine plane, built
in 1957, smashed into trees in a field about 10 miles north of
Cartersville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB investigator Phil Powell said investigators are examining
the plane's systems and fractures in the wreckage to determine what
caused the crash. Powell said he had brief statements from
witnesses and planned to conduct further interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Sky Warriors issued a written statement that said: ``Our
heartfelt sympathy is extended to the families and friends of those
on board the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sky Warriors has operated without incident for eight years,
and everyone associated with the company is both shocked and
saddened by what has occurred. It is truly a tragic loss for our
closely bonded squadron.''
</P>
<P>
   Both McFann and Bouck were members of the Delta Airline Pilots
Association in Atlanta. Andy Deane, ALPA union spokesman, said
McFann was a major volunteer in the group and was well liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Capt. McFann from the time I started flying 24 years
ago in Miami,'' Deane said. McFann served on various committees and
as a representative to the Master Executive Council, which governs
ALPA, a pilots labor union with about 50,000 members in the United
States, Deane said. Atlanta is the largest council.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very polished and professional,'' Deane said, ``in fact
so much so one of his last positions with us was chairman of the
professional standards committee.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee deals with the professional conduct of flight
crews. Dean described McFann as ``thorough and hard-working.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a very hard worker for the interests of Delta pilots,''
Deane said.
</P>
<P>
   Even after McFann retired more than a year ago, he still
attended ALPA meetings and social events.
</P>
<P>
   McFann and Bouck's attraction to Sky Warriors is natural, Deane
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us come to the job from a military career,'' he said.
``If you're not shooting real bullets at each other, it's an
incredibly exhilarating sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since the romance of WW I and open cockpits, the Red
Baron and dogfights, ... there has been a romance to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Lynch, a close friend of the McFann family, said the
retired pilot was ``very important in a lot of pilots lives. Ted
was always there for them.'' She said he served in the Navy, but
did not fly in wartime. McFann's son works for Delta, but not as a
pilot, she said.
</P>
<P>
   McFann, who lived in Alpharetta, was born in Marion, Ohio, and
served in the Navy. He was an officer with the Miami Police
Department before joining Delta in 1966. He was honored for 31
years of service when he retired in 1997. When he retired, he was
flying international flights on a L-1011 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the Alpharetta Presbyterian Church and is
survived by his wife, Barbara; a daughter, a son, grandchildren and
a sister. The funeral is scheduled for Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Sturniolo, a Delta pilot who was based in Miami with
McFann, has known him for about 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted was very outgoing,'' he said with a chuckle. ``He was
always heard in an audience. He was the consummate master of
ceremonies. I saw him master a major retirement party of 600 people
_ he commanded attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Sturniolo said McFann liked to tell a story about when he was a
motorcycle cop in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``While working, he was actually run over by a Orange Bowl
float. He liked to tell that story,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bouck's family could not be reached for comment. Funeral
arrangements for the Atlanta resident have yet to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   John Kennedy, a Delta spokesman, said Bouck had worked for the
Atlanta-based airline for 21 years. He was based in Atlanta and as
captain flew 767s and 757s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my understanding that several Delta pilots are involved
with the Sky Warriors,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   There are only three actual-flight air combat simulation firms
in the country including Sky Warriors. The FAA classifies these
operations as flight instruction businesses. Its only stipulation
is that there must be a certified flight instructor in each
airplane.
</P>
<P>
   The combat simulators themselves have rigid safety rules.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Reinolds writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
