<HEADER>
A6325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-AUTOS-NYT &LR;      04-20 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-AUTOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZILIAN GOVERNOR DELAYS GM AND FORD PLANS TO BUILD FACTORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ Citing the pressure from other priorities on
his state's finances, an opposition governor in southern Brazil has
disrupted plans by General Motors and Ford Motor Co. to build two
car factories regarded as prototypes for automobile manufacturing
of the future.
</P>
<P>
   GM has delayed by at least six months its plans to produce
compact cars at a plant code-named the ``Blue Macaw'' project in
Rio Grande do Sul, Brazil's southernmost state. The delay could
affect the automaker's plans for similar factories in the United
States and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has put on hold plans to build a plant for its ``Project
Amazon,'' also intended to produce inexpensive small cars.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 10,000 jobs related to the factories and more than $1
billion of investments are at stake as the two leading automakers,
already frustrated by a plunge in car sales as Brazil struggles
with recession, seek an agreement with Olivio Dutra, the outspoken
Workers Party governor of Rio Grande do Sul, an industrial state of
10 million people bordering Argentina and Uruguay.
</P>
<P>
   Dutra, who took office in January, suspended an accord that his
predecessor had made with GM and Ford to provide the two companies
with about $280 million of financing and infrastructure in exchange
for their decision to build the factories near Porto Alegre, the
state capital.
</P>
<P>
   One of the rising stars of the Workers Party, the main organized
opposition to President Fernando Henrique Cardoso's government,
Dutra contends that his state needs the money previously designated
for the factories to finance programs in education, health care and
housing. His statements, peppered with nationalistic sentiment,
have resulted in an impasse between the state government and the
two companies.
</P>
<P>
   The president of GM's Brazilian subsidiary, Frederick Henderson,
said in an interview that ``there are certain things we need like
gas, waste-water treatment, roads and electricity, to proceed.''
Without the government's help in finishing these projects, the GM
factory will not be ready to produce cars until mid-2000 _ about
six months later than expected, Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict between the car producers and Dutra is part of a
wider argument, in which several Brazilian states have resorted to
unorthodox measures to shore up their finances. Another governor,
Itamar Franco of Minas Gerais in central Brazil, declared a
moratorium on his state's debt payments to the federal government
at the beginning of the year, a decision that contributed to a
market panic and a currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Dutra also threatened to default on his state's debt, although
he backed off after pressure from Cardoso. He has since refocused
his energies on GM and Ford.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's conflict with the automakers is complicating what
until recently were plans for the two advanced factories, which
have been closely followed by world automakers. GM's Blue Macaw
plant is designed to function as a ``factory condominium,'' as
described by Henderson, in which 16 suppliers operate on the same
site. GM has hoped to produce as many as 150,000 compact cars
annually at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   At the nearby site for the Ford factory, where only the ground
has been prepared for construction to start, suppliers are also
expected to be more involved in production. The Ford plant was
scheduled to start production in 2001, with annual output of
150,000 cars.
</P>
<P>
   Since the factory is in such an early stage, representatives
from the state government have said there is a possibility that
Ford may switch the location to another state. Officials from
Ford's Brazilian subsidiary declined to comment on their
negotiations with Rio Grande do Sul.
</P>
<P>
   Dutra has tried to explain his actions by saying that the
incentives granted by the previous governor, Antonio Britto, were
unrealistic, given Rio Grande do Sul's need to provide improved
basic services to the people. In addition, the state government
faces a budget deficit of roughly $60 million a month.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luiz Vianna Moraes, the state development secretary
responsible for negotiating directly with GM and Ford, said that as
a result of Britto's concessions, ``now we're paying the price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-FUEL-NYT &LR;      04-20 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FUEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO'S ABILITY TO CUT OFF YUGOSLAV FUEL SUPPLIES IS QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as Defense Secretary William Cohen asserted
again Tuesday that NATO was succeeding in cutting off the supply of
fuel for Yugoslav troops, a growing number of U.S. and European
military experts and planners say that goal will not be reached for
many months, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take months at the very least,'' said a NATO military
official. ``Yes, the oil refineries are destroyed and so are some
oil storage depots but the Serbs will continue to have the fuel
they need for months and months.''
</P>
<P>
   Stopping the flow of fuel needed to run Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic's war machine has become a top goal of the
alliance's air campaign. But Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
said Tuesday that the diplomats coming to the NATO summit meeting
in Washington this weekend have yet to agree on how to solve ``the
problem of oil coming into the area.''
</P>
<P>
   The immediate problem centers on how to block oil shipments
arriving at the port of Bar in Montenegro, one of two republics
remaining in Yugoslavia, along with the larger Serbia. Since the
air war began, an American analyst said Tuesday, 8 to 10 oil
tankers have docked at Bar and delivered 40,000 to 45,000 metric
tons of refined fuel, or roughly 300,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tankers came from Greece, Russia and Ukraine, the
analyst said. But the ``biggest culprit'' was a merchant tanker,
the Kaliope, flying the Panamanian flag. It is a newcomer to the
Adriatic Sea and has been operating along the coast and picking up
cargo from other tankers.
</P>
<P>
   Since NATO air strikes recently cut off the pipeline connecting
Bar to Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, the oil has had to be
shipped overland for use by Milosevic's troops.
</P>
<P>
   At the insistence of the United States, the NATO allies are
considering setting up a naval picket line outside Bar to prevent
tankers from delivering oil. But European political leaders,
especially the French, are worried that any naval blockade would
widen the war and require approval by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   But as military experts point out, the problem is larger than
the port of Bar. Aware of the debate and the vulnerability of Bar,
Milosevic is already trying to bring oil in through other coastal
ports, the American analyst said, and on overland routes through
neighboring countries like Bulgaria.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the Serbs' campaign of ejecting Albanians from the
Serbian province of Kosovo requires very little fuel compared with
traditional military campaigns. And Serbian troops in Kosovo are
dug in with stockpiles of food and supplies, including fuel.
Finally, even in classic air wars, cutting off fuel supplies is one
of the trickiest endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's completely crazy,'' said Elliot Cohen, who directed the
Pentagon's study of the air war in Iraq. ``During World War II, it
made a difference because the Germans had to consume a lot of fuel
to wage war. The Serbs barely have to drive around.''
</P>
<P>
   While the allies have convinced Croatia, a former Yugoslav
republic, to cut off its pipeline to Serbia, it still receives fuel
smuggled in from the Serbian area of Bosnia, another former
republic, and from Bulgaria. With such porous borders, experts
argue, the allied campaign to choke off the fuel supplies would be
far more effective if ground troops were involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air war will cut off enough fuel so that the Serbs won't
be able to resist a ground war,'' said Michael O'Hanlon of the
Brookings Institution. ``But they'll have enough to defeat the
KLA,'' the Kosovo Albanian rebels, ``and complete ethnic cleansing
in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials deny that is the case and argue that something
has to be done to cut off supplies brought through the port and by
smugglers across the borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true you don't need tanks to run unarmed women and
children out of villages,'' said a Pentagon spokesman. ``But it
would make no sense to ignore those oil supplies coming in when
we're trying to destroy Milosevic's ability to retain control over
Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Gulf War Air Power Survey, the definitive Air Force study
of the war, Cohen found that even though the allies waged a far
more intense air campaign and the air strikes ``succeeded in
reducing the flow of supplies'' from Iraq to Kuwait, the Iraqis
nonetheless had enough fuel and other supplies ``to sustain an
inert army.''
</P>
<P>
   To underline that point, Cohen quotes one of the commanders of
the air war in the gulf, Charles Horner, then a lieutenant general,
on the shortcomings of an air war on its own in cutting off the
supplies of fuel and other essentials of warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody that does a campaign against transportation systems
had better beware!'' he said. ``It looks deceivingly easy. It is a
tough nut to crack.``
</P>
<P>
   Other experts argue that the heavy concentration on the fuel
supplies is a surrogate for the bombing campaign the alliance
military planners wish they could wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a surrogate, a stopgap, for the targets they can't
hit, `` said William Arkin, an air power expert. ``When you set up
a targeting strategy where leadership, electricity and other things
are off the list, then you hit what you can hit.``
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
