u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILIP-EARNINGS-NYT &LR;      04-20 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIP-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIP MORRIS CITES PROFIT GAIN FOR QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Showing considerable strength despite financial pressure from
shrinking demand for cigarettes and the cost of tobacco-related
lawsuit settlements, Philip Morris Cos. said Tuesday that its
first-quarter profit rose 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Profit from operations rose to $1.96 billion, or 80 cents a
diluted share, from $1.93 billion, or 79 cents a share, in the
quarter a year earlier. That met analysts' estimates, according to
First Call Corp., which tracks company earnings. Revenue rose 6.1
percent, to $19.5 billion from $18.4 billion
</P>
<P>
   Net income was $1.79 billion, or 73 cents a share, up from $1.38
billion, or 57 cents a share, in the quarter a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The results came even as the company paid out $1.1 billion to
the 46 states involved in the $206 billion settlement of
tobacco-related litigation last November. Moreover, operating
income in its domestic tobacco business fell 7.3 percent, to $1
billion, at a time of shrinking sales and intense promotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They earned slightly more money, even after incurring that
$1.1 billion,'' said Marc Cohen, a tobacco analyst for Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co. ``That's phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the reason, he added, was that sales of cigarettes were
stronger than expected after a large price increase, which was
announced on the heels of the settlement last fall. Even though
Philip Morris' domestic cigarette sales volume fell, he said, it
dropped less than expected. ``There was great concern earlier this
year that we would see massive volume declines as a result of price
increases,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, more of those sales were higher-priced Marlboros,
rather than less-expensive brands. The market share of the heavily
promoted Marlboros rose 2.2 percentage points, to 36 percent, while
that of Basic, a low-budget brand, rose just 0.1 percent, to 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had been concerned about a trading-down that might occur,
so they put Marlboro on special,'' said Emanuel Goldman, a global
consumer products analyst for Merrill Lynch. ``What they got
instead was a trading up. The percentage of volume in the premium
end actually increased.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's international tobacco profits grew slightly, with
slumping demand in markets like Russia, Germany and Brazil erasing
much of the gains made elsewhere. Sales in Korea, Singapore,
Malaysia and Thailand rose, the company said, although overall
international volume declined 11.2 percent in the quarter.
Operating income rose nine-tenths of a percent, to $1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Miller Brewing Co. unit, where lagging performance
led to the dismissal of three top executives earlier this month,
had a 6.3 percent increase in operating income. Shipments of Miller
Lite, the flagship brand, fell 1.2 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Income at Kraft Foods North America, which makes products such
as Oscar Mayer meats and Velveeta, rose 5 percent, which analysts
said was somewhat weak. ``It appears that the underlying growth
rate is still 2 to 3 percent, and that there was some
inventory-building in the fourth quarter,'' Cohen said. ``Broadly
speaking, the categories looked strong, although Maxwell House was
soft.'' The company's Post cereal brands also declined in volume,
which the company blamed on ``aggressive competitive activity and
an overall decline in the ready-to-eat cereal category.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft Foods International increased its operating income by 5.1
percent in the quarter, although lower costs were offset in part by
shrinking sales volume in Eastern Europe and Latin America. The
division also spent heavily to advertise its brands.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Philip Morris rose $1.125 Tuesday, to $34.25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
