<SLUG> BC-TANZANIA-STITH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STITH TOUTS AFRICAN NATIONS' INVESTMENT POTENTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After years of prodding banks to reinvest in the inner city,
Charles R. Stith has found another marginalized constituency to
trumpet to US investors _ the entire continent of Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Stith assumed the job of US ambassador to Tanzania last August
amid the turmoil after a terrorist bomb struck the embassy in Dar
Es Salam within hours of a twin bombing in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been easy for the former Boston minister and black
activist to have been mired in security issues the past eight
months. Then there was Clinton's trip _ the first visit of a US
president to Africa _ to help coordinate earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Stith, 48, has kept his focus on what he sees as a much
greater threat to Africans than terrorist bombs over the long term
_ being marginalized in a global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Africa has not had the infrastructure or the
regulated banking system to rate equal footing with trading
partners around the world, Stith said Tuesday at a lunchtime speech
to the World Affairs Council in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, Germany's former enemies gave the recovering
nation a debt ceiling of 3.5 percent on loans from the the allies
to rebuild the country. But no cap has ever been set on African
countries that have been forced by famine and war to rely heavily
on western lending.
</P>
<P>
   Tanzania itself, although stable for the past 30 years, has been
spent most of that time under socialist rule. It still suffers, he
said, ``from a socialist hangover.''
</P>
<P>
   The past weighs heavily on the economy: Tanzania presently
spends three times more money on debt service to various countries
than it does on educating its children.
</P>
<P>
   How, Stith asked, will Tanzania's workers ever compete in a
global economy if they are not schooled to do so?
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to turn handouts to hand-ups,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stith said the bombing itself was a sign of change in Dar es
Salaam, the Tanzanian capital. Terrorist violence had been
sporadic, he said, evident from the translation of the name itself:
``city of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the bomb went off on Aug. 7, it was clear that the rules
had changed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the shift to a market economy in 1986, and more recently
to a multiparty government, Tanzania had become more vulnerable to
the rebels it used to accommodate in its socialist days, Stith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as capitalism takes root in Africa, some of the
continent's most promising business and academic leaders are taking
advantage of newly opened borders to flee.
</P>
<P>
   One tally holds that more than 30,000 Africans with doctorate
degrees live outside the continent, Stith said.
</P>
<P>
   To keep budding business leaders in Africa, Stith said, banks
must be backed by enough foreign capital to give customers the
confidence that they can keep their money in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Stith said he learned that lesson from an embassy employee who
was so afraid to put his savings in a local bank that he sought to
keep it in the ambassador's safe.
</P>
<P>
   There are promising developments, however, that should encourage
investment, Stith said. Mining exploration has skyrocketed over the
past six months, reflecting confidence in stability.
</P>
<P>
   And the entire continent has been buoyed by President Clinton's
visit, highlighting US interests in a long-term investment in
Africa, Stith said.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States has a long way to go if it is to close the
``gap between rhetoric and reality,'' in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how to `talk the talk,' he said. ``Now we need to
`walk the walk.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6333 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POP-MUSIC-IDENTITY-2T     04-20 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POP-MUSIC-IDENTITY-2TAKES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRYING ON NEW NAMES TO PLUMB THE MYSTERY OF ``I''  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Michael Kramer is the pop-jazz producer at nytoday.com, a New York
Times web site.  
 By MICHAEL KRAMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Identity is the crisis can't you see,'' declared the female
singer Marion Elliott, better known as Poly Styrene, in a 1978 punk
rock song. Proving the prescience of Ms. Elliott's words, a number
of musicians have begun to explore notions of identity, so often a
part of pop music's appeal, by adopting not just one pseudonym but
many.
</P>
<P>
   They make the continual reinventing of musical personas perhaps
as entertaining and meaningful as the music itself.
</P>
<P>
   The hip-hop producer Robert Diggs (known as RZA), the
underground rocker Will Oldham (Palace) and the electronica
experimentalist Paul Miller (DJ Spooky aka That Subliminal Kid),
among others, move through multiple aliases as if names were so
many outfits in a costume closet.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing that pop music is as much about role-playing as
instrument playing, they raise intriguing questions about identity.
Is a person by any other name still the same person? Can a renamed
individual actually become someone new? Or do musicians with more
than one name become something in between?
</P>
<P>
   Using aliases to refashion identity has a long history in
popular culture, from Hollywood actors to pulp fiction authors. In
pop music, some names have been humorous, as in the Big Bopper
(Jiles Perry Richardson). Others have transformed musicians into
more marketable entities: Gordon Sumner became Sting, Steve
Georgiou became Cat Stevens, Mary O'Brien became Dusty Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Not until recently, however, have individual musicians employed
so many different pseudonyms, and rarely have they used them so
often to examine identity.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say they're the first musicians to experiment with
more than one pseudonym. In the 1970s, David Bowie (born David
Jones) recreated himself as Ziggy Stardust, Aladdin Sane and the
Thin White Duke. But Bowie's name changing always came across as
self-indulgent and commercially calculated.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes the current batch of multiple
pseudonym-takers is that they seem less concerned with the
stylishness or financial success of their alter egos than with the
simple thrill of continually concocting new versions of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Something very American and democratic also unites them. In
their hyperkinetic fashion, these musicians echo a practice of
taking new names that runs deep in American culture, from European
immigrants eager to assimilate to African-Americans reacting
against the legacy of slavery. They enact a kind of egalitarianism,
the longheld American dream that given identities matter less than
self-invented ones.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, their multiple aliases are reflective of modern
developments like the Internet, in which identity becomes a
scrambled, many-layered thing of alternate e-mail names and
disembodied chat room exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We named everything like Adam named things in the Garden of
Eden,'' Diggs, said last year, referring to how he and the members
of the loosely affiliated group he leads, the Wu-Tang Clan,
recreate themselves and their environs from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   When Diggs put on a mask, took on a new moniker and released an
album called ``RZA as Bobby Digital in Stereo,'' his behaviour
harked back to the Mississippi blues guitarist Charlie Patton. In
the 1920s, Patton also concealed his face and took on a new name,
the Masked Marvel.
</P>
<P>
   But while Patton's disguise was merely a promotional gimmick _
his record label gave away free recordings to anyone who could
identify the singer _ Diggs' alter ego is more complicated. Bobby
Digital is a full-fledged fictional character, the street-tough
protagonist (played by Diggs) of a direct-to-video movie. The
pseudonym is also an allusion, at once casual and coldly high-tech,
to Diggs' actual name.
</P>
<P>
   Playing himself once removed, Diggs obfuscates his true
identity. Behind his mask, he teases listeners. Is the real Diggs
the violent, low-down Bobby Digital or the artistic, sophisticated
RZA? Shifting between his alter egos, Diggs manages to become a
sort of trickster figure, changing names and shapes like a video
game superhero.
</P>
<P>
   Oldham pursues a similar strategy of multiple aliases. Recording
his quirky songs _ which can resemble the folk-rock musings of Neil
Young _ Oldham has employed different pseudonyms for a decade. He
possesses a fine sense of the absurd, releasing solo albums under
the name of Palace Brothers and group efforts, recorded with his
actual brothers, under the name Will Oldham.
</P>
<P>
   Best known as Palace, Oldham now calls himself Bonnie Prince
Billy, an apparent nod to Prince (born Prince Rogers Nelson), a
musician infamous for changing his name to an odd symbol.
</P>
<P>
   The lyrics on Oldham's album aren't related to anyone in actual
life, he said recently. Yet his songs are rife with what seem to be
ironic self-references. Characters like Stable Will, Billy Riley
and Pushkin Will make appearances, suggesting that Oldham himself
is a central, if fictionalized, figure in his own work; a listener
doesn't know which is part of the allure of Oldham's songs.
</P>
<P>
   Oldham's many pseudonyms, like his songs, possess a spiritual
component. For him, changing names is, as he put it, ``religious
more than anything.'' Going one step farther than the country
singer Hank Williams, who used the alter ego Luke the Drifter to
tell tales of sin and salvation, Oldham adopts multiple names to
make himself timelessly enigmatic yet ultra modern.
</P>
<P>
   While Oldham can strike a rustic pose with his pseudonyms,
Miller uses his aliases to create an air of science fiction. ``For
me it all comes down to the word persona,'' he said. ``It comes
from the word per, which means person but also means through, and
sona, which is like sonar _ sound waves _ so persona means a person
moving through sound waves.''
</P>
<P>
   While his etymology may be suspect, Miller makes music that does
seem to move through sound, creating evocative but disembodied
sonic collages under the guise of his two-pronged alias (Spooky
comes from a television commercial and That Subliminal Kid from a
William S. Burroughs novel). He also writes articles under his
given name.
</P>
<P>
   While his writing can be almost musical in its stream of
consciousness, the music Miller makes is highly abstract and
theoretical, sampling other recordings to comment on their cultural
significance. Moving among his aliases, he confounds the
traditional roles of performer and critic.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the disorienting world of multiple aliases created by
Miller, Diggs, Oldham and others like the rappers Keith Horton
(Kool Keith, Dr. Octagon, Black Elvis) and Russell Jones (Ol' Dirty
Bastard, Big Baby Jesus, Osirus), the quandary of identity can
appear to take place in a funhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Because they use so many pseudonyms, even their given names seem
to become distorted images of the actual person, who can never
truly be recognized. These musicians make identity something
joylessly unstable, forever mutating and ultimately mysterious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a common thing to change your name,'' one of pop music's
most famous name-changers, Bob Dylan (ne Robert Zimmerman), said in
a 1978 interview with Playboy magazine, adding: ``It isn't that
incredible? Many people do it. Names are labels so we can refer to
one another. But deep down inside us, we don't have a name. We have
no name.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
