<P>
   Stith said the bombing itself was a sign of change in Dar es
Salaam, the Tanzanian capital. Terrorist violence had been
sporadic, he said, evident from the translation of the name itself:
``city of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When the bomb went off on Aug. 7, it was clear that the rules
had changed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the shift to a market economy in 1986, and more recently
to a multiparty government, Tanzania had become more vulnerable to
the rebels it used to accommodate in its socialist days, Stith
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as capitalism takes root in Africa, some of the
continent's most promising business and academic leaders are taking
advantage of newly opened borders to flee.
</P>
<P>
   One tally holds that more than 30,000 Africans with doctorate
degrees live outside the continent, Stith said.
</P>
<P>
   To keep budding business leaders in Africa, Stith said, banks
must be backed by enough foreign capital to give customers the
confidence that they can keep their money in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Stith said he learned that lesson from an embassy employee who
was so afraid to put his savings in a local bank that he sought to
keep it in the ambassador's safe.
</P>
<P>
   There are promising developments, however, that should encourage
investment, Stith said. Mining exploration has skyrocketed over the
past six months, reflecting confidence in stability.
</P>
<P>
   And the entire continent has been buoyed by President Clinton's
visit, highlighting US interests in a long-term investment in
Africa, Stith said.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States has a long way to go if it is to close the
``gap between rhetoric and reality,'' in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know how to `talk the talk,' he said. ``Now we need to
`walk the walk.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
