<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0281 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6336 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAD-TV-$ADV25-NYT &LR;      04-20 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAD-TV-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAD TV': IT'S SOMETIMES LIVE! IT'S ON SATURDAY NIGHT! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 25)  
 Margy Rochlin's most recent article for The New York Times Arts and
Leisure section was about actor Sean Hayes.  
 (bl)  
 By MARGY ROCHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At the Hollywood sound stage where ``Mad TV'' is
filmed, a pair of sketches were being shot recently that perfectly
encapsulated this late-night show's fascinating inconsistency. In
one of the pop culture parodies at which the show excels, series
regular Aries Spears was using an impression of hothead
prizefighter Mike Tyson to spoof a Gap clothing commercial. ``This
is easy!'' Spears exclaimed in a high-pitched lisp, shortly after
burying his head into the neck of one of the extras swing dancing
around him, then rearing back with a bloody prosthetic ear jiggling
from his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour later, the ``Mad TV'' gang went to work on the other
kind of bit they are known for. In ``Singing Telegram
Misadventures,'' a ball-gowned psychotic (Nicole Sullivan) kidnaps
a man (Pat Kilbane), forces him to warble ``Happy Anniversary''
with her to a married couple (Andrew Bowen and Debra Wilson), then
whips out a gun and kills everyone in the room. At the end,
inexplicably, the ``Yo quiero Taco Bell'' Chihuahua appears. If
ever a sketch was destined to elicit a ``huh?'' instead of laughs,
this was it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, erratic quality is de rigueur for the sketch-show
genre. It's all about the overall content: if the touchdowns are
memorable enough, it's worth sitting through the incomplete passes.
The young male demographic has grasped this about ``Mad TV'' since
1995, when Quincy Jones and David Salzman pitched the series as a
way for Fox to siphon away the X-chromosome contingent from NBC's
``Saturday Night Live'' audience. (``Mad TV'' starts at 11 p.m., a
half-hour before ``Saturday Night Live.'')
</P>
<P>
   But if the boys and girls in baggy jeans whooping and hollering
in the bleachers at a recent Friday night taping were any
indication, the show has become as much a draw to 12- to
17-year-olds, of both sexes. And now ``Mad TV'' is gaining among
18- to 49-year-olds as well, showing 18 percent growth in this age
group _ a group that includes grown-ups heretofore considered far
too loyal to ``Saturday Night Live'' ever to switch to an
alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Mad TV'' cast and creative staff have detected other
evidence of rising popularity: thank-you notes and
cellophane-wrapped muffin baskets have arrived at their office,
expressions of gratitude from some of Hollywood's hottest producers
for how deftly they satirized their films or television shows. For
a hard-working group that has always lived with the threat of
cancellation and borne the indignity of having an already spartan
budget whittled down to about $700,000 per episode (``Saturday
Night Live'' reportedly spends twice as much), finding itself the
hip underdog is a sweet morale boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, when I came to `Mad TV,' it was like we were
Juliette Lewis in `The Other Sister' _ the retarded one that nobody
talked about,'' said Terry Sweeney, a ``Saturday Night Live''
alumnus and now a ``Mad TV'' staff writer. ``Now we're like
Cinderella. We're just trying to get past our big, ugly stepsister,
`Saturday Night Live,' and get to the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The exact reasons behind this change aren't clear. There is the
theory that the three new cast members _ Michael McDonald, Mo
Collins and Andrew Bowen, each of whom arrived with a clutch of new
characters _ meshed so perfectly with the seven established
principal players that the whole became greater than the sum of its
parts. Some point to this season's hiring of Dick Blasucci as
executive producer. Blasucci, a veteran of the hallowed comedy show
``Second City TV,'' encouraged the actors to collaborate more with
the writing staff, a group of 10 who are mostly in their 30s and
notably not part of the Ivy League baby mafia that seems to have
taken over television comedy. He also managed to get the network to
lift its most degrading mandate: to mimic ``Saturday Night Live''
by opening the show with famous guest hosts, even though ``Mad TV''
could usually attract only not-quite-brand-name stars like Adam
Arkin and Pam Grier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has taken over, but it's hard to put my finger on
what,'' said Blasucci, sitting in his office, which is wallpapered
with colored index cards that itemize each cast member's repertory.
Under Alex Borstein's name, for example, Blasucci had printed:
``Janeane Garofalo, Rosie O'Donnell, Mary Bono, Chelsea Clinton,
Miss Swan.'' The last is an original creation that Ms. Borstein
worked up with a couple of the writers, a quietly stubborn Asian
manicurist at the Gorgeous Pretty Beauty Nail Salon who speaks
English only well enough to drive listeners around the bend. To get
the outburst of applause that typically greets a ``Saturday Night
Live'' favorite, like Molly Shannon's implosive Mary Katherine
Gallagher, Ms. Borstein need only step from the wings dressed in
Miss Swan's trademark rainbow plaid apron. And she is but one of a
stable of characters that the ``Mad TV'' cult can call its own.
</P>
<P>
   Almost weekly, for example, the 6-feet 4-inch Michael McDonald
daubs rouge on his cheeks and claps on a grayish Prince Valiant wig
to play Stuart, a wriggling man-baby who is always defying adults
in a creepily soft whisper. Blasucci said he became convinced of
Stuart's breakout potential in January, when his 12-year-old
daughter, Maria, began reporting to her parents that ``Stuart is
huge'' among her classmates. When reached by telephone, Maria
seemed understandably wary of an adult reporter who would call and
ask her to verify her Stuart-love. But she wasn't shy about why she
and her friends' way-past-bedtime viewing preferences don't include
``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not funny,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Ms. Blasucci is only contributing to a debate that
has long raged on the Internet as to which show is better.
``Saturday Night Live'' has the glitz factor that comes with
celebrity hosts and high-profile bands. ``Mad TV,'' about half of
whose skits are pretaped (the other half are shot before a live
audience), has the luxury of editing out a botched line reading;
blunders on ``Saturday Night Live'' are there to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mad TV'' isn't above presenting the occasional political
sketch, like ``Something About Monica,'' a fusion of the Farrelly
brothers' hit movie and the Lewinsky scandal. (Instead of a terrier
chewing on Ben Stiller's leg, the skit had Hillary Rodham Clinton's
teeth clamped on her husband's ankle.) But the show tends to leave
the topical satire to ``Saturday Night Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the typically male-dominated sketch comedy world,
Terry Sweeney believes that ``Mad TV'' has an edge. Rarely are
women in the cast stuck playing hastily conceived ancillary roles:
the nagging housewife or the ditzy girlfriend. Indeed, when they
are stuck, it's at the epicenter of a sketch that can't be saved.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Mad TV' is just more woman friendly; on `SNL,' the men are
always being characterized as a woman's victim,'' said Sweeney,
whose most notable character during his ``Saturday Night Live''
term was that of Nancy Reagan. ``Here, we're not hostile to women.
We just make them powerful in themselves, and the world is just
going to have to deal with them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
