<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6337 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUBAIDULINA-MUSIC-2TA     04-20 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUBAIDULINA-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APOSTLE OF INNER STRUGGLE AND REDEMPTION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25)
</HEADLINE>
 (af) 
By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A woman among composers; a freethinker among Soviet
apparatchiks; a Christian among atheists; an Easterner, half Tatar,
among Europeans; a modernist among reactionaries, and a reactionary
among modernists, Sofia Gubaidulina has lived with many conflicts,
both with the outside world and within herself.
</P>
<P>
   Her arrival, in her 50s and 60s, at moments of extraordinary
musical power has been a triumph of persistence and self-searching.
Ms. Gubaidulina, now 67, has become a great light, and her
achievement has happily been matched by steadily increasing public
recognition, which reaches a culmination in New York on Thursday
evening, when two big new works will be presented almost
simultaneously: ``Two Paths,'' at Avery Fisher Hall, and ``In the
Shadow of the Tree,'' at Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Paths,'' for two violas and orchestra, will be played by
the New York Philharmonic, with its front-desk violists, Cynthia
Phelps and Rebecca Young, as soloists and Kurt Masur conducting.
The work was commissioned by Masur's wife, Tomoko, who was herself
a violist.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Shadow of the Tree'' also has multiple solo parts, but
in this case they are played by one musician, Kazue Sawai,
performing on Japanese instruments: koto (the floor-level plucked
harp), bass koto and zheng (a similar instrument, but Chinese
rather than Japanese and with a wider range). Here the commission
came from the orchestra of Japanese radio, the NHK Symphony, which
will be conducted by Charles Dutoit.
</P>
<P>
   That both scores should be concertos is no accident. For Ms.
Gubaidulina, the relationship between soloist and orchestra,
whether combative or consolatory, provides an image of the
individual in the world and of the truth to be found amid what she
has called the ``staccato'' of life.
</P>
<P>
   And it was with a concerto, ``Offertorium'' for violin and
orchestra, that she began to gain attention outside Russia.
Composed in 1980, ``Offertorium'' was taken around the world by
Gidon Kremer, who recorded it at the end of the decade. By then,
thanks to glasnost, Ms. Gubaidulina was at last receiving official
acclaim in Russia, but in 1992 she left for a new home in Hamburg,
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offertorium'' is typical of Ms. Gubaidulina's work, in that it
is a journey through conflict toward new knowledge and
illumination, it uses a wide range of musical means, and it
justifies that range as a crucial necessity to a composer intent on
immediate expressive force.
</P>
<P>
   She exhibits no commitment to fine style. The characteristics of
her music are instead abruptness, ripped change and a finish that
is often rough, raw and ragged. ``Offertorium'' sounds like a page
torn ruthlessly from a book: a book whose subject would have to be
the spiritual life. It even makes the tearing sound, as it breaks
away from a Bach theme orchestrated by Webern _ two composers Ms.
Gubaidulina reveres above all others _ and embarks on a quest for
its own continuation and its own way to end.
</P>
<P>
   Along the line of Ms. Gubaidulina's artistic journey,
``Offertorium'' was a message from halfway. She was born nearly 50
years before, in 1931, in Chistopol, the daughter of a
Tatar-Russian couple. Her childhood years were spent largely in the
nearby big city, Kazan, in an environment that the musicologist
Theo Hirsbrunner has described in terms that surely came from the
composer herself: ``Life there ... was rather uninteresting: no
trees in the backyard, just a patch of grass here and there _ yet
the sight of the sky with its passing clouds captivated the child.
A buffoon played the accordion, and Gubaidulina danced to its
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Dance, as an image of the body and therefore the soul in perfect
tuning, has stayed with her; among her recent pieces is ``Dancer on
a Tightrope'' for violin and piano, the latter mostly strummed. And
the accordion has stayed, too, for several of her works use the
instrument in its ethnic Russian form, the bayan.
</P>
<P>
   Even beyond these examples, many of her scores carry traces, in
their long sustained tones and their orchestral clamor and wheeze,
of the dancing girl and the folk musician.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gubaidulina started her conservatory studies in Kazan soon
after World War II and completed her education at the Moscow
Conservatory between 1954 and 1963. She remained in the capital,
though without much encouragement or support.
</P>
<P>
   Her regular studies seem to have been less important to her than
the contact she made with Philipp Herschgowitz, a Webern pupil who
was a vital source of instruction to young Russian composers at a
time when anything in non-Russian music since Debussy was virtually
proscribed. Her straying from ``the bright, pleasant aspects of
life'' was noticed by an early reviewer, but Shostakovich privately
expressed to her his hope that she would continue on her ``wrong
course.''
</P>
<P>
   She did. As a result, her works were rarely played and never
recorded. As another result, she had to earn her living by writing
film scores. Her achievements in this area include the music for
Rolan Bykov's ``Scarecrow'' and a number of collaborations with Ida
Garanina on animated films. But this sort of work was not a chore:
it provided her with another kind of education, since the need to
match music to gesture gave her a strong sense of how instruments
can speak and how music can mimic physical action or, by extension,
movements of the mind and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Neglect also proved useful to her, throwing her back on herself,
alone or in the company of a few colleagues. With Alfred Schnittke
and Edison Denisov, both recently deceased, she was a leader of the
quiet musical opposition, and she made up for the lack of
performances by forming an improvisation group with the composer
Viktor Suslin and the ethnomusicologist Vyacheslav Artyomov, whose
collection of instruments from the Caucasus and Central Asia gave
the group a wide sound-world.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The works Ms. Gubaidulina wrote in the 1960s and early '70s
already reveal her liking for the soloist-accompaniment format of
the concerto, song or instrumental piece with piano, but not until
the later '70s was she able to make her expressive purposes
explicit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hour of the Soul,'' of 1976, was an early instance: a
half-hour percussion concerto in which the soloist stirs up the
orchestra; eventually a mezzo-soprano emerges, singing verses by
Marina Tsvetayeva. Like most of Ms. Gubaidulina's pieces before and
since, ``Hour of the Soul'' was written for a particular player, in
this case Marek Pekarski, so that, in the composer's words, ``only
at the end does the truly feminine nature appear.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gubaidulina would almost inevitably have been drawn to
explore in her music issues of maleness and femaleness, and ``Hour
of the Soul'' is by no means the only work in which she has done
so. But she adopts a rather conventional position in expressing the
contrast in terms of dynamism and stasis, rationality and
irrationality, thought and feeling, and it would be hard to
identify her musical voice as that of a woman and therefore unlike
those of such contemporaries as Schnittke, Henryk Gorecki or Giya
Kancheli.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Paths,'' the Philharmonic work, looks at another polarity,
for this double concerto is a double portrait of Martha and Mary,
the sisters of St. John's Gospel. These were women who had, as the
composer puts it, ``two ways of loving: to love taking upon oneself
worldly cares and by so doing insure the foundation of life, and to
love dedicating oneself to the sublime, to experience together with
the Beloved the route of terrible suffering to the cross, so as to
procure light and blessing for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Wild gestures in the orchestra _ loud swirls and anapaest
rhythms _ provoke a response from the two soloists, a response they
deliver alone. The second viola, as Martha, starts in the middle
register and almost at once slides down toward the bottom of the
instrument's range. The first, as Mary, begins just above her
sister and moves higher.
</P>
<P>
   Both sisters are not only much quieter than the orchestra but
much slower and more centered, in keeping with the composer's
archetypal view of sexual differences. It will be interesting one
day to hear the work performed by male soloists with a woman
conducting.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is a sequence of variations. The orchestra returns
to attack mode, and this time the violists' move together in
response. Mary, in her higher register, makes downward slips;
Martha, below, starts to lift, and the two flow side by side in
duets.
</P>
<P>
   Then woodwind soloists enter the conversation. Once the
unaccompanied viola duetting has been restored, the two soloists
crisscross through pitch space over a percussive ostinato, and
these mirroring upward-downward movements spread into the
orchestra. After this tumult, the Martha violist settles on a theme
she will hold to the end, while the Mary figure pursues her lyrical
flights. A last cruel orchestral outburst does not stop them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Shadow of the Tree'' also has a binary contrast, but
now between whole ensembles. A little more than half the orchestral
strings play in normal tuning, the rest being tuned a quarter-tone
down.
</P>
<P>
   The koto and bass koto are aligned with the first group, as are
the winds and tuned percussion instruments. (Ms. Gubaidulina,
herself a percussionist, uses large percussion sections in both new
works.) But the zheng's intonation places it with the ``mistuned''
strings, which are said to represent ``a region of shadow.''
</P>
<P>
   The work begins in light and ends there, on the same note played
on the koto with the kind of undulating insistence by which Ms.
Gubaidulina gives her simple musical facts the force of freshness.
But along the way, the shadow comes into its own, and the soloist
is able to move from one side to the other.
</P>
<P>
   The shadow music is not particularly negative or sinister, and
its effect is not so much to contradict the light as to gentle it.
So one may come to understand, with the composer, ``that shadow is
the sphere of existence from which life emanates, and even light.''
</P>
<P>
   Initial contradictions _ between shadow and light, between
Eastern and Western instruments, between improvised and notated
music (in the solo part) _ come to seem less important than the
equal necessity of both aspects. And though ``In the Shadow of the
Tree'' may, from its title, contain some Christian reference, Ms.
Gubaidulina's message lies at this other level, at once more
abstract and more immediate.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same message she has always delivered in her best
works, a message of fierce struggles and ecstatic coming home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 1941EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
