<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6343 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HARVARD-RADCLIFFE-BOS     04-20 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-RADCLIFFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD TO ABSORB RADCLIFFE COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE AND JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Radcliffe College, founded 105 years ago to
educate a gender Harvard University rejected as ``too
promiscuous,'' said Tuesday it would cede the education of
undergraduate women to its long-time male partner.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the merger between Harvard and Radcliffe
ends nearly two years of secretive and sometimes strained
negotiations, during which the colleges' trustees themselves were
unclear whether they were arranging a marriage or a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Radcliffe officials termed the arrangement a union, ``the end of
a very long engagement.'' And like the most old fashioned of
marriages, the key issues were dowry and status. Harvard will
absorb Radcliffe's $450 million in endowment and real estate.
Radcliffe is to become an institute for advanced studies with a
focus on women, gender and society on a par with Harvard's law,
medical and business schools.
</P>
<P>
   For Harvard, it is a significant step toward solving its long
standing ``women problem,'' which by the college's own admission
has left women feeling less invested in the nation's oldest
university, both as undergraduates and alumni.
</P>
<P>
   Radcliffe forces Harvard to institutionalize its commitment to
the study of women in society.
</P>
<P>
   ``This places the responsibility on Harvard for making sure
undergraduate education is excellent both for women and men,'' said
Harvard President Neil Rudenstine, ``The creation of an institute
with absolutely major resources, that's a major event. We're really
creating something significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the arrangement, approved by the governing boards of the
two colleges last week, Harvard will absorb Radcliffe's assets into
its own $13 billion endowment. Women students who have until now
applied and paid tuition to Radcliffe and gotten a degree signed by
the presidents of both colleges will be students exclusively of
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Radcliffe will give up its legal independence and lose the name
college in its title, becoming the Radcliffe Institute for Advanced
Studies. Harvard officials said it was one of only four such
institutes in the nation and the only one focused primarily on the
study of women. While the new Radcliffe will not grant degrees it
will now hire faculty for the first time. When Radcliffe was
founded its classes were taught by Harvard professors in their off
hours. The Institute will also offer a place for professors and
artists from any field and any institution, including Harvard, to
spend their sabbaticals.
</P>
<P>
   Radcliffe's three research institutes will be absorbed into the
new creation. President Linda S. Wilson will step down replaced by
a new dean who for the interim will be Mary Maples Dunn, the former
president of Smith College and now head of Schlesinger Library at
Radcliffe.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard has promised a $300 million endowment to the new
institute. The size of the new Radcliffe faculty is to be
determined in discussions beginning this summer. The two colleges
will also decide whether Harvard will be allowed to solicit
donations from women who graduated before 1977. The 1976 agreement
that made Harvard classes coeducational prevented Harvard from
doing so.
</P>
<P>
   To the outside world the negotiations may have seemed like
bickering over seating arrangements at the same elaborate dinner
table; women students have been admitted jointly to Harvard and
Radcliffe since the mid 1970s. But to many, the discussions neatly
symbolized the long-standing conflict over the status of women at
the nation's oldest university. Radcliffe said Harvard didn't
understand, Harvard officials asked what all the fuss was about. In
a report on the status of women two years ago, Harvard said the
continued existence of Radcliffe as an undergraduate school
confused students and alumni. Radcliffe reminded people that
Harvard had not been hospitable to women _ an image Harvard was
trying to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know quite how to define a full commitment to
women when we haven't been able to demonstrate that,'' said
Rudenstine, ``It's been hard for Harvard to know what it could and
should do without treading on Radcliffe's territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Radcliffe alumni and officials however worry that Harvard wanted
to do away with Radcliffe entirely, or reduce it to an ``affiliate.
At several points during negotiations, concerned that Harvard was
not taking seriously the need to focus on women, Radcliffe
threatened to walk out on Harvard entirely. And as late as early
this month, people close to the negotiations were suggesting
Radcliffe might become an entirely separate entity granting its own
graduate degrees and hiring its own faculty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing for me was the understanding of the
mission,'' said Dunn. ``To make certain that everyone involved at
Harvard and Radcliffe understood that this new institute would
continue to have a primary concern with issues having to do with
women. It isn't just that they write it down on a piece of paper
but they understand it and internalize it. That happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wilson said that the new institute would merely enhance
Radcliffe's role within Harvard. ``The new incarnation will make
the commitment to women much more obvious,'' Wilson said.
``Physically we're not moving, but symbolically becoming part of
the university means our ability to contribute will be larger.
Moving inside will give Radcliffe greater statute. This will be
alongside the nine other schools at Harvard and contributing to
each.''
</P>
<P>
   If Radcliffe had gone it alone, its current programs on the
study of women might have been marginalized. Merging with Harvard
gives it the extra stability of the university's resources.
</P>
<P>
   Radcliffe's officials also noted the endowment of the new
Radcliffe will be larger than the endowment of the design,
education and divinity schools at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at both Harvard and Radcliffe tried Tuesday to
reassure nervous alumni who had turned out for discussions about
Radcliffe's future in ten cities nationwide last fall. ``It will
continue to be a warm welcoming community,'' said Nancy-Beth Gordon
Sheerr, head of Radcliffe's Board of Trustees, ``by the nature of
what's going on here, and the people brought here to work on the
issues of women, gender and society.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, the new position of Radcliffe reflects the
uncertain place of women's colleges nationwide. Leaders of the
other traditional seven sisters Tuesday affirmed the importance of
single-sex education. But they also said they did not believe
Radcliffe was selling out on the education of young women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radcliffe is embarking on a new period in its distinguished
history that I'm sure will enable it to play a significant
leadership role in defining and examining the role of women in
society,`` said Judith R. Shapiro, president of Barnard College.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6344 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ILLEGAL-NATO-N     04-20 1648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ILLEGAL-NATO-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 IN KOSOVO, JUSTICE and the U.N. CHARTER COLLIDE  
 &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.)  By MICHAEL J. GLENNON  
 c.1999 Foreign Affairs Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   As the 20th century fades away, so too does the international
consensus on when to get involved in another state's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and NATO _ with little discussion and less
fanfare _ have effectively abandoned the old U.N. Charter rules
that strictly limit international intervention in local conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   They have done so in favor of a vague new system that is much
more tolerant of military intervention but has few hard and fast
rules. What rules do exist seem more the product of after-the-fact
rationalization by the West than of deliberation and pre-agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But the death of the old rules on peacekeeping and peacemaking _
under which most bloody conflicts were simply ignored as ``domestic
matters'' _ should not be mourned. Events since the end of the Cold
War starkly show that the old anti-interventionist regime has
fallen out of sync with modern notions of justice.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in Kosovo illustrates this disjunction and America's
new willingness to do what it thinks right _ international law
notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   The horror of ethnic cleansing in the Serbian province was well
publicized. As Slobodan Milosevic thumbed his nose at the
international community, pressure built to use force against him,
whether the U.N. Charter allowed it or not. Thus when the Western
allies launched air strikes, the move was largely popular.
</P>
<P>
   It was not, however, technically legal under the old U.N.
regime. After all, Kosovo is still part of Yugoslavia. No
cross-border attack _ the one circumstance where the charter allows
an international military response _ had occurred, and the Security
Council had never authorized NATO military measures.
</P>
<P>
   Thus in Kosovo, justice _ as it is now understood _ and the U.N.
Charter seemed to collide. But it is not only that the U.N. Charter
prohibits intervention where enlightened states now believe it to
be just. Its problems run even deeper.
</P>
<P>
   For the charter is grounded on a premise that is simply no
longer true _ the assumption that the core threat to international
security still comes from interstate violence. What's more, thanks
to Cold War deadlock and the veto power held by the Security
Council's five permanent members, the old rules never even
prevented interstate violence in the first place _ witness
Afghanistan, Vietnam and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Just as generals too often refight the last war, when the
drafters of the U.N. Charter set its limits on state power, they
responded to the crises precipitating World War II, without
anticipating those that would follow it.
</P>
<P>
   They devised a legal regime they hoped would govern the use of
force for generations to come _ recognizing all states as sovereign
equals, prohibiting interference in their internal affairs, and
permitting the nondefensive use of force only when authorized by
the U.N. Security Council, and then only in limited circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Today's recurrent problem, which is intrastate violence, is not
addressed effectively by the charter.
</P>
<P>
   Thus in Haiti, Somalia and Rwanda _ all conflicts within a
single country _ when the international community stepped in to
halt the slaughter of civilians, it did so without the blessing of
international law. Although intervention was authorized by the
Security Council, its consent flew in the face of the constraints
of the charter and 40 years of U.N. precedent that virtually
ignored civil war and instability.
</P>
<P>
   The charter regards internal violence as a question of
``domestic jurisdiction'' only _ that is, beyond official
international concern.
</P>
<P>
   When American embassies were bombed in Kenya and Tanzania last
August, world attention focused entirely on the propriety of
American air strikes against perpetrators allegedly ensconced in
Afghanistan and Sudan. The idea that the United Nations might
actually DO something to combat such bombings was never even
raised, so conditioned had observers become to expect it to do
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Had the United Nations ever been effective in curbing interstate
violence, its charter's anachronistic focus might be tolerable. But
it was not.
</P>
<P>
   The charter generated no formal international response to Soviet
intervention in Hungary, Czechoslovakia or Afghanistan, none to
American intervention in the Dominican Republic, Grenada, Panama or
Nicaragua, and none to that of India in Goa, Indonesia in East
Timor, China in Tibet, Argentina in the Falklands or Vietnam in
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatic historians have yet to identify a single instance of
interstate violence that was actually stopped by the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The West's new rules of thumb on intervention accord less
deference to the old idea of sovereign equality _ the erstwhile
notion that all countries, large or small, are equal in the eyes of
the law. The new posture recognizes the hollowness of this concept,
accepting that all states are not in fact the same in their power,
wealth, or commitment to human rights or peace.
</P>
<P>
   The new system acknowledges something else the U.N. Charter
overlooks: that the major threats to stability and well-being now
come from internal violence as or more often than they do from
cross-border fighting _ and that to be effective, international law
needs to stop the former as well as the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the cost of abandoning the old anti-interventionist
system will be offset by the benefits of the newly emerging one
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, replacing a formal system with a set of vague,
half-formed, ad hoc principles can be dangerous. Untested rules may
have unexpected consequences, and justice formed on the fly may
come to be resented. But the failings of the old system were so
disastrous that little will be lost in the attempt to forge a new
one.
</P>
<P>
   No one, as yet, has devised safeguards to guarantee that power
will not be abused by the strong, that coercion will not be
misdirected to undermine the values that it was established to
protect. Until such safeguards are devised, the global rule of law
will remain a dream.
</P>
<P>
   But what of justice? Can it be achieved in the meantime? That a
new interventionist regime might not at the outset be a legal one
does not mean that enhanced global justice need remain a fantasy.
International justice can in fact be pursued ad hoc, without a
fully functioning legal system.
</P>
<P>
   This evidently is what NATO and the United States have recently
set out to do. And they have achieved some success: A child saved
from ethnic cleansing in Kosovo by NATO's intervention is no less
alive because the intervention was impromptu rather than part of a
formal system.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is dangerous for NATO to unilaterally rewrite the rules
by intervening in domestic conflicts on an irregular, case-by-case
basis.
</P>
<P>
   The test of the new interventionism is not whether it can be
contrived to generate immediate popular support. Of course it can,
at least in influential Western publics, in ways known to all
military planners and their publicists: with smart-bomb strikes
portrayed in the media as being undertaken only after patience has
run out. Such attacks are a swift, short, and successful method of
punishing a demon and vindicating international honor.
</P>
<P>
   They produce few (CNN-reported) civilian deaths and still fewer
Western casualties. The script for successful military spinning is
no state secret.
</P>
<P>
   But that script is not the best way to give a new
interventionist regime long-term acceptance. The real test of a new
system will be whether succeeding generations throughout the
community of nations _ not simply in centers of wealth and power _
believe the system and the actions it prescribes to be just.
</P>
<P>
   Even if its purposes are widely approved of, sooner or later the
exclusionary decision-making process is likely to create
resentment, particularly as inevitable foul-ups occur and lives are
lost through error and oversight.
</P>
<P>
   Justice, it turns out, requires legitimacy; without widespread
acceptance of intervention as part of a formal justice system, the
new interventionism will appear to be built on neither law nor
justice, but on power alone.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, unless a critical mass of nations accepts the
solution that NATO and the United States stand ready to offer, that
solution will soon be resented.
</P>
<P>
   But the new interventionists should not be daunted by fears of
destroying some lofty, imagined temple of law enshrined in the U.N.
Charter's anti-interventionist proscriptions. The higher, grander
goal that has eluded humanity for centuries _ the ideal of justice
backed by power _ should not be abandoned so easily.
</P>
<P>
   Achieving justice is the hard part; revising international law
to reflect it can come afterward. If power is used to do justice,
law will follow.
</P>
<P>
   (Michael J. Glennon is professor of law at the University of
California, Davis, Law School. He is a former legal counsel to the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee and the author of
``Constitutional Diplomacy.'' This article is adapted from a longer
version in Foreign Affairs.)
</P>
<P>
   ------------------------ &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
