<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6346 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SECRETARY-COX     04-20 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRETAR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 Y-COX &HT;    Job descriptions may have changed, but secretaries remain
 &HT;    By Julie Kemble Borths
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Shorthand and mimeograph machines may be extinct
but there are still secretaries powering most businesses. Like
Thelma Landis, they just do it now with computers and e-mail and
fax machines.
</P>
<P>
   Landis has seen it all in 50 years as a secretary, one of 3.4
million in the U.S. according to the International Association of
Administrative Professionals. While many go by other titles like
administrative assistant and office managers, their roles in all
kinds of businesses are celebrated today on Secretaries Day.
</P>
<P>
   And next week, Landis retires with a sense of pride: being a
secretary is important to the running of a business, Landis said.
``Just doing the general work that comes in,'' she said. ``That's
what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   For Landis, that eventually meant handling probate work for the
firm, recently merged and renamed the Equity Land Title Agency in
Two RiverCenter. Such responsibilities were part of a natural
progression for a woman who always wanted to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of going to college but I couldn't afford it,'' she
said. ``And I was from a small town (Pitsburg in Darke County) and
I didn't know too much.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Landis went off to Miami-Jacobs College and learned typing
and shorthand for a year. She walked into the Brooks T. Carson &AMP;
Sons office, then one of the largest real estate title firms in the
area, and evolved along with the business.
</P>
<P>
   For Landis, most of the changes in those years had more to do
with technology than anything else. First there were adding
machines and manual typewriters with carbon paper. Later there were
copying machines that needed a messy gel applied with each use. And
now, Landis' tidy office overlooking Main Street in downtown Dayton
includes a computer with e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't just the machines that changed over the years.
Landis said the real estate world changed too and she always kept
up.
</P>
<P>
   One of her bosses, attorney James C. Kiefer, said that's what
has made Landis so valuable. ``She has more knowledge than anyone
else. Sometimes, when I wasn't available, attorneys would just call
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Landis said she has never stopped learning about the detailed,
complex world of real estate law.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I always found the work very interesting because of the
law aspect,'' she said. ``But I never went in for studying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Kline has worked with Landis since 1984. ``She's taught me
everything I know here,'' Kline said. ``And she's the world's
nicest person. She doesn't have a gossipy bone in her body.''
</P>
<P>
   Landis said gossiping or playing office games never appealed to
her. Brought up on a farm, she retained a strong work ethic. A bit
embarrassed, but also a bit proud, she said she never took a sick
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to be real organized,'' she said of balancing her
work life with her life at home. For 48 years, she's been married
to Ted Landis Sr., a former Drexel Elementary teacher and a
minister at several churches. They sent a son and a daughter to
college and now have four grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the 1950s, when many mothers did not work, Landis said
she continued on the job. ``It was a way of life,'' she said. ``I
had a commitment to my job, my family and my church.''
</P>
<P>
   That commitment is missing in younger people Landis sees working
today. ``You have to be on time, do the best you can, be
conscientious,'' she said. ``But sometimes, all (people) seem to
want is a paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   But after 50 years of balancing it all, Landis said she's
looking forward to devoting more time to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I won't do my laundry at night anymore,'' Landis smiled.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Kemble Borths writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
