<HEADER>
A6354 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-BANKS-COX     04-20 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-BANKS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stockpiling money in preparation of Y2K not a good idea, Federal
Reserve employees say
 &HT;    By Angela Townsend
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The Federal Reserve Board and financial
institutions want the public to know their money isn't going to
disappear or become inaccessible once the clock strikes midnight on
Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the banking industry on Tuesday gathered at the
Cincinnati office of the Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland to
deliver a message: They are ready for Year 2000, or Y2K, on all
levels.
</P>
<P>
   The banking industry has tackled the technological issues of Y2K
and will soon shift to educating the public about what it doesn't
need to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Henshaw, vice president in charge of the Federal
Reserve's Cincinnati office, wanted to emphasize that customers
don't need to hoard money for fear that they won't be able to get
to it.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve is already talking with the armored carrier
industry to make sure that banks get the money they need when they
need it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that we'll have plenty of cash. There is no
need to take currency outside insured institutions,'' Henshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   And Bud Burkle, vice president of Banking Supervision at the
Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland, said he thinks once all is said
and done, Y2K is going to be a non-event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't promise that there won't be a few glitches somewhere
. . . (but) that happens without Y2K,'' Burkle said.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve Board's next check on the Y2K compliance of
all banks is June 30. About 95 percent of banks have been given a
satisfactory rating, a passing grade of sorts, by the regulating
agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an industry, we're way ahead of the curve,'' said Bob
Elberfeld, a vice president of Firstar Bank in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon (Ohio) Citizens National Bank re-created itself as a
second bank for testing purposes, operating on critical dates such
as Dec. 31, Jan. 1 and Feb. 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``We checked to make sure that everyone's accounts were still
there,'' bank President and Chief Executive Stephen Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin Stamen, president and chief executive of Second National
Bank in Greenville, has said, ``Community banks are as well
prepared as larger banks. We're not that far from being able to do
things manually if we need to. But we don't need to. Our bank is
well prepared.'' Consumer tips
</P>
<P>
   Be aware of scams. Report scam artists who offer to ``hold''
your money through the date change or offer any ``Yokeproof''
investments, products or services.
</P>
<P>
   Never give out your Social Security number or bank account
number over the phone unless you are the one initiating the call or
you are sure the person with whom you're speaking is legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   Keep good records of all your banking transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Consider asking your lender for a printed history of the
payments on your mortgage, car loan or other debts.
</P>
<P>
   During the date change, take out as much cash as you would for
any holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Angela Townsend writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
