<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, DEMOCRATS HOPE CASH KEEPS FLOWING AT HOUSTON FUND-RAISER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
and ALAN BERNSTEIN 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton drops by La Colombe d'Or in
Houston Wednesday evening, he won't be just sampling the French
cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   As he has so many times in the past the president will be
prospecting for cash in the Lone Star State, this time on behalf of
the Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   But the trip comes at a time when Democrats are competing for
scarce campaign dollars. The state Democratic Party's fortunes have
never been lower, and Republican Gov. George W. Bush has been
vacuuming up campaign funds for his expected presidential bid. Of
the $7.6 million that Bush has raised for his exploratory committee
this year, $4 million came from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Further, many wealthy Democrats would rather give to
congressional campaigns where they are assured the money will
remain in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly competition for campaign money in Texas
these days,'' said Houston political consultant Nancy Sims.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Sims said corporate executives, lawyers and others in
Texas who want to nourish simultaneous bonds with Republican and
Democratic leaders will continue to find a way to signal their
support for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   And Texas is still viewed as a gold mine by national Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent election cycle ending last December, the
national Democratic Party and its candidates scooped up more than
$16 million from Texas, about 40 percent of all money raised in the
state over the two-year period, according to the Center for
Responsive Politics. Only in New York, California and Illinois did
the party do better.
</P>
<P>
   Houston is the top city for Democratic fund-raising, followed by
Dallas, San Antonio and Beaumont-Port Arthur.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee alone raised $1.4 million
during the 1997-98 election cycle from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Although the official reason for Clinton's one-day visit to
Texas is to dedicate the new Austin-Bergstrom International
Airport, he will spend the bulk of his time raising money.
</P>
<P>
   In Austin, after the airport event, he will attend a fund-raiser
at the home of Roy Spence, the advertising executive who has known
Clinton since the two worked on George McGovern's presidential
campaign in 1972. With a minimum contribution of $1,000 required
and a crowd of 125 expected, the event should generate $250,000,
according to DNC officials.
</P>
<P>
   In Houston, the fund-raiser will be a more intimate _ and more
lucrative _ affair with 30 to 40 people expected at La Colombe
d'Or. The price of admission: $20,000 a couple. And Democrats hope
to raise $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   The event is hosted by Kenneth Bailey, a successful trial lawyer
whose law partner is John Eddie Williams, one of five attorneys
sharing a $3.3 billion fee because of their role in a recent state
tobacco settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey is a generous contributor to Democrats, giving $70,000
alone to the Democratic National Committee in the last election
cycle, according to Federal Election Commission records. His law
firm, Williams &AMP; Bailey, gave a total of $250,000 to the DNC during
the cycle, more than any other individual or group.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic National Committee spokesman Peter Kauffmann said the
Texas Democrats' troubles do not seem to have rubbed off on the
fund-raising circuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly didn't have any trouble filling these two
fund-raisers,'' he said, adding that the president still remains a
big draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``People like to go to events where he speaks,'' Kauffmann said.
</P>
<P>
   A fund-raiser Clinton headlined for Democratic gubernatorial
candidate Garry Mauro last September netted about $250,000 for
Mauro's campaign, despite a disastrous finish at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   However, the president's approval rating has declined in Texas
since his impeachment ordeal, according to the latest Texas Poll.
The survey of 1,003 Texans found that 48 percent believe he is
doing a good job as president while 49 percent disapprove of his
job performance. In a previous survey, conducted during the Senate
impeachment trial, Clinton's job approval stood at 56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And many Democrats are unhappy that DNC fund-raisers tend not
only to siphon money out of the state for projects that do not help
elect local candidates but also end up hampering other fund-raising
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they don't do well,'' one top Democratic House aide
said of the national party's fund-raising events in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The aide said the congressional Democrats need all the cash they
can raise to help retake the House in 2000. If Democrats hope to
regain the House they cannot afford to lose the 17 seats they now
hold in Texas.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Furthermore, the aide said, Democrats are focusing on keeping
control of the Texas House and retaking the state Senate to ensure
the party can play a role in congressional redistricting after the
2000 Census.
</P>
<P>
   For these reasons, some Texas Democrats say they prefer to give
to the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee, which earlier
this month hosted a series of fund-raisers in the state that
generated more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
