<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAD TO THE CUP BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not even a week beyond the staggering loss of Wayne Gretzky to
retirement, the National Hockey League tries to get its legs back
with the start of the Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,107-game prelude to the postseason ended Sunday, only
hours after the Great One took his final, tearful twirl around
Madison Square Garden. Wednesday night, the long winnowing process
begins, with 16 teams facing the difficult prospect of winning 16
more games to clinch the Cup. One qualifier, the San Jose Sharks,
won only 31 games the entire season.
</P>
<P>
   If we are to believe the final standings, the New Jersey Devils
will meet the Dallas Stars in the best-of-seven finals some six
weeks from now. Ah, but this is playoff hockey, where things seldom
go according to form. First-round upsets are de rigueur, often
spiced with curious (the buzz adjective for ``expletive deleted'')
officiating and bizarre goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins should beat the Carolina Hurricanes, but weren't we
saying the same thing last year when the Black-and-Gold met the
Washington Capitals? If not for Tim Taylor's interloping toe, the
Bruins might have won. Instead, they were rubbed out in six games
and the Capitals went on to play the role of clay pigeons in the
Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   So it begins. By no later than June 19, the final Stanley Cup
champion of the 1900s will be crowned. Gretzky, the greatest
point-getter the game ever knew, got his name on four of those
Cups. But in '99, No. 99 has left and gone away. Never has a second
season begun with such a tinge of sadness. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey (1) vs. Pittsburgh (8) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four years after carrying the Cup around Exit 16W, the Devils
are poised for a long postseason run. We were saying the same last
year, of course, but their offense disappeared in Round 1 as they
lost to the Senators in six games, outscored, 13-12. Don't look for
the same choke. They've got a more balanced, more aggressive attack
under coach Robbie Ftorek, and there's a tendency to forget that
Martin Brodeur ranks among the game's top 3-5 netminders. Are they
unbeatable? No. But it's a talented, smart squad that easily could
see its No. 1 seed hold up through the first three rounds. The
Penguins have the best player in the world, Jaromir Jagr, and they
spice up the offense with the ever-enigmatic Alexei Kovalev, one of
the world's great one-on-one performers. Tom Barrasso isn't
Brodeur's match, but he won two Cups in Pittsburgh's heyday and
still has the skills to carry a club in a series. But the Penguins
have issues, such as their continuing odyssey in bankruptcy court
and a lack of depth among the forwards and blue liners. Watch for
Scott Stevens to be behind the Washington blue line every time Jagr
is on the ice. And look for Devils forward Peter Sykora to be the
offensive star he never has been in the playoffs. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey injuries: None.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh injuries: Neil Wilkinson (groin pull); Jeff Serowik
(concussion).
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Devils, 4-1-0
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Devils in 6. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ottawa (2) vs. Buffalo (7) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate pick 'em, no matter that the Senators led the
conference for much of the second half. The Sabres could show up
with the Hamilton-Wenham Knights skating the wing, and as long as
Dominik Hasek is in their net, they'd enter the series even money
(witness: the 1998 Czech Republic gold-medal Olympic squad). The
Senators softened up a little over the last month and slipped to
the No. 2 seed, but they've got perhaps the best overall speed in
the Original 27. They had a nasty habit of giving up the game's
first goal late in the season, and they don't want to be handing
Hasek 1-0 leads with, say, 3:27 clicked off the clock. The Sabres
can't come close to matching the Senators for mobility and depth
among the forwards, and Michal Grosek, perhaps their best power
forward, followed a strong start this season with overwhelming
mediocrity. However, ex-Oiler Miroslav Satan finished with a
slightly surprising 40 goals (suppose the Oilers would send back
Barrie Moore and Craig Miller for that kind of touch?). Ottawa will
pressure the puck with one of the game's best forechecks _ sprung
from a basic trap _ and hope to pick apart a sometimes vulnerable
defense. The Sabres will try to use their edge in the muscle
department, because the Senators don't have an enforcer. But the
Rob Rays and Paul Kruses of the world don't mean much in April and
May anymore. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo injuries: Joe Juneau (concussion).
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa injuries: Shawn McEachern (groin pull); Andreas Johansson
(back spasms).
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Senators, 4-0-1.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Senators in six. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carolina (3) vs. Boston (6) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They are, and forever will be, the Forever .500s, the one-time
Hartford Whalers, and here they are _ in their first postseason
visit since '92 _ to face their archenemy from the Hub. If not for
the NHL's seeding method, which awards divisional winners the 1-2-3
spots, the Canes would have been the No. 8 seed and played the
broad-shouldered Devils, and the Bruins would be opposing the
Flyers. They've tried, but the Canes haven't been able to make that
big roster upgrade to be someting other than also-rans (remember
the failed attempt during the '98 Olympics to woo Sergei Fedorov
away from the Wings?). The Carolina offense revolves around two
pivots, Keith Primeau and Ron Francis, and Primeau has been
suffering of late with a bad back. If he's not in top shape, the
Canes will have an extremely difficult time generating a bona fide
attack. Just as Byron Dafoe is the key to Boston's game, the Canes
are nowhere without Arturs Irbe in their cage. Dafoe has the extra
incentive of never having won a postseason series. This should be a
breeze for the Bruins, provided that two-line attack they fashioned
late in the season doesn't fail them now (read: if Joe Thornton's
shoulder is a problem, the offense could hiccup badly). &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston injuries: Joe Thornton (shoulder); Tim Taylor (groin
pull); Shawn Bates (hamstring).
</P>
<P>
   Carolina injuries: Keith Primeau (strained lower back); Ray
Sheppard (strained neck); Sean Hill (fractured jaw); Glen Wesley
(sprained ankle); Nolan Pratt (sprained shoulder).
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Even, 2-2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Bruins in five. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Toronto (4) vs. Philadelphia (5) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Clarke's worst nightmare. The Flyers' general manager
didn't chase Curtis Joseph in the free-agent market and CuJo went
home to Ontario and backstopped the Leafs back to franchise status.
The Flyers instead paid to bring in John Vanbiesbrouck, a move that
had Clarke briefly ordering rookie Jean-Marc Pelletier into action
in a prolonged late-season slump. The Leafs made serious strides
this year with Pat Quinn behind their bench, CuJo in net, and Mats
Sundin joining another free agent, Steve Thomas, in shaping a
formidable No. 1 line (with a vareity of right wingers). Behind the
blue line, the Leafs are lacking, although ex-Ranger Alexander
Karpovtsev (picked up for Mathieu Schneider) wasn't the bust
everyone thought, and Bryan Berard makes up for a lot of his
negatives with his positive offense. The Flyers got some good news
over the weekend: Mark Recchi, having suffered two concussions in
23 days, was cleared to play (his dizziness and nausea weren't
caused by the concussions). Nonetheless, they must move ahead
without their captain, Eric Lindros, who continues to build his
strength back after suffering a collapsed lung on April 1. Even
with Lindros at full strength, the Flyers fell apart in the second
half, and even with some of the games most talented forwards,
they're looking at a short postseason. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Toronto injuries: Alyn McCauley (concussion); Igor Korolev
(fractured finger).
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia injuries: Eric Lindros (collapsed lung).
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Philadelphia, 3-1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Toronto in six. &QL; 
 &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
