<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA SEEKS MEDIATING ROLE IN KOSOVO CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Four weeks after NATO began bombing Yugoslavia, Russia
_ one of the few countries to have lent a sympathetic ear to
Belgrade and turned a blind eye to reports of atrocities in Kosovo
_ is now eagerly auditioning for the role of mediator.
</P>
<P>
   While his Communist-nationalist opposition keeps itself busy
with dreams of a Slavic union, President Boris Yeltsin has moved
Russian diplomacy onto more pragmatic ground.
</P>
<P>
   On the day after a telephone conversation with President
Clinton, Yeltsin sent his newly named special Balkans envoy, former
Prime Minister Victor Chernomyrdin, on a tour of Russia's
neighbors, seeking support for Moscow to lead the way out of the
impasse in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In a another sign of Russia's stepped-up diplomatic activity,
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan is to visit Moscow in
late April.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with Russian journalists Monday, Yeltsin stressed
Moscow's readiness to play the role of intermediary between the
NATO alliance and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, a role
that Western leaders have said they would welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready,'' he said in off-the-cuff remarks, reported in
Russia newspapers Tuesday. ``They know that, and in that context,
we are collecting points. Good points.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia has much to gain if it succeeds in brokering a political
settlement in Yugoslavia. By playing its part in bringing peace to
the Balkans, Russia would be able to reclaim an important role in
world affairs, a role that it realized with a jolt it had lost when
NATO ignored Moscow's opposition to the use of force in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   And in openly soliciting Moscow's services, the West has already
signaled its interest in drawing Russia out of its isolation, and
in reinforcing Yeltsin's tattered credentials as a world leader.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin still has to walk a fine line at home, where he has
been pressed in by a tide of anti-Western feelings let loose by
televised images of NATO airplanes bombing a fellow Slavic nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For political reasons, Yeltsin is trying to differentiate his
position from one staked out by the Communists, by trying to find
an active role for Russia in seeking a political solution,'' a
Moscow-based Western diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kremlin on Monday, Yeltsin said that Milosevic would
never capitulate, and that Russia will not stand by and watch
Kosovo turned into a NATO protectorate. But he also cautioned the
journalists not to exaggerate the prospects of a union linking
Russia, Belarus and Yugoslavia, a proposal that has been
enthusiastically endorsed by the opposition-dominated Russian
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will consider it,'' he said. ``That's it. We cannot discard
it now because then we would abandon Milosevic. And we want to
embrace him a bit more closely. And hold him tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Just what Yeltsin had in mind with his bear-hug imagery was not
immediately clear. But according to Russians and Western diplomats,
Moscow clearly hopes to use its access to Milosevic to persuade him
to open peace negotiations on terms likely to be accepted by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin doesn't want to be locked in an embrace with Milosevic
that is not under his control,'' the Western diplomat said. But as
many here have noted, it is still not clear what leverage Moscow
has over Belgrade, if any.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia has no influence over Belgrade, as Milosevic has proven
over the years,'' said Maksim Yusin, a foreign-affairs analyst for
the Russian newspaper Izvestia. ``He has used Russia only when he
wants to frighten the West. Otherwise, he is always ready to play
behind our backs.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early days of the war, Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov came back empty-handed from a diplomatic mission to
Belgrade. According to Yusin, Primakov then floated a proposal
involving the partition of Kosovo but apparently that idea was
rejected by Milosevic, perhaps because it came too early in
Belgrade's campaign to push Albanian Kosovars out of the province.
</P>
<P>
   According to Yusin, the main bargaining in any future
negotiations will likely be over the makeup and command structure
for international security forces to be deployed in Kosovo. NATO
has insisted on sending in its own force, under its own command,
but a parallel force, including Russian troops operating under
another flag, may be a negotiable point.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment of Chernomyrdin is seen in Moscow as a ploy by
Yeltsin both to open a new diplomatic front with NATO countries,
and to counterbalance the Russian Foreign Ministry, which has
remained the domain of Primakov, the former foreign minister known
for his hard-line stance.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have criticized the appointment, noting that
Chernomyrdin, with his affable manner and fumbling speech, will be
too compliant with the Western leaders he came to know as prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``A nonprofessional in diplomacy has only two options _ to
please everyone or agree with the strongest,'' said Dmitri
Gornostayev, a commentator for the Independent Newspaper, which has
been harshly critical of NATO's campaign. ``Both options would lead
to an impasse.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last weeks, Russian officials have toned down the harsh
Cold War language that characterized their first response to the
NATO strikes. But the anti-Western mood in the country is still
strong, as Russian politicians and much of the media continue to
focus on the damage caused by NATO bombs, treating reports of
Serbian-led atrocities in Kosovo with skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   But there were new signs this week that Russia is now willing to
hear other views of the situation in Yugoslavia. Foreign Minister
Igor Ivanov, who is to set off soon for a tour of the Middle East,
met Tuesday with members of the Islamic Conference Organization,
and listened as Foreign Minister Kamal Kharazi of Iran condemned
the ethnic purges in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting on Tuesday first with Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze in Tblisi and then with Azerbaijan President Heydar
Aliyev in Baku, Chernomyrdin heard both leaders condemn both the
NATO strikes, and the ``ethnic cleansing and genocide'' in Kosovo,
words that Moscow has until now refused to accept.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin is to go on Wednesday to Kiev, the Ukrainian
capital, where he is to meet with President Leonid Kuchma, who
despite pressure from Moscow, will be leaving this week to attend
NATO's 50th anniversary meeting in Washington. Chernomyrdin's next
stop on his diplomatic search is still not known.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's isolation not only from its erstwhile Western partners
but also from its former Soviet neighbors was brought home recently
at a summit meeting of the heads of the Commonwealth of Independent
States, where leaders of the former Soviet republics shunned
Moscow's harsh language, and adopted a generally worded resolution
on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   And in a sign of a subtle shift in Russian public opinion, the
patriarch of the Russian Orthodox Church, Aleksei II, arrived
Tuesday in Belgrade with a message in which he for the first time
suggested that Russia's Eastern Orthodox brethren in Serbia bear a
share of the responsibility for the tragedy that has befallen their
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``See to it that reconciliation and accord triumph,'' Aleksei II
told a crowd in Belgrade, according to a report by the Russian news
agency Interfax. ``Then nobody can reproach you for sinful deeds in
vindicating their own sin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
