<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6366 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSINESSDEANS-COX     04-20 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESSDEANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deans discuss challenges facing business schools
 &HT;    By Ernest Holsendolph
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Deans of the nation's business schools, laboring in
the eye of technological change, gathered in Atlanta this week to
grapple with the problems of teaching business leaders even as the
environment churns around them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Technology Revolution in Management Education'' is the
theme of the meeting of some 1,000 deans and other policy-makers in
higher education whose three-day meeting at the Atlanta Hilton
concludes today.
</P>
<P>
   The members of the International Association for Management
Education were augmented by delegates from more than 30 countries,
underlining the international thrust of business education in the
growing global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Among the individual challenges business colleges face, on the
undergraduate and graduate levels, are ways to use computer
networks to upgrade traditional teaching in classrooms and to reach
students in remote locations.
</P>
<P>
   At a roundtable, deans from Duke, Georgetown University,
University of Maryland, Colorado State, Boston University and
University of Florida discussed the challenges of teaching
management in the turmoil of a constantly changing technology
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Among the major challenges facing the schools and the business
of educating managers are the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ Mobilizing the latest teaching technology, such as software
for teaching on the Internet, including full-motion video,
archiving, and live discussions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finding, training and keeping the informed and skilled
teachers needed to to keep curriculum fresh and pertinent to the
latest needs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dealing with the growing influx of students from abroad, all
seeking to learn American secrets of management.
</P>
<P>
   _ Apportioning resources among the various tasks such as
undergraduate education, graduate education and response to
specific needs of businesses.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keeping clear the distinction between education _ the
traditional role of colleges and universities _ and training, which
has mostly been the job of businesses and industries.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all institutions are now adopting programs like the
Georgia Tech system for teaching by using the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the University of Florida is just embarking on a
program to put subject matter on the Internet and also conduct live
``discussions'' among students and teachers on various business
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be able to award the Masters in Business Administration
to students who will gather on campus only about eight times,''
said John Kraft, dean of the business schools at Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Another twist on the traditional MBA is the global program
operated by Duke, where graduate students, who come from around the
world, actually do their studies during intensive residential
programs on various continents to catch the international flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Frank, dean of business at the University of Maryland,
said one-third of his applications for advanced business training
are from abroad, with a substantial portion from Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 39 percent of the enrolled students are women,'' he
added, ``and 29 percent are minorities, including
African-Americans, Hispanics and other groups _ and the faculty
very much reflects the diversity of the students.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar patterns were evident on campuses around the country,
the deans said.
</P>
<P>
   Deans who discussed their programs agreed that the new shifting
demands on teaching resources required new team teaching tactics,
more cooperation among departments, including the library
resources, as well as team approaches to student learning.
</P>
<P>
   Rex Adams of Duke pointed out that technology enables business
schools such as his to offer advanced education in cities like
Frankfurt, Germany, where Duke is setting up an auxiliary program.
Frankfurt is a major industrial and transportation hub without a
business school. Duke is located in small-town North Carolina with
a ``podunk'' airport, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Frankfurt business will work with a Duke because we have
something they don't have in their city,'' Adams said, and that
pattern could affect various schools around the world.
</P>
<P>
   For all the hand-wringing over new approaches, bigger missions
and more complex challenges for colleges, the institutions are
helped by remembering their primary charge, the educators said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is what we are about, teaching students how to
think, analyze and so on,'' said Louis E. Lataif, Dean of Boston
University's school of management, ``and we should leave the
training to business.''
</P>
<P>
   Others gave a different spin: In the hierarchy of functions, the
university does best at education and research, with the echoes
from those activities resonating down the line in training and
other programs more dependent on the moment-by-moment changes in
technology and needs.
</P>
<P>
   But the way those functions are delivered could radically change
in the next several years. ``Those who will be delivering it may
not be seated around this room today,'' Lataif said. ``It could be
Microsoft hiring faculty as consultants to teach management to its
computer executives.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Holsendolph writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
