<HEADLINE>
WESTERN CONFERENCE 

</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... Toronto in six.  Dallas (1) vs. Edmonton (8) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most lopsided matchup of the first round. Dallas (114
points) was a powerhouse, finishing first overall in league
standings. The Stars may have overpaid for aging free agent Brett
Hull, but his play with Mike Modano and Jere Lehtinen gave head
coach Ken Hitchcock not only a prolific trio (84 goals), but also a
disciplined defensive line, an unexpected two-for. Derian Hatcher
will miss the Stars' first five postseason games, part of his
sentence for an ugly elbow that left the Coyotes' Jeremy Roenick
with a fractured jaw. Hatcher is a key loss back there, but the
Stars are fortunate to be getting him back at all _ the hit was far
worse than the one Dale Hunter put on Pierre Turgeon a few years
ago, leading to Hunter's suspension for a quarter-season. Can Eddie
Belfour truly be a Cup-winning netminder? This could be eagle-eyed
Eddie's last chance to prove it. Meanwhile, ex-BC Eagle Bill Guerin
was the Oilers' No. 1 scorer until he suffered knee damage in a
leg-to-leg collision with the Sharks' Marco Strum. He's down until
at least Game 4. The Oilers easily handed the Flames in the
end-of-season Battle of Alberta, but they're much too thin on
offense and may or may not have a No. 1 goalie (Tommy Salo? Bob
Essensa?) even to wish upon beating the Stars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dallas injuries: Dallas: Brian Skrudland (torn rib cartilage);
Richard Matvichuk (groin and knee); Pat Verbeek (sprained left
knee)
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton injuries: Bill Guerin (knee); Josef Beranek (knee).
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Dallas, 3-0-1.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Dallas in four. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colorado (2) vs. San Jose (7) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche were slow to get going, but rookie coach Bob
Hartley survived his club's early lethargy and saw GM Pierre
Lacroix pull off the late-season trade for Theo Fleury that makes
this an interesting postseason package. Not a bad power play: Joe
Sakic between Peter Forsberg and Claude Lemieux, with Fleury and
Sandis Ozolinsh at the points. Ex-BU Terrier Ted Drury made a
legitimate Rookie of the Year statement with 20 goals, 44 points,
his playing time affected by a star-studded cast up front.
Ozolinsh, an early-season holdout, revived the offense immediately
upon coming to contract terms. In net, Patrick Roy remains the key,
his skills still sharp enough to pull off another Cup. Sharks head
coach Darryl Sutter keeps talking about going with Mike Vernon in
net to start the series. Curious, because Vernon was 0-4-1 in his
last five games while ex-Sabre Steve Shields was almost CuJo-like
down the stretch when the Sharks desperately needed points. The
trade-deadline acquisition of Vincent Damphousse helped bring
together a sporadic offense (definition of sporadic: Joe Murphy the
top goal-scorer with 25). The picture would be brighter here if
Gary Suter hadn't been lost for the season after biceps surgery.
They're moving up, but it won't be this year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colorado injuries: Adam Deadmarsh (eye); Valeri Kamensky (broken
forearm); Cam Russell (separated shoulder).
</P>
<P>
   San Jose injuries: Marco Sturm (knee); Murray Craven (knee).
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Colorado, 3-1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Colorado in five. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Detroit (3) vs. Anaheim (6) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even in their red-hot era of the '50s, the Wings never won three
straight Cups, but even their boastful late-seson maneuverings
don't categorize them as ``favored returnees.'' Remember, they
picked up Chris Chelios, Ulf Samuelsson, Wendel Clark, and Bill
Ranford at the trade deadline in one of the boldest and broadest
roster upgrades in memory. OK, they're better, and they could win
again, but they by no means are to be considered the conference
heavyweight. The Avalanche play with more eagerness. The Stars have
someting to prove: that the regular season wasn't a fluke. In the
end, the Wings will need big performances out of Fedorov and
Brendan Shanahan, neither of whom had commanding regular seasons,
both of whom could be moved if the Wings don't make a serious run
here. Teemu Selanne's 47 goals led the Ducks and also the league,
making him the first winner of the Rocket Richard Award. With Paul
Kariya and Selanne, there is a lot to like about the sons of
Disney, but not enough (their 83 points wouldn't have gotten them
into the East playoffs). They're about one line and a pair of
defensemen away from getting in with the likes of Detroit,
Colorado, and Dallas. It could be a wait. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Detroit injuries: Uwe Krupp (back).
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim injuries: Steve Rucchin (strained groin).
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Detroit, 3-1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Detroit in 6. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix (4) vs. St. Louis (5) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That flying elbow Hatcher delivered to Roenick's noggin
fractured JR's jaw in three places, broke or cracked eight teeth,
and cut the Coyotes' playoffs chances off at the knees. The ex-Jets
had the best first half in franchise history, began to erode in the
second half, then crumpled with the Hatcher hit. Captain Keith
Tkachuk likely now will have either Robert Reichel or rookie Daniel
Briere dishing him the puck; neither can provide the fire and drive
that Roenick brought to the pivot. Once more, too much falls to
Tkachuk (reminiscent of Winnipeg days) and, once past him, it all
falls to goalie Nikolai Khabibulin. The Cup won't come to cactus
country this spring. The Blues patched up their net (remember when
they hustled to get Jim Carey?) with the surprising return to form
of Grant Fuhr. Ex-Bruin Geoff Courtnall shook off concussion
symptoms and got back in just before the close of the season to
finish with 24 goals. In all, it's a surprisingly perky offense,
led by Pavol Demitra (37 goals, 89 points), Pierre Turgeon (31, 65)
and big-shooting Al MacInnis on the blue line. The Blues just
barely would have qualified in the East, but they're plucky enough
to win at least one round in the wild West. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix injuries: Jeremy Roenick (broken jaw); Gerald Diduck
(broken foot); Deron Quint (concussion).
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis injuries: Michal Handzus (shoulder separation); Kelly
Chase (shoulder separation); Marc Bergevin (abdominal surgery);
Jimmy Campbell (abdominal surgery).
</P>
<P>
   Season series: St. Louis, 2-1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: St. Louis in 6.
</P>
