<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elder-Beerman exceeds earnings expectations
 &HT;    By Jim Bohman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Elder-Beerman Stores Corp. topped analysts
estimates by 2 cents a share in fiscal 1998 by reporting year-end
earnings per share of $1.76, including special charges.
</P>
<P>
   Net income totaled $25.5 million compared with a net loss of $29
million a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding several one-time charges, the Moraine-based retailer
reported net profit per share of 95 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The consensus estimate of three analysts was that the chain
would earn 93 cents a share, excluding unusual charges, according
to First Call Corp., a Boston-based analyst monitoring service.
</P>
<P>
   In the fiscal fourth quarter, ended Jan. 30, the chain, with 60
department stores across eight states, earned $1.51 per share
including special items. Without those items, the company earned 66
cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimated the company would earn 64 cents in the fourth
quarter, according to First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Net income for the quarter, including special items, was $23.8
million. In the fourth quarter a year ago, the company posted a net
loss of $16.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The one-time adjustments to income include costs to assimilate
the Stone &AMP; Thomas stores; a gain on sale of real estate, and a
favorable settlement of bankruptcy-related items.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick J. Mershad, chairman and chief executive, said 1998
was a record year for operating performance. ``I am proud of what
we have achieved on both a financial and operational basis,
particularly in light of our recent history. Since emerging from
bankruptcy on Dec. 30, 1997, we have been entirely focused on
growing and developing the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Mershad predicted a 2 percent to 3 percent gain in sales from
stores open a year or more this year.
</P>
<P>
   Three stores in the works are in Warsaw, Ind., Frankfort, Ky.,
and an unnamed location.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus this year will be on flawless execution of our
business strategies throughout our organization, merchandise
planning enhancements and development of new design and customer
service concepts for our new stores,'' Mershad said. ``We are very
excited about developing these new store concepts. Although this
means our new stores will not open until late third or early fourth
quarters, we expect to learn much in these stores that we will be
able to implement over time in our existing stores.''
</P>
<P>
   Elder-Beerman shares (NASDAQ: EBSC) closed Tuesday at 9, up .
The 52-week trading range is 7-29.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bohman writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
