<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWAN-LAKE-BALLET-2TAKES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEND IN THE SWANS: AT 50, CITY BALLET EMBRACES A CLASSIC  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Balanchine once told Peter Martins: ``You know, dear, we
should call all ballets `Swan Lake.' People will come.''
</P>
<P>
   Martins certainly hopes people will come to the complete ``Swan
Lake'' he is staging for the New York City Ballet. It opens the
company's spring, 50th-anniversary season at the New York State
Theater on Thursday night and will be performed through May 9.
</P>
<P>
   But during a recent interview at the State Theater, Martins
revealed that the popularity of Tchaikovsky's classic is not his
sole reason for producing it.
</P>
<P>
   Martins admires the ballet's passionate score and its story of
how Prince Siegfried becomes enamored of Odette, a beautiful
princess transformed by Rothbart, a sorcerer, into the queen of the
swans. She can permanently regain human form only if a lover stays
true to her.
</P>
<P>
   But when Odile, Rothbart's daughter, disguises herself as
Odette, the deceived Siegfried pledges himself to her instead.
Odette and Odile are usually danced by the same ballerina, the dual
role displaying her dramatic and technical powers.
</P>
<P>
   Martins, the City Ballet's ballet master in chief, first staged
``Swan Lake'' in 1996 for the Royal Danish Ballet, with which he
danced before coming to New York in 1969. The invitation from the
Danish company to create a full-evening ballet initially befuddled
Martins, who specializes in short works and had no large-scale
plans. Then, after realizing that the Danes had not performed
``Swan Lake'' for many years, he fell under the ballet's spell.
</P>
<P>
   ``His `Swan Lake' was a success,'' said Erik Aschengreen, the
dance critic for the Copenhagen newspaper Berlingske Tidende, in a
telephone conversation. ``It challenged the dancers, and energized
them, too.'' But Aschengreen indicated that its nonrealistic
scenery had surprised audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Copenhagen and New York productions are designed by Per
Kirkeby, a Danish painter. ``His `Swan Lake' is unlike any other,''
Martins said. ``Some people may see it and wonder, `Where's the
lake?' But others will marvel: `Look at the lake! Isn't it
divine?'''
</P>
<P>
   Americans have long loved to look at ``Swan Lake.'' The San
Francisco Ballet staged the first complete production in the United
States back in 1940. American Ballet Theater and the various
touring Ballets Russes troupes regularly performed the second act
from the 30s through the early 60s.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1951, the New York City Ballet has danced a one-act
version by Balanchine. Martins said that although he had been
inspired by Balanchine, he was not directly borrowing from that
staging. With ``Swan Lake,'' City Ballet now has productions of all
three of Tchaikovsky's ballets in its repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, ``Swan Lake'' is an ugly duckling. Tchaikovsky's
first ballet , it was the last to achieve success. Staged by a
minor choreographer named Julius (also occasionally known as
Wenzel) Reisinger, it received its premiere by the Bolshoi Ballet
in Moscow in 1877, and made little impact there.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, two major St. Petersburg choreographers for the
Maryinsky Ballet collaborated fruitfully with Tchaikovsky: Marius
Petipa, who created ``The Sleeping Beauty'' in 1890, and Lev
Ivanov, whose ``Nutcracker'' of 1892 followed the specifications of
Petipa, who had fallen ill.
</P>
<P>
   Curious about ``Swan Lake,'' Petipa examined the score and liked
it. Yet Tchaikovsky died in 1893 before they could plan a
production. The next year, Ivanov aroused interest in the music by
choreographing the second act for a memorial program.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in 1895, the Maryinsky offered a complete ``Swan Lake''
with the first and third acts (the palace scenes) by Petipa and the
second and fourth (the lakeside scenes) by Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
   This production is the foundation for any complete ``Swan Lake''
that can be considered traditional, including the one by London's
Sadler's Wells (now Royal) Ballet that astonished New York in 1949,
and American Ballet Theater's British-based version of 1967.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, ``Swan Lake'' has been subjected to much
tinkering (and, some might say, vandalism). The results have ranged
from what could be called ``Petipa-Ivanov respectfully revised'' to
such determinedly idiosyncratic efforts as John Neumeier's for the
Hamburg Ballet, which makes ``Swan Lake'' a demented vision of
Ludwig, the mentally unstable 19th-century king of Bavaria, and
Matthew Bourne's modern-dress reinterpretation with male swans,
recently seen on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Martins says his ``Swan Lake'' is basically his own
choreography, as influenced by Petipa, Ivanov and Balanchine. To
intensify its dramatic momentum, he will break the four-act work
with only one intermission.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
