NYT-04-20-99 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6378 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWAN-LAKE-BALLET-2NDT     04-20 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWAN-LAKE-BALLET-2NDTAKE-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: one intermission.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any producer of ``Swan Lake'' has to decide what it's all about.
``There's a moral tale there,'' Martins said. ``Life provides you
with choices, and you must make them, right or wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not the only moral ``Swan Lake'' can have. Here, for
instance, are the ideas behind another new ``Swan Lake,'' presented
earlier this month by the Tulsa Ballet: ``Its themes are impossible
love and the realization that both good and evil are inside us.''
</P>
<P>
   Those notions were advanced during a telephone interview with
Marcello Angelini, the Italian dancer who since 1995 has directed
the enterprising Oklahoma company founded in 1956 by Roman Jasinski
and Moscelyne Larkin, two veterans of the Ballets Russes.
</P>
<P>
   Act by act, producers must make important decisions. Thus,
should the first-act party include a Jester? This character,
unknown to Petipa and Ivanov, was invented by Aleksandr Gorsky for
a Moscow version of 1920. Enormously popular in Russia, the Jester
has capered his way into many later productions there.
</P>
<P>
   But American producers usually consider him superfluous.
Angelini pronounced him ``a nuisance.'' Martins, in contrast, finds
him appealing. Therefore City Ballet will have a Jester.
</P>
<P>
   Although modifications have been made in its adagio for Odette
and Siegfried, Ivanov's intricately patterned second act has been
left relatively unaltered over the years. Nevertheless, producers
have to decide what Rothbart symbolizes here. For Martins, he is
simply a wicked sorcerer. ``This is a `Swan Lake' without fancy
psychological twists or metaphors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other interpretations have been psychologically kinky. Take Erik
Bruhn's 1967 staging for the National Ballet of Canada: it made
Rothbart a woman, a Black Queen who, in murky Freudian symbolism,
served as a sinister counterpart to Siegfried's mother.
</P>
<P>
   The male Rothbart in Tulsa is an alter ego of Siegfried himself.
Angelini explained, ``Siegfried and Rothbart symbolize aspects of
the same personality, Siegfried representing the rational mind,
Rothbart representing the unconscious. And the unruly dark impulses
of the unconscious make it impossible for Odette and Siegfried to
remain together.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Martins and Angelini have Odile bewitch Siegfried in the
third act Black Swan pas de deux, in which she does 32 whipping
turns known as fouettes. At least, for Martins, she can do so if
she wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a fan of the fouette as a step,'' he confessed, adding
``I don't really like 32 of anything.'' In Copenhagen, Martins
permitted his ballerinas to perform the fouettes if they chose; if
they declined, he invented other steps for them. He will continue
that policy in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Swan Lake'' can end in many ways. In the Ivanov version, which
Ballet Theater retains, the remorseful Siegfried rejoins Odette and
they throw themselves into the lake. Their self-sacrifice defeats
Rothbart and unites them in the afterworld.
</P>
<P>
   But in Russia during the Soviet era, when supernatural themes
were suspect, Siegfried would vanquish Rothbart in a struggle; the
lovers then lived happily ever after on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Angelini conceived a happy ending of another kind. In his
confrontation between Siegfried and Rothbart, the two forces _ the
rational and the irrational _ are gradually reconciled, the ensuing
harmony causing Odette and the other swans to be human again.
Impossible love is impossible no more.
</P>
<P>
   Aschengreen called Martins' unhappy Copenhagen finale extremely
eloquent. But when asked what he plans for New York, Martin just
smiled enigmatically and said; ``If I told you how my ballet ended,
you might not go to see it. So come and find out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
