<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6386 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTENEGRO-BORDER-BOS     04-20 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTENEGRO-BORDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV MOVE INTO MONTENEGRO RAISES `CLEANSING' FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROZAJ, Yugoslavia _ The Yugoslav military has moved into the
northeast, Muslim region of the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro,
leading to fears that the ``ethnic cleansing'' in Kosovo could
spill over the border.
</P>
<P>
   Six civilians _ including at least one woman and a 13-year-old
boy _ were killed Sunday night in the area around the Muslim
municipality of Rozaj by Yugoslav Army soldiers or paramilitary
soldiers, Rozaj Mayor Nusret Kalac said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were ethnic Albanians killed by the Yugoslav Army,''
Kalac said. ``The situation is very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian news agency Beta said Yugoslav soldiers killed four
ethnic Albanians in a firefight near Rozaj Sunday night but claimed
the four were members of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Yugoslavia sent an estimated 200-300 Yugoslav
soldiers into the demilitarized zone of Prevlaka, between
Montenegro and Croatia. They also closed off the only working
border between the two lands. Montenegrin authorities said the
Yugoslav soldiers demanded that the police give up their posts to
Army control, but the police refused to leave.
</P>
<P>
   In Rosaj, Montenegrin Deputy Prime Minister Drgisa Burzan said
he saw ``bullet holes and blood'' in the area, and met two people _
a Kosovar and a Montenegrin villager _ wounded in the
shooting.``There are no discrepancies, in my eyes, of the stories
told by them,'' Burzan said. ``We take this as an extremely serious
matter, and we will launch a full investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the shooting, frightened residents of the tiny border
villages of Kaludjerski Laz and Bukelj have fled their homes for
relative safety in Rozaj, Kalac and international observers said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with reports Tuesday night that the Yugoslav army has
withdrawn from two of the villages, the Kosovar refugees who
trekked for hours or days from Kosovo, hoping to find relative
safety in Montenegro, are terrified that they are again in danger _
this time, with nowhere to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all very afraid, men, women and children, that we are
not safe here,'' said 47-year-old Hadzi Balaj, who arrived three
weeks ago from Istok, Kosovo. ``We are afraid they will come here,
and we wouldn't have a chance to go anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Razaj has taken 30,000 refugees _ nearly doubling the size of
the town. More than 2,000 are in the Kristal camp alone, warming
their shoes in old, open-front ovens and waiting desperately for a
way to go somewhere safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nineteen of my neighbors were killed'' by Yugoslav soldiers in
Istok, said 42-year-old Ramaj Salija. ``We are afraid the same
thing could happen here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro, which, with the larger Serbia, makes up Yugoslavia,
is in a tight, and increasingly tense, position with the federal
government in Belgrade. Montenegro's president, Milo Djukanovic,
has been sharply critical of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic,
and men here are dodging the aggressive draft effort by the federal
army.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having been bombed by NATO, Montenegro has sought to
stay out of the war. Many here feel Milosevic is trying to provoke
a civil war in Montenegro, destabilizing the republic and leaving
it vulnerable to a virtual takeover by Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The Montenegrin leadership has defiantly held off creeping
control from Belgrade, but the pro-Milosevic forces here are
becoming more aggressive, vocal, and numerous.
</P>
<P>
   Socialist Party leaders _ including representatives of what
Montenegrin authorities term ``illegal'' delegates to the federal
Yugoslav government _ are planning massive anti-NATO rallies in the
next two days.
</P>
<P>
   After the Yugoslav incursion into the demilitarized zone with
Croatia,
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Simonovic, the Croatian ambassador to the United Nations,
made an official protest to the UN Security Council, saying the
soldiers were not allowed in the area. Yugoslavia disputes the
piece of territory, which is under UN monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation at the border is delicate, sensitive, and
extremely tense,'' a UN observer told Reuters news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegrin police were being prohibited Tuesday from entering
the northern, Muslim village of Bukelj to assess the situation
there _ an extremely bold move against the jurisdictional right of
the local authorities over their own territory, Kalac said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the Montenegrin police would not charge into the
village, which could lead to a nasty confrontation with Yugoslav
Army soldiers. ``They are trying to provoke us,'' Kalac said. ``We
want to resolve it peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Details of the six dead are still sketchy. Kalac and
international observers say they believe the bodies have been
returned to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether the Yugoslav Army was deliberately
targeting refugees and locals in Montenegrin territory, or whether
the deaths were casualties in a Yugoslav effort to cut off the
Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The two villages are near Kalau Pass, the only road that
connects Montenegro with Kosovo. The Yugoslavs may have been in the
act of cutting off the food, oil and weapons route for the KLA,
observers said.
</P>
<P>
   The border pass also sits above Rugova Valley in Kosovo, where
KLA members are believed to be stationed.
</P>
<P>
   International observers were reluctant to call the killings and
near-emptying of these villages ``ethnic cleansing,'' noting that
the details of the incident are not clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something sparked an incident, and there was some shooting,''
said Rob Breen, an observer for the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees office in Podgorica. ``Were they closing
off an exit route? Who knows?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But ``there is a great fear among refugees, as well as people in
this town'' that the Yugoslav Army may start moving against Muslims
_ both Montenegrin and Kosovar _ in Montenegro, said Vehbija Bibic.
Bibic is director of the Kristal refugee camp _ so named for the
non-operating glass factory now used as barracks for refugees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
