<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6399 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKBOS-JACKSON-BOS &LR;      04-20 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKBOS-JACKSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKBOSTON'S JACKSON SAYS HE'LL DEPART AFTER FLEET MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- After more than a decade spent reshaping BankBoston
Corp.'s public image from a Brahmin institution indifferent to the
community to a bank committed to inner-city areas and local
projects, Ira A. Jackson is leaving.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, for 12 years the face of BankBoston before activists,
charities and lawmakers, has not been offered a position at the new
company to be formed from his bank's merger with its rival, Fleet
Financial Group Inc., BankBoston said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 50, is the second major BankBoston executive who will
not join the combined company. Chief financial officer Susannah
Swihart, as previously announced, will step down after the merger
to head a foundation for the new bank.
</P>
<P>
   Not a significant figure with Wall Street, but a powerful, if
controversial, lobbyist and spokesman in the company's hometown,
Jackson said he knew when he first learned of the merger in March
that he would not have a place at the new bank, which will be led
by Fleet chief executive Terrence Murray.
</P>
<P>
   ``The responsibilities I have must report directly to the chief
executive and it must be honest, symbiotic, and driven by chemistry
and magic,'' Jackson said. ``That's not something you can easily
transfer to another individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray has built a close relationship with Jackson's counterpart
at Fleet, Anne Finucane. Like Jackson, Finucane handles media
relations, philanthropy, sponsorships, regulatory affairs, and
community investments, as well as advertising and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The functions that report to Ira will be reporting to Anne
Finucane, who also retains her responsibilities for marketing,
advertising, and marketing research after the merger is
completed,'' Fleet spokesman James Mahoney said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's planned departure is an early sign of changing
chemistry and culture at Fleet and BankBoston, as the two different
companies chart out how they will meld into the nation's
eighth-largest bank. Merger analysts say that setting up a
communications and public relations staff is a crucial decision
that can help shape a company's success in putting together a new
organization and crafting a new public image.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Jackson, 215-year-old BankBoston is widely viewed as
more sympathetic to community-lending projects, while
entrepreneurial Fleet, a favorite on Wall Street, is seen as a
bottom-line business.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he ``knew instantly'' that he would not be part of
the new bank when BankBoston chief executive Charles K. ``Chad''
Gifford told him in the second week of March to prepare to fly to
New York to hammer out a final agreement that weekend to merge into
Fleet.
</P>
<P>
   In the 10 days after the $15 billion deal was completed, Gifford
and Jackson did not discuss Jackson's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at the end of March, the two men had a 20-minute
conversation in Jackson's 25th-floor office.
</P>
<P>
   True in spirit to BankBoston's patrician roots _ the company is
descended from the nation's oldest bank _ little was said but much
was understood, according to Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad is the essence of class and good breeding and good
values,'' he said. ``We both knew what the conversation was going
to be about, and there was quiet understanding that I would be
moving on.'' Jackson, who was hired by Gifford's media-shy
predecessor, Ira Stepanian, has had a stormy relationship with the
more public Gifford, who sometimes chafed at Jackson's prominence.
Gifford will head the combined bank when Murray retires in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston native who attended Harvard University, Jackson oversaw
a team of 60 staffers that completely revamped BankBoston's image.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the company in 1988 at a time when it was tarnished by a
money-laundering scandal and viewed as arrogantly aloof from
community matters, Jackson later earned plaudits for helping
establish Eagle Corps, a community service unit staffed by
BankBoston volunteers, and City Year, a youth work program. He also
got the bank involved with a host of local organizations, including
the Dimock Community Health Center and The Ten Point Coalition, a
inner-city religious alliance, and won recognition for BankBoston's
community bank group, one of the nation's largest inner-city branch
networks.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when corporations around the country were drawing
increased scrutiny for their community work, Jackson helped
BankBoston win top marks among local activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wrote the book on corporate social responsibility,'' said
Karen Schwartman, a former BankBoston spokeswoman who worked with
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of Jackson _ and there are many _ carp that he promotes
himself as much as the bank.
</P>
<P>
   But a BankBoston statement released Tuesday lavished praise on
the man and his achievements and said Jackson would continue as
chairman _ a largely ceremonial role _ of the company's urban
investment bank, BankBoston Development Corp. Jackson said he had
not yet decided where he will go after leaving when regulators
finalize the merger later this year.
</P>
<P>
   Although they are just now starting to hammer out a new
corporate structure, Fleet and BankBoston have said they will
continue their strong involvement in community affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was an administrative assistant to former Boston Mayor
Kevin H. White, an associate dean at Harvard's Kennedy School of
Government, and head of the Massachusetts Department of Revenue
under Governor Michael S. Dukakis before joining Bank of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   An executive with a six-figure salary, Jackson will leave
BankBoston with a generous severance package that includes millions
of dollars' worth of stock options, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   While Jackson lobbied tirelessly for his employer before
lawmakers, he said he never pushed for a position at the combined
bank. Sources said there had been no friction with Finucane, his
Fleet counterpart, because Jackson was never in the running for a
job to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became awkward, if not embarrassing, to read about
jockeying and efforts on my behalf,'' Jackson said. ``But the
decision was made a while back. I'm glad it's finally out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
