<HEADER>
A6404 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-COX     04-20 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Student recall moments of horror
 &HT;    By Ted Taylor
 &HT;    and Chris Barker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Columbine High School students Tuesday
described a scene of ``absolute fear and panic,'' after two
classmates opened fire during lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was absolute craziness,'' said Daniel Yager, a sophomore at
the Littleton school. ``There was a riot toward the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Yager said he and friends were just sitting down to lunch when
school officials screamed for the students to get down, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within 30 seconds, everyone started running for the stairs,''
Yager said. ``At the top, we heard three or four gunshots right
behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Tran was also eating lunch when he heard a small rumble
behind him. At first, he said, he thought it was a fight brewing.
</P>
<P>
   After school officials warned students, Tran's first thoughts
were, ``This can't be happening.''
</P>
<P>
   A few seconds later, he said, students jumped up and ran for the
doors.
</P>
<P>
   On the stairs, Tran said, he heard more gunshots. ``In about one
second it went from eating lunch to something weird's going on to,
`Oh my God you're about to die. Run,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Students hurried across the street to Leawood Park, Yager said.
There, he said, six more explosions in the school could be heard.
</P>
<P>
   Reports said the students believed to be involved in the
shooting were involved in a group called the ``Trenchcoat Mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Mike Zimmerman said the students were often picked on
for the way they dressed _in all-black, gothic fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were a group of outcasts basically,'' Zimmerman said.
``They kind of asked to be made fun of and picked on. It seemed
kind of obvious that something could happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The mass shootings at Columbine High School left Denver-area
motorists driving through rush-hour traffic in tears.
</P>
<P>
   Near the school last night, the situation was still unsettled,
with one report that police were searching for parked cars that
might have been booby-trapped with explosives.
</P>
<P>
   Six hours after the shootings began, many motorists on streets
leading to the school could be seen crying and talking on cellular
telephones.
</P>
<P>
   Leawood Elementary School, which is near Columbine High School,
was serving as a command post for law enforcement. Milling outside
were police, media and law enforcement officials . Many people,
including clergy members, arrived at the scene to offer whatever
assistance they could.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Poos-Benson is the pastor at Columbine United Church. He
said one of the wounded students attends his church. He expressed
the shock that undoubtedly many in this community felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, you never think ... it could happen here. The
message here is that it can happen anywhere. The community together
needs to assume responsibility for their children,'' Poos-Benson
said. The neighborhood near the school can be described as upper
middle class suburban with large homes.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and Barker write for the Daily Sentinel in Grand
Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
