<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      04-20 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS, SAYING CLINTON'S WEAKENED MILITARY, PLEDGE TO BEEF IT
UP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ariz., Idaho, Fla., Miss.)  (mk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans in Congress, charging that President
Clinton has weakened the nation's military, pledged Tuesday to add
billions of dollars for defense to his emergency request for funds
to finance NATO's airstrikes on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   They are discussing doubling the president's $6 billion
emergency request and using the money to beef up the national
arsenal. Some even talk of trying to triple the request, but say
they doubt they can win the votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans say they will use hearings and debate in coming
days to challenge Clinton's conduct as commander in chief, question
the progress of the war and call for sharp increases in Pentagon
spending.
</P>
<P>
   The House majority leader, Rep. Dick Armey, R-Texas, said
Clinton had created a national security crisis by misusing the
armed forces, and suggested that Republicans might scale back plans
for a huge tax cut, or cut domestic programs, to help pay for
missiles, munitions and other military needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton bled defense,'' Armey said. He and fellow Republicans
said Clinton had worn down the American military by repeatedly
using it for operations other than war, and that he had depleted
the nation's arsenal by using cruise missiles as a tool of armed
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   The president has presided over ``six years of neglect'' of the
military, ``a failed intelligence system'' and ``failed foreign
policy initiatives,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   His harsh words were a preview of the coming debate over the
Kosovo conflict as Congress weighs the emergency request this week
and next.
</P>
<P>
   The terms of that debate widened Tuesday when Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., a candidate for the Republican presidential nomination and
a former Navy aviator, offered a joint resolution authorizing
Clinton ``to use all necessary force'' to accomplish NATO's
objectives.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hoped his measure would ``encourage the
administration and our allies to find the courage and resolve to
prosecute this war'' in a way likely to win it.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress think the administration has been less
than forthcoming about its plans and aims in the conflict. Now, a
growing frustration with the progress of the bombing, fed by a
perception that the need to achieve consensus among NATO's members
is hobbling the military, is stoking anger at the president,
several senators and congressmen said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, chairman of the Senate Republican
Policy Committee, said that ``what Dick Armey was expressing has
been expressed to me'' in caucuses and corridors of the Senate _
that Clinton's conduct of foreign policy has been ``depleting the
military,'' and that ``the military needed more money.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. C.W. Young, R-Fla., chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee, whose defense subcommittee will begin to consider the
president's emergency request on Wednesday, said he could not allow
his fellow Republicans to run away with the spending bill. But
Young said the United States had been ``excessively deploying our
troops'' and ``wearing out our equipment'' under Clinton. ``We have
a lot of catching up to do'' in national defense, he said, adding
that ``the wish list'' for weaponry is long.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans did not agree Tuesday how much to add to the
president's request, said Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the Senate
majority leader. Nor are they likely to agree this week. Senior
Republicans in the Senate and the House, including Craig and Young,
said suggestions from fellow members that the emergency request
should be $15 billion, $18 billion or more were unlikely to pass
Congress. House staff members said they have heard Republican
proposals as high as $22 billion.
</P>
<P>
   They also have not decided what the money should buy, or where
it will come from. Many would rather dip into surplus Social
Security funds for a one-time emergency than scale back their plans
for an $800 billion tax cut over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's emergency request seeks $6.05 billion. About $5.46
billion would go to the Pentagon. Of that, $3.3 billion is for
military operations, $850 million for military contingency funds,
$698 million for bombs and missiles, $335 million for multilateral
refugee resettlement efforts and $274 million to pay for military
operations against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Additional funds include $386 million for food, shelter and
water for refugees, to be meted out by the State Department and the
Agency for International Development; $150 million to help the
nations to which Kosovo Albanians have fled, and $55 million for
diplomatic operations _ like evacuating the American Embassy in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon already takes more than half of the money Congress
spends, excluding mandatory programs like Social Security, Medicare
and interest on the national debt. Congress has vowed to keep
spending down and to keep its hands off extra Social Security
funds. Additional new funds for the Pentagon in coming years may
require breaking those promises or cutting popular programs,
congressional staff members said.
</P>
</TEXT>
