A6413 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SHOOTING-BOS &LR;      04-20 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SHOOTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAPPED STUDENTS TURNED TO TV FOR LIFE-SAVING ADVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``If you're watching, kids, turn your TV off, or at least
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The voice of authority speaking those words Tuesday was not a
police officer but a local television news anchor in Denver,
addressing students trapped inside classrooms at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo., who had apparently tuned in to TV for
information on their own life-and-death crisis.
</P>
<P>
   When masked gunmen opened fire inside a school that had
televisions in each classroom, TV news stations in Denver found
themselves drawn into the middle of the story, which at times lent
a self-consciousness to their coverage. ``We are assuming (the
gunmen) are able to watch all the coverage,'' noted a reporter for
KMGH-TV in the middle of the crisis. An anchor added: ``We would
say: `Give yourselves up.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a student unable to escape from the school used a
cell phone to call KUSA-TV in Denver, whereupon he described the
terrifying scene while hiding under a desk in a locked classroom.
The student even started to say where he was before an anchor
stopped him and urged him to call 911. The student did so, but
found the 911 line jammed, and placed another call to the station,
which connected him with the emergency line.
</P>
<P>
   There was dramatic footage aplenty, much of it transmitted
nationally by the major networks, but the shootings also
underscored the role of emotional barometer that television often
plays in times of crisis, reflecting a community's horror and
incredulity. An anchor at KMGH-TV gasped, ``Look at that!'' as a
blood-streaked youth dropped from a second-story window. Her
co-anchor expressed disbelief ``that this could happen in our
area.''
</P>
<P>
   In the heat of the moment, missteps occurred. At one point, the
information was broadcast that one youth was trapped inside the
school's ``choir room,'' a potentially risky step if the gunmen
were watching TV inside the school.
</P>
<P>
   At another point, KUSA initially urged trapped students to call
the station with information for the police on the gunmen's
whereabouts. ``Any students that might be hiding at the school,
call the station,'' said Kim Christiansen, an anchor at KUSA-TV.
``We will put you in touch with the police.''
</P>
<P>
   But minutes later, Christiansen retracted those instructions,
saying to students: ``Do not call the station. Be quiet. Stay where
you are.''
</P>
<P>
   News executives at KUSA-TV could not be reached for comment, and
a spokeswoman said she did not know the reason for the retraction.
Cory Shields, a spokesman for MSNBC, which carried the KUSA feed,
said the station altered its instructions to students ``once they
realized it was a security issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at KMGH-TV and KCNC-TV, the other Denver stations
that supplied footage to the networks Tuesday, also could not be
reached. NBC, CBS and ABC all interrupted regular programming to
carry the story, but the all-news cable networks _ CNN, MSNBC, Fox
News Channel and New England Cable News _ devoted the most time to
the story.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, televised images illustrated a scene both
shocking and dishearteningly familiar: the stricken faces of
students and parents, the cluster of paramedics and SWAT teams, the
chaotic aftermath of yet another shooting inside a school.
</P>
<P>
   There were heart-rending interviews with students such as the
girl who told how she begged for her life while the gunmen waved a
gun in her face and laughed. ``Everybody near me got shot,'' she
sobbed. A teenage boy told of seeing ``a friend of mine's head
blown off.''
</P>
<P>
   The trauma was evident on the faces of those who escaped. One
student, a freshman, worriedly told reporters that ``one of my best
friends, Ashley, is in there.'' A teenage boy said bitterly that
the shooters were known beforehand as ``the scum of the school.''
Another youth reported that ``it was another casual day'' in the
moments before bullets began ``ricocheting off lockers.''
</P>
<P>
   Some reporters struggled with their emotions in reporting the
story; others were plainly stunned. ``This is a very tense
situation out here,'' one said. ``It's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   TV news cameras captured some striking sights: dozens of
students fleeing the school under the protection of a SWAT team;
three friends of the shooting suspects being ordered to lie
face-down in a field by police officers; helicopter shots of a
once-tranquil school transformed into a battleground.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a role that often falls to local TV stations when
tragedy strikes, the Denver stations served as information
clearinghouses. They posted hotline numbers for parents to call and
reminded them to stay away from the cordoned-off school area with
the chilling words, ``Your child is in lockdown. Do not go to pick
him or her up.'' They directed students to an address for ``crisis
counseling'' near the school. And some anchors even admonished
parents who could not be reached by their children, exhorting them
to supply their offspring with a number where they could be
contacted.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those interviewed expressed an ``it-can't-happen-here''
shock at the shootings, but one man said sadly: ``We've got a great
neighborhood, but this stuff happens everyplace.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
