<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPERMINATOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SPERMINATOR BILL' BEGINS JOURNEY IN TEXAS HOUSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ With more than 3,800 Texas House bills on file
already, there's no huge clamor for more. But one member won
overwhelming approval to submit a bill well past the filing
deadline, perhaps because of its unusual nature.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed by one colleague as the ``sperminator bill,'' House Bill
3830 by Rep. Brian McCall, R-Plano, relates to ``certain
post-mortem procedures.'' It would bar harvesting a dead man's
sperm for reproductive purposes unless he gave permission while
alive.
</P>
<P>
   The measure requires that the sperm donor give written
permission before his death and that any such request come from his
spouse.
</P>
<P>
   McCall's late bill would take effect Sept. 1, if it clears the
many procedural hurdles that await. He said he's not addressing any
particular incident but is trying to keep pace with biotechnology
and to prevent possible abuses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6415 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHARTER-PROBE-COX     04-20 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARTER-PROBE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CBS to air investigation of mental health facilities
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (a) General news and (f) Financial categories.)
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ CBS News tonight plans to report a yearlong
investigation of Alpharetta, Ga.-based Charter Behavioral Health
Systems, alleging dangerous conditions, falsification of medical
records, and lack of employee training in company psychiatric
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations _ including injuries and two patient deaths _
are part of an hourlong ``60 Minutes II'' program, reported by Ed
Bradley, to be aired tonight at 9. Charter late Tuesday filed a
motion for a temporary restraining order in Federal District Court
in Charlotte to keep the program from being aired, according to
CBS.
</P>
<P>
   CBS said it will oppose the motion. A hearing has been scheduled
for 1:30 this afternoon, CBS said. Charter officials could not be
reached for comment on the motion.
</P>
<P>
   A videotape of the CBS program, which focuses on children's care
in Charter hospitals, begins with a death of a 16-year-old North
Carolina youth in a Greensboro, N.C. facility last year. Tristan
Sovern died in what are called ``restraints,'' where a patient's
ankles and wrists are locked into cuffs or straps.
</P>
<P>
   CBS also shows former and current Charter employees describing
inadequate training, lack of physician supervision, and hospital
practices that endangered both staff and patients. CBS said it
interviewed dozens of employees from more than 20 Charter hospitals
in 15 states.
</P>
<P>
   Charter executives said Tuesday they had not seen the program.
But they strongly denied CBS's charges of widespread problems.
Charter also said that CBS, in its reporting, may have breached
patient confidentiality laws.
</P>
<P>
   CBS bases much of the segment's reporting on a social worker,
Terrance Johnson, who wore a hidden camera during eight weeks of
employment at a Charter facility in Charlotte. CBS said Johnson was
not hired or paid by the network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone to great lengths to obscure the identity of any
patient who was shot,'' Bradley said in an interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Charter, a private company, operates 91 psychiatric hospitals in
32 states. Eleven facilities are in Georgia, with six in metro
Atlanta. It's the largest chain of private psychiatric hospitals in
the country, with annual revenues of more than $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   Charter Behavioral is 50 percent owned by Atlanta-based Magellan
Health Services, which has tried unsuccessfully to sell the
hospitals to Charter's co-owner, Crescent Operating.
</P>
<P>
   None of the employees or reported incidents used on camera
involve the company's Georgia facilities. Charter did not consent
to an on-camera interview by CBS, but instead sent a letter to the
network, saying that ``Charter's mission is to combine compassion
with the highest quality of comprehensive care.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley interviews the mother of Tristan Sovern. The 16-year-old
was restrained at the Greensboro hospital, and then, according to
the CBS report, had a towel and then a sheet wrapped around his
mouth. He died of asphyxiation, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Michael French, who took over as Charter chief executive and
president in October, said he couldn't comment on the death because
of ongoing legal proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Through Johnson's camera, CBS also shows an employee altering a
patient record.
</P>
<P>
   Any falsification of records would be grounds for firing,
Charter's French said. The company has a hotline for employees, and
family members to report any problems at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``These problems aren't typical in our institutions,'' French
said. If they occurred, they'd be very isolated or rare, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The industry as a whole has little local or federal oversight,
Bradley reports. He also notes that at least 32 patients have died
while being restrained in facilities other than Charter.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, meanwhile, is considering national standards on the
use of restraints and on seclusion, or being isolated in a
designated room. A series by the Hartford Courant recently
documented that 142 people have died in physical or mechanical
restraints in the past 10 years in psychiatric facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Charter, in fact, recently announced a company-wide initiative
to greatly reduce the restraint and seclusion practice in its
hospitals. The company said it started reviewing these practices
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to come out as an industry leader,'' said French. He
denied the removal plan was a public relations ploy or an effort to
head off congressional action.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Young of the National Mental Health Association said the
problems described in the ``60 Minutes'' report are present _ but
not epidemic _ in psychiatric hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be hard pressed to say one set of facilities is better
or worse than another,'' Young added.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
