<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6417 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORSTMANN-SCHOLARSHIP     04-20 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORSTMANN-SCHOLARSHIPS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIER RAISES LEVEL OF DEBATE OVER SUPPORT FOR PRIVATE
EDUCATION
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A billionaire Wall Street financier who raised $170
million in scholarships to send low-income children to private
schools said on Tuesday that more than a million families had
responded to his offer, or nearly one out of 50 school-children in
America.
</P>
<P>
   The financier, Theodore J. Forstmann, better known for his
leveraged buyouts of companies like Gulfstream Aerospace, Dr Pepper
and General Instruments, said he had turned his business savvy to
helping thousands of children escape failing public schools and go
to private and religious schools. But the response to his offer
surprised even him, he said, and it has added fuel to the debate
over privatization of the nation's education system.
</P>
<P>
   Although the scholarships were open to students now enrolled in
either public or private schools, the majority of applicants came
from public schools, indicating a deep level of dissatisfaction
with the education they are getting, Forstmann said. The 40,000
winners, chosen over the last few days by a computerized lottery,
are to be announced on Wednesday at simultaneous ceremonies in New
York and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In capturing public attention, Forstmann was armed with fervor
for his cause, his immense wealth, and a well-oiled public
relations machine, which generated public service announcements by
the baseball star Sammy Sosa, the poet Maya Angelou and the rap
artist Will Smith. In February, Forstmann benefited from a dollop
of Oprah Winfrey, who instructed viewers to turn off their vacuum
cleaners while she interviewed him. A Republican, Forstmann
assembled a board decked out with public figures in both parties,
from Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York to Gen. Colin L.
Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Forstmann said the number of applicants _ 1,237,360, including
nearly one out of three qualified students in New York City;
Newark, N.J.; New Orleans; Philadelphia, and Washington, D.C. _ was
even more compelling given that the scholarships will amount to
only $600 to $1,600 a year for four years, not enough to cover the
$2,500 average tuition at parochial schools, and that the winners
will be required to make a matching contribution averaging $1,000 a
year from their own pockets.
</P>
<P>
   He called the response ``a cry from the heart.'' Noting that
poor students get a free public education, he added, ``So they're
quite impoverished, they get their product for nothing and they're
lining up around the corner to pay $1,000.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics said that while giving out scholarships seemed
benign on the surface, they wondered what would happen in four
years, when the current funds run out. Some said Forstmann and his
partner, John Walton, heir to the Walmart discount-chain fortune,
were more likely to shore up financially ailing Catholic schools
and provide opportunities for private education entrepreneurs than
to reform the education system.
</P>
<P>
   Wittingly or not, they said, Forstmann and his associates could
become an important tool in pushing state legislatures across the
country toward the adoption of taxpayer financing of vouchers to
send children to private and religious schools. Forstmann, who is
Catholic, has supported Catholic-school scholarships in the past,
and critics of voucher proposals noted on Tuesday that Walton has
ties to a profit-making corporation, Tesseract Group, that manages
charter and public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly become a stalking horse for vouchers,'' Sandra
Feldman, president of the United Federation of Teachers, said on
Tuesday. ``Raising money for private and parochial schools is a
longtime tradition in the U.S. But now you've got people telling
parents over and over again that their kids can do better than what
they do now. It's all over television, it's on Oprah. When you
listen carefully there's something going on about getting kids out
of the public schools, and that's terribly unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the opposition acknowledges that Forstmann has elevated
the debate over whether the public schools are fulfilling their
mission of providing an equal education to all, especially black,
Hispanic and immigrant children in the inner city. Using an idea
that would warm the heart of a free-market economist _ leveraging
scholarships to help thousands of children seek a better education
_ Forstmann has tapped into the deepest fears and hopes of parents
about the future of their children.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the applicants came from New York City, the nation's
largest school system, where 168,184 students applied, or 29
percent of the 587,092 public and private school student who met
the eligibility guidelines. Students were eligible, officials said,
if their family income was just above the cutoff for the federal
free lunch program, a measure of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago had the next highest number, with 59,186 applicants, or
26 percent of those eligible, Los Angeles had 54,444 applicants, or
18 percent. In Baltimore, 44 percent, or 46,011, of those eligible
applied.
</P>
<P>
   Winners are being notified this week, before Wednesday's
ceremony. Most of the scholarships will be awarded in Los Angeles,
with 3,750; New York and Chicago will get 2,500 each and other
cities will get hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at some point the public schools start to fail our
children, and I think the third-grade is that cutoff,'' said
Shelitha Harrelson, a New Yorker whose daughter, Brittney Tucker,
was told this week that she is one of the 40,000 winners.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harrelson, whose daughter is in third grade at P.S. 279 in
Brooklyn, said she hoped to use her stipend to help pay the costs
at Marymount, a Manhattan private school where tuition costs
$12,000 a year, or Epiphany, a religious school where tuition is
$4,000. Ms. Harrelson, an administrative coordinator at Polo Ralph
Lauren and a single mother, met the income criterion of $29,295 for
a family of two, just above the cutoff to qualify for the lunch
program.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM STARTS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   New York City's schools chancellor, Rudy Crew, who threatened to
resign last month when Mayor Rudolph Giuliani began lobbying for a
government-financed voucher program, said he had no quarrel with
the fund, as long as it used private money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never claimed the public school system is a perfect
system'' Crew said. ``I think this is on the natural; it's going to
happen. It is a sign that there are people who want choice.'' Crew
said he was trying to meet that demand as well with a push to
create charter schools independent of the Board of Education and
some union rules.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, Paul Vallas, the chief executive of the public
schools, said: ``I'm all for it. Here you have people from the
private sector pooling their money to help make a child's education
better. How can you be against that?''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS HERE)
</P>
<P>
   Forstmann and Walton started the program, called the Children's
Scholarship Fund, eight months ago by contributing $50 million
each, and said they have since raised another $70 million.
</P>
<P>
   The program is the biggest privately financed scholarship
program in the country, Forstmann and his associates said, and also
dwarfs experiments with taxpayer-financed voucher programs to send
poor children to private schools in Milwaukee and Cleveland.
Neither Milwaukee nor Cleveland are among the cities receiving
scholarships, according to a list released on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the fund's national board of advisers,
including Moynihan and Rep. Charles Rangel of Manhattan, said they
had signed on to the program because they saw it as a chance for
children to attend better schools than the ones they were in, not
as an attack on the public-school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm against vouchers,'' Rangel said. ``I support scholarships
for public schools, private schools, and any other kind of
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he saw no long-term threat that private schools
would take over. ``We don't have enough private schools in the city
to absorb the kids even if they did have the vouchers. I'm not
concerned with people who debate these things at cocktail parties
and have their kids already in private schools. I encourage that
type of debate and discussion but I'm not turning down the
scholarships while I'm doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carole Shields, president of the People for the American Way
Foundation, said Walton's connection with Tesseract Group, the
for-profit education company, suggested that he could profit from
the scholarships. Walton did not return requests for comment left
at the fund's New York offices. But Forstmann said there was no
conflict. ``It seems to me so massively irrelevant,'' he said. ``Do
you know how much money John Walton's got?''
</P>
<P>
   Forstmann said he had no interest in promoting vouchers or
Catholic schools, only in challenging what he called the
government's monopoly control of education. ``We need a competitive
environment,'' Forstmann said. ``I'm in the airplane business. Let
me tell you, you don't fly a Russian airplane, which is state
sponsored.''
</P>
<P>
   As for what the alternative might be, he said: ``I'm not a
politician. I do believe that parents should have a choice, but
that's as far as I can go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
