<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-AWARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNIS GURU COLLINS TO BE HONORED BY EDITORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- With his colorful prose and trousers to match, Bud
Collins has brought unequaled exuberance and expertise to sports
journalism. At the Associated Press Sports Editors national
convention June 25, the NBC tennis commentator and Globe
correspondent will be honored with the Red Smith Award, the APSE's
highest commendation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably the biggest honor I've had,'' said Collins. ``I
was very pleased. I think to be voted for something by your peers
is always an honor. I knew Red slightly, but admired him mightily.
Jim Murray was a friend. I think I know all the (former award
winners) but one. I consider many of them friends. It's a nice cast
to be part of. I'm glad just to be a walk-on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Smith Award recognizes a writer who has made ``major
contributions to sports journalism.'' APSE established the award in
1981 and named Smith, a columnist for The New York Times, the first
winner. Collins also joins the elite company of Pulitzer Prize
winners Murray and Dave Anderson, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``This award recognizes a brilliant career in which Bud's wit,
creativity, and intelligence served his readers well,'' said Globe
editor Matthew V. Storin. ``In particular, he probably did more
than any other writer to bring the game of professional tennis to
the height of its popularity.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins's writing has appeared in the Globe since 1963. He has
covered it all, from the Red Sox to the British Open to the
Olympics. He cited his coverage of the Vietnam War and Muhammad
Ali's career as points of pride. But his take on tennis is
legendary.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous honor, and one Bud richly deserves,''
said Don Skwar, the Globe's assistant managing editor for sports.
``Bud is Mr. Tennis. He's known not just in the country but all
over the world as the preeminent writer and voice of the game. When
it comes to his body of work over the last 30-plus years, there's
only one way to put it: Advantage, Collins.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Collins made his indelible mark as a tennis writer and
television commentator, leading the way for writers to showcase
their talents as broadcasters when he left the Globe as a full-time
employee in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Through his writing and TV work, Collins has become a well-known
and well-respected figure in the tennis community. The top players
past and present are never more than a phone call away. After a day
of matches last year at Longwood in Boston, fans lined up for a
copy of Collins's new book, ``The Bud Collins' Tennis
Encyclopedia,'' and a few words with the 1994 inductee into the
International Tennis Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Collins makes the game fun for the masses with his playful
nicknames and witty commentary. He brought us ``Chris America'' for
Chris Evert, the ``Bucharest Buffoon'' for Ilie Nastase, ``Fraulein
Forehand'' for Steffi Graf, and most recently ``Sisters
Sledgehammer'' for Venus and Serena Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel lucky to do both (television and sports writing) on a
national and international level,'' said Collins, who calls himself
a ``scribbler and a babbler'' with characteristic humility.
``(Covering sports) beats working for a living. I've always felt
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
