A6424 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUKAS-MUSIC-2TAKES-$A     04-20 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUKAS-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDISCOVERING THE WORK OF A GREAT SELF-DEPRECATOR  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 David Mermelstein writes about music for The New Criterion.  
 By DAVID MERMELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the average American knows the name of the French composer
Paul Dukas at all, it is probably in connection with an image of
Mickey Mouse wearing a baggy red robe and a wizard's hat, battling
anthropomorphic broomsticks to the strains of Dukas' ``Sorcerer's
Apprentice.''
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney's use of that piece in the movie ``Fantasia'' made
Dukas more famous than he might have dreamed, or even hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Dukas, who died in 1935, five years before ``Fantasia'' was
released, would probably have been appalled if he had lived to see
``The Sorcerer's Apprentice,'' a 12-minute symphonic scherzo,
achieve world renown. One of music's great self-deprecators, he
firmly believed that nothing he wrote was good enough.
</P>
<P>
   He destroyed much of his work and was plagued by doubts about
the music his friends persuaded him to publish. That he was also a
professional music critic, as well as a respected teacher, may have
contributed to his feelings of inadequacy.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen of Dukas' well-wrought works survive, including the
ballet ``La Peri'' and one opera, ``Ariane et Barbe-Bleue,'' which
is virtually unknown in America. The Metropolitan Opera, which gave
the work's American premiere in 1911 and performed it the next
year, has since ignored it.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Keene, as general director of the New York City
Opera, longed to stage it but never managed to do so. But Sunday
afternoon, Leon Botstein will conduct the American Symphony
Orchestra in a concert version of the opera at Avery Fisher Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Renate Behle, the Austrian soprano who will sing the female
lead, is a veteran in the part, having performed it at the Hamburg
Opera in 1997 and 1998. Though hardly a repertory staple in Europe,
``Ariane'' is occasionally staged on the Continent. It was
presented at the Paris Opera in the mid-1970s with Grace Bumbry and
at the Theatre du Chatelet in Paris in 1991 with Francoise Pollet.
(In 1984, the French label Erato issued a recording of the work,
now out of print.)
</P>
<P>
   The indefatigable Botstein, who is committed to broadening the
repertory, has championed a host of neglected scores, but this is
one of his most ambitious efforts yet. ``Ariane,'' in three acts,
runs two hours without intermissions, and the role of Ariane is
strenuous. Yet Botstein believes in Dukas' opera, which he calls
``fantastically well written.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is he alone in his enthusiasm. After the work's Vienna
premiere in 1908, Schoenberg, Webern and Berg congratulated Dukas.
So did Mahler, though his wife, Alma, reported that only the
opera's first act enchanted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ariane'' was of ``decisive importance'' in the development of
the Austrian-American composer Erich Wolfgang Korngold, Brendan G.
Carroll writes in ``The Last Prodigy,'' a recent Korngold
biography. The American film composer Hugo Friedhofer, Carroll
adds, said that Korngold had admitted to ``living off `Ariane' for
many years.''
</P>
<P>
   And Messiaen, Dukas' greatest student, not only praised the
opera but also found religious inspiration in it, seeing in
Ariane's quest for truth and eventual liberation an echo of the
gospels. In an essay published a year after Dukas' death, Messiaen
called ``Ariane'' a ``still misunderstood masterpiece,'' and Dukas'
music a ``magic legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ariane,'' with a libretto by Maurice Maeterlinck, relates the
grim story of Bluebeard and his wives in semi-inspiring fashion.
Though based on the 17th-century fairy tale by Charles Perrault, in
which Bluebeard has killed his many wives, Dukas' opera finds them
alive but imprisoned; Ariane discovers them through her ceaseless
curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2033EDT &QL; 
