A6425 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG)     04-20 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDRAFTED BRUINS SIGN DEALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A slew of undrafted UCLA football players have
signed free-agent contracts and will participate in minicamps this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Brendon Ayanbadejo signed with Atlanta, safety Tod
McBride with Seattle, guard Andy Meyers with Buffalo and tight end
Ryan Neufeld with Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``My agent was telling teams not to draft me when it got past
the fourth or fifth round,'' Meyers said. ``(As a free agent) you
have a much better chance of finding the right fit.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, kicker Chris Sailer, fullback Craig Walendy and
tight end Mike Grieb are expected to join the San Francisco 49ers,
whose personnel director is former UCLA coach Terry Donahue.
</P>
<P>
   The free-agent frenzy is becoming routine in Westwood. Although
UCLA is tied with Arizona State for the most victories in the
Pac-10 in the last three years (25), the Bruins rank ninth in the
conference in draft picks produced over that period.
</P>
<P>
   The differential indicates coach Bob Toledo's staff has made the
most of the shallow talent pool inherited from the Donahue regime.
Donahue's last three recruiting classes (1993-95) have produced
just six draft picks: none in 1997,; three last year (Shaun
Williams, Skip Hicks, Chad Overhauser) and three this year (Cade
McNown, Kris Farris, Larry Atkins).
</P>
<P>
   __ QB update: Toledo wants to establish a starting quarterback
when the Bruins break spring practice May 1. At minimum, he hopes
to whittle the contenders from five to two.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, not Drew Bennett, Scott McEwan, Cory Paus, Ryan
McCann or J.P. Losman has claimed the top spot. ``There is no
clear-cut guy,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury update: Josh Webb has joined his brother, Micah, on
the injured list _ leaving the Bruins with two scholarship tackles:
incumbent Brian Polak and redshirt freshman Blake Worley. Josh
(shoulder) and Micah (knee) are expected back for training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackles Anthony Fletcher (hamstring) and Ken Kocher
(arthroscopic knee surgery) are out indefinitely. Without them,
redshirt freshman Sean Phillips, converted offensive lineman Steve
Morgan and walk-on Kory Lombard are taking the snaps.
</P>
<P>
   __ Positions to watch: At least 12 starting positions are
undecided. Here are a few spots the coaches are examining closely
(excluding quarterback):
</P>
<P>
   ++ Right guard: Jim Ghezzi, the former Glendale College star,
will give redshirt freshman Mike Saffer, perhaps UCLA's most gifted
lineman, a run for the No. 1 spot.
</P>
<P>
   ++ Tight end: Gabe Crecion, Randy Hakes and Bryan Fletcher are
competing before heralded recruit Mike Seidman arrives in August.
</P>
<P>
   ++ Safety: Jason Stephens played well last season and probably
has one spot secured, but Eric Whitfield and freshman Audie Attar
are battling for the other.
</P>
<P>
   ++ Defensive end: Starter Santi Hall has been suspended for
spring practice and might not return for training camp _ leaving
Travor Turner, Steve Sua and redshirt freshman Rusty Williams to
compete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6427 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUKAS-MUSIC-2NDTAKE-$     04-20 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUKAS-MUSIC-2NDTAKE-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: ceaseless curiosity.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dukas' opera was first performed in 1907 at the Opera-Comique in
Paris, with Georgette Leblanc, Maeterlinck's companion, in the
female lead. The Met staging, with the legendary soprano Geraldine
Farrar, came four years later, conducted by Arturo Toscanini.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Aldrich, reviewing that performance in The New York
Times, praised Toscanini and Farrar. He found the opera as a whole
not quite worthy of ``sensation or undue excitement,'' though he
termed the score ``in many ways a remarkable achievement,'' adding
that ``there is much that is fascinating, seizing and beautiful in
the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Dukas' lush and glinting strains are rife with
high-octane outbursts, both vocal and orchestral. Though the opera
is distinctly Dukas', it is punctuated by moments of Wagnerian pomp
right out of ``Die Meistersinger.''
</P>
<P>
   And it is often compared to the lone opera by Dukas' friend
Debussy, ``Pelleas et Melisande,'' which had its premiere in 1902
and also used a Symbolist text by Maeterlinck, set in a
quasi-medieval cosmos. But unlike ``Pelleas,'' ``Ariane'' was
intended for a musical setting from the start. (Maeterlinck
apparently wanted Grieg to compose the score at first.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Ariane'' is perhaps closest kin of all to Bartok's one-act
opera, ``Bluebeard's Castle,'' which has received far more
attention on stage and on records. (Christoph von Dohnanyi and the
Cleveland Orchestra will give a concert performance of
``Bluebeard's Castle'' on May 8 at Carnegie Hall.)
</P>
<P>
   Both works take their inspiration from Perrault's story, and
Bela Balazs' text for ``Bluebeard's Castle'' was, like
Maeterlinck's ``Ariane'' libretto, always intended for the opera
stage.
</P>
<P>
   As in ``Ariane'' (and ``Pelleas''), the action in ``Bluebeard's
Castle'' is relatively static. Bartok divides the score's vocal
honors neatly between the abusive Bluebeard and his fourth wife,
Judith, whereas Dukas lavishes most of his music on Ariane,
Bluebeard's sixth wife. In fact, Dukas' Bluebeard has a mere eight
lines in the first act, is banished altogether in the second and
stands mute on stage in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the musical styles of the two works are dissimilar, and they
differ most strikingly in the ways they conclude. In Bartok, Judith
joins Bluebeard's women as darkness descends. In Dukas, Ariane
leaves Bluebeard's castle (and his other wives) to venture into the
light.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Behle, for one, likes Dukas' more upbeat ending, seeing in
it the promise of female emancipation. But she acknowledges that
the part of Ariane is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is singing and singing and singing,'' Ms. Behle said
recently from Dresden, Germany, where she was performing. ``It
doesn't stop.''
</P>
<P>
   As for performing a concert version, Ms. Behle suggested that
the work might prove more effective in this sparer setting.
(Aldrich, in his Times review of 1911, implied much the same.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The opera is very tough to act,'' Ms. Behle said. ``So much is
poetic and internal between a husband and a wife, and it's
therefore very difficult to stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Behle, who has proved a commanding Isolde, is strongly
attracted to the role of Ariane, seeing the character as
particularly vital. But she is less enamored of Dukas' score,
finding it ``romantic and beautiful'' but a pastiche.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a reason it is not done very often,'' she
said. ``It is not `Pelleas.'''
</P>
<P>
   Botstein begs to differ. ``I have a lot of allegiance to
Dukas,'' he said. Besides, he added, ``we need to rescue this guy
from Mickey Mouse.''
</P>
</TEXT>
