<HEADER>
A6435 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHIPPING-COMPETE-ART-     04-20 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHIPPING-COMPETE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEMI-DEREGULATION OF OCEAN SHIPPING: HIGHER COSTS ON THE HIGH
SEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on West Coast container trade with East Asia and
graphic on top 10 U.S. container lines are being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The ocean-shipping business will be largely
deregulated on May 1, setting off a scramble among shipping lines
to lure customers with discounts. The same day, however, virtually
all ships carrying goods from Asia to the United States plan to
raise their rates by the same, mutually agreed, amount.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds contradictory, it is. But the state of affairs
reflects the forces buffeting the shipping business, which is now
going through some of the biggest changes in its tradition-bound
history.
</P>
<P>
   Under the partial deregulation, container shipping lines for the
first time will be able to sign individual, confidential contracts
with importers and exporters. The competition to sign up such
customers is expected to greatly loosen the grip of the cartels
that have legally set rates for ocean shipping for more than a
century.
</P>
<P>
   But the shipping industry's unusual immunity from federal
antitrust laws _ something it has enjoyed almost ever since there
were antitrust laws _ is not being eliminated. So even as they
enter a less-regulated era, the shipping lines, reeling from low
profits and overcapacity, are collectively raising rates on imports
from Asia by 30 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a clash between the old and new ways of doing
business, and no one is quite sure how it will turn out.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts expect that eventually container shipping will
follow the paths of airlines, trucking and railroads, which began
their deregulation two decades ago. There will be lower prices and
better service over all, but also a brutal period of mergers and
bankruptcies among the competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Others say that the continued right to set rates collectively
will blunt these effects. ``It isn't going to be airlines,'' said
Ashley Craig, a consultant at Rodriguez &AMP; Associates, a Washington
law firm that represents small importers and exporters. ``It isn't
going to be rail or trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of which way shipping costs move, consumers might not
notice much difference. This is because that, for most goods, such
as imported sneakers or videocassette recorders, shipping costs
contribute only a tiny amount to the final price.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with more than $400 billion in goods entering or leaving
the United States each year on container ships, even little changes
mount up. Moreover, shipping lines, pressed to cut costs further,
might make even more demands for concessions from
taxpayer-supported ports. Sea-Land Service, a unit of CSX Corp.,
and Maersk Inc. of Copenhagen, a subsidiary of AP Moller Group, are
now making such demands of the ports of New York and New Jersey and
Baltimore, which are vying for the lines' business, with jobs and
income at stake.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing many shipping executives want right now is more
competition. The economic downturn in Asia, which has led to record
trade deficits for the United States, has also caused serious
imbalances for their lines. And the situation may well continue:
The Commerce Department reported Tuesday that the nation's trade
deficit jumped to a new monthly high of $19.4 billion in February,
largely on the strength of imports and the weakening demand for
exports.
</P>
<P>
   Ships bringing imports to the United States from East Asia, the
largest trade route in the world, are stuffed to capacity, but the
ships going back to Asia are half-empty. Shipping lines say they
need revenue on both legs to make a profit. And that is why they
are raising rates in the busy direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the business 30 years and the imbalance has never
been that bad,'' said Albert Pierce, chairman and executive
director of the Transpacific Stabilization Agreement, the group of
carriers that decided on the May 1 rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   The bulging trade deficit can be seen in the form of empty
shipping containers stacked four high on the piers at the adjacent
ports of Long Beach and Los Angeles, which together handle about a
third of the nation's container traffic. For many months last year,
as exports to Asia dried up, more empty containers were being sent
back to Asia than full ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our No. 1 export was empty containers,'' said Harold Hilliard,
marketing manager for the Port of Long Beach, the nation's largest.
In the last few months, amid some signs of recovery in Asia, loaded
containers heading to Asia have slightly outnumbered the empties.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, imports have been unusually strong early this year as
importers ship early to beat the May 1 increase and a possible
strike by longshoremen this summer. They also fear a repeat of the
delays that occurred last year, when not enough ships and
containers were available to handle all the imports from Asia that
had suddenly become cheaper for Americans when Asian currencies
were devalued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite a few of our Christmas decorations arrived too late for
the season,'' said John Carrier, import traffic manager of World
Bazaar Inc., a housewares importer based in City of Commerce. The
per-container price he paid rose from $1,400 to as much as $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many executives expect the same thing to happen this summer.
``The big issue this year is `I don't care what it costs, just get
me on a ship,''' said Tom Craig, head of the LTD Shippers
Association, which represents 500 small importers and exporters.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of the seller's market, the shipping lines said
they would raise rates by $900 for a 40-foot container coming to
the West Coast from Asia, with an additional $300 surcharge from
June through November, the peak season. That represents an increase
of 30 percent to 100 percent over current rates, which range from
$1,100 to more than $3,000, depending on the merchandise and the
route.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Camarena, vice president for operations and global
logistics for Vans Inc., a footwear company, said that shipping
contributed about 35 cents to 50 cents to the cost of a pair of
shoes; the rate increase, he said, would add 15 cents to 20 cents
to that. An executive at another footwear company cited even lower
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while consumers might not notice, even pennies matter to
corporate profit margins. Retailers ``won't even take a 15-cent
hit,'' Camarena said, worried that his company might have to absorb
the increase on millions of pairs of shoes.
</P>
<P>
   A major question, however, is whether such a coordinated rate
increase will hold under the new Ocean Shipping Reform Act, enacted
in October by Congress. These changes, the first in 15 years, will
allow importers and exporters to sign confidential contracts with a
shipping company. Big importers _ the Wal-Marts and Nikes of the
world _ are expected to obtain hefty discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Until now container shipping lines have been ``common carriers''
like the phone company, accepting all customers at published rates.
Most rates have been set by cartels known as conferences. Importers
and exporters could negotiate their own contracts, often with the
entire conference, sometimes with an individual shipping line. The
terms of such contracts were public and other importers or
exporters had the right to demand the same rate.
</P>
<P>
   The conference system has already started to fray in
anticipation of May 1. The Asia North America Eastbound Rate
Agreement, known as Anera, which sets rates for containers heading
from Asia to the United States, will disband April 30, as will its
westbound counterpart. Somewhat similar changes are occurring on
the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Anera is being replaced by the Transpacific Stabilization
Agreement, a ``discussion group'' that is housed in the same office
in San Francisco. Such groups will not have legally binding
rate-setting authority, as the conferences do. But that has not
stopped members of the group from ``voluntarily'' agreeing to raise
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Shipping is one of the few industries _ others include Major
League Baseball and farm cooperatives _ to enjoy some immunity from
antitrust laws. First granted in 1916, immunity was apparently
rationalized as a way to prevent price wars and bankruptcies that
could lead to a shortage of shipping capacity. It applies to
regularly scheduled shipping lines, not to oil tankers and bulk
commodity carriers, which are not regulated and thus not affected
by the new law.
</P>
<P>
   The container shipping lines fought successfully to retain the
antitrust exemption in October's legislation, arguing that the
United States had to be in accord with other nations, which allow
collective rate-setting. An argument was also made that U.S.
shipping lines, which are more easily subject to prosecution by the
Justice Department than foreign companies, would be at a
disadvantage if immunity ended _ even though few U.S. lines remain.
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation was pushed most strongly by big importers and
exporters, which wanted not only lower rates but also the more
tailored service they could get through contracts with a single
shipping line. While these companies wanted to eliminate the
antitrust immunity, they compromised with the shipping lines to get
the bill passed. Peter Gatti, director of policy for the National
Industrial Transportation League, which represents major importers
and exporters, said that in an era of individual contracts,
collective rate-setting would not be as important as before anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Even without deregulation, the shipping conferences have been
the cartels that couldn't shoot straight. Companies added so many
new ships that overcapacity resulted, driving down prices. Some
major shipping companies, such as Taiwan's Evergreen line, never
joined.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been much less successful than even OPEC,'' said Torey
Presti, vice president of regulatory affairs for APL Ltd., a major
shipping line based in Oakland. Neptune Orient Lines of Singapore,
which acquired APL in 1997, lost $263 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   APL's sale left Sea-Land Service as the only U.S. shipping line
among the 10 largest global carriers serving the United States _
this despite government subsidies of about $2 million a year to
ships with U.S. flags and crews that can be turned over to the
Pentagon in times of war.
</P>
<P>
   Sea-Land's operating profits, after growing for several years,
dropped by half in 1998 and there are rumors that CSX might sell
all or part of the shipping line.
</P>
<P>
   Sea-Land president and chief executive John Clancey predicted
that deregulation would actually lead to higher profits for the
best shipping lines, which would be able to develop closer
relationships with key customers.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like Sea-Land and APL hope to offer global contracts,
rather than ocean by ocean, and to provide more sophisticated
services, such as coordinating a customer's entire supply network.
APL, for instance, is managing the shipments of parts to a General
Motors factory in Thailand, even the shipments over land.
</P>
<P>
   To speed cargo movements and cut costs, APL has also invested
heavily in cargo terminals like the one here in Los Angeles, where
200 trucks come and go each hour, picking up or dropping off
containers that are assigned spaces by a computer in a vast parking
lot.
</P>
<P>
   Changes to the business might be gradual, but jarring just the
same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maritime finds it harder to change than almost anybody because
it's steeped in tradition,'' said Jil Morley, transportation
manager for Blue Diamond Growers, a cooperative of almond growers.
But with deregulation, she said, ``I'm expecting it to get more
like the real world, like the rest of the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
