<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRADE-REPORT-ART-800&AMP;     04-20 1181
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-REPORT-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE DEFICIT JUMPS TO NEW MONTHLY HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's trade deficit jumped unexpectedly to
previously unheard-of levels in February as consumers bought
growing quantities of imports and declining demand from abroad hurt
exporters, the government reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The deficit in goods and services in February surged to a new
monthly high of $19.4 billion, the Commerce Department said, $2.6
billion more than January's deficit of $16.8 billion, which itself
had been a record. Economists had expected February's deficit to be
around $16.7 billion. The figures are adjusted to smooth out
seasonal variations in trade patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Imports in February rose by $2.1 billion, to $96 billion.
Exports declined by $500 million, to $76.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The figures reflected the persistent and in some ways increasing
gap between the economic strength of the United States and the
downturns plaguing nearly all of its trading partners, from Asia to
Europe to Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Alone among the world's major countries, the United States is a
magnet for imports of goods and services, helping to avert even
deeper global economic problems. With unemployment low and stock
prices up sharply since the beginning of the year, American
consumers have been spending freely, and they are finding bargains
in imports.
</P>
<P>
   But because demand for American-made goods has been diminished
by weakness in other countries, the growing trade deficit is
hurting many manufacturers and farmers in the United States and
slowing growth. Economists said declining exports appear to have
slowed the economy's expansion to about a 3 percent annual rate in
the first three months of the year from twice that in last year's
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in the deficit after a year and a half of economic
upheaval around the world added to an escalating debate over how
willing the United States should be to leave its markets open to
other countries that do not fully reciprocate.
</P>
<P>
   Groups like farmers, steelworkers and textile makers are already
howling about unfair competition from abroad, and making their
influence felt in Washington. The next major flash point is likely
to come in a few months, when the Clinton administration is
expected to complete a deal to bring China into the World Trade
Organization and seek approval from a deeply divided Congress.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton used the figures announced Tuesday to bolster
his call for an overhaul of the world's financial system in the
wake of the turmoil that sped from Asia to Russia and Latin America
in the last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though our economy has continued to grow, we have been
affected by the Asian financial crisis as you can see by our trade
figures, by what has happened in steel and by the loss of markets
by our farmers,'' Clinton said in a speech at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that this was ``not a moment for complacency,'' Clinton
outlined a series of principles he said the United States would
advance in coming months as the major industrial nations consider
how to overhaul the financial system and avert future international
economic upheaval. They include tightening bank lending rules and
encouraging developing nations to rely less on short-term loans.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of free trade have become increasingly worried about
what they see as growing protectionist pressures. Alan Greenspan,
the Federal Reserve chairman, denounced protectionism in a speech
last Friday and made a case that while dropping trade barriers can
be painful, it ultimately adds to the nation's prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   But organized labor and companies in the industries being hit
hardest continue to argue that fair trade rather than free trade
should be the nation's goal. John Sweeney, the president of the
AFL-CIO, called Tuesday's trade figures ``cause for real alarm,''
and said the worst may not yet be past for American workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last year we lost over 350,000 manufacturing jobs,''
Sweeney said in a speech in Chicago. ``And no one knows how long we
can survive as an island of prosperity in a sea of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   With Japan still mired in recession, growth in Western Europe
slowing and Latin America struggling, some economists and business
groups said they expected demand for exports to be tepid for the
rest of the year. Rising oil prices could also make the deficit
look bigger in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The trade deficit, said Gordon Richards, an economist at the
National Association of Manufacturers, ``won't improve
substantially until the world economy recovers, and that is still
some time away.''
</P>
<P>
   Other economists, however, said there were signs that the
decline in export demand had bottomed out and that manufacturing
was ready to rebound. Among the signs they cited was a rise in
export orders tallied by the National Association of Purchasing
Management in February and March, suggesting that shipments to
foreign customers could pick up in coming months.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   February marked the fourth consecutive month of declining
exports, and the figures showed weakening demand in February from
most of the country's major trading partners. The deficit of trade
in goods with Mexico increased to $1.8 billion from $1.4 billion,
using figures that are not seasonally adjusted. The goods deficit
with Japan increased to $5.3 billion for the month from $4.7
billion in January. Demand from Western Europe dropped sharply,
sending the monthly deficit in trade of goods to $2.2 billion from
$1.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the decline in exports was in agricultural products,
including soybeans, and in commercial aircraft, a notoriously
volatile component of the figures that is almost totally dependent
on Boeing Co.'s delivery schedule for sales to foreign airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in imports was concentrated in consumer goods,
including clothing, toys and sporting goods, with a surge as well
in the number of imported cars.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few relative bright spots was a slight decline in the
deficit with China. The goods deficit with China declined to $4.6
billion in February from $4.9 billion in January. But over the last
few years, the deficit with China has grown to the point that it
rivals the deficit with Japan as the biggest two-way trade gap.
</P>
<P>
   But with the administration about to make a push to seal a trade
deal with China, Commerce Secretary William Daley said Beijing
still had to prove that it was willing to play by international
rules and drop the barriers that have kept companies from the
United States and other countries out of its markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If China wants to be a true global trading partner and a
member of the World Trade Organization,'' Daley told reporters
Tuesday, ``the Chinese government must promptly agree to open her
markets to foreign goods and services.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
