<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWSROOM-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A `NEWSROOM' WHERE THE NEWS IS IRRELEVANT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's always a breaking story at the nightly ``Toronto News.''
For example, George Findlay, the show's producer, throws a racist
tantrum when he doesn't get his bran muffin. Or when his BMW needs
a $3,200 muffler system. Or when he has once again hit on a woman
half his age (late 40s) and she has complained to management.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally events from the outside intrude on George's total
self-absorption, but on ``The Newsroom,'' Ken Finkleman's dry,
riotous take on a Canadian television news organization, any war,
plane crash or nuclear accident had better have the right spin
potential if it hopes to compete for attention with who gets the
prime indoor parking spot or which assistant to hire, the black
lesbian or the blond ski bunny.
</P>
<P>
   A huge hit on Canadian television, ``The Newsroom'' made its way
south to PBS in 1997 (last New Year's Eve, WNET in New York reran
all 13 episodes back to back) and has recently been released in a
four-tape set by Acorn Media. WNET plans to show the series again
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The writing, acting and direction appealed in every way,''
said Anne Gorfinkel, the station's deputy director for programming.
</P>
<P>
   Finkleman also conceived and wrote the show and stars as George.
A former Hollywood screenwriter (he wrote and directed ``Airplane
2''), he was driven back home in the early 90s by what he describes
as the studios' idiotic treatment of his material. Resettled in
Toronto, he sold the Canadian Broadcasting Company on a satire
about television news.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's idea about news being corrupt has just gotten into
the conventional wisdom,'' he said. ``There's always this need to
impose a narrative. That's what I find very destructive.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Newsroom'' George is maniacally driven to mount
dramatizations that play to ratings. ``No need to paint ourselves
into a factual corner here,'' he says about coverage of a killer
virus. Other priorities are staying out of the way of management
and tending to personal matters, often having to do with George's
efforts to persuade women, usually virtual strangers, to go away
with him for the weekend (separate rooms, he assures them).
</P>
<P>
   As paranoid as he is sex-obsessed, George continually fears for
his position. At one point he leaves a telephone message in which
he threatens to quit. His assistants say he should have dared
management to dismiss him, which would require showing cause.
Panic-stricken, George orders a long-suffering intern to break into
the voice-mail system and erase the message.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a situation at the Pickering power plant threatens
another Chernobyl 20 minutes from downtown Toronto. In the
interests of narrative, George decides the event needs a name _
``Pickering, Mon Amour,'' someone suggests _ and, thinking the
situation could use a more sensational aura, plans to model the
story after the coverage of the O.J. Simpson trial.
</P>
<P>
   George says he wants a ``nuclear holocaust twist to the O.J.
thing _ to crank up the old addiction.'' Later he tosses in
elements of ``Apocalypse Now'' and ``Jaws.'' No, wait, ``The China
Syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone rounds up a nuclear expert to tell viewers what is
actually going on at Pickering. George, who has moved on to matters
of costume and personal appearance, says that's all right, but adds
that if the man wants to get on the air, he'd better lose the
scraggly hairdo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
