<HEADER>
A6441 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAKESPEARE-BOOK-ART-     04-20 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKESPEARE-BOOK-ART-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BARD, BY THE BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25)  
 (af)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now is the spring of content for friends of the Bard.
With ``Shakespeare in Love'' still drawing audiences, they can look
forward to ``The Taming of the Shrew'' this summer at the Delacorte
Theater in Central Park in New York. Before that, comes a movie of
``A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' with Kevin Kline as Bottom, and,
later this year, the screen will bring us Julie Taymor's version of
the rarely performed ``Titus Andronicus,'' with Anthony Hopkins as
that much-suffering monster.
</P>
<P>
   But it is a fair guess that at least one eminent Bardolator,
Harold Bloom, is reining in his expectations for these latest
attempts at casting a fresh light on the canon. His book
``Shakespeare: The Invention of the Human'' leaves no doubt of his
irritation with most of the interpretations he has encountered in a
lifetime of worshiping the plays; for him, the more daring the
attempt, the more excruciating the experience.
</P>
<P>
   Here and there in his 741 pages, Bloom dredges up a kind word
about a legendary turn by an actor whom he has never seen _ Kean or
Irving as Shylock _ or a production that he saw long ago: most
memorably for him, the Henry plays with Ralph Richardson as
Falstaff and, incidentally, Laurence Olivier alternating between
Hotspur and Shallow.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom reports that Richardson's performance, seen at the age of
16, gave him his ``first understanding of Shakespeare.''
</P>
<P>
   He has applause, too, for Peggy Ashcroft and John Gielgud (also
a half-century ago) in ``Much Ado About Nothing'' and for Katharine
Hepburn's 1950 ``triumph'' in ``As You Like It.'' But such praise
is rare in this otherwise praiseful work. Bloom does not make life
easy for directors and actors who perforce try to come up with
novel interpretations of a much-performed repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, in the Bloomsian view, directors and actors are doing
very badly, out of sheer incompetence or under the influence of the
hour's ideologues, be they feminists or Marxists or
multiculturalists. He allows that a few minor plays, like ``Titus
Andronicus,'' are beyond redemption and that a few major
characters, like Shylock, can hardly be represented at all in a
post-Holocaust world. But his sympathies remain firmly with the
plays, not the players.
</P>
<P>
   He charges, to take his favorite example, that ``Hamlet'' has
suffered from four centuries of misreading, culminating not long
ago in the Broadway ``travesty'' starring Ralph Fiennes mumbling
and racing through the ``To be or not to be'' soliloquy. One fears
to imagine what Bloom will make of the promised return of the play
set in the corporate 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Naming names of his least admired directors, our textualist
comes down hard on Peter Brook and Jan Kott for their ``brutal''
mishandlings of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.'' Joining their
company are those who have made ``The Tempest'' Shakespeare's
``worst interpreted and performed'' comedy.
</P>
<P>
   George C. Wolfe is cited, with exasperation, for scoring a
success in Central Park some seasons ago by turning the half-human
Caliban into a Third World freedom fighter with an attitude.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as Bloom does not fail to note, the Shakespearean canon
was made to be acted well before scholars got their hands on it.
Along with playing the Ghost in ``Hamlet,'' Shakespeare left us,
through the exceedingly intelligent Dane, the pithiest and most
enduring stage direction in history: ``Suit the action to the word,
the word to the action.''
</P>
<P>
   Granted, that tag does not settle much, but it does suggest the
differing starting places for Bloom and the interpreters he cannot
abide, like ``the gender and power covens'' who have tampered with
his cherished heroine, Rosalind, and succeeded in making ``nearly
every production of `As You Like It''' _ Ms. Hepburn excepted _ a
libel on ``the most remarkable and persuasive representation of a
woman in all Western literature.''
</P>
<P>
   That sort of failure, he maintains, is symptomatic of ``the
authentic decline of our cognitive and literate culture,'' under
the assault by movies, television and computers. If, as he laments,
as great a work as ``King Lear'' defies ``a Shakespearean staging
of Shakespeare,'' then the society is plainly losing its literary
tradition and probably its bearings.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the situation: Where the Bardolator dedicates himself
to defending the text against the barbarians, the directors have
the challenge of finding audience-engaging ways that reflect the
times and perhaps the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Bloom understands this, yet takes refuge in the faith that
Shakespeare's ``more select'' admirers have always been his readers
rather than his ticket buyers, and proposes, perhaps seriously,
that the works would be better served by public readings than by
ill-directed and inadequately performed productions.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you see the situation as the mandarin versus the
wrecking crew or a puritan versus the progressives, the definitions
don't get us very far. For the directorial disposition, the
familiar words on the page, however sublime, must seem a sort of
imprisonment of one's creative abilities or pretensions.
</P>
<P>
   Where the Bloomsian is committed to defending the text or his
version of it, after so many Hamlets and so many Lears the theater
people are likely to be desperate for an original if at times
dizzying spin.
</P>
<P>
   The clash is as inevitable and irreconcilable as that between
the anointed Richard II and the usurping Bolingbroke. Who is to
rule the Shakespearean kingdom? Season after season, it is not only
careers that are in opposition but entire world views.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2042EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6445 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-SUIT-BOS &LR;      04-20 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWIS' WIDOW SEEKS TO BAR EVIDENCE OF DRUG USE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Lawyers for Donna Harris-Lewis are expected to ask a
judge Wednesday to bar evidence of illegal drug use by her late
husband, Reggie Lewis, from an upcoming malpractice trial spurred
by his death, arguing that the allegations have been raised ``for
the sole purpose of trashing the good name, reputation and legacy''
of the former Boston Celtics star.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also argue that damaging testimony about Lewis'
alleged cocaine use ``can have no purpose other than to attempt to
intimidate (Harris-Lewis) into dropping this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis has sued Dr. Gilbert H. Mudge Jr. and three other
doctors, Peter L. Friedman, Mark A. Creager and John D. Rutherford,
for failing to diagnose her husband's life-threatening heart
condition. Lewis died in 1993 shortly after collapsing on a
basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   But attorneys for Mudge, who contends that Lewis confessed to
him two weeks before his death that he had used cocaine, argue that
Lewis impeded Mudge from making an accurate diagnosis by previously
denying his drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Among the evidence Harris-Lewis's attorneys want barred from
trial is testimony by 13 witnesses, including sportscaster Bob
Lobel of WBZ-TV in Boston. Mudge's attorneys contend the witnesses
have some knowledge of Lewis's alleged cocaine use.
</P>
<P>
   Contacted by the Globe Tuesday, Lobel said he was not aware he
had been named as a witness and declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to papers filed by Harris-Lewis's attorneys, Robert G.
Harley and Bridget Asaro of New York, several of the witnesses are
expected to testify that they saw other individuals take illicit
drugs in Lewis's presence. Such testimony ``is a back door attack
on his character, which is not an issue in this case,'' the
attorneys wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense counsel would like to raise this (drug) issue before
the jury as often as possible,'' they continued. ``However, Reggie
Lewis isn't on trial here, and his reputation should not be subject
to repetitive, unsubstantiated allegations of illicit drug use.''
</P>
<P>
   Mudge's attorney, William J. Dailey Jr., refused to comment
Tuesday. But in court papers, Dailey accuses Harris-Lewis' lawyers
of ``trying to inflame the court,'' calling Lewis's alleged drug
use ``well-founded and legally relevant'' to the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plaintiff has employed this tactic repeatedly to attack
the defendants and their counsel with the obvious aim of diverting
the court's attention from the real issue concerning Mr. Lewis's
history of cocaine use: whether or not Mr. Lewis's failure to
earlier disclose his use of cocaine contributed to the confounding
nature of Mr. Lewis's complex cardiac diagnosis. This issue, like
many other factual disputes in this case, ultimately is a medical
issue,'' the motion in opposition states.
</P>
<P>
   Local defense attorney Tim O'Neill, who specializes in medical
malpractice cases, said Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith is likely to
permit evidence of alleged drug use to be admitted at trial since
it relevant to the case's central issue: whether negligence by
Mudge led to Lewis's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``My instinct tells me that if the defense can connect the heart
condition to the use of drugs with reasonable scientific
evidence,'' evidence of alleged drug use is likely to be admitted,
O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a balancing act the judge has to do,'' he added. The
judge must weigh whether the prejudicial value of the evidence
outweighs its value to Mudge's defense, O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The balancing would be tipped pretty heavily to the defense in
this case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if evidence of alleged drug use were to be barred, the
result wouldn't necessarily be favorable to Harris-Lewis, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what other kinds of evidence there are, but there
may be other issues that makes Mudge's approach (to Lewis's
diagnosis) quite reasonable,'' he said. ``There may be many, many
other reasons that justified Mudge thinking the way he did.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill also said that in medical malpractice cases, juries are
told not simply to determine if a doctor made a mistake, but if the
doctor's diagnosis was reasonable given his knowledge of a
patient's condition.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, he said, a doctor doesn't ``have to be right, he
just has to be reasonably within the range of judgment that doctors
make in these cases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
