<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6447 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STROKES-DRUG-TEX     04-20 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STROKES-DRUG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO MANY STROKE PATIENTS MISSING OUT ON POWERFUL DRUG, DOCTORS SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLOTTE HUFF 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Before the night was over, it seemed that
everyone at All Saints Episcopal Hospital knew about the stroke
patient who watched ``Judge Judy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lila Shaw's fondness for the feisty judge of daytime television,
backed up by a quick call to 911, helped give doctors the
confidence to use a powerful but time-sensitive, clot-busting drug
called t-PA. By midnight, Shaw was well on her way to recovery.
</P>
<P>
   But three years after the drug's approval, doctors say, too many
patients are missing out on its potential. Studies show that only 3
percent to 5 percent of those eligible nationwide get the
intravenous medication, according to American Heart Association
officials.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, lying on her bed one afternoon last month, had reached for
the remote control to tape the rest of the ``Judge Judy'' program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could move my arm, but my hand couldn't pick it up,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   When she called out to her son-in-law, her mouth wouldn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got up,'' the 73-year-old Fort Worth woman said, ``and
realized that my leg was going out, too. I was kind of dragging it
along. I managed to leap from one piece of furniture to another
until I got to the hallway.''
</P>
<P>
   To be effective, t-PA must be started within three hours of a
stroke's onset. The drug is designed to attack clots in the brain's
vessels and dissolve them before too much of the surrounding brain
tissue is damaged.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes after Shaw's son-in-law called 911, paramedics were
standing in her bedroom, debating exactly when ``Judge Judy''
aired. The start time of the three-hour clock, doctors say, must
date back to when the patient last felt normal.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, trying to interject, held up four fingers, managing to get
out the word ``thirty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind was clear _ it didn't knock out my mind or anything,''
Shaw said. ``But I realized, though, that my arm and leg were
getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Too often, doctors say, the race against time breaks down.
</P>
<P>
   Patients hesitate to go to the emergency room, unable or
unwilling to acknowledge the early signs of a stroke. A hospital
may not have the necessary specialists available to quickly examine
patients and do the necessary tests.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, formally known as tissue plasminogen activator, does
come with a worrisome catch. Even if t-PA is used by the third
hour, there is still a small risk that the powerful drug may
trigger bleeding into the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a very minor bleed or it could be a
life-threatening bleed,'' said Fort Worth neurologist Krishnababu
Chunduri, who helped treat Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, about 500,000 Americans have a stroke, according to
the National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke. A
blood clot to the brain causes about 80 percent of the brain
attacks _ a term more frequently used now to indicate the urgency
of the stroke crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Chunduri, chairman of Plaza Medical Center's stroke team,
estimates that about half of his stroke patients would have been
eligible for t-PA if they had arrived at the hospital soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   But patients may not realize that they are having a stroke. An
October 1997 study published in the journal ``Stroke'' found that,
even among recent stroke patients, almost four in 10 lacked basic
knowledge of the symptoms and risk factors.
</P>
<P>
   And doctors can get nervous about administering the powerful
drug, said Dr. Errol Bryce, who helped treat Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lack of experience is one,'' he said. ``Fear of a worse
outcome is another one. You can actually kill the patient giving
them t-PA.''
</P>
<P>
   Before receiving t-PA shortly after 6 p.m., Shaw underwent an
examination, including a brain scan to verify that a lodged clot,
rather than bleeding, caused her stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw, who is quick to acknowledge that her own personality
matches the feisty judge's, said she was willing to take a risk if
it meant living with less disability.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a very independent person,'' she said. ``It would have
been hell on earth for me to be paralyzed.''
</P>
<P>
   The clot-busting properties of t-PA have been demonstrated for
years with heart attack patients.
</P>
<P>
   The drug's 1996 FDA approval for emergency stroke treatment came
after a study published the year before in the New England Journal
of Medicine. At least one-third of the patients who got the drug
experienced a partial or complete recovery.
</P>
<P>
   But the study showed that in about 6 percent of patients, the
medication could trigger bleeding into the brain.
</P>
<P>
   After the medication started flowing into her arm, Shaw noticed
that her speech and mobility on her right side were worsening.
</P>
<P>
   She was talking more and more out of the left side of her mouth,
daughter Linda Simmons said.
</P>
<P>
   ``She started telling my sister and I that she loved us,''
Simmons said. ``She said that she wanted to tell us while she still
could.''
</P>
<P>
   As she lay with her right side completely immobilized, Shaw
wondered whether she would ever be able to write again.
</P>
<P>
   Then, she said, ``I felt an involuntary jerk or tic in my right
arm and I tried to move my fingers and I was moving them.''
</P>
<P>
   By shortly after midnight, Shaw was enjoying a sandwich and her
new-found celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``She became famous throughout the hospital,'' Simmons laughed,
``as the woman who watches ``Judge Judy'' and survived a stroke.''
</P>
<P>
   Several days later, as Shaw was being discharged, Chunduri told
her about his mother's 1995 stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his quick response, rushing his mother to a hospital in
the middle of the night, little could be done, he said, even as her
left side became gradually paralyzed. Today, Chunduri said, his
mother depends on a walker for limited mobility.
</P>
<P>
   ``With tears in his eyes,'' Shaw recalled, ``he said, `This
would have saved her.'''
</P>
<P>
   The next time Shaw saw Bryce, she greeted him with a hug and a
kiss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is really a disservice to patients not to consider this,''
Bryce said.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks later, Shaw's only complaint is some dizziness
related to her medications. Her family, she said, tends to fuss
when she ventures outside into the sunshine with her dogs to feed
the birds.
</P>
<P>
   But she doesn't bid them any mind.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, she hates most television.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my brain semi-intact and the wisteria and the trees
blooming, I just have to go out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Stroke Symptoms
</P>
<P>
   When in doubt, go straight to the emergency room if you think
you're having a stroke. Some warning signs:
</P>
<P>
   _Numbness, weakness, or paralysis of the face, arm or leg,
especially on one side of the body.
</P>
<P>
   _Loss of balance or coordination.
</P>
<P>
   _Sudden, blurred or decreased vision in one or both eyes.
</P>
<P>
   _Difficulty speaking or understanding language.
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE: National Stroke Association
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Charlotte Huff writes on health issues for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7689, or e-mail:
huff(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
