<HEADLINE>
IN LIGHT OF TURKEY'S VOTE, PARTY CHIEFS ARE PRESSED TO QUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Several of Turkey's veteran political leaders
are under growing pressure to resign after poor showings in
Sunday's national election.
</P>
<P>
   The resignations, if they come about, could reshape Turkish
politics, especially if they are accompanied by measures increasing
democracy within political parties.
</P>
<P>
   One of the country's largest newspapers, Sabah, onm Tuesday
carried front-page photos of the center-right party leaders Tansu
Ciller and Mesut Yilmaz, both former prime ministers, and the
center-left leader Deniz Baykal, under a banner headline reading:
``Enough!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      04-20 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN LIGHT OF TURKEY'S VOTE, PARTY CHIEFS ARE PRESSED TO QUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Several of Turkey's veteran political leaders
are under growing pressure to resign after poor showings in
Sunday's national election.
</P>
<P>
   The resignations, if they come about, could reshape Turkish
politics, especially if they are accompanied by measures increasing
democracy within political parties.
</P>
<P>
   One of the country's largest newspapers, Sabah, onm Tuesday
carried front-page photos of the center-right party leaders Tansu
Ciller and Mesut Yilmaz, both former prime ministers, and the
center-left leader Deniz Baykal, under a banner headline reading:
``Enough! The Nation Doesn't Want to See Any More of You!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop blocking Turkey's future,'' the newspaper said in a
front-page appeal to the three leaders. ``The voters have shown
that they do not want you or trust you. Recognize this and accept
the course of democracy. Please, for the love of God, leave
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Another newspaper, Radikal, published a front page dominated by
photos of Ms. Ciller, Yilmaz and the leader of the
religious-oriented Virtue party, Recai Kutan. Above the photos a
headline demanded, ``What Are You Waiting For?''
</P>
<P>
   The Motherland and True Path parties led by Yilmaz and Ms.
Ciller won a total of 52 percent of the votes in the 1991 election.
They dropped to 40 percent in 1995 and barely 25 percent on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For Baykal, the humiliation may have been even greater. His
People's Republican Party was established 75 years ago by the
revered founder of the Turkish Republic, Mustafa Kemal Ataturk.
Sunday it failed to take even the 10 percent of votes necessary to
qualify for representation in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   None of these leaders have made a public statement since Sunday,
but according to press reports all are considering quitting.
</P>
<P>
   The Virtue party finished in third place with 15 percent of the
vote, a sharp drop from the 21 percent and first-place finish
enjoyed by its predecessor, Welfare, in 1995. Its chairman, Kutan,
had predicted that his party would finish first, and pledged to
step down if it did not. Now, he appears to be reconsidering.
</P>
<P>
   Young figures in the Virtue party are eager to depose Kutan and
his mostly elderly leadership team. They want to pull the party
away from its religious orientation and turn it into a
broader-based conservative force.
</P>
<P>
   These insurgents have remained largely silent until now, but
after their party's poor result Sunday they may decide to mount a
challenge. Virtue is to have a party congress later this year, and
if Kutan does not resign, the insurgents may seek to depose him
there.
</P>
<P>
   Party rebels, however, have a difficult challenge in Turkey.
Laws governing political parties are crafted to protect incumbent
party leaders. As a result, leaders often hold onto their posts for
years or even decades.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish voters in their 30s often complain that the country is
governed by a rotating clique of party leaders who were already in
power when they were children. Some dare to hope, however, that
Sunday's results may force at least a few of them from power.
</P>
<P>
   ``These leaders have been holding back the force of change here
for a long time, because they knew that if change came, they
wouldn't be able to manage it and would probably be swept away,''
said Kemal Koprulu, who heads a civic group that is campaigning for
political reform. ``Now, suddenly, a lot of people are saying that
the election laws and political party laws have to change. Things
are a lot different today than they were a couple of weeks ago, and
this is good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The election results may not look too positive at first, but
they show that a lot of votes in Turkey are roaming from one party
to another,'' Koprulu said. ``You can always get them to roam back
to the proper channel, but you have to create that channel. I think
we now have an excellent chance. In Turkey, things have to reach
the very bottom before they change, and we're pretty close to
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
