<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO DETAILS `KILLING FIELDS OF KOSOVO' ATROCITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four weeks into allied air strikes against
Yugoslavia, NATO officials Tuesday made the starkest accusations
yet of Serb troops conducting mass executions, gang rapes and
numerous other atrocities against ethnic Albanians in ``the killing
fields of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO report came as Serb forces expanded their aggression in
the Balkans, spreading their campaign of ``ethnic cleansing'' into
the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro, exchanging gunfire with the
Albanian Army along the Kosovo border, and sending 300 troops into
a demilitarized zone in Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   As some senators raised the possibility of deploying US ground
forces to Kosovo, NATO authorities said the Serbian ``crimes
against humanity'' include forcing as many as 700 teenage boys to
act as human shields or ``blood banks for Serb casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea, citing reports ``too numerous'' to
ignore of war crimes in Kosovo, said, ``All this means that the
killing fields of Kosovo are going to be on our minds for many
years to come, as we try to piece the full story together and
ensure that those responsible are brought to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The NATO allegations of atrocities are based largely on military
intelligence reports and accounts from ethnic Albanian refugees.
International authorities are expected to fully investigate the
allegations when the hostilities end.
</P>
<P>
   As Serb forces appeared intent on widening the conflict beyond
Kosovo, Albanian President Rexhap Meidani said in an interview with
the Globe that officials in Albania are trying to ``keep our cool''
so as not to escalate the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   These other developments unfolded as the NATO attack against
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's forces entered a fifth
week:
</P>
<P>
   _ President Clinton, meeting with former German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl, reiterated his commitment ``to defeat the cynical
vision embodied by Mr. Milosevic in which the most primitive
hatreds and brutal oppression are more important than mutual
respect and common progress.''
</P>
<P>
   _ With NATO expected to weigh the possible use of ground troops
during its 50th anniversary summit starting Friday in Washington,
Defense Secretary William S. Cohen said the Pentagon could ``rather
quickly'' send American ground forces to Kosovo if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   _ Montenegrin President Milo Djukanovic was quoted on Wednesday
as saying he had rejected a Yugoslav army order to place his
republic's police force under military command. ``It is out of the
question that the Ministry of the Interior could be subordinated to
the Yugoslav army,'' Djukanovic told the Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
   _ Texaco Inc. said it will halt shipments of gasoline to
Yugoslavia after admitting it made such a shipment on April 10,
nearly three weeks after the air war began. A company spokesman
said Texaco had received assurances that the gasoline would be used
only within Montenegro, which has said it is neutral in the current
conflict. However, the Texaco spokesman said the company will not
be making any further shipments there under an existing contract.
</P>
<P>
   _ British Prime Minister Tony Blair said NATO has destroyed half
of Yugoslavia's best fighter jets, MiG-29s; 25 percent of its
MiG-21s; and 30 percent of its Super Galebs, which have been used
to attack ethnic Albanian civilians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But Blair said NATO is unable to immediately help tens of
thousands of homeless ethnic Albanians who are hiding in the
mountains and forests of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO spokesman, Shea, said Serb forces are shelling many of
the homeless refugees who are hiding in Kosovo, forcing them into
the open, then marching them toward the border. ``What we are
seeing as we study these movements of people is a kind of safari
operation ongoing by the Serb security forces against the Kosovar
Albanians,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Relief agencies said they have lost track of more than 100,000
Kosovars who were seen heading for the Albanian border on Saturday.
Only about 100 of the refugees reached the border.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Pentagon said muddy conditions in Albania have
delayed the arrival of 24 Apache helicopters that are expected to
significantly bolster the NATO attack on Serb ground forces in
Kosovo. Barring additional rain, the gunships should arrive by the
end of the week, according to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, NATO carried out daylight bombing raids on strategic
Serb military positions throughout Kosovo and continued striking
sites in Serbia Tuesday night with cruise missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Russian diplomats met with leaders of several Islamic
nations, seeking a plan to end the hostilities in the Balkans. But
they reported no breakthrough in Russia's continuing effort to
mediate a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, who met with Patriarch Alexiy II, the head of the
Russian Orthodox Church, said on Yugoslav national television that
Russia will ``contribute to establishing peace as soon as possible
and to halting this aggression that is not grounded in a single
moral, legal or any other principle.''
</P>
<P>
   An Albanian hospital near the border with Kosovo reported that
two members of the Kosovo Liberation Army were killed and 13 others
were wounded after clashing with Serb forces in the region. The
KLA's Kosova Press agency reported that three of the army's ``high
officers'' were killed in the fighting that left ``many dead and
injured, especially on the side of our enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   As the injured KLA members were treated, Meidani, the Albanian
president, rejected the rebel group's plea for ammunition and arms
from the Albanian military. ``It is not possible,'' Meidani said.
``The problem is how to help the civilians inside Kososo, in the
mountains and in the forests. They have other channels to get
arms,'' he said of the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   Meidani said supplying the KLA not only would be strategically
difficult because of Serb land mines and troops along the border,
but it could be politically dangerous. He said the arms transfer
would ``be used like propaganda'' by Milosevic, who has tried to
demonize Albania as a NATO pawn.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels, Shea detailed allegations of
Serb atrocities in Kosovo. In recent days, he said, NATO
conservatively estimates that 3,500 ethnic Albanians have been
slain in mass executions throughout the province. About 100 adult
males ``were summarily shot dead at point-blank range'' in one
village, Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   Without providing the number of victims, Shea alleged that
ethnic Albanian women have suffered gang rapes in their homes and
on the roadsides. He said the women have been separated from their
families and sent to Serb army camps, where they have been raped,
and were rounded up and taken to a hotel, ``where the local
commander apparently has organized a roster of his soldiers to
allow them all an evening at the hotel.'' He also said they have
been raped at factories, ``where some hundred women remain.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO also reported that Serb troops have forced ethnic Albanian
men to dig defensive positions for Milosevic's army in Kosovo.
Other men were forced to stand in front of tanks in the rain for
two days with their hands tied behind their heads, Shea said. He
said a few of the men escaped after paying the soldiers 10,000
deutschemarks, the equivalent of $5,500.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, NATO denounced the Serb practice of herding tens of
thousands of homeless Kosovars toward the Albanian border, then
stalling them until so many have gathered that they create chaos
when they eventually reach refugee camps on the other side. ``It's
extremely depressing that human beings are used as pawns on this
type of macabre and rather Machiavellian chess board,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kornblut reported from Tirana, Albania. Wire service material was
used to preapre this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
