<SLUG> BC-INFLATION-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: NO NEED FOR MAJOR CONCERN ON INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rate of inflation, as measured by the Consumer Price Index,
is likely to jump this year, from the exceedingly comfortable 1.6
percent of last year to more than 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That would not constitute a surge. But the rate of increase has
shrunk for three straight years. And in annual terms, the inflation
rate has risen only twice in the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   If oil prices continue to gather steam, though, the monthly data
could even prompt headlines about inflation rising at an annual
rate approaching 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The possibility that such numbers might upset the stock and bond
markets on the days they are reported led Abby Joseph Cohen,
co-chairwoman of the investment policy committee at Goldman Sachs &AMP;
Co., to warn her clients recently that investors in the coming
months should be wary of the ``noise'' in the CPI and the related
Producer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is no reason to worry too much about these numbers.
The main culprit is higher oil prices, and the inflation
projections are based on the assumption that these prices will
stick, not a sure thing. Even if they do, neither the Federal
Reserve nor the bond market will get too upset if that's the only
problem, as it is not considered big enough to alter the long-term
outlook for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan warned Congress in February
that several one-time factors that depressed inflation in 1998 _
including low oil prices _ would not be present this year.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that ``recent experience does seem to suggest that
the economy has become less inflation-prone than in the past, so
that the chances of an inflationary breakout arguably are, at least
for now, less than they would have been under similar conditions in
earlier cycles.''
</P>
<P>
   The March consumer price data seemed to prove him right.
Although the energy index jumped 1.6 percent _ its first increase
since October _ the overall index rose just 02. percent, resulting
in a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 1.5 percent for the first
three months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Another positive sign: other commodity prices remain generally
low. Though the Bridge/Commodity Research Bureau index of 17
commodities has jumped 4 percent from the 24-year low it set at the
end of February, the index is virtually unchanged for the year _
even with oil included.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices, which have added to their gains in the last week,
are up 48 percent this year, and scrap metal prices have risen 3
percent. But the prices of raw industrial materials are down 2.6
percent and food prices are off 4.7percent.
</P>
<P>
   Prices paid for imports have also slumped, in part because of
the growing strength of the dollar this year, a rally many
forecasters did not expect. In March, prices of imports other than
fuel fell four-tenths of 1 percent, the biggest decline in seven
months.
</P>
<P>
   Surprising gains in worker productivity, especially this late in
an economic cycle, are also restraining inflation by partly
offsetting the increase in wages. And the pace of wage increases
themselves, despite the lowest unemployment rate in 29 years, is
slowing.
</P>
<P>
   All these positive forces have led many forecasters to dismiss
concerns about a change in the inflationary climate, even if rising
oil prices push the overall number on the CPI higher. In fact, a
move toward 2 percent would only bring the index in line with the
``core CPI,'' the index without the volatile food and energy
components. Last year, this core index rose 2.3 percent from 1997.
So the only element being lost is the extra bit of help that the
CPI got last year from plunging oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   The bond market seems to share that view. Investors did push
interest rates sharply higher in January when it became clear that
1999 economic growth would be much stronger than had been expected.
But by the time oil prices began to take off in late February, the
yield on the 30-year bond had already surged to 5.70 percent. And
now with the price of a barrel of oil just shy of $18, the yield on
the 30-year bond has retreated to 5.50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In their February meeting, Fed policy-makers said that ``a
somewhat less favorable inflation performance was viewed as likely
over the year ahead,'' according to minutes of the meeting. But
they concluded that this would not result in ``any substantial
deterioration in the inflation climate.''
</P>
<P>
   What could alter the climate? Oil prices could keep rising. But
more threatening would be a revival in other commodity prices. That
would signal a significant rebound in world economic growth, which
in turn would increase wage and inflationary pressures here.
</P>
<P>
   But it's too early to worry.
</P>
</TEXT>
