<SLUG> BC-JASPER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawyers in Texas dragging death want change of venue
 &HT;    By Zach Maxwell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Capital murder suspect Lawrence Russell Brewer's
defense attorney claims the county's ``vested interest'' in the
outcome of the trial warrants moving Brewer's day in court out of
Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, a 32-year-old Sulphur Springs, Texas native, will go on
trial May 17 for the dragging murder of James Byrd Jr. on June 7,
1998. John William King in February was convicted and sentenced to
death, while third suspect Shawn Berry of Jasper awaits trial.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Doug Barlow on Tuesday presented reams of
newspaper articles and 11 hours of news reports as evidence of the
media saturation the killing and trial have received. He also
expressed concerns over the jury pool of 25,000 Jasper County
residents available for the trial, but his main point of contention
was the possible motive of local jurors to repair the county's
``tarnished'' image with guilty verdicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that Jasper County is the only county in the state
with a vested interest in the outcome of these trials,'' he said.
``The people believe their reputation and image to the entire world
rest on these cases. The headlines have said the (King) verdict
pleases the community.''
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Monte Lawlis is expected to rule on the
change of venue motion on Thursday. Barlow has suggested Beaumont
as a possible location, but said he has considered Lufkin,
Nacogdoches and other East Texas sites if the venue should be
changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Publicity is not the thing we are trying to avoid,'' he said,
pointing to ``compelling'' evidence that local residents would be
affected by increased taxes due to the trials and other issues.
``If this does not set the standard (for a change of venue), there
is no standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Barlow presented one witness, a Beaumont advertising executive,
while District Attorney Guy James Gray called seven people to the
stand to refute the motion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he proved facts to have it changed,'' Gray said.
``We tried to factually prove we can get a fair jury here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray called to the stand Jasper County Judge Joe Folk, Sheriff
Billy Rowles, two county commissioners and other county officials
in an effort to establish the county's ability to assemble an
impartial jury. Rowles said the venue should be changed only if
``our jury panel dwindles to nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray said Lawlis expected to send out 500 summonses, with as
many as 200 expected to respond to the jury call.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, wearing a white button-up shirt over the electronic stun
belt around his waist, shared a lengthy hug in the courtroom with
his brother John Brewer, girlfriend Tammy Perritt and friend Kara
Pruitt. He held a handwritten sign upon entering the Jasper County
Courthouse on Tuesday morning, wishing ``all mothers a happy
Mother's Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Zach Maxwell writes for The Lufkin Daily News, Lufkin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
