<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS TALKING TO ALLEN'S AGENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Terry Allen may not be what he once was, but
he might be good enough to be the Patriots' feature back for a year
or two until second-round pick Kevin Faulk can take the job.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, 31, was released by the Washington Redskins Monday, and
the Patriots have already been in contact with his agent.
</P>
<P>
   They don't have much money to spend after signing Larry Whigham
(four years, $4 million, $650,000 signing bonus), Lamont Warren
(five years, $5 million, $500,000 signing bonus), and John Friesz
(two years, $1.5 million, which hasn't been filed with the league
officially), but if they can get Allen cheap, they likely will take
the plunge.
</P>
<P>
   In his heyday, Allen was rushing for 1,200-1,300 yards a season
in the mid '90s. He has had several knee surgeries but may be able
to give New England 700-1,000 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots did sign 10 rookie free agents Tuesday, including
four defensive linemen, addressing a need that they didn't on draft
day. Backup help is needed after the departure of Ferric Collons
and Mark Wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   Those signed were Florida defensive end Willie Cohens, Illinois
defensive tackle Garrett Johnson, Tulsa defensive end Tim Martin,
Central Michigan defensive tackle Jonathan McCall, Auburn
cornerback Jayson Bray, Boston College guard Daniel Collins,
Florida receiver Nafis Karim, Auburn offensive tackle Kendell Mack,
North Carolina State tight end Devon Smith, and Ohio State tight
end John Lumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   Cohens, 6 feet 3 inches, 265 pounds, had knee surgery in '98 but
still started 10 games. He's considered a good pass rusher, with 5
1/2 sacks in '97 and 2 1/2 last year. Johnson, 6-3, 300 pounds,
sacked the quarterback 5 1/2 times last year and is considered
someone who plays more on adrenaline than talent. McCall, 6-2, 270,
seems to be a classic tweener: too small for tackle, not quick
enough for end, and an underachiever. He did have nine sacks and 13
tackles for losses.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has had an injury-filled career and has spent much of it
as a defensive end. The 6-4, 245-pounder caught 12 passes for 146
yards in nine starts last year. Lumpkin, at 6-7, 262, is a former
Buckeye basketball player, and caught 31 passes the past two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
