<HEADER>
A6462 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NUHNCOLUMN-SCHOTT     04-20 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NUHNCOLUMN-SCHOTT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Schott's real offense was not fitting in
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ She fought the good old boys club, and the good
old boys club won.
</P>
<P>
   I will never defend the dumb things Marge Schott said. But the
last time I looked, there wasn't any rule against saying dumb
things.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she was pushed out of baseball for those and
another offense, something about fudging numbers at her former car
dealership.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, was apparently much worse than George
Steinbrenner's illegal contributions to the Richard Nixon campaign
_ a federal offense _ so baseball's leadership pursued Schott as if
she were Bonnie of Bonnie &AMP; Clyde.
</P>
<P>
   And they got her.
</P>
<P>
   They made her sell her controlling interest in the Reds. And
soon they'll probably change the locks on the offices at the
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I think her real offense was being a dowdy, old
woman who didn't fit into the new corporate image of baseball. She
wasn't the multi-billionaire Tribune Co., or the multi-billionaire
News Corp. or the multi-billionaire Disney Co., so she was
expendable.
</P>
<P>
   They pushed her, and she was too old and too infirm to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Congratulations, guys. Well done.
</P>
<P>
   So a new era in Reds history begins, and I'm not so sure you're
going to like it. This much I'll assure you: It will cost you more
to go to a game: More for tickets, more for food, more for parking,
more for souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   More to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   All this won't happen tomorrow, but it will happen.
</P>
<P>
   We have just witnessed the demise of the last owner who not only
cared about putting a presentable team on the field, but also cared
_ not just lip service _ but cared about the well-being of the
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Wait 'til you see the prices in the new park. You'll be
screaming for Marge and her dog and her eccentricities.
</P>
<P>
   Her reputation was that she didn't know what she was doing, that
she couldn't tell a hit-and-run from a squeeze play, that she was a
cartoon character with a slobbering dog.
</P>
<P>
   All of which was true.
</P>
<P>
   Also true: She never understood the need for scouts because
``All they do is watch games;'' she once named Kansas City as one
of the Reds main threats; and she actually believed her dog's hair
had more to do with the team's success or failure than the players.
</P>
<P>
   But in Schott's 13-year tenure as general partner of the Reds,
her team had an average finish better than every other team
currently in the National League Central Division.
</P>
<P>
   Was that just luck?
</P>
<P>
   Or was she smarter than the rest of them?
</P>
<P>
   She kept hiring competent people; albeit after she had fired
other competent people.
</P>
<P>
   When her general manager asked her to open her checkbook and
sign a big-buck player, she did. But then she took grief for
counting staples.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in these pages, you'll find a ``chronology'' of
Schott's reign of terror and error. I wouldn't do or say any of it,
but you must realize she was and is a product of her upbringing.
Many people are able to break those ties, but she wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Her people skills _ at least in dealing with employees _ were
straight out of a Dickens' novel. The people she didn't fire, she
bullied.
</P>
<P>
   She was so cheap, she squeaked when she walked.
</P>
<P>
   If not racist in her heart, she was certainly racist with her
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Should any of that disqualify her from owning a baseball team?
</P>
<P>
   It did in this man's game.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
