<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6463 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GYM-HEIDI-LADN-(SLANG     04-20 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYM-HEIDI-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEYMAKER BANKING ON SYDNEY IN 2000
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Nadia Comenici was 16 when she achieved
international fame. Olga Korbut also was a teen-ager. No one on the
1996 U.S. Olympic gymnastics team was older than 19. Dominique
Moceanu was 14, Kerri Strug 17.
</P>
<P>
   Elite gymnasts often are young, but UCLA's Heidi Moneymaker _
considered old at 21 _ will try the unorthodox strategy of using
college as a springboard to the national team.
</P>
<P>
   But first things first. Moneymaker is the reigning NCAA champion
in the uneven parallel bars. She will defend her title, try to
capture other individual honors and lead her team to its second
NCAA team championship in the meet that begins Thursday in Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Most elite gymnasts are between 14 and 16 and use college to
wind down their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll go for myself and see what I can do,'' she said. ``I'm
going to have the experience and it will be a lot more fun because
of my maturity.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a long shot, to be sure. Twenty-one-year-old women standing
5-feet-2 aren't usually physiologically able to perform routines as
well as the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you change your center of gravity, and things grow where
they didn't before, it takes some getting used to,'' fellow UCLA
gymnast Lena Degteva said.
</P>
<P>
   In Moneymaker's favor is U.S. Gymnastics raising the minimum
competing age to 16 for the 2000 Olympics. But since she wasn't on
the international scene when she was younger, no one has heard of
her.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the belief that older women can't compete at the
elite level. But in a sport which seems to give advantage the
young, Moneymaker is showing age and development has its place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heidi has, genetically, the bod that will be able to do
gymnastics for a long time,'' UCLA coach Valerie Kondos said. ``If
they can perform the skills, the judges appreciate the maturity an
older gymnast brings.''
</P>
<P>
   In Moneymaker's case, she lacked the poise and confidence to
execute her routines when she was 16. She wasn't interested in
pursuing a career in gymnastics growing up in Northern Calfifornia,
practicing only four hours a day, half of what the elite gymnasts
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, when she competed, her body tensed up. Moneymaker suffered
from the same mental block many athletes have: they can nail
routines in practice but can't come through in big meets.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would get very tense and tight,'' Kondos said. ``Now we
try and focus that energy through breathing and visualizing so she
can let go in competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even tendinitis in her shoulder is stopping Moneymaker,
although she said it will impede her chances of repeating as bars
champion. The vault might be the event she wins this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is stopping her,'' Degteva said. ``I know she loves
doing it more than anyone else I know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6464 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0421-C     04-20 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0421-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIR STRIKES CONTINUE TO ESCALATE, MEETING AT NATO SUMMIT PLANNED
 &HT;    With JOURNAL-ALBANIA-0421; KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0421;
REFUGEES-STAYING-0421.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (w) Washington
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has scrapped a long-scheduled
slate of formalities to make way for a three-hour meeting with NATO
leaders Friday to try to forge a plan for seizing the initiative in
the alliance's troubled air war with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials conceded Tuesday that a month of air strikes have
not halted Serb atrocities inside the embattled province of Kosovo,
amid signs that the repression has begun to spill over into
neighboring Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's top national security officials insisted that NATO
intends to continue its strategy of steadily escalating air strikes
combined with whatever diplomatic pressure it might bring to bear
on the regime of Serbian leader Slobodan Milosevic, the president
of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   With a growing contingent of NATO ground troops in the region,
however, and two dozen Apache combat helicopters expected in
Albania over the next two days, Clinton's National Security
Adviser, Samuel E. Berger said the leaders of the 19-nation
alliance would discuss ``the full range of issues,'' surrounding
the conflict when they meet on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a working meeting of a military alliance
in the middle of a conflict,'' Berger told reporters at the White
House. ``I am confident that NATO can, must and will achieve its
objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   The heads of state from the 19 NATO countries, as well as 25
NATO partners, have been invited to Washington this weekend to mark
the 50th anniversary of the transatlantic alliance, created in
April, 1949. What was to be a celebratory -- and largely
perfunctory -- summit, however, has turned into something very
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a council of war,'' said Robert Hunter, former U.S.
ambassador to NATO.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon officials showed fresh evidence of the air
campaign's daily toll on Serbian military and paramilitary forces
in Kosovo: another dozen tanks and troop trucks destroyed, another
pair of bridges dropped, a highway overpass bombed to ruin, several
ammunition dumps blasted and more MiG-21 fighters shattered to
wreckage by laser guided bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is signs that we're grinding them down,''
said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon. ``But it's slow and it
will require a lot more attacking on our part and NATO is prepared
to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as the air campaign gathered steam -- U.S. and allied
pilots flew 603 combat sorties during the 24-hour period that ended
early Tuesday, in one of the highest levels since the bombing runs
began March 24 -- NATO was working toward expanding its armada of
warplanes. The Pentagon is reviewing a request by U.S. Army Gen.
Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, for 300 additional combat planes,
refueling tankers and other support craft, which would push the
NATO force to more than 1,000 airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   Romania -- a formal NATO partner but not a full member -- agreed
in principle to permit alliance warplanes to use its air space and
neighboring Bulgaria, a partner as well, was weighing a similar
request. Those developments would provide new avenues of approach
for NATO warplanes attacking Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks, though, haven't stopped Serbian forces on the
ground from pressing their campaign of repression targeting ethnic
Albanians in the Kosovo province. NATO officials said Serbs
continued as late as Tuesday to compile a long and growing list of
offenses ranging from mass executions and systematic rape to the
shelling of civilians and the burning of entire villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
   Against that background, NATO spokesman Jamie Shea confirmed
earlier allegations of Serbian paramilitary activity along Kosovo's
short border with Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian forces reportedly cleared at least three border
communities of ethnic Albanians over the past two days. Montenegro,
which has its own internal tensions between Serbs and ethnic
Albanians, is the other state, along with Serbia, remaining in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said he could not confirm reports of Serbian incursions
into neighboring Croatia -- site of four years of war between Serbs
and Croats that ended as part of the Dayton Peace Accords in 1995.
Bacon warned that Serbian attacks in that region would be regarded
as ``an affront'' to the United Nations, which established a
demilitarized zone as a buffer between Croats and Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a problem that the U.N. and members of the
Security Council would have to deal with,'' said Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
