<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6465 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-SCHOOLVIOLENCE-C     04-20 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-SCHOOLVIOLENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Governor ready to sign school violence legislation
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio - Gov. Bob Taft is poised to sign legislation
aimed at curbing violence at Ohio's schools after the House and
Senate reached final agreement on the bill on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is glad that they were able to move on it in such a timely
manner,'' said Scott Milburn, Taft's spokesman. A date for signing
the bill has not been set, said Milburn.
</P>
<P>
   Milburn said the bill's passage on the same day school violence
flared in the Denver suburb of Littleton pointed up its importance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the point that if students are going to learn to the
best of their ability, they have to feel that their school is a
safe haven,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The school safety legislation, Senate Bill 1, is the second of
Taft's education initiatives to win legislative approval. The
governor last month signed into law House Bill 1 establishing the
OhioReads program, aimed at assuring that every fourth grader can
read at grade level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is equally important to provide a safe learning environment
as it is to teach them to read,'' Rep. Charles Braiding, chairman
of the House Education Committee, said.
</P>
<P>
   The safety bill would add two years to prison terms for crimes
such as assault, burglary, breaking and entering when they are
committed in school ``safety zones.'' The zones include school
grounds, school buses and school activities.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the bill would empower school authorities to expel
students for up to a year for knife- and gun-related offenses that
occur at school-sponsored events off school property.
</P>
<P>
   It also permits expelling a student for up to a year for
inflicting serious physical harm on other persons or property
within the school safety zone. The maximum expulsion now is 80
days.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 93-1 for the bill Tuesday after making minor
changes to the version approved earlier by the Senate. The Senate
concurred with the changes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ray Miller, D-Columbus, cast the only vote against the
legislation, saying some punishments are too stiff and will simply
put more students on the streets and eventually in prisons. Under
the bill, a student could be expelled for a year for busting a
classmate`s nose, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just goes to far,'' said Miller.
</P>
<P>
   House approval of the legislation came after members set aside
an amendment by Rep. Ron Hood, R-Canfield, that would have
incorporated Hood's legislation permitting Ohioans to carry
concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joy Padgett, R-Coshocton, sponsor of a competing bill to
permit the carrying of concealed weapons, successfully proposed
tabling Hood's amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the place and this is not the time,'' said
Padgett.
</P>
<P>
   William Hershey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
