</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Learning To Sell Online
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I am constructing a Web site for E-tailing my products
but know little about the subject. Are there specific associations
or publications available for small-business owners to learn the
protocol for doing business on the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; Answer: &LR;  You might start out with ``Selling Online for
Dummies,'' (IDG Books, $24.99). Author Leslie Heeter Lundquist
concedes that new versions of specific products like Microsoft's
FrontPage software for creating Web pages may have come out since
her book was published last year. But information on getting a
domain name, setting up a Web server, creating content and
accepting payments is current.
</P>
<P>
   Lundquist was talking yesterday to U.S. Department of Commerce
officials about establishing a central clearing house to tell
small- and medium-size businesses how to conduct business on the
Web. But so far, there is no such location.
</P>
<P>
   She also suggests other information sources:
</P>
<P>
   _E-Business Advisor magazine ( &LR; www.advisor.com &LR; ) provides
articles, tips, product news and conference schedules.
</P>
<P>
   _Internet World ( &LR; www.internetworld.com &LR; ) provides plenty of
e-commerce info and tech talk.
</P>
<P>
   _CommerceNet, a Palo alto nonprofit organization that
evangelizes online commerce ( &LR; www.commerce.net &LR; ) has a full range
of information including book listings and answers to common
questions.
</P>
<P>
   _The Center for Software Development in San Jose
( &LR; www.center.org &LR; ) provides information about e-commerce, seminars
and other events.
</P>
<P>
   Cyberspace Bind
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Q: I work for a small manufacturing company that sells to
catalog companies, large department and chain stores, and smaller
retailers. We are considering getting into e-commerce but are
worried about competing with our clients for retail business. Do
you have any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Competing with your customers can be tricky, but Lundquist
has some suggestions to ease possible tensions:
</P>
<P>
   You might sell different products online. For example, Gibson
Musical Instruments sells new guitars though stores but has a very
successful online site ( &LR; www.gibson.com &LR; ) that sells guitar
accessories and has an online auction for used guitars.
</P>
<P>
   Another way not to undercut your wholesale customers might be to
bundle products like travel agents who provide air and hotel travel
packages. That way you are not competing by selling precisely the
same products.
</P>
<P>
   You might also contact your traditional customers and brainstorm
ways to work together. Perhaps you could sell the same items they
do, and even charge a lower price, if you help the stores out by
providing them banner ads or other promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Procrastination Crisis
</P>
<P>
   Q:I have a good job but I'd really like to start my own
business. I'm told, though, that you need to be a self-starter. I
have had a lifelong problem with procrastination. Should I forget
about self-employment?
</P>
<P>
   A: Why not put off worrying about this until later. Seriously,
before you make the leap to self-employment, you might want to deal
with your procrastination problem on someone else's budget.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland career counselor and author Marty Nemko suggests trying
one or more of these techniques to see if you can control your
propensity to put things off at your job:
</P>
<P>
   _If you are paralyzed because a task seems too big, ask
yourself: What is the next 10-second task you need to do, like
calling a supplier. That might be enough to get you rolling.
</P>
<P>
   _Allow no more than 60 seconds to struggle with a stumbling
block. Find a way around it, seek help or proceed to the next task.
</P>
<P>
   _Break a big problem into tiny tasks. For example, if you own a
small business and desperately need 20 new customers or you'll go
broke, it's easy to feel overwhelmed. Instead, look up the phone
number of your best prospect and dial.
</P>
<P>
   _Realize that your excuses for putting off a task are bogus.
</P>
<P>
   To the hedonist who says ``Doing the work is painful; I always
find something I'd rather do,'' Nemko responds, ``Procrastination
is like a credit card: fun when you use it, painful when the bill
comes in.'' If you truly like pleasure more than pain, get your
work done efficiently so maximum time is left for pleasure, without
guilt or negative consequences to spoil the fun.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the ``fear-of-failure'' excuse is if you don't
try, you're guaranteed failure.
</P>
<P>
   _Try the Scarlet Letter technique. Write the letter ``P'' (for
procrastination) on your palm. This procrasti-cure may sound hokey,
but Nemko says this ongoing reminder helps some people from sliding
back into old habits.
</P>
<P>
   _Realize that sometimes procrastination is a sign that you
 &LR; shouldn't  &LR; be doing the task. How can you tell? Write the
advantages and disadvantages of doing it. Then decide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6468 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON &LR;      04-20 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Microsoft Earnings Leap 43%
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Benny Evangelista &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Microsoft Corp.'s net income jumped 43 percent for the third
quarter behind strong demand for its Windows NT corporate server
software and Office business programs.
</P>
<P>
   As the leading maker of personal computer software, Microsoft is
considered a bellwether for the technology sector. Its results,
which were posted after the market closed, came on a day when tech
stocks rebounded from a steep drop on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which said it benefited from rebounding sales in
Japan, posted net income of $1.92 billion (35 cents per share) for
the quarter ended March 31. That compared with income of $1.34
billion (25 cents) for the same quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 15 percent to $4.33 billion. Microsoft's earnings
beat the average estimate of 32 cents per share of analysts
surveyed by First Call Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with stock analysts, Microsoft Chief
Financial Officer Greg Maffei was typically cautious about revenue
growth in the next two quarters, warning as he has in the past that
the Year 2000 computer problem may delay corporate spending on
computers and software.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the evidence is anecdotal, but it appears several
large organizations are delaying projects,'' Maffei said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Maffei also said he expects revenues to increase by
more than $500 million by the end of calendar year 1999 as
Y2K-budget restrictions ease. Also, he noted Microsoft will see
increased revenues from the release of Office 2000, expected to be
available in stores June 10.
</P>
<P>
   The third-quarter results did not include about $400 million in
revenue from pre-release sales of an Office 2000 upgrade. That
revenue will be deferred through the following quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Licensing of Windows NT Workstation to computer manufacturers
led to a 26 percent increase, to $2.05 billion, in Microsoft's
platform product revenues. Microsoft also saw increases in
licensing of its SQL Server and Exchange Server products.
</P>
<P>
   ``While there were jitters during the quarter, the PC market
seemed to remain fundamentally healthy,'' Maffei said.
</P>
<P>
   North American sales growth was moderate, but Maffei said sales
increased 22 percent in Asia during the quarter, particularly in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Microsoft benefited from a drop in PC prices
because demand for its operating software remained steady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Price wars are good for Microsoft,'' said Mike Stanek, an
analyst at Lehman Brothers, told Bloomberg News. ``They get their
bounty for each box, regardless of what's being charged.''
</P>
<P>
   And continued growth in sales of Microsoft's corporate products
like NT Workstation and SQL Server 7.0 are a good ``hedge'' against
any slowdown in PC sales because those products generate twice as
much profit as Windows 98, said William Epifinio, an analyst with
J.P. Morgan Securities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a solid performance and it was certainly nice to see
that Japan was a source of improved growth,'' Epifinio said.
</P>
<P>
   Earnings were released after the close of trading on Nasdaq,
where Microsoft stock closed at $83.13, up $2.13. In after-hours
trading, shares of Microsoft were at $82.12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
