<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETOYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EBay Delays IPO, Will Buy BabyCenter
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Web retailer eToys Inc. postponed its initial stock sale yesterday
after agreeing to acquire San Francisco's BabyCenter Inc., which
sells infant goods on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   EToys, a Santa Monica online seller of toys _ which gained
national exposure in a series of Visa TV ads last Christmas _ will
give BabyCenter shareholders a 15 percent stake in the combined
company. After the IPO, that stake could be worth $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of eToys and BabyCenter ``is a natural fit for
target marketing of consumers from womb to infant to toddler to
adolescent,'' said Ron Rappaport, analyst at Zona Research in
Redwood City. ``You'll be able to buy everything from Chewbacca
bibs to Beanie Babies jumpers to Sony PlayStations.''
</P>
<P>
   EToys had planned to sell 8.2 million shares at $10 to $12 in an
initial public offering this week. The sale, which could have
raised up to $98.4 million, will be delayed until an undetermined
date, according to Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., which is handling the
offering.
</P>
<P>
   The 200-person company eventually intends to sell more than 100
million shares, giving it a market value in excess of $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers typically require a new filing with the Securities and
Exchange Commission before an IPO can proceed.
</P>
<P>
   BabyCenter co-founder Mark Selcow and an eToys spokeswoman, both
citing the pending IPO, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But one analyst said the merged company ``adds fuel to the
fire'' of eToys' forthcoming stock offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``It already was one of the most highly anticipated IPOs in a
maelstrom of online ventures,'' Rappaport said. ``Everyone is
treating eToys as the biggest thing since Amazon.com and eBay.''
</P>
<P>
   EToys recorded an elevenfold jump in sales, to $22 million,
during its fourth quarter, ended December 31, from the previous
quarter. In the three-month period ended September 30, the firm
logged $2 million in revenues, largely from the online sale of
Barbie dolls, Legos, Fisher-Price toys and other brand-name toys.
</P>
<P>
   BabyCenter had just under $5 million in maternity and baby
product sales last year. Sources said the company is in the process
of moving to a larger office, at Fifth and Bryant streets, and
beefing up its 110-person staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wean customers on BabyCenter, who then graduate to eToys.
Who knows, maybe they'll buy Wedding.com next and extend their
e-commerce site to the pre-birth market,'' said Ken Cassar, digital
commerce analyst at Jupiter Communications in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the online market for toys and infant goods will
suffice. Cassar estimates toy-related sales online will top $500
million in the United States by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic baby goods market, meanwhile, is $18 billion. U.S.
parents spend on average about $7,100 in their child's first year,
according to BabyCenter officials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
