<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Intel Speech Online Dispute Comes to Head Soon
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Dan Fost  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
In a case seen as having broad First Amendment implications for
speech online, a state court judge will rule next week in a dispute
between Intel Corp. and a former employee.
</P>
<P>
   Although Intel initially sought monetary damages from the former
employee, Ken Hamidi, the company is now seeking only to make
Hamidi stop sending his mass e-mails to thousands of Intel
employees.
</P>
<P>
   In asking Sacramento Superior Court Judge John R. Lewis for a
ruling of summary judgment _ which would end the case without a
trial _ Intel on Monday said it sought only to charge Hamidi with
trespassing, not with creating a nuisance, as it had earlier
charged.
</P>
<P>
   Hamidi, 51, is a former engineer from Intel's Folsom plant who,
in his bitterness over losing a workers' compensation battle, began
sending bulk e-mail to thousands of Intel employees, saying Intel
lies and mistreats its workers. Intel warned him to stop, and when
he didn't, filed suit, saying he was trespassing by using the
company's internal network to communicate with employees. In
November, Lewis issued an injunction ordering Hamidi to stop
e-mailing Intel employees.
</P>
<P>
   Hamidi sees the case as a fight over his right to free speech.
Groups ranging from San Francisco's Electronic Frontier Foundation
to the Harvard Law Review agree.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has said the Internet is a public forum
where free speech is protected, said Bill McSwain, an editor at the
law review. ``If Hamidi was standing in a public park and pointing
a megaphone into Intel's building, they couldn't shut him up,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Intel doesn't view the case as having anything to do with
the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not freedom of speech. It is trespass,'' said Intel
spokesman Chuck Mulloy.
</P>
<P>
   Mulloy cited numerous cases of Hamidi exercising free speech
without any Intel opposition: ``Hamidi has done mailings and flyers
to universities where we recruit. He's demonstrated at Intel sites.
He has exercised his freedom of speech to an amazing level. He's
been very persistent. Where we believe he crosses the line is the
e-mail, which we believe is equivalent to demonstrating in the
hallways of our building.''
</P>
<P>
   That point is still in contention. Shari Steele, an attorney
with EFF, said, ``The definition of a trespass should be a physical
intrusion, not just someone sending me a message I don't like.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamidi hasn't sent any e-mails since the November injunction. He
maintains a Web site critical of Intel at  &LR; www.faceintel.com.  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to challenge the injunction,'' he said yesterday. ``I
would like to start sending e-mail to inform and educate those
Intel employees so they don't get victimized like I did.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest development, Intel said it dropped its request for
damages to expedite the case.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge grants Intel's motion for summary judgment next
week, then Hamidi will likely appeal. If the judge denies Intel's
motion, then the case is set for trial in July.
</P>
<P>
   In dropping its request for damages, Intel not only eliminated
the spectacle of a company with $6.1 billion in profits last year
seeking money from a bankrupt ex-employee, it also did away with
the prospect of a jury trial.
</P>
<P>
   Because Intel and Hamidi agree on the facts _ that Hamidi sent
the e-mails _ the only issue for the judge to decide is whether
that action broke the law. Hamidi's lawyer said not having a jury
could benefit Intel, as a jury might be more sympathetic to the
little guy taking on a big corporation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
