<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-EARNINGS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT EARNINGS BEAT ANALYSTS EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Microsoft Corp. on Tuesday again beat analysts
expectations with quarterly earnings 43 percent above those of a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly on the strength of continued strong sales of its Windows
operating systems and Office software in the quarter ended March
31, the company said Tuesday it had net income of $1.92 billion or
35 cents per diluted share, compared with $1.34 billion for the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues totaled $4.33 billion, a 15 percent increase over last
year's $3.77 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts surveyed had predicted earnings per share of 32
cents, according to CBS MarketWatch. But the company, while warning
to the contrary, regularly has beat earnings estimates by 2 or 3
cents.
</P>
<P>
   So analysts were not expecting stock prices to surge when the
market reopens Wednesday. The earnings were reported after the end
of trading Tuesday, when Microsoft stock closed at $83.13, up
$2.13. It lost another dollar, falling to $82.13, in after-hours
trading, reflecting investors sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very respectable numbers,'' said Tom Hensel, vice
president of research at Everen Securities in Chicago. ``People
have to realize not every quarter is going to be a blowout for
Microsoft.'' Many past quarters have been characterized by even
higher revenues and earnings per share, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a pretty good quarter,'' echoed Scott
McAdams, president of Seattle brokerage McAdams Wright Ragen. ``I
wouldn't say it was a blowout quarter, so I don't see the stock
spiking.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleased by the results, top executives at the Redmond,
Wash-based software giant said they anticipate similar numbers for
the current quarter. But chief financial officer Greg Maffei warned
that corporations delaying software projects so they can focus on
the Y2K issue may lead to a slowdown between now and the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate concerns that computers will malfunction when the year
2000 arrives, because the year 00 will confuse computers, are
diverting dollars and attention away from purchases of new
software, Maffei said.
</P>
<P>
   But widespread concern that the personal computer market is
declining appear to be misplaced, he said. Microsoft's revenues
from sales of operating system software to PC vendors grew 29
percent compared with the same quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   The quarter's growth was driven primarily by continued migration
to the Windows NT operating system, demand for the Office suite of
business applications despite an upgrade set for release in
mid-June, and strong sales of SQL Server 7, a much improved version
of Microsoft's industrial-strength database manager. SQL Server 7
shipments increased 50 percent over the year-ago quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The quarter also saw the announcement of BizTalk, which put
forth Microsoft's product strategy for electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Microsoft's Asian revenues increased 22 percent over
the same period last year, to $475 million, largely on the strength
of Office sales. ``We're cautiously optimistic that maybe we're
starting to turn the corner'' in Asia, Maffei said.
</P>
<P>
   Key milestones in the current quarter include the shipment of
the third and final beta, or experimental, version of Windows 2000,
which will succeed Windows NT 4.0. Carla Lewis, Microsoft senior
director of investor relations, called it ``a reasonably held
industry hope'' that the operating system will ship by year-end.
</P>
<P>
   For at least the last three consecutive quarters, Microsoft has
turned in earnings per share that are at a minimum 20 percent
higher than the prior year's equivalents. Earnings per share,
adjusted for dilution, have also increased each quarter over the
past year, from 25 cents per share, except that EPS for the quarter
just ended were 1 cent less than those for the prior quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
