<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARS GROW THAT REFUGEES ARE BEING BLOCKED FROM LEAVING KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOJAN, Macedonia _ For the second day, only a few refugees
trickled through official border crossings from Kosovo while
thousands more, reporting attacks around the town of Gnjilane,
crossed at other points.
</P>
<P>
   About 3,000 refugees from the Gnjilane area walked into the tiny
mountain village of Malina Mala just inside Macedonia on Tuesday,
said officials for the U.N. high commissioner for refugees. The
group joined 3,000 refugees who had already fled to the remote
village, where 600 families are now caring for 6,000 refugees.
</P>
<P>
   A second group of 1,000 to 3,000 refugees from Gnjilane appeared
here in Lojan Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, roughly 100 people crossed into Kukes, Albania, and
about 150 entered Blace, Macedonia, border posts that were flooded
with refugees over the weekend, the officials said. The slow
traffic through official crossing points heightened fears that
Yugoslav forces were preventing refugees from leaving Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The second day of silence along the borders was accompanied by
reports of intensifying attacks by Yugoslavs in Kosovo. A Western
diplomat who spoke on condition of anonymity said Kosovo Liberation
Army commanders were reporting that over the last several days,
Yugoslav army units had systematically shelled hills in
northeastern Kosovo where thousands of civilians were hiding.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat said that according to the guerrilla army's
commanders, dozens of people were killed in the shelling, east of
the town of Podujevo. Thousands of others fled from the hills and
were herded into a long column by Yugoslav forces and driven south
toward Pristina, the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to the column is unclear. Guerrilla commanders
said it was turned back north of Pristina, said the diplomat, who
spoke with them by phone. Some of the refugees were placed around
police installations or in camps, they said. The accounts could not
be independently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts of young men of fighting age being separated from
groups of civilians were emerging for the first time in
southeastern Kosovo, the diplomat said. Refugees fleeing attacks
around Gnjilane last Wednesday and Thursday were giving consistent
accounts of young men being forced to join work details where they
dug trenches or graves. In some cases, they were later executed,
the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, reports of the separation of men of fighting age have
emerged mostly from western Kosovo, particularly areas of heavy
guerrilla activity. Gnjilane and other towns in southeastern Kosovo
recently attacked by Yugoslav forces were not Kosovo Liberation
Army strongholds, the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Tuesday night what the refugees experienced
inside Kosovo because Macedonian officials blocked aid workers and
journalists from speaking with them. After allowing one food convoy
in Malina Mala on Sunday, Macedonian officials barred aid groups
and journalists from driving into the village because it lies close
to the border with Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
