<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6473 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DANCE-ARCHIVE-ART-2TA     04-20 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCE-ARCHIVE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR NEWCOMERS, AN ARCHIVE IN HUMAN FORM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 25)  
 (af)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Somewhere in a studio at American Ballet Theater, at
any given moment in the months leading up to the company's season
at the Metropolitan Opera House, which opens Monday, there was a
dancer waiting to learn about the history of the classical ballet.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson would not be learned from books or written notes or
even videotapes, though all contribute to an intellectual sense of
the centuries-old art and the specific work to be studied that day.
It was a history that walked quietly through the door, turned to
the pianist and clapped its hands for the rehearsal to begin.
</P>
<P>
   Four centuries of ballet tradition and evolution are encoded in
the bodies and minds of the dancers' teachers and coaches: in
Frederic Franklin, one of the last of the Ballet Russe de Monte
Carlo stars of the 1930s, in the great Soviet ballerina Irina
Kolpakova, who performed with the Kirov Ballet in Leningrad from
the 1950s through the mid-1980s, and in Georgina Parkinson, a
leading ballerina with the England's Royal Ballet in its late glory
days through the 1970s. The history lives, too, in former Ballet
Theater dancers like Kevin McKenzie, now company director, Victor
Barbee, the gifted character dancer, and Susan Jones, who is known
for her encyclopedic memory.
</P>
<P>
   The first recorded attempts to codify dance steps in a script of
symbols occurred in mid-15th century Italy. Today, whole ballets
and modern-dance works are written out and quickly retrievable in
computer programs, down to the smallest steps and gestures and most
complex positionings and travels of dancers across the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Films and videotapes are also useful, and Ballet Theater tapes
every rehearsal for archival purposes. But dancers say that nothing
captures the flavor and impulse of choreography as well as watching
an informed body dance it out.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the pieces Ballet Theater will perform at the Met _
among them a new production of Kenneth MacMillan's ``Anastasia,''
revivals of Twyla Tharp's sassy ``Push Comes to Shove'' and Paul
Taylor's lyrical ``Airs,'' and ballets by George Balanchine and
Jiri Kylian _ were created recently enough so that the
choreographers or their hand-picked representatives are available
to restage the works.
</P>
<P>
   For others, like such classics as ``La Bayadere,'' ``Don
Quixote'' and ``Giselle'' and a revival of Leonide Massine's 1938
``Gaite Parisienne,'' the company and its dancers must rely on the
articulate bodies and memories of earlier generations.
</P>
<P>
   The highly stylized organized chaos of the Massine ballet is
very far from the experience of most dancers today, products of
training that tends to emphasize clean, forceful technique and
near-abstraction in style and dramatic expressiveness. How to pass
along the frou-frou of ``Gaite Parisienne?'' Giuseppe Picone, who
will dance the Baron in the ballet this weekend, said of Franklin.
``Anytime he moves, I can see exactly why the style.''
</P>
<P>
   Music is the key to recalling choreography for Franklin, who is
at Ballet Theater to restage ``Gaite'' and who danced the first
Baron after learning just about every other male role in the
ballet. Ms. Jones describes the process as ``hearing the rhythm of
the steps in your head to come up with the right steps.''
</P>
<P>
   The score was played wrong for the company's last revival of the
piece, Franklin said, with too many pauses and lulls that slowed
the crucial momentum of the dancing. At a rehearsal at Ballet
Theater earlier this month he stood by the piano, beating out the
rhythm with his foot and singing along.
</P>
<P>
   But not for long. Soon he was dancing beside Picone and
Christine Dunham, who plays the alluring Glove-Seller, his
84-year-old body brimming with the gaiety and restless energy of
Offenbach's Paris cafe, where the ballet takes place.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Massine everything is all at once,'' Franklin said. ``I
show them the basic things, then let them have a go at it and see
how it comes out. Though this is new for them, the Ballet Theater
dancers are used to the big old classics. They are used to roles
and strange characters on the stage, which most dancers today
aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbee is there sketching out steps with his body as well as
learning Franklin's way of presenting it. Like Ms. Jones, Barbee
will now be available for teaching the ballet to new dancers after
Franklin leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Each ballet master and coach rehearses a little bit of
everything, they say, though each has an area of concentration. Ms.
Kolpakova works, for example, with the classics. David Richardson,
the assistant artistic director, is the company's Balanchine
specialist. And each dancer studies with a variety of teachers and
coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Learning a role begins, of course, with learning the steps and
at times adjusting them. All is not written in stone and certainly,
as Barbee points out, it would not be possible for dancers today to
perform ``Giselle,'' the oldest ballet in the company's current
season, the way it was done at its premiere in 1841.
</P>
<P>
   Audiences have changed; dancers' bodies are different. ``We do
steps now that they didn't do 20 years ago,'' he said. ``You try to
preserve what you have learned from another generation, but you
also have to keep it going into the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbee estimates that teaching a solo or small ensemble dance
can take anywhere from a half hour to two hours. But dancers must
also understand the way the step is done _ its dynamics and also
the style of the choreography _ in a particular ballet. Only 20
percent of a performance, Barbee said, is ``where do I go, and how
do I get there?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I ask someone to do a glissade assemble, they know what I'm
saying,'' Barbee continued, referring to a simple ballet waltz
step. ``But the glissade assemble changes according to how fast or
slow it is. Is it down into the floor or out of the floor? Is it a
liquid movement or a rock-solid movement? And if it is liquid, is
it liquid like water, mercury or silk?''
</P>
<P>
   In some modern choreography, too, the steps are only remotely
recognizable as standard ballet vocabulary learned in the
classroom. ``So how do you relay that? It can only be done through
the experience of someone who knows what the intention of the step
was. In our vocabulary there's a tremendous amount of information
lacking. And it's up to the ballet master to provide that
information.''
</P>
<P>
   If Barbee were to write out the step sequence of a dance _ say,
the second-act adagio in ``Giselle'' _ anyone with a good knowledge
of dance could probably visualize the sequence. ``But you're not
going to read the steps and have tears come to your eyes,'' he
said. ``So how do you produce something in a performance that can
have that effect on an audience?
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt, if I know what the moment feels like, I know
what the step is. If I've just learned the step, it means no more
to me than that adagio on that piece of paper. But once you've
discovered what a moment feels like, whether it's emotional or
physical, I think you've arrived at something you can recreate _
not reproduce _ from one performance to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   But how to transmit the quality of the moment and the history
that implicitly colors it?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Each coach has a distinctive approach. Ms. Jones is briskly
sympathetic. As a longtime corps dancer, she has a special feeling
for that important but sometimes underrated job. ``This is not just
about my ability to take 24 girls from 24 different schools and say
something in a way they'll understand so that they start to move
together,'' Ms. Jones said. ``This is about giving them the belief
that they are the support system of the entire ballet. They have to
be encouraged and inspired.''
</P>
<P>
   Working as an organism, the corps can bring an extra, though
often intangible, glow and polish to everything from classics like
``La Bayadere,'' where corps discipline is responsible for one of
the ballet's most poetic passages, to the jazzy roilings of Ms.
Tharp's ``Push Comes to Shove.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie is known for his intensive approach to dramatic
interpretation, which can range from working out the tiniest
dramatic details of each moment in a character's scene in
``Giselle,'' for example, to making sure in a plotless ballet that
dancers are aware of the space they're filling and the space that
surrounds them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the specificity that replaces the storytelling in a
story ballet,'' McKenzie said. ``There is nothing in dance that
doesn't have some form of emotional motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Steps and technique are the equivalent of words and sentences.
The larger meaning comes with a ``specific blueprint'' for a role,
as he puts it, learned with the choreography as an interpretive
tool or a departure point. Absorbing the lessons of the artists
around one continues the fine-tuning.
</P>
<P>
   For him, Barbee and Ms. Jones, those artists included some of
the great stars of 20th-century ballet, among them Erik Bruhn,
Anthony Dowell, Mikhail Baryshnikov, Cynthia Gregory and Natalia
Makarova, who staged Ballet Theater's production of ``La
Bayadere.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parkinson is known for being outspoken yet empathic, with a
sensitivity for dramatic characterization developed through work
with MacMillan and Bronislava Nijinska, a choreographer who figured
prominently in the modernist ballet experimentation of the 1920s in
Paris. The principal dancer Ashley Tuttle recalls one of the most
useful correctives Ms. Parkinson gave her, early in her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, darling, you were so (italics)boring,''(end italics) Ms.
Parkinson said, embroidering the adjective with an earthy
expletive, when asked by the then-fledgling dancer for an opinion
on a particular performance.
</P>
<P>
   The comment stung. But Ms. Tuttle, laughing now at the memory,
never forgot the lesson that the steps, which came easily to her,
were not enough. Working with Ms. Parkinson, she learned everything
from helpful tips about not straining upward when she was nervous
to the confidence to know that Ashley Tuttle had something of her
own to give to Giselle in her mad scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be much easier now,'' Ms. Parkinson once told her
after an exhaustive session on a difficult classical solo. ``And it
was,'' Ms. Tuttle said, adding that those specifics carried over
into everything else she danced.
</P>
<P>
   The Ballet Theater repertory is large, as is the roster of
principals and soloists. ``Every dancer you get is under pressure
because of the way we work,'' Ms. Parkinson said. ``There is no
really great quality time because there isn't that much time. So
they may come unsure of themselves, or not prepared to be naked in
front of you. And you have to help them to get over that. You have
to make them realize that each of them has got something to say,
and that what you're trying to do is get them in touch with that so
they can be confident and free enough to make things their own.''
</P>
<P>
   The process can be heartbreaking. With so many dancers vying for
important roles, few get a chance to do more than one performance
of a role each season, robbing them of the chance to grow steadily
in that role.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be a dancer these days is so hard,'' Ms. Parkinson said.
``We all should be allowed to make mistakes. But there isn't much
room. So all the coaching has extra pressure on it. It's not a
slow, quality process where you can build each day.''
</P>
<P>
   With Ms. Kolpakova, dancers get a dose of vivid history along
with stylistic and technical corrections. Ms. Kolpakova trained
with Agrippina Vaganova, the seminal Soviet teacher and
theoretician. And as a Kirov Ballet dancer her roots go back to
Marius Petipa and Lev Ivanov, the creators of most of the
style-setting Russian ballet classics of the late 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kolpakova has been known to encourage dancers, often tired
at the end of a long day of rehearsals, simply to scream in order
to ``feel something'' and relax. ``Dance is theater,'' she says.
``They are afraid to lose their balance, to fall down. This is
boring, not interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   She is a highly physical teacher who tugs, pushes and pulls at
bodies to give dancers a sense of the physicality of a step. But
she also peppers her teaching with quotations ranging from
Alexander Pushkin's immortalization of the ballerina Avdotia
Istomina in ``Eugene Onegin'' to colorful descriptive passages from
the critical writing of Theophile Gautier and Andre Levinson and
stories of her teachers and ballerinas who danced for the Czar.
</P>
<P>
   It was to Ms. Kolpakova that Susan Jaffe, a senior ballerina at
Ballet Theater, turned in 1990 when she sensed that she needed a
new direction in her dancing. Ms. Jaffe, who also studies with the
acting coach Byam Stevens, wanted to learn firsthand about
Vaganova's teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went back to square one,'' Ms. Jaffe recalled. With Ms.
Kolpakova, she learned to make full use of her upper body, an area
often neglected in American ballet but the instrument of expression
and nuance. She even relearned the basic arabesque.
</P>
<P>
   The two worked painstakingly for over a year. Then Ms. Jaffe
decided she needed to show Ms. Kolpakova, slowly and thoroughly,
what she had learned. She asked her voluble teacher not to say
anything at first as she worked her way from a colorlessly correct
to a nuanced technical demonstration in a process that lasted an
entire month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to erase what she had taught me so I wouldn't be a
copy,'' Ms. Jaffe said. ``I had to allow my own body to take over.
It was very difficult for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kolpakova laughs, recalling what amounted to a
life-and-death struggle for both. ``She was tired and I was
picky,'' she said of Ms. Jaffe and the unusual venture. ``Then I
understood that I was in a way too much. I wanted her to do
everything. Now Susan knows. And she can teach someone else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
