<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: AOL's Steve Case to H&AMP;Q's Dan Case: Hey, Maybe Next Year
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
It might mean nothing. Then again, it could be a sign of something.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously absent from this year's line up at the Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist technology stock conference next week is America Online.
Management from the Internet blue chip is not slated to appear at
the annual confab being held at the Westin St. Francis hotel, where
fund managers traditionally shop for their favorite technology
shares.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's decision to bypass the H&AMP;Q stock show is especially
curious since AOL Chairman Steve Case is the brother of H&AMP;Q
Chairman Dan Case. I mean, it's not like the invitation could have
been lost in the mail? (In fact, AOL was included on a
``preliminary list of invited public companies'' published by H&AMP;Q.)
</P>
<P>
   AOL presented at last year's H&AMP;Q conference, and it also told
its story to investors at Hambrecht &AMP; Quist's Internet stock
conference held last month at the Snowbird ski resort in Salt Lake
City. (Geez, these fund managers really rough it, don't they?)
</P>
<P>
   And while AOL will be AWOL from this year's H&AMP;Q event, other
Internet heavyweights, such as Yahoo and Amazon.com, will be there
with bells on. Adding intrigue to all of this is the fact that AOL
is expected to announce its first-quarter earnings on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Oftentimes, companies schedule their earnings announcements to
coincide with their appearances at stock conferences. This, of
course, is usually the case when news is especially upbeat. It
gives management a chance to gloat when things are going well.
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, companies usually avoid stock conferences that
are scheduled prior to the release of their financial earnings when
the news is somewhat ugly or there are untoward surprises, says a
conference planner at a bulge-bracket brokerage and investment
bank.
</P>
<P>
   Executives don't want to be in a position to reveal financial
problems before the official release of quarterly numbers, the
source says. &UR;  &LR; The most egregious warning sign _ which I want to
emphasize does not appear to be the case here with AOL _ is when
companies scratch their appearances after putting their names on
schedules to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It raises a lot more red flags when a company cancels,'' a San
Francisco fund manager says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, many fund managers keep track of original conference
lineups and compare them with the schedules released immediately
prior to events. And when names are missing, negative suspicions
about the canceled companies are raised, says one Silicon Valley
hedge fund manger.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, an H&AMP;Q spokeswoman says that  &LR; AOL elected not to
present at her company's conference because it appeared at the
Internet stock event in Utah last month. Presumably, AOL feels that
it just recently told its story and doesn't need to repeat it so
soon. An AOL spokeswoman was unable to respond before deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street still loves AOL. According to IBES, a financial
research firm, about 95 percent of the 41 Wall Street analysts that
follow AOL recommend its shares as a ``buy.'' Their consensus
estimate for first-quarter earnings to be released next week are 9
cents a share. Buoyed by yesterday's rebound in technology, the
company's shares soared about 12 percent yesterday to close at
$128.69.
</P>
<P>
   When you're a component of the S&AMP;P 500 and nearly every fund
manager's favorite holding, maybe you can afford to blow off a
stock conference here and there _ even if it is being thrown by
your brother.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CASE STUDY: &LR;  Speaking of H&AMP;Q and Dan Case, the San Francisco
investment bank reported earnings after the market closed of 98
cents a share for the quarter ended March 31. That beat the
Street's consensus estimate by a whopping 45 cents. Case
attributes, among other things, a ``sharp improvement in the equity
underwriting environment, (H&AMP;Q's) strong position in the market
(and) robust levels of brokerage activity`` for the stellar
performance.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;Q's shares jumped almost a point to $33 a share prior to the
news yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, when you look at how well the Bay Area investment
bank fared during the quarter, it makes you wonder how BankAmerica
can blame its investment banking business, namely Montgomery
Securities, for dragging down the Charlotte bank's earnings during
the same quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, from the this-town-is-too-small file: H&AMP;Q also
announced that it has named former BankAmerica Chairman and CEO
David Coulter to its board of directors. And you wonder why they
call the banking business ``clubby.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
