<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO NATIONS CONTEMPLATE RECONSTRUCTION FOR BALKANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The western military alliance has begun promoting
the idea of a sweeping reconstruction of the Balkans, even as it
destroys refineries, bridges, roads and buildings in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Though the idea is still vague, the Clinton administration hopes
that the NATO summit meeting in Washington this weekend will
produce a framework for the project, which would cover all the
countries of the Balkans, the poorest part of Europe.
Administration officials insist that carrying out any plan,
especially in the countries surrounding Yugoslavia, would not hinge
on a resolution of the Kosovo conflict or the ouster of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
said Tuesday that millions of people in the Balkans are depending
on an economic rescue and could not be ``held hostage'' by the fate
of one man.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has not begun to define the scale of
such a project or to focus on the nuts and bolts of how much it
would cost, which countries would participate and what the precise
goals would be. But the theme of such a reconstruction plan is as
important as the details in that it signals to Milosevic's
supporters international pressure will be brought to bear on the
region to promote economic cooperation and that Yugoslavia's future
lies with its integration into Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Various European nations have talked of rebuilding the Balkans
off and on over the last few years, with little to show for it.
With the war in Kosovo now in the process of ruining the province's
capacities for production and its transportation system and
accelerating the mass exodus of its population into already
distressed neighboring countries, the alliance says it is more
determined now to seek a broad-scale permanent solution.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who discussed the rebuilding of the Balkans
privately with British Prime Minister Tony Blair two weeks ago,
first publicly raised the notion of United States participation in
the plan last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should try to do for Southeastern Europe what we helped to
do for Western Europe after World War II and for Central Europe
after the Cold War,'' he said during a speech in San Francisco in
which he focused on the future of Kosovo, which NATO has been
bombing since March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been careful to avoid describing the rebuilding as a
modern-day Marshall Plan, which invites comparison with one of the
most comprehensive _ and most expensive _ peacetime initiatives in
world history. Over four years, 16 countries rebuilt a Europe
devastated by World War II in an attempt to halt starvation,
prevent the spread of communism and stabilize the international
order to promote free-market economies. The plan, to which the
United States contributed $13 billion starting in 1948, laid the
foundation for NATO.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said that the Clinton administration and the
European Union are nonetheless striving for a thematic vision
comparable to that of the Marshall Plan to signal the west's
intentions of bringing long-term stability to the region.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott said that to achieve
long-term stability the alliance would need to bolster the nearby
countries of Albania, Bosnia, Bulgaria, Croatia, Romania and
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ability to be confident when this conflict is over that it
will be over once and for all and the United States and its allies
won't have to once again come back with military force,'' he said,
``is going to depend a lot on the security, the stability and the
prosperity of those countries in the region which have been part of
the solution, as opposed to Serbia, which has been part of the
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   How much physical rebuilding of Serbia would be undertaken and
when it might begin are major political questions that the alliance
has yet to address. But Albright suggested Tuesday that it would
not necessarily depend on the fate of Milosevic's regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether Milosevic and Yugoslavia is a part of that depends on
how this ends and whether we see a democratically elected
government in Yugoslavia,'' Ms. Albright told reporters at a White
House briefing. ``We cannot hold the whole region hostage to
Milosevic's policies,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The still-sketchy plan has evolved from notions of tinkering
with ways to promote trade within the Balkans to a more expansive
economic program that would offer technical and development
assistance to the neighboring countries, compensate them for losses
in trade and help them pay off their debts. As one European
diplomat put it, ``We need something substantial to make sure we
never get into this mess again.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials hope any economic program would involve international
institutions like the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund as well as most if not all nations of the NATO alliance. Some
analysts involved in the planning said it could be patterned on the
smaller $5-billion, four-year plan to help rebuild Bosnia in which
several dozen agencies and nations are participating.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said that the plan had emerged from discussions among
European allies and that the allies expected to delve into the
subject when the leaders of the 19 NATO countries gather here later
this week for their summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as we respond to this crisis in Kosovo,'' she said, ``we
must concern ourselves more broadly with the future of the region.
Our explicit goal should be to transform the Balkans from Europe's
primary source of instability into an important part of its
mainstream. And we must work to insure that NATO forces will not
again be called on to fight terror and destruction in this corner
of the continent. And in our discussions at the summit, we will
begin to do just that.''
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere and agenda of the summit meeting have changed
markedly since the beginning of the aerial bombardment of
Yugoslavia a month ago, according to National Security Adviser
Samuel Berger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had planned a summit that focused a bit on the past and a
great deal on the future,'' Berger said Tuesday. ``Now it's
necessary to have it focus intensely on the present as well. This
is going to be a working meeting of a military alliance in the
middle of a conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton briefly mentioned the NATO gathering at a
White House ceremony at which he presented the Medal of Freedom to
former German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the crisis in Kosovo was evidence of a need to
project Western power and values into Eastern and Southern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can and must remain willing to act,'' Clinton said,
``because the work of building a new world never ends.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
