<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHARLIE WARD NEEDS A ROBE, AND A GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darryl. Gretzky. Olympic Scandals. The Draft. Piazza Hurt.
Darkness Looms for Garden. Zim Sasses Boss.
</P>
<P>
   Other weird events rush past, and a columnist has to play
catchup ball. As people often ask, ``But what do you really
think?''
</P>
<P>
   1. Charlie Ward Wants Female Journalists Banished From the
Locker Room.
</P>
<P>
   Now we know what Ward is really thinking as he stares past most
people in his path. The Knicks' point guard is brooding about being
seen in a state of undress in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Ward should get a bathrobe. He should also worry more about
being seen in a state of undress on the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is Ward is one of the least effective point guards in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   Ward passed out quotes from the Rev. Reggie White the other day,
saying women should not be in the locker room. At least Reggie
White has a personality. At least Reggie White can play his game.
</P>
<P>
   It is people like this who give organized religion a bad face:
the widespread fear of women, the obsessive division of the world
into a few of ``us'' and a lot of ``them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had a run of talented and smart guards in the past
decade: Mark Jackson, Doc Rivers, Derek Harper. I never heard them
whining about female journalists. I suggest there is a link between
Ward's lack of vision on the court and his lack of tolerance off
the court. Some of his colleagues think he's sneaky-dirty, also.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody in the front office vastly overrated Charlie Ward. Now
he should seek his level _ quarterback in the NFL Europe League.
Maybe there are no women there.
</P>
<P>
   2. Isles' Owner Rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   The vaunted scouting combine of the National Football League did
its homework on Howard Milstein. His bid to buy the Washington
franchise was turned down for a rather basic reason: it was
overleveraged. However, right in its backyard, the NFL could also
see the skid-row Islanders getting worse under Milstein and Steven
Gluckstern.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise of Torrey and Arbour, Bossy and Potvin, went
downhill under an absentee owner and continued under another owner
who eventually went to jail. It continues under a bunch of
mall-builders who could not get their bulldozers chugging in the
first half-hour of their stewardship, so they gave up trying. The
sooner these guys are gone, the better.
</P>
<P>
   3. Boxing Judge Couldn't See the Punches.
</P>
<P>
   When did that ever make a difference? Every time something
ludicrous happens in boxing _ like the fraudulent draw favoring the
American, Evander Holyfield, against the Brit, Lennox Lewis: boxing
fans treat it like an aberration. Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   There are two inherent flaws in boxing. One is that the state
should not be licensing human beings to hurt each other, unlike any
other so-called sport. The other is that the character of the
business is so marginal (boxers are usually the most decent part)
that there is no reason to expect honesty.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Senate Commerce Committee will hold a hearing into
this sordid enterprise. For anybody who takes a match seriously, or
tries to find a redeeming path for boxing, I would use the
schoolyard phrase _ ``SUCK-UHHH!''
</P>
<P>
   4. Bulls Score 49 Points.
</P>
<P>
   The former team of Jordan and Pippen scored chump-change points
in a full game. Never mind that it was against the martial-arts
tactics of Pat Riley's Miami Heat, who scored 82 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls' stunning total was the lowest for any team since the
league installed 24-second clocks to encourage the lumbering giants
to fling the ball toward the rim more quickly, back in 1954-55. The
Chicago 49ers finished 9 points below the league record for a
single quarter.
</P>
<P>
   This low figure is a tribute to Jerry Reinsdorf, who managed to
run off his championship cast but still charges big-time prices.
What a guy. The 49 points are also a tribute to the league owners,
who engineered a lockout that has produced an artistic disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The new breed of player also deserves credit for stubbornly
resisting team play, coaching tips, basic shots, correct angles off
the backboard, simple logic and basketball wisdom in favor of
degree-of-difficulty highlight-tape shots.
</P>
<P>
   Clueless players and arrogant management are leading us backward
to the era when crude pioneers stumbled around the court, whacking
each other into the potbellied stoves that warmed the drafty
arenas. The NBA values its history so much that it is trudging back
to it. At contemporary prices, of course.
</P>
<P>
   There. I'm caught up.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
