u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWAIR-AIRBUS-NYT &LR;      04-20 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWAIR-AIRBUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW LOW-FARE AIRLINE TO BUY AIRBUS INDUSTRIE JETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Air, a start-up airline that plans to offer low-fare service
from Kennedy International Airport in New York beginning early next
year, has decided to buy narrow-body jets made by Europe's Airbus
Industrie, dealing a blow to the Boeing Corp.'s competing 737 jet.
</P>
<P>
   New Air is expected to sign a deal with Airbus as early as
Wednesday. The agreement includes firm orders for 25 A320 jets and
options and purchase rights for 50 more jets in the A320 family,
which includes the smaller A319 and the larger A321. If New Air
bought all 75 planes at list prices, the deal would be valued at
more than $3.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The sale by Airbus, the jet consortium jointly owned by four
European companies, based in Toulouse, France, is particularly
painful to Boeing because virtually every major executive at New
Air came from carriers that fly the 737.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into this, we fully expected to choose the 737,'' said
David Neeleman, the founder and chief executive of the airline,
which is calling itself New Air until it picks a flashier brand
name. Neeleman previously ran Morris Air, a low-fare carrier based
in Salt Lake City that flew only 737s. ``The more we took a look at
that airplane,'' he added, referring to the A320, ``the more we
liked it. There was unanimity among our management team.''
</P>
<P>
   The 737 was introduced in the mid-1960s. There are more than
3,300 flying today, making it the most successful commercial
airplane of all time, according to Boeing. But the A320, which was
born in the mid-1980s, has been rapidly gaining ground in recent
years. Last year, Boeing delivered the first of a new, updated
version of the 737 in order to slow the A320s advance.
</P>
<P>
   The new plane has been very successful despite several crashes
of older models for which safety officials have blamed the rudder
design. Boeing is now making a record 27 737s every month. But
studies show that the A320 has a slight edge over the 737 in new
orders and future deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Airbus delivered its 1,000th A320. In the
last year, key Boeing customers such as British Airways, UAL's
United Airlines and U S Airways have chosen the A320 over the 737.
Tuesday, Airbus announced that CIT Group, an aircraft leasing
company in New Jersey that owns mostly Boeing airplanes, had
ordered 25 planes in the A320 family.
</P>
<P>
   Both Airbus and Boeing were eager to capture New Air because
they knew whatever plane the airline chose would most likely be a
lifetime commitment. As a low-fare carrier, New Air wants to use
only one type of jet to save money on maintenance and training.
</P>
<P>
   Most low-fare carriers, notably Southwest Airlines, the nation's
largest and most successful, rely exclusively on the 737. Southwest
announced Tuesday that it had exercised options to buy six more
737s.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that it will probably never be able to sell a plane to
rapidly growing Southwest still rankles Airbus. In an interview
last month, John Leahy, Airbus' senior vice president in charge of
sales, said that New Air was particularly attractive because it
would allow Airbus to showcase the A320 in New York, one of the
world's media capitals. He also predicted that Boeing would have to
build yet another version of the 737 to keep up with Airbus, a
notion Boeing has dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Neeleman said that Airbus offered very good terms for the jets.
``The price got our attention, and the product put us over the
edge,'' he said. ``We became very convinced that this was the
airplane for us regardless of the cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Neeleman said that he was won over by the fact that the A320
cabin is seven inches wider than the 737 cabin, allowing for
greater passenger comfort and larger overhead storage bins. He was
also impressed by Airbus' cockpit technology and the fact that the
A320 in the all-coach configuration required by New Air carries 24
more passengers than the 737, for a total of 162.
</P>
<P>
   New Air plans to power the jets with engines made by
International Aero Engines, a consortium that includes United
Technologies' Pratt &AMP; Whitney unit and Rolls-Royce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
