<HEADER>
A6482 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-MOLESTATION-ACQUI     04-20 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-MOLESTATION-ACQUITTAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teacher acquitted of molestation in Florida case
 &HT;    By John Holland
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A jury acquitted Maurice LeFlore
Tuesday, saying even his own confession couldn't overcome gaps in
the testimony of the nine girls who claimed he molested them.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors deliberated about 3-1/2 hours before clearing the former
Riviera Beach teacher of four counts of lewd assault, one day after
the judge formally tossed seven other counts. He had faced more
than 60 years in prison, but instead is free to return to teaching.
</P>
<P>
   The Palm Beach County School District did not renew his contract
after his March 23, 1998 arrest and he said Tuesday he'll return
home to South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a terribly difficult year and I'm just thankful to
God and my family for their support,'' LeFlore, 23, said. ``I
didn't do anything wrong and I'm glad it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Riviera Beach police arrested LeFlore after several girls told
police that he fondled their breasts and buttocks and rubbed them
with his groin. In a seven-minute taped interview with police,
LeFlore confessed to touching two of his students, ages 13 and 14.
</P>
<P>
   But during the trial, some of the girls' statements waffled or
changed entirely, leaving Assistant State Attorney Maura McGuigan
to rely heavily on LeFlore's confession. That confession was
inconclusive, jurors said, and weakened by the lack of supporting
evidence and poor police work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way they should have brought 11 counts, because
they didn't have anything to back it up,'' defense attorney Lynn
Whitfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about that statement a lot, but there wasn't an
ounce of evidence that backed it up,'' juror Mark Taggart said.
``The girls weren't believable and the police officer didn't go to
the school or spend any time investigating. But I think the real
problem is with the school.''
</P>
<P>
   LeFlore's prosecution raised serious questions about the school
system and the way it investigates accusations against its
teachers. Seven school employees, including the John F. Kennedy
Middle School principal, vice principal and three counselors, knew
about the accusations but took no steps to protect the girls,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The employees didn't call police or the state attorney's office
and they didn't call the state's child abuse hotline as required by
law. Instead, they conducted their own investigation, threatening
witnesses to recant and telling the accusers that they would report
their allegations to LeFlore.
</P>
<P>
   Police learned of the complaints after one student called 911
anonymously and police traced the call to a pay phone and found
her.
</P>
<P>
   Only one employee, counselor Rebecca Price, was fired. In
February, a judge acquitted former Principal Clifford Durden of
failing to report the incident.
</P>
<P>
   After the LeFlore verdict, McGuigan praised the girls for coming
forward against such pressure. McGuigan, who is due to give birth
Saturday, declined to hand off the case because she didn't want to
abandon the girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect the jury's decision, I really do, but it's
disappointing,'' McGuigan said. ``When I filed the case, the girls'
statements were very strong. I think the process (of the court
case) is what made their testimony deteriorate.''
</P>
<P>
   John Holland writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
