<SLUG> BC-NFL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. CHOOSES STADIUM SITE IN NFL BID 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN WILLIAMS 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This city's muddled NFL bid gained clarity Tuesday
when league officials designated the aging Los Angeles Memorial
Coliseum as the preferred stadium site over a waste dump in nearby
Carson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came to understand ... that having two competing sites in
the Los Angeles area was ultimately counterproductive for Los
Angeles, because the real competition, as you all know, is
Houston,'' NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the league would select a final ownership team
rather than put the 32nd franchise up for auction.
</P>
<P>
   Though the league might get more money through a high-stakes
bidding war, which garnered a $470 million expansion fee from
Cleveland last year, NFL officials hope to create a more
cooperative spirit in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Such cooperation is needed to tackle a variety of issues Los
Angeles must meet by the Sept. 15 deadline set by NFL owners, or
else Houston likely will get the team.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of the list is providing enough safe parking close to
the Coliseum that will give fans enough confidence to ensure
selling out all games are avoiding a television blackout.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Los Angeles bidder _ Hollywood deal maker Michael Ovitz
and investor Eli Broad _ has guaranteed sellouts as has Houston
businessman Bob McNair, who hopes to land the 32nd team.
</P>
<P>
   While Tagliabue and other NFL officials were cautious to point
out that Los Angeles has a lot of work to do, including upgrading
the Coliseum area, city officials sounded like the decision to
expand to Los Angeles has already been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``NFL football, welcome back to Los Angeles,'' said an
enthusiastic Mayor Richard Riordan. ``We can't wait to be here for
our first Super Bowl game.''
</P>
<P>
   Before that happens, Ovitz and the team of Broad and Ed Roski
must present a comprehensive business plan to NFL officials by the
end of May. The plan, which would outline anticipated ticket sales
and other revenue streams, would become the basis for determining
the expansion fee.
</P>
<P>
   The bidders also must have a development plan for the stadium
area that focuses on providing 27,000 parking places solely for NFL
games.
</P>
<P>
   Then, both sides must come up with plans for renovating the
74-year-old Coliseum, which was home to both the Rams and Raiders
before both fled for better stadium deals in other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Roski has already come up with a plan to gut the Coliseum's
inner workings and replace it with a state-of-the-art stadium
surrounded by the memorable facade of a building that has housed
two Olympics Games.
</P>
<P>
   Under Roski's plan, seating would be reduced from 93,000 to
66,000, increasing the chance of sellouts.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz, who dropped his plans for a Carson deal last week, said
he would come up with his own plan for the Coliseum location.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives for Ovitz twice called the Los Angeles Sports &AMP;
Entertainment Commission Tuesday for directions to the Coliseum for
Ovitz, who drove alone to the south-central location in his red
Porsche convertible.
</P>
<P>
   However, Tagliabue did not discount the possibility that another
ownership team would emerge. Some NFL officials have shown
interest, including former Los Angeles Dodgers owner Peter O'Malley
in an ownership group.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tagliabue said NFL owners have gained more confidence in the
Coliseum area since the Raiders played there before rowdy crowds
before leaving for Oakland after the 1994 season.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, several team owners and NFL officials traveled down the
revitalized Figueroa corridor, which has seen great economic
development to the north with construction of Staples Center, a new
cathedral and additions to the convention center.
</P>
<P>
   The group, traveling in a bus, did not go farther south past the
Coliseum, where the neighborhood becomes much tougher.
</P>
<P>
   Denver Broncos owner Pat Bowlen, a member of the league's
Expansion Committee that met in Los Angeles, said the final project
must spruce up Exposition Park around the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needs open space and grass,'' Bowlen said. ``It can't just
be a football stadium in a sea of concrete.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue said he realizes it would be hard to solicit tax
dollars for the stadium because California voters can overturn such
taxes through initiative and referendum. But he continued the
league's mantra that some public-private partnership is needed to
get a final deal done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
