<HEADER>
A6491 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRBUS-BOEING-717-SPI     04-20 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRBUS-BOEING-717-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING STILL WEIGHING COST-EFFECTIVENESS OF KEEPING 717 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Even as The Boeing Co. prepares a major marketing
campaign to find buyers for its slow-selling 717, executives have
the 100-seat plane squarely in the crosshairs of an initiative to
identify programs that can't make money for the company.
</P>
<P>
   Those programs that don't cut it will either be sold off or shut
down.
</P>
<P>
   Despite sluggish orders for the Boeing plane, European rival
Airbus Industrie has decided to proceed with developing its own
100-seater. An official announcement that the A-318 will be built
is expected within days, an Airbus spokeswoman said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That will make it even tougher for Boeing to win a significant
number of new orders for the 717 and keep it viable, according to
industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm convinced there is a big market (for a 100-seat passenger
jet),'' Boeing Chairman Phil Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the issue will be, can we or anyone build an airplane at a
cost that can be bought in quantity by people operating in that
market? That market assessment is part of what we are doing right
now...''
</P>
<P>
   Condit said Boeing will make a decision on the 717 before the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Airbus is moving ahead with its A-318, which will be
the smallest member of the A-320 family.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus' supervisory board gave a green light Monday for the new
A-318 to be produced, and Airbus informed key customers that it
would be built, several news organizations reported.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus has more than 110 firm orders for the jet, the Wall
Street Journal reported.
</P>
<P>
   That's about what Boeing has for its 717 _ 115 firm orders. But
the 717 _ launched in 1995 before Boeing acquired McDonnell Douglas
_ has been in the marketplace for several years.
</P>
<P>
   The 717 is now in flight testing; the first production airplane
will be delivered to AirTran later this summer. To spur sales,
Boeing will fly the 717 to the Paris Air Show in mid-June, and
afterward will take it on a 10-day sales tour through Europe, with
visits to London, Berlin, Madrid, Athens, Milan, Zurich and
Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Boeing lands new orders, analysts question whether
it can ever make money for Boeing. And that makes it a prime
candidate in the company's all-out push to identify ``value
destroying'' programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are certainly questions whether the program meets the
return on investment criteria to remain part of the Boeing product
line,'' said Peter Jacobs of Seattle's Ragen MacKenzie. ``That will
depend on the company realizing substantial new orders. Right now,
(its current firm order of) 115 planes doesn't cut it. But even
more important is whether Boeing can get costs down to a level that
it can make acceptable returns.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Boeing assembles the 717 in Long Beach, Calif., much of
the structure is produced by partners. Korean Air and Hyundai
supply the nose assembly and wing. Other major parts come from
Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing made commitments to its partners to produce enough planes
to recover the costs of setting up plants to build the parts.
Analyst Paul Nisbet of JSA Research said if Boeing ended the
program before it produced the target number of planes, which he
said is probably about 300 planes, it would have to repay
suppliers. That could amount to more than $100 million, Nisbet
said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that both TWA and AirTran, who have placed a total of
100 firm orders for the 717, have options for another hundred. That
gets Boeing much closer to its target, he said, and would
significantly reduce Boeing's liability.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Boeing will likely continue production until all
existing orders are filled, Nisbet said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very embarrassing, to put it mildly, if they did
not honor their contracts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If customers who have waited all these years found out they
would not get any planes, it would be very damaging for Boeing's
credibility. Boeing would have to eat a ton of crow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
