<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6493 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-HNS &LR;      04-20 1398
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-PLAYOFFS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DALLAS _ They remember. Oh, do they ever.
</P>
<P>
   The overtimes. The seventh game. Joe Nieuwendyk being stoned by
Curtis Joseph from point-blank, an improbable shot slipping through
Andy Moog's legs at the other end and, finally, the sickening sound
of silence as a sellout crowd filtered out of Reunion Arena in
shocked disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   A walkover, this first-round playoff series against the Edmonton
Oilers?
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's best regular-season team knows better than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no problem with keeping the focus on a daily basis,''
Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock said as the Stars got ready for
tonight's Game 1 of their first-round Western Conference playoff
series with the Oilers at Reunion Arena. ``I think our team learned
a lot from that thing two years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Colorado Avalanche learned, too. Edmonton was at
it again, knocking the No. 2 seed out for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've done the same thing for two or three seasons now,''
Nieuwendyk said. ``They've played the regular season and struggled
at times, but this time of year they always seem to pick up their
game.''
</P>
<P>
   These things happen in the NHL, which sets the stick-and-puck
game apart from its more play-to-form counterparts in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   Just last year, for instance, No. 8 Ottawa took out No. 1 New
Jersey in the East. In 1995, the New York Rangers shocked Quebec in
a similar matchup, just a year after San Jose ousted Detroit in a
1-8 pairing.
</P>
<P>
   So Dallas rolls into this series in possession of the
President's Trophy (most regular-season points) and the Jennings
Trophy (fewest goals against), mindful that none of that goes for
much when the puck is dropped this evening. The Stars remember the
sickening feeling of two years ago and insist they won't be caught
napping.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of dredging up bad memories or trying to
redeem yourself,'' center Mike Modano said. ``But you remember, and
you know what can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Should anyone forget, a spoiler or two will be happy to come
along and refresh their memories in the weeks to come.
</P>
<P>
   A look at each of the NHL's first-round series, which begin
tonight:
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN CONFERENCE &QC; 
 &UR; Dallas (1) &QC; 
vs. Edmonton (8) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &UR;  &LR;  &UR; Outlook: &LR;  The Stars beat the Oilers in a tough five-game
second-round series last spring and went 3-0-1 against them this
season. They'll be at less than full strength with defenseman and
captain Derian Hatcher sitting out the last five of a seven-game
suspension for a hit that broke the jaw of Phoenix's Jeremy
Roenick. (Nieuwendyk will wear the ``C'' in Hatcher's absence.) Pat
Verbeek also is out, nursing a sprained knee.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonton is hurting, too, though, with Bill Guerin (the club's
leading scorer with 30 goals and 64 points) and Josef Beranek out
with knee problems.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Joseph's play in the nets made all the
difference. He's in Toronto now, and trade-deadline acquisition
Tommy Salo _ hero of Sweden's 1994 Olympic gold-medal team but
making his first NHL playoff appearance _ is being counted on to
keep the Stars in check as the Oilers go for another upset. Dallas
counters with the one-two punch of Ed Belfour (35-15-9, 1.99
goals-against average) and Roman Turek (16-3-3, 2.08 GAA).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prediction: &LR;  Stars in five. &QL; 
 &UR; Colorado (2) &QC; 
vs. San Jose (7) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &UR; Outlook: &LR;  The Avalanche rallied from a dismal start to claim
the second seed in the West. Goaltender Patrick Roy, one win short
of 100 in the postseason, is back on top of his game, and the
acquisition of right wing Theo Fleury gave an indifferent club a
much-needed lift. With the likes of Peter Forsberg (30 goals, 97
points) and Joe Sakic (41 goals, 96 points) on hand, Colorado is as
talented as any team in the NHL. San Jose, which won only one of
its last five, beat the Avalanche once in four meetings this season
and hopes to play the spoiler again.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prediction: &LR;  Avalanche in five. &QL; 
 &UR; Detroit (3) &QC; 
vs. Anaheim (6) &QC; 
 &LR;  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &UR;  &LR;  &UR; Outlook: &LR;  The two-time defending Stanley Cup champion Red
Wings appeared dead in the water before trade-deadline deals
brought Chris Chelios, Ulf Samuelsson, Wendel Clark and goalie Bill
Ranford, putting the Wings right back into the picture. A year ago,
Detroit spotted the Stars the President's Cup, then came back to
beat Dallas in a six-game Western Conference final, and no one will
be surprised if those two are the last left standing again. Anaheim
chugged in just a game over .500 (35-34-13) after a 1-5-1 finish
and is basically a two-man outfit with wingers Paul Kariya and
Teemu Selanne asked to carry too much of the load.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prediction: &LR;  Red Wings in five. &QL; 
 &UR; Phoenix (4) &QC; 
vs. St. Louis (5) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &UR; Outlook: &LR;  The Coyotes won't have leading scorer Jeremy
Roenick, whose ``head got in a bad place'' between a Derian Hatcher
forearm and the Reunion Arena boards, according to the Dallas
defenseman. That makes a tough job even more difficult for a team
that lost five of its last six. Keith Tkachuk moves from left wing
to center to replace Roenick, but Phoenix will rely heavily on
goaltender Nikolai Khabibulin (2.13 GAA, eight shutouts) to keep
things competitive. St. Louis used a 6-1-2 finish to edge Anaheim
for the fifth spot and could use a big showing from veteran goalie
Grant Fuhr, who has a history of coming up big in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prediction: &LR;  Blues in six. &QL; 
 &UR; EASTERN CONFERENCE &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; New Jersey (1) &QC; 
vs. Pittsburgh (8) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &UR; Outlook: &LR;  Wayne Gretzky thinks the Penguins' Jaromir Jagr is
the game's best young player. Unfortunately, Jagr _ in addition to
being the NHL's top scorer with 44 goals and 127 points _ also is
one of its biggest crybabies, and not a particularly bright one at
that.
</P>
<P>
   Normally tight-lipped with the North American media, Jagr told a
magazine back in the Czech Republic that Kevin Constantine isn't
much of a coach. Yo, Jaromir! It's a small world with that Internet
thing going around, eh?
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey won eight of 10 down the stretch; Pittsburgh went
2-8-2. The Devils, who set a league record with 28 road wins,
should add two to the total before closing this one out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &UR; Prediction: &LR;  Devils in four.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ottawa (2) &QC; 
vs. Buffalo (7) &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &UR; Outlook: &LR;  The Senators held the top spot in the East before
going 0-1-3 over their last four games and being passed by the
Devils in the season's final days. Ottawa's power play enjoyed only
a 14.9 percent success rate during the season, but the Senators can
lean on Ron Tugnutt (22-10-8 with a 1.79 GAA) or Damian Rhodes
(22-13-7, 2.44) to provide high-quality goaltending. The Sabres
have The Dominator _ Dominik Hasek (30-18-14, 1.87) _ but that No.
7 seed says much about the quality of the supporting cast. Still,
the teams played five OT games this season, with the Senators
getting the only win.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prediction: &LR;  Senators in six. &QL; 
 &UR; Carolina (3) &QC; 
vs. Boston (6) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &UR; Outlook: &LR;  The Hurricanes are the most lightly regarded No. 3
seed in recent playoff memory, coming in first in the Southeast
Division despite winning just four more games than they lost
(34-30-18) and compiling the conference's eighth-best record. Other
than lacking talent, tradition (in their previous incarnation, they
were known as the Hartford Whalers) and fans, they have it all
going their way. The Bruins, in turn, racked up 91 regular-season
points (to Carolina's 86) and won the season series 2-1-2 but
finished just third in the Northeast Division. They dropped their
final regular-season game, to Philadelphia, but earn a better
matchup in the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prediction:  &LR; Bruins in five. &QL; 
 &UR; Toronto (4) &QC; 
vs. Philadelphia (5) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &UR; Outlook: &LR;  The Flyers were fading from among the elite even
before Eric Lindros went out with a collapsed lung and surgery that
included the removal of a blood clot. Philly went just 7-5-3 over
its last 15 but salvaged a No. 5 seed by beating Boston in the
final game of the regular season. That might not be much of a coup,
because it set up a first-round series against a Toronto team that
scored a league-best 268 goals in support of Joseph, who won 35
games with a 2.56 GAA. The Flyers opted for John Vanbiesbrouck
(27-18-15, 2.18) in free agency last summer, and the goalie matchup
might decide which team upgraded the most.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Prediction:  &LR; Maple Leafs in five. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
