<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COMBAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Troops from the elite 82nd Airborne Division began arriving in
Albania, assigned to provide security for 24 Apache attack
helicopters expected this week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yugoslav and Albanian troops exchanged gunfire across the
Albanian border with Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Croatia said up to 300 Yugoslav soldiers crossed into the
United Nations-controlled zone of Prevlaka in southern Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO and Pentagon officials said Serbian security forces had
begun driving ethnic Albanians from Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER DEVELOPMENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Russian President Boris Yeltsin sent Viktor Chernomyrdin, the
former prime minister, on a tour of Russia's neighbors, seeking
support for Moscow to lead the way in resolving the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   _ The U.N. refugee agency estimated that more than 603,000
Kosovo refugees have fled to neighboring countries and Montenegro
since conflict broke out in Kosovo more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE WEB &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict in Yugoslavia is available
from The New York Times on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
