<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6499 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS &LR;      04-20 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT URGES NO DECLARATION OF WAR AGAINST YUGOSLAVIA &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration said Tuesday that it
would oppose any attempt in Congress to declare war officially
against Yugoslavia, insisting that such a move would help
destabilize Europe and further damage already strained U.S.-Russian
relations over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright stressed that the NATO
alliance does not consider itself at war with the Yugoslav people
even though the alliance's bombardment of Serb military-related
targets throughout the country has continued for 28 days.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to derail a movement in the House to invoke the War
Powers Act and either declare war or withdraw U.S. forces from the
NATO operation, Albright said President Clinton would welcome
congressional support for the current ``military action.''
</P>
<P>
   But she suggested that it should take the form of a resolution
authored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., calling for the use of ``all
necessary force'' to drive Serb army and paramilitary units from
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do strongly oppose a resolution that would call for a
declaration of war because we don't consider ourselves at war with
Yugoslavia or its people,'' Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony came as Congress began to consider a $6.05 billion
emergency funding request from Clinton to help pay for the U.S.
portion of the NATO operation through the remainder of this fiscal
year if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans leaders said Tuesday that they hope to wrap up
consideration of the emergency request within the next two weeks.
But they said they hope to add substantially more funding to the
request and threatened to use the debate to bash Clinton's military
and foreign policies, not only in the Balkans but around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Irving, for example, accused
the president of allowing military readiness to erode to a
``crisis'' point where U.S. forces cannot respond adequately to
challenges around the world. He also charged that the nation's top
military commanders had lied to Congress about the state of the
nation's defense capabilities because of political pressures from
the White House to cut spending.
</P>
<P>
   Describing U.S. military readiness as ``a national security
crisis'' that should be corrected with more Pentagon funding, Armey
suggested Congress might increase the president's request from $6
billion to at least $10 billion, which would be paid for from an
estimated $85 billion in budget surpluses this year.
</P>
<P>
   He said the increased funding may force the GOP-led Congress to
re-evaluate plans to set aside all Social Security surpluses and to
cut taxes by $800 billion over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must first respond to what I believe is a critical,
dangerous emergency at this moment,'' Armey said. ``Then I'm going
to invite Congress to re-examine our priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   The House and Senate appropriations committees will begin
hearings Wednesday on the funding request, with initial votes on it
scheduled for next week. But a number of lawmakers said there was
no agreement over how much money or what specific programs to add
to the emergency spending bill.
</P>
<P>
   Predictions ranged from $4 billion in additional funding to as
much as $14 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever decision is made on funding, Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., said ``the American people need to understand
that it's coming out of Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress began considering the emergency request as NATO
intensified its air attacks on Serb military targets Tuesday,
taking advantage of clear weather to zero in on Serb troops,
weapons and equipment in Kosovo. Allied planes also went after more
communications sites and other military facilities, including oil
and fuel supplies.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, allied officials
reported more ``disturbing'' incidents of Serb soldiers raping
ethnic Albanian women and using civilians as cover for some of
their military operations.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance spokesman Jamie Shea told reporters that Serb forces
are also shelling hillsides in an attempt ``to flush'' out hiding
Kosovar Albanians. He said once captured, they were either being
killed or placed in forced marches or on trains going to the
borders of Macedonia and Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said Kosovars are also being used as human shields and
forced to march in front of advancing Serb tanks with their hands
tied behind their backs. In addition, NATO officials said Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic's forces are still carrying out mass
executions and forcing people from their homes with tear gas and
fire.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster NATO's assault on the Serbs, 24 U.S. Army Apache
attack helicopters will begin arriving in Albania Wednesday with
support troops and ground-based rocket launchers.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said they would be deployed as soon as
possible and are expected to allow NATO to attack from low
altitudes in a way they have not yet done thus far in the allied
campaign.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the White House, meanwhile, Clinton's top national security
advisers said the Apache deployment would harden the pressure on
Milosevic to succumb to NATO demands that he withdraw his forces
from Kosovo and allow the Kosovar refugees to return to their homes
under the protection of an international security force.
</P>
<P>
   They said NATO leaders would discuss how to bring more economic
pressure on Milosevic at the alliance's 50th anniversary meeting
beginning Friday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Great Britain are trying to persuade the
other allies to go along with an oil embargo that would cut off
Milosevic's ability to resupply his forces with fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``His resupply of fuel has to be stopped, and we will take
measures to achieve that,'' said Defense Secretary William Cohen as
he joined with Albright and national security adviser Sandy Berger
in briefing reporters on the NATO summit.
</P>
<P>
   Albright described the alliance as ``rock solid'' on continuing
the Kosovo operation ``until this crisis ends on just and durable
terms.'' But she said there would be no negotiations with
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic is responsible for the ``ethnic cleansing'
and all the depredations that are taking place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point here is that we are not going to negotiate with him.
We believe that the Serb people would be better served by having a
democratically elected government that represents their values,''
she added.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also used the briefing to drive home the alliance's view
that the airstrikes are starting to pay off, despite reports that
Milosevic has sent additional army and police units into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that the Serb forces think they have to put more
personnel in now shows that our campaign in fact is starting to
have an impact on them. ... As a matter of fact, they are running
short of refined petroleum. We have eliminated their refining
capacity. We have cut in half their ammunition production
capability,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite NATO's claim that the air campaign is working, McCain
and other senators, who favor the use of ground troops, introduced
a resolution Tuesday that would authorize the president ``to use
all necessary force and other means'' to accomplish the NATO
objectives in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the resolution was postponed by Lott until next week.
McCain is running for president in the 2000 election.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
