u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-CITIES-COX     04-20 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-CITIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shootings bring up memories of past school horrors
 &HT;    By RacheL Sauer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tuesday's shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton
reopened wounds for residents of several American towns and cities
that experienced similar tragedies in their schools.
</P>
<P>
   Since October 1997, Pearl, Miss.; West Paducah, Ky.; Jonesboro,
Ark.; Edinboro, Pa.; Fayetteville, Tenn.; and Springfield, Ore.,
all have had students and teachers shot in their schools.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases it's not just the lost innocence, the feeling of
``that happens in other towns, but not here.'' Many residents of
those towns lost their feeling that their city is a safe place to
live.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always feel secure until something like this happens,''
said Craighead County, Ark., Sheriff Jack McCann. ``You kind of sit
around wondering if it's going to happen again. And there's always
that feeling that you can't believe it's happening here.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann said Jonesboro, a town of 51,000 on the Mississippi
River, drew closer together as a result of the March 24, 1998,
shooting rampage during which four junior high school girls and one
teacher died, ``but there's a lot of anger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem for people I've talked to is there's never
been an answer to why. I think if anyone could ever answer why, it
would help a lot, but I don't think that's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The two boys convicted of the killings will serve five and four
years, respectively, in a juvenile detention center, and unless
Arkansas builds a facility for juvenile offenders to keep them
until they're 21, they will be released at age 18. McCann said that
fact only adds to the anger and confusion that irritates wounds
trying to heal ``because they can go to Wal-Mart the day they get
out and buy a gun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   West Paducah, too, has had roadblocks that stand in the way of
the city's ability to heal. Families of three of the students
killed in the Dec. 1, 1997, attack have filed three lawsuits. One
is a $130 million lawsuit against entertainment companies that
produce violent movies and computer games, but the other two name
as many as 42 city, county and school officials whom the families
say they believe could have prevented the tragedy, said McCracken
County Judge Executive Danny Orazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were going through a healing process, passing
the first anniversary, going through the Michael Carneal trial (the
boy convicted in the three student deaths),'' Orazine said. ``We
thought surely this would be the end of it, but you don't ever get
completely over it and
</P>
<P>
   then something like (the lawsuits) comes along.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Orazine and McCann said their school districts have
implemented strong security measures: in West Paducah, at least
four security guards patrol district schools on a rotating basis,
which didn't happen before, and Jonesboro got a federal grant to
have a full-time security officer at the school where the shootings
happened. West Paducah added a security system to the high school
so any visitor has to be admitted from inside.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Rich Harrison of the Springfield, Ore., Police Department
said the biggest impact the May 21, 1998, fatal shooting of two
teens had was to change the town's attitudes about what places are
safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ways of when you can send your child to school and feel
100 percent sure they're going to come home at night are no longer
there,'' Harrison said. ``One of the last places you could consider
safe for your child is school, and that's no longer true.''
</P>
<P>
   McCann and Orazine said the youth of their community seemed
ready to go back to school when the schools reopened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably was hard to go back, but I think kids are so
active, they've got so much life ahead of them, that they handle
their sorrow differently,'' Orazine said. ``School is where their
life is, and that's where they needed to heal, but the memories and
scars they'll always have.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison said dealing with the tragedy wasn't just an issue for
those with ties to the school, ``it goes out to the whole
community,'' he said. ``It goes way past the parents and students.
You don't have to have a child at that school or know somebody who
goes there to be affected. We've had to work through this is a
community and that's probably what
</P>
<P>
   Littleton will have to do, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Sauer writes for the Daily Sentinel in Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
