u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELIMINATE-CLINTON-TEX     04-20 0054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIMINATE-CLINTON-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
April 20, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Editors:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ELIMINATE-CLINTON-TEXAS (Washington) By By Bennett Roth and Alan
Bernstein _ This is a mandatory kill for CLINTON-TEXAS. The
president has canceled his trip to Texas. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Houston Chronicle
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0390 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6508 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-ART-N     04-20 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS REPORTED TO BE EMPTYING OTHER REPUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mb) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO and Pentagon officials said Tuesday that
Serbian forces had begun driving ethnic Albanians from Montenegro,
signaling a widening of the Balkan conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs' actions appeared to be focused on Albanians who had
fled to Montenegro. Serbia and Montenegro form what remains of the
former Yugoslav federation.
</P>
<P>
   But initial reports were sketchy and could not be confirmed on
the ground, or by other agencies monitoring developments in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the reports at a briefing in Brussels, NATO spokesman
Jamie Shea said: ``This is something rather new and distressful if
this pattern is now spilling over elsewhere into Yugoslavia. It can
only exacerbate the problem, which is already, as you know, of
alarming proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said NATO had evidence
suggesting for the first time that troops in Montenegro are driving
out Albanian refugees who had escaped from the Serbian campaign in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials also reported that NATO warplanes flew 603
missions in the 24 hours through Tuesday morning, the highest
number in the four-week bombardment. Military officials said the
planes had attacked ammunition depots, an ammunition plant near
Belgrade, tanks, trucks and a high-level command post. For the
first time, NATO said it had destroyed a support site for Yugoslav
Frog surface-to-surface missiles, which have a range of 40 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Shea assailed Yugoslav authorities with the most grisly list of
reported executions, rapes and mass graves in Yugoslavia that the
alliance has issued so far. Among other horrors, Shea said Serbs
had taken about 700 Albanian youths, some as young as 14, ``either
to use as human shields or as blood banks for Serb casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   American and other allied officials have watched with growing
alarm as tensions intensify between the republican government in
Montenegro and the federal government of President Slobodan
Milosevic in Belgrade. Montenegro, a poor mountainous region with a
population of 640,000, has been trying to forge economic ties with
the West while balking at control by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The government of Montenegro no longer recognizes the legality
of Milosevic's regime. Its special forces have clashed with forces
from the Yugoslav Interior Ministry in recent days, and there have
been reports that the Serbs shelled refugee camps just inside
Montenegro. About 73,500 Kosovars have sought refuge in the
republic.
</P>
<P>
   American intelligence has reported other signs of a potential
widening of the war. For example, the Montenegrin government has
approached Croatia to buy anti-armor weapons and 2,000 sets of
fatigues for its security forces to distinguish them from the
Yugoslav military police.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia, once also part of Yugoslavia, has cooperated with NATO
in its campaign, closing down an oil pipeline into Yugoslvia on
March 28.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been American intelligence reports that senior
officials in Montenegro have complained that the NATO air war has
been counterproductive, galvanizing nationalistic fervor in Serbia
and putting more pressure on the Montenegro government.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, Romania's defense chiefs gave approval Tuesday
for NATO to cross its airspace if it decides to mount attacks from
the east. The decision will be put to the Parliament for a vote.
Bulgaria has already agreed to allow such overflights, though no
plans have been announced yet to use those corridors.
</P>
<P>
   And the first of 24 U.S. Army Apache helicopters remained
grounded in Italy Tuesday, awaiting clearer weather in Albania so
the aircraft and their supporting units can fly into makeshift,
mud-clogged landing areas there. Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, a senior
officer on the Joint Staff, said the first Apaches should arrive in
Tirana, Albania, on Wednesday, barring more rain, and the remainder
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is still considering how to meet a request from
Gen. Wesley K. Clark, the NATO military commander, for 300 more
American warplanes and support aircraft. Military officials have
not yet decided whether to divert the aircraft carrier Enterprise
and its 70 aircraft to the Aegean, and break a near-ironclad policy
of keeping sailors and pilots at sea no longer than six months at a
time.
</P>
<P>
   The Enterprise was sailing through the Suez Canal on Tuesday and
is expected to be in the Mediterranean by early Wednesday. Navy
Secretary Richard Danzig and Adm. Jay Johnson, the chief of naval
operations, oppose extending the Enterprise's tour.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier Theodore Roosevelt is now in the Adriatic.
</P>
<P>
   Even as military officials said the air war is grinding down
Belgrade's ability to rearm and resupply its 40,000 troops in
Kosovo, NATO officials in Brussels described in gruesome detail the
atrocities reported from the besieged province.
</P>
<P>
   Shea said more than 3,500 ethnic Albanians had been executed as
part of a strategy by Milosevic to keep NATO off balance by
developing a ``surge capability that he can sort of switch on and
off as he desires whenever he wants to start a new flood of
refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Kosovar refugees that Shea emphasized Tuesday
included the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ Near Orahovac, as many as 700 Albanian men were used as human
shields last week. The men were forced to stand in front of tanks
in the rain for two days with their hands tied behind their heads.
A few eventually escaped by paying the soldiers 10,000 German
marks, about $5,400.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Pec, Serbian forces had rounded up young Albanian women and
taken them to a hotel where the local Yugoslav commander apparently
has organized a roster of his soldiers to allow them all an evening
at the hotel with the women.
</P>
<P>
   _ During Serbian raids in some villages, young women have been
gang-raped in the homes or on the roadside by soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this will have to be investigated,'' Shea said. ``But
the reports are too numerous to suggest that these are completely
without foundation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
