<HEADER>
A6516 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTINGS-PREVENTION-     04-20 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTINGS-PREVENTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experts say some school crises can be avoided
 &HT;    By Ted Taylor
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Schools, if they would just take the
time, have the power to help stop
</P>
<P>
   school violence, two national experts on the subject said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty minutes a day is all it would take, said Scott Poland,
director of psychological services for the Cypress Fairbanks School
District in Houston, Texas, and an expert on school crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to take 30 minutes out of the school day to work on
problem solving, anger management and violence prevention,'' he
said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we'll have to lengthen the school day to do it. The
answers to youth violence are complex,'' he said, ``and we must
address it.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools also must concentrate on the three ``Ps'' to ensure a
safe learning environment, said Pamela Riley, executive director of
the Center for the Prevention of School Violence, based in Raleigh,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   While Riley concedes that incidents like Tuesday's shooting in
Littleton could happen anywhere, proactive measures to make sure
they don't can be taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools need to be actively involved in safe school planning
efforts,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   Riley, in a telephone interview from a Winston-Salem television
station, said a school's place, including the lighting and access
to school grounds, need to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make sure students feel safe. Sometimes metal
detectors or cameras are needed,'' she said. ``You need to make a
way to secure the physical environment of the school but not turn
the school into a
</P>
<P>
   prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley, a former high school principal, also said schools needed
to provide positive relationships within the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students must have a feeling of comfort or trust,'' she said.
``When a student hears of a threat or suspects something ... they
need to be able to feel like they can tell someone.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she said, the true purpose of schooling needs to be
readdressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of schooling is teaching and learning,'' she said,
``not drug dealing and bringing guns to school. ``We need to
provide educators with the opportunity to get back to the business
of education and let law enforcement do their job,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   School District 51 has taken a step in the right direction by
installing uniformed school resource officers in its buildings,
Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't always mean a school will be free of violence.
Columbine High School had not only a SRO, but video surveillance
cameras as well.
</P>
<P>
   This year has been a quiet year, Riley said, in terms of
schoolyard violence. The last incident similar to Tuesday happened
in May of last year when a 15-year-old shot and killed his parents
and two classmates
</P>
<P>
   in Springfield, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   The respite, albeit relatively short, Riley said, showed schools
were understanding the need to look further at safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools have addressed the issues,'' she said. ``But there are
no guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   The only guarantee, Poland said, is that Tuesday's massacre will
forever change those involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The school and community is going to be tortured by the why
and how this could have occurred,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Taylor writes for The Daily Sentinel, Grand Junction, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
