NYT-04-20-99 2151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 21:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6517 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NICHOLS-AWARD-2NDTAKE     04-20 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICHOLS-AWARD-2NDTAKE-$ADV25-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: Romanov prince.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And, over his seafood salad, Nichols rattles on with casual
eloquence about just about anything, from his favorite film (George
Stevens's ``Place in the Sun'') to his favorite ``Seinfeld'' (the
one where they are all lost in an endless parking garage) to the
entirely accidental way the seemingly perfect ending to ``The
Graduate'' evolved (a tribute more to the directorial unconscious
than brilliant foresight).
</P>
<P>
   There is, for example, his disquisition on the Big Soap Opera,
his term for the non-stop cavalcade of media extravaganzas that
have become the culture's leading form of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Soap Opera now exists in the space in which we used to
have, for want of a better word, art, fiction,'' he said. ``The Big
Soap Opera has appropriated metaphor, and one of its dangers is
that we tend to look at actual events as if they were a narrative.
Diana was heartbreaking, but it had such an effective, powerful
ending. The Senate investigation of Clinton took too long. I think
people in the polls were voting their irritation. Give us Monica as
the girl in the red velvet swing. That's what we have now. You hear
stories about Monica having had too many drinks at the Academy
Awards party and you think: `Right! That's it. That's the coda for
the story.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we have something we haven't had for a long time, a
chapter of The Big Soap Opera based on something that is actually
happening, which is Kosovo. Usually, what we have is journalism
masquerading as events. It seems to be the most important thing
that's happening but, of course, it's carefully chosen out of
hundreds of thousands of things as the most powerful metaphor
going. It makes it much harder if you deal with fiction and
metaphor in your work because it's tough to compete with.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols ran into that most painfully with ``Primary Colors,''
his film of Joe Klein's anonymous roman a clef about Bill Clinton's
presidential campaign. The movie received wonderful reviews, came
out, as if choreographed, at the grand opening of the Monica
Lewinsky episode, but flopped at the box office. Apparently people
got enough of the story free on television without having to go out
and buy movie tickets.
</P>
<P>
   He is asked whether his film career ever led him to ponder a
move to Los Angeles, a question he greets with a pained expression,
as if he had been asked to recall a particularly bad meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't,'' he said. ``There's a virus I have no protection
against if I'm there: How am I perceived? And you can do whatever
you like, put towels at the bottom of the door, not read the
trades, which I have not done for 35 years, if you're there long
enough, you will think, `But how am I perceived?' If you're
vulnerable to the virus, you've got to stay away from its matrix.''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't New York breed its own strain?
</P>
<P>
   ``New York is a shrug,'' he said with a shrug. ``The thing about
status is there is always someone higher. You can finally refine it
down to two or three people _ only the Agnellis and the Mellons are
really worthy _ but it has no real meaning. In New York there are
too many people, too many movies, too many theaters, too many
restaurants, too much sex for status to ever make a difference
except to a few people high up on Fifth Avenue who care about it.
But no one knows who they are, and no one cares about what they
care about.''
</P>
<P>
   This, no doubt, is easy to say when you are Mike Nichols, you
are married to Diane Sawyer, and you do so many things well (except
roller skate, says Ms. May). His friend Nora Ephron says that when
she watches Nichols act, which he has done occasionally over the
years _ most recently in ``The Designated Mourner'' _ she sometimes
worries that ``the greatest actor of our time has spent his career
as a director.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Nichols' place in the cinematic pecking order, it is hard
to be sure. A critical assessment might be that every Mike Nichols
film comes pre-certified for intelligence, wit and style, and few
directors have such a gift for getting performances out of actors.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for a would-be psychiatrist, Nichols' directing style is
like an elegant form of transference, where he schmoozes about his
own life and in the process invariably jars loose something in the
actors' experience.
</P>
<P>
   But Nichols made his biggest splash with his earliest films and
with ``Silkwood'' in 1983. And he has surely had his share of duds
too, like ``Day of the Dolphin,'' ``The Fortune,'' ``Wolf'' and,
most famously, ``Catch 22.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Among all the movies I've made, it's the one where I would
have done a number of things differently,'' he said of ``Catch
22.'' ``I would do it funnier, looser. I somehow found a style for
it that took care of the despairing and surrealistic aspects of it,
but discouraged the comedy.''
</P>
<P>
   But personally, he says he's happier than he has ever been. He,
as always, has movies ideas stacked up like jets over La Guardia
and says he's thinking for the first time in years of perhaps
directing some plays as well. His next film is ``What Planet Are
You From?'' starring Gary Shandling as an extra-terrestrial sent to
earth to impregnate a female human for world domination.
</P>
<P>
   After that is likely to be a remake of the 1949 Alec Guinness
classic ``Kind Hearts and Coronets,'' which he describes as a
comedy about a serial killer, being written by Ms. May and starring
Robin Williams.
</P>
<P>
   And he is producing the film of Cormac McCarthy's ``All the
Pretty Horses.'' So, with his New York shrug, he figures he has
better things to do than worry about where he stands in anyone's
film pantheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was directing Orson Welles in `Catch 22,' he once told
me, `All those questions about where we fit, who comes first and
who's second, leave that to them.' And when, very occasionally, in
the middle of the night, I start thinking along those lines, I
think: I'll never know. It's not important. It's nothing I can do
anything about. And whatever my answer is, it's completely
immaterial. Who was it that said: `I'm the bird. You're the
ornithologist.' That's my answer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
