<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY COMPANIES REBOUND FROM MONDAY'S SELLOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shares of technology companies rebounded in heavy
trading Tuesday after Monday's huge selloff, and investors were
seen moving out of economically sensitive cyclical stocks, like
industrial and oil companies, which have been rallying for a week
or more.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index, which is laden with technology
issues, recovered 64.03 points of its 138-point loss on Monday and
closed at 2,409.64, up 2.7 percent. And Thestreet.com's Internet
index, which fell 16 percent on Monday, jumped 35.14 points
Tuesday, or 6.3 percent, to 595.95.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, on the other hand, edged up
8.02 points, or less than one-tenth of a percent, to 10,448.55.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last week or so of trading created a lot of extremes,''
said Jonathan Olesky, head of block trading at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. ``The sharp decline in leadership stocks like technology
and rise in cyclical and value stocks created a short-term
overbought/oversold excess. Today, stocks that were most oversold
had a bounce, and stocks that were bought have had some
correction.''
</P>
<P>
   A sharp rebound in stocks like America Online, Microsoft and
Dell Computer helped to push the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
up 16.69 points, or 1.3 percent, to 1,306.17.
</P>
<P>
   Small stocks also staged a slight recovery. At the close, the
Russell 2000 index was up 2.93 points, or seven-tenths of a
percent, to 415.34.
</P>
<P>
   Volume was heavy, with 985.4 million shares changing hands on
the New York Stock Exchange. On the Nasdaq market, volume was 1.13
billion shares.
</P>
<P>
   The rebound in technology shares and the decline in cyclical and
value stocks did little to resolve debate about whether the
market's leaders have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday's selloff in technology was not so much of a top as it
was a correction in excesses,'' said Bryan Piskorowski, a market
analyst at Prudential Securities. ``Technology was priced for
perfection going into the earnings season and cyclicals suddenly
came out of the shadows.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which fell 6.5 percent on Monday, rebounded Tuesday,
rising 2 1/8, to 83 1/8. After the market closed, the software
giant reported earnings for its third quarter that were better than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks, which have also been battered lately, staged a
recovery Tuesday after Johnson &AMP; Johnson reported first-quarter
profits that exceeded Wall Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson &AMP; Johnson was the best-performing Dow stock, gaining 6,
to 96 1/4. Merck, another Dow component, gained 2 1/8, to 75 1/4.
And Abbott Labs rose 3 5/16, to 50 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of extreme price movement in
pharmaceuticals,'' Olesky said. ``All of it bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investors chose to take profits in economically
sensitive stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Mining and Manufacturing fell 2 5/8, to 81 5/8. Alcoa,
which is up more than 40 percent since the start of the year,
dropped 1 13/16 Tuesday, to 52 7/8. And big oil stocks like Exxon,
Royal Dutch Petroleum and Chevron all declined despite another rise
in spot oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Tuesday's pullback, ``I think you will see more strength
in these sorts of industrial stocks,'' said Richard McCabe, chief
market analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. ``A lot of these big stocks
have spent the last year or more going sideways.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks, which plunged on Monday, recovered some ground
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   America Online rose 12 13/16, to 128 11/16. Inktomi gained 26,
to 115, after analysts at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. put the stock on the
firm's ``recommend'' list. Doubleclick gained 24 3/16, to 128 3/16;
E-Trade rose 16, to 89 13/16, and Amazon.com rose 13 1/16, to 172.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
