<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT SAYS EARNINGS OUTDO EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sailing above the price wars that have battered personal
computer makers, Microsoft Corp. reported third-quarter earnings
Tuesday that exceeded Wall Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft reiterated warnings that growth could slow in coming
quarters if companies defer technology purchases because of the
Year 2000 problem. But company officials said sales to Asian
markets had recovered, partly because of increased spending by the
Japanese government. Sales in Latin America, particularly Mexico
and Brazil, remain depressed, they said.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended March 31, Microsoft reported earnings of
$1.92 billion, or 35 cents a diluted share, up 43 percent from
$1.34 billion, or 25 cents a share, in the period a year earlier.
Revenue rose 15 percent, to $4.33 billion from $3.77 billion. The
per-share figures reflect March's stock split.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Microsoft to earn 32 cents a share,
according to First Call Corp., which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Before the results were released, shares of Microsoft closed at
$83.125, up $2.125, and helped lead a rebound in technology issues
after Monday's broad selloff. But in after-hours trading, Microsoft
slipped to $82.
</P>
<P>
   Although the quarter did not have the kind of huge positive
surprise Microsoft has delivered in the past, analysts said it was
still a solid performance that should reassure technology investors
about the health of the overall computer market.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's results again appeared unaffected by the Justice
Department's antitrust suit, which is in recess. The company also
appeared not to suffer from the much-delayed shipment of Windows
2000 as sales of the current product, Windows NT 4.0, continued to
grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's consistent success has a bit of a monotony about
it,'' said David Readerman, an analyst with Thomas Weisel &AMP;
Partners. ``Despite being in a bit of a product drought, with
Office 2000 just shipping now and Windows 2000 maybe by the end of
the year, they continue to crank it out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The quarter's revenue does not include unearned revenue of $400
million related to Microsoft's Office 2000 Technology Guarantee, a
program that enables buyers of Office 97 to upgrade to the new
program. This revenue will be recognized in coming quarters.
Microsoft also realized investment gains of more than $350 million
during the quarter because of unspecified stock sales.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft chief financial officer Greg Maffei said in a
telephone interview that these two special items essentially
canceled each other out in terms of earnings per share.
</P>
<P>
   Maffei said the well-known problems of PC vendors like Compaq
Computer Corp. or IBM did not reflect weakening demand over all.
Microsoft, whose Windows 98 program runs on 90 percent of new
personal computers, saw a 29 percent increase in sales of operating
systems and applications preinstalled on new computers. Most of
this was due to increased PC shipments, but some was due to a shift
to Windows NT, which costs more, and more application sales, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to speak ill of our partners, but I think they had their
own operational ills in each case that do not speak to the overall
health of the market,'' Maffei said. ``A few highly visible guys
might have had less than stellar results, but I don't think that
speaks to overall demand. There was a lot of talk that the PC
market is in deep decline, but we didn't see that,'' he said.
Microsoft expects PC shipments to grow 16 percent to 17 percent, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft had forecast that revenue would decline by about $300
million from its second quarter; the company beat that forecast by
about $100 million. Looking forward, Maffei said Microsoft expected
fiscal fourth-quarter revenue to grow by about $500 million
compared with the third quarter, reflecting the release of Office
2000, which began shipping in April. That would correspond to
year-over-year revenue growth in the low to mid-20 percent range,
with earnings-per-share growth of about 40 percent, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
