<HEADLINE>
CHELIOS CHANGES HIS TUNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Much has been made of Chris Chelios' past battles with
Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne, but he went out of his way Tuesday
to praise the Anaheim standouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are two great players,'' he said. ``You try to contain
them, but they are going to get their opportunities. Everybody is
aware of them, you just do the best you can.
</P>
<P>
   Chelios, now of the Detroit Red Wings, did his share of hacking
and slashing at Kariya while a member of the Chicago Blackhawks,
but he couldn't say enough nice things about Kariya on the eve of
the series opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have all the respect in the world for him,'' Chelios said.
``He's a great player, a great ambassador for the game and
soft-spoken kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Chelios also insisted that he would be doing nothing out of the
ordinary to stop him, especially since the Ducks' power play is so
lethal and the two-referee system will be in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be real disciplined, you've got to play it by
the book.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Tough Ducks? Detroit winger Kris Draper has been quoted as
saying Kariya and Selanne don't like to be hit, but Red Wings
teammate Darren McCarty doesn't think they can be intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They battle in the corners for loose pucks, plus they are
tough to hit,'' he said. ``I think the best way to combat them is
to deny them the puck. If you try to run them, you'll just end up
taking a stupid penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg said his two offensive standouts
thrive on rough play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul and Teemu have played their best when it has been nasty
and intense,'' he said. ``I'm sure it's going to be like that, so
great.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit has great players and we are going to do our best to
hit and bang them, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya certainly didn't back down when asked about being hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy the physical part of the game; it gets me into the
game, gets me focused,'' said Kariya, who shattered his career high
in penalty minutes with 40 this season. ``They can think whatever
they want, it's a free country.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya was involved in a scuffle with San Jose's Alexander
Korolyuk last Saturday and the former Lady Byng winner (for
gentlemenly play) was called for roughing.
</P>
<P>
   Some were calling it his first fight, but when asked about that,
Chelios laughed and said, ``That was no fight.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Tally tandem: Selanne (107 points) and Kariya (101), finished
second and third in scoring behind Jaromir Jagr's 127.
</P>
<P>
   Fredrik Oluasson finished fourth in points by a defenseman with
56. His 16 goals was second to Al McInnis' 20.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks finished with three of the top four in power play
points. Selanne led the league with 54, while Kariya and Olausson
tied for third with 43. Selanne also led the league in power-play
goals (25).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
