<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO OPEN FIRE, THROW GRENADES IN COLO. SCHOOL; 25 MAY BE DEAD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.) (With COLO-SCHOOL-SCENE, COLO-SCHOOL-SUSPECTS) 
 (mb) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Two young men invaded a suburban high school
here at lunch time, killing as many as 25 people and wounding at
least another 20, authorities said. The two were later found dead
in the school library.
</P>
<P>
   Sowing mayhem, the gunmen threw grenades and shot students and
teachers as they moved through Columbine High School, beginning at
11:30 a.m., from the parking lot to the library and then to the
cafeteria. Students who saw them and escaped said one suspect was a
student and another was a dropout.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw two kids in trench coats with guns,'' said Chris
Weischer, a reference to a group of students that some students
called ``the trench coat mafia.'' Weischer was one of several
students freed by SWAT teams four hours after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   By early evening, FBI agents and police SWAT teams were still
moving through the school, searching for more victims and
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blood was going all over,'' one shaken girl said as she was
comforted by her father. Recalling the carnage in the school
library, she said, ``They were saying that they wanted Judas for
their revenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers brought out one young man in handcuffs, but a sheriff's
spokesman later said it was believed that he was a friend of the
gunmen and did not take part in the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   A sunny spring day turned into a nightmare as ambulances ferried
injured and dying students through this middle-class suburb
southwest of Denver past tennis courts, a baseball diamond and a
packed student parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so scared,'' Liza Madden, a 16-year-old sophomore, said
after making her escape. ``Every time I heard gun shots I was
crying. I was so scared.''
</P>
<P>
   After police used a fire truck and an armored car to get close
to the building, dozens of students raced from the two-story
building, some slipping in the mud, others holding up their hands
in the air. The police later said they feared that the shooters
would try to escape by mingling with the fleeing students.
</P>
<P>
   One bloodied youth, an arm hanging limply from his side, broke
out a window on the second floor and climbed down into the hands of
waiting police officers.
</P>
<P>
   As some of the hundreds of the law-enforcement officers who
responded to the carnage established a wide perimeter around the
school, stunned students and school workers gathered on nearby
streets and told of the chaos and horror.
</P>
<P>
   As fire alarms rang in the halls, students who had seen the
gunmen trampled each other to get out of the building, running
through one exit where three bodies lay on a staircase. Trapped
inside, others took refuge in classrooms, bathrooms and a choir
room, frantically barricading doors with desks and file cabinets.
</P>
<P>
   One cafeteria worker who barricaded herself in a bathroom said,
``We could hear them blowing the heck out of the place.''
</P>
<P>
   One student, Jonathan Ladd, said, ``I heard gunshots going off,
bullets ricocheting off lockers.''
</P>
<P>
   In a state with a relatively low crime rate, the siege after the
shootings was broadcast live by Denver television stations, without
commercial breaks all afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Several trapped students used cellular telephones to call
television stations when they could not get through to authorities
on 911.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear a couple of gunshots, people running up and down,'' a
student told KUSA, a Denver television station, in a frightened
whisper. Identifying himself only as James, he added ``There are a
bunch of kids downstairs, I can hear them crying.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware that the gunmen might be watching on a classroom
television set, he said, ``I am staying upstairs,'' then hung up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a cultural virus,'' Gov. Bill Owens said before going
to the school. The governor, who has a 16-year-old daughter who
attends a different high school in suburban Denver, said, ``We have
to ask ourselves what kind of children we are raising.''
</P>
<P>
   In mid-afternoon, the police briefly detained three youths in a
nearby park who were wearing camouflage pants and black jackets.
After they were released, the three said they knew the gunmen.
Emblazoned on the back of one man's jacket were the words, ``Ban
Religion'' and a stop sign printed over a cross.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were wearing masks, they were members of the `Trench Coat
Mafia,' '' said David Mesch, another student, who was searching for
his mother, an employee at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope the American people will be praying for the students,
the parents and the teachers,'' President Clinton said from the
White House as television images showed police officers training
shotguns on the school.
</P>
<P>
   Those here were reminded of other recent school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the seventh time it has happened,'' one student,
Bob Sapin, told a television station minutes after watching the two
gunmen shoot students. ``I just can't believe it is happening at my
school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
