<HEADLINE>
N.J. CONGRESSMAN LEAVES BELGRADE AFTER ``MYSTERY'' MISSION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.) (mk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Jim Saxton, R-N.J., left Yugoslavia Tuesday
after spending more than two days in Belgrade meeting with high
government officials on an unofficial mission whose purpose remains
a mystery to most of official Washington and even to some of his
staff.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief statement released Tuesday, Saxton described his trip
as a ``fact-finding mission,'' but declined to elaborate. ``It has
been an informative trip, but I am happy to be coming home,'' he
said in the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Official Yugoslav news agencies have reported that Saxton, who
is from Mount Holly in southern New Jersey and who arrived in
Belgrade on Sunday, met with the Yugoslav foreign minister and the
president of the foreign affairs committee of the Yugoslav
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The official newspaper Politika also reported that Saxton toured
areas where NATO bombs had damaged civilian property, and that he
was traveling with an aide, Joseph Bodansky. Saxton sits on the
House Armed Forces Committee and is chairman of the House Task
Force on Terrorism and Unconventional Warfare. Bodansky is an aide
on the task force.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Saxton said they could not confirm those reports.
Although Saxton has been in daily contact with them, they said he
had been unwilling to tell them details of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Washington said Saxton's trip had taken them by
surprise. One of the few officials Saxton consulted beforehand was
House Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, who advised him not to go, a
spokesman for the speaker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speaker cautioned him that this is very, very dangerous,
since we are bombing over there,'' the spokesman, John Feehery,
said. He added, ``We're pretty sketchy on all the details of the
trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Some congressional officials said they thought Saxton had gone
to Yugoslavia in hopes of negotiating the release of the three
American soldiers being held by Yugoslav forces. But Saxton's
spokesman denied that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congressman Saxton did not travel to Yugoslavia to secure or
negotiate the release of the POWs,'' said Jeff Sagnip Hollendonner,
the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Saxton's motivations, Hollendonner noted that
McGuire Air Force Base is in Saxton's district and would probably
send many military personnel to the Balkans if the conflict there
escalates.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not just airmen, they are constituents,''
Hollendonner said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
