<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6539 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-20 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: INSIDE GORE'S HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He says he's at the top of his game.
</P>
<P>
   Gimme a break.
</P>
<P>
   What does Bill Bradley have that I don't have? He's stiff. He's
wooden. He's plodding. He takes himself too seriously. He bores
people to death. He has zero personality.
</P>
<P>
   Fine. I can do that.
</P>
<P>
   He's much more of a snooze than I am. He's obsessed with taxes.
And CBS dumped him because they couldn't bear his windy
commentaries on values and the Cold War anymore. I, on the other
hand, can balance bats and spoons on my nose, and do the booty-call
line dance.
</P>
<P>
   He has a spot, too. You just can't see it, because he's such a
beanpole. Tipper doesn't find him a bit attractive.
</P>
<P>
   I am so ticked off. My polls are dropping faster than a pig out
of an F-117, as we used to say down on the farm. All of Clinton's
sex scandals are dragging down my numbers. He has the sweet tooth
and I get the cavity.
</P>
<P>
   Monica is no sooner over than we get buffeted by Juanita,
charges that the Chinese filched nuclear bomb technology, and that
inconvenient creep in Belgrade. Clinton is just a magnet for
trouble. Worse, I'm a magnet for Clinton's trouble. Even Tipper is
mad at him.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire and Iowa are exhausting enough. But now I have to
deal with the Kosovo primary. John McCain is winning that one.
While I'm schlepping to fund-raisers, McCain has suspended his
campaign during the Yugoslavia crisis and is getting more tube time
than I am. The only good news is that W. is losing the Kosovo
primary, too.
</P>
<P>
   But just when I can relax a little about W. because he's
bumbling around without any intelligent opinions about life outside
of Austin, I have to start worrying about Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   I was never supposed to go one-on-one with this guy. I thought I
had scared or charmed other Democrats out of the race. Bradley was
the only one I didn't target. So I miscalculated a little. But now
things are getting totally out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, people are falling in love with that goody-goody when
they're supposed to be falling in love with this goody-goody.
</P>
<P>
   I've been trying to schmooze the press lately, but all they do
is fawn over him. I've raised $8.9 mil and all the press can talk
about is Bradley's ``impressive'' $4.3 mil. I wanted to hurl at the
description of him in USA Today: ``A 6-foot-7 gentle giant slipping
in and out of roles as coach, author, interviewer, college prof and
Sunday school teacher ... this is what it would be like if Mr.
Rogers ran for president.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not Mr. Rogers! I'm Mr. Rogers!
</P>
<P>
   I'm sick of him poaching my stars and my turf. I get Dreamworks.
Then he gets Michael Eisner, JFK Jr. and Michael Jordan. I spend
years sweet-talking all those executives in Silicon Valley and they
give me a paltry $400,000. Then Bradley drops into San Francisco
and raises $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't that whole basketball hero thing getting pretty tired?
They didn't even have the three-point shot in his day. And he had
to wear those silly- looking short shorts. If I see another quote
from that old John McPhee New Yorker piece about what an amazing
athlete and role model he was, I'll set fire to the barn. Everybody
forgets that McPhee also wrote that ``He can't seem to resist
throwing a certain number of passes that are based on nothing but
theory and hope,'' and that he psyched himself for Princeton games
by listening to ``Climb Every Mountain.'' How corny can you get?
</P>
<P>
   Besides, I can shoot hoops, too. My St. Alban's yearbook called
me a ``basketball standout'' and said ``Al is frighteningly good at
many things.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Bradley was just another tired, burned-out
Beltway hack. Now everyone is oohing and aahing at his refreshing
new face.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's made ``trust'' his campaign code word. Subtle. OK,
maybe I exaggerated at the Rose Garden impeachment rally when I
blurted out that Clinton would ``be regarded in the history books
as one of our greatest presidents.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he's running on Big Serious Things, while I'm running on
Little Puny Things. He's talking about racial unity while I'm
talking about lost luggage. He's talking about child poverty while
I'm talking hot lines for local traffic congestion.
</P>
<P>
   He's wrong. I do have one really big idea: Bill Bradley should
get lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
