<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6540 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELECOM-NYT &LR;      04-20 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE GIANTS SAY MERGER HINGES ON ROLE OF GERMANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Telecom Italia and Deutsche Telekom tentatively agreed on
a merger pact Tuesday night to form the world's largest
telecommunications provider, but they said a final deal required
assurances that the German government abdicate its voting rights in
the combined company.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia's board, which met for a second consecutive day
to discuss the merger, said it ``approved in principle.''
</P>
<P>
   The approval came after Deutsche Telekom promised it would
support a Telecom Italia demand that the German government,
Deutsche Telekom's biggest shareholder, not interfere in the new
company's structure or management.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the Italian and German companies pushed the
merger one step forward toward formal approval. It put the ball
clearly in the court of the German government, which would retain
about a 45 percent stake in the new company.
</P>
<P>
   A Telecom Italia board member said a decision from the German
side could come as early as Wednesday, after which the merger would
be formally announced. The Telecom Italia board would then call a
shareholder meeting to approve the plan.
</P>
<P>
   A merger of Deutsche Telekom and Telecom Italia would create a
mammoth phone company, with a market capitalization of almost $180
billion, making it even larger than the planned merger of SBC
Communications and Ameritech, at $173 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear Tuesday night how the government of
Chancellor Gerhard Schroder would respond. German newspapers
reported Tuesday that Bonn was favorable to reducing its voting
rights in the planned company to match those of the Italian
government, which holds a 3.4 percent stake in Telecom Italia, and
to setting a schedule for divesting itself of the rest.
</P>
<P>
   A German Finance Ministry spokesman was quoted Tuesday night by
the Italian news agency ANSA as saying only that the government was
preparing a decision, which would require a vote of Deutsche
Telekom shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian government appears to support the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Massimo D'Alema, the Italian prime minister, discussed the
merger with Schroder in a phone call on Friday. Italian and German
finance ministers took time off from a meeting of European finance
ministers in Dresden, Germany, at the weekend to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is not without German critics. Uwe Jens, the economic
spokesman for Schroder's Social Democratic Party, was quoted
Tuesday as saying German antitrust officials should step in to
``stop this nonsensical movement.'' Executives of Mannesmann AG,
Deutsche Telekom's main domestic rival, have also criticized the
government for appearing to support it.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Deutsche Telekom said they had no way of knowing
how soon Bonn would respond. A Deutsche Telekom spokesman, Hans
Ehnert, said, ``We want the alliance, the merger.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to the merger discussions have said the merger
amounts to a Deutsche Telekom takeover of Telecom Italia that
values the Italian company at about 12 euros a share, which would
make the value of the deal about $95 billion. That would be the
biggest corporate takeover ever.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia, in a statement released after the board meeting,
said the plan was to create a combined holding company that would
swap its shares for common stock in Deutsche Telekom and for
Telecom Italia's ordinary and savings shares.
</P>
<P>
   It remained unclear whether the swap would include the shares in
Telecom Italia's mobile phone unit, Telecom Italia Mobile, but if
that were so, the deal would be worth roughly $106 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The board member who requested anonymity said that Deutsche
Telekom was expected to offer three of its shares for every one
Telecom Italia share, leaving Deutsche Telekom shareholders in
control of roughly 56 percent of the combined company. Shares in
the company would be quoted on the exchanges in Frankfurt, Milan
and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecom Italia board, in its statement, said it was
``essential that the terms be made clear under which the German
government will limit the exercise of its voting rights in the new
holding company,'' pending full divestiture of its shares. The
board also asked Telecom Italia's chief executive, Franco Bernabe,
to present an industrial plan for the proposed combined company.
</P>
<P>
   Bernabe has sought the merger with Deutsche Telekom to thwart a
hostile $65 billion takeover bid by the Italian company's chief
domestic rival, Olivetti SpA.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, the Italian government has been sensitive to the
idea that the merged company would be under German control, and
Italian officials have insisted the merger must be a partnership of
equals.
</P>
<P>
   The companies had originally scheduled a news conference for
Tuesday in London to announce the merger plan, but the board member
said no announcement would be forthcoming until the Italian board's
condition was met.
</P>
<P>
   The board member said the key issue in the discussions Monday
and Tuesday was the question of German government voting rights.
``In a sense, it's an artificial problem in a public company,'' he
said. Yet with the German government in control of 45 percent of
the company, ``the Italian government would have opposed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Though it is a minority shareholder in Telecom Italia, the
Italian government has a ``golden share'' that gives it veto rights
over any merger.
</P>
<P>
   The board did not specify what form a German assurance would
take, but the board member said it could be given as a written
guarantee or a withdrawal of Bonn representatives from the merged
company's supervisory board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
