<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6543 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCH-FIRES-NYT &LR;      04-20 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCH-FIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN IS INDICTED IN 10 CHURCH FIRES IN INDIANA AND GEORGIA, ONE IN
WHICH A FIREFIGHTER DIED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ind., Ga., Minn., Ohio)   (af)  
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Indiana drifter with a history of dabbling in Satanic rituals
was charged in dual federal indictments Tuesday with setting 10
church fires in Indiana and Georgia, including one last year in
which a firefighter died.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials from the National Church Arson Task Force,
which was established three years ago to investigate hundreds of
church blazes across the South and Midwest, said it was the largest
number of church burnings linked to one suspect since the task
force was formed.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, who said some of the church fires the task force
was looking into had been motivated by racism, said all the burned
churches in Indiana and Georgia linked to the man charged, Jay
Scott Ballinger, 36, were in predominantly white rural communities.
</P>
<P>
   Ballinger, who is white, confessed to federal agents in February
that he had set up to 50 church fires from 1994 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer in Indianapolis, Steven J. Riggs, said he was
defending Ballinger against the charges for setting seven fires in
Indiana and could not comment on other charges.
</P>
<P>
   Riggs said his client had suffered severe burns over 35 percent
to 40 percent of his body in a fire set in February. Ballinger has
undergone four skin grafts and is being held at the United States
medical center for federal prisoners in Rochester, Minn., the
lawyer said. The lawyer said that legal proceedings were on hold
until Ballinger was well enough to return to Indiana, which could
take up to three months.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have not decided where Ballinger, of Yorktown,
Ind., will be tried.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick J. Berarducci, a spokesman for the Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms, which is part of the task force, said
additional fires possibly set by Ballinger were under investigation
in more than 20 states.
</P>
<P>
   Richard H. Deane Jr., the United States attorney for the
northern district of Georgia, said no decision had been made on
whether to seek the death penalty for Ballinger in connection with
the death of a firefighter in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The firefighter, Kennon Loy Williams, 27, a volunteer, was
killed on New Year's Eve in 1998 when the burning roof of the New
Salem United Methodist Church in Commerce, Ga., collapsed on him.
Three other firefighters were injured in that blaze, which
Ballinger has been accused of setting.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum penalty Ballinger faces for his 7-count indictment
in Georgia is 50 years in prison, while the 12-count indictment in
Indiana carries a minimum of 90 years in prison. In addition, he
faces possible fines up to $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ballinger was apprehended after he failed to seek medical
treatment for two days for severe burns he received while trying to
set fire to a church in Brookville, Ohio, on Feb. 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A detective from the Ball State University police department
recognized Ballinger's name on the scanner when ambulances were
sent to his parents' home in Indiana. Ballinger was hospitalized
with severe burns on his face, chest, legs and hands, and said that
he had been injured in a bonfire.
</P>
<P>
   The officer knew that Ballinger was an arson suspect. The
officer went to the hospital and called federal investigators after
he discovered from Ballinger's father that his son had refused to
go to the hospital until Feb. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Scott D. McCart, an Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms agent, said in
an affidavit released Tuesday that a search of Ballinger's father's
house uncovered a new two-gallon plastic gasoline container with
some fuel in it that had been stored in a paper bag; Satanic
materials that included books, notes and writings, and credit card
slips that put Ballinger in the vicinity of church fires in various
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ballinger admitted to setting a total of approximately 30 to
50 church fires in Indiana and various other states,'' the
affidavit said.
</P>
<P>
   A motive for the fires remained unclear. Investigators said
Ballinger's girlfriend and another man have admitted taking part in
burning at least one Indiana church where they painted an
upside-down cross on the steps as a Satanic ritual.
</P>
<P>
   Ballinger's girlfriend, Angela Wood, 24, of Macon, Ga., and a
friend, Donald A. Puckett, 37, of Lebanon, Ind., have been arrested
but were not charged in the federal indictments.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal task force, which combines law-enforcement agencies
from the Departments of Justice and Treasury, has opened
investigations into 752 fires at churches since Jan. 1, 1995.
Law-enforcement agencies have arrested 331 people in connection
with 249 of those attacks, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A September report by the task force said federal, state and
local prosecutors have obtained convictions of 235 people connected
to 173 of the fires.
</P>
<P>
   Though some of the attacks have been motivated by racism, the
report said, the reasons behind the arson attacks ranged from
random vandalism to pyromania and even included neighborhood
disputes over parking. Most of the defendants were not members of
hate groups, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
