<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6542 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-WEISS-SHOOTING-CO     04-20 0243
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-WEISS-SHOOTING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Colorado resident Weiss kept abreast of shooting developments
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The family of Braves shortstop Walt Weiss lives in
the Denver suburb of Aurora, and two of his three children _
12-year-old Blake and 4-year-old Brody _ go to a private school
only a few miles from Columbine High School where Tuesday's tragedy
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss said his children's school was locked down and they were
sent home Tuesday. He spoke to his wife and children by telephone
several times during the day and watched news reports from the
Braves' clubhouse at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about literally close to home,'' said Weiss, who was just
home with his family when the Braves played the Colorado Rockies
this past weekend. ``All the streets they're naming, I've been on
those roads they're talking about. It's a perfect snapshot of
suburbia. Talk about a shocker. It's disturbing. It enrages me. It
makes me sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss said he always worries about his children, and this
incident intensifies that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sick world we live in,'' Weiss said. ``Obviously these
kids have problems. I don't think it's hard to see that. I don't
know the whole story, but these are kids with no value for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
