<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6546 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNGLASSES-COX     04-20 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNGLASSES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shades give students cool time on playground
 &HT;    By Chuck McGinness
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ Students now look hip when they hop, skip and
jump during gym class at Boca Raton Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   During the 40-minute period when they're out on the playground,
they get to wear neon-colored shades, the gift of a local bank
executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really fun having sunglasses,'' third-grader Charlene
Toussaint, 9, said Tuesday. ``My eyes don't turn red.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, things weren't so cheery on the school's
playground. The kids were quite lethargic playing in the hot sun,
physical education teacher Juanita Tiona said.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing steamier days were on the way, she came up with an idea.
</P>
<P>
   Tiona asked the school's business partner, Philip Friedly, vice
president of the local Washington Mutual bank branch, about
providing sunglasses for her students.
</P>
<P>
   Friedly came through with 30 pairs of shades with lenses that
block ultraviolet rays. Tiona keeps the sunglasses in a cardboard
box and passes them out at the start of each class.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're happier and willing to do more,'' said Tiona, who has
taught at Boca Raton Elementary for five years. ``They're not
giving me that `I don't like P.E.' look.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 40-minute class Tuesday, students did push-ups, ran
laps and practiced tennis strokes. No one's sunglasses fell off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're good,'' fifth-grader Chris Laporta, 11, said.
``You get to see better instead of squinting all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   A Palm Beach County school district spokesman said he didn't
know of any other school where students have a ready stash of
sunglasses for PE class.
</P>
<P>
   Friedly said he didn't blink twice when Tiona called.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things you never think about,'' he said.
``The kids needed sunglasses and I had no problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
   And the kids say it's cool to look fashionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like them because they come in red and that's my favorite
color,'' third-grader Jackie Pastor, 9, said.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck McGinness writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
