their family at a refugee camp near the border with Kosovo. When
Behrami crossed the border from Kosovo he had no idea he was
leaving one nightmare only to enter another. (Edward Keating/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) KUKES, Albania -- April 20, 1999 -- KOSOVO-FAMILY-4,
4-20 -- Ymer Behrami, left, and Aslan Hasani, flank a wagon used to
transport members of their family from Kosovo. The dimensions of
what is happening in Kosovo are almost incomprehensible. But in
each tractor and in every fearful face that comes across, there is
a wrenching drama. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MARINO, Albania -- April 20, 1999 -- KOSOVO-FAMILY-2,
4-20 -- A small wooden cradle, called a djep, is one of several
possessions hanging from a tractor being driven by Ymer Behrami
while he and his family head for a refugee camp in Kukes, Albania.
It was not that Behrami expected to need a djep, the youngest of
his 10 children is nine years old. But for Behrami, as for many
Kosovo families, the djep is a symbol of the future, wherever one
might be. ``If we left the djep, the Serbians would end up burning
it, just like they have destroyed everything else,'' said Behrami.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
