<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN MIGHT DH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ The Angels are trying to take the cautious approach
with first baseman Mo Vaughn, but it seems it would take an army to
keep him out of the lineup today, when he's eligible to return from
the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, who sprained his left ankle on opening night, is likely
to serve as the designated hitter in the final game of the series
against the Blue Jays, who play on artificial turf in SkyDome.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as I don't like to DH, I can't say I'm going to play
first base if I'm not capable of playing.'' he said. ``We'll see
what happens in the next couple of days. But the faster I get back
to first base, the stronger our lineup can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn did some running Tuesday for the first time since the
injury. He also took batting practice and fielded ground balls at
first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still limping, but I'm not known for my speed,'' he said.
``I'm going to have to play with some pain, that's just the way it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Expected exit: The loss of Jim Edmonds to shoulder surgery
took no one by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``(General manager) Bill (Bavasi) and I had running
conversations with Jimmy on a daily basis,'' Angels manager Terry
Collins said. ``We knew where he was coming from. It hurts, but
we'll do OK. Obviously we hoped to get him through the season. . .
. He's a great player, but someone else with pick up the slack,
because good teams do that.''
</P>
<P>
   With Edmonds out, Garret Anderson becomes the permanent center
fielder, although Collins said he has thought about putting Darin
Erstad in center and moving Anderson back to left.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rookie's a hit: Troy Glaus has gotten off to such a fast
start (.435, 3 HRs, 11 RBI through Monday) that other teams have
responded by pitching him inside. He was hit by a pitch against the
A's and then the Mariners hit him twice over the weekend. In the
span of four games, he was hit three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to throw me inside and I get hit, that's fine,''
Glaus said. ``It's not going to intimidate me or get me off the
plate. I got thrown at in high school, I got thrown at in college
and I got thrown at in the minor leagues. It's not something I've
never had to deal with. . . . It always surprises me, but it's not
going to change my approach, change what I do at the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Brawl benching? Collins said he expects Todd Greene to be
suspended for charging the mound in Sunday's game against the
Mariners. But Greene, who fought with Mariners pitcher Brett
Hinchliffe after Hinchliffe hit him with a pitch, said he isn't so
sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I should,'' he said. ``I was defending
myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0418 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-CLINTON-N     04-20 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, `SHOCKED AND SADDENED,' HOPES FOR PREVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (With COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING; skedded earlier as CLINTON) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A somber President Clinton said Tuesday night that
he was ``profoundly shocked and saddened'' by the school shooting
in Colorado, and he expressed the hope that the country would,
somehow, find ways to prevent future bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know yet all the hows or whys of this tragedy,''
Clinton said. ``Perhaps we may never fully understand it. St. Paul
reminds us that we all see things in this life through a glass
darkly, that we only partly understand what is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, his face flushed and eyes downcast as he spoke in
the White House briefing room, said he had asked Attorney General
Janet Reno; her top deputy, Eric Holder, and Education Secretary
Richard Riley to assist the stricken Colorado school system any way
they could.
</P>
<P>
   But otherwise, his brief appearance amounted to a shared
outpouring of grief and a call for prayer, rather than a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could say more tonight, but I don't think I can,''
Clinton said in response to questions.
</P>
<P>
   There will be time enough for analysis, he said, adding that
Tuesday night was a time for prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community is an open wound right now,'' the president said
of Littleton, Colo., the Denver suburb where the bloodshed
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had been in Littleton _ ``It's a wonderful place'' _
and that if such a thing could happen there, it could happen
anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Clinton expressed the hope that ``perhaps now
America would wake up to the dimensions of this challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   And minutes later, he remarked that ``there are a lot of kids
out there who have access to guns.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And apparently more than guns,'' the president added,
referring to early reports that the Colorado gunmen may have had
explosives as well as firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know that we must do more to reach out to our children
and teach them to express their anger and to resolve their
conflicts with words, not weapons,'' Clinton went on. ``And we do
know we have to do more to recognize the early warning signs that
are sent before children act violently.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said he had consoled officials in Colorado and had
spoken with Rep. Carolyn McCarthy, D-N.Y., whose husband was one of
several people shot to death by a gunman on a Long Island Rail Road
train in 1993. He did not discuss the substance of their telephone
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who in the past year has made school safety a priority
and who organized a White House conference on the subject last
fall, seemed to express the anguish and frustration of his
countrymen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only say tonight that the prayers of the American people
are with you,'' he said to the citizens of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The president said he did not want to use the word ``epidemic''
in describing Tuesday's killings and similar spates of violence in
schools and on the streets. But in promising that the federal
government would help any way it could, he said, ``We do have, from
bitter and sad experience, a great cadre of grief counselors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
