<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6564 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-BRADLEY-NYT     04-20 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-BRADLEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY, IN FIRST OF ISSUES TALKS, TURNS TO DIALLO SHOOTING AND
RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Invoking the Amadou Diallo shooting as evidence of
persistent racial discord in America, former Sen. Bill Bradley said
Tuesday that he would make the ``quest for racial unity'' a central
pillar of his White House if he was elected president. Bradley
called racism the ``defining moral issue of our time'' and pledged
to raise the subject regularly as he seeks the Democratic
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ronald Reagan was president, everyone knew that if you
wanted to please the boss, you talked about cutting taxes,
increasing military spending and fighting communism,'' said
Bradley. ``If I'm president, I want one thing to be known: If you
want to please the boss, one of the things you'd better show is how
your department or agency has furthered tolerance and racial
understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who is competing for the nomination against Vice
President Al Gore, chose Manhattan to give what his organization
described as the first in a series of major addresses on what he
believes will be issues crucial to the campaign. Race is an issue
with which Bradley has regularly identified himself during his
career, and he returned to it Tuesday by invoking February's fatal
shooting of Diallo, an unarmed West African immigrant, by four
white New York City police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley described the shooting as ``an extreme example of the
targeting that most African-Americans have experienced with the
police at some time in their lives.'' He deplored the response of
public officials, describing it as the loss of an opportunity to
confront the relations between the police and minorities, and to
help whites understand what he described as ``the white-skin
privilege.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is a Diallo-like event a potential catalyst, not just toward
police reform but toward deeper understanding?'' Bradley said,
speaking before students and television cameras at Cooper Union.
``Why can't this stark tragedy come across in a compelling enough
way to open the eyes of all of us today, just like the church
explosion in Birmingham did 36 years ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why doesn't some public official ask our schoolchildren to
observe the tragedy with a moment of silence in memory of another
life lost to senseless violence and tell all of us that if we want
to, we can change our lives, our relationship, our communities, for
the better?''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's speech opened a phase of his campaign in which, his
aides said, he will try to present himself, with a series of policy
addresses, as more substantial than Gore, who has so far run a
relatively unadventurous campaign. Democrats across the nation have
awaited these speeches to see whether Bradley, who has a reputation
for being stronger at articulating problems than at offering
solutions, will begin to flesh out his own White House agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But during his 44-minute speech Tuesday, Bradley offered no
programs to promote racial unity. He also largely avoided
discussion of affirmative action, and strongly suggested that most
of the remedies that could be applied by law or the courts had
already been undertaken.
</P>
<P>
   He signaled instead that much of his response to dealing with
racism would be exhortation, an approach he displayed for his young
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you care about race?'' he asked the students, peering up
over his glasses. ``If you do, then do something about it. Start
with your life and the life of a friend. Go from there to your
parents, your dorm, your club, your team and more friends. Make
racial unity a part of your being.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley urged his listeners to ``take this issue and find a way
of making it yours _ of blowing away the acrid odor of racism as
well as the stultifying pessimism that nothing will change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are on the eve of the 21st century,'' he said. ``Let us
affirm that when we get to its third decade, or maybe even the
second decade, the racial divisions of America will be mended.
Pledge that it will be your generation that will put those stupid
attitudes behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley noted changing demographics that will make the nation
increasingly diverse. In 2010, he said, fewer than 60 percent of
people entering the work force will be native-born white Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The need for racial healing should be a common-sense
impulse,'' he said. ``But if morality doesn't bring you to the
table with enthusiasm, how about self-interest?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
