<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6566 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCHOOL-SHOOTI     04-20 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CHALLENGES NATION TO HELP PREVENT SCHOOL VIOLENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c. 1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, confronted with another gruesome
school shooting, called Tuesday for ``a candid assessment'' of
steps the nation can take to prevent classroom violence.
</P>
<P>
   In nationally broadcast remarks from the White House, Clinton
said the ``hows or whys'' of the tragedy in Littleton, Colo., may
never be known, but added:
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know that we must do more to reach out to our children
and teach them to express their anger and to resolve their
conflicts with words, not weapons. And we do know we have to do
more to recognize the early warning signs that are sent before
children act violently.''
</P>
<P>
   After his comments, the White House announced Clinton had called
off his Wednesday trip to Texas, where he was to speak at the
opening of the new Austin airport and attend Democratic
fund-raising events in the state capital and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the tragic circumstances in Colorado, the president
thought it was best to cancel,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart
said in a statement Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a number of school shootings, including one in
March 1988 at Jonesboro in his native Arkansas, Clinton convened a
White House conference on classroom safety last October.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the administration announced it would award
more than $300 million to 50 communities to improve school safety,
including programs to combat violence, drugs and destructive
students.
</P>
<P>
   As the investigation in Littleton began, Clinton said there are
additional proposals he had in mind to fight school violence, but
he did not detail them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, I think the American people ought to be thinking
about those folks in Littleton,'' he said, calling the community
south of Denver ``an open wound right now.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow and in the days ahead, we'll have a little more time
to kind of gather ourselves and our determination and go back at
this again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that as the families in Littleton grieve and the
facts of the incident are gathered, ``the rest of us have a
responsibility to do everything we can to make sure this doesn't
make 1999 a year like last year, that we don't have another rash of
this, that we really can be more effective in preventing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton turned aside a reporter's suggestion that there may be
an ``epidemic'' of school violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I would like to know is whether we can learn enough from
this, which in its dimensions apparently is much greater than even
the others were, and see what else we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing a report prepared for the White House conference,
Education Secretary Richard Riley said that ``the vast majority of
America's schools are still among the safest places for youngsters
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Tuesday that ``statistically, for all the whole 53
million kids in our schools, it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But, you know, from the facts we're hearing about what
happened at this school, and the possibility that explosives were
out there, that hand grenades were available, that other things
were there, it obviously wasn't true there.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was obviously the most dangerous place in Colorado
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference resulted in an ``early-warning guide'' to help
educators and parents spot potentially violent students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you know that there are a lot of kids out there who
have access to weapons, and apparently more than guns'' in the
Littleton incident, Clinton said. Some young people, he said,
``build up these grievances in their own mind and ... are not being
reached. And it's not just Littleton. We know that now. We've had
lots and lots and lots of places.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said he had asked Attorney General Janet Reno and
Education Secretary Riley ``to stand ready to assist local law
enforcement, the schools, the families, the entire community during
this time of crisis and sorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
