<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0422 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6570 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EVERGLADES-FIRE-COX     04-20 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-FIRE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Everglades fire sparks greater anti-arson battle
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore and Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTON, Fla. _ As weary foresters finally contained a four-day
fire that streaked across the Everglades, devouring 155,000 acres
and turning skies a dirty brown with acrid smoke and ash, the state
hatched a tough new strategy to hunt down and punish the arsonists
causing much of the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush doubled the reward for arson tips to $10,000 after
learning many of the fires were deliberately set by teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people responsible for starting these fires need to be
held accountable,'' Bush said. ``In some cases, parents may be
ordered to pay for damages.''
</P>
<P>
   Mindful that the fire season is barely under way, and Florida's
battle may have just begun, Bush dumped an extra $5.6 million in
emergency money into the fire fight _ more than a half million for
arson investigation alone.
</P>
<P>
   From Apalachicola National Forest to the Everglades, in parched
forests and brittle scrub, more than two dozen fresh fires erupted
over the last two days. But while conditions remain dire, the
monster Everglades fire _ this year's largest _ was successfully
trapped by roads, levees and backfires, the Division of Forestry
said. Once back-burning is complete, foresters estimate 175,000
acres of saw grass will have burned, down from the 45,000 they
predicted Monday.
</P>
<P>
   There was good news for motorists, too. The Florida Highway
Patrol reopened Interstate 75, the state's main coast-to-coast
highway, after closing it Saturday when fires dropped a curtain of
smoke and made driving dangerous. For three days, truckers and
other motorists have had to take a circuitous detour, snaking
around southern Broward County via U.S. 27 to the Tamiami Trail.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, more than 2,500 fires have burned more than 230,000
acres this year. Forestry officials expect erratic winds and dry
weather to remain for several more days, making new fires quick to
start and difficult to fight. In Port St. Lucie, where ferocious
blazes whipped by 30 mph gusts of wind destroyed 42 homes Thursday,
officials worry they could be hit again.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as simple as someone tossing a cigarette butt out of the
window and we could have another incident like last Thursday,''
said St. Lucie County Fire District spokesman Ron Parrish.
</P>
<P>
   Months ago, foresters warned that this year could bring fires
even worse than last summer, when blazes devoured 500,000 acres and
damaged or destroyed 370 buildings. A single firestorm forced the
evacuation of Flagler County.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the La Nia weather phenomenon rising out of the
Pacific, the state has endured desert-like conditions since
February. Temperatures have also run higher than normal, further
baking and drying forests and underbrush.
</P>
<P>
   Before the fires cranked up, Bush slashed $30 million out of
Agriculture Commissioner Bob Crawford's budget. Crawford's
department includes the Division of Forestry.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, Bush was in a fighting mood. He said he has
``started the conversation'' with advisers about a fireworks ban
and wants to throw another $555,000 into the fight against wildfire
arson.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators suspect up to 35 percent of the state's fires have
been the work of arsonists; 12 of 13 arson arrests in the past
three weeks have been of juveniles. More than 100 other cases are
under investigation, Florida Department of Law Enforcement
Commissioner Tim Moore said.
</P>
<P>
   Moore's agency is assisting 36 arson investigators from the
Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a hard enough time dealing with Mother Nature,''
Crawford said. ``It's frustrating that some of the fires are being
caused intentionally.''
</P>
<P>
   FDLE added a $5,000 reward to a similar one offered by the
Florida Forestry Arson Alert Association, bringing the total to
$10,000. State officials urged anyone with information to call the
arson hotline at (800) 342-5869.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a prank or a joke,'' Moore said. ``It's a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who willfully starts a fire that damages a building with
someone inside would be guilty of a first-degree felony, punishable
by up to 30 years in prison. Juveniles as young as 14 can be
punished as adults for arson, and state courts can order parents to
make restitution.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the state will spend $1.2 million to lease a mammoth
Sikorsky helicopter for 20 days. The helicopter carries a
2,200-gallon water tank for aerial dousing. The state is also
paying for another 10 days' use of a Fire Hawk helicopter with an
800-gallon bucket.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters and rangers will also get improved communication
equipment and 1,000 lightweight protective suits better suited for
fighting fires in Florida's brutal heat.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after Bush announced his arson crackdown, foresters
said someone sparked a new blaze near the northeast corner of the
Everglades fire. Worse, the fire was set across a levee rangers had
been using as a fire barrier. Witnesses told rangers they saw a
black Ford Explorer leave the area just before they saw the fire
spring up. However, with winds considerably calmer and the humidity
slightly up, rangers were able to contain it, said Division of
Forestry forester Erin Albury.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, another section of the Everglades fire burned
within a few miles of the Seminole Tribe's Big Cypress reservation,
where 300 Seminoles live. Tribal firefighters set their own
backfires to protect against the advancing flames. Late Tuesday,
the fire did not appear to pose a serious threat.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the area remains particularly volatile, especially with
I-75, also called Alligator Alley, open and carrying thousands of
motorists who could carelessly ignite a blaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here certainly shouldn't let their guard down,'' Albury
said. ``The fire situation is extremely dangerous. A cigarette,
match, spark from a catalytic converter, you name it, any kind of
ignition device.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elmore and Jenny Staletovich writes for the Palm Beach
Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
