<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO STUDENTS KILL 25, WOUND 20 IN COLORADO HIGH SCHOOL ATTACK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
and KIM COBB 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Two students, throwing explosives and firing
automatic weapons &UR; , &LR;  stormed a high school here Tuesday, killing as
many as 25 and wounding 20 as they hunted students hiding under
furniture and in classrooms. The gunmen killed themselves as SWAT
teams moved in.
</P>
<P>
   A third suspect was led from the suburban Denver school,
Columbine High School, in handcuffs. Police said he was an
``associate,'' and was not charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just shooting,'' said one student who escaped.
``They didn't care who they shot. They were just shooting. We
didn't think it was real and then we saw blood.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack, which began at 11:30 a.m. CST, dragged out for more
than four hours, moving from the school parking lot to the
hallways, into the cafeteria and finally to the library, where the
dead gunmen, one identified as a junior, were found.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers, dressed in black trench coats, sprayed lockers
and hallways with gunfire and threw bombs as students broke for the
exits. As the ordeal continued into the afternoon, one wounded
student was pushed through a smashed second floor window to waiting
SWAT officers. Many of the school's 1,870 students were trapped in
classrooms and the cafeteria. Ten to 15 bodies were found in the
library with the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first we thought it was fireworks, then we saw them
shooting,'' sophomore Jake Apoeaca said. ``He saw us and then he
started shooting at us. Then a guy in a white T-shirt threw two
hand grenades on the roof. We hit the ground and then we started
running.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 police surrounded the large school and went
classroom by classroom to rescue students, some of whom used their
cellular telephones to call family and officials from their hiding
places.
</P>
<P>
   Police said bombs were found inside and outside the school and
also at the house of one of the dead gunmen. A police spokesman
said a detonator was found on the body of one of the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   As evening fell, FBI agents and police were still moving through
the school, searching for victims and explosives, and the bodies
had not been removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just going to take us some time because of how many rooms
we have bodies in,'' Jefferson County Sheriff's spokesman Steve
Davis said late Tuesday. ``We still have a SWAT team in the
building going into the attic, the crawl spaces, everywhere.'' He
said the pair had a large amount of ammunition and police were
searching for live bombs before moving the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone said 25 people may have been
killed, but it was not immediately known whether they were all
students or teachers and what the motive might have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears to be a suicide mission,'' Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   Some students blamed the shooting on eight to 10 students in the
school who wear black trench coats every day and are known as the
``Trench Coat Mafia.'' But it was not clear whether they were
involved in the shooting. Other students said athletes and
minorities had been targeted.
</P>
<P>
   Student Bob Sapin said the gunmen were all in black, in trench
coats and masks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They walked down the stairs and they started shooting
people,'' said another student who gave her name as Janine.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were shooting people and throwing grenades and stuff,''
she said. ``Me and my friends got to my car and drove off. We saw
three people get shot. They were just shooting. Then something blew
up.''
</P>
<P>
   During the SWAT search, three youths wearing black were stopped
by police in a field near the school. The Colorado Bureau of
Investigation said the three were friends of the gunmen who were
being taken in for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   The attack was the most recent and the worst in a series of
school shootings in the United States. Since 1997, children and
teachers have been killed in Pearl, Miss., three at West Paducah,
Ky., five at Jonesboro, Ark., and two in Springfield, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   A somber President Clinton, in two statements after the
shooting, asked the nation to pray for the victims and called for a
``candid assessment'' of steps the nation can take to prevent such
violence. He also canceled his Texas trip, which was to bring him
to Houston today for a fund raiser.
</P>
<P>
   The scene outside the school Tuesday, broadcast on national
television in fitful tragic snatches, swung from tragedy to relief
to tragedy. At nearby Clement Park, students were shaking and
crying as parents wandered about, looking for their children.
Police helicopters whirled overhead and hundreds of officers
patrolled the area.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty people were taken to hospitals, including a girl who
suffered nine shrapnel wounds to the chest and the student passed
from the second story window to rescuers.
</P>
<P>
   Kari Mackecher, spokesman for HealthOne, which runs Swedish
Medical Center, said five students were taken there, all in serious
condition but conscious.
</P>
<P>
   Five other hospitals reported getting 15 people, at least one of
them in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   Littleton, population 35,000, is southwest of Denver.
Single-family homes line winding roads through the school
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening, parents, students and community members
gathered at a nearby Catholic church to talk about the tragedy.
Hundreds showed up with drivers parking wherever they could. People
milled about, not really knowing what to say or do. Many families
sought out grief counselors who attended from local organizations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
