<SLUG> BC-LAWSUIT-SWEEPSTAKES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON STATE SUES THREE SWEEPSTAKES COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE HADLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Washington State Attorney General Christine Gregoire
announced lawsuits Tuesday against the nation's three largest
sweepstakes companies, saying their promotions have become
blatantly deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers, especially the elderly, are being duped into buying
products they don't need or want on the false promise that they
have a good chance of winning a large prize, Gregoire said.
</P>
<P>
   The suits were filed in King County Superior Court in Seattle
against Publishers Clearinghouse Inc., American Family Enterprises
Inc., also known as American Family Publishers, and Time Inc., also
known as Guaranteed and Bonded. Company officials could not be
reached for comment on the lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Also sued were celebrities Ed McMahon and Dick Clark, who
promote the American Family Publishers sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   Gregoire said many people have a hard time taking the
sweepstakes seriously as a scam because they throw them away
without reading them. But for many others, especially the elderly,
they are effective.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, at least 10 Washington state consumers spent more than
$10,000 each ordering merchandise _ including magazines, watches
and coins _ to increase their chances of winning a large
sweepstakes prize, Gregoire said. And 450 Washington residents
spent more than $2,500 each in one year on sweepstakes merchandise,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dreadful deceptions by these companies are tragically
effective,'' Gregoire said. ``Many seniors are absolutely convinced
they will win millions.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, their chances of winning the Publisher's Clearinghouse
prize are 1 in 200 million, Gregoire said. Their chances of winning
the Guaranteed and Bonded sweepstakes are 1 in 120 million, the
lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   An 80-year-old Bellingham, Wash. woman spent half her monthly
Social Security check on sweepstakes, Gregoire said. A Spokane
woman was so convinced that she had won that she baked a cake and
put a banner sent by the sweepstakes company in her front yard. The
banner said: ``Prize Patrol Stop Here.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit against Publishers Clearinghouse accused the company of
specifically targeting the elderly, the first time the state has
ever filed a specific charge of that kind, Gregoire said. The
company has said that 30 percent of the people who buy its products
are older than 65. That's double the percentage of that group in
the general population.
</P>
<P>
   The sweepstakes promotions from American Family Publishers and
Publishers Clearinghouse use personalized messages to imply a
personal relationship or interest, the suits say. All three
companies use official-looking documents designed to convince
consumers that the companies are endorsed or approved by the
government, the suits say.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuits, the companies misrepresent that
consumers have won a prize and also falsely imply that consumers
have an improved chance of winning by making a purchase, which is
illegal. The process for entering the Publishers Clearinghouse and
the Guaranteed and Bonded sweepstakes without making a purchase is
improperly cumbersome, the suits alleged.
</P>
<P>
   The mailers of all three companies also create a false sense of
urgency to respond, Gregoire said.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional testimony indicates that one company sent as many
as 144 separate mailers in one year to some consumers who responded
to the first mailer, Gregoire said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is nothing more than predatory conduct by these
companies,'' Gregoire said. Besides the elderly, they also prey on
the lonely and people without much money who dream of winning the
large prize.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits ask the court to stop the companies from continuing
their deceitful conduct, ask for $2,000 in fines for each
violation, and ask that the companies be made to pay restitution to
consumers harmed by the sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The penalties could be in the millions of dollars,'' Gregoire
said.
</P>
<P>
   The suits were brought under the state's Promotional Advertising
of Prizes Act and the state's Consumer Protection Act. Three other
states _ Connecticut, Wisconsin and Indiana _ sued the companies
under their laws earlier this year, Gregoire said. And attorney
generals of 40 states are engaged in conference calls about the
companies, presaging more lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Washington and 30 other states entered into an ``assurance of
discontinuance'' agreement with American Family Enterprises last
year, but despite agreeing to alter its conduct, the company has
made few changes in its mailings, Gregoire said.
</P>
<P>
   The state wants the companies to prominently display the odds of
winning, quit telling people they've won prizes when they haven't,
quit mimicking government documents, stop implying an urgent need
to act, and to stop implying that consumers would improve their
chances of winning by buying a product.
</P>
<P>
   Gregoire showed one Guaranteed and Bonded sweepstakes promotion
that she herself received that told her she had won $833,337 in
cash. Gregoire said she read the promotion carefully and then
showed it to her husband. They both concluded that the mailing was
definitely telling her she had won the money.
</P>
<P>
   Omak, Wash., attorney Richard Price is one of more than two
dozen attorneys nationwide who have filed suit against American
Family Enterprises, essentially alleging the sweepstakes mailer
told their clients they had won $11 million and the company must
now pay the money.
</P>
<P>
   Price said yesterday his 91-year-old client, a well-respected
Omak orchardist, responded to seven or eight mailers in a row. The
mailers strongly implied that he had won. One of the final ones
told him he had definitely won $11 million, Price said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to stop these guys is to make them start paying
out on these outlandish statements,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed in Okanogan Superior Court, but American
Family Enterprises had it moved to federal court in Spokane. It was
then consolidated with a number of other similar lawsuits filed
around the country and moved to federal court in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Brighton, a North Seattle resident, said his wife Helen
was spending $500 a month buying products from the sweepstakes
companies. He started noticing when their basement began to fill
with junk, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple finally called Publisher's Clearinghouse to try to
get the company to stop sending the mailers, but it was difficult
to get them stopped, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife was waiting for the armored truck to pull up in front
of the house to give us all this money,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sweepstakes have been operating for many years. Asked why
the states are only now filing suit, state Assistant Attorney
General Regina Cullen said, ``It's been a gradual buildup over
time. The language has just gotten more and more egregious. The
come-ons are more blatant, and the disclosures are smaller and
smaller. They're pushing the envelope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
