<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6688 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADCLIFFE-HARVARD-ART     04-20 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADCLIFFE-HARVARD-ART-850&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RADCLIFFE PACKING UP AND GOING TO HARVARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ After more than 100 years of arm's-length
interaction between the his-and-hers institutions at the pinnacle
of academic prestige, Radcliffe College has agreed to be fully
absorbed into Harvard University, officials announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Radcliffe, which lost much of its initial mission as a women's
annex when Harvard turned fully coeducational in the 1970s, is to
be renamed the Radcliffe Institute for Advanced Study and expand
its study of women and gender, among other subjects, bolstered by
an infusion of $150 million from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   But the change in Radcliffe's status means it will give up its
vestigial claims on undergraduate women at Harvard _ it had still,
technically, accepted their applications and put its seal on their
diplomas, even though they studied at Harvard _ and act as a center
for scholarship much like a similar institute at Princeton
University, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The move also carried heavy symbolic weight. An institution long
known as one of the world's foremost educators of women is to merge
into the formerly all-male bastion with which it has had a close
but often-fractious partnership.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part of the negotiations on the merger, said
Nancy-Beth Gordon Sheerr, chairman of the soon-to-be-dissolved
Radcliffe College Board of Trustees, was ``weighing the tremendous
opportunities of moving in this direction against the meaningful
nature of independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by a sprinkling of initial reactions, current Harvard
women and Radcliffe alumnae greeted the news of the merger with
tentative approval tinged by an undertone of concern that programs
for women might suffer. Officials of the Radcliffe College Alumnae
Association said that though they had not met formally yet to vet
the decision, it has their ``qualified support.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's tremendous potential here and I'm excited
about the possibilities,'' said Susan Eaton, secretary of the
association. ``It's probably time for the study of women to be
fully integrated into Harvard's mission, and that's what I hope the
Radcliffe Institute will be able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time,'' Ms. Eaton said, ``I can't help feeling a
sense of loss. It's been a very important institution in the lives
of generations of women, not just those who had the good fortune to
attend here but those who benefited from the presence of others
here.''
</P>
<P>
   At Harvard Tuesday, Alyssa Glass, a senior in computer science,
said she had had little contact with Radcliffe and had always found
it ``kind of insulting to know that I'm not considered the same
type of Harvard student as my male counterparts.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Glass said, she supported the merger only ``as long
as the sorts of programs that are out there from Radcliffe, such as
the mentorship program, are maintained by Harvard in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate for those to be lost because Harvard doesn't see that
as much of a priority anymore,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard is not talking about cutting Radcliffe programs, but
rather about increasing its scholarly wattage with some of the cash
that a university with an endowment of about $12 billion can afford
to transfer into its newest division.
</P>
<P>
   Radcliffe's new incarnation will have the resources to become a
center for advanced scholarship the likes of which there are only
two or three in the world, Dr. Neil L. Rudenstine, president of
Harvard, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are creating something rare,'' Rudenstine said.
</P>
<P>
   The president of Radcliffe, Dr. Linda S. Wilson, who announced
Tuesday that she would be resigning after 10 years in the post,
said, ``We do not see this as giving up anything for the students
or anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what would happen to Radcliffe's identity, now that it was
merging with Harvard, Wilson responded that it was ``clearly a
legacy we bring with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement in principle, which is not expected to be
formalized for months, Radcliffe will have a dean rather than a
president, who will be appointed by the president of Harvard in
consultation with a Harvard-Radcliffe committee. The dean will
participate in major Harvard decisions just like the deans of the
medical school, the law school and other Harvard faculties; in
essence, Rudenstine said, Radcliffe's position will be comparable
to those other schools within Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, Radcliffe becomes part of Harvard, and its assets,
including an endowment of about $200 million and some choice
Cambridge real estate, become Harvard's. But Harvard contributes
$150 million to Radcliffe, and previous contributions made
specifically to Radcliffe remain within Radcliffe's purview.
Rudenstine said he doubted that the move would lead to great
savings in administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement ended months of rumors that Harvard was
planning to somehow swallow Radcliffe, talk that played upon the
nerves of many Radcliffe alumnae with deep emotional ties to their
alma mater and still-vivid memories of how women were openly
dismissed, excluded and disrespected here in the bad old days.
</P>
<P>
   Many have kept up the pressure on Harvard to keep improving its
treatment of women, including a group of Radcliffe alumnae who put
their contributions to Harvard's capital campaign in escrow until
the university improved its record of hiring and awarding tenure to
women. About 12 percent of Harvard's tenured professors are women.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen what effect the merger will have on
fund-raising. Rudenstine said Harvard would seek aggressively to
raise more money for the new Radcliffe institute, since such
centers for advanced study get no tuition revenue.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For him, Rudenstine said, the hardest part of the merger
negotiations was finding a way to both honor Radcliffe and make a
``clean break'' with its independent past, because ``anything less
than a clean break would have left so much ambiguity.''
</P>
<P>
   Ambiguity has characterized much about Radcliffe's relations
with Harvard ever since the college signed an agreement with
Harvard in 1977 that effectively handed over all responsibility for
educating college women to Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Radcliffe has offered mentorships, internships,
social action and arts programs and the like, all particularly
geared toward women, and guaranteed women ``a yard of their own.''
It has also developed highly respected scholarship and seminar
programs, from the Schlesinger Library, considered by many to be
the foremost American library on the history of women, to the
Bunting Institute, a center for women fellows from various
disciplines, to the Radcliffe Public Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   But it has not, by most definitions, been exactly a college. So
to some extent, Tuesday's announcement merely formalized changes
that happened long ago. And the absorption by Harvard, too, seemed
logical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've cherished a child that we're now sending out into the
large world, I think,'' Mrs. Gordon Sheerr said.
</P>
<P>
   For some, however, concerns lingered over how the loss of
independence for Radcliffe, an institution founded and run by and
for women, would affect Harvard women.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an environment that's overwhelmingly male and doesn't have
a high percentage of tenured women,'' said Joanna B. Strauss, an
alumna and clinical social worker, ``will there be enough force
left to pay more than lip service to the particular needs of women
in education?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
