<DOCNO> NYT19990420.0433 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 23:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6681 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDREN-FOUND-DEAD-C     04-20 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-FOUND-DEAD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investivators wait for autopsy results in child killings
 &HT;    By Jason Spencer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUTTO, Texas _ A small boy and girl believed murdered and dumped
while still wearing their diapers in a shallow Williamson County
creek remained unidentified Tuesday as investigators fielded calls
from law enforcement agencies and worried parents from around the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Results of autopsies being performed by the Tarrant County
medical examiner in Fort Worth were not available late Tuesday,
leaving investigators wondering how the children, who may be
siblings, wound up in Brushy Creek south of Hutto Monday afternoon.
The boy and girl had been in the creek for a matter of hours before
a Round Rock couple having a picnic found their bodies near County
Road 137, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday was one of the saddest days of my career,'' said
Hutto Police Chief Richard Miller, who was one of the first
officers at the scene Monday. ``It makes me wonder why I'm doing
this job. And it makes me think about my own children. I just can't
imagine that happening.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and Texas Rangers are helping about 15 sheriff's
investigators assigned to the case, said Chief Deputy Richard
Elliott of the Williamson County Sheriff's Department.
</P>
<P>
   Sketches of the children were released Tuesday and posted on the
Texas Department of Public Safety's Internet web site. A bulletin
describing the children was distributed to law enforcement agencies
across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were some of the most beautiful children I've ever
seen...and I know there is family and people out there just like
myself that this has got to touch their heart,'' said Ed Richards,
Williamson County sheriff. ``I make a heart-felt plea to anyone
that can come forward with information to help us find out what
happened to these children and help us identify them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're following a lot of leads. The whole world is a suspect
until we can find out who did it. The real dilemma we have is
making identification first.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever left the children in the creek is probably acquainted
with the area, Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, when there are bodies in a remote area, we find they
are familiar with the area,'' he said. ``That doesn't mean they
live in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   The DPS Missing Persons Clearinghouse has listed 74 cases of
missing children fitting the children's general descriptions, said
Mix Cox, a DPS spokesman. A pair of Texas Rangers are
systematically going through the list in search of matches, Cox
said.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of ``minor trauma'' was apparent on the children's
bodies, Richards said. He declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have virtually ruled out the possibility the dead
girl may be one of two girls reporting missing from the Dallas-Fort
Worth area, Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's department officials assigned additional deputies to
field phone calls about the case, but so far none of the calls has
developed into a solid lead, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a large number of telephone calls that have come in
since last night...because of the volume, we're having to get some
help from other police agencies,'' Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators returned to the creek bed surrounded by corn
fields and the Hutto Cemetery to question nearby residents and
search for evidence Tuesday, and plan to be back in the area today,
Richards said.
</P>
<P>
   They worked slowly through shin-high weeds, raking grass and
wildflowers alongside FM 1660 with collapsible metal batons,
slicing the brush for clues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Mike Gleason was asked what the officers were trying to
find in the debris amid the roadside fields. ``Anything. We don't
know what we're looking for, but we'll know it when we find it.''
</P>
<P>
   The midday sun and a steady wind trailed the six officers from
the sheriff's department, as did a police van stocked with water
and Kool-Aid. The probe turned up bottles and a red plastic tray,
junked lottery tickets, stray business cards and a $10 bill.
</P>
<P>
   Potential clues began turning up more than an hour after the
officers started walking when one man found what appeared to be a
white piece of paper. More officers were called in, the area was
photographed and the item was placed in a brown container and then
carted back to Hutto Police Department. The scene repeated several
times that afternoon and K-9 units joined the search party _ hints
of progress in an investigation that, so far, has been slow to
yield clues.
</P>
<P>
   The grim search was a reminder that times are changing in the
Hutto area, where residents gathered Tuesday to ask for news or
wonder why two small children would be killed.
</P>
<P>
   In Snuffy's restaurant on U.S. 79, a lunch-time spot where the
menu is printed on marker on brown paper bags, many said they
couldn't imagine that the children are local, because if kids were
missing ``we'd know about it,'' said waitress Kim Morgan, 38.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say the whole town is pretty shocked,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Audra Flegal, 20, a receptionist who lives near the creek, said
the news rattled her small-town sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hits you harder when you live in a small town and something
like this happens,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Hutto, farming and old-timers are slowly being eclipsed by
the growth that has consumed Williamson County. Since 1990, Hutto's
population has more than doubled to about 1,300.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got here it was more of a farming community,'' Miller
said. ``Now it's getting more like Round Rock. And the old-timers
don't outnumber the newcomers anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Hickman, a 21-year-old welder and machinist, said that as
a kid he used to play in the creek, where he said the fishing isn't
very good but the scenery is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to run around there all the time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In City Hall, the discovery created such a stir that ``even my
staff's relatives are calling in asking if we know anything,''
Yantis said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are asking anyone with information on the case to
contact the Williamson County Sheriff's Department at 943-1313.
</P>
<P>
   Texas had 30 children age 4 and under murdered in 1997,
according to DPS statistics. The number of children the same ages
murdered nationwide the year before was 622. In Williamson County,
the apparent murders near Hutto are the latest in a recent string
of child homicides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had numerous over the years and they're extremely
traumatic for everyone involved in them,'' Elliott said. ``The idea
of finding two deceased children murdered in Brushy Creek is
unthinkable. I can't even express in words what we feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last three months, we had a young child shot and
murdered, we had a 15-year-old murdered and now we have these two
children. The cases aren't connected. I wish I knew the reason
behind murders of innocent children, but there is no reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Spencer writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. Christian Davenport, David Hafetz, Pamela LeBlanc and Bob
Banta contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
