<HEADER>
A6690 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-COVERAGE-COX     04-20 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-COVERAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Littleton saga became America's
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just 19 days left until the end of the school year at
Columbine High.
</P>
<P>
   When some students at the sprawling Littleton, Colo., school
first heard the noise, they thought it was the seniors playing a
prank _ perhaps firecrackers in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they said there was shooting, and we all got down in
corners,'' said Seth, a student interviewed on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just, like, prayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything stopped for a few hours Tuesday as the nation was
transfixed by the horrific images being broadcast from the suburban
Denver high school.
</P>
<P>
   Parents returning from work in Atlanta and around the country,
high school students shouldering their bookbags into the house, if
they turned on any of the major television networks, saw and heard
the news unfold.
</P>
<P>
   For a few hours at least, there was no war in Yugoslavia, no
soap operas, no local news _ only the Columbine school saga.
Parents everywhere watched as Littleton parents waited,
desperately, to see their children as they were evacuated from the
school. Teenagers watched their Columbine peers, looking so
teenage: untucked polo shirts, backward baseball caps, sprinklings
of acne, a girl with a double-pierced eyebrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like it was out of a movie,'' said one girl
interviewed on Denver TV. In the chaos of the live coverage, many
of the witnesses were identified by their first name or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   A Denver television reporter literally ran down a barefoot girl
in a leather jacket who was tearing down a sidewalk, recently freed
from the school by one of the police SWAT teams.
</P>
<P>
   She lost her shoes, she said, huffing and puffing. Her friend, a
curly redhead, spoke frantically about seeing a friend, Anne-Marie,
lying on the floor of the school, covered in blood. She was still
talking when the cameraman swung around and captured a middle-aged
dad in a Nike warmup jacket running up to his daughter on the
sidewalk. The two hugged so hard it looked as if they'd never part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad, I'm glad you're here,'' sobbed the girl. ``Let's go
home.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, the drama became too overwhelming for the
professionals covering it. A reporter for Denver's CBS affiliate,
describing the emotional reunions of surviving students and their
parents, broke down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for a parent,'' she said, turning away from the
camera to wipe her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else mattered. President Clinton came on for an
unscheduled live statement in the late afternoon. The situation at
Columbine was still fluid. No one knew if the gunmen were still
alive, and the word ``fatalities'' had scarcely been spoken yet,
though it was surely already thought by anyone watching the story
unfold. Clinton urged the nation to pray for the students, their
teachers, the parents, then started to say something about an
economics meeting. In a blink, all television _ CNN and the rest _
cut the president off in midsentence.
</P>
<P>
   Back to Columbine High School, back to raw video of students
jogging from danger, hands clasped behind their heads like
prisoners of war. Apparently the SWAT teams had told them to hold
that position after they were out of the school, so they wouldn't
be mistaken for the attackers.
</P>
<P>
   Back to pictures like the one capturing a woman hugging her son,
her face as tightly scrunched as a wadded washcloth. Images like
the kids who had fled to a nearby house, then made their way across
a rock-strewn drainage ditch to safety once it became apparent that
the assailants were dead inside the school. As the teenagers picked
their way across the large rocks, many held hands to support one
another.
</P>
<P>
   The national news media were depending on the four Denver TV
stations, which were in turn depending, at times, on the police.
Some students inside the school were watching their own captivity,
and many were equipped with cell phones. The TV news anchors told
the students to call a special number to get through to police. A
short while later, the students were told not to call, to remain
silent. Apparently no one knew at that point whether the killers
were still shooting up the school.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Littleton residents were being asked by Air Touch
Cellular not to use their cell phones in case of emergency. They'd
been put to good use throughout the day, though, by students who
had them. Early in the afternoon, one student called a Denver
station that was being carried nationally by CNN. He was hiding in
some bushes near the school, he said, his voice trembling.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the injury toll kept rising, starting at eight,
then 13, 14, 18, 21. There was little early speculation about
fatalities, but the kids pouring out of Columbine told tales of
trench-coated invaders carrying pipe bombs, shotguns and automatic
weapons, spraying bullets through the cafeteria and the library.
``Bullets were ricocheting off lockers,'' said student Jonathan
Ladd.
</P>
<P>
   At a little after 6 p.m. in Atlanta, a solemn-faced John Stone,
the Jefferson County sheriff, held a press conference outside the
school and made official what had been feared: He estimated about
25 people were dead inside.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time as Stone's grisly announcement, there
were scenes of jubilation from nearby Leawood Elementary School,
where the parents had been told to wait for news of whether their
children were dead or alive. As students were evacuated, they were
loaded into yellow buses and driven to Leawood.
</P>
<P>
   A handsome boy with a goofy grin leaned out a school bus window.
</P>
<P>
   Two girls, tears streaming down their faces, awaited word of
their friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more people keep showing up, so we have more and more
reason to be happy,'' said a girl in overalls who looked like Joey
on ``Dawson's Creek.''
</P>
<P>
   As the sheriff spoke to reporters, news helicopters circled
overhead. He was immersed in a sea of reporters, their microphones
all lined up in concentric circles, pointing inward.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of media attention of these kinds of
situations,'' the sheriff said, ``and you don't know how much that
gives other people the idea to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But did he have any idea of a specific motive, asked a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Craziness,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
