<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-20 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6692 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-FAMILY-ART-1ST     04-20 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-FAMILY-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM `PARADISE' TO HORROR: A FAMILY'S EXODUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: SUBS to change spelling from ``Bujora'' to ``Bujore'' in 12th
graf, beginning ``Creeping undetected ...'')  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ The moment he crossed into Albania and
registered with police at the shabby border station about 10 miles
east of here, Ymer Behrami was given four blankets, a large green
tarp, and what he believed was a chance for him and his family to
leave behind the madness in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But he had no idea that by passing into Albania he was now
engaged in a new struggle _ to provide for the seven children on
his wagon. As it turned out, the apartment he expected to be
waiting for him in Albania never appeared. Obtaining food, even a
piece of bread, forced him to fight and claw like an animal. The
intimidation and humiliation he thought he had left behind with the
Yugoslav forces in Kosovo found him again, only this time from his
own side.
</P>
<P>
   Within hours, he heard Albanian soldiers bark orders at him and
saw Albanian children taunt him with the three-fingered Serbian
salute. He watched his children shiver with cold and cry from
hunger.
</P>
<P>
   And after surviving the threats and beatings of Serbian police,
he was among those rounded up by armed members of the Kosovo
Liberation Army, the Kosovo Albanian rebels, who questioned him and
frightened him so much that after he was released he took his
family and fled yet again.
</P>
<P>
   For every one of the more than 600,000 Kosovo Albanians expelled
by Yugoslavs over the last three weeks, the escape from Kosovo was
but a single point in a long exodus of terror and pain, preceded by
months of anxiety and followed by long days of disappointment and
vulnerability. Their journey did not start at the border, nor end
there.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was natural for Behrami, a stern and stoic 58-year-old
of Albanian descent whose family had been in Kosovo for many
generations, to feel the bright, warm sun of midafternoon and think
he was lucky still to be alive. The last nine months had been a
relentless round of intimidation and fear, starting with the rifle
shots and mortar rounds he heard approaching his village, Kotore, a
rebel stronghold southwest of Mitrovica, last July 25.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was fighting and they started to bomb,'' he recalled.
After two days of listening to the Yugoslav shells come nearer,
Behrami felt he had to flee. He packed his wagon and hitched it to
his 1978 C-355 Ursus tractor, with a lucky horseshoe hanging over
the radiator grill. He took one, last, heart-searing look at his
home, the product of 40 years of working hard in an ore- processing
plant and on his beloved farm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had good water, beautiful mountains, big trees,
everything,'' he said. He had built three houses for his large
family, solid houses of stone and cement. He had eight cows and
boasted that they gave so much milk the pails overflowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was,'' he said, ``paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also said that his Serbian neighbors were suspicious and
jealous, even after he had lived near them for so many years. As he
left for the last time, they came out.
</P>
<P>
   ``My neighbors were wearing the uniforms of the Serbian army,''
he said. ``They beat us, and put a knife under my chin and told me,
``Go to NATO. Go to the USA and let them help you.''
</P>
<P>
   Creeping undetected along a mountain path, he drove 10 hours to
his older sister's house in Bujore, within the resource-rich
northern part of Kosovo that the Yugoslav government is intent on
keeping. But it was already crowded with refugees. He went on to
his daughter's house in the city of Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
   During the nine months he stayed there, the days rang with rifle
fire, and the nights were lit by mortars and flames. Last week
Serbian police, some in black ski masks, returned to Mitrovica,
systematically crisscrossing the city in search of ethnic Albanians
in hiding. Finally, at about 10 a.m. on April 15, they arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came up the street walking,'' he said, describing an
almost tranquil scene that contrasted greatly with the events
unfolding, ``and when they saw me they shouted, `What are you doing
here? You must leave the house and leave Kosovo.'''
</P>
<P>
   Knowing they would eventually arrive, he had loaded his wagon
weeks before. Forced to decide what cherished parts of his life in
Kosovo to take with him, and what to leave behind, Behrami had
chosen carefully.
</P>
<P>
   He took what he thought would be useful things, like an ax, a
small stove and a sack of flour to make bread. He took blankets and
cushions for the 21 people in his extended family who would ride on
the rattling wooden wagon.
</P>
<P>
   And Behrami brought along a small wooden cradle, called a
``djep'' (pronounced dyep). Not because he expected to need it _
the youngest of his 10 children is 9 years old. But because for
him, as for many Kosovo families, the djep is a symbol of the
future, wherever one might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we left the djep, the Serbians would end up burning it,
just like they have destroyed everything else,'' he said. ``Now
they can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Serbian police watched and waited until they left. It took about
10 minutes. They started heading toward the city of Pec, but were
stopped by police and forced to wait with other refugees overnight.
</P>
<P>
   It was there that they found Aslan Hasani, 48, who is married to
Behrami's younger sister. Hasani's family had taken refuge in the
city after having been forced from his own village, Rezane, near
Mitrovica, by Yugoslav forces on September 15.
</P>
<P>
   A middle-school biology teacher with brown, tightly curled hair,
Hasani looked as if he were already half dead. He had spent a
horrible night tortured by doubts about his wife and son, whom he
had left behind.
</P>
<P>
   For six days before the Serbs showed up, Hasani's son Bajram,
16, had suffered severe stomach pains. Hasani was reluctant to
bring him to the hospital in Mitrovica and run the risk of
encountering police.
</P>
<P>
   Finally his wife, Naile, took the boy to the hospital and stayed
with him until he received the necessary appendectomy.
</P>
<P>
   She was still there when police banged on the door of their
house. ``I asked them if I could go to the hospital to tell my
wife,'' Hasani said, his eyes reddening. ``The policemen said no,
`You can only go to Albania.'''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Two days and two nights later, having been robbed and beaten by
police twice on the way, and having eaten nothing but hard bread
and salt, Hasani cared for his other four children and worried
about the part of his family that had been taken from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they are dead,'' he said from atop the wagon hitch on
which he rode Saturday afternoon on the approach to Kukes, in
northern Albania. ``I'm afraid that since she doesn't have money to
pay the hospital, they will do something to her and to our son.''
As the tractor neared Kukes, the family got its first glimpse of
what life would be like for them in Albania. At a bend in the road,
the Italian government had built a refugee camp, surrounded by
barbed wire. Tractors and wagons were scattered everywhere. There
was no clear way to get in _ or out _ and no official to ask.
</P>
<P>
   Behrami, who had driven all the way from Mitrovica, finally got
off the tractor. ``What can I do now?'' he asked his
brother-in-law. He spoke through the barbed wire to someone in the
camp, asking first for information about relatives, then about
conditions in the camp. With optimism draining from his angular
face, he looked around and sighed.
</P>
<P>
   Three rifle shots sounded just then, and not far away he could
see an Albanian guard chasing after local children who had stolen
something from the camp. He adjusted the dirty black beret he never
removed and shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to Kukes,'' he quietly told one of his sons. ``We
will have to pay for a room, and it will be very expensive, but we
cannot stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimly, he moved the tractor forward again. He fell silent a few
minutes later when he saw the chaos of the unorganized tractor
encampments that have sprung up around Kukes. Unlike the official
camps, which are at least organized, if inadequate, these
unofficial camps are nothing more than open fields. The refugees
organize themselves, if ``organize'' can be used to describe the
utter disorder of tens of thousands of lost families struggling to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   Behrami is the unquestioned patriarch of his family, a strong
figure with a steely gaze who makes all decisions. Now he was lost,
and the uncharacteristic indecision seemed to sap his strength. ``I
don't know where to stop,'' he told his sons on the tractor.
``Where do we go?''
</P>
<P>
   It was a painful scene for the family, lasting until one son,
Lavdim, whose arm had been fractured by a blow from a Serbian
policeman, gestured for his father to pull into a vacant spot
alongside the road.
</P>
<P>
   The women and children did not get down from the wagon. Behrami
immediately ventured into the muddy field to find food. A bread
truck came and tried to distribute some hard loaves, but the
distributors haughtily told the mob that no bread would be given
out until they formed a single line. Behrami pushed his way to the
front, and his hand was upraised and pleading when the truck driver
pulled away to teach the disorderly refugees a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Behrami lined up again, and this time he came back with a
few unwrapped loaves. He broke off a piece and ate it, not with
pleasure but to fortify himself for the next fight.
</P>
<P>
   After insuring that everyone in the family had bread, he
wandered into town, stopping to ask peddlers and old men sitting on
stoops about finding shelter. With less than an hour left before
nightfall, he resigned himself to sleeping in the muddy field.
</P>
<P>
   While Behrami searched the field for a site that blocked the
fierce wind, Lavdim drove the tractor. But the boy was
inexperienced and nearly tipped the wagon over. Dark was
approaching, and a crescent moon was already cut out sharply in
front of the towering mountains. The women asked when they would
leave the field. Behrami had to tell them they would not leave that
night.
</P>
<P>
   But he knew that after being squeezed into the wagon for two
days, they had to have room to stretch out. He and his
brother-in-law, Hasani, wearily began to unload the tractor when a
stranger offered to let them use a nearby empty wagon. Behrami
gladly accepted and sent the women and children over. He spent his
first night in safety sleeping in his wagon under the green tarp
given to him at the border.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The next day was a continuation of the last: fruitless searching
for a room, continuous worrying about his family. ``I am a family
man,'' he told a peddler who promised to bring him information
about an available rural house. ``If we must live here without food
and without shelter we will die.'' He had not spoken to a single
official or relief worker.
</P>
<P>
   Walking to another encampment in a city park, he found a friend,
who took Behrami to his married daughter, Fidaije, from whom he had
been separated in the refugee column. She had come with her husband
in their own tractor, bouncing along on one tire because a Serbian
policeman had shot out the other after she said she did not have
money to give him.
</P>
<P>
   For a second night the extended family slept in the wagons _
Behrami's brother-in-law, Hasani, and that side of the family in
the borrowed wagon at the muddy field; Behrami's wife and children
in a garbage-filled lot in the center of Kukes. There he was
offered the use of another empty wagon.
</P>
<P>
   The following morning, after the rains stopped, Behrami trudged
once more through the dilapidated city searching for a room, hoping
to get his family under a roof somewhere. Still he had not spoken
to any relief worker.
</P>
<P>
   Discouraged, he returned to the tractor at midday to find a
thuggish-looking man accusing him of having taken his wagon the
night before without permission. A contingent of Kosovo rebel
soldiers, heavily armed and wearing new uniforms and identification
tags, came up to Behrami and order him to go with them. In Kukes,
local authority has been almost completely usurped by the rebels,
whose presence in the city is inescapable.
</P>
<P>
   It was a nightmarish repeat of what he had been through before
in Kosovo. Without a chance to tell his wife anything, Behrami was
taken away. With his hands in the pockets of his coat, his beret
firmly on his head, he walked with them, hunched over, not looking
back.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers took him around the corner to a local outpost where
the man who made the complaint against him gestured threateningly
with a large wrench. The rebels chased away observers. Then, moving
quickly, they hustled Behrami into a small red Lada sedan,
squeezing him into the back seat with three rebels, their automatic
rifles planted between their legs. As the car sped off, the rebels
looked menacingly at passers-by, while Behrami stared blankly
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Other refugees said that Behrami returned a few hours later and
parked the tractor in a lot somewhere. Then, along with the members
of his side of the family, he took a bus to the capital, Tirana.
This is something he had said repeatedly he would not do; the
rebels had obviously changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   The djep was left behind.
</P>
<P>
   As they had begun several days before, the family was ending
this part of its sad odyssey split apart. Behrami left for Tirana
without a word to his brother-in-law, who was still in the first
borrowed wagon on the edge of the muddy field. Paralyzed by worry
over the fate of his wife and son in the hospital in Mitrovica, he
had done nothing to secure a home. He worried that his family would
be put out of the wagon that night.
</P>
<P>
   But then the owner of the wagon he had been using, who had
already found shelter in a rural village, came along. He and Hasani
met for the first time. They shook hands, and smoked a cigarette.
``We have very little,'' said the owner, Hatim Merdiu, who came
from the Kosovo village of Brodosane, near the Albanian border.
``But we must take care of each other.'' He told Hasani to stay in
the wagon as long as he needed.
</P>
<P>
   People who arrived in the camps after him told Hasani they heard
that his son was dead. Some said they had seen two bodies in his
house. He tried not to believe them. His responsibility now was to
care for his four other children, little ones who cry at night for
their mother.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Advam, 4, has the same curly hair as his father. He
is a dirty-faced imp with eyes that have already seen things a boy
should never see. Hasani said he regretted that he had not brought
any toys for the children to play with, but there had been so
little time, and so little space, for anything that was not
essential.
</P>
<P>
   The sun came out, and the air turned warm. Advam took from his
pocket his own treasure, a set of marbles. He knelt down and shot
one expertly, knocking another into a puddle. And there, at that
moment, in the mud and waste, it appeared he had made a home from
the fury of war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
