<SLUG> BC-GLF-BEN-HOGAN-EXHIBIT-TEX </SLUG>
 
HOGAN MEMENTOS GO TO USGA museum 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ After spending four decades on display at
Colonial Country Club, the primary mementos from Ben Hogan's
record-setting PGA Tour career will be unveiled June 9 at the U.S.
Golf Association's Museum and Library in Far Hills, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Opening day for the Ben Hogan Room, a 1,000-square-foot area
that will include more than 300 personal items donated by the Hogan
family, was announced yesterday by USGA officials.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Hogan, widow of the legendary golfer from Fort Worth who
died in 1997, agreed last July to move the majority of Hogan's
artifacts out of Colonial so the items could be displayed in a
museum environment that offered greater public access and
heightened security measures. The USGA museum, also known as Golf
House, is open daily and is free to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he would be so pleased that the public can come to see
his things,'' Valerie Hogan said. ``This is what he wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the medals from Hogan's nine major championships have
been moved to Golf House, fans who attend the MasterCard Colonial
(May 20-23) will not be denied a sense of Hogan's contributions to
his hometown tournament. Colonial officials will continue to fill
the shelves of its Ben Hogan Room in the main clubhouse with
vintage photographs, instructional books, a Colonial champion's
jacket and trophies that USGA officials deemed more pertinent to a
regional audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Hogan is giving us some things, and some members are
helping us add to our inventory,'' said Dr. Wally Schmuck, a member
of the Hogan Room Committee formed to reconfigure Colonial's
permanent shrine to its only five-time champion. ``Everything in
the room will be Hogan-related. We still have a lot of items. We're
just spreading them out a little more than we used to.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
