<SLUG> BC-SMUGGLED-CHINESE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIP'S CARGO CONTAINER USED TO SMUGGLE IN 19 CHINESE NATIONALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Nineteen people, including as many as three juveniles,
endured two weeks stuffed into a cargo container on the rolling
decks of a freighter as it crossed the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   It was an attempt to reach America, the land of freedom and
opportunity. But they had precious little freedom and no
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Police and security guards apprehended the 19 Chinese males just
after they climbed out of a cargo container on the Sea-Land
Navigator early Sunday morning in the Port of Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   They apparently are the customers of Chinese smugglers who are
increasingly using the giant container ships that ply the Pacific
and visit West Coast ports for their human cargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of a troubling trend,'' said Bob Coleman, deputy
district director of the Immigration and Naturalization Service in
Seattle. ``This fits an existing pattern of soft-top container
smuggling.''
</P>
<P>
   The INS has had other cases in which Chinese citizens were
smuggled in in containers with tops made out of vinyl or other
fabric, Coleman said. That allows air to get in so those being
smuggled can breathe.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the INS and the U.S. Coast Guard discovered 11
Chinese nationals hidden in a cargo container on a Korean ship that
had just pulled into Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, INS agents discovered an empty cargo container in
Tacoma, Wash., and evidence that people had been living in it
during the voyage across the Pacific. None of the stowaways was
found.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea-Land Navigator, which can carry as many as 1,000 40-foot
containers, made port calls in Hong Kong and Kao-hsiung in Taiwan
in early April, said Clint Eisenhauer, a spokesman for Sea-Land
Service Inc. at its Charlotte, N.C., headquarters. The Korean ship
carrying the 11 Chinese apprehended in California also made stops
at Hong Kong and Kao-hsiung.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very rare,'' Eisenhauer said. ``They are the first
stowaways from Asia ever (for Sea-Land).''
</P>
<P>
   The 19 males on the Sea-Land Navigator had food and water, but
little else in the way of comforts. ``It's a horrible trip,''
Coleman said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the stowaways agreed to pay as much as $40,000 to
smugglers to reach the United States. ``It's better than cocaine
smuggling,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In past cases, Chinese citizens have made a down payment on the
trip, then promise to pay the rest after finding a job in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   INS officials were questioning the 19 people Tuesday, trying to
determine at which port they got into the cargo container and how
they managed to elude detection until they were caught.
</P>
<P>
   The INS will decide what will become of the stowaways; most will
likely be deported.
</P>
<P>
   At least one and as many of three are juveniles, an INS
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Navigator crossed the Pacific and arrived in Tacoma on
Saturday, Eisenhauer said. Early Sunday morning, Tacoma police
asked for help from port security to catch the stowaways.
</P>
<P>
   Security guards found and stopped the 19 near the cargo
container.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said the agency is ``working strong investigative
leads'' to determine if any of the 19 were smugglers or whether the
smugglers had local connections.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese smugglers have become adept at bringing in illegal
aliens by air, sea and land. In the past year, law enforcement
agents have discovered that:
</P>
<P>
   - Smugglers were using a fishing boat to bring Chinese from
South America, then transferring them to the United States by small
power boats based in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   - Chinese citizens were arriving in Vancouver, British Columbia,
by air, then taken across Canada in a van. They were smuggled into
the United States through a Mohawk Indian Reservation along
Canada's border with New York state. Soon, they were on their way
to New York City.
</P>
<P>
   - Moss Landing and Half Moon Bay in Northern California were
used to smuggle in Chinese, whom smugglers turned into virtual
slaves in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
