<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALL MAJOR INDEXES REBOUND A DAY AFTER A BIG SELLOFF
</P>
<P>
   Shares of technology companies rebounded in heavy trading after
Monday's selloff, and investors were seen moving out of
economically sensitive cyclical stocks, like industrial and oil
companies, which have been rallying.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index recovered 64.03 points of Monday's
138-point loss and closed at 2,409.64, up 2.7 percent. The Dow
Jones industrial average edged up 8.02 points, or 0.1 percent, to
10,448.55, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 16.69
points, or 1.3 percent, to 1,306.17.
</P>
<P>
   BROWSER RIVALS JOIN FORCES
</P>
<P>
   Hadi Partovi, the former lead product manager for Microsoft's
Internet Explorer, is joining a Silicon Valley software start-up
founded by two former enemies from Netscape, Michael McCue and
Angus Davis, and backed by Jim Clark, the co-founder of Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD NEWS FOR DRUG STOCKS
</P>
<P>
   A steep selloff in drug stocks halted after three large drug
makers reported first-quarter earnings gains and and a fourth
received a recommendation from a government panel that a new drug
be approved. What surprised analysts was Johnson &AMP; Johnson's 12.3
percent gain. The earnings news lifted the shares of many drug
companies, with Johnson &AMP; Johnson rising $6, to $96.25.
</P>
<P>
   CAR MAKERS DELAY FACTORIES
</P>
<P>
   An opposition governor in southern Brazil has disrupted plans by
General Motors and Ford Motor to build two car factories regarded
as prototypes for the future.
</P>
<P>
   PROFIT RISES AT SEVERAL BANKS
</P>
<P>
   Several of the nation's big banks reported big gains in
earnings. Chase Manhattan said first-quarter net jumped 61 percent,
Bank One said profits were up 23 percent, and Wells Fargo reported
a 29 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
   Despite pressure from shrinking demand for cigarettes and the
cost of tobacco-related lawsuit settlements, Philip Morris posted a
1.4 percent increase in first-quarter profit.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the nation's largest phone companies _ Sprint,
BellSouth, Ameritech and SBC Communications _ reported strong gains
in first-quarter earnings.
</P>
<P>
   AUDITING BOARD CONSIDERS CHANGE
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Accounting Standards Board, which sets the
nation's accounting rules, is expected to vote Wednesday for strict
limits or even a ban on the use of the pooling of interest
accounting method, which played a prominent part in many of the
largest corporate mergers and acquisitions in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   INQUIRY HURT BRAZILIAN MARKETS
</P>
<P>
   Nervousness over a legislative inquiry into reported
irregularities during a Brazilian government bailout of two
investment banks earlier this year unsettled financial markets
there. The Bovespa stock index gave up 4 percent before
recuperating to close at 10,989.42, down 207.18 points, or 1.85
percent. The bailout was organized by Francisco Lopes, who has
since been replaced as head of the central bank and is now a
consultant in Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   INFLATION IS EXPECTED TO RISE
</P>
<P>
   The rate of inflation, as measured by the Consumer Price Index,
is likely to jump this year to more than 2 percent from the 1.6
percent of last year. It could increase even more if oil prices
continue to rise, upsetting the stock and bond markets. Market
Place.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA IS SEEKING DEBT DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Russia is holding foreign investors to a deadline of Wednesday
for agreeing to a plan that restructures $40 billion in defaulted
government debt at a fraction of its face value.
</P>
<P>
   PROTECTING INTERNET PRIVACY
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission has proposed new rules to protect
the privacy interests of children on the Internet. They would
require commercial Web sites to get parental consent before seeking
information from children younger than 13 and would require the
sites to post notifications about what they do with any information
obtained from children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
