</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: WITH CONFUSION AND FEW FACTS, NONSTOP
COVERAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (With COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING) 
 (nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Network news came on in time to report that the local police
chief estimated that 25 people had been killed in a high school in
Littleton, Colo., probably by two people in long coats and masks,
perhaps members of a group known as the trench coat Mafia, who had
then killed themselves. The chief referred to them as
``gentlemen,'' then apologized for his undue politeness.
</P>
<P>
   For seven or so hours before, the cable channels had had the
assignment once again of covering a big story that lacked known
facts. And with the exception of a striking picture or two, it did
not make for much of a television story. Trapped by their reason
for being and by the competition, they had to deliver nonstop
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the televised images from Columbine High School in
Littleton, a suburb of Denver, were of police officers running here
and there, doing it was hard to say what. They were identified as
SWAT teams. But then came a batch of students, fleeing the school,
hands behind their necks for some reason. In the most dramatic
moment, a wounded student was helped from a second-story window by
two officers.
</P>
<P>
   These few images were repeated and repeated and repeated. Time
was also used up on all channels with lists of other schools that
had known shootings in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The national networks, broadcast and cable, turned for help to
affiliate stations in Denver, whose anchors and reporters were hard
put to find words, not because of the enormity of the event but
because of the scarcity of information. A man in Denver resorted to
praise for the camaraderie he witnessed: ``We ought to be very
proud of that as Coloradans.'' A local official concurred. He said
his town was full of caring people.
</P>
<P>
   Shaken, weeping girls told of their moments of panic. Official
spokesmen appeared after a while, bestowing credits on every
law-enforcement agency on the premises. We were reminded on MSNBC
that in past school shootings in Oregon, Arkansas and Alaska, the
perpetrators were all young men with behavioral problems.
</P>
<P>
   It was also reported that the Colorado Rockies and the Denver
Nuggets had canceled their ballgames.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter pressed a student to speculate on whether the episode
might have been connected with a feud of some sort or a racial
confrontation. The student resisted. He attributed the shooting to
``sick people.'' That was as persuasive an analysis as anything
else we had been hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Another student called the killers ``social outcasts.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 8 p.m., President Clinton appeared and said a few
words about ``trying to prevent these things from happening.'' He
also said he needed more facts to say much more. The reporters
asked a few empty questions and must have envied the luxury of
getting off camera as easily as the president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
