<SLUG> BC-MERGERS-ACCOUNTING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTING RULES MAY CHANGE FOR MERGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The board that sets the nation's accounting rules is expected to
vote Wednesday for strict limits or even a ban on the use of an
accounting method that played a prominent part in many of the
largest corporate mergers and acquisitions in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund Jenkins, the chairman of the Financial Accounting
Standards Board, said Tuesday that his staff had recommended that
the board eliminate the accounting method known as pooling of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   But the seven-member board is also considering whether to
continue to allow pooling in the small number of cases where two
companies of equal size decide to merge, Jenkins said. The board
will discuss whether the rules can be written in a way that would
prevent companies of unequal sizes from finding ways to squeeze
through loopholes so that they can still use pooling accounting.
</P>
<P>
   The board will not force companies that have already merged to
change their accounting, Jenkins said, although it may make the
changes effective for mergers and acquisitions that take place
before the final rules are issued, probably in late 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, the board expects to issue a draft of the
proposed rules. Companies will then have three months to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, many corporate executives and Wall Street
dealmakers have come to count on pooling accounting because it
allows merging companies to avoid expensive charges relating to the
intangible asset known as good will, which reduce future earnings.
Pooling accounting is being used in deals like those between Exxon
and Mobil and Daimler-Benz AG and Chrysler Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the pooling method, including federal securities
regulators, say that it allows corporate executives to use
shareholders' money to make expensive acquisitions but never record
the price of those decisions in the accounting ledgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pooling does not leave an adequate trail of management's
acquisition activities,'' Jack Ciesielski wrote recently in his
newsletter, the Analyst's Accounting Observer, which is published
in Baltimore. ``A mediocre acquisition can still look decent and
accretive to earnings if pooling is used.''
</P>
<P>
   Under pooling, the accounting ledgers of two companies are
simply added together, and any premium that one company may be
paying for the other disappears.
</P>
<P>
   But under the other merger accounting method, known as purchase
accounting, the acquiring company must record the full value of the
cash and stock that was paid for the other company. If the company
is paying a large premium, most of the excess is generally recorded
as good will, which must be gradually written off.
</P>
<P>
   The standards board, based in Norwalk, Conn., has also
tentatively agreed on new rules for accounting for good will.
Instead of continuing to allow companies to write it off over as
many as 40 years, the board has decided to shorten the maximum
period to 20 years. Under the shortened schedule, many companies
would have larger reductions in earnings each year, until the good
will was written off, than they would have had if they had been
able to stretch the process out over a longer time.
</P>
<P>
   But Jenkins said the board was reconsidering some of its
decisions on good will after reading letters sent by companies in
response to a paper proposing that pooling accounting be
eliminated. The paper was written by a group of authors including
two members of the standards board; members of similar rule-making
boards in Canada, Britain, Australia and New Zealand, and
representatives of the International Accounting Standards
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies said that if pooling were to be eliminated, the
standards board should work harder to clarify the purchase
accounting rules, especially those that pertain to good will.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the letters, Jenkins said, the board is
considering other options for the accounting for good will,
including allowing companies to leave it on their books
indefinitely if they can prove that its value has not diminished or
allowing them to write it off immediately if it appears to have no
future value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
