<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS SEEK MEDICARE COVERAGE FOR PRESCRIPTION DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats in Congress on Tuesday kicked off a major
effort to secure Medicare coverage of prescription drugs, one of
the biggest expenses for millions of elderly people.
</P>
<P>
   The fight for such benefits promises to continue into next
year's elections, as candidates from both parties search for ways
to plug a conspicuous hole in Medicare coverage and try to solve
the program's long-term financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   Most employers who provide health benefits to employees help pay
for prescription drugs. But Medicare generally does not pay for
drugs used by patients outside the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   In offering the Democratic proposal, Sen. Edward M. Kennedy,
D-Mass., said Medicare's failure to cover prescription drugs was
``the greatest single gap'' in the program.
</P>
<P>
   Many elderly people receive drug benefits through health
maintenance organizations or through private insurance that
supplements Medicare. But Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., said there was
a growing clamor for Medicare to cover drug costs because HMOs were
cutting back drug benefits, and private Medigap insurers have
sharply increased premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, a Medicare beneficiary would have to pay a
deductible of $200 a year in drug expenses, but Medicare would then
pay 80 percent of the cost of each prescription. The government
would pay $1,200 of the first $1,700 in annual drug expenses. It
would provide additional coverage for people with very high drug
costs, so beneficiaries would have to spend more than $3,000 of
their own money each year.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats said they did not yet have an estimate of the cost
of their proposal. Beneficiaries would pay some through higher
premiums. Other possible sources of money include higher tobacco
taxes and the anticipated federal budget surplus. In addition,
Democrats said, proper use of drugs could save some money by
reducing the need for more costly treatments, hospitalization and
nursing home care.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they had modeled their proposal after the
arrangements already used by many employers to manage the cost of
prescription drugs provided to employees.
</P>
<P>
   The government would award contracts to private organizations to
manage drug benefits for Medicare patients. These private entities
could include groups of retail pharmacists, insurers and
specialized companies like PCS and Medco. PCS, now a subsidiary of
Rite Aid Corp., and Medco, a unit of Merck &AMP; Co., manage
prescription drug care for employers, labor unions and health
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans agreed that many elderly people needed help with
drug bills, but said the Democratic plan was likely to prove very
expensive. Drug companies welcomed the Democrats' effort to use
private ``pharmacy benefit managers,'' but said there would be far
too big a role for the government.
</P>
<P>
   One of the drug companies' big concerns is that Medicare would
be a huge purchaser and could command discounts similar to those
available to other big buyers, like HMOs and large employers.
Indeed, the Democrats' bill says Medicare beneficiaries shall
receive drug discounts comparable to those provided to ``large
private sector purchasers.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dichter, executive vice president of PCS Health
Systems in Scottsdale, Ariz., said the government's ability to
achieve such savings would depend on how much latitude it gave to
the managers of Medicare drug benefits. The Democrats would allow
companies to establish lists of preferred drugs and to recommend
low-cost generic versions of brand-name medications.
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies have long been nervous about Medicare coverage of
prescription drugs because they fear it could lead to federal
regulation of drug prices.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Feldbaum, president of the Biotechnology Industry
Organization, a trade group, praised the Democrats on Tuesday for
``backing away from the type of price control legislation they
proposed in 1993-94,'' as part of President Clinton's plan to
redesign the health care system.
</P>
<P>
   But Feldbaum said the Democrats' bill gave the secretary of
health and human services ``quite extensive authority to set rules
for Medicare drug benefits, without much guidance from Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the Ways and Means
Committee, expressed cautious interest in the Democrats' ideas. ``I
look forward to working in a bipartisan way to provide some form of
prescription drug coverage to Medicare beneficiaries,'' Archer
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
