<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BONILLA ENDS HIS DROUGHT WITH TIE-BREAKING BLAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Strikeout followed popout. Popout followed
strikeout. The runners he left on base were piling up.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was Bobby Bonilla in a rut. While he stumbled through
the first two weeks of the season, the self-analysis he kept
offering sounded more like an excuse than anything profound.
</P>
<P>
   One road trip. One homestand. The middle of the month. That is
all Bonilla said he needed to regain his batting stroke. He had
missed most of spring training with a partly torn ligament in his
right knee, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Getting away from the boos he has grown so accustomed to at Shea
Stadium could not have hurt much, either. But whether it was a new
road trip, a less hostile environment or just the right time of the
month mattered little to the Mets in the aftermath of their 3-2
victory over the Cincinnati Reds on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   That was because Bonilla slugged a one-out, seventh-inning home
run off Pete Harnisch that broke a 1-1 tie.
</P>
<P>
   The homer was Bonilla's first of the season and first with the
Mets in nearly four years. It seemed almost as long since his last
extra-base hit.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla was 6 for 37 _ all singles _ before his homer. And while
it came a little late for Orel Hershiser, Bonilla's timing in the
cleanup slot was perfect for a team that will be without Mike
Piazza for five more days.
</P>
<P>
   John Franco, who came on in the ninth with a two-run lead,
yielded one run but got the last two batters out with the bases
loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser took a 1-0 lead into the sixth inning, thanks to a
two-out, second-inning triple from Mike Kinkade followed by Todd
Pratt's run-scoring single. But the player Hershiser really had to
thank for the lead was shortstop Rey Ordonez, who robbed the Reds
of a run in the fourth with a terrific relay throw.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Larkin had opened the inning by drawing a four-pitch walk.
Sean Casey followed with a double into the left-field corner.
Kinkade, a converted catcher-third baseman who was making just his
second start in the majors, did his job by fielding the ball
cleanly and hitting his cut-off man, Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' two-time Gold Glove winner took Kinkade's throw in
medium left field and in one blur of a motion pivoted and fired a
one-hop strike to Pratt at the plate. Pratt's tag beat Larkin's
head-first dive. And after Casey made a base running mistake on a
grounder hit to Ordonez for the second out, Hershiser was able to
escape the inning with his lead intact.
</P>
<P>
   But Hershiser could not escape the sixth. Mike Cameron pushed a
bunt between the mound and first base and under Hershiser's reach
for a single. Cameron stole second on a pitch to the backstop, then
took third on Larkin's grounder to second. Casey followed with a
run-scoring double to left center. After walking Greg Vaughn,
Hershiser, the 40-year-old right-hander, was done for the night.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Cook retired the next two Reds on flies to keep the score
1-1. And so Hershiser's line read five and a third innings, five
hits, one run, three walks and three strikeouts, lowering his
earned run average to 3.60 after three starts.
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch _ the former Met _ had been given new life. But then
Harnisch left a pitch up to Bonilla leading off the seventh. And
Bonilla responded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
