<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH HULL, STARS ALIGNED IN QUEST FOR STANLEY CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ If you believe in fate, if you believe that
coincidences don't really exist and that events are a byproduct of
karma and the juxtaposition of Stars in the universe, then you know
perfectly well why Brett Hull is here.
</P>
<P>
   You know there's a reason he skates for the Dallas Stars tonight
at this point in space and time. You knew it last summer, when
owner Tom Hicks opened his treasury to sign him.
</P>
<P>
   It was July 3, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars celebrated Independence Day 24 hours early.
</P>
<P>
   The moment we've been waiting for since that hot July afternoon
has arrived. The NHL's second season, the one that matters, is
here.
</P>
<P>
   This time the difference-maker is here.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge playoff for Brett Hull,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said yesterday after the final practice at Stars Center
before the first-round playoff matchup with Edmonton tonight at
Reunion Arena. ``Huge.''
</P>
<P>
   It's huge because the 34-year-old winger has never had a better
chance at a Stanley Cup. In 11 previous full seasons in the NHL, he
has been past the second round of the playoffs only once _ two
games of the 1986 Stanley Cup as a newly called up rookie with
Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a team game, and there's not a lot you can do if the
people above you don't give you the team to carry on with,'' Hull
said. ``There's obviously pressure on me. I'm the guy they brought
in that they felt would put them over the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's just my internal pressure. All I can do is play
within the group and play hard and do the best I can. I'm not one
to sit there and be afraid, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull afraid? When pigs fly and the Rangers beat the Yankees in
the playoffs, maybe.
</P>
<P>
   This opportunity is why he came here. It's why he has tamed his
game, given up much of his free-wheeling offense to fit within a
system that emphasizes defense and hard work first. Everything
else, including egos, is somewhere down the line.
</P>
<P>
   That Hull has willingly accepted Hitchcock's philosophy tells
you how much he wants to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a style that's changed my game from the kind of guy who
hides and jumps into hole,'' Hull said. ``There's no hiding on this
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this situation and on this team, you go right from the
get-go. There's no more waiting around and picking your spots. That
was a big change for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hull has adapted well, scoring 32 goals, including an NHL-best
11 game-winners, and teaming with Mike Modano (34 goals) to give
the Stars as strong an offensive line as there is in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a little bit of your creativity, because now you're
right in the middle of things and people have their eye on you all
the time,'' Hull said of the Stars' style of play. ``That's not the
way I've played before. It took 30-35 games before it became
instinctual and I didn't have to think about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you are \Ra great star\S on this team you're not
because of the way they play. I don't know, in this style, if
they'll ever have a 50-goal scorer. But every night there's a new
guy who steps up and does something to help you win. You don't come
up with 110 points by accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Hull has given the Stars something they lacked, a
scorer with a big shot, an offensive threat who can score from
anywhere inside the blue line. Fifteen of his 32 goals have come on
the power play. When teams get too frisky and take penalties, Hull
is the man who makes them pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hull's given us confidence that we've got people on our team
who can score from a distance,'' Hitchcock said. ``In the playoffs,
with the tenacity that people defend with, you have to have people
who can do those things. He's scored a number of goals from the
same locale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost, at times, surprising for us because we're not
used to that type of player being on our team. At the start, it was
hard trying to find that player. We're always looking for that
player going to the net, not finding that empty space in the slot
or in the higher areas. It took us half a season to get used to him
playing in that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember the playoffs last season? With Joe Nieuwendyk out
courtesy of the San Jose snake, Bryan Marchment, the Stars just
hoped they could slop in a goal or two and hang on with defense.
Hull and Modano on the ice together puts double pressure on
defenses, each opening up space for the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're on the bench, you can feel the scoring chance
coming,'' Hitchcock said. ``When he's out on the ice, you can feel
it coming from somewhere, especially when there's a longer
possession in the zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's Hull who scores, or whether he's opening it up for
Modano or another of the Stars, the bottom line is winning. First
this series, then the next, and the next, right on to the Stanley
Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   He could have stayed in St. Louis and scored goals. He came here
to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking it up, and Hully hasn't played on a team
that's had a lot of playoff success,'' Hitchcock said. ``It's a big
challenge for him. Brett had the opportunity to go to a number of
teams, but he wanted to have team success.''
</P>
<P>
   While the rest of the Stars were shrugging about winning another
Presidents' Trophy, Hull was thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Presidents' Trophy wasn't delivered on time, for
whatever reason, he's the one who led the big uproar,'' Hitchcock
said. ``Everybody wanted to downplay the darn thing because you
think it's the kiss of death when it comes out there, but he was
really, really upset and he came out and said, `You know what,
that's the first team trophy I've ever won.' He wanted that thing
badly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when it started to hit home that individually he's had
a great career, but now he's looking at other things. He wants to
be a part of team success and he's pretty focused in that area
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   This is why he's here. Brett Hull and the Stars have come
together at this point in space and time for a reason.
</P>
<P>
   They're here for the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Independence Day, Stars style, has arrived.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
