<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH COURT WEIGHS FEDERALISM IN STATES' IMMUNITY FROM LAWSUITS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.J.)   (bl)  
 By LINDA GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The fault lines within the Supreme Court over basic
questions of federalism were on full display Tuesday as the
justices heard arguments in two cases on whether states can be
forced into federal court to defend their business practices.
</P>
<P>
   In a pair of 1992 laws, Congress made states liable to private
damage suits in federal court for unfair trade practices, like
false advertising, and for patent infringement. The question for
the court Tuesday was whether, in either of these areas, Congress
had the authority to nullify the states' constitutional immunity
from suits in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   But it was clear from the justices' questions and comments
throughout the two hours of arguments that much more was at stake
than the fate of the two laws, the Patent Remedy Act and the
Trademark Remedy Clarification Act.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Congress passed these laws, the ground shifted on
federalism as a series of Supreme Court decisions began to sweep
away long-held assumptions about the authority of Congress to make
federal laws binding on state governments. The real question before
the court Tuesday was how much of that authority is left.
</P>
<P>
   Both cases began as lawsuits by a bank that markets certificates
of deposit for financing future college expenses, against a Florida
agency that the state set up to offer a similar investment program
for Florida residents. The College Savings Bank, based in
Princeton, N.J., charged that Florida had both infringed its patent
on its financing methods and had also engaged in false advertising
of the state program, in violation of a federal law, the Lanham
Act.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits, filed in 1994, were still pending in U.S. District
Court in Newark, N.J., when an unrelated Supreme Court decision
limited federal jurisdiction over a large category of suits against
states. In that decision, Seminole Tribe vs. Florida, the court
ruled that in the ordinary exercise of its power to regulate
interstate commerce, Congress lacked authority to abrogate the
immunity that states enjoy under the 11th Amendment from suits in
federal court.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the district court dismissed College Savings Bank's
false advertising case against Florida. But it refused Florida's
request to dismiss the patent infringement case. The court reasoned
that because the legal system regards a patent as a type of
property, the 1992 law that made states liable to suit for patent
infringement was not ordinary commercial legislation. Rather, the
district court found, it was an exercise of Congress' power under
the 14th Amendment to protect against the deprivation of property
without due process of law, a power that the Supreme Court had not
directly attacked in the Seminole Tribe case.
</P>
<P>
   The 3rd Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals, in Philadelphia, agreed
with the dismissal of the false advertising suit, while the U.S.
Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, a specialized appeals
court in Washington that has nationwide jurisdiction over patent
cases, agreed that the College Savings Bank could still pursue its
patent infringement suit. Each side appealed the case that it lost
to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments Tuesday ranged over a number of issues. Could the
right to be free of unfair competition, like false advertising, not
also be considered a type of property right? Could a state that
enters the commercial marketplace, either by selling an investment
contract or opening a coffee bar _ an image the Justices seemed to
find particularly engaging _ be seen as waiving whatever special
immunity from suit it might otherwise possess?
</P>
<P>
   But the most important issue appeared to be the current
definition of Congress' power to protect constitutional rights
under Section 5 of the 14th Amendment. The amendment, adopted after
the Civil War, prohibits the states from violating the guarantees
of due process and equal protection; Section 5 authorizes Congress
to ``enforce, by appropriate legislation'' the amendment's
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor General Seth Waxman, defending the patent infringement
law and arguing on the side of the College Savings Bank, told the
court that Congress was aware in 1992 that states were becoming
major players in the fields of technology and intellectual property
and that private patent holders felt threatened. ``Congress heard
there was a problem,'' Waxman said. ``It was emerging. It was
getting worse. It was unique. State remedies were inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, he continued, was whether the method Congress
chose, to permit patent holders to sue states, was ``appropriate''
legislation under Section 5. Congress' conclusion was entitled to
the Court's deference, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Florida Assistant Attorney General Jonathan Glogau told the
court that the patent infringement law was unconstitutional because
Congress' authority under Section 5 was limited to remedying
constitutional violations. The proper question, he said, was not
whether Congress found that the states were likely to infringe
patents, but whether in doing so they would deny patent holders due
process. There was no due process violation as long as states
offered some redress in their own courts, as Florida did, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter objected that there was a need for
uniformity in the application of federal patent law, rather than a
patchwork of 50 state remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Using the format of posing questions to the Florida lawyer,
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia, and Anthony M.
Kennedy then began to debate Souter, who is as strong an advocate
of federal authority as the other three justices are of states'
rights.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't the fact that patent cases can be appealed to the Supreme
Court provide sufficient guarantee of uniformity, O'Connor asked?
</P>
<P>
   Scalia wanted to know why, when the Constitution did not even
require the creation of the lower federal courts, the Supreme Court
should deduce a requirement for federal jurisdiction over patent
cases.
</P>
<P>
   The patent case is Florida Prepaid Board vs. College Savings
Bank, No. 98-531. The false advertising case is College Savings
Bank vs. Florida Prepaid Board, No. 98-149.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
