<SLUG> BC-MINIMED-STOCK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSULIN PUMP, NEW BLOOD GLUCOSE SENSOR KEEP MINIMED OUTLOOK HOT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two days after splitting its stock 2-for-1,
MiniMed Inc. is expected to post a 41 percent gain in first quarter
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of microinfusion pumps, based in the Sylmar community
of Los Angeles, is expected to post earnings of 12 cents per share,
according to a consensus of seven analysts surveyed by Zacks
Investment Research. The company earned 8.5 cents per share in the
first quarter of 1998. MiniMed is expected to have first-quarter
revenues between $34 million and $37 million.
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed's pumps are worn by diabetics to release insulin as
needed into their bodies. The company is using the same technology
to develop treatments for other chronic conditions that require
regular drug injections.
</P>
<P>
   Driven by strong sales of the pump and anticipation of U.S. Food
and Drug Administration approval of a new blood glucose sensor,
MiniMed's share price has climbed steadily from a low of $40.3750
in July 1998 to a high of more than $110 earlier this month. Such
growth prompted the company's board of directors to authorize
Monday's split. MiniMed shares closed Tuesday at $53.50, up $2.375.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say they expect few surprises in the earnings report.
``Their business is very strong, and I expect a continuation of
that,'' said Marc Davis at investment bank B.C. Ziegler and Co.
``I'm not looking for anything special.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he rates MiniMed shares a ``buy,'' B.C. Ziegler's
highest rating for a stock.
</P>
<P>
   The company's share price got a boost last quarter when an
advisory panel for the FDA said it would recommend approval of a
new MiniMed blood sugar sensor that can be worn by diabetics for up
to three days at a time. Diabetics must now prick their fingers
several times a day to draw blood for testing, a process MiniMed
hopes to make redundant with its sensor.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kotler, an analyst at ING Barings, said the sensor has the
potential for major revenue growth for MiniMed if it is approved by
the full FDA. But even the pump market has not been fully tapped,
Kotler believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``U.S. markets are underpenetrated,'' he said. ``Only 7 percent
of Type 1 diabetics now use a pump, and there are 900,000
(potential customers) out there.''
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed is expected to report earnings after the close of U.S.
markets.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
