u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT &LR;      04-20 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: PAYING FOR KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Wednesday, April 21: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The war in Kosovo ought not to be the occasion for budget
gamesmanship in Congress. Unhappily, some Republicans are trying to
manipulate an emergency spending bill for the war to inflate the
Pentagon budget and to lay the groundwork for cuts in domestic
programs. Both schemes should be soundly rejected by the House and
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has asked Congress for $6 billion to help pay
for the war and the cost of caring for the hundreds of thousands of
ethnic Albanians driven from their homeland by marauding Serbian
troops. It is a reasonable request and should be promptly approved.
Several Republican lawmakers, however, want to load up the measure
with unrelated military items, like increases in military pay and
retirement benefits, to circumvent the budget ceilings that apply
to defense spending. These sneaky tactics demean the budget process
and trivialize the Balkan emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Military experts in Congress are right to scrutinize the
administration's request and raise appropriate questions about
plans for prosecuting the war. But the emergency funding must not
be turned into a vehicle for extraneous spending that should be
debated as part of the overall defense budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans say the emergency request cannot be separated
from what they view as an overall decline in military readiness
under President Clinton. That is not so. What the Pentagon needs
now is money to pay for the aircraft, missiles, munitions and fuel
required to sustain the air war over Serbia. Broader questions
about the state of the armed forces can be considered later in the
year. As Sen. John McCain and others have pointed out, some of
spending pushed by members in both parties is being driven more by
pork-barrel projects than by a desire to upgrade the military.
</P>
<P>
   Money for Kosovo need not force cuts in other programs, another
idea being floated by some Republicans. The Congressional Budget
Office is projecting a surplus of $111 billion this year alone. But
the Republicans have created a budget trap for themselves by
enacting a budget blueprint for the next fiscal year that calls for
a tax cut of nearly $800 billion over the next 10 years, and a
spike in military spending. Because of previously established
ceilings, these steps cannot be taken without deep cuts in
appropriations for health, education and the environment. Not even
the Republicans think such cuts will be approved.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans may think it is clever to get around this trap
by pushing as much of the spending as they can into ``emergency''
bills that, by law, do not have to comply with the ceilings. That
is a backdoor route to fiscal irresponsibility. Instead, both
parties and the White House should admit the obvious and revise the
budget ceilings. At a time of extraordinary prosperity and budget
surpluses of hundreds of billions of dollars in the future, there
is enough money to meet the spending needs of the country and also
pay for legitimate emergencies like the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
