A6733 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-BAN-COX     04-20 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-BAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Partial birth abortion foes will introduce legislation banning
procedure
 &HT;    By Joann Rouse
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ During a news conference in Cincinnati on
Tuesday, the Ohio, Dayton and Warren County Right to Life
organizations announced that U.S. Senator Mike DeWine
(R-Cincinnati) plans to reintroduce national legislation banning
so-called partial birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has overturned similar legislation twice in
the past three years. On Sept. 18, 1998, the U.S. Senate fell three
votes short of overriding the veto, but senate majority leader
Trent Lott pledged to keep fighting for it.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the presentation, medical technician Shelly Lowe
recounted the story of ``Baby Hope'' born prematurely April 7 at
the Bethesda North Hospital in Cincinnati at 22 weeks. The day
before she was born, a doctor at the Women's Med Center in Dayton
had begun a three-step abortion procedure that would have
terminated the pregnancy April 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say its just a bunch of cells,'' said a teary-eyed Lowe
as she held up a tiny doll. ``But this is a baby, a small baby, but
she would have lived. My life will never be the same after what I
went through in that medical room.''
</P>
<P>
   Attending physicians judged the infant's lung development
insufficient to permit sustained respiration. The baby was healthy
otherwise, said Dayton Right to Life Society spokeswoman Peggy
Lehner.
</P>
<P>
   The death was ruled natural and no autopsy was ordered.
</P>
<P>
   The partial birth abortion - or dilation and extraction
procedure - is used after the 20th week of pregnancy and involves
two days of dilating the woman's cervix and on the third day,
delivering the baby feet-first until only the head remains inside
the mother, said Dr. William Stalter, president-elect of the
Montgomery County Medical Society and past Chief of Staff at Miami
Valley Hospital in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor then inserts a suction tube in the back of the baby's
neck that removes the brain, causing the head to collapse, Stalter
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Dr. William Haskell of the Women's Med Center in
Dayton credited himself with developing the procedure used on
``Baby Hope.'' The classic dilation and extraction procedure used
previously involved dismembering the fetus inside the uterus with
instruments and removing the pieces through an adequately dilated
cervix, Haskell wrote in a presentation dated Sept. 13-14, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Haskell did not return phone calls Tuesday, but Women's Med
Center vice-president Valerie Haskell, who is Martin Haskell's
wife, issued a news release condemning the right-to-life press
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hundreds of women miscarry during the second trimester in the
United States each week,'' the release stated. ``It is unfortunate
that Right to Life has chosen to exploit an individual patient's
most personal circumstance for the sake of a publicity stunt to
promote their latest round of anti-choice legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   The release further described the news conference as the Right
to Life group's attempt to manipulate the public.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Woodward-Ginther, executive director of National Abortion
and Reproduction Rights and Legislation also denounced the news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad attempt to further their own political
agendas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joann Rouse writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
