<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON CHECKS OUT SUBURBS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton made a campaign-style trip
Tuesday into the heart of the Long Island suburbs that would be
crucial to winning a race for U.S. Senate, then came back into
Manhattan for two more events to finish off a 13-hour day.
</P>
<P>
   But in a total of six appearances before such Democratic
constituencies as teachers, lawyers, women, Jews, members of
minority groups and patrons of the arts, Mrs. Clinton made no
teasing references to her potential Senate race, as she has in the
past, and stayed within the bounds of First Lady.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this first lady's business is sometimes hard to
distinguish from a candidate's stump speech. In an address at
Hofstra University in Hempstead, Mrs. Clinton first mentioned her
failure on pushing Congress to enact sweeping national health care
reform _ ``Clearly that approach did not work, and we're not going
to try that again, rest assured'' _ then described herself as a new
incrementalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from the school of smaller steps now,'' she said,
adding that 3.1 million New Yorkers have no health insurance and
that 1,500 children in New York may lose their insurance as they
get older.
</P>
<P>
   One notable moment of the day came at a lunch for the Long
Island Women's Agenda at the Crest Hollow Country Club in Woodbury,
where Mrs. Clinton sat on the dais next to Libby Pataki, the wife
of Gov. George Pataki. The Republican governor has a quarrelsome
relationship with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York City, a
potential opponent of Mrs. Clinton in a Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   The two women chatted cheerfully and praised each other in their
speeches; Mrs. Pataki called herself ``the warm-up act'' for Mrs.
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton started her day at the Village Elementary School in
Syosset, where she spoke about the need for more teachers and
after-school programs. ``She did not seem to be playing to a
broader audience,'' said Jeffrey Rozran, the president of the
Syosset Teachers' Association. ``She was playing to this audience,
and I'm grateful for that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon at the New York University School of Law, Mrs.
Clinton presented awards to Archishop Desmond Tutu of South Africa
and Dr. Alexander Boraine, a professor in the school's global law
program. In one of the only public references Tuesday to her
possible campaign, Boraine told the first lady to cheers from the
law students that ``who knows, we may see more of you in New
York.''
</P>
<P>
   In the evening, Mrs. Clinton attended fund-raisers for the
United Jewish Appeal and the Whitney Museum of American Art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-20-99 2339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
