u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SENATE-GOP-NYT &LR;      04-20 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-GOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP FEARS GIULIANI-PATAKI FEUD COULD COST U.S. SENATE RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The tensions between New York Gov. George Pataki
and New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani are causing growing
concern among Republican officials on Capitol Hill, many of whom
want Giuliani to run for the U.S. Senate next year and are worried
that the feud will hurt the party's chances of winning the seat,
particularly if Hillary Rodham Clinton is the Democratic candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's main rival for the Republican nomination is Rep. Rick
Lazio, a Suffolk County Republican who has been aggressively
courting Pataki. Neither man has formally announced his candidacy,
but many New York Republicans say Pataki's allies have been quietly
helping Lazio build support. Aides to Pataki deny those assertions.
</P>
<P>
   But in Washington, a large number of Republican officials and
fund-raisers view Giuliani as the party's strongest candidate.
Those Republicans have been puzzled that Pataki, the state's most
powerful Republican, has not joined Giuliani's bandwagon, and they
are angered by reports that Pataki's supporters have been trying to
undermine the mayor, particularly upstate, where Pataki's support
is strongest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans in Washington figure that Rudy would be by far the
strongest candidate,'' said a New York Republican congressman York
who is close to Pataki. ``They want to coalesce around him early.
So there is frustration. They think the state is not helping.''
</P>
<P>
   A prominent Republican lobbyist in Washington who has spoken to
both the mayor and governor in recent days said: ``The whole thing
is baffling. Everybody agrees Giuliani is a sure thing. It's good
for the party. Every national figure agrees it is the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the latest show of Washington support for Giuliani, the mayor
is scheduled to appear at a news conference Wednesday on Capitol
Hill with several Republican senators. After that, he will speak
before a group of major contributors to the National Republican
Senatorial Committee, which raises money for Senate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Though the senatorial committee is not allowed to take sides in
a Republican primary, the speech is widely viewed among Republicans
as giving an important lift to Giuliani's candidacy by giving him
the chance to meet major Republican donors from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   While Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., chairman of the senatorial
committee, has not endorsed Giuliani, he has made very clear that
he considers the mayor the best possible Republican candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's supporters have expressed dismay that McConnell has been
so supportive of the mayor. But they assert that while Giuliani may
have stronger support in Washington, Lazio is gaining momentum
among Republican leaders in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I checked, they don't have votes in New York,''
said a Republican official close to Lazio, referring to Washington
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican official added that allies of Pataki have been
helpful in directing Lazio to upstate Republican leaders who remain
angry with Giuliani for endorsing Gov. Mario Cuomo in his 1994
campaign against Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get in the door because they hate Rudy,'' the official
said. ``But we stay in the room because they like Rick Lazio.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio himself has not been shy about promoting himself in
Washington as a close ally of Pataki. Last week, Lazio glowingly
introduced Pataki when the governor testified on tax cuts before
the House Committee on government Reform.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who are close to Pataki say the governor has
encouraged Lazio to work at building support upstate so that the
party will have a viable candidate if Giuliani decides not to run.
Pataki spoke with Giuliani on Tuesday, but aides to both men
declined to say what they discussed.
</P>
<P>
   But other Republicans say Pataki's allies have gone further than
that, asking local leaders to withhold support from Giuliani. And
Republican fund-raisers say that some Republican contributors in
New York are unwilling to give money to Giuliani as long as he is
fighting with the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in New York is hanging in limbo waiting,'' said a
Washington Republican with strong ties to the New York Republican
Party. ``At some point, there has to be a brokered peace.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
