<HEADLINE>
3 LARGE DRUG MAKERS REPORT EARNINGS GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A steep weeklong selloff in pharmaceutical stocks
halted Tuesday, after three large drug makers reported
first-quarter earnings gains and Merck &AMP; Co. received a
recommendation from a government panel that its new drug for
arthritis and acute pain be approved.
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter net income at the Schering-Plough Corp. rose 20
percent, to $539 million, or 36 cents a diluted share, meeting
analysts' expectations. SmithKline Beecham PLC's first-quarter
profit increased 14 percent, to $540 million, or 48.9 cents an
American depository receipt, which surpassed expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But what surprised analysts was Johnson &AMP; Johnson's
first-quarter gain of $1.13 billion, or 82 cents a diluted share, 2
cents above consensus estimates and a 12.3 percent gain from the
comparable period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products, which also reported Tuesday, said its
earnings rose less than 1 percent, to $654.9 million, or 49 cents a
diluted share, in line with analysts' projections.
</P>
<P>
   The earnings news lifted all four stocks as well as the shares
of many of their competitors. Johnson &AMP; Johnson rose $6 a share, to
$96.25. SmithKline Beecham's ADR's increased $3.9375, to $66.6875.
American Home Products increased $2.5625 a share, to $62.3125. And
after plunging 20.4 percent in the last week, Schering-Plough's
shares closed up 3.9 percent, or $1.875, at $50.375.
</P>
<P>
   ``After Lilly and Pfizer unexpectedly missed the mark last week
with their earnings announcements, investors were reassured that
Johnson &AMP; Johnson and the others all made their expectations,''
said Viren Mehta, a partner with Mehta Partners.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every major United States drug maker participated in
Tuesday's rally. Shares of Merck, lifted by the recommendation from
an advisory committee to the Food and Drug Administration that
Vioxx, its arthritis drug, be approved, rose 2.8 percent, or
$2.125, to $75.25.
</P>
<P>
   But what was especially noteworthy was Pfizer's volatile
performance. After being the industry darling for most of last
year, Pfizer was dumped by investors last week when the company
announced that its second-quarter earnings gains might be less than
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Pfizer's shares had fallen 21.4 percent since then and appeared
to be rebounding strongly Tuesday, up as much as $4.1875 in
afternoon trading, when investors sold again. The stock closed at
$118.75 a share, up a mere 81.25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company should have earnings gains of 25 percent during
the second half of this year,'' said David Saks, a managing
director at Gruntal &AMP; Co. ``Investors also don't realize that
Pfizer recorded strong sales from Viagra last year in the second
quarter. If you hit that many home runs in one inning, of course
you're aren't going to beat it by a huge percentage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
