<HEADER>
A6746 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      04-20 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Nine games. That's all that's left in the Rockets' 1999 NBA
regular-season schedule. Nine games.
<TEXT>
<P>
   That's all the time the Rockets have to tweak the offense,
fine-tune the defense and get everyone on the same page.
</P>
<P>
   These final nine games will serve as a lab experiment of sorts,
in which the Rockets attempt to capture their playoff chemistry in
a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   That process starts tonight against the Dallas Mavericks. The
Mavs drag a 14-27 record into Compaq Center, but Hakeem Olajuwon
isn't about to overlook the team that picked up two of those wins
last week by knocking off San Antonio and Minnesota and beat
Phoenix on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot take anything for granted,'' Olajuwon said. ``Every
game is so big by now.''
</P>
<P>
   A win tonight would clinch a playoff berth for the Rockets, but
that was almost a foregone conclusion for a team that features
Olajuwon, Scottie Pippen and Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets have their sights set higher, and overtaking the San
Antonio Spurs for the No. 3 seed in the Western Conference playoff
field would be nice.
</P>
<P>
   But with nine games before the playoffs, the Rockets have things
to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's true,'' Olajuwon said. ``The key is to stay focused and
just keep playing. We have nine games left now, and each one of
these games is important _ critical _ in the standings. We are
taking it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game is another steppingstone in the maturity of this
team. We see Scottie getting so much more aggressive and feeling
much more comfortable out there, and then there's Charles, who is
so quick on his feet, making such nice moves to the basket and
getting key rebounds. The team is coming together.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, ever the pragmatist, knows what he wants to accomplish
in these final nine games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to win them,'' he said. ``I just want to win, man.
That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen is focusing on getting the team to lose the one bad habit
it has acquired this season _ blowing leads. The most recent
examples of that came in their past two games.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets coughed up a 23-point lead in Sunday's 86-83 loss at
San Antonio, then watched a 16-point lead shrink to four with less
than three minutes to play Monday against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   They pulled out the game, but Pippen is troubled by the Rockets'
overly generous ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to see us close out games better,'' Pippen said.
``That's been the biggest disappointment for this team as a whole,
that we haven't been able to complete any games like we would like
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize that we have a very dominant team. Dream can score
on anyone, (as can) Charles. When we're all rolling like that, it's
tough to defend us.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not holding on to what we work hard for. We're
allowing teams to get back into games too fast and too easy,
especially (Sunday's) game. We worked for a quarter to build such a
great lead on that team, but they got back into the game within six
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realize that we've let a lot of games slip away from us,
and these last nine games, we have to really stay focused and
realize that it's important that we try to carry this momentum into
the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's game is the first step in starting that momentum, even
though Barkley contends the Rockets are competing with just one
team in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing against ourselves,'' Barkley said. ``We have to
play up to our capabilities. I think we've played really well this
past week, and we have to keep building on that. I can't worry
about who we're playing against.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dallas is obviously a team that has been struggling, but we're
not playing against Dallas (tonight). We're competing against
ourselves, and I'm very happy. We've played really well this past
week.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich hopes that stays true over
these final nine games.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every game some new problem comes up (because of) the other
team _ what they do, their strengths and how we set our defense to
that _ or if they do something on their defense,'' Tomjanovich
said. ``We worked on some things that Dallas hurt us with (on March
24) with their defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at it on tape, and we worked on it. Once you get
into the season, the schedule and the opponent sort of takes care
of your work, and as you take care of that, you grow as a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just moving right along. We have nine games left, six at
home and three on the road. We have to go out, take care of
business, approach each game with a businesslike focus and come out
and play with intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything is going to work out all right for us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
